 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   Robertson
</P>
<P>
   Dawson quiet &QL; 
about role in &QL; 
Comets' birth
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CARROLL Dawson won't talk about the birth of the Comets. All he'll
tell you is he just got ``real lucky,'' because he doesn't know a
darn thing about women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   That may be true. But basketball is basketball, and Dawson, a
lifelong honor student of thump-thump, knows a player when he sees
one.
</P>
<P>
   And a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson isn't much for taking credit. Never has been. He's the
consummate back-room kind of guy. The truth is, however, that he
quietly helped nurture Rudy Tomjanovich into one of the NBA's elite
coaches, and the groundwork he laid for the Comets was so
incredibly solid that they may already be the finest women's team
in history.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, name a better one. You can't. The USA's 1996 Olympic
gold medalists? While they clearly had more star power, they didn't
have anywhere near the worldliness or the experience, much less the
cohesiveness, the Comets have developed through winning the WNBA's
first title and an encore season that thus far has been a
hard-to-equal sequel.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fine folks in Columbus, Ohio, would probably cast a
bunch of votes for their two-time American Basketball League
champions, the Quest never reeled off 14 victories in a row or
built a 19-1 record like the Comets have. The Quest has its stars,
to be sure, but it doesn't have stars quite like Cynthia Cooper and
Sheryl Swoopes, or anything approaching the Comets' depth.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets are so amazingly good, they can look godawful for the
longest while against a solid, fired-up foe like Phoenix and still
make winning look simple in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you can do it the way we did it tonight,'' coach Van
Chancellor said, ``I guess that means we're a pretty good
basketball team. I began to think we weren't ever going to score.
But we've got players who make plays, who step up when they have
to. That's how we're doing what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets fell behind 9-0 Tuesday night, missing seven shots in
a row at the outset before Cooper _ who else? _ drove the lane and
flipped in a nifty little lefthanded layup with more than six
minutes gone. And they wouldn't finally go in front until Cooper _
who else? _ drained a 3-pointer with 2.4 seconds left in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury hung around awhile longer, making a nuisance of
itself, but the Comets would have none of such insolence and wound
up on top 72-62, rewarding the rowdy sellout crowd of 16,285 for
its boisterous support.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen-and-one. Fourteen in a row. And SRO. In a word, wow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely proud of what Van and his team have
accomplished,'' Dawson will say, but that's it. End of interview.
Somebody else is going to have to tell us about the hundred hours
of video C.D. watched before concluding that Cooper, 34 and almost
forgotten in America because she had been playing elsewhere for so
long, was a franchise player, the player Houston absolutely had to
have.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, it was Dawson who presented Coop a ceremonial ball
before the game Wednesday night, honoring her as the league's first
1,000-point scorer.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody else is also going to have to tell us about how C.D.
nearly burned up his VCR, then his phone line, learning everything
he could about Chancellor before he concluded that Van was the,
gulp, man to pull everything together.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson tried to hire a prominent female coach, as per the
strongly worded ``advice'' coming down from the WNBA's higher-ups.
He called Texas Tech's Marsha Sharp and Tennessee's Pat Summitt,
among others, but they weren't interested. Chancellor, a veritable
institution himself at Ole Miss, was a tad skeptical as well, but
his ego was still in check once he committed.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't come to Houston intending to steal the Rockets'
thunder, or trying to one-up Rudy T. It has, well, just sort of
happened that way of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play hard, and they practice just as hard,'' Dawson says
of the Comets. ``You watch Van work them, and it's not surprising
what kind of season they're having.''
</P>
<P>
   The only surprise is they aren't 20-0. Yes, Phoenix stole one
early out there, but the Comets have replied with victories at
America West and at Compaq Center. Perhaps the Mercury will get
another shot in the playoffs _ coach Cheryl Miller has already
predicted a Phoenix win _ but the Comets would have no reason to
fear another such planetary encounter.
</P>
<P>
   In the solar system of women's hoops, they are hardly a fleeting
interloper. If anything, they have become the sun itself. So ol'
C.D. should feel proud of himself, too. The Comets are very much
his baby, even if he politely refuses to concede paternity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
