<HEADLINE>
TESTS LIFT HOPES FOR OFFICER SHOT IN HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Though a bullet remained lodged in his brain, the
police officer shot in a Staten Island housing project Sunday
showed some encouraging signs during tests Tuesday, and doctors
began to express cautious optimism about his condition.
</P>
<P>
   As the tense vigil continued Tuesday for the wounded officer,
the 17-year-old ex-convict being held in the case was arraigned on
charges including the attempted murder of the officer and the
murder of another man two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Gerard Carter, 28, remained in critical but stable
condition Tuesday at the St. Vincent's Campus of the Sisters of
Charity Medical Center on Staten Island. Doctors had initially
given Carter only a 50 percent chance of survival, but hospital
officials said Tuesday that they were heartened that he had
survived the first 24 hours. But they added that the next few days
would be crucial in determining whether he would suffer serious
brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   Carter exhibited signs of basic brain activity during a series
of tests performed Tuesday: his pupils dilated when doctors shone a
light into his eyes, and his reflexes worked when they pricked his
fingers and toes with pins. ``It's still too early to give any
prognosis, but we have every reason to be optimistic.'' said Bill
McCann, a hospital spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors were most concerned that damage could be caused by the
swelling of the brain, which occurs after a serious injury like a
gunshot wound, McCann said. To reduce and contain the swelling,
they removed dead brain tissue and used a catheter to drain excess
fluid.
</P>
<P>
   The young man accused of shooting him, Shatiek Johnson, was
arraigned in Staten Island Criminal Court on charges of the
attempted murder of the officer and of second-degree murder in the
July 16 slaying on Staten Island of Eric Trotman, 20, who was shot
more than 15 times in the head and torso.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Carter, who was patrolling the West Brighton Houses on Sunday
night in a van with his partner, Officer Eric Storch, had
recognized Johnson on a path as someone detectives wanted to
question in the Trotman case, police said. After driving past him
and checking a picture that was distributed to many officers in the
precinct, the officers returned to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   Before they could, police said, the man opened fire through the
windshield of the van, striking Carter in the temple. Storch
returned fire but did not hit the gunman, who then fled.
</P>
<P>
   After an intense manhunt and a five-hour armed standoff, Johnson
was arrested Monday morning, hiding in a closet of an apartment in
a building adjacent to the crime scene. Later that morning, two law
enforcement officials said, Johnson signed a statement admitting
the shooting of Carter. That afternoon, he signed another statement
admitting the shooting of Trotman, according to the law enforcement
officials, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's lawyer, Alex Shulman, acknowledged that his client had
signed the statements but said he would argue to have them ruled
inadmissible in court because, he said, Johnson had initially been
denied his right to see a lawyer. Shulman said Johnson told him
that he had asked to speak with a lawyer before being interrogated
but was never given one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he wanted a lawyer, but they made believe they didn't
hear it or they ignored it,'' Shulman said.
</P>
<P>
   According to law enforcement officials who have seen the
statements, both begin with the statement, ``I have been advised of
my rights'' _ a reference to Miranda rights, which give suspects
the right not to speak with detectives and to confer with their
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said Johnson tried to portray the shooting as an
act of self-defense in the statement, contending that he saw Storch
drawing his service pistol and that he wanted to be the one to
shoot first. He claimed in the statement that he had been aiming at
Storch, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being sought in the murder case, Johnson was
wanted on two other arrest warrants: officials said he had skipped
a day of community service he had been sentenced to after being
convicted of subway fare-beating in Times Square, and he had
stopped seeing his parole officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew he was wanted,'' said Chief Assistant District
Attorney David Lehr. ``The police had been to his house a number of
times on fare beating and the parole violation.''
</P>
<P>
   In Johnson's statement about the Trotman case, he said he fired
his gun only after Eric Trotman pointed a gun at him, the law
enforcement officials said. Trotman was shot between 15 and 18
times, the police said. No guns were recovered at the scene, they
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
