A7431 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAWLEY-SUIT-NYT &LR;      07-29 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAWLEY-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURORS URGED TO SILENCE BRAWLEY ADVISERS THROUGH LARGE DAMAGE
AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Shortly before the jurors began discussing
Tuesday what damages to set in the Tawana Brawley defamation case,
the lawyer for the plaintiff urged them to punish the three Brawley
advisers with an award large enough to ``shut them up.''
</P>
<P>
   After the summation from the lawyer, William Stanton, and legal
instructions from the judge, the jurors deliberated for about three
hours before they asked for some testimony to be reread and for
certain documents to be supplied in the jury room.
</P>
<P>
   The court was adjourned without a verdict just after 3 p.m.
Deliberations are to continue on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton employed the staccato style he has used throughout the
eight-month trial, implying that it was obvious that there should
be a large assessment against the three Brawley advisers, the Rev.
Al Sharpton, C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton said the advisers had subjected his client, Steven
Pagones, to humiliation, mental stress and physical suffering by
falsely asserting that he had raped Ms. Brawley in 1987. ``The only
way you can shut them up,'' he said, ``is by returning a verdict in
a large sum of money that will teach them a lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   The jurors are considering what compensatory damages to award
Pagones, a former assistant district attorney, for such losses as
pain and suffering. In his instructions, Justice S. Barrett Hickman
of state Supreme Court said the jurors were required to award him
at least $1 in compensatory damages.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the jurors are weighing whether to assess punitive
damages, which are intended to punish wrongdoers and to discourage
others from engaging in similar conduct. Hickman said they could
award any amount they deemed appropriate, including no punitive
damages. In his complaint, Pagones is seeking $150 million in
damages, but Hickman did not specify any upper limit in his
instructions to the jurors today.
</P>
<P>
   The final arguments in the case were laced with the
argumentative oratory that has typified the long trial. But the
demeanor of the lawyers suggested exhaustion more than efforts at
exhortation.
</P>
<P>
   The day began with Maddox completing the summation that he began
on Monday afternoon. He contended that he should not be punished
merely for expressing his ``beliefs'' about Pagones. He sought to
evoke the spirit of the country's Founding Fathers in asking the
jurors to preserve American liberties by giving Pagones only
nominal damages.
</P>
<P>
   And he insulted Pagones, although not with the energy he
displayed months ago. Maddox argued, for example, that Pagones did
not suffer stomach irritation, as he claimed, because he was
anxious over the advisers' public accusations. Instead, Maddox
theorized, it was because Pagones consumes too much food. ``He
doesn't eat to live,'' Maddox said. ``He lives to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   When Stanton took the lectern, his first move was an effort to
show that Maddox was still hurling gratuitous insults at Pagones.
As lawyers do at the start of a summation, Stanton greeted the
judge, his opponents and the jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he greeted Pagones. ``And Fatso,'' he said politely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
