u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BEACH-NEEDLES-NYT &LR;      07-29 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BEACH-NEEDLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE SYRINGES AND VIALS FOUND ON BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lifeguards found more needles and crack vials on
Rockaway Beach Tuesday, prompting city officials to declare New
York City's longest beach off-limits to swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   Parks Department officials said that the flotsam appeared to be
drug paraphernalia and not illegally dumped medical waste. And
while city officials were still investigating the sources of the
syringes and vials, three theories had emerged Tuesday, said Henry
Stern, the parks commissioner: that they had been lying on the
ocean floor and had been stirred by recent choppy waters and winds;
that they came from the city's sewer system, or, least likely, from
recent illegal dumping.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Stern stressed that the amount of waste was
relatively minor; nothing of the magnitude, certainly, of a
situation in the late 1980s, when syringes, hazardous medical waste
and dead rats washed ashore in Rockaway and at several other city
beaches, sometimes for days on end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a small thing,'' Stern said of the current incident,
``but we have zero tolerance for beach defects. We will open the
beaches as soon as the coast is clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five days, officials have recovered 53 hypodermic
needles, 92 crack vials, assorted needle caps and an intravenous
pouch over a 5-mile stretch, from Beach 30th Street to Beach 130th
Street, with the bulk in the Beach 90s.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, city officials on Monday closed sections of
Rockaway Beach. After cleaning up the beach Tuesday morning, city
officials reopened it to swimmers for a few hours, but quickly
closed all 6.4 miles of the beach when lifeguards spotted more
syringes and crack vials.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, lifeguards are expected to follow the same
pattern: Head to the beach at 5 a.m., inspect the area, clean it up
if necessary, and determine whether the water is safe.
</P>
<P>
   The beach closure Tuesday was the first caused by needles
washing ashore since 1988, when Rockaway Beach, Fire Island and all
the municipal beaches in Brooklyn and on Staten Island were closed
for days, or weeks in some cases, because of medical waste and
sewage that had washed ashore. The scare was so widespread that
some beaches in New Jersey and Connecticut were closed for several
weeks as well.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the garbage and medical waste that washed ashore was
later traced to the Fresh Kills Landfill on the western shore of
Staten Island. In addition, driftwood, plastics and other items
floated from New York Harbor and landed on New Jersey beaches or
Long Island's South Shore.
</P>
<P>
   For a time thereafter, many swimmers were reluctant to venture
into the water _ or even to go near the beach, fearful that they
might come into contact with HIV-infected materials. As a result,
businesses tethered to the summer beach economy lost millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But the impact was felt in other ways, too. The closures
received widespread national attention, and quickly became a
metaphor for all that was perceived to be wrong with New York City
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the amount of beach debris has declined somewhat,
said Cynthia Zipf, executive director of Clean Ocean Action, a
coalition of groups dedicated to cleaning the waters off New York
and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no reports of accidents involving the needles
that have washed up at Rockaway in the last five days, said Ed
Skyler, a spokesman for the Parks Department. Even so, the
Department of Sanitation is testing the debris, and the Department
of Health is encouraging anyone who gets pricked by a needle to get
a tetanus shot.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether people will follow that advice.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, after the lifeguards went off duty at 6 p.m., at
least a dozen people played in the strong surf of the Beach 90th
Street area, where most of the detritus had been found. Some people
said they had not seen signs indicating that swimming was
forbidden; others said that they could not resist a dip on a warm,
humid day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care,'' said Kelly Tien, 25, of Valley Stream,
N.Y., who was with her 3-year-old son, Aaron. ``I've loved the
beach ever since I was a little girl, and it doesn't matter if
there's medical waste. I'll still come and swim.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
