<HEADER>
A7435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-GASOLINE-TAX-350&AMP;A     07-29 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-GASOLINE-TAX-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACKING BIPARTISAN SUPPORT, REPUBLICANS SCRAP WHITMAN'S GAS-TAX
RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Gov. Christie Whitman was dealt a major setback
Tuesday as members of her own party officially scuttled her plan to
raise the state's gasoline tax to pay for new mass transit and
highway projects.
</P>
<P>
   With traffic congestion a significant concern of voters in the
state, Whitman had made increasing spending for transportation a
top goal of her second term. But in the end, her efforts to push
through a 4-cent-a-gallon rise in the tax over three years failed
mainly because she had helped bolster anti-tax sentiment in New
Jersey by emphasizing tax cuts in her first term.
</P>
<P>
   The final blow came late Tuesday afternoon, when Assembly
Speaker Jack Collins, R-Salem County, formally announced that he
had canceled a scheduled vote on the proposed tax increase because
of a lack of bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement between the Whitman administration and Republican
lawmakers to raise the gasoline tax began to fall apart Monday when
Democrats in the Assembly surprised their Republican colleagues by
banding together to oppose the tax increase. After they reiterated
their position Tuesday, Collins said that Assembly Republicans
would not support a tax increase alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats have indicated again that there would be no
support,'' Collins said in a statement. ``It is unfortunate that
partisan politics has scuttled this important legislative
initiative and placed future transportation infrastructure projects
and jobs in jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Anthony Impreveduto, D-Secaucus, who led the debate
on the gas tax for his party, said no Democrats would change their
minds before Thursday. ``It is over,'' he said. ``It is a done
deal, as far as we are concerned. My Democratic caucus is
steadfastly opposed to increased taxes at this point in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans control the Legislature and Collins said
that he personally approved of the tax increase, some Republican
lawmakers were reluctant to support any tax increase because they
feared reprisals from Democrats during next year's re-election
campaigns.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Democrats pointed out that they were badly punished by New
Jersey's tax-weary voters, losing the Legislature in 1991 and the
governorship in 1993, after supporting Gov. Jim Florio's $2.8
billion package of tax increases in 1990 without bipartisan
support. And Democrats said they were not going to provide cover
for their Republican colleagues who have been branding Democrats as
tax-and-spenders for years.
</P>
<P>
   What cemented their opposition, some Democratic lawmakers said,
were comments that Whitman made over the weekend at the Republican
National Committee meeting in New York. At the meeting, Whitman
told her fellow Republicans from across the country that the party
needed to emphasize its commitment to cutting taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time that she is saying that Republicans need to
reduce taxes, she is asking us to increase a tax on gasoline in New
Jersey,'' Impreveduto said. ``We're not going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman was trying to win legislative approval before Aug. 3 to
meet a constitutional deadline to put a referendum on the November
ballot, asking voters whether they wanted to dedicate motor vehicle
taxes to transportation projects.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman had put together an unusual coalition of labor leaders,
environmental advocates and business owners to help lobby
legislative support for her plan. She had initially recommended a
5-cent-a-gallon annual increase to increase spending for
transportation projects and an additional 2-cent-a-gallon increase
for her plan to preserve 1 million acres of undeveloped land over
the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers said the 5-cent-a-gallon increase, which would
have raised state taxes on gasoline to 21.5 cents a gallon from
14.5 cents, was too high. And they opposed using any gasoline tax
revenues for her open space proposal.
</P>
<P>
   To address their objections, Whitman agreed with Republican
legislative leaders to scale back her proposal. They agreed to
raise the gasoline tax a penny a gallon this year, 2 cents in 2000
and another penny in 2001. Even so, there remained some opposition
in the Assembly. But Senate lawmakers said that they were prepared
to approve the tax increase if it first won passage in the
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman also abandoned using a gasoline tax increase to buy
undeveloped land and agreed instead to borrow up to $100 million a
year over the next 10 years to buy the 1 million acres. The
borrowing plan would be paid for with existing sales tax revenues
over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although the borrowing proposal to preserve open spaces was
approved by the Assembly's Appropriations Committee on Monday, its
fate remains uncertain in the Legislature on Thursday, lawmakers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said Tuesday that she was disappointed by the recent
turn of events but that she remained hopeful that her proposal
would still be considered Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very hopeful that at the end of the day there will be
enough Democrats that will come across and vote for this because
this isn't a political issue,'' she said. ``It's not something to
be used by one party against another. I'm the tax-cutting governor.
I've cut taxes 17 times. I came into office talking about cutting
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like talking about a tax increase, but there are times
when you need substantive dollars to be able to accomplish
something that is very important for the future of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the administration's five-year transportation plan, the
gasoline tax increase would have allowed the administration to
increase spending to $900 million from $700 million this year for
transportation projects. Spending would have been at $900 million
the next year, and then increase to $950 million a year over the
next three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are passing up is the opportunity to increase the pace
and expand the number of projects that need to be addressed,'' said
Pete McDonough, the chief spokesman for Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Democratic Leader Joseph Doria argued that the Whitman
administration could use part of the state's $850 million budget
surplus to cover the cost of expanding transportation projects.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Whitman did not help her lobbying efforts with
her comments over the weekend. ``The actions and comments of the
Whitman administration in recent weeks has poisoned the well of any
potential Democratic support of a gas tax hike,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
