<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-SCHUMER-365&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER SAYS D'AMATO IS NO FRIEND OF NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an assault on what has been the heart of Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato's political appeal, Rep. Charles Schumer challenged
the image of D'Amato as an advocate of New York on Tuesday,
asserting that he regularly voted with Republicans against New York
interests on issues ranging from crime to health care.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, trying to find an appeal that will elevate himself in
the three-way Democratic primary, described D'Amato as an
undistinguished incumbent who had sat by as fellow Republican
leaders curbed programs that benefit the Northeast. The Brooklyn
congressman, in an early-morning speech to a group of young
Democrats, asserted that D'Amato's votes in the Senate would be his
downfall as he sought to win a third term this November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to let every voter in New York know about your
record in Washington,'' Schumer declared, addressing an absent
D'Amato. ``You can count on that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said D'Amato was ``playing the champion for New York when in
reality he was working and voting against New York interests.''
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, New York City Public Advocate Mark Green, one of
Schumer's opponents in the primary, offered a somewhat different
prescription for unseating the senator. Green said the key to
Democratic victory was to remind voters aggressively of what he
described as the senator's history of ethical lapses, while
attacking his voting record at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, Schumer had argued that there was limited benefit
to questioning D'Amato's ethics, since voters were familiar with
the issue, and that Democrats would win by spotlighting D'Amato's
record. But Green's attack seemed to have succeeded in changing
Schumer's mind somewhat: he peppered his speech with questions
about D'Amato's ethics as he tried to combine the two themes.
``Even if he did deliver for New York, his ethics alone would be
repulsive enough to deserve defeat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato declined to comment on Schumer's comments. But the
senator's spokesman, Harvey Valentine, said: ``It's unfortunate
that Mr. Schumer has nothing positive to say to the people of New
York, and so he's attacking Senator D'Amato. It's getting
tiresome.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The third candidate in the Democratic primary, Geraldine
Ferraro, the former Queens congresswoman and vice presidential
nominee, continued to keep a notably low public profile,
notwithstanding her advisers' assertions that she would be
campaigning more aggressively with the Sept. 15 primary
approaching. Her aides said she was spending this week raising
money to pay for television advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   There were new signs of friction between Schumer and Green on
Tuesday, this time over what Congress should do to protect the
Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   Green, echoing President Clinton, said that any national
budgetary surplus should go toward shoring up Social Security, and
that there should be no discussion of other uses of a surplus until
that is done.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has also said the surplus should be directed to helping
Social Security. But as he has campaigned, he has repeatedly
invoked the surplus as a source of funds to pay for programs he has
proposed, including more spending on education and making college
tuition tax-deductible.
</P>
<P>
   Green said Tuesday that Schumer was being misleading in saying
he could do both; Schumer's aides said he had made clear that
Social Security was the top priority.
</P>
<P>
   In making his case against D'Amato before a group of young
Democrats known as the Democratic Leadership for the 21st Century,
Schumer pointed to D'Amato's opposition to the Brady Law, which
imposed a waiting period on the purchase of handguns, and his
opposition to the ban on assault weapons as examples of positions
on criminal law that he said were out of step with most New
Yorkers. He noted that D'Amato supported the Republican leadership
in pushing huge cuts in Medicaid and Medicare that would have
particularly hurt New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Pothole is a myth,'' Schumer said, referring to the
nickname the senator has embraced as a way of telegraphing his
concern with issues of local concern. ``Senator Pothole is a
fake.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer departed from his text to argue against the contention
that D'Amato was a skillful politician who was invulnerable to this
type of attack because he moderates his positions as elections
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a notion _ it's usually held, when it's held at all,
in elite circles _ and that is that Al D'Amato is a brilliant
politician because he switches his votes around election time,''
Schumer said. ``This is not political brilliance of any kind. It is
crass chicanery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
