<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-INSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY GIVEN MONTH TO LIST HAZARDOUS SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
   (rl) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Following a state court's ruling that New York City
does not properly inspect and maintain its schools, a judge in
Manhattan has given city officials 30 days to list all schools with
hazardous conditions and to create a plan to fix them promptly.
</P>
<P>
   The order, issued late Monday by Justice Barry Cozier of state
Supreme Court, raised the possibility that the board of education
would be publicly identifying hazardous buildings just before they
open for the start of school in September. In the past, such
hazards have included things like falling bricks, masonry and
plaster.
</P>
<P>
   But board officials said Tuesday that any hazards would be
eliminated by the first day of school. ``We would not leave a
condition that could harm a human being,'' said Chiara Coletti, the
board's public affairs officer.
</P>
<P>
   She said that conditions in some schools were still unrepaired
but that school officials had taken steps to keep them from
endangering students. If any more hazards are found, she said, ``we
may have to put up netting'' or sidewalk bridging if ``the job is
just too big to complete by the beginning of school.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a number of accidents, including one in which a
16-year-old girl was killed by a falling brick, drew public
attention to efforts to fix the schools.
</P>
<P>
   The city has yet to say whether it will appeal the decision.
Tuesday afternoon, city lawyers said they were studying the order.
</P>
<P>
   Cozier's order also covered nonhazardous building code
violations and set a 90-day deadline for the city to create a plan
to make its inspections and repairs a continuing process.
</P>
<P>
   The order results from a 1994 lawsuit by the city teachers'
union, the United Federation of Teachers, which maintained that the
board had failed to keep school buildings safe for students and
teachers. In March, the union won a strong ruling in which the
judge scathingly criticized the ``sorry state'' of city school
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The union's suit had cited a 1996 memo by Robert Buxbaum, the
board's former director of school facilities, saying there were
hazardous conditions in 237 school buildings, about one in five.
Since the memo was written, board officials have said, the hazards
have been addressed by emergency measures _ including sidewalk
bridges _ and are no longer an immediate danger to students.
</P>
<P>
   The poor condition of city schools is a result of decades of
deferred maintenance in which aging buildings were allowed to
deteriorate. More than half the 1,200 city school buildings were
built over 50 years ago, and many remain in bad condition even
though the city and state have spent billions on repairs to city
schools in the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The March decision on the union lawsuit also ordered the union
and the city to work out a plan for inspecting and repairing the
buildings. Tuesday, union officials complained that the city had
not been cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad commentary when the City of New York has to be sued
to keep its schools free from hazards and in good repair,'' said
Randi Weingarten, president of the union, at a news conference.
``It's even sadder when, in the face of a court decision affirming
its responsibility to do so, the city continues to drag its feet
rather than take the most common-sense steps to assure the safety
of one million schoolchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said she hoped the city would not appeal the judge's
order, saying it would just drag out a matter that has been pending
for several years. ``This order is good for parents, it is good for
schools, and it is good for school kids,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement released Tuesday, Chancellor Rudy Crew
said the board would comply with Cozier's order to list schools
with hazards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could possibly be of more importance to us than the
safety of our students and staff,'' Crew's statement said. ``The
city and the board have been making every effort to address the
issues raised in the court's determination.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew said the board was working to make permanent repairs to all
237 schools cited in the 1996 memo and had repaired 98 other
schools in recent months. He said the board was planning to make
permanent repairs in 73 more schools not listed in the memo, and
had spent $285 million on repair projects last year.
</P>
<P>
   The board has commissioned an engineering survey of all city
school buildings. Board officials said the engineering study was in
its final review but was not ready for release. The last such
survey was done in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Crew said that even before Monday's court order, ``the board had
begun compiling a list of other city schools with conditions in
need of immediate attention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore,'' he said, ``we will have no difficulty in
complying with Barry Cozier's order today requiring that such a
list be ready for submission to the court before school opens this
fall and that a plan be prepared to address those conditions in a
timely manner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
