<P>
   SWEEPSTAKES-ELDERLY-II (Undated) _ Second of two articles: As
the mailboxes of the elderly overflow with sweepstakes offers from
big-name American magazine publishers, a new class of con artist is
using the same promise of riches to bilk the elderly out of
hundreds of millions of dollars each year. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT8) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOLARSHIPS-EDUC (Undated) _ IN response to complaints from
donors that their gifts are not making much difference and to
criticism that some colleges use generous national scholarships to
shore up their own financial aid accounts, some colleges appear to
be moving toward letting students keep more of the outside
scholarships they win. By Ian Zack.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
[NYT10) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-CONVENTION (Los Angeles) _ Over two solid days, the cream
of this city's civic leadership has courted the Democratic Party's
national convention for 2000 with every carrot at its command, and
somewhere between the margaritas and the mariachis, the exploding
wall of balloons and the flying angel, the intensity of the effort
took on a sweetly comic small-town air. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT17) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LITTLELEAGUE-RAGE (Sturgeon Bay, Wis.) _ Call it Little League
rage. Adult misbehavior is becoming a familiar blight on children's
games in all sports, say league officials, coaches and parents.
Fathers yell at coaches. Mothers belittle players. And umpires are
attacked. Game officials have long taken verbal abuse, of course.
But now they are shoved and spat on, even stabbed and shot. By Bill
Dedman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT16) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
