   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TACTICS _ News analysis: Kenneth Starr is finally
hurrying, but Bill Clinton has a new, specific reason for delay _
wanting Monica Lewinsky to testify first so he had a chance of
knowing what she says. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SECURITY (Undated) _ A serious security flaw has been
discovered in popular e-mail programs published by Microsoft Corp.
and Netscape Communications Corp. that would permit a malicious
person to send a message containing a virus that could crash a
computer, destroy or even steal data. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   GM-OUTLOOK (Flint, Mich.) _ Like estranged spouses who
reluctantly decide to live together again, GM and the United
Automobile Workers union have ended their quarrel but face the task
of rebuilding a tattered relationship. GM's factories are among the
least efficient in the industry, partly because labor and
management distrust each other.
</P>
<P>
   GTE-DEAL (New York) _ It isn't often that a merger announcement
drives down the prices of stocks across an industry. But it
happened on Tuesday, as investors absorbed the news that Bell
Atlantic was paying $53 billion in stock for the GTE Corp. in a
deal structured as a merger of equals. At the end of the day's
trading, the Bell Atlantic-GTE combination looked more like the pin
that burst the telecommunications stock bubble than a go-go
megamerger. The group, which had traded at a price-earnings
multiple of 27 earlier this year, was down to a below-market
multiple of 21 on Tuesday. Months of merger hype and investor hopes
went pop. Like that. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Ever since Michael F. Price sold
the manager of the Mutual Series family of funds to the Franklin
Templeton Group for a small fortune two years ago, the funds have
labored under a cloud of uncertainty. Shareholders have waited
nervously for the day Price would give up stock-picking on his own
and fly off to his vacation home in Colorado. Price cleared the air
on Tuesday, announcing that he will step down as chief executive of
the group effective Nov. 1, taking advantage of an option outlined
in his contract which allowed him to depart on the second
anniversary of the company's sale. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT16) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Remember that old slogan for
Bufferin asking ``Why trade a headache for an upset stomach?'' A
new survey on a hot trend in advertising _ aiming sales pitches for
prescription drugs directly at users rather than at doctors _
indicates that consumers may be pondering a similar question today.
By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
