   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PLANTAINS (New York) _ To many Americans raised on eating sweet,
mushy bananas, it is difficult to imagine one that does not taste
sweet and needs to be cooked. But the plantain, a tropical fruit of
near miraculous variability, is spilling over from bodegas and
flooding into supermarkets and restaurants all over New York. It is
becoming so pervasive that it seems poised to join the list of
mainstream ingredients that were exotic not so long ago, like
cilantro, jalapenos and lemon grass. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT4,5) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-MENUS (New York) _ Anyone who's been dining out at some of
the newest New York restaurants recently might have noticed that
the menu has become a rather puzzling document. Buttons of
milkweed? Mint love letters? Hot Eel Dice? Huh? The newest rage
about town is a menu so special, so exclusive, that even you, the
special, exclusive diner who is paying for the privilege, has no
idea what you are about to eat. By Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   EAST-GERMANY-RESTAURANTS (Dresden) _ In Dresden, which is
rapidly repairing the physical damage from the hideous allied
fire-bombing of 1945, if not the psychological damage of the dismal
decades that followed, the dining room of the Bulow Residenz, a
small hotel in a stunning canary-and-white Baroque mansion, has won
a richly deserved Michelin star for cooking that would pass muster
in Paris. Gun-toting cops are long gone, replaced by shining
crystal and fresh flowers. In eastern Berlin, one is spoiled for
choice; indeed, many knowing visitors turn their backs on the
fading glamour of the Kurfurstendamm in the western part of town to
stay and eat in Mitte, the heart of the east. There, too, is a
Michelin-starred restaurant, called Vau, a handsome room with a
modern barrel-vault ceiling, sharp service, and fresh, light German
cooking. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
