<HEADLINE>
U.S. HIGH COURT DECLINES TO BAR NYC SEX ZONING LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The U.S. Supreme Court rejected a last-ditch appeal
Tuesday by a coalition of sex shops that had sought to block New
York City from enforcing a new zoning law against X-rated
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Although lawyers for the sex shops said they would continue to
press their challenges, the court's refusal to grant an injunction
cleared away the last legal hurdle to enforcement of the law. The
court issued a one-line order, without dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Building inspectors have already been entering establishments to
see whether performers are complying with the law, a city official
said, and lawyers for 107 shops affected by the law predicted an
onslaught of litigation by owners seeking to keep individual shops
open.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was a big victory for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who
said Tuesday that the city could now proceed with what he had set
out to do three years ago, ``which is to reduce and regulate the
sex shops that were ruining the neighborhoods of New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the shops and their customers, who had fought their
legal battle against the zoning law for 28 months, reacted with
disappointment and bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that these inspectors would be better off
inspecting scaffolding in buildings where a woman was killed and a
whole section of the city is tied up for days,'' said a lawyer for
the shops, Herald Price Fahringer, ``rather than going around and
checking sex shops to see whether they are in compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Fahringer and Beth Haroules, a lawyer with the New York Civil
Liberties Union, each said they would ask the Supreme Court to
review the constitutionality of the law in the fall term. But even
if the court were to agree to hear the case, they said, and order
the law stayed pending its consideration, the damage would have
been done, with shops closing or changing their inventories or the
nature of their business.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Haroules, whose organization had challenged the zoning law
on behalf of four customers of sex shops, said that even without
shutdowns, the impact of the law was already being felt.
</P>
<P>
   Stores have been getting rid of sexually explicit videotapes and
books, she said, and covering up nude dancers, thus denying such
entertainment to customers as well as violating the rights of the
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she said, with customers aware that undercover police
officers or building inspectors may be conducting surveillance
inside a theater or an X-rated business, ``obviously that has a
chilling effect on people's choices to partake of sexually explicit
entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Fahringer said he had been advising clients to bring shops into
compliance immediately to avoid shutdowns or criminal charges. He
said he had not heard from any of his clients that the city has
moved to padlock an X-rated establishment.
</P>
<P>
   City officials continued Tuesday to refuse to provide details of
enforcement strategies, or say when they might seek a court order
to close a shop. But Giuliani expressed satisfaction at the court's
ruling, telling reporters that this was a battle that former Mayor
Ed Koch had once ``bet us that we would never win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't paid his bet yet,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Koch said Tuesday night that he did not remember such a bet, but
that if the mayor could produce any ``credible evidence'' that he
had, he would be happy to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to congratulate the mayor in getting this done,'' Koch
said by phone. ``I approve of exactly what he's doing here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
