<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS ISN'T WORRIED ABOUT FOLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Glenn Foley's eyes grew wide when he imagined
how the New York Jets' offense would perform this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know, come time, the offense is going to be a juggernaut,''
Foley said after Tuesday morning's workout at Hofstra University.
</P>
<P>
   Juggernaut was not a word uttered by Bill Parcells. The coach
stopped the morning workout, ordered the first offensive unit off
the field and told it to run to a far corner of the field and back
before resuming practice.
</P>
<P>
   The mistakes committed may not have been all Foley's, but as the
starting quarterback, he has the responsibility of getting the
offense in sync. So far, he has struggled.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has given Foley the benefit of the doubt, acknowledging
that Foley is still feeling the effect of last season's sprained
ligament in his left knee. Parcells speculated that Foley could be
tired from taking the majority of the snaps. And the coach admitted
that the offense usually lags behind the defense early in camp.
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested that he might be providing excuses for his
inexperienced quarterback, Parcells' eyes grew almost as bright as
Foley's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making excuses for anybody,'' he said. ``I'm just
telling you the circumstances. I'm not usually one to make excuses
for players. I must be mellowing out a little.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion of a mellow Parcells would be news to his players,
particularly the offensive unit that drew his wrath Tuesday.
Parcells said his decision to get the unit running came because
Keith Byars committed two mental errors and missed an assignment on
the first three plays. But Foley accepted the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, positively, I take it personally,'' Foley said.
``It's really my huddle. As quarterback, you want to think it's
your team. Everybody's performance, if somebody screws up or if
somebody is doing something right, everything's a reflection on the
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time this year that we've had to run. It's a
daily thing. We're getting hundreds of plays a day, and if Bill
doesn't like it, somebody is going to be running. Today it was the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my fifth camp. I've seen some pretty good quarterbacks
come through here and work and go through the same problems I've
been going through now. But, again, it's the process. It takes a
while to iron things out. I'm not worried about it.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even though Foley was handed the job when the team waived Neil
O'Donnell, his experience last year included only four games of
significant playing time. And this is the first training camp that
he has entered as the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stuff we do now, maybe you get one-hundredth of it during
a game,'' Foley said. ``Our playbook is pages and pages long. There
is a lot mentally and a lot going on physically. It's a grind. You
just have to get through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said: ``All I can tell you about Glenn right now is
that this is a different set of circumstances for Glenn Foley. He's
getting the majority of the reps. He gets tired. He hasn't had this
many reps in five years. All I can tell you is it's different.
People that haven't been involved in it don't appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems I've got right now is that the defense is
ahead of the offense. We have put a lot of stuff in, and that
affects the receivers. Bill Belichick has got some schemes in that
are neutralizing some of the things we're trying to do. It
exasperates you.''
</P>
<P>
   But Foley still wants the job and remains confident that he and
the rest of the offense will work through the kinks. ``It's just a
matter of executing,'' Foley said. ``I don't have any doubt that
another couple of days, another week or so, this is going to be a
high-flying offense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
