<HEADLINE>
FASSEL PUTS AN END TO TEAM FIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In the first three days of Giants training camp,
there were fights between scrimmaging players during every one of
the team's two-a-day workouts. The total had reached seven.
</P>
<P>
   To revise an old joke, one could go to a fight and expect a
Giants training camp to break out.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Giants coach Jim Fassel reached his boiling point. At a
team meeting Monday night, Fassel ripped into his players,
reminding them it was a very public, on-the-field spat between
defensive players that contributed to the Giants' downfall in their
playoff loss to the Minnesota Vikings last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about poise, keeping your head and keeping your focus,''
Fassel said of his address to the team. ``I'll never stop getting
on them about that.''
</P>
<P>
   As an additional reminder, Fassel told his players _ who later
described Fassel's harangue as ``a lot of yelling and screaming'' _
that starting immediately, any fight would mean an extra 15 minutes
of sprints for the entire team at the end of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Two fights would mean an extra 30 minutes of end-of-practice
sprints, which are called gassers.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the extra work did not only apply to the combatants _ a
fight meant the whole team would run.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel got his message across. Tuesday, for the first time since
training camp opened, there were no fisticuffs in either the
morning or afternoon sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, players on both sides of the line were encouraging each
other, occasionally helping each other up off the ground. ``I liked
what I saw,'' Fassel said. ``And I liked what I didn't see.''
</P>
<P>
   Flare-ups by 300-pound players in full pads practicing under a
hot summer sun are hardly new to pro football. But in the context
of how the Giants' season ended last year _ with defensive players
engaged in hostile on-the-field quarrels as the team was
squandering a 9-point lead _ it was interesting to note how quickly
Fassel reacted when he spotted a flaw in his team's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings debacle, and the sight of players losing their cool
in the middle of the field on national television, is never too far
from Fassel's agenda. Fassel considered those squabbles evidence
that his young team showed a lack of maturity at a big moment. He
was convinced that several players lost their focus, helping to
create an atmosphere that led to the late-game collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Giants opened their 1997 season with a 1-3 record, a
time when they frequently argued with officials and with each other
during games, Fassel has emphasized that he wants his players to
show more poise. A year later, he is doing it again.
</P>
<P>
   According to Giants players, on Monday Fassel told the team: ``I
want a team that's feisty _ I don't want to curb your
aggressiveness _ but you have to be smart. There will be no more
fighting here in training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   The tussles in practice this week have been borne by the
dominance of the Giants' defense, a unit that is the team's
strength. Last year's Giants defense ranked seventh in the National
Football League, and it's no surprise that the Giants' offense,
which ranked 27th, has initially had trouble making yardage against
their defensive counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   This has bred frustration. Affecting the situation are the
feelings of several Giants defenders, who want the defense this
year to play with a certain cockiness. These Giants believe that in
1998 the defensive unit can take the next step and become one of
the elite defenses in the NFL. They have decided to start staking
that claim in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, it generated some ill-tempered, touchy moments on
the practice field. And Fassel addressed the brewing bad blood.
</P>
<P>
   Today was another steamy, humid day on the practice fields of
the SUNY-Albany campus. But the mood was different, with an
all-for-one feel. Every player kept his cool.
</P>
<P>
   The end-of-practice sprints were no longer than usual.
</P>
</TEXT>
