<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SURPRISE TOUGH PADRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Mets stare at the San Diego Padres and
they become envious. The Padres have a gigantic lead in the
National League West and are destined to play post-season games.
Any team other than the Yankees and the Braves should probably envy
them. The Mets wish they were as confident about their plans for
the future.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night the Mets eliminated their envy, at least for
one night, and felt confident about the present as they shocked one
of the best pitchers in baseball and defeated San Diego, 7-3, on a
humid evening at Shea Stadium. Andy Ashby had a 3-0 lead in his
quest to become the first 15-game winner in the major leagues, but
the plucky Mets forced him to unravel and started their pivotal
10-game homestand splendidly.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud's three-run homer, his 14th of the season, sparked a
four-run fifth inning. It came one pitch after manager Bobby
Valentine's decision to send two runners had helped the Mets avoid
what would have been an inning-ending double play. Instead, the
inning barely continued on the grounder to shortstop. Instead, the
Mets hung on to their lead behind a nail-biting bullpen and with
the help of another homer from Brian McRae.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these games are going to be like playoff games,'' Brian
McRae said. ``For the remainder of the season, if we stay in
contention or stay close, it's going to be like that. If we want to
get to the playoffs, we've got to treat them like playoff games.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine pinch-hit for Hideo Nomo in the fifth inning after he
had permitted three runs while striking out eight, and the Mets
needed a sturdy effort from their relievers. They received it.
</P>
<P>
   Four relievers followed Nomo and held the Padres scoreless, even
though San Diego had men in scoring position in all four innings.
Nomo (5-8) won his third start in a row and is 3-1 in nine outings
with the Mets. Ashby is now 14-6.
</P>
<P>
   Mets reliever Greg McMichael pitched one and two-third innings,
recorded his second save of the season and struck out Greg Vaughn
to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mets clinging to a 4-3 lead and two on and two out for
the Padres in the seventh, Dennis Cook was gutsy in a battle
against Ken Caminiti. After Caminiti fouled off three two-strike
pitches, Cook fired a fastball on the inside corner that left the
lethal hitter staring and shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of big pitching in that game and a lot of big
pitches,'' Valentine said. ``They're a good team. We were a good
team tonight, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Lopez added: ``This is a good team. When we play together,
things take care of itself. We're a good team. Watch out for the
Mets.''
</P>
<P>
   McRae helped the Mets relax by poking his 16th homer, and his
sixth in his last 17 games, in the seventh. He celebrated by
raising his arms in triumph as left the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets used smart strategy and expert execution to clobber
Ashby for their four runs in the fifth. After Luis Lopez's one-out
double to right-center field, Valentine inserted Bernard Gilkey as
a pinch-hitter for Nomo. Gilkey walked, and McRae then singled to
drive in Lopez and slice the Padres' lead to 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and second and a 3-2 count on Edgardo
Alfonzo, Valentine instructed Gilkey and McRae to move with the
pitch and it proved to be pivotal. Alfonzo grounded to shortstop
and the Padres just missed being able to turn a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being out of the inning, Ashby had to face Olerud
with runners on second and third, and Olerud sent the first pitch
into the right-field seats for a three-run blast that put the Mets
ahead, 4-3. Valentine's little dose of daring had kept the critical
inning alive.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo began the game by stranding two Padres in the first inning,
when he retired Wally Joyner on a fly ball. But he began the third
ominously by walking Ashby on four pitches. It was a mistake Nomo
would regret. After Quilvio Veras sacrificed Ashby to second, Tony
Gwynn did not give Nomo much of a chance to ponder the perilous
situation; Gwynn hammered the first pitch over the
right-center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   The ball sailed over the 371-foot mark, traveling a total of 378
feet, and gave the Padres a 2-0 lead. The shot also gave Gwynn two
homers in his last three at-bats against Nomo and 10 hits in 19
career at-bats off the right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo rebounded to strike out Ken Caminiti, who was the National
League's most valuable player in 1996, and Greg Vaughn, who might
be the MVP this season. It simply made the walk to Ashby more
mystifying.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth inning also started poorly for Nomo, as Joyner lashed
a ball into the Mets' bullpen for his ninth homer and the 1,000th
run batted in of his career. The second homer off Nomo in a span of
four batters gave the Padres a 3-0 cushion. Nomo left after the
fifth, which is when the Mets arrived and stopped being envious of
the Padres.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
