<HEADER>
A7452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LILCO-PAYMENTS-NYT     07-29 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LILCO-PAYMENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW COMPANY HURT BY SPECIAL LILCO PAYMENTS, EXECUTIVE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARMINGDALE, N.Y. _ The president of the newly formed Marketspan
company testified Tuesday that it has been seriously damaged by the
furor over the $67 million paid to executives of its predecessor,
Long Island Lighting Co.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning at a state legislative hearing here, the
president, Robert Catell, said that the dispute had dragged down
Marketspan's stock price, hurt staff morale, caused internal
tension, hurt the company's image and hampered its efforts to get
organized and expand.
</P>
<P>
   His comments placed on public display the turmoil and power
struggles that Marketspan has suffered since it was formed on May
28. When the state's Long Island Power Authority bought most of
LILCO's electricity service on that day, the rest of LILCO merged
with Brooklyn Union Gas and its holding company, Keyspan, to form
Marketspan.
</P>
<P>
   A week after the takeover and the merger, state officials
disclosed that LILCO had made special payments of $42 million to
its departing chairman, Dr. William Catacosinos, and $25 million to
25 other executives. They all assumed new jobs at Marketspan, with
Catacosinos as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Catell, who had been chairman of Brooklyn Union and Keyspan,
became president of the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Today's hearing, conducted by the State Assembly at the State
University at Farmingdale, gave a platform for the first public
statements on the payments by both Catell, who has been critical of
them since they were first disclosed, and his merger partner,
Catacosinos, who continues to defend them.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, who had pushed for the LILCO takeover to
enable an average 20 percent cut in the highest electricity rates
in the continental United States, has denounced the executive
payments as ``a secret act of greed.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor has demanded that Catacosinos return the money and
resign.
</P>
<P>
   Catacosinos said the payments were benefits that he and the
other executives were legally entitled to under their contracts. He
added that the payments had been publicly disclosed in advance,
although not the exact amounts.
</P>
<P>
   But Catell testified that he did not know about the payments
until Catacosinos informed him at a breakfast meeting on May 22,
five days before the secret LILCO board meeting at which they would
be approved. ``It came as quite a shock and a surprise to me,''
Catell said, especially since a LILCO executive had told Brooklyn
Union officials months earlier that there would be no executive
payments.
</P>
<P>
   He said he should have been notified sooner, and if he had known
he might have been able to change the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Catell said he opposed the payments because none of the LILCO
executives were losing their jobs but instead were automatically
getting new positions at Marketspan.
</P>
<P>
   He called an emergency meeting of the Brooklyn Union-Keyspan
board the day before the deal closed. It decided to go along with
the merger but insisted that Marketspan's new officers be appointed
only temporarily until the new board reviewed the issue of the
LILCO payments.
</P>
<P>
   Marketspan's board, which hired a law firm to study the problem,
will meet on Friday. Many politicians have joined Pataki's call for
Catacosinos' removal and are hoping for a showdown.
</P>
<P>
   But Catacosinos claims he has the support of major institutional
stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly doesn't put Marketspan, the new company, in the
positive light we would have hoped,'' Catell said of the dispute.
Marketspan's stock price has dropped more than a fourth, to 27 5/8
from 37 5/8, which he conceded ``is a very significant drop, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Catell expressed concern about the chill that the dispute has
placed on Marketspan's relationship with the Power Authority, which
is controlled by Pataki and which hired the company to run the old
LILCO system. ``Lipa is our largest single customer,'' Catell said,
``and obviously it's important to have a good working relationship
with our largest single customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on tensions at Marketspan, Catell said, ``It's
certainly strained at the upper levels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The morale of the former Keyspan officers is low,'' he added,
``based on a feeling they haven't been treated fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   And asked whether the company is troubled, Catell said: ``It's a
very fair statement. We have not advanced the company the way we
would have hoped. The stock price has suffered significantly, and
we have not been able to move forward aggressively as we had hoped.
Certainly the company has been negatively impacted.''
</P>
<P>
   Catacosinos argued that the payments should not be a concern to
the state since they came from stockholder funds and did not affect
the value of what the state took over.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the executive entitlements had been disclosed in
public filings over the years and that no one from the state
inquired about them.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded, however, that the exact amounts were never listed,
that the most significant number in calculating his benefits was
not decided until the very end and ``you would have to have an
actuary'' to figure out the amounts.
</P>
<P>
   He himself had a major disagreement with the LILCO board,
claiming he was entitled to $63 million instead of the $42 million
he settled for.
</P>
<P>
   As for his future, Catacosinos said, ``I have not made a
decision to resign.'' Asked if that meant he has decided against
resigning, he did not clarify. Asked if he would abide by the
Marketspan board's decision, he was noncommittal. ``Obviously we
will look at it,'' he said, ``and then we will make a
determination.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they are Marketspan's top two officials, the two came
and left here not as a team but separately, each accompanied by his
own set of aides.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting his turn to speak, Catacosinos slipped into the audience
during Catell's testimony. Catell, apparently unaware of
Catacosinos, departed along a side aisle, just a few seats away
from him. The two men did not greet each other or even exchange
glances.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Catell played down the significance of their separate
ways. ``We're both busy guys,'' he said. ``We have a big company to
run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
