u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-FURNITURE-SA     07-29 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-FURNITURE-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMENDMENT SEEKS TO DELAY RULES ON COMBUSTIBLE UPHOLSTERED
FURNITURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Va.)   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For nearly four years, the federal government's top
consumer agency has been working to fashion regulations to make
upholstered furniture more fire resistant. The agency, the Consumer
Product Safety Commission, acted after a group of fire marshals
filed a petition in 1994 that said fires from upholstered furniture
accounted for hundreds of household fire deaths in the nation each
year, many of them children.
</P>
<P>
   But this month a legislative rider suddenly appeared on a House
appropriations bill that would stop the commission from putting
rules into effect any time soon. The provision was inserted by Rep.
Roger Wicker, a Republican from Tupelo, Miss., which is known, with
some justification, as the upholstered furniture capital of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Wicker acted after consultations with the American Furniture
Manufacturers Association, which has asserted that there has not
been enough testing on the flame-retardant chemicals that its
members would be obliged to use to meet any new agency standards.
Wicker said the chemicals could be dangerous, even cancer-causing,
for both the people who will use the furniture over many years and
the factory workers who handle the chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the rules would raise the price of furniture,
furniture lobbyists said, and may make the upholstery stiffer and
less appealing.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates like Mary Ellen Fise, general counsel of
the Consumer Federation of America, said the furniture industry was
merely playing for time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about delays on an issue that clearly needs
action by the federal government,'' Ms. Fise said. ``We're talking
about a lot of deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fise said she believed that the furniture industry was
hoping that if it could delay any regulations for a few years, the
political composition of the consumer agency might change and the
costly regulations might never get adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a pitched political battle in Washington has involved
lobbyists for consumer groups, the furniture industry, fire
marshals and even major chemical companies. The combat has ranged
across the fiefs of several committee chairmen and has largely
occurred behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened here is clear and is something that happens
all too often in Washington,'' Ann Brown, chairwoman of the
consumer commission, said in an interview. ``The lobbyists came in
in the dark of night and inserted this horrendous language, which
is designed to delay the process of finding a way to prevent
hundreds of deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown who said more than 100 deaths occurred annually from
highly combustible upholstery and accused Wicker and the furniture
trade group of trying to sabotage her agency's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But Wicker insisted that his last-minute provision was not
intended to block rules to make upholstered furniture safer.
Rather, he said in an interview, he does not trust the consumer
agency to judge which chemicals are safe.
</P>
<P>
   About 100,000 workers make upholstered furniture in the United
States, the furniture makers trade association said, and Wicker's
office staff estimated that 30,000 were in his congressional
district, in northern Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   His rider would block the agency from proceeding with any
regulations until after extensive testing from the National
Institute of Environmental Health Sciences, a part of the National
Institutes of Health in Research Triangle Park, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Wicker's proposal would also require the agency to appoint a
panel of scientists to evaluate the issue for at least a year
before any action could be considered. Consumer groups estimate
that the requirements would delay any regulations until 2002,
although Wicker's staff contends that the delay will be less than
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Medford, an official at the consumer agency, said that
although both steps appeared reasonable, they duplicated work
already under way and that their only purpose was delay. Medford
said the agency had already enlisted the Environmental Protection
Agency to examine possible flame retardants.
</P>
<P>
   Wicker's rider was tacked on to a bill authorizing
appropriations for the Department of Veterans Affairs and the
Department of Housing and Urban Development, both of which have
nothing to do with consumer issues.
</P>
<P>
   The bill may be voted on this week, but the issue will probably
be fought again in the fall when the House and Senate versions must
be reconciled.
</P>
<P>
   As Wicker was moving to satisfy the furniture industry's
concern, the chemical industry, which is an even more powerful
lobby, informed their allies in Congress that they were eager to
have the federal government require furniture makers to buy the
flame-retardant chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical industry had a powerful ally of its own, Rep.
Thomas Bliley, R-Va., who heads the House Commerce Committee, which
has jurisdiction over the consumer agency, and whose district is
home to Albemarle Corp., a leading manufacturer of flame-retardant
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley agreed to allow the legislative rider to go forward as
long as the chemical industry's concerns were taken into account,
congressional aides said. One chemical industry lobbyist said a
compromise was worked out in a meeting in the Capitol on July 13
under which the chemical industry would not have to wait so long to
sell its products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
