<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYS-HEALTH-COMMISSIONER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., R.I.) 
</HEADLINE>
   DeBUONO TO DEPART AS N.Y. STATE HEALTH COMMISSIONER  
 (bl)  
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dr. Barbara DeBuono said Tuesday that she would step
down as the New York state commissioner of health, a position she
has held for nearly four years in a time of great change in the
state's health care system.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. DeBuono, 43, will become what amounts to the No. 3 executive
at New York Presbyterian Healthcare System, the new conglomeration
of 28 hospitals, nursing homes and other health care agencies
assembled around one of the nation's most prestigious medical
institutions, the New York and Presbyterian Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   She will stay in office virtually through the re-election
campaign of her boss, Gov. George Pataki, and begin her new job
Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Both blunt and politic, Dr. DeBuono was viewed in the
administration as a tough and loyal administrator who oversaw some
of the most ambitious initiatives of the Pataki administration. Her
critics complained that the initiatives were inspired too heavily
by the budgetary goals of the Pataki administration and that she at
times did not consult with advocates for patients and poor people
before making big decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Just after his election in 1994, Pataki lured Dr. DeBuono away
from her job as the top state health official in Rhode Island to
oversee what he described as one of his major goals: to enroll
millions of the people on Medicaid into managed care plans. She
also was charged with negotiating the governor's positions with the
Democrats in the Legislature earlier this year in a major expansion
of a program to provide health insurance to children.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, she oversaw the deregulation of the state's
hospitals and the rates they were paid.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. DeBuono will be leaving just as the Medicaid program begins
to enroll large numbers of people into managed care. While she
would not discuss her new salary, she said it was more than her
$152,000-a-year government salary. ``It was an opportunity that was
very hard to turn down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Pataki praised her as the state's first female
health commissioner and for showing ``consummate professionalism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 0032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
