<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-COLLAPSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE RETURN, ALMOST, OF TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, July 29:
</P>
<P>
   The blare of traffic is back. Sidewalks along Broadway are full
_ the usual mass of people buying, selling, gawking, pushing, all
at different speeds and in different directions. A small ark of
animals has been rescued from a building on 44th Street, including
12 cats, two illegal ferrets, several goldfish, one cockatiel, a
guinea pig, a gerbil and a hamster.
</P>
<P>
   Except for those areas in the shadow of the Conde Nast building,
where loose scaffolding caused part of an elevator tower to break
away a week ago, crashing into a residential hotel and killing an
elderly woman, Times Square is almost back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   With most of the city's crossroads reopened, and with the
breakaway scaffolding slowly being secured with what one television
reporter called ``our giant nylon stocking,'' this is a good time
to find out what really happened. Speculation is now focusing on
the possibility that beams holding the scaffolding to the building
on the 21st floor may not have been properly fastened by
contractors working on the facade. Workers often remove the beams
holding the elevator tower while they apply the facade. The
question is whether someone neglected to re-attach the beams or
whether they were somehow wrenched from the building in the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and insurance companies are now circling the site,
undoubtedly setting the stage for a number of lawsuits. The U.S.
Commerce Department, meanwhile, is investigating whether some of
the bolts used in the scaffolding are counterfeit. And the U.S.
Occupational Safety and Health Administration is looking at safety
issues.
</P>
<P>
   However, the primary responsibility for discovering causes of
the accident, and making sure that construction can safely proceed,
lies with New York City. City officials announced plans Tuesday to
hire an outside company that specializes in figuring out the causes
of construction accidents. That is a good start, but the city must
make certain that the report is finished quickly and used to help
prevent any similar accidents in this high-density area.
</P>
<P>
   At another hour and on a busier street, this accident could have
taken a far greater toll on human life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CAPITOL-SHOOTING     07-29 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAPITOL-SHOOTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: KEEPING THE CAPITOL SAFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, July 29:
</P>
<P>
   When tragedy strikes, it is natural for people to ask themselves
if there was any way it could have been averted. That is even more
true when the awful event takes place at a site as familiar and
freighted with symbolic import as the Capitol in Washington. Since
a gunman opened fire there last week, members of Congress have
offered suggestions for improving security that range from
requiring guards to wear bulletproof vests to building an
underground entrance where the public could be screened for
weapons. Fencing off the Capitol grounds is another frequently
mentioned option.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitol has developed a fairly extensive security apparatus
over the years, with additional protections often being added after
a violent incident. Visitors must walk through metal detectors, and
officers from the 1,200-member Capitol police force are everywhere.
Last week the gunman, Russell Weston Jr., was able to get only a
short way into the Capitol before he was brought down by police
gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it would be foolish to dismiss an incident in
which two officers died and gunshots reverberated through the halls
of Congress as proof that the system works. Lawmakers have an
obligation to conduct a thorough inquiry into how safety might be
improved.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the security searches at every door, the Capitol has an
air of openness and accessibility that members of Congress
rightfully treasure. It is impossible to walk past the White
House's tall fences, guard posts and traffic barriers without being
reminded that ours is a society that has learned to worry
constantly about the president's safety. But even though the
Capitol has seen sporadic violence, its crowded corridors,
meandering tourists and open lawns speak of a government of the
people. That is a symbol in itself, and one that should not be
given up lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's shooting has revived talk about creating an
underground entrance for tourists that would serve both as a
security stop-point and orientation center. Such a facility would
not necessarily prevent a disturbed gunman from trying to charge
past metal detectors, and shooting guards or tourists in the
process. But it would put the security clearance procedures well
away from the Capitol interior, where the proximity to members of
Congress and the actual House and Senate may incite a deranged
visitor with a grudge to action.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor center might also be helpful in giving tourists a
useful preparation for what they are going to see. The idea was
first proposed after a bombing incident in 1983, but was eventually
shelved due to objections to its cost. Some Republicans in Congress
are now suggesting that the center be paid for with private
donations.
</P>
<P>
   A commemorative coin issue has already raised almost $25 million
of the estimated $125 million construction price. But any idea of
collecting the rest from private donors should be dropped
immediately. The United States is certainly capable of coming up
with the money to provide security for the home of its legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-IRAQ-NYT &LR;      07-29 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HALLUCINATIONS ABOUT IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, July 29:
</P>
<P>
   Awash with money from Congress for covertly promoting Iraqi
opposition to Saddam Hussein, the Clinton administraton is once
again dreaming about engineering his ouster. The only problem is
that no one in Washington has figured out how to do so. Instead the
administration is preparing to renew its courtship with Massoud
Barzani, a Kurdish factional leader who betrayed Washington and
other opposition groups by forming a temporary military alliance
with Baghdad in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   There are no magic strategies for managing Saddam Hussein,
parrying his threats against neighboring countries and blocking his
efforts to develop mass-destruction weapons. That will take patient
diplomatic containment and occasional shows of American military
force. Washington should also overtly encourage credible opposition
forces that could one day rescue Iraq from the international
isolation, internal terror and blighted development hopes of the
Saddam Hussein era.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of covert operations is that they are relatively
cheap, do not require American troops and can proceed without
Washington's skeptical gulf war allies. In recent months, Congress
has pressed the administration to step up covert activity against
Baghdad. But Iraq's opposition groups are even more divided and
discredited now than in 1996, when Barzani invited Iraqi troops
into the Kurdish region to thwart a rival leader, Jalal Talibani.
The soldiers smashed the CIA's operations center and executed
opposition activists. Yet for want of a better alternative,
Washington has invited Barzani, along with Talibani, to new
planning talks.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious internal opposition to Saddam Hussein comes
from Iranian-backed Shiite groups in southern Iraq, from which the
United States keeps a healthy distance. The Iraqi National
Congress, which Washington once hoped would create a broad-based
opposition, has little remaining support. Iraqi military officers,
meanwhile, are understandably reluctant to plot against Saddam
Hussein without clearer promise of American military backing than
Washington is prepared to offer. The United States should learn
from past mistakes and steer clear of covert operations in Iraq. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
