<SLUG> BC-SWIM-GOODWILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOMEN SWIMMERS TROUNCE CHINESE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST MEADOW, N.Y. _ The world's fastest women's swimming team
represents the United States. If China has faster swimmers, they
stayed at home and missed Tuesday night's Goodwill Games debacle in
which the Americans ran away with their rare dual meet, 88-34.
</P>
<P>
   This was an old-fashioned grudge match, at least for the
Americans. They believe the Chinese women won 12 of the 16 gold
medals in the 1994 world championships because they had used banned
bodybuilding drugs. With random drug testing, the international
federation has clamped down on the offenders, and in January's
world championships in Australia the American women won eight gold
medals, the Chinese three.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the Americans and the Chinese met in 14 events. But only
17-year-old Yen Chan _ a world champion and world record-holder _
and 16-year-old Xue Han were here from China's 1996 Olympic team,
and most of their teammates here were just as young and less
experienced.
</P>
<P>
   The tone for this meet was set in the first event, the 400-meter
medley relay. The Americans won by almost half the length of the
50-meter pool in the new Nassau County Goodwill Games Swimming and
Diving Center.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the near-capacity crowd at the 1,700-seat pool watched
the Americans win 11 events. Each team had two swimmers in each of
the 12 individual events, and the Americans finished 1-2 in eight
of them. That was especially impressive because the Americans are
preparing for their national championships in two weeks, and some
are not fully rested.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive performances came from Cristina Teuscher, a
20-year-old Columbia University junior from New Rochelle, N.Y., and
Jenny Thompson, a 25-year-old Stanford graduate from Dover, N.H.
Teuscher set a Goodwill Games and personal record for the 200-meter
freestyle, winning by 15 feet in 1 minute 59.63 seconds. Then she
won the 400-meter freestyle by 10 meters in 4:12.16.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a world champion, won the 50-meter freestyle in 25.77
seconds, beating her teammate Ashley Tappin by a hundredth of a
second, or less than an inch. Then she beat Tappin in the 100-meter
freestyle in 55.56 seconds, a Goodwill record. Then she, Teuscher
and Tappin swam on the U.S. team that set a Goodwill record of
3:43.98 in the 4x100-meter freestyle relay.
</P>
<P>
   Before the meet, Thompson expressed how she and her teammates
felt about the Chinese drug issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're on the blocks,'' she said, ``it's not an issue.
They are our competitors. We have to beat them. All we can do is
race.''
</P>
<P>
   They certainly did that Tuesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
