<HEADER>
A7468 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-BASS-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      07-29 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BASS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASS FANS FINALLY GET A NOVEL FROM THE FORMER HOUSTONIAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  ``WHERE THE SEA USED TO BE''; By Rick Bass (Houghton Mifflin, $25) 
 
By MICHAEL BERRYHILL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Houstonian Rick Bass has had plenty of preparation for
writing his first novel, publishing 11 volumes of personal essays,
short stories and environmental tales, all dominated by his urgent,
passionate and vulnerable voice.
</P>
<P>
   Bass is a man we feel we know. We know about his Texas
upbringing from ``The Deer Pasture,'' a book about an annual family
deer hunt in the Hill Country. From his book ``Oil Notes'' we know
how he courted his wife, Elizabeth, making her BLT sandwiches in a
park, using a microwave he carried in his car trunk for weeks while
looking for an opportunity to ask her for a seemingly casual date.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Winter'' we know how he and Elizabeth moved to the Yaak
Valley, in the far northwestern corner of Montana near the Canadian
border, and how Bass at last found his home and vowed never to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   And we know how much he loves the wilderness, and understands
it, from his books about the Yaak Valley and wolves and grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   If Bass never wrote a line of fiction, his literary reputation
would be secure in his essays and memoirs. Yet he has also
persisted in writing short stories, with his most ambitious ones
collected in ``Platte River.'' But a major literary reputation
(though reputation is not, assuredly, what drives Bass) can
scarcely be built on short stories. We demand the big thing, and it
was inevitable that Bass would persist, like a man building a rock
wall in the forest, hauling a truckload of boulders a day,
insisting that he eventually would get it built.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent reading, Bass said he took 14 years and made eight
major revisions before he had a novel worth publishing, and the
effort was sometimes humiliating. After what he thought was the
final and best revision, his editor and agent told him to try
again, and he wondered whether he knew any longer what writing was
about.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort, on his part, and the wait, on his readers' part,
have been worth it. With ``Where the Sea Used to Be Bass'' has
almost single-handedly created North American magical realism, part
Paul Bunyan, part Herman Melville, and all of it solidly,
believably his.
</P>
<P>
   Texas readers will recognize Old Dudley, the obsessed Houston
oil geologist who is the driving force of the novel. Nearing the
end of his life and plenty rich, Old Dudley wants nothing more than
to find oil in a remote Montana valley where he has already punched
18 dry holes.
</P>
<P>
   Having burned up one young geologist in his quest, he recruits
another, sending him to map the valley again and to befriend his
estranged daughter, a biologist who has been tracking the
activities of a pack of wolves for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Old Dudley is a mix of Glenn McCarthy, Hugh Roy Cullen and
Michel Halbouty, with a lot of wolverine thrown in, and Bass has
made him both perfectly recognizable and comically exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   He is Bass' Ahab in a book that deserves comparison to
Melville's symbolic epic about a hunt for a white whale. Like Ahab,
Dudley has only one name, and, like Ahab, he has his humanity. This
is a mythic novel, and in myth, all the forces, voices, demons and
urges a person can have become characters, and we watch these
characters act as though impelled on iron rails, to use Ahab's
description of why he must kill the white whale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the Sea Used to Be'' is about hunting of all sorts. In a
brilliant set piece near the end of the book, the two geologists
embark on a two-week-long epic elk hunt in which they nearly die.
Mel, Old Dudley's daughter, hunts wolves, but only for information
about their lives. Wallis, the new geologist who falls in love with
Mel, hunts for oil. His technology is mapping, studying the
formations above the ground in order to imagine the structure
beneath the earth, where the sea used to be, where organic material
has been trapped under pressure and turned into oil.
</P>
<P>
   As with most myths, the structure is simple: A vulnerable hero
is sent into a mythical place, a valley like the Yaak Valley, and,
aided by various figures, retrieves some magical thing that will
heal the wounded world he has left behind. The basic plot is so
well-known that Hollywood script writers are required to consult it
as formula.
</P>
<P>
   So the magic lies not in plot but in our recognition of what is
eternal and in details, the things Mel knows about wolves, for
instance, and how people of the valley pull together against the
forces of the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   In the isolation of the valley, people are freed to become fully
themselves, which is to say fully obsessed. An isolated carpenter,
for example, lovingly creates painted coffins in sculptural animal
shapes for every person who lives in the valley. Shades of
Queequeg, building his own buoyant coffin that will save Ishmael at
the end of ``Moby Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   As does Melville, Bass offers a good deal of realistic detail.
You can learn the fundamentals of hunting for oil or elk, just as
you can learn the fundamentals of hunting whales from Melville. But
such information is transformed alchemically into spiritual
knowledge. Eventually, Mel quits tracking the wolves and starts
teaching what she knows to the children. It is a change that she
doesn't really think about. She just does it.
</P>
<P>
   For this is not a book about what people think, as in, say,
Richard Ford's ``Independence Day,'' but a book about what people
do. There is no internal psychology here, little pondering and
weighing of motive, little rumination on what it all means. These
are characters who are taking action for better or for worse and
who are seeking how to live and how to die when that is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The act of mapping for oil, a geologist assures me, is just like
writing a book. You are hoping to find something down there, but
you don't know where it is, and you need all the data you can get
in order to make a good guess. Sometimes you can make a map as good
as you can make it, believe in it completely and get a dry hole, as
Wallis does. Or you can figure out the history of geology and
evolution and declare unequivocally, as Old Dudley does, that man
belongs at the top and deserves to dominate the earth and
everything on it. Such maps, no matter how carefully and rationally
created, can be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the Sea Used to Be'' does what a great myth does; it
maps the human psyche of a man we have come to know, Rick Bass:
geologist, naturalist, lover, hunter, lover of the wildest places
of all, in the human heart, brains and guts.
</P>
<P>
   For all its mythological structure, this book is deeply
personal. Bass is a fabulist, a brave but necessary choice, it
seems, in a world that is being devoured by our obliviousness to
its inherent beauty and mystery.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
