<HEADLINE>
BOB HOPE MAKES MORE MEMORIES WITH STARBUCKS VISIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- An elderly gentleman at a Starbucks counter
quietly sipped a small black coffee-of-the-day -- and made everyone
else's day.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hope arrived Tuesday morning in a white sport-utility
vehicle and waited on a bar stool at the window counter while his
driver got him a small drip coffee and a pastry.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed comfortably for a hot day in cream-colored slacks and
matching button-down shirt, the legendary comedian noshed and
sipped while heads started to turn his way.
</P>
<P>
   Soon one customer asked for Hope to autograph a brown paper bag.
Another placed a comic strip hastily torn from the morning
newspaper in front of the 95-year-old entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought you'd get a laugh from this, after all the laughs
you've given us,'' the man said to Hope, who read the comic and
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of Hope's 20-minute visit to the suburban Sherman
Oaks coffeehouse, just about everyone had figured out that a legend
was in the joint.
</P>
<P>
   As Hope and his driver rose to leave, four men sitting at a
couple of tables put down their coffee and newspapers to break into
a spontaneous and heartfelt rendition of Hope's theme song, first
introduced in ``The Big Broadcast of 1938,'' his 1934 film debut.
</P>
<P>
   It was a little off-key, but the words rang through the room:
``Thanks for the memories . . .''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
