<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINANT PITCHING KEYING YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Twenty or so years from now, when baseball
historians reflect on 1998, there's a good chance they'll declare
it the Year of the Home Run.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire and Ken Griffey Jr. have seen to that.
</P>
<P>
   The current members of the New York Yankees will probably have
cause to smirk and plea for some revisionism.
</P>
<P>
   The Year of ``The Pitching Staff,'' offers Darryl Strawberry,
their most potent slugger to date _ with a paltry 16 homers.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are bucking convention in the American League,
building their fortunes on their starting pitchers and not
troubling themselves over the fact they have no particular big gun
in the heart of their lineup. And yet their success is astonishing:
a record of 74-26 following Tuesday night's pounding of the Angels
at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have those types of players here. We don't have big
home run hitters,'' said manager Joe Torre. ``This ballclub is more
of a line-drive, contact-type team. More of a productive team. We
get a lot of walks. We put the ball in play. We don't sit around
and wait for one guy to do something....
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a pitching staff like ours, you don't
necessarily have to think in big terms.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees prefer to think microscopic _ as in 3.38, the
combined ERA of starters David Cone, Andy Pettitte, David Wells,
Hideki Irabu and Orlando Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing against the guys having success hitting home runs,
chasing records,'' said Strawberry, New York's designated hitter
and occasional left fielder, ``but you've got to be realistic about
what teams are, and the intentions of winning and going to
postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that (a formidable home run threat) going to get you to
where you have to get? Normally, it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball might be fascinated with the exploits of McGwire and
Griffey, who had combined for 85 home runs. But their teams, St.
Louis and Seattle, have also combined for a .462 winning percentage
_ 278 points behind that of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're winning through different ways,'' said catcher Joe
Girardi. ``It's not typical of Yankee teams. You think of bombers.
But I think this is more exciting for the players.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't really happen by design, in that the pitching has
exceeded its reasonable expectations and the power hitting has
fallen short of its forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Tino Martinez hit 44 home runs with 141 RBI last
year, but he is nowhere near that homer pace now (14 homers, 78
RBI). Meanwhile, Chili Davis, who had 30 home runs with Kansas City
last year before signing with the Yankees as a free agent, has been
out since the first week of the season after suffering an ankle
injury that required reconstructive surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Torre says he feels Martinez's current output is closer to what
should be expected of him, and the career stats bear him out
(Martinez had averaged 22 homers per year over his previous seasons
with Seattle and New York).
</P>
<P>
   As for the starters, with the exception of Pettitte, it would
have been difficult to imagine they'd perform as they have.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Cone (15-3, 3.33):!off! In '97, one year after overcoming
surgery to remove an aneurysm in his right arm, he broke down
again. Cone suffered an injury to his throwing shoulder that
ultimately knocked him out of the playoffs and required surgery at
season's end. How much was left in that arm at age 35?
</P>
<P>
   Plenty, apparently. ``He wasn't ready to say, `I'm getting
older, maybe I can't do this anymore,'' said Girardi. Cone, indeed,
has impressed the Yankees not only with his effectiveness but his
staying power. He has worked seven innings or more in 10 of his
last 11 starts.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Pettitte (13-6, 3.70):!off! The ace of New York's staff
last year got off to a rough beginning in '98, compiling a 6-5
record and 4.88 ERA through May. Pettitte later admitted that his
mind wasn't entirely on baseball but on his wife, who was home in
Texas preparing to give birth to their second child.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Irabu (9-4, 3.19):!off! He had a rocky indoctrination to
American baseball in '97, putting up a 7.09 ERA despite striking
out 56 in 531/3 innings. Girardi says Irabu is more ``relaxed''
this year, and it's evident in the production. This is more what
the Yankees anticipated when they agreed to part with promising
outfielder Ruben Rivera to pry Irabu's rights away from San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Wells (12-2, 3.68):!off! It happens now and then _ an
aging warhorse of a pitcher puts up a career season when least
expected. Wells, who turned 35 in May and has never been mistaken
for a fitness enthusiast, was 27-24 with a 4.68 ERA over the last
two years, which were split between Baltimore and New York. And now
this?
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Hernandez (5-2, 2.43):!off! Like Irabu, he was something
of an unknown quantity _ just from a different country. After
defecting from Cuba, Hernandez has made so smooth a transition to
the American pro game that he bumped Ramiro Mendoza out of the
rotation and is impressing observers with his array of pitches and
his savvy.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the adversity he went through (in getting out of
Cuba),'' said Girardi, ``anything he experiences on the mound is
going to be minuscule.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre knows only to accept the prosperity of this staff. And
appreciate it profoundly. When reminded that his team is brazenly
defying baseball fashion _ 12 teams have hit more home runs than
his Yankees _ he said only, ``Good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you pitch well,'' Torre went on, ``that means less runs
win the game. We try to think small. It's a lot easier to go into a
slump when you're sitting around waiting for a three-run home run
than when you're trying to manufacture something.''
</P>
<P>
   Take it from a team that has required only 100 games to
manufacture 74 wins. &UR; !dlim!!end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
