<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETBACK HAS YOUNG SITTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; PHILADELPHIA _ Second baseman Eric Young did not come off the
disabled list Tuesday after experiencing tightness in his strained
left thigh muscle over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Young, among the league leaders with 33 stolen bases despite
being sidelined on four separate occasions, did some light running
Tuesday but probably won't be back until Friday, when the Dodgers
open a four-game series against the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping he can be back by then, but we're really going to
have to wait and see,'' manager Glenn Hoffman said. ``He had been
coming along well but had a setback on Friday when he tried to push
it a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said he wasn't holding Young out because of the
artificial surface at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who is in the first season of a four-year, $18.5 million
contract, was mentioned in trade speculation in Toronto. But the
Dodgers denied the report, which had Young headed to the Blue Jays
for pitcher Juan Guzman, a former Dodgers minor-leaguer who has
struggled recently. Guzman is earning $5 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   A player cannot be traded when he is on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Worry about Valdes: Although Ismael Valdes is scheduled to
miss only two starts while on the disabled list for a strained left
side, there is concern the injury could keep him out a few weeks
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, injured while pitching in Sunday's 5-3 Dodgers victory
against Arizona, does not have arm problems. But side injuries can
throw off pitching mechanics, which can lead to arm injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's back in L.A. working with (physical therapist) Pat
Screnar and we should know better where we stand in a week,''
trainer Charlie Strasser said. ``We'll see how he is responding to
treatment. Could it be longer? It all depends on how he responds.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Judd for now: Right-hander Mike Judd, scheduled to start
Saturday in place of Valdes, has had his own physical problems this
season. He started the season at Triple-A Albuquerque and went 1-7.
For the first month, Judd, 27, suffered from the flu and lost most
of the velocity on his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   He rebounded to win his last four decisions, but the team is
looking at him as a spot starter until a pitcher is acquired before
Friday's trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a guy pitch as sick as he was,'' said Hoffman,
Albuquerque's manager until June 22, when he replaced Bill Russell.
``For the longest time he just didn't get better. But when he
finally recovered, he pitched very well for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Judd, one of the pitchers former executive vice president Fred
Claire protected in last November's expansion draft, also will
pitch Thursday in Montreal if a trade is not made.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Local guy: Westlake High product Mike Lieberthal was placed
on the 15-day disabled list last Friday by the Phillies, but he
could be there a lot longer. Lieberthal, the Phillies' starting
catcher, suffered a stress fracture to the pelvic region, which
makes it difficult to squat or run or even walk.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies are using the injury to look at rookie catcher
Bobby Estalella, who was called up when Lieberthal went on the DL.
Estalella came into Tuesday's game with four hits in eight at-bats
in his first two games. Against the Dodgers, he batted fifth and
went 1 for 4 with a double.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance if Estalella plays well the rest of the
season, the Phillies could trade Lieberthal during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Quick hits: Wilton Guerrero is hot at the plate but not
exactly a classic leadoff hitter. He entered the game with 11 hits
in his past 20 at-bats, but his first-inning walk was just first in
26 games and 100 at-bats.... Catcher Charles Johnson is expected to
rejoin the team today after his wife, Rhonda, gave birth to the
couple's first child in Los Angeles.... Phillies first baseman Rico
Brogna went 2 for 5 with an RBI single. He entered the game 8 for
12 against the Dodgers this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
