<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-BLUE-JAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS, BLUE JAYS DOWN RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ It appeared to be a double-play ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   A form of the word ``appears'' often serves as a disclaimer on
any ground ball put into play toward the Rangers' infielders these
days.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, of course, failed to record an out, and the Blue
Jays erased a rare, three-run deficit for right-hander Roger
Clemens and beat their struggling visitors, 8-3, last night at
SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we turn that double play in the second inning,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said, ``who knows where the ballgame goes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who have lost four in a row, know the direction it
took.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who pitched despite a temperature in excess of 100
degrees and symptoms of the flu, surrendered three runs in the
first two innings. That represented more than the Rangers scored
during 32 innings against the four-time Cy Young Award recipient in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it would go to waste.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers third baseman Fernando Tatis and second baseman Mark
McLemore botched a potential inning-ending, double-play grounder
off the bat of third baseman Ed Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Aaron Sele (12-8) then surrendered a single to
shortstop Alex Gonzalez, a run-scoring walk to left fielder Tony
Phillips and a two-run single to outfielder Shawn Green.
</P>
<P>
   Tatis fielded Sprague's grounder cleanly, but his high-and-wide
throw pulled McLemore off the bag. McLemore caught the ball, but it
fell from his glove as he attempted to touch the bag with his left
foot and throw simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't work,'' said McLemore, who was given the error on
the play.
</P>
<P>
   Sele also shared in the blame for not minimizing the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to deal with the situation at hand,'' said Sele,
who will enter his scheduled start Sunday with a 4-6 record and
6.62 earned-run average during his past 12 appearances. ``It's my
job to get another double-play ground ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates dismissed Tatis' throw as the inconsistency with which a
manager lives with a young player in the lineup.Clemens (13-6) took
advantage of the mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who allowed run-scoring groundouts to left fielder
Rusty Greer and designated hitter Lee Stevens and a run-scoring
double to Tatis in the first two innings, surrendered only a single
and issued two walks during the next four innings despite being
ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes him one of the great pitchers,'' Sele said.
``That's what separates the great pitchers from the good ones. He
just figures out a way to win. If you told him to go out and throw
the ball left-handed, he'd figure out a way to beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprague and Gonzalez ignited the Blue Jays' three-run sixth
inning with a one-out double and a run-scoring single,
respectively, on weakly hit balls. Right fielder Jose Canseco later
laced a two-run double that gave the Jays a 6-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays manager Tim Johnson removed Clemens after his 99th
pitch with two runners aboard and two outs during the seventh
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going on,'' said Clemens, who vomited
shortly before his first pitch. ``My temperature has been going
crazy. I was laboring out there all night long. It was a tough game
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays' final two runs crossed the plate on an
eighth-inning, inside-the-park home run by center fielder Shannon
Stewart, who replaced Canseco during the seventh inning. On the
play, Greer missed a diving attempt for Stewart's sinking liner.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers had decided the outcome well before then.
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least it appeared that way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
