<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS WORK ON HYDRATION TO BEAT THE HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ As the temperature was pushing toward triple
digits, Michael Sinclair was pushing his way past another 325-pound
tackle.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes earlier, the Seahawks' Pro Bowl defensive end had
been dropping 10 yards off the line to provide blanket coverage and
force an incompletion to a tight end in the end zone. A few minutes
later, he would be running wind sprints at the end of another
training-camp practice.
</P>
<P>
   In between, however, Sinclair made his way to one of the water
caddies stationed around the practice field. Sinclair didn't just
drink, he squirted water onto his sweat-drenched face and hosed
down his steaming shaved head.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get this far, you're not just a top athlete, you're a
commodity,'' Sinclair said later. ``Water for me is like oil for a
racing car. I need that or I'm going to burn my engine out.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this is not the Eastern Washington University
training camps of the late 1970s and early '80s that were ruled
with a clenched fist and an even tighter jaw by Jack Patera, the
team's first coach who banned water from the practice field.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the players are not only urged to drink, they're prodded to
replenish lost fluids.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question there's a conditioning effect training in this
heat,'' strength and conditioning coach Dana LeDuc said. ``But you
have to be smart about it. The main thing is hydration, and our
trainers have done a great job of educating the players and then
making sure that there's water at every turn _ coming on the field,
off the field; on the field; at the dining hall; in the dorms.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Sperber, the team's assistant trainer, ordered 350 cases of
Gatorade before camp started, and had to endure barbs about being
on the company's payroll. Well, another 350 cases of the stuff was
delivered Tuesday, along with 350 cases of bottled water to replace
the 350 that already have been consumed.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that might last us another week,'' head trainer Jim
Whitesel said of the new shipment.
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair estimates that he alone was responsible for draining
three cases of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are drinking fluids like crazy. You have to,'' Sinclair
said. ``Last year, I was like, `Ah, I don't feel like drinking.' I
cramped up. This year, I've been hitting the fluids and I've had no
problems. You live and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   And drink.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing fluids actually began during the team's offseason
conditioning program, when Sperber offered hydration seminars.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to be working. Despite practicing 16 times in
96-degree-plus heat during the first nine days of camp, there have
been only two cases of leg cramps _ rookie running back Ahman Green
and reserve fullback Oscar Gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of a lot of things,'' LeDuc said of the
lack of cramping and other dehydration problems. ``It's the fact
that the players worked extremely hard in the offseason. It's that
they're continuing to work hard here. But a big part of it is
stressing hydration.''
</P>
<P>
   Patera, coach for the first 6{ years of the franchise, drew a
lot of heat for his no-water edict. And the day Patera surprised
his troops with Popsicles on the practice field in 1982 is a
cornerstone of the team's training camp lore.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the norm in those days. It was then considered a
training benefit to subject players to rigorous workouts without
allowing them to drink water during practice. Honing mental
toughness, and all that macho stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really surprised somebody didn't die in those days,''
Sperber said, ``because your body will shut down without water.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Brown remembers that, if not fondly, at least with a sense
of pride. One of the original Seahawk players, Brown now coaches
the team's defensive backs and remains the only Seahawk cornerback
ever voted to the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing. I remember it being hot, and there was no
water on the field _ (begin ital) no water (end ital),'' Brown
said. ``I also remember being very thirsty at times and having
unbelievable cotton mouth. We chewed a lot of gum.''
</P>
<P>
   But they never drank water on the practice field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
