<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-LOPEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOPEZ MAKES MOST OF HIS VARIOUS CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In spring training of 1997, the San Diego Padres
traded Luis Lopez to the Houston Astros. Fifteen days later, the
Astros traded Lopez to the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of confused,'' Lopez recalled on Tuesday night.
``Definitely I was confused. It took me a little time to settle
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, with whom Lopez began his professional and major
league careers, are the ones who needed settling on Tuesday night
after Lopez played a pivotal role in the Mets' 7-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   With the Padres ahead, 3-0, and Andy Ashby having thoughts of
becoming the first 15-game winner in the majors, Lopez drilled a
fifth-inning double that ignited a four-run outburst. Two innings
later he beat out an infield grounder for a single and scored on
Brian McRae's home run. Then, in the eighth inning, he singled home
the Mets' final run. Not a bad night's work for a utility player
filling in for the ailing Rey Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lose Rey Ordonez and Luis steps in and does the job,''
Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``It's great to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets acquired Lopez in a trade of convenience. Tim Bogar
wasn't going to make the team that spring, and he was out of
options. Lopez had options left and could easily be sent to the
minor leagues. Gerry Hunsicker, the Astros' general manager, had
been with the Mets and liked Bogar. Joe McIlvaine, then the Mets'
general manager, had been the San Diego general manager and liked
Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets didn't think enough of Lopez to rush him to the
majors after Ordonez broke his hand June 1. First they made Manny
Alexander the shortstop, but he tore cartilage in his right knee.
Then they declared Shawn Gilbert the shortstop, but before he had a
chance to make his first start, he came down with a staph infection
in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Lopez, whose right knee was healthy, became the
substitute shortstop. ``It was confusing,'' Lopez said, sitting at
his locker in the Mets' Latin quarter. ``But that's past. I was
ready. I just waited for my time. I worked my way back.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Puerto Rican, who looks younger than his 27 years, is
confused this season, it's only because he has to remember where to
head when he goes on the field. A utility infielder before this
season, he has started games in left field and right field as well
as at second base, shortstop and third base.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have even asked him to play winter ball this year so he
can gain more experience in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luis asks people what his best position is,'' related Omar
Minaya, the Mets' assistant general manager. ``I told him his best
position is where they put him every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez has started the past four games in place of Ordonez, who
strained an abdominal muscle in the first game of a doubleheader in
Chicago last Friday. His temporary starting role, however, doesn't
alter his routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take pride in my job,'' he said. ``I go early to the ball
park and take my grounders at third, short and second and then go
to the outfield and work out there, too. My job is to be a
defensive player.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lopez contributes, too, offensively. His performance against
the Padres was his fourth three-hit game of the season, and it
raised his average to .280 in 78 games and 175 times at bat. His
first hit on Tuesday night was especially critical. ``He was my
teammate in San Diego when I played there,'' Lopez said of Ashby,
who began the game with the third lowest earned run average (2.49)
in the National League. ``He's a very competitive guy, one of the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   After striking out Todd Hundley with two on and two out in the
first inning, Ashby looked like he was going to be tough to catch.
But then Lopez rapped the hit that prompted Ashby to begin to
unravel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got a good pitch to hit,'' Lopez said. ``He threw me a
fastball inside, then he threw another fastball over the middle of
the plate. I think he was going to bust me in and the ball just
stayed out in the middle. I got pretty good wood on it.''
</P>
<P>
   That he lined that pitch to right-center field for a double,
then added a pair of singles was satisfying enough. But to do it
against the Padres added the chocolate icing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good feeling,'' he acknowledged, ``but that's past. I'm
looking forward to tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
