<SLUG> BC-GOLF-SAHALEE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAHALEE ERECTING `THREE-RING CIRCUS' FOR UPCOMING PGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELLIS CONKLIN AND ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND Wash. _ The serenity of Sahalee Country Club has been
shattered.
</P>
<P>
   The gentle murmur of geese fluttering overhead and golf balls
plunking off towering Douglas firs have yielded to the sound of
hammers, saws and drills.
</P>
<P>
   A city is emerging, a lavish tent city springing up between the
fairways.
</P>
<P>
   This City on the Course is complete with 23 TV-camera towers,
1,200 phone lines, 9,000 grandstand seats, 31 air-conditioned
corporate chalets, 300 toilets, 5,000 pounds of salmon and shrimp
and more than $48,000 worth of hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget the 1,500 kegs of beer on order, or the
five-plus miles of chain-link fence that now surrounds the wooded
course. Or the 100-by-215-foot structure built to hold 1,000
members of the national and worldwide media.
</P>
<P>
   This is no ordinary event.
</P>
<P>
   The weeklong 80th PGA Championship that begins Aug. 10 has been
in the making for a solid two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a circus. It's many circuses. This is a
three-ring circus of major proportions,'' said Richard MacIntosh,
Sahalee's assistant vice chairman for marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot help but be impressed and amazed.''
</P>
<P>
   Most impressive is the level of intricate detail involved in
this mammoth undertaking. Marketing plans had to be devised,
security plans concocted, transportation schemes worked through.
Nearly 600 people had to be hired, and several training sessions
scheduled for the more than 2,500 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In coming to Sahalee for the first time, and holding a major
championship for the first time (in the Northwest in more than) 50
years, we've got one shot to do this thing right,'' said PGA
tournament director Andy Odenbach.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA staff has secured contracts with hundreds of vendors.
Many of them are local, like Gretchen's Of Course, a catering
service north of Boeing Field that is leasing out its
23,000-square-foot kitchen to the PGA.
</P>
<P>
   Food will be shuttled in refrigerated trucks, much of it being
delivered to the 3,300 people who will be reveling inside those
corporate chalets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of hospitality (in the chalets) will be unequaled.
Beyond the Super Bowl,'' said Mike Kalian, who chairs the marketing
committee. ``There's linens, flowers, landscaping, plush carpeting
and decks with covered verandas. And we'll be doing beanies and
weeners to lobster and Dom (Perignon).''
</P>
<P>
   The guts of the operation flow from a vast army of some 2,500
volunteers who will be continually on the move. These are serious
golf junkies for the most part _ many of them retirees or junior
golfers _ who paid $155 to the PGA to be part of the action. You
won't miss them in their striped white, navy and wine-colored
shirts and stone-colored slacks and skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has been left to chance. Some 1,000 volunteers will be
marshaling the course, keeping spectators in their proper places
and clearing paths between holes for the players to pass through.
</P>
<P>
   Another 350 volunteers are assigned to the 13,000-square-foot
PGA Golf Shop where 47,976 hats ($11 to $25) will be on sale, along
with 20,680 golf balls and thousands of jackets and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   The 40,000 pounds of merchandise are being warehoused at Lincoln
Moving &AMP; Storage in Kent. Susan Hickman, who handles the retail
efforts for the PGA, figures it will take five moving vans to get
all the goods to Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   Another 250 volunteers are charged with meeting the 156 PGA
players at the airport, getting them to their hotels and assisting
them in picking up the brand-new Oldsmobile the PGA customarily
provides each player free of charge during the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, 40 Sahalee groundskeepers have spent months
raking bunkers, mowing fairways and chiseling greens down to a
linoleum-hard [-inch. And Craig Rogers has been meeting with his
caddies committee. It's up to him and his crew of 18 to secure the
bag room, take care of the caddies' credentials and collect and
distribute the bibs that the caddies will wear during the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bob McFaddin, a Sahalee club member, is overseeing a
group of 64 adult volunteers who will be supervising a litter
patrol of 100 teenagers. They call it the ecology committee.
Anything that doesn't make it into the 500 garbage bags posted
across the course and fastened to metal tripods is up to McFaddin's
troupe.
</P>
<P>
   It seems they have formed a team for just about everything.
There's a crew devoted to providing refreshments at the tee, a team
of 80 walking scorers, along with a leaderboard squad and a platoon
of greenside reporters who will stand inside the ropes recording
hole-by-hole scores with hand-held computers.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a group of volunteers assigned to keeping order in
the gallery, and another cast overseeing the 150 golf carts that
will be whizzing around.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there is Bob Kelliher. He is the locker room chairman. He
has 15 people charged with showing the players where their lockers
are, suggesting good places to dine, taking their messages and
keeping their shoes shined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to make them happy,'' Keliher said.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Bain, a Sahalee real estate agent, co-chairs the player
accommodations committee. She has been working for more than a year
lining up homes for the couple of dozen players _ most of them with
families _ who plan to stay at private houses rather than at nearby
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Bain said the house hunters are willing to pay Sahalee residents
around $3,000 for the week for the use of their home. For security
reasons, none of the residents, Bain added, are allowed to disclose
the name of the pro golfer using their dwelling until the
tournament is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most of the people renting out their homes plan to use
the money for furniture or a vacation trip,'' Bain said.
</P>
<P>
   Sahalee general manager Tom Halsey said that meticulous
preparation has been a prelude to the rapid deployment going on
now. ``The past three years have been drudgery. The past 3{ weeks
have been great fun,'' he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   If all is done well, MacIntosh doesn't believe many of the
25,000 spectators will even realize the effort it took to put the
tournament together.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not going to notice the facility,'' he said. ``They
are going to notice that it is a great event.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
