<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAREW NO STREAKS FAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Hitting coach Rod Carew now shares the Angels
club record for longest hitting streak at 25 consecutive games with
Garret Anderson, who singled in the ninth inning Tuesday to tie the
mark. It is the longest streak in the majors this season.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra of the Red Sox hit in 24 straight.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Garret Anderson putting together a run for the record,
Carew said he isn't one to get excited about hitting streaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't mean much to me,'' said Carew, a seven-time batting
champion. ``I would rather get a bunch of hits in a short span of
time than a long hitting streak with 1 for 4's and 1 for 5's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes if you're thinking about it, if you get a hit your
first time up, you're satisfied. But if I'd get one hit, I'd want
two and three.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Anderson has had his share of 1-for-4 games during his
streak, Carew said the Kennedy High graduate doesn't get
complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``During his streak, a lot of his 1 for 4's have been big
hits,'' he said. ``Garret wants a hit every time up there. That's
his outlook. He's not satisfied. If he gets four at-bats, he wants
four hits. With that attitude, it takes all the pressure off the
hitting streak.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Trade deadline looms: Manager Terry Collins knows that Friday
is the trading deadline. But he prefers not to worry about what
might happen, even something as big as the rumored Jim
Edmonds-to-the-Mets-for-Mike Piazza deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Billy's (Bavasi, general manager) problem, not mine,''
Collins said. ``It can't be on my mind. I've gotten phone calls
about the Piazza thing, but I tell them I'm the wrong guy to talk
to. It's one thing to say, `Would you like to have him?' Who
wouldn't? But until someone new comes out here in an Angel uniform,
I can't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite having the best record in baseball, the Yankees also are
looking to improve themselves with a trade, and even Randy
Johnson's name has been mentioned. But while Johnson would make the
Yankees seemingly unbeatable, Yankees manager Joe Torre says the
club has to be smart about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, a guy like that would be nice to have,'' Torre said.
``But if you make a deal to make yourself better, are you going to
hurt yourself somewhere else? That's treading water. You still have
to find out what the other end of the equation is.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Greene hitter: Todd Greene, playing first base and DH at
Triple-A Vancouver, is hitting .300 and ready to be promoted to the
big club. The problem is there is no room for him on the Angels'
roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a letter from the (Pacific) Coast League, and they said
to get him out _ he's hit five or six home runs in 10 days,''
Collins said. ``I just talked to him (Monday) and told him we don't
have any spots. With what's happened to Chuck (Finley, hit on left
arm by line drive Friday), we've got to hang on to 12 pitchers. If
we stay healthy, in the next three or four days we've got to decide
what way we're going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Randy Velarde (elbow) will begin a rehab
assignment at Triple-A Vancouver today. Pitcher Jack McDowell
(elbow) threw Tuesday and will begin a rebab assignment at Single-A
Lake Elsinore in the next three days. Pitcher Ken Hill (elbow) has
begun to throw split-finger fastballs, but there has not been a
date scheduled for him to begin a rehab assignement.
</P>
</TEXT>
