<HEADLINE>
DODGERS TAKE CARE OF PHILS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ While Tom Lasorda worked the phone Tuesday night
from his front-row box, the Los Angeles Dodgers worked over the
Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   The players know the trade deadline is just three days away, but
they also know the Phillies are one of the teams ahead of them in
the National League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Their 7-3 victory in front of 24,828 at Veterans Stadium wasn't
without a little ninth-inning tension. But in the end, the Dodgers
opened a critical 10-game road trip with the confidence of a team
making a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things aren't won in July, but you do things now that
can get some momentum going,'' said Eric Karros, who hit a two-run
homer in the first inning. ``This is a team that is ahead of us. If
we play well, things will take care of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda tried to do his part, talking to eight clubs about
everything from a No.1 or 2 starter to a left-fielder and a
left-handed hitter. With Ismael Valdes on the disabled list for two
weeks and probably longer with a strained left-side muscle,
pitching depth could be a major need down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   So far the players like what they've seen in Lasorda's
aggressive style. The acquisition of closer Jeff Shaw at the
All-Star break sent a message this difficult season was not lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he made the Shaw trade, I think it showed us that he
wanted to win now,'' said Karros, critical in past seasons when the
team failed to make second-half moves. ``Players like to see that
and I think the feeling is he is trying to make the club better.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda's July 10 trade for left-hander Brian Bohanon (4-6)
showed more dividends Tuesday night. Bohanon allowed one earned run
in a season-high seven innings for his second consecutive victory.
Bohanon, who has made four starts since coming over from the New
York Mets, has a 2.78 ERA during that span and has limited opposing
batters to a .210 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Glenn Hoffman thinks Tuesday marked Bohanon's best
effort yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``After his first start (a 6-3 loss to San Diego), I said wait
until the next start,'' Hoffman said. ``After the second (a 4-1
loss to St. Louis), I said wait until the third. That one was
better (a 6-4 victory over Houston). But this one clearly showed us
what he can do. He got a lead and kept them off balance all night.
He threw over 100 pitches (111) and had his strongest inning at the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon was bolstered by a three-run first inning, the highlight
of which was Karros' two-run homer against right-hander Tyler Green
(6-8). For Karros, it extended his hitting streak to seven games
(13 for 26) and gave him 58 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, who had more than 30 homers and 100 RBI the past three
seasons, is on pace to drive in 89 runs. He has 13 homers.
</P>
<P>
   After the Dodgers first, the Phillies never recovered. And this
is a team that had a couple of comeback victories while taking
three of four from Florida in its last series.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi had a two-run homer in the fifth, his 23rd, and the
Dodgers' 3-4-5 hitters (Mondesi, Gary Sheffield, Karros) finished
the game 6 for 9 with two doubles, two homers and six RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' No.1-2 hitters, Wilton Guerrero and Juan Castro,
combined for three walks and scored each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, those were the big guys,'' Hoffman said. ``We got the
long ball tonight, but we also manufactured runs. We've got to do
that to win this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon, who gave up a run in the first on Scott Rolen's 21st
homer and one in the second after an error by Guerrero at second,
was not surprised by his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was with the Mets last season, they gave me a chance to
make 13 consecutive starts,'' he said. ``I went at least five
innings in all of them. Knowing that you are going to go out there
every time is so important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see myself as a fourth starter. I look at myself as a
guy who can do the job for you every time out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon turned the game over to Antonio Osuna, who walked a
batter but pitched a scoreless eighth. Scott Radinsky pitched the
ninth and Hoffman felt good enough to let newcomer Sean Maloney
throw in the bullpen. But when Radinsky allowed a run on three
hits, Maloney sat down and Shaw started throwing.
</P>
<P>
   Radinsky recovered and the Dodgers went four games over .500 _
at 55-51 _ for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what I see,'' said Mondesi, whose homer landed in the
seats just below the second deck. ``These are the teams we have to
beat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
