<HEADLINE>
L.A. LAYS IT ON IN BID FOR DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 7th graf to fix time element) 
(ATTN: Pa., Colo., Mass., Minn., La., Fla.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4304.) 
(mk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Over two solid days, the cream of this city's
civic leadership has courted the Democratic Party's national
convention for 2000 with every carrot at its command, and somewhere
between the margaritas and the mariachis, the exploding wall of
balloons and the flying angel, the intensity of the effort took on
a sweetly comic small-town air.
</P>
<P>
   By the time a chorus of irresistible inner-city children
serenaded the 50-odd members of the party's site-selection
committee Tuesday morning with the soothing strains of ``California
Dreamin,''' the message was clear: The Democrats would be safe and
warm ... if they were in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   For this much-mocked metropolis, winning a national political
convention for the first time since John Kennedy was nominated here
in 1960 would mean more than playing host to thousands of delegates
and journalists, with their attendant tourism and perhaps $150
million in spending. It would also amount to a kind of massive
international coming-out party for a city that has largely
rebounded from the economic, natural and social disasters of the
early '90s and is bursting to tell the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city frankly gets a bad rap in the Eastern press and the
international press,'' said Eli Broad, the billionaire chairman of
Sun America Inc. and one of a bevy of high-powered local leaders,
including the entertainment mogul David Geffen, recruited to lead
the city's lobbying effort and $35 million public-private pledge of
financial support for the convention. ``They think of the Simpson
trial, the recessed economy, the loss of aerospace and defense
jobs, and perceptions lag reality. We want the opportunity to show
what L.A. is today.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is not alone in wanting the psychic and economic
boost that a convention would bring, and though party officials say
it has a very good chance, senior Democrats both here and in
Washington say that Vice President Al Gore _ who will get the final
say _ has a definite fondness for Philadelphia, where his old
friend Mayor Edward Rendell is making his own strong pitch to
revive a city beleaguered by economic and social woes.
</P>
<P>
   The site-selection committee, which is also considering Denver,
Boston, Minneapolis, New Orleans and Miami and is to make a
recommendation late this year, was supposed to visit Philadelphia
last month. But it arrived only to find picket lines in place for a
bitter transit strike and decided to postpone its visit just hours
after it arrived. The strike has since been tentatively settled and
the visit is to be rescheduled for this fall, but the Angelenos are
pressing every perceived advantage, chief among them California's
54 electoral votes, which all experts agree any Democratic
candidate must now have to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we get it,'' said Susan Estrich, who managed Michael
Dukakis' 1988 campaign and is now a professor at the University of
Southern California law school, as she munched crispy rolled
taquitos at a welcoming reception for the committee in downtown Los
Angeles on Monday. Her reasoning: The nominee ``either comes here
in the summer, or he spends the whole fall here campaigning. He's
got to spend the spring here anyway raising money, so he might as
well come in the summer when he can do both effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, as the committee members toured the sprawling
Convention Center downtown, which would serve as media work space
and staging area for the convention, and saw a spiffy video on the
new Staples Arena, the state-of-the art stadium that is being built
just across the street and that would house the convention itself,
the visitors all got Los Angeles Kings hockey jerseys emblazoned
with their names and the number 54.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The committee members entered the cavernous convention center
through a wall of hundreds of balloons, which spelled out ``LA
2000'' and exploded on cue to let them pass, then sat down to a
breakfast of golden raspberries and other fresh fruits, smoked
scallops and salmon and wild mushroom hash with poached egg. Broad
stood up to welcome a performer, who was slowly lowered, feathery
angel wings and all, from the rafters of the glass-domed center,
bearing the city's official bid to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the committee had dinner on a converted sound
stage at Universal Studios. Tuesday afternoon, it toured the new
Getty Center and prepared for a dinner at Mayor Richard Riordan's
home before heading off to dance at the Conga Room, a new Latin
music nightclub partly owned by the actor Jimmy Smits.
</P>
<P>
   But in a city that has been the master of self-promotion since
colorful orange crate labels lured frozen Midwesterners here at the
turn of the century, the overall effect was oddly low key, low tech
and homey. The organizers missed no chance to emphasize the city's
racial and ethnic diversity, as a string of union workers from
various trades stepped up to make brief speeches beginning, ``I
want the 2000 Democratic National Convention because ... ''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to know what the outreach is in a city to minority
business, we want to know what the labor situation is,'' said
Rosalind Wyman, a Los Angeles native and the doyenne of California
Democratic politics, who is a member of the site-selection
committee and confesses a preference for her hometown. ``We care
about having an environmentally sensitive city, and whether there's
access for the disabled and whether the host committee is
broad-based. Obviously, I think we would put on an incredible
convention.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are said to be leaning to cities in old-line
swing states like Chicago and Philadelphia, and at least some
Democratic officials have worried that the risk of coming to Los
Angeles is that liberal celebrities might overshadow the
proceedings. Then again, since no one expects conventions to decide
anything of importance in an age of primary elections, why not come
to the home of show business in hopes of at least producing
interesting television?
</P>
<P>
   ``The good reason to come here would be if you wanted to try and
re-invent the convention,'' Ms. Estrich said. ``That would be the
exciting challenge. Because the truth is, if they do it the old
way, no one will watch anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
