<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LESS THAN PERFECT VS. YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ If there is a formula for beating the New York
Yankees, it is to play perfect baseball. Obviously not an easy
task.
</P>
<P>
   On a pace to win a major-league record 120 games, the Yankees
make opposing teams pay for their mistakes, and Tuesday night
before 36,241 at Edison Field, they did just that to the Anaheim
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees hit three home runs off Angels starter Jason Dickson
and took advantage of three Angels errors to come away with a 9-3
win. Yankees starter David Cone gave up three runs (one earned) and
six hits in seven innings to become the first 15-game winner in the
majors (15-3).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees improved to 74-26, their best record through 100
games in franchise history, one game better than the 1927 club and
only one game behind the best start by any team this century (the
1902 Pittsburgh Pirates were 75-25).
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had been the only team in baseball with a winning
record against the Yankees this season _ winning two of the first
three _ before Tuesday. Now the season series is tied at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss, the Angels remained alone in first place, one
game up on Texas in the A.L. West. The Yankees lead the A.L. East
by 15 games over Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels made all three of their errors in the sixth inning,
including one by the usually sure-handed shortstop Gary DiSarcina.
Going into the three-game series against the Yankees, DiSarcina
said he knew that there was no room for error.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is you have to play error-free, mistake-free
baseball,'' he said. ``They're a team that constantly takes
advantage of everything you do wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can bring out the best in you, or make you fold up the
tent. They either bring you up to their level, or you go home.
That's what they do to you, they can embarrass you.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter, Darryl Strawberry and Bernie Williams homered off
losing pitcher Jason Dickson (9-8). Dickson gave up eight runs (six
earned) and 11 hits in 51/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' only good signs were Tim Salmon's second-inning home
run _ his second homer in two days coming after a 30-game drought
without a homer _ and Garret Anderson's ninth-inning single, which
extended his hitting streak to 25 in a row, tying Rod Carew's club
record.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the Yankees starting lineup either drove in a run or
scored one. And that has been typical of the Yankees season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're an incredibly talented team,'' DiSarcina said. ``They
don't have an MVP-type candidate on it. The thing you have to look
at is the depth they have. They've got guys coming off the bench
left and right. And the guys on the bench are just as good if not
better than than some of the starters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees took a 1-0 lead in the first inning on Jeter's home
run but did more damage in the second making the most of the little
things.
</P>
<P>
   The first six batters in the second inning reached base, but
only one hit the ball out of the infield _ Strawberry _ with a
two-run homer. The other five had three infield singles, a
bases-loaded walk and a batter who reached base when Dickson threw
too late trying to get the lead runner on a sacrifice attempt.
</P>
<P>
   It added up to four runs in the inning and a 5-0 Yankees lead,
but Dickson managed to stick around.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels cut the Yankees' lead to 5-1 when Salmon led off the
second inning with his 17th home run of the season. Singles by Jim
Edmonds and Darin Erstad _ with help from an error by Williams in
center field _ resulted in a run for the Angels in the third,
cutting their deficit to 5-2. But that would be as close as the
Angels would get.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' solo homer in the fifth off Dickson increased the
Yankees' lead to 6-2 and they scored three unearned runs in the
sixth, thanks to the errors by third baseman Dave Hollins,
DiSarcina and catcher Matt Walbeck.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored their final run after Erstad doubled and
scored on a throwing error by Jeter at shortstop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
