<SLUG> BC-TEN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI SERIOUS ABOUT REGAINING FORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Andre Agassi's week in Los Angeles began Monday
night with a comic doubles match for charity. He and Robin Williams
took on Patrick Rafter and Billy Crystal. Paparazzi lined the court
and for a change Agassi wasn't their No. 1 target.
</P>
<P>
   Williams played in goggles and camouflage pants. Crystal used a
tennis racket and a baseball glove. By the time anybody paid
attention to the score, Rafter and Crystal led 3-1. Agassi barked
at Williams in mock anger, ``Quit screwing around and get it
together!''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, about to serve, stared back at his straight man and
said sarcastically, ``Just 'cause you won WASHINGTON.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of Westsiders laughed at the gentle dig. Not
Wimbledon. WASHINGTON. The man who won Wimbledon in 1992, the U.S.
Open in '94 and the Australian Open in '95, came here as the winner
of last week's Legg Mason (who?) Classic in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Winning Washington is not what made Agassi the most familiar
name in U.S. tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is winning matches like the one Tuesday night in which
Agassi defeated 20-year-old Bob Bryan of Camarillo 6-4, 6-3 in the
first round of the Mercedes-Benz Cup at the Los Angeles Tennis
Center.
</P>
<P>
   But victories like these, and the 15 straight winning sets since
his second-round dismissal from Wimbledon in June, are what will
make another Grand Slam splash possible.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing his ranking drop as low as No. 141 in the world
last year, mainly through neglect, Agassi is moving quickly down
what he calls ``this road back.'' Convinced he has recaptured the
skills that made him No.1 before the '95 U.S. Open final loss to
Pete Sampras, he strives now for consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game is as good as it's ever been,'' Agassi said after
Tuesday night's victory. ``It's become a question of consistency,
so it can come out match after match.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago Agassi lost to Justin Gimelstob in the first round of
the Los Angeles tournament, ``somewhat embarrassing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That and other on-court embarrassments inspired him to call an
end to the ``sabbatical'' that covered most of 1996 and '97,
coinciding with his engagement and marriage to Brooke Shields.
Well, who wouldn't be distracted?
</P>
<P>
   The comeback took him through places farther from Wimbledon than
even Washington. At his low point last December, he won a
minor-league tournament in Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, now 28, though you're excused if you assumed he was 10
years older, has been the Truman Burbank of the tennis world since
he came on the scene in 1986. The first star to have grown up
entirely in the era since Connors and Evert and
tennis-as-soap-opera, he's a sweet-natured guy who has been made to
face all of life's temptations, distractions and corruptions with
the camera rolling for our entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The Las Vegas upbringing, the prize-fighter-size entourage, the
incredible wealth, the ``Image is Everything'' commercials, the
Hollywood romances, the wild fluctuations in weight and hair length
_ all are topics for our discussion and judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and the wild fluctuations in Agassi's world ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, he lost in the semifinals in Adelaide to
now-156th-ranked Lleyton Hewitt, in round one at the French to No.
75 Marat Safin, and in round two at Wimbledon to No. 40 Tommy Haas.
</P>
<P>
   But victories in San Jose (beating Sampras in the final) and
Scottsdale, Ariz., and his current streak have lifted his ranking
to No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Agassi has been blowing through matches as if his
private 727 is double-parked. In his seven straight match
victories, he has needed barely more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan, the NCAA singles champion from Stanford, gave his boyhood
hero a tougher _ and longer _ time than Agassi might have expected.
Any of five break points against Agassi could have made it 4-4 in
the second, but he finally put that game away with his 11th ace.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi will play Jan-Michael Gambill in the second round of the
four-round tournament at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing very well. I think I can step on the court with
anybody and expect to win,'' said Agassi, who plans to play
tournaments in Toronto, Cincinnati and Indianapolis between now and
the start of the U.S. Open on Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely worked myself into enough of a hole where I had
some doubts about whether I could come back. (But) I think it's
realistic to go to the Open and expect to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   He quit screwing around and got it together. Now, is there any
hope for Robin Williams?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
