<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEINBRENNER EAGER TO BRING BIG UNIT TO THE BRONX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A single player stands between George Steinbrenner and
the 1998 World Series. And unless Mariner ownership loses its guts
again, he just pitched his last game in a Seattle uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee owner has long coveted Randy Johnson, for reasons
evident Tuesday night. In a valiant finale, Johnson struck out 12
and gave up four hits. But since two were home runs, he lost 4-3 to
the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing the end of an epic sports career in Seattle, 31,124
stood and pounded palms for Johnson's last long strides from the
Kingdome mound. Regardless of the bitterness of the last year and
its 9-10 mark, the legacy is grander than the ledger: He helped
change forever the fate of major league ball in the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Now he seems destined to be the hood ornament on the Yankee
steamroller. Steinbrenner almost always gets what he wants. Even
when he doesn't need it.
</P>
<P>
   At 74-26, the Yankees have been so smashing this season that
even Godzilla is two skyscrapers behind in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But Steinbrenner knows baseball history is littered with
regular-season dreadnoughts whose ribs poke from the postseason
mud. He also knows if the eager Indians get Johnson, or even if he
stays in Seattle while the Mariners finally play to their
capabilities, the Yankees could face in the postseason the one
pitcher who can shut down their formidable lineup in the first and
fifth games of a division series.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly all that was built _ one of the great seasons in Yankee
and baseball history _ would be in jeopardy. For the tempestuous
Steinbrenner and New York's perpetually hyperventilating fans and
media, it would be better to never have gone at all than to enter
the postseason with magnum expectations and fail.
</P>
<P>
   So acquiring Johnson is Steinbrenner's insurance policy against
the biggest player threat to a second World Series appearance in
three years. Remember, too, that Steinbrenner is in an extortionist
caterwaul with Big Apple politicians over a new stadium, so the
stakes are higher. In New York, leverage is as valued and hard to
come by as a parking space.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that Mariner management, after ham-fisting the
Johnson affair for more than a year, might be afforded an
opportunity to salvage something worthwhile because in New York,
too much is never enough.
</P>
<P>
   Any trade won't be Johnson's equivalent, of course. That doesn't
exist. But given how ownership and Johnson's own petulance have
diminished him in Seattle, the prospect of getting a quality
starter such as Hideki Irabu would be a move that not only doesn't
represent a surrender of the '98 season, it might be an improvement
in team chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella claimed Tuesday he is out of the loop
regarding trade talks until a deal is in hand, but acknowledged
that ``it will be a very interesting four days'' up to Friday's
non-waiver trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in the hypothetical about the dicey prospect of trading
superstars, Piniella said, ``The final determination is what you
get in return. I don't have to get sold on a trade. It's my job to
get the best out of the talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This organization will do what is best for the ballclub. I'm
very confident with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many share Piniella's view, given the decision-making
paralysis that has gripped ownership since it has been on the hook
for the breathtaking cost overruns on America's most expensive
ballyard.
</P>
<P>
   But this little nuisance of the 1998 season has reached a
crossroads that begs ownership's attention. Even though the Big
Unit's fate should never have come down this way, it's obvious that
his place on the team is beyond rescue.
</P>
<P>
   His rambling monologue Monday on a Seattle radio station was
riddled with defensiveness, confusion, contradiction and silliness.
Just imagine what might happen to the next teammate who commits the
clubhouse crime of TURNING UP THE STEREO!!!
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's time in Seattle has come to an end, which is sad and a
shame. He was, and is, the greatest pitcher in club history, one of
the nation's most compelling sports figures who made each
appearance a happening.
</P>
<P>
   The causes for his decay have been well-chronicled. Blame has
been fervently dished. Anxiety is profound and well-deserved, given
what has happened when the Mariners trade stars (see Omar Vizquel
and Tino Martinez).
</P>
<P>
   But the last three trading deadlines have seen the Mariners swap
youngsters for veterans in failed attempts to make the World
Series. The well of expendable talent has dried up. The club has to
get younger and fill multiple holes.
</P>
<P>
   The emotions and the baseball history around Johnson have to
become secondary to a reloading project, in order to avoid a
rebuilding project.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland GM John Hart has consistently rattled the baseball
world with his trades of marquee players. But the Indians have
remained among the elites because most of his risk-taking has
worked by gaining talent of equal or greater value.
</P>
<P>
   If reports of Steinbrenner's eagerness are accurate, ownership
needs to take the handcuffs off Woody Woodward, endure the wrath of
Johnson's many fans and the loss of some electric history, and take
the risk that Irabu likes loud music.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
