u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT &LR;      07-29 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TROUNCE ANGELS, 9-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Before David Cone falls asleep, he carefully
positions his body, lying on his left side or back, so that his
right arm rests free. When he wakes each morning, Cone will slowly
lift his right arm, to see how it feels.
</P>
<P>
   It's pitchers' roulette, in a sense, for there may come a day
when Cone won't be able to raise his arm above his head in the
morning, like last year, when he needed surgery. But now Cone is
throwing as well as he ever has. He became the first 15-game winner
in the major leagues on Tuesday night, giving up six hits in seven
innings as the Yankees whipped the Anaheim Angels, 9-3.
</P>
<P>
   In their 100th game of the season, the Yankees achieved their
74th victory, and if they win merely half of their remaining games,
they will finish the year with 105 victories. Their magic number
for clinching a playoff spot is down to 40.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who opened the season here with back-to-back
losses, barreled into Edison Field and flattened the Angels with
absolute precision and purpose. Derek Jeter launched the game's
fourth pitch for a home run, and Paul O'Neill lined the fifth pitch
off the rump of Anaheim's Jason Dickson. The Yankees added four
more runs in the second inning _ Darryl Strawberry blasting a
two-run homer, his 16th _ and three in the sixth, all of it far
more than Cone required.
</P>
<P>
   Cone (15-3) allowed more runs on Tuesday night than he had in
any start in more than a month, but he was in total command. He
never went to a two-ball, no-strike count in the first six innings,
and only twice did an Angels hitter work the count to 3-1 in that
time, never 3-0. Cone was never forced into a situation where he
had to throw a fastball, where he had to throw a pitch the hitter
was anticipating. The Angels were guessing all night long, and
faring quite poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Cone struck out six, continuing his recent success. Over his
last 11 starts before Tuesday night's, Cone compiled a 9-2 record
and a 1.96 earned run average, walking only 15 batters in 731/3
innings and striking out 86. Opponents batted .192 in that time,
with just 5 hits in 44 at-bats (.114) with runners in scoring
position. His era has decreased in every start but one since May
19, and his pitches per inning _ a barometer of his control and
effectiveness _ had dropped from 20.93 on April 18 to 16.08 before
Tuesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7531 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-29 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON FANS 12, BUT INDIAN HOMERS DO HIM IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Brilliant, but fallible.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson was all of that Tuesday night. His longwinding
Mariner career could be summed up in a similar fashion as well.
Finally, it might be time to write the epithet.
</P>
<P>
   In what easily could have been his Seattle farewell, the lefty
threw one too many fastballs to Manny Ramirez in the sixth inning
and David Bell in the eighth, and watched as their home runs
carried the Cleveland Indians to a 4-3 victory at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the unhappy one toyed with a no-hitter, then a
shutout. He permitted only four hits. But befitting his crumbling
image in Seattle, Johnson came away empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Pinstripes, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   With rumors ripe that Johnson might be bound for the Big Apple
and the Yankees, he locked in a superb pitching duel with
Cleveland's Charles Nagy. For 52/3 innings, they kept everyone
scoreless. Ramirez and Bell spoiled the going-away party, if that
is what it was.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching a complete game, Johnson left to a standing ovation
from the 31,124 in the stands. The reception inside the Mariner
clubhouse, however, more resembled a funeral procession as players
considered the possibility of life after the Big Unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't help but feel it,'' designated hitter Edgar Martinez
said. ``He's a friend. He means a lot to people in this clubhouse.
You think about all the good times we've had, and it's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ken Griffey Jr.: ``Until they say he's traded or done
something else, he's still part of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, of course, had nothing to say. He quietly dressed, took
a swig of a beer and avoided postgame interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners (48-57) squandered a great opportunity to pick up
ground in the AL West race, as front-running Texas and Anaheim were
both losers Tuesday. Instead, they sit nine games back. The
repercussions of the latest Seattle setback might have speeded
Johnson's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shame to lose this game,'' Mariner pitcher Jeff
Fassero said. ``If we can win the next two and be 6{ games out of
first, I can't see them getting rid of him. I think what happens
the rest of this series will dictate what they do with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Said manager Lou Piniella: ``Whatever happens is going to
happen. We'll just have to wait and see. ... I think it's been a
distraction, but outside of that, we've still got to go out and
play. One way or another, it will be over soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Against a watered-down Indian lineup _ Kenny Lofton, among
others, didn't start _ Johnson was at his best the first two times
through the order. Then he ran into a few trouble spots.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez leaned into a 2-0 pitch and sliced one onto the aisleway
in right, where a balding man in shorts made an awkward grab. Bell,
who had reached on a fielder's choice, and Omar Vizquel, who had
walked, scored ahead of the slugger, who collected his 23rd homer,
and the Indians had an instant 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners made it 3-2 in the seventh when Jay Buhner singled
home Martinez and David Segui with no outs, causing Nagy's exit.
But a double-play grounder snuffed more possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, as he has all season, then suffered a critical letdown
against an unlikely opponent in the eighth inning. He served up a
first-pitch homer to Bell, Cleveland's No. 9 hitter, and what would
be the game-deciding run. The ball sailed about 10 rows up in the
left-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners pulled within one in the bottom half of the inning,
when Griffey reached on a high chopper to second, stole his 14th
base and scored on Martinez's single to center. But the damage was
done.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson faced the minimum number of hitters through four
innings, permitting just one baserunner, Vizquel. Leading off, the
former Mariner walked and was caught in a rundown after Ramirez
struck out.
</P>
<P>
   The no-hit bid ended in the fifth. Leading off, Travis Fryman
slugged an 0-2 pitch high off the blue wall in right, off a credit
card advertisement, for a double. Buhner, the Mariner right
fielder, conceded the hit early in its flight, backpedaling from
the wall almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (9-10) finished with 12 strikeouts, the 95th time he has
done that in his career. He whiffed former Mariner Mark Whiten
three times.
</P>
<P>
   His final batter Tuesday, was Bell, whom he retired on a popup
to second. Of course, he made things difficult to the end, loading
the bases after retiring the first two hitters. Then he walked off
to cheers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very nice gesture,'' Piniella said. ``We'll see if
it was ill-founded or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
