 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 395- JULY 29, 1998   NEWS and FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 395 -- July 29, 1998 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. SCREAM GIRL : THE RETURN OF JAMIE LEE CURTIS In 1978,
``Halloween'' launched Jamie Lee Curtis on the road to stardom, a
road which took her to ``Trading Places,'' ``A Fish Called Wanda,''
and ``True Lies.'' Now she's back in 'Halloween H20,'' a
20-years-later sequel. Curtis talks about the new movie, why she
won't let her children watch it, how her mother (actress Janet
Leigh) kept her from seeing ``Psycho'' as a child and why she sees
``H20'' as both a terrifying slasher film and a serious look at
victimization and a woman's struggle to rebuild her life after
being terrorized. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,300 words + photo. 2. ADRIAN
LYNE BRAVES A HURRICANE CALLED ' LOLITA' Since the 1950's, no work
of art has been able to raise as much of a stir as Vladimir
Nabokov's classic novel, ``Lolita,'' the story of a man's erotic
obsession with a 12-year-old girl. Now the book has been made into
a film for the second time, and proven so controversial that it
couldn't get an American distributor. Director Adrian Lyne talks
about the new film, his past controversial films such as ``Fatal
Attraction'' and ``Indecent Proposal,'' why he felt it essential to
retain the film's sex scenes between Jeremy Irons and young
Dominique Swain and why he thinks that there is a fine line between
protecting and over-protecting children. By Jeanne Wolf and Shep
Morgan. 1,400 words + photo. (N/A in England.) 3. NICOLAS CAGE
KEEPS THE ACTION COMING Nicolas Cage has a Best Actor Oscar for the
prestigious 1996 film ``Leaving Las Vegas,'' and all the esteem
that carries. But he's also an action hero, with a string of hits -
and a $20-million-per-film paycheck - to prove it. Cage talks about
his latest thriller, ``Snake Eyes,'' whether he's sobered from his
days as one of Hollywood's edgier actors, how he got along with
often-criticized director Brian De Palma on ``Snake Eyes,'' and why
he doesn't regret having set his family - and wife Patricia
Arquette - to one side during his recent blitz of hit films. By Ian
Spelling. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
FACE VALUE : PUSHING HIS LUCK? By Ricardo Castaneda In this new
cartoon feature from The New York Times Syndicate, artist Ricardo
Castaneda offers an hilarious depiction of the upcoming film
``Snake Eyes,'' with Nicolas Cage holding a pair of dice. 5. NIKITA
SERGUEVITCH MIKHALKOV, RUSSIAN CINEMA'S NEW TSAR There are signs of
a renaissance in Russian cinema. ``We should unite to restore
Russian cinema to its former glory,'' exclaimed Nikita Mikhalkov
recently during the closing ceremony of the ninth Open Russian
Festival. His message was loud and clear : If professional Russian
film-makers want to get their industry out of the doldrums in which
it has been languishing for the past ten years, they will have to
forget their divisions and rally to a single leader - Makhalkov
himself. By Pierre Daum. From Le Monde. (English translation
available.) 1,500 words. 6. IN THE POST-POLITICALLY CORRECT ZONE
WITH 'SOUTH PARK'
</P>
<P>
   AND 'BASKETBALL' With their new movie, the sports parody
'Basketball,' Trey Parker and Matt Stone are waging a two-man
offensive against sensitivity. ``This is what every guy lives
through - the whole sports, buddy, triumph-glory bull - and we're
making fun of a lot of that, and this is the way guys talk.'' By
Jonathan Van Meter. From The New York Times Magazine. 2,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
DIONNE WARWICK FINDS HER HEART'S HOME IN RIO DE JANEIRO With over
30 years in music, and legions of fans and awards, Dionne Warwick
is the grande dame of pop and R&AMP;B. However, even with such fame,
she still lives by the principles she grew up with : God, family,
friendship and music. And when she recently found a house
overlooking Rio's beach front and the giant statue of Christ the
Redeemer, she knew she was 'home.'' ``Living here I feel like the
weight of the world is off my shoulders,'' she says. ``I found in
Brazil what used to be the priority in America : values, standards,
regard for one another. They care about God.'' By Sabrina Lamb.
From Black Elegance. 2,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
MAKING 'PRIVATE RYAN' Steven Spielberg and Tom Hanks have been
friends for years, but the two Hollywood heavyweights hadn't worked
together until ``Saving Private Ryan,'' the World War II epic about
a platoon sent to rescue a soldier whose three brothers have died
in combat. Both men committed themselves to creating the most
authentic war movie ever made, and the controversy surrounding the
film's brutual battle scenes suggests that they have. By Joshua
Mooney. 1,100 words. BPI.
</P>
