<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7814 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THREATS-COMPUTER-$ADV     07-29 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THREATS-COMPUTER-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CYBER-TERRORISTS POSE THREAT TO A NETWORKED AMERICA
 &HT;    With THREATS .
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Aug. 2.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It starts with an unexplained power blackout in a
major southeastern city. As utility workers struggle to restore
service, telephone systems across the country become paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, misrouted freight and passenger trains collide,
killing and injuring many passengers. Civilian air traffic control
systems go haywire, causing still more accidents and deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Before the nation can recover from those blows, malfunctioning
pipeline flow-control mechanisms trigger oil refinery blasts.
</P>
<P>
   As alarm and fear begin to spread, electronic ``sniffers''
sabotage global financial systems, disrupting fund transfers and
causing stocks to plunge on world exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   At neighborhood banks, automatic teller machines randomly credit
or debit customers' accounts. As reports of the berserk ATM units
spread, depositors panic and rush to make withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   Television networks and local stations, seeking to keep tabs on
the mounting chaos, lose control of their programming. An
orchestrated disinformation campaign mysteriously airs on their
channels, sowing further confusion.
</P>
<P>
   As the Pentagon mobilizes to restore order, dial-in attacks
paralyze phone systems at military staging bases. More ominous yet,
sensitive computer-controlled weapons' systems begin to show signs
of electronic malaise.
</P>
<P>
   This scenario, outlined in a recent report by the Rand Corp. for
the Defense Department, provides a chilling picture of how the
Information Age has left the United States vulnerable to a
``digital Pearl Harbor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Information war has no front line,'' the study notes.
``Potential battlefields are anywhere networked systems allow
access'' through their satellite and fiber-optic links to the rest
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``In sum, the U.S. homeland may no longer provide a sanctuary
from outside attack,'' it concludes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're extremely vulnerable,'' said Sen. Fred Thompson,
R-Tenn., who chairs the Senate Government Affairs Committee, which
shares legislative jurisdiction over terrorism issues. If an enemy
state or terrorist groups wanted to strike at America, he said,
``the first thing they would do is screw up our computers.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen nations are known to have active
information-warfare programs, including Russia and China and such
potentially hostile states as Libya, Iraq and Iran. Foreign teams
have broken into both U.S. government and corporate computer
systems to find vulnerable points and, perhaps, to deposit unseen
digital ``trap doors'' and ``logic bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fear that among the flood of tech workers hurriedly
imported to deal with the Year 2000 computer problem, foreign
agents may be planting more software surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The extent to which the nation's essential services stand
exposed chills top government officials. It has led directly to a
high-priority program aimed at ``hardening'' U.S. digital defenses.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton last May issued ``Presidential Decision
Directive 63,'' mobilizing ``a national effort to assure the
security of the United States' increasingly exposed and
interconnected infrastructures, such as telecommunications, banking
and finance, energy, transportation, and essential government
services'' by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has sought $64 million in the next fiscal
year to fund the coordination of government and private efforts to
ward off threats to critical computer operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government has to lead,'' Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., chairman of
the Senate Judiciary subcommittee on terrorism, told CQ Weekly
magazine this spring. ``Until the government is seen to recognize
the threat in a significant way, it's a little hard to get industry
to focus on the threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Most attention to the dangers of information warfare has focused
on the vulnerability of the Pentagon's own systems, the subject of
a series of hearings in recent years by the Senate permanent
investigations subcommittee under former Sam Nunn of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   According to the General Accounting Office, Pentagon computers
were infiltrated as many as 250,000 times in 1995. The exact number
was difficult to calculate, the GAO said, because the hackers
rarely were even detected.
</P>
<P>
   Over a period of decades, intruders have stolen, changed or
destroyed sensitive data or software in Pentagon computers. In some
cases, they installed files to cover up their break-ins or to make
future infiltration easier.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, the National Security Agency staged a ``red team''
exercise, code-named ``Eligible Receiver,'' in which agents
pretending to be North Koreans infiltrated the command-and-control
facilities of the U.S. Pacific Command in Honolulu _ demonstrating
their ability to neutralize most U.S. armed forces from Okinawa to
San Diego for many hours without firing a shot.
</P>
<P>
   With such methods, cyberspies track the precepts of Sun Tzu, who
lived in China four centuries before the birth of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attaining 100 victories in 100 battles is not the pinnacle of
excellence,'' he wrote in ``The Art of War,'' the earliest known
treatise on military science. ``Subjugating the enemy's army
without fighting is the true pinnacle of excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. officials are also concerned about attacks on civilian
information networks, which the military has no legal or political
authority to protect in peacetime.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a thief with a laptop computer in an apartment in
St. Petersburg, Russia, broke into Citibank Corp. accounts in
Chicago and transferred millions of dollars before being caught by
old-fashioned police work.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing last June before the Senate Judiciary subcommittee on
technology, terrorism and government information, Ellie Padgett,
deputy chief of the NSA's office of defensive information warfare,
told of one aspect of the ``red team's'' worrisome success in
``Eligible Receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   In a phase of the exercise that simulated attacks, she said,
``we scripted (an) Internet message (that) would be sent out to
everybody saying there was a problem with the 911 system,
understanding that human nature would result in people calling the
911 system to see if there was a problem'' _ thus causing the
overloaded phone system to crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line of all of this is that it doesn't take a lot
of people to do this,'' Padgett said. ``It can probably be done,
this sort of an attack, by a handful of folks working together. ...
They can get the tools off of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
