<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7816 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THREATS-GERM-$ADV02-C     07-29 1674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THREATS-GERM-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PUBLIC HEALTH SECTOR POORLY PREPARED FOR GERM ATTACK
 &HT;    1050&AMP;add. With THREATS, THREATS-GERM-POX and THREATS-GERM-LIST.
For release Sunday, Aug. 2.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the spreading chaos that could develop if
terrorists deliberately started an epidemic of smallpox, ebola or
another deadly disease in America, the country's first line of
defense would be the doctors, nurses, hospital personnel and public
health workers who would care for victims and try to figure out
what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Clinton administration, which plans to spend about $1.3
billion next year to defend the country against chemical or
biological warfare attacks, would invest only about 3 percent of
that amount _ $42 million _ to reinforce an underfunded and poorly
equipped network of state and local health departments.
</P>
<P>
   And even that money is in jeopardy, thanks to the
administration's failure to provide a routine report to the House
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon spends about $1 billion a year to defend against
chemical or biological attacks. The money goes for research,
equipment and a new $300 million program to establish 50 or more
``rapid response'' units in the National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   But the quick action _ or lack of it _ that could mean life or
death for hundreds of thousands of Americans in a terror-spawned
epidemic would rest with state and local public health departments,
currently so poorly equipped that many still use rotary phones.
</P>
<P>
   Many do not have Internet connections or the ability to share
information electronically. They plod through outbreaks of E. coli
and salmonella, playing telephone tag with other departments as
they try to report unusual ``clusters'' of illness and waiting for
unreliable fax machines to deliver badly needed expertise from the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The $42 million President Clinton has proposed that the CDC
spend to begin upgrading this system ``is a very small amount of
money,'' said Dr. Donald A. Henderson, dean emeritus of the Johns
Hopkins University School of Public Health and former director of
the World Health Organization campaign that eradicated smallpox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our best approach is to strengthen the infrastructure that is
so important to detecting and responding to a disease,'' Dr.
Henderson said, ``and that is the public health and medical
infrastructure. We need better surveillance, better laboratories,
better protection.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be this system _ not ``rapid response'' teams from the
National Guard or other teams being trained by the Marines or by
the Army at Aberdeen Proving Grounds _ that would first learn of
and respond to a biological attack against America, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary Selden, who specializes in chemical and germ warfare
matters for Business Executives for National Security, said
preliminary exercises indicate that efforts by various federal,
state and local civilian and military agencies to cope with an
actual bioterrorism attack likely could end up ``with a lot of
people yelling at each other and nobody in command. It's going to
be very confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's got to be in overall control, and that just hasn't
happened,'' Selden said. He said that only a nationally known
figure such as former Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., retired Joint Chiefs of
Staff Chairman Gen. Colin Powell or former White House national
security adviser Brent Scowcroft could command the attention and
respect of the different groups.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's model for responding to terrorism is
weighted in favor of a chemical attack, such as the nerve gas that
killed a dozen people when released in a Tokyo subway in 1995,
Selden said. Paramedics, firemen, police and other ``first
responders'' at the site of that kind of terrorist attack must know
how to protect themselves and others from lethal chemicals or
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Such training could be irrelevant in a biological attack.
</P>
<P>
   A ``suicide cougher'' who had allowed himself to be infected
with smallpox could expose thousands of people in a few days _ and
they would in turn expose many thousands more. By the time his
actions became known, victims could be all over the country, and
would need doctors, nurses and quarantined hospital beds, not
military units.
</P>
<P>
   If ebola virus, which causes one of the most gruesome deaths
imaginable _ the victim starts hemorrhaging and bleeding from every
body orifice, including the eyes _ were scattered among Americans,
it would be from two to 21 days before the first exposed victims
began to fall ill.
</P>
<P>
   And while anthrax does not spread in epidemic fashion from one
person to another, the sooner it is recognized, the quicker victims
can be treated with penicillin or other antibiotics that could save
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three hundred million dollars for the National Guard doesn't
really make a lot of sense,'' said Michael Osterholm, state
epidemiologist of Minnesota. ``It's kind of like investing all of
your money in an expensive fire truck when what you need first is
the ability to find the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Training and equipping the National Guard's first-response
groups would not be affected by the additional $300 million which
President Clinton last month asked Congress to appropriate in germ
and chemical warfare preparedness funds.
</P>
<P>
   The new money would be divided among several agencies, including
the FBI, the Federal Emergency Management Agency and the Department
of Health and Human Services (HHS). A total of $51 million would be
used to start a civilian stockpile of antidotes, antibiotics and
vaccines necessary to respond to acts of bioterrorism.
</P>
<P>
   On July 14, the House Appropriations Committee approved the $51
million Clinton had requested for the medicines stockpile, but
dropped the $42 million in public health infrastructure funds.
</P>
<P>
   A committee report stated that HHS, which includes CDC, had
``declined to provide'' a routine report detailing how the money
would be spent. An HHS spokesman said the department's failure to
deliver the report on time was the result of a ``misunderstanding''
that was subsequently cleared up.
</P>
<P>
   A committee spokesman said that if the committee received the
report, it would try to get the $42 million included later this
summer, when House and Senate budget writers meet to hammer out a
final fiscal 1999 federal budget. But in the high-stakes atmosphere
of a conference committee meeting on the federal budget, nothing is
certain to happen or not happen.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as they wait to see whether the funding will be
provided, leaders of associations of state and local public health
associations say they have not been included in any planning for a
terrorist attack. Some say they wonder whether anyone in the
federal government realizes what burdens would fall on their
shoulders if one took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be some kind of assumption that the response to
a bioterrorism event will be mounted by the federal government and
the military,'' said Dr. Edward Thompson, a physician who serves as
Mississippi's public health commissioner. ``If the country is
attacked, it seems reasonable that the military would respond. The
problem with that is that it will inevitably be state and local
public health systems that will detect an act of bioterrorism in
the first place and bear the brunt of mounting a response.''
</P>
<P>
   If smallpox virus leaked from former Soviet Union germ warfare
stockpiles were obtained by terrorists, then released in a subway
or airport in a large city, public health experts say the disease
would spread wildly among Americans, virtually none of whom have
valid immunizations. The disease typically has a 30 percent
mortality rate among healthy adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer the release event goes unrecognized, the more
widespread the infection,'' said Dr. Thompson. ``The number of
eventual victims could quickly become millions.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern that this very thing could happen has led Dr. Henderson
to call for a new campaign to manufacture and stockpile enough
smallpox vaccine to immunize 150 million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Defectors from the former Soviet Union say biological
laboratories in Russia worked with both smallpox and ebola as
potential germ warfare weapons _ and even tried to engineer both of
them into a new organism.
</P>
<P>
   Public health officials such as Osterholm and Thompson say they
shudder at the thought of their understaffed and poorly equipped
departments having to deal with a deliberately introduced epidemic
of smallpox or ebola hemorrhagic fever or with millions of dying
anthrax victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently, electronic communications are the best way to send
and receive data quickly, and the Internet is the best way to share
data and get access to current information about a disease,'' Dr.
Ralph Morris, executive director of the Galveston County, Texas,
Health Department and president of the National Association of
County and City Health Officials, told a Senate subcommittee in
early June.
</P>
<P>
   He added that while such communications are ``taken for
granted'' in the military and law enforcement, ``most health
departments still rely on the phone, the fax machine, and paper and
pencil to track down the information they need.''
</P>
<P>
   About half of all local health departments do have have
electronic mail, he said, and at least 1,000 do not have access to
the Internet. Among those that do, one-third are not linked to
their state health departments and fewer than one-fourth can share
data with other departments electronically, Dr. Morris testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't afford to get any further behind,'' he said.
``Whether the cause of a health emergency is an innocent cook at a
church supper or an international terrorist, our need to respond
quickly remains the same. Saving time means saving lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
