<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WINBLAD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 A Company of Her Own  
 By Julia Angwin   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ann Winblad is the best-known female venture capitalist in
Silicon Valley _ and not just because she's Bill Gates
ex-girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   She's renowned as a successful and witty software advocate who
has become something of an unofficial _ and unusual _ spokeswoman
for her industry.
</P>
<P>
   Although soundbite-savvy Winblad can be found on the speakers'
roster at nearly every high-tech forum in the country, she holds
herself aloof from the rest of the chummy venture capital world.
</P>
<P>
   Her firm Hummer Winblad has offices in San Francisco's South
Park _ 30 miles away from VC row at Sand Hill Road in Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   Winblad said she keeps her distance partly out of fear of
alerting competitors to the nature of her deals and partly because
she eschews the herd mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eagles don't flock,'' Winblad explained. ``As Buffy the
Vampire Slayer says, `Does the word `duh' mean anything to you?'''
</P>
<P>
   Winblad is unique among high-tech financiers because her firm
invests only in software startups _ excluding other lucrative
segments of the industry, such as computer hardware, chips and
networking.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Internet exploded, software was a hard sell in a
Silicon Valley that worshipped hardware makers such as Apple
Computer and Silicon Graphics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Software was the Rodney Dangerfield of the computer industry _
it got no respect,'' Winblad said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, software is a hot field and Winblad is enjoying
her time in the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   She travels so much that some office-mates say they rarely see
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ann who?'' asked Neil Weintraut, a venture capitalist who
shares office space with Hummer Winblad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ann is so active in industry activities that she is rarely in
the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Winblad says her job as a professional speaker is secondary to
her prime mission of ``finding, funding and building'' startups
into bigger companies.
</P>
<P>
   Winblad founded her first $35 million fund with former NBA star
John Hummer in 1991 _ and it earned a 50 percent return on the
money it initially invested.
</P>
<P>
   In total, Hummer Winblad has collected about $200 million from
pension funds and institutional investors and distributed the money
to nearly 50 startups.
</P>
<P>
   Hummer Winblad's top picks have included Berkeley Systems, the
makers of After Dark screensavers that was sold to CUC
International for $13.8 million last year, and Arbor Software, a
Sunnyvale database software firm that has doubled in market value
since it went public in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Hummer Winblad also nurtured the growth of Wind River Systems,
an Alameda firm whose stock has soared eight-fold to $36.38
yesterday from a opening of price in 1993 of $4.22, adjusted for
stock splits.
</P>
<P>
   Even if success and attitude didn't set Winblad apart, she would
stand out as a women and Midwesterner among the mostly male,
East-coast-bred venture capitalist crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Winblad, 47, was raised in Farmington, Minn., _ a small town
with one stoplight.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of six children, she had an entrepreneurial flair at
an early age.
</P>
<P>
   Winblad's sister Patty Jorgensen recalls that while she and her
siblings would draw pictures, Ann would sell their drawings to the
neighborhood parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember she'd be making Barbie doll clothes and selling
them and I'd beg for one,'' Jorgensen said. ``She said, `No, I'm
selling them.'''
</P>
<P>
   Winblad went to a Minnesota women's college but took all her
classes at the all-male campus nearby. She majored in business and
mathematics _ but also fell in love with computers.
</P>
<P>
   During school, she wrote computer programs for male classmates
in exchange for their girlfriends typing her papers.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation she looked for a job where she could work with
computers and landed at the Federal Reserve Bank in Minneapolis as
a computer programmer.
</P>
<P>
   But the bank was too slow-paced for Winblad.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1975 she convinced three programmer colleagues from the
bank to quit and start their own company building accounting
software.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, Open Systems, was successful enough that Winblad and
her partners sold it for $15 million in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Winblad took her share of the money and high-tailed it to
Silicon Valley, where she worked as a consultant and started dating
Microsoft founder and CEO Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Although she and Gates were an item for three years, Winblad's
friends say she never tried to profit from the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ann's success has nothing to do with Bill,'' said Seattle
consultant Jonathan Lazarus, a longtime friend of both.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't supply capital for her. He doesn't make contacts for
her. She doesn't depend on him for introductions, references or
deals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gates-Winblad duo was apparently a merger of workaholics.
</P>
<P>
   Gates has described one of his favorite trips with Winblad when
they spent a week holed up in Santa Barbara watching videos about
biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched movies for hours even when it was sunny outside,''
Gates told Wired magazine in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our fun discoveries was a series of brilliant lectures
Richard Feynman gave on physics which Ann subsequently made
available to high school students.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Winblad doesn't like to talk about her
relationship with the nation's richest man, although the two are
still good friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to a lot of big dogs in this industry,'' Winblad says,
changing the subject when the topic arises.
</P>
<P>
   Gates is now married and has a daughter. Winblad has no
children, but spoils her two dogs _ both Samoyeds, or Siberian sled
dogs _ and the children of her friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's great with my kids, they call her Auntie Ann,'' said
longtime friend Heidi Roizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really gets far more down and dirty with my kids than you
would expect and she's a little bit Auntie Mame-ish with giving
presents.''
</P>
<P>
   Roizen, a Silicon Valley consultant, said Winblad treats her
entrepreneurs the same way: She likes to rumble with them and
shower them with money.
</P>
<P>
   When Roizen was CEO of T/ Maker, she said Winblad helped her
make a pivotal decision that turned the company around _ to get out
of the word processing software market.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't walk in one day and say, `You're going to divest
this product line,''' Roizen said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Winblad, who was a director and major investor in the
company, waited for Roizen to suggest the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``But once the cat was out of the bag, she really pushed me on
it,'' Roizen recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very tough but I grew a lot under her mentoring.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-22-98 2224EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
