<HEADLINE>
COMICS, CRATERS AND COOL COUPLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By TOMMY CUMMINGS   
 c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELEMENTARY SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   Ever get busted in chemistry class for reading a comic book
instead of your textbook? It's too late now, but had the Web been
around, you might have gotten off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   You could have informed the teacher that you were involved with
the Periodic Table of Comic Books project
(www.uky.edu/\Pholler/periodic/periodic.html).
</P>
<P>
   The project was created in 1994 by Jack Selegue and F. James
Holler, University of Kentucky chemistry professors with an
affinity for comic books.
</P>
<P>
   Their site's main page features the all-too-familiar elements
table, but instead of a mind-numbing lesson, you get a comic-book
image or story that features the element.
</P>
<P>
   Click on the symbol for iron (Fe) and up pops the cover of
Marvel's Iron Man. Click on Krypton (Kr) and _ yep _ you get the
element that makes Superman want to hurl.
</P>
<P>
   Selegue points out that many comic-book writers used science as
a basis for character ideas and plot developments drawn from
physics. Examples: X-Men are chemically altered mutants, and the
Fantastic Four were overexposed to cosmic rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``On close inspection, the attitudes of comic-book writers and
artists toward their readers, traditionally children, become
apparent,'' Selegue said.
</P>
<P>
   Geez, where was Selegue when we needed him?
</P>
<P>
   MAKING AN IMPACT
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of fun with science, NASA's Earth and
space-science site (observe.ivv.nasa.gov) is featuring impact
craters and tsunamis to coincide with this summer's disaster
movies, ``Armageddon'' and ``Deep Impact.'' In a recent news
release, NASA is promoting two online articles about the possible
aftereffects of a celestial collision.
</P>
<P>
   FIND A COUPLE THAT CLICKS
</P>
<P>
   Help Bruce Willis and Demi Moore find new spouses at Hollywood
Online's Bruce &AMP; Demi Matchmaker poll (www.hollywood.com). For
Willis, the choices are Elizabeth Berkley, Cher and Phyllis Diller
(Phyllis Willis, get it?). For Moore, it's Rob Lowe, Brad Pitt or
Jonathan Demme (Demi Demme, get it?).
</P>
<P>
   _ Tommy Cummings (817) 390-7397
</P>
<P>
   dragon\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-22-98 1729EDT &QL;
</P>
