<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-LA-INTERNET-KIDPORN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. POLICE CITE NET THREAT TO KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   BY PATRICK McGREEVY AND DOUGLAS HABERMAN   
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Saying that arrests for Internet-related crimes
against children in Los Angeles are up 150 percent over last year,
Police Chief Bernard Parks warned parents to watch their
youngsters' computer use more closely.
</P>
<P>
   Because if they don't, pedophiles certainly will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people have been enticed to meet pedophiles, or they are
sent a bus ticket,'' Parks said during a news conference Wednesday.
``These are things we think come about from unsupervised
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks said an ``explosion'' in the number of home computers has
given pedophiles infinitely more opportunity to troll the Internet
for new victims and trade photos.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the LAPD unit that handles sex crimes against
children says it has arrested 15 people for computer-related crimes
involving minors _ compared to six arrests last year _ and is
investigating 14 other reports.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the anonymity of the Internet, police are unsure
exactly how many pedophiles lurk in cyberspace, but they said
detectives constantly are busy trying to outfox computer-savvy
molesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get cases every day,'' said Detective Raul Galindo of the
Los Angeles Police Department's Child Sexual Exploitation Unit.
``This is new, and this is more underground than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The unit has five detectives that handle sex crimes against
minors, the same as last year despite the growing problem. But none
of them can devote time exclusively to Internet porn, said
Detective Bill Dworin, head of the child sex crime unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a computer nerd in here,'' Dworin said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that many parents are caught unaware by the
dangers of the Internet, the city also is grappling with how _ and
whether _ to control online access in public libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Library policy now places the responsibility for restricting
children's Internet access on their parents and guardians. A June 9
memorandum from the City Attorney's Office recommends that if any
revision is planned, it should be an interim policy to protect
children from obscene materials without infringing the rights of
adult library patrons. The City Council's Arts, Health and
Humanities Committee is scheduled to revisit the issue Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Internet-related crime against children falls generally into
several categories: the downloading, distribution and production of
photographs and pornographic material, and the solicitation of
minors through ``chat rooms'' and bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   New technology has allowed pedophiles to scan pictures into
computers at home and even take videotape and send it anywhere on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's material that we have never seen before. These are
children who are being molested now,'' Dworin said. ``These are
children we are trying to identify.''
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a 13-year-old Los Angeles girl was lured into
meeting a man from San Diego to have sex, and she was molested
while a video camera captured it, Dworin said.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, the LAPD arrested veteran rock guitarist Robert
``Waddy'' Wachtel and his wife, Annie, on suspicion of possessing
child pornography. Police said they found illegal images on his
computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The victims were are dealing with often lack attention and
affection at home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell our children don't talk to strangers,'' Dworin said.
``We then give the child a computer and put it in their bedroom to
be used as a baby-sitting tool and frequently parents have no idea
who their children are contacting in the various chat rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Internet spans the world, Dworin said detectives
have found that many pedophiles and networks of them operate out of
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``One investigation may easily lead to many others based upon
what is found on computers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to laws against physical molestation of children,
Dworin said it is illegal to use sexual language in computer
conversations with children. Upon a second conviction of that
misdemeanor law, the person must register as a sex offender, Dworin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other crimes that have led to arrests by his unit include
distribution of child pornography for commercial purposes and
production of child pornography. The latter crime, if for private
viewing, is a misdemeanor and could lead to one year in jail; if
for commercial purposes, a conviction would draw a maximum sentence
of eight years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Computer technology, however, also can be used to block children
from viewing unacceptable material. But child advocates said that
parents themselves are the best guardians.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet can be a powerful learning tool but ``in order to
keep it like it is, parents have got to keep kids away from the
dangers,'' said Jayne Murphy Shapiro, founder and president of
Granada Hills-based Kids Safe, an advocacy group on child safety
education.
</P>
<P>
   Educate your children to the dangers, set rules and impose
discipline if they break them _ just like for any other activity,
said Shapiro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents do not have to know how to use a computer _ but they
do have to teach their kids when they're on it to be very
careful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-23-98 0110EDT &QL;
</P>
