 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 RealNetworks, Apple Take Aim At Microsoft  
 By Julia Angwin   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new front has opened in the government's war against
Microsoft: multimedia software.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, antitrust allegations against the software giant have
focused mostly on its Web browsing software and on agreements with
Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday, Rob Glaser, CEO of RealNetworks in Seattle, told
a congressional panel that Microsoft's latest multimedia software
causes his firm's competing software to ``break.''
</P>
<P>
   And Apple Computer disclosed that the Justice Department is
investigating whether Microsoft tried to bully Apple out of the
multimedia software market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one more segment of the industry stepping forward
and saying, `It's happening to us, too,''' said Ed Black, president
of the Computer and Communications Industry Association in
Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The new claims illustrate how broadly Microsoft's influence is
felt in the high-tech industry. And they also could spur the
Department of Justice to expand its antitrust case against the
Redmond, Wash., company.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft denies both allegations, saying the problem with
RealNetworks was due to a technical glitch and that it never tried
to bully Apple. However, Microsoft refused to send a representative
to defend the company during the congressional hearing chaired by
Senator Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't feel it was a sincere effort to provide a balanced
forum, and we chose not to participate,'' said Microsoft spokesman
Greg Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the panel of speakers at the Senate Judiciary Committee
hearing yesterday read like a list of Microsoft rivals: Larry
Ellison, the outspoken Microsoft critic who is CEO of Oracle Corp.;
Mitchell Kertzman of Sybase (which makes competing database
software); Jeff Papows of Lotus (a division of IBM that makes
competing office software); and Rob Glaser of RealNetworks (which
makes competing multimedia software).
</P>
<P>
   Many of the CEOs rehashed to the committee complaints that they
already had taken public _ such as Kertzman's allegation that
Microsoft tried to force him out of the market by giving away its
software for free.
</P>
<P>
   But RealNetworks CEO Glaser, a former Microsoft senior vice
president who had been silent in the Microsoft debate, stunned the
industry by joining the ranks of Microsoft critics.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser's change of heart was especially surprising because
Microsoft owns a 10 percent stake in his firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here because Microsoft is taking actions that simply stop
our company's products from working,'' Glaser told the committee.
``This is not fair play.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaser demonstrated how RealNetworks' video playing software
stopped working after he loaded Microsoft's competing product onto
a personal computer. He said Microsoft had refused to fix the
problem despite repeated requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft asks consumers in its advertisements, `Where do you
want to go today?''' Glaser said. ``But if Microsoft continues on
its present course, consumers will increasingly be asking, `Is
there anywhere I can go except where Microsoft wants me to?'''
</P>
<P>
   However, Microsoft said it has traced the problem to a glitch in
RealNetworks' software _ not its own. Microsoft said it soon will
post a description of the bug on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, allegations emerged that Microsoft asked Apple
to curtail its development of multimedia software called QuickTime.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported yesterday that Microsoft asked
Apple three times to stop making QuickTime for Windows in exchange
for Microsoft endorsing other Apple software.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft denied the charges. Apple executives would not comment
but confirmed that they had been subpoenaed by the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multimedia is one area where Microsoft and Apple have some
disagreements, but we're trying to resolve them professionally,''
added Apple spokeswoman Katie Cotton.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations could add fodder to the pending antitrust case
against Microsoft, which was filed in May by the Justice Department
and 20 states. The suit accuses Microsoft of using its Windows
monopoly to promote its Web browser software.
</P>
<P>
   However, experts say it's unlikely that government prosecutors
could include new charges before the trial date of September 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have time to investigate these charges while they
are getting ready for trial,'' said Rich Gray, an antitrust
attorney in San Jose. ``But once they get to the other end of this
trial, then they'll come back to it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
