u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-CONGRESS-MICROSOF     07-29 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CONGRESS-MICROSOFT-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLY OR FOE? A COMPLAINT ON MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of a young, fast-growing software
company testified at a Senate hearing Thursday that Microsoft Corp.
had introduced a competing product that crippled his company's most
recent technology.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors commonly complain that Microsoft business practices
are unfair. But this complaint appears particularly intriguing
because it comes from a company with close ties to Microsoft _ and
one that is engaged in a promising niche of the Internet software
market in which the government is investigating Microsoft tactics.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint was made by Robert Glaser, a former Microsoft
executive. Microsoft holds a 10 percent stake in his Seattle
company, Real Networks Inc., and licenses Real Networks technology.
After his appearance before the Senate Judiciary Committee, Glaser
said, ``I loved my 10 years at Microsoft and, even after today, I
think I have friends there.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaser's company is the leader in the emerging field of
so-called streaming software, which is used for sending recorded
voice and television-style video over the Internet and receiving
such multimedia programming on personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser's appearance before the committee included a computer
demonstration of how the latest version of Microsoft's software for
receiving streaming media, Windows Media Player, cannot play
Internet multimedia programming that is based on the latest Real
Networks technology.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser also read excerpts from an e-mail exchange with Bill
Gates, Microsoft's chairman, starting on July 6. Glaser said he
first became concerned about the problem caused by Microsoft's new
program, and the potential effect on his company, in May.
</P>
<P>
   By July, Glaser said, he was growing increasingly alarmed. Sen.
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the chairman of the Judiciary Committee, had
been in touch with him about testifying in Washington, and Glaser
sent Gates an e-mail saying that he might go. In his testimony,
Glaser suggested that the communication with his old boss was a
final effort to settle his dispute instead of voicing it publicly.
</P>
<P>
   According to Glaser's account, Gates seemed in no mood to reach
an accommodation. Glaser said that Gates had said he was ``not very
familiar with our business relationship'' and later added that he
found it ``interesting'' that Glaser felt he had no choice but to
go to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Gates closed his last e-mail to Glaser with what seemed to its
recipient a chilly dismissal. ``While you're in Washington, I
suggest you visit the National Gallery and the Smithsonian,'' Gates
wrote, according to Glaser.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft vigorously denies Glaser's version of the recent
conflict between the two companies. Microsoft officials say the
software breakdown that seemed to be so convincingly shown by
Glaser's computer demonstration in the Senate hearing room applies
only to a test, or beta, version of Real Networks' software that
was posted on its Web site for downloading only a week or so ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This smoking gun turns out to be a water pistol,'' said Mark
Murray, a Microsoft spokesman. ``That demonstration was something
of a misleading stunt.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Microsoft, Glaser was mainly using his Senate
appearance as a negotiating ploy. And Microsoft was able to present
that view forcefully before the committee, thanks to its allies in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., introduced an
affidavit of Paul Maritz, a group vice president at Microsoft. The
affidavit said Glaser called Maritz on Wednesday afternoon and said
that he was prepared to ``negotiate all night if that's what it
takes'' to come to terms with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The Maritz affidavit added, ``Mr. Glaser said that if the
negotiations he proposed for the night of July 22 resulted in an
agreement between the two companies, he would not testify the next
day before the Senate Judiciary Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after the hearing, Glaser said his call to
Maritz was merely a courtesy call. At the time, Glaser said, he was
in Washington and on his way to speak to Hatch before appearing
Thursday. The Maritz affidavit, Glaser said, ``is simply not
true.'' ``I was locked, loaded and ready to testify,'' Glaser said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The committee hearing comes prior to a trial of the Justice
Department's antitrust case against Microsoft, which is scheduled
to begin on Sept. 8 in U.S. District Court in Washington. The
government contends that the company is unfairly using its
near-monopoly of the market for desktop personal computer software
to dominate the new market for Internet software.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives characterized Glaser's allegation as an
inexplicably overwrought reaction. ``We are still willing to have
our engineers sit down with the engineers of Real Networks and work
these problems out,'' said Murray, the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, agreement among the engineers might be difficult as well.
Wednesday night, after six hours of software testing by its
programmers, Microsoft had concluded that the problem was with Real
Networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a bug in their program, not ours,'' said Yusuf Mehdi, an
executive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-23-98 2142EDT &QL;
</P>
