<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-CHILDCARE25-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Company developes child care internet computer system 
By Sanjay Bhatt  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH _ A Palm Beach Internet company's plans could help
the Murphy Browns of the world spend more time with their kids.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe inspire a few budding Murphy Browns, too.
</P>
<P>
   While some Internet companies use videocameras to give parents
the ability to watch their child in day care, Safe Technologies
International plans to take the concept a step further and give
parents the ability to have a conversation ``face-to-face'' on a
computer screen with their child or child's teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is using a novel business strategy to bring its
child care computer system to market: Rather than selling its
services to day-care centers, Safe Technologies is focused on
buying these centers and weaving its services into their programs.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Safe Technologies announced it had signed a letter
of intent to buy its first child-care center operator, Toddler's
Learning Center, which runs two day-care centers in Stuart. Twelve
teachers and 13 other employees run a pre-school for children from
infants to the age of 5 and an after-school program for children
from ages 5 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to buy more child-care centers over the next
few years in Florida and the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We envision mothers who travel a lot will use this,'' said
Barbara Tolley, the 61-year-old chairwoman and CEO of Safe
Technologies International. ``She could carry a laptop and an
Internet phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Safe Technologies is a penny-stock company that emerged five
months ago from Tolley's take-over of Safe Aid Products, a holder
of patents on medical products. It employ 15 people, five in Palm
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   While its shares (SFAD) were selling for only about 10 cents
Thursday on the Over The Counter market, Safe Technologies has some
influential partners. In May, it announced that it signed a deal
with AT&AMP;T to put the phone company's Internet access software on
all Safe Technologies' new Internet software products.
</P>
<P>
   Tolley said Thursday that VocalTec Communications Ltd., an
Israeli company that had $7.7 million in losses on $15.7 million in
sales in 1997, will provide the technology for
video-teleconferencing. VocalTec's Internet Phone provides
real-time, two-way voice transmission over computer (much like a CB
radio), thus avoiding long-distance line charges.
</P>
<P>
   Hed goes here In general, Internet companies who sell the
monitoring service use a camera to capture a child's image in a
room every few seconds and transmit it to a secured computer.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and other authorized users, such as grandparents, must
have an Internet address and password to access the image from
their computer via phone lines. Many such Internet sites also give
parents news of upcoming events, report cards and immediate
emergency notices.
</P>
<P>
   Safe Technologies plans to use a similar set-up and will add
teleconferencing equipment to simulate a face-to-face conversation.
The company also is considering giving parents CD-ROMs with
age-appropriate educational content developed by child-care centers
to reinforce lessons taught.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just so many ramifications of how this (Internet)
could be used,'' Tolley said.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right mix _ a profitable one _ is where Safe
Technologies hopes to buck the general trend of costly,
money-losing Internet ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole concept of this company is making acquisitions'' in
a variety of industries and integrating the Internet into the
company's operation to make it more efficient and profitable,
Tolley said. The company is looking to buy businesses in real
estate, technology, marketing, health care and travel.
</P>
<P>
   Safe Technologies has bought two companies since February _
Tampa-based Total Micro Computers, a computer systems seller, and
Miami-based Precision Imaging, a graphics printer which helps
produce Boca Raton Magazine, she said. She declined to say how much
the purchases cost.
</P>
<P>
   Tolley knows how much start-up capital Internet companies need
and how much money they can lose. As a marketing consultant, she
worked with AT&AMP;T in the early 1990s to develop a real estate search
engine for its private information services division.
</P>
<P>
   The product, PII.Net, moved to the Internet in 1995 before
another well-known search engine, Yahoo!, did, Tolley said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet's free-lunch culture sapped the product's
profitability, and Tolley said she moved on to develop an Internet
mall for ``the rich and famous,'' and a CD-ROM for real estate
brokers called Real Estate 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The CD-ROM _ which allows brokers to access information and hold
video teleconferences _ paved the way for Safe Technologies' child
care CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   Safe Technologies' plans to use videoconferencing and buy child
care centers is unique, say heads of similar Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard of anyone doing this with their own chain of
centers,'' said Seth Steinberg, president of Atlanta-based
ParentNet Inc., one of about 12 companies around the country that
sell Internet systems to day-care centers.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly 2-year-old company provides 4,000 parents and other
authorized users with glimpses of their children at day care over
the Internet and expects to double that number by September.
</P>
<P>
   The brainchild of Steinberg's wife, who is the company co-owner,
ParentNet will soon service day-care centers in Jacksonville and
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Hed goes here Boca Raton-based Center-View.com Inc. also markets
an Internet system to child-care systems.
</P>
<P>
   ParentNet's monitoring service adds about $2 to the $120 a week
that parents pay for day care, Steinberg said. ``We expect true
growth to come in the future as it's accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg isn't so sure Safe Technologies' videoconferencing
will be a hit with education-oriented centers. ``It's disruptive to
the classroom. What's nice about (our) system is parents don't poke
their head in.''
</P>
<P>
   Observing his own 9-month-old boy and 3-year-old girl has
convinced Steinberg this technology's time has come.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows you to see the games they like best, the kids they
interact with, how they nap. . . . It gets you in sync with them so
when you spend time with them you're reinforcing routines. That's
what a child needs _ structure and routine.''
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-23-98 2314E
</P>
