<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-HEALTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS: COMPUTER BUG POSES HEALTH CARE CRISIS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By ANDREW J. GLASS  
c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's health care industry has fallen victim
to the millennium bug syndrome _ with no quick cure in sight.
</P>
<P>
   That was the diagnosis reached on Thursday by Sen. Bob Bennett,
R-Utah, who chairs a special Senate panel on the Year 2000 computer
glitch. As Bennett sees it: ``If tonight when the clock strikes
midnight the calendar flipped to Dec. 31, 1999, large portions of
the health care system would fail.''
</P>
<P>
   His views were echoed by Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who
said what people really want to know is whether ``people are going
to die as a result of Year 2000 complications in the medical
industry?''
</P>
<P>
   Dodd's answer: ``I don't think so. There's no need to put people
into a sense of panic. But it's entirely possible that millennium
conversion could put the health care industry into intensive
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Potential industry problems include the need to replace
thousands of kidney dialysis units, costing $14,000 apiece, that
will improperly shut down for maintenance when they are unable to
read the correct date. Similarly, there is concern about
malfunctioning computer-based scanners and patients' medical
records that become locked up or lost as systems fail.
</P>
<P>
   Rural and inner city hospitals and clinics are expected to be
especially hard-hit in light of their limited resources to finance
fixes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the key issues raised at the hearing:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Health Care Financing Administration, which pays Medicare
claims, admitted that it recently had to revise its estimate of its
bug-infested programs from 20 million to 49 million lines of
computer code after an outside contractor performed an audit. But
Nancy-Ann DeParle, the agency's administrator, said ``we are making
substantial progress in addressing the Year 2000 problem'' after
she had made it her ``top priority.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Food and Drug Administration has achieved only a 10
percent response rate to its repeated inquiries to the makers of
medical devices seeking Year 2000 compliance data. But Michael
Friedman, the FDA acting chief, said that the data gathered so far
shows ``no indications that there will be significant problems
which will place patients at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not reassuring,'' Dodd told Friedman, citing the low
response rate. ``I find that frightening. We've got to have the FDA
become a lot more aggressive about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharing the senators' concern, Jennifer Jackson, speaking for
the 5,000-member American Hospitals Association, called on Congress
to enact legislation that would force medical equipment makers to
impart information on whether their devices are Year 2000
compliant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have the legislative or regulatory authority to
compel disclosure,'' Jackson noted.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association also voiced its concern over
the threat the Year 2000 problem poses to patient care. A
spokesman, Donald Palmisano, called on Congress to work with the
health care industry to forge a uniform definition of Year 2000
``compliant'' with regard to medical devices.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a bevy of administration and industry witnesses in the
health field, Bennett and Dodd cast doubt on optimistic government
forecasts that a fix would be in place before their
mission-critical systems were put at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The senators also berated makers of biomedical devices for
having failed to set up a central clearing house where the data
needed to repair the problem could be processed.
</P>
<P>
   But Ramin Mojdeh, speaking for the Health Industry Manufacturers
Association, stressed the complexity of the problem, which came
about when programmers wrote software and designed chips that can't
decode dates in 2000 or beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found that the challenge posed by the Year 2000 bug
doesn't represent a single problem that will yield to a single
solution,'' Mojdeh said, because the sensitivity to the bug varies
dramatically among medical devices.
</P>
<P>
   The Medical Device Manufacturers Association, excluded from
testifying at the hearing, contended that the risk posed the Year
2000 problem has been ``overstated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer technology is not a component of most medical devices
and the vast majority of medical equipment that does rely upon
computer hardware and software is not date-sensitive,'' the trade
group argued.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has set up a web site,
www.fda.gov/cdrh/yr2000/year2000.html, that contains information on
products identified by their manufacturers as not being Year 2000
compliant as well as a list of those products said by their makers
to be unaffected by the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
