<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7886 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-WEBSITE     07-29 1630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-WEBSITE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT'S HOMEADVISOR SITE PLAGUED WITH PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ARTHUR M. LOUIS   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. has created a new Web site called HomeAdvisor,
which it claims will provide you all the help you need to buy a
house and find a mortgage loan.
</P>
<P>
   But the site, at www.homeadvisor.com, is bogged down by
technical glitches and information gaps during what Microsoft calls
a ``preview'' stage, which began about two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the promised features are missing, and the site is
plagued with technical problems that make it tough to use _
sometimes impossible, depending on your browser.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says it started with a preview version to iron out the
kinks and get consumer reaction. It says the site will be
``substantially modified'' over the coming weeks _ which would be a
good thing. Right now, it is about as useful as a house without a
roof.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Ian Morris, lead product manager for HomeAdvisor, why
Microsoft would jeopardize its world-class reputation by posting a
primitive, faulty Web site, even temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   He replied that ``you really can't predict every issue'' before
activating a site. He contends that despite the glitches, the site
has gotten ``tons of positive responses'' from users.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers point out that Microsoft has done this sort
of thing before _ putting out bug-ridden products to establish a
position in a market before gradually improving the quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sooner they get into a market and make everyone nervous _
so no one else will come in _ the better,'' says one veteran
Microsoft-watcher. ``It's like a dog marking its territory.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Microsoft, once HomeAdvisor progresses from
``preview'' to ``officially live,'' you will be able to use it to
tap into all 500-plus Multiple Listing Services nationwide and call
up data and photos for all the houses offered for sale in any
neighborhood you choose.
</P>
<P>
   You will be able to screen them by community, neighborhood,
price, size and amenities _ such as air conditioning, family rooms
and formal dining areas.
</P>
<P>
   If you find a house that seems appealing, you can enter data
about your finances to find a mortgage loan that suits you. And you
can contact a lender online, to see whether you qualify.
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft makes good on all those promises, it should have
the most useful home-buying site on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, that distinction belongs to San Francisco-based
HomeShark, which operates a Web site at www.homeshark.com.
HomeShark has the edge now because it has a much more complete
database than HomeAdvisor.
</P>
<P>
   HomeAdvisor is woefully short of listings. Even where houses are
listed, the photos haven't materialized yet. And the choice of
mortgage lenders is slim _ just three institutions in the entire
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, the Web site is a technological nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   When I tried navigating with Netscape, I frequently got stymied
by blank white screens or error messages _ especially the dreaded,
fatal ``JavaScript'' error, from which there is no appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on it,'' says Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that the sly technicians at Microsoft built
incompatibility into the site to discredit arch-rival Netscape?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. Morris says HomeAdvisor also doesn't work well
with Microsoft's own Internet Explorer, version 3.0.
</P>
<P>
   HomeAdvisor does work with Internet Explorer 4.0 but just
barely. After you bring up the site _ which can take several
minutes _ you encounter interminable delays as you move from page
to page. The experience is as frustrating as coaxing a lame mule up
Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   Morris says that's partly because the site has been handling
traffic ``many times higher than expected'' since it opened on
Bastille Day. ``We've added some servers, and the performance has
gotten better.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Microsoft, HomeAdvisor currently offers listings
for only about a fourth of the 1.2 million or so homes nationwide
that real estate agents list for sale at any given moment.
</P>
<P>
   There are big gaps in the Bay Area: few or no listings for San
Francisco, Mill Valley and Pleasanton, for example. On the other
hand, there are plenty of listings for San Mateo, Burlingame and
Montara.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know anything about Montara before using HomeAdvisor,
so I seized the opportunity to test the site's demographics
section, which offers background information on every community.
</P>
<P>
   HomeAdvisor says that Montara, located on the coast in San Mateo
County, has 2,832 residents and a median household income of
$83,555. It describes Montara as a place where people ``play
racquetball ... rent foreign videos ... own an Acura ... read
Rolling Stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Its students rack up good test scores, perhaps because the ratio
of students to teachers is less than 19. But if you want a more
complete report on the schools, you have to pay $34. There also is
an extra charge _ $20 _ for detailed crime statistics.
</P>
<P>
   That seems exorbitant. School information is available free from
the board of education in virtually every California community.
Crime statistics are available free from the Federal Bureau of
Investigation, among other sources.
</P>
<P>
   Morris says Microsoft is still negotiating to get home data from
most of the Multiple Listing Services. It has signed up less than
half of them, and many of those still haven't been included online.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the things that makes this project
challenging,'' Morris remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Each home listing is supposed to be accompanied by a color
photograph _ but I couldn't find any, despite numerous attempts.
Whenever I called up the data on a particular house, I found a
rectangular frame surrounding the legend ``No Photo Available.''
</P>
<P>
   Photos will be added soon, Morris promises.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft eventually plans to give HomeAdvisor users a broad
selection of mortgage lenders to choose from, but at the moment it
has lined up only American Finance and Investment, Principal
Residential Mortgage and Homeside Lending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a number of discussions,'' Morris says. ``But those
three give the average consumer a good starting point. They offer
broad coverage, good pricing and great service.''
</P>
<P>
   In reviewing HomeAdvisor, I compared it head to head with
HomeShark.
</P>
<P>
   I pretended to be a prospective buyer interested in houses in
San Mateo with at least three bedrooms and priced between $350,000
and $400,000. San Mateo is one of the more prominent Bay Area
communities already included in HomeAdvisor.
</P>
<P>
   HomeAdvisor came up with 16 houses that fit the parameters,
while HomeShark produced 13.
</P>
<P>
   It was impossible to tell how much the listings overlapped,
because HomeShark didn't disclose seven of the addresses.
HomeAdvisor disclosed them all.
</P>
<P>
   I focused on a house on 30th Avenue, with an asking price of
$399,000, that appeared on both lists. HomeShark showed a color
photo of the house, while HomeAdvisor didn't, but otherwise
HomeAdvisor's display was more useful.
</P>
<P>
   I learned from HomeAdvisor that the house has interior space of
1,247 square feet, three bedrooms, two bathrooms, a fireplace and a
two-car garage.
</P>
<P>
   HomeShark mentions the number of rooms and bathrooms, but
nothing else. It refers homebuyers who want more information to the
listing broker.
</P>
<P>
   The pages that display information on individual houses follow a
uniform format on HomeAdvisor. On HomeShark they differ greatly,
because the listing agents design them. Some agents don't include
photos.
</P>
<P>
   If you are ready to look for a mortgage loan, HomeShark directs
you to eight lenders, all with a large assortment of mortgages.
That gives it an edge over HomeAdvisor, with its three lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike HomeAdvisor, HomeShark doesn't provide demographic
information.
</P>
<P>
   There are several other Web sites designed for people who want
to find or finance homes. None of them offers the breadth of
information you get from HomeShark, or will get _ the gods of
technology willing _ from HomeAdvisor. Some of them provide only
loan information, with no home listings.
</P>
<P>
   The following sites deserve at least a look from prospective
homebuyers:
</P>
<P>
   _www.quicken.com, from Intuit, provides as much detailed
information on individual houses as HomeAdvisor intends to provide.
But it covers only about 40 percent of the United States. In the
Bay Area it is limited to Alameda and Contra Costa counties. You
can use the site to get prequalified for a loan.
</P>
<P>
   _www.realtor.com, sponsored by the National Association of
Realtors, purports to contain every real estate listing nationwide.
Yet I found only six in my control group _ San Mateo houses priced
in the $350,000 to $400,000 range. That's less than half the number
offered by HomeAdvisor and HomeShark. The listings don't include
square footage, addresses or photos.
</P>
<P>
   _www.bankrate.com, from Bank Rate Monitor, is the most
comprehensive of the mortgage-only sites, listing some 50 different
lenders and a huge variety of loans. You can apply for a loan
online.
</P>
<P>
   _www.eloan.com, from E-Loan Inc., provides a long list of
lenders and mortgages and lets you get the loan of your choice
preapproved online. However, you must pay a $9.95 preapproval fee.
</P>
<P>
   _www.homebynet.com, a joint venture of Banc One Mortgage and
NeoLogics Software, helps you find a loan and lender with minimal
fuss. You can get a prequalification verdict for free, without
disclosing your identity. The other Web sites won't let you stay
anonymous if you want to prequalify.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, once you actually apply for a loan, you have to tell
the lender who you are, and provide a lot of intimate details about
your finances.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-26-98 2151EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
