<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7887 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTIN-HOSTEL30-COX     07-29 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-HOSTEL30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin hostel provides unique view of city
 &HT;    By James Hibberd
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Taos has teepees. Yosemite a mountain cabin. Portland a
lighthouse and Hartford a Victorian mansion. Death Valley has a
squat mobile home on hardpan desert and, in its publicity photo,
you can almost see heat waves baking young travelers inside.
</P>
<P>
   Austin has . . .well, what does Austin have? If hostels are, as
one veteran traveler said, the windows through which a city is
viewed, then the Austin hostel is a one-way mirror. The modest
building on Lakeshore Drive is tucked away on the southeast side of
Town Lake, unseen by most of the city's bustling downtown and
university populations. Our hostel is so nondescript even neighbors
stop to ask what it is (''It's what?'' they reply. ``A hotel? A
hospital?'').
</P>
<P>
   Looks can be deceiving. Inside this small hostel, more than
9,000 visitors from every corner of the globe each year make a
temporary home in 40 beds. They come to Austin, almost all for the
first time and most staying no longer than a week, and peer at our
city through the prism of this lakeside window. They see Austin
unfettered by traffic, environmental threats, crime, racism or
political bickering _ a snapshot of a place these travelers say is
one of the friendliest cities in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Hostel territory
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pollard returns the hostel's rental canoe to the storage
shed, towels off and comes inside to escape the 95-degree noontime
heat. He's in the hostel's common area, where European flags hang
from the high ceiling and several hungover guests watch TV or bury
their tired faces between couch cushions. Sunlight beams through
the large picture windows and prevents any serious napping.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard's girlfriend stops writing an e-mail on the hostel
computer and looks at him quizzically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Been canoeing,'' he explains in his strong English accent.
``Not quite Belize revisited, but refreshing nonetheless.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollard, 30, is wearing Tevas, shorts and a T-shirt. It's the
unofficial hosteling uniform and, if you get a group of guests
together, they look like a staff of summer camp counselors.
</P>
<P>
   They're at an Austin summer camp for adventurers who can't
afford fancier travel accommodations. This camp is one link in the
5,000-plus Hostelling International chain, a non-profit network of
beds, baths and communal kitchen for globetrotters on the cheap.
Formerly called ``Youth Hostels,'' the network now accepts visitors
of all ages, but 18-to-30 year olds still dominate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the U.K., most hostels are in old houses, but this is
really clean and folks here go out of their way to help you _ it's
the best we've stayed in,'' Pollard says. ``We came here because we
heard that Austin's the best place for live music. It's all rather
brilliant. I think Austin's kind of . . . radical? Liberal?''
</P>
<P>
   On his way back to the men's sleeping quarters, Pollard chats
with Keith Burns, a 20-year-old from Atlanta, who is sweeping the
floor. Last night, Burns learned how to acquire drinks on Sixth
Street without a legal ID and plans to perfect his technique
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible here,'' he says of Austin's nightlife. ``In
Atlanta, a girl won't even talk to you unless you have a hot car.
Here, all you have to do is smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns performs three hours of daily cleaning in exchange for a
free stay (the price is normally $13 for Hostelling International
members, $16 for non-members). This is his first hosteling
experience, a warm-up before taking on the European hostel circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected a bunch of cots in a big gym, where you'd have to
keep an eye on your stuff,'' Burns says. ``Even the name `hostel'
sounds like a trashy, rugged place. This is like a small resort. We
got TV, AC, Internet _ anything goes here.''
</P>
<P>
   Except littering. Bobby Peele and his wife Sam, who run the
hostel, require few of the chores demanded of guests at many
hostels, but they do insist visitors put trash in the appropriate
bins. It's tougher than you think, since there's a half-dozen
separate recycling containers for every sort of waste, from paper
to colored glass to compost.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the environmental emphasis that's been
characteristic of the Austin hostel since it opened in 1989 (the
only other Texas hostels are in San Antonio, Houston and El Paso).
The Lakeshore Drive facility has the distinction being the first
U.S. hostel to operate entirely on solar power and sponsors a Town
Lake clean-up four times a year.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental philosophy is not just the Peeles' ideology,
but the pioneering spirit of hosteling. A German school teacher,
Richard Schirrmann, founded the movement in the early 1900s, saying
the industrial revolution was depriving students of the opportunity
to travel and experience nature.
</P>
<P>
   So this is Austin
</P>
<P>
   A young man from New York climbed out of a taxi. Setting down
his backpack, he paused to survey the hostel. The lawn was green
and glorious Town Lake peeked around the sides. Sitting on the
grass was pretty, nose-ringed hostel staffer Teresa Barber.
</P>
<P>
   The young man spread his arms and said, ``So this is Texas!''
</P>
<P>
   Barber relates the story with a laugh. She sits behind the
check-in counter next to local entertainment listings and collage
of postcards sent from around the world. Under the counter are
supplies such as razors, shampoo and patches that say ``I Sleep
With Strangers at the Austin Hostel.'' One of her job
responsibilities is feeding Town Lake ducks that waddle up from the
shore.
</P>
<P>
   She's waiting for the nightly wave of incoming travelers. About
60 percent are from U.S. cities and the rest from abroad. If, as
happens about 15 weekends per year, she fills the hostel's 40 bunk
beds (in four rooms separated by sex), she'll call the
Goodall-Wooten or Taos Cooperative, University of Texas-area
private dormitories that accept hostelers during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get people in here and they're so excited,'' Barber says.
``They're like, `Where's Sixth Street? How can we see the bats?
Where's Stevie Ray Vaughan?''
</P>
<P>
   Some guests are so excited, they don't go home.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Boyle, 23, is one of many hostel visitors using the
facilities while establishing residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got here, I was staying at this $200 weekly-rate
motel on South Congress,'' says the San Diego transplant.
``Prostitutes were going in and out and somebody robbed the food
mart next door.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Boyle looked up ``Hostel'' in the Yellow Pages and moved
into the Lakeshore Drive facilities. Although guests are only
typically allowed to stay for one week, Boyle has been allotted a
little more time while he searches for a job and an apartment. He
says his South Congress experience hasn't spoiled the otherwise
pleasant culture shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the coast, everybody's gotta have this front, an
attitude,'' he says. ``I expected everybody to be really laid back
and friendly in Austin, and I heard right.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the hosteler's point of origin, observations like
Boyle's are the common denominator: Austin's so friendly, the live
music is so wonderful, the residents are so laid back . . .
</P>
<P>
   The flattering phrases are a cliched litany we hear less
frequently nowadays around Austin and they lend a sense of
nostalgia to the 9-year-old hostel. It's as if the environmental,
youthful and idyllic Austin has been bottled up in this little
building. Travelers seek the Austin they've heard so much about and
still find it among the soaring rents and congested traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, to visit the hostel, to stay among visitors who've
never been to Austin before, is to be reminded of why people choose
to live here. Travelers look through this window and see what we've
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you learn most working here,'' Barber says, ``is how much
we take Austin for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information: Hostelling International-Austin 2200 S.
Lakeshore Blvd. Austin, TX 78741 Phone 444-2294 Hostelling
International-American Youth Hostels U.S. National Administrative
Office: 733 15th St. N.W., Suite 840, Washington, D.C. 20005. Phone
202-783-6161 Hostelling International-American Youth Hostels:
http://www.hiayh.org/ Hostelling International:
http://www.iyhf.org/ Memberships
</P>
<P>
   A one-year Hostelling International membership is available for
$10 for those 17 and under, and $25 for adults. All ages are
welcome. Although membership is not required to stay, members pay
discount rates at hostels worldwide and receive discounts at
participating restaurants and attractions. Go to http://www.
hiayh.org/ for a complete directory of U.S. and international
hostels, tips and reservation information.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
