<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7888 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALAMANDER-CONSERVATI     07-29 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALAMANDER-CONSERVATION30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salamander-conservation plan for Barton Springs pool debated
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox New Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Swimmer after swimmer at an Austin, Texas public
hearing recently criticized a proposed salamander-conservation plan
that calls for a new dam, reduced cleanings and other changes
intended to accommodate the endangered amphibians while allowing
public use of Barton Springs Pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to allow people to be forced out of that
pool,'' said Mark Gentle, a local lawyer and regular swimmer,
drawing a burst of applause from about 50 like-minded people at the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Leoda Anderson, a retired University of Texas administrative
assistant who has swum at the pool for more than 20 years, said:
``The salamanders have not suffered through 70 years of cleanings.
And nobody has produced a stepped-on salamander yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jack Lawrence, a computer programmer and 25-year pool user,
said swimmers are ``the truly endangered species. This is kind of a
ham-fisted approach. This is not an aquarium and there's no way it
can be absolutely safe for the salamander.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan was drafted by the City of Austin and is under review
by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service. The wildlife service listed
the 2.5-inch-long Barton Springs salamander as an endangered
species last year.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is a key part of the city's application to the wildlife
service for a permit that would allow continued cleaning, swimming
and wading even if salamanders occasionally were killed or injured
in the process. The city, in turn, would pursue conservation
measures estimated to cost about $2 million over the 15-year life
of the permit.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for a 3-foot-high dam separating the shallow and
deep ends. This would allow more frequent cleaning of the shallow
end without affecting the deep end, where the salamanders
congregate. The deep end would be lowered only four times a year
for cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a gravel-bottomed area known as the beach would be
deepened so that people would be less likely to step on
salamanders. And an area of limestone ledges and underground
openings known as the fissures would be roped off permanently.
Sunken Gardens, a nearby spring outlet that until recently was open
to unfettered public swimming, would be restricted to educational
uses.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Duncan, the city's environmental officer, said the plan,
including the number of deep-end cleanings, is subject to change.
Wildlife service officials agreed. ``This is a crown jewel for
Austin and always has been -- but also for the salamander,'' David
Frederick, the wildlife service's supervisor for interior Texas,
said in an interview. ``This proposal shows the rest of the nation
that Austin wants all things to exist.''
</P>
<P>
   But Grant Godfrey, a lawyer for the Save Our Springs Alliance,
an environmental group, criticized the federal agency and the city
for not doing more to guard against larger threats to the
salamander. Government and independent scientists agree that urban
development and a toxic spill are the main hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Runoff of stormwater washes soil, fertilizer, oil and other
pollutants into streams that feed an underground limestone
formation known as the Barton Springs segment of the Edwards
Aquifer. The formation supplies well water to 45,000 people and
flow at the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Roads, pipelines and railroad tracks across the watershed pose a
continuing threat of a gasoline or chemical spill that could wipe
out the species in a single stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason the salamander is endangered is that it cannot
escape upstream pollution, which all gets funneled through Barton
Springs,'' Godfrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Brandes, a local landowner, said the chafing by swimmers
and environmentalists at proposed pool-use restrictions was
reminiscent of how landowners reacted when the wildlife service
sought to limit property development to protect endangered
songbirds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Landowners have had to give up large percentages of land to
comply with the Endangered Species Act,'' Brandes said. ``What is
being asked of the swimming public is insignificant by
comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   The wildlife service is expected to make a final decision on the
city's conservation proposal in late August or early September,
Frederick said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
