r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOW-AIRFARE30-COX     07-29 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOW-AIRFARE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Agency's software scans for lowest airline prices
 &HT;    By Marguerite M. Plunkett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ The Travel Company of Delray Beach is
installing computer software that quickly searches all airfares
available to find the lowest rate, the company announced at its
first annual meeting recently.
</P>
<P>
   The system, called Flight Attendant, ``does what a perfect
travel agent would do: searches, searches, searches'' until it
finds plane tickets that fit the customer's needs, Chairman Joseph
Vittoria said.
</P>
<P>
   The installation of the system, which will occur at its
subsidiary Travel 800, is central to The Travel Company's intention
of offering one-stop shopping for travel.
</P>
<P>
   The Travel Company (Nasdaq: TRVL, $31.13) provides leisure
travel services, including booking flights, cruises, auto rentals
and lodging. Travel 800 in San Diego, which is one of 18 companies
under The Travel Company banner, sells discounted airline tickets
over the phone at 1-800-FLY-CHEAP. The company gets 500,000 calls a
month, Vittoria said. It charges a $10 shipping fee for each
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The Flight Attendant system automatically searches several
airline reservation systems as well as a database of discounted air
fares The Travel Company has negotiated, Vittoria said after the
meeting, held at the Boca Raton Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   The system, which The Travel Company developed, does
automatically what Vittoria says is too costly for a travel agent
to do because of the time involved.
</P>
<P>
   It also is designed to be more user friendly than current
systems. Maryann Bastnagel, senior vice president and chief
information officer, said employee training on the new system takes
about 2 1/2 days, compared with two or three weeks for current
systems.
</P>
<P>
   By October, consumers will be able to use the same Flight
Attendant system on the Internet to search for their own plane
tickets, Bastnagel said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also expects to start using the system in its
cruise-booking companies by the end of the year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
