A7893 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATESCHOOL-BUS30-COX     07-29 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATESCHOOL-BUS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    tate School sanctioned for use of steaming bus
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Throughout this fireball summer, nearly 40 people with
mental retardation were forced to endure bus rides on the Austin
State School campus in an unair-conditioned bus where temperatures
soared to 110 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   State inspectors deemed the situation life-threatening,
particularly because some of the disabled residents have seizure
disorders and take anticonvulsant drugs that put them at high risk
for heat stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too hot, too hot,'' screamed some of the residents, according
to Department of Human Services inspectors who boarded the bus at 4
p.m. July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Other residents, their faces bathed in sweat, became jumpy and
nervous while riding the bus, inspectors said in their report.
</P>
<P>
   Public health officials say heat stroke can be imminent for
people exposed to temperatures of 105 degrees or hotter.
</P>
<P>
   A bus driver told inspectors that at least two mentally retarded
passengers had seizures while riding the bus this summer, though it
was not clear whether the heat contributed to the seizures.
</P>
<P>
   Austin State School officials immediately stopped using the bus.
Although the air conditioning had been broken for nearly two years,
it was not repaired because the $7,000 cost was viewed as
prohibitive, said Doug Ferris, director of safety and
transportation at the institution at 35th Street and MoPac
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I realized how long they stayed on that bus, I was
flabbergasted,'' said Ruth Snyder, whose daughter lives at Austin
State School but does not ride the bus. ``I just couldn't believe
nobody cared enough to do anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin State School's decision to use the faulty bus is the
latest problem at the institution for 450 residents. Earlier this
month, DHS inspectors froze the institution's $57,000-a-day
Medicaid money because workers failed to report sexual activity
among residents. Inspectors cited improperly trained staff as part
of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the institution has a shortage of 35 workers. Some
recreational and vocational workers have been reassigned to direct
care, such as bathing and grooming. The school has also been forced
to start paying $100-a-month bonuses to direct-care workers willing
to work the evening shift.
</P>
<P>
   After human-services agency inspectors discovered the broken bus
air conditioner, the institution began using air-conditioned vans
to shuttle residents between their cottages and on-campus
workshops. Officials spent $4,400 to put seats in a bus that had
been used to carry wheelchair users. That bus was put into use on
Monday, Ferris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the bus was intended as an on-campus shuttle to prevent
individuals from having to walk from building to building in the
heat, there was clearly a better way to do that,'' said Karen Hale,
interim commissioner of the Texas Department of Mental Health and
Mental Retardation, which oversees Austin State School.
</P>
<P>
   Human-services inspectors reported the temperature inside the
bus was 110 degrees at 4 p.m. on July 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these clients remained on the bus for 30 minutes even
though the temperature never dropped below 105.4 Fahrenheit,''
their inspection report said. ``When the bus was in motion, the
temperature inside the bus dropped down to 105.4 Fahrenheit, and
when it stopped to pick up or drop off the clients, the temperature
would go up to 108.3 degrees Fahrenheit.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the school's Medicaid money already was halted, DHS
officials imposed a second hold on the money because of the problem
with the bus. Under the previous sanction, the school was given
until Oct. 1 to correct problems.
</P>
<P>
   The latest incident prompted regulators to put the school on a
fast-track correction plan. Now, all problems must be fixed by
mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid money, which pays about 85 percent of the institution's
operating costs, will be paid retroactively if Austin State School
corrects problems.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Murphree, a disability advocate at Advocacy Inc., a
federally funded agency that provides legal help to Texans with
disabilities, said her agency ``is shocked that the residents of
Austin State School would have their health and safety put at risk
day after day for two summers for the cost of air conditioning in a
bus.'' Jim Armstrong, superintendent of Austin State School, said
he had been unaware that the bus air conditioning was broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a mystery to me, to tell you the truth,'' he
said. ``I believe we had some people who probably, looking back on
it, wish they had called that in. But they didn't, so consequently
we went on transporting people in a bus that was not air
conditioned for, I guess, two years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me feel sad,'' he said. ``I felt bad about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
