u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTER-RESEARCH     07-29 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-RESEARCH-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL WILL URGE MAJOR SPENDING FOR COMPUTER RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A presidential advisory commission made up of
some of the nation's leading computer scientists plans to deliver a
report Monday to the White House, calling for a significant
increase in federal spending on advanced computer research in order
to create ``expeditions to the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, a draft of which was given to The New York Times by
someone close to the committee, calls current federal support for
research in information technology ``dangerously inadequate,'' and
too narrowly focused on ``near-term problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel, known as the Presidential Advisory Committee on High
Performance Computing and Communications, Information Technology
and the Next Generation Internet, has as its co-chairmen William
Joy, a founder of Sun Microsystems, and Ken Kennedy, a computer
scientist at Rice University.
</P>
<P>
   The draft report calls on the federal government to finance
research centers that will pursue broad-ranging computer research
in the spirit of the early explorers of North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much like Lewis and Clark opened the West,'' it says,
``virtual centers focused on future technologies and applications
can, by making bold assumptions about the future, give us key
research insights into the manifold possibilities of the 21st
century technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Such new research centers might build upon, but move beyond work
done at today's federally financed supercomputer research centers
and their attempts to advance scientific computing.
</P>
<P>
   Computer research with such government backing has resulted in
some of the most significant new industries created since World War
II, including personal computing and the Internet. Almost all of
those advances came from basic exploratory research, rather than
research and development efforts aimed at solving specific
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although total federal spending for R &AMP; D has remained steady,
there has been a marked shift toward support for applied R &AMP; D,''
the report says.
</P>
<P>
   It also stresses the need for new emphasis on software research,
saying that the nation has become too dependent on outmoded
software, like systems long used by the Federal Aviation
Administration and the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FAA and IRS systems have proved to be amazingly difficult
to upgrade,'' the authors write, maintaining that while there have
been dramatic improvements in computer hardware in the last 40
years, the ability to develop software has not kept pace.
</P>
<P>
   The report also warns that federal funds for supercomputing have
largely collapsed since the breakup of the Soviet Union. The
authors argue that failing to support high-performance computing is
a national security risk that the nation cannot afford to take.
</P>
<P>
   In order to keep the United States leading in building the
world's fastest computers, the nation should set a goal of creating
machines capable of reaching the speed of a petaflop _ one thousand
trillion mathematical operations a second _ by the year 2010, the
report says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-26-98 1906EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7896 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-MURARI-PROFILE-AR     07-29 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MURARI-PROFILE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 CASTELLETO, Italy: avoid damage. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shift toward MEMS at ST Microelectronics has been made with
the blessing of Pasquale Pistorio, the company's president and
chief executive, for whom Murari has worked for much of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the freedom from Pasquale to do what I want to do,''
Murari said during a recent interview as construction workers
nearby completed a new MEMS research wing of the Castelleto center.
</P>
<P>
   ST Microelectronics does maintain a satellite laboratory in San
Jose, Calif., in the heart of Silicon Valley. And Murari, who
visits that lab about four times a year, acknowledges that in many
ways chip design is easier in the Valley, with its network of
support services and ready availability of specialized talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end it made it more difficult by staying here,'' he
said. ``We would have been able to achieve the same results in half
the time in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, part of the recipe for the success of this Italian
laboratory may be Murari's own homegrown independent style as a
researcher and a leader, a combination of ardor and insight. It is
what one of his customers, Thomas Froeschle, an engineer at Bose,
the U.S. audio company, refers to as ``management by enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruno is a remarkably creative person,'' Froeschle said. Bose
designed several of its most popular circuits with the help of
Murari's team, and Froeschle remembers that while other engineering
firms are frequently proprietary about their work, he was struck by
the willingness of the ST Microelectronics engineers to discuss
design ideas freely, without concern for ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Castelleto, Murari makes certain that each of his 300 or
so designers has time for what he calls ``play'' _ the 10 percent
to 15 percent of their time that is set aside for them to use
thinking about and working on their own ideas.
</P>
<P>
   That sense of play frequently spills into his own design work.
</P>
<P>
   Murari is a former world champion designer of model glider
planes built with carbon fiber and Kevlar. Chesson, the Canadian
engineer, remembers a discussion of mechanical design with a large
American customer in which engineers from the two companies were
becoming frustrated. Each side was having trouble understanding the
other's notion of how the product's mechanical and electronics
systems would interact.
</P>
<P>
   One morning, to illustrate his point, Murari took in a
carbon-fiber glider wing he had designed.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Chesson remembers, ``the Americans were looking at
each other with expressions that said, `This guy's off the wall.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then,'' he said, ``a light went off in their eyes. Bruno had
come out of left field, but his idea bridged the gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Murari doesn't reserve his left-field flourishes for outsiders.
Several years ago, when he was pushing his team to come up with a
new design for packaging its circuitry onto chip surfaces, no one
seemed to be grasping the concept.
</P>
<P>
   Then one morning Murari burst in to the laboratory and threw a
compact and elegant chip package onto the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' he said. ``This is what the competition is doing, and
it's a shame we're not doing the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Only after he had left the room did one of the engineers venture
over to examine the ``competitor's'' system.
</P>
<P>
   The device was not really a rival's _ and not even a real chip.
Instead, it was a tiny block of painted wood onto which Murari,
equal parts engineer and artisan, had painstakingly carved his
circuitry design.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-26-98 1900EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
