<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7897 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINOR-OPERA30-COX     07-29 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-OPERA30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Opera, from the mouths of babes
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The kids are sitting at a big, round table, doing their
Rob-Buddy-Sally routine a la The Dick Van Dyke Show. They're
writing. An opera. About a gang.
</P>
<P>
   One of the characters is in a wheelchair, shot in the back by
some nasty street kid. Gang warfare, it appears. Another character
is about to steal some liquor from Dad's stash, which, as we all
know, is not a very bright move. But it adds to the on-stage drama.
And they love the drama.
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon, though, the kid writers have a little problem.
It's called writers' block. In fact, their plot is at a downright
standstill. They're barely into Scene 2, and they're already
thinking they just might crash and burn at this, their first
writing gig. Angst abounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on,'' says the obvious Rob Petrie of the group. ``Get
serious. We need to write, man. What happens next?''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' says someone else. ``The mom is watching TV.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's dumb. That's not going to work. Come on, you guys. Get
busy,'' spouts Rob Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, yeah, it will. She's deaf to the outside world. She's
watching Days of Our Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Short pause.
</P>
<P>
   Big pause.
</P>
<P>
   Huge, long pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man,'' says some kid named Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hard.''
</P>
<P>
   And instructor Karen Long-hofer stands there and smiles. Her
little scheme is working. These kids are actually thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Ava Coleman, director of development for Palm Beach Opera, says
she's wanted to do this camp for a while. She saw her first opera
when she was 7 years old, growing up in France. She went with her
grandmother, her godmother and two cousins. She wore a pretty
dress.
</P>
<P>
   The opera was Madama Butterfly, and it was glorious. The
7-year-old girl cried. And she never forgot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my children were growing up, we went to the opera,'' said
Coleman. ``But we could afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Coleman says, she's thought it would be nice if the
opera could pay for kids who wouldn't otherwise be going anytime
soon. Last year, she worked out a deal with the folks who run the
summer camp at the Kravis Center. But it didn't suit Coleman, who
appears to be quite fussy about her art forms.
</P>
<P>
   There was too much regular old theater work at the Kravis camp.
It wasn't opera, opera and more opera. Coleman waged on.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Coleman struck a deal with Mac Schwebel, who owns
Sherbrooke Golf and Country Club in Lake Worth. Mr. Mac Schwebel
also happens to support opera, you see. He might even be the
president of the Palm Beach Opera board.
</P>
<P>
   Can we have the camp out at Sherbrooke? Coleman asked. Sure, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman says she went out and collected $10,000 from opera
supporters for the four weeks of camp. They got the kids, about 40
in all, on the recommendations of local social service workers and
school music teachers.
</P>
<P>
   When all that was arranged, Schwebel threw in some golf lessons
in the morning and a decent lunch right after that. Coleman added
some brush-ups on good manners _ ``It cannot hurt,'' she says _ and
she called the whole thing Swing and Sing Summer Camp, which she
thought was pretty darn clever. In fact, it still makes her
chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   In charge of it all were Karen Longhofer and her husband,
Gordan. He's a free-lance performing artist who often works with
the Palm Beach Opera. She teaches at Crystal Lakes Elementary in
Boynton Beach, this year, fifth grade. She's been to the New York
Metropolitan Opera to take classes on _ guess what? _ how to teach
kids how to write an opera. What a coincidence! Together, the
couple teaches these kids how to write and produce an opera in two
quick weeks. There are set designers, composers, costume designers,
performers.
</P>
<P>
   They do it all. But I'm ahead of myself.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing the Longhofers do is ask the kids, about 20 of
them in each two-week session, about their perception of opera. And
it never fails.
</P>
<P>
   Opera singers, they are told, are fat. All of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they look at me, and they'd hear me sing, and they say,
`How does all that sound come out of that body?''' Gordan said.
Gordan, you see, is a beanpole with a big voice.
</P>
<P>
   What else do kids think about opera?
</P>
<P>
   Singing. Headaches. History. Italian. Sad movies. Scenes.
Cartoons. Acting.
</P>
<P>
   And my personal favorite: Men in tights.
</P>
<P>
   The first camp session _ there will be just two this summer _
performed an opera called A Gazillion Miles Away. It was the story
of siblings who moved from Dallas, where they had lived in a
``spacious home'' all their lives, to a small apartment in New York
City. ``It was wonderful,'' says Karen Longhofer. ``And this one
is, too. But they're as different as night and day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That first week, they really started coming out with some
things,'' said Karen, about the kids' pre-writing conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they talked about crime and punishment and how our society
doesn't punish people for their crimes. And one of the kids said,
`We should have these conversations more often because I didn't
know other people felt the same way I did.'''
</P>
<P>
   Karen loved that exchange, mainly because it's the little things
like that in life that keep us all going.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and by the way. That little number they called A Gazillion
Miles Away? It was really an operetta. The difference? An operetta
is shorter, and there is some spoken dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Geez. Don't you guys know anything?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
