<HEADER>
A7898 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-REVIEW-PARENT30     07-29 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-REVIEW-PARENT30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Upscale decor upstages actors in flat `Trap'
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you didn't know that this new Parent Trap comes courtesy of
the same team behind the 1991 remake of Father of the Bride (and
its sequel), here's a clue.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at the houses.
</P>
<P>
   Director/writer Nancy Meyers and writer/producer Charles Shyer
can't resist letting a camera linger over the details of a
well-made home, be it a sprawling California ranch or a posh London
townhouse. Heck, they even make a cabin in a summer camp look like
the Grand Palais.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's the big deal, you may ask, especially when there's a
good story to be told? Details don't intrude. They just add, well,
detail.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Meyers/Shyer formula, details become the means to an
end. They overwhelm the story, the acting, the pacing. For the sake
of indulging in some fantasy of upscale decor, the filmmakers turn
an otherwise delightful tale into a bore. This Parent Trap is more
than a trap: It's a hostage takeover _ with the audience as victim.
Adults might tolerate it, as they tolerated the slightly amusing
Father of the Bride I and II, which had their own umpteen-bedroom
``simple'' family homes. But kids are the target audience here _
and they couldn't care less whether you live in a palace or a
poorhouse.
</P>
<P>
   What's really the tragedy is that Meyers/Shyer have assembled
such a fine cast. And they've kept the charming essence of the
story known to millions from the 1961 Disney original, which
starred Brian Keith, Maureen O'Hara and Hayley Mills.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, there's a pair of divorced parents: Nick Parker
(Dennis Quaid), a California winemaker who's equal parts hunk and
heart; and Elizabeth James (Natasha Richardson), a London designer
of wedding dresses who's proper, prim and sexy all at the same
time. Long before the couple began fighting, they managed to
conceive a set of twin daughters. The split resulted in Hallie
(newcomer Lindsay Lohan) heading home with Dad, and Annie (also
Lohan) with Mom. Neither twin knows of the other's existence.
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't you know, both girls end up at the same summer camp
in Maine _ and their blood connection becomes clear. To bring their
parents back together, they hatch an ingenious plan to pose as each
other and then force a meeting of their torn-apart families. Just
to add some comedic potential, Dad's gold-digging girlfriend gets
in the way.
</P>
<P>
   The film should ride on finding the right Hallie/Annie: Lohan,
discovered after an exhaustive search in eight cities, does no
wrong. She's mastered the difficult task of playing two characters
and short-shrifting neither. Her Annie is dignified and devious;
her Hallie tomboyish and.... devious. Each has her own quirks, but
both play a mean game of poker.
</P>
<P>
   Quaid and Richardson don't disappoint, either. The former is a
one-note actor, a kind of man's man for all seasons, but since the
part doesn't ask for more, he's not in trouble. The latter is a
subtler cinematic presence _ and she manages to flesh out what
could have turned into a two-dimensional role.
</P>
<P>
   But all that presence can't compensate for the film's
insufferable slowness. As the setting moves from Maine to London to
California to London, one wonders how long it's going to take, how
many more glittering interiors Meyers/Shyer are waiting to capture
on celluloid. The movie could easily be trimmed by 30 minutes. Or
those 30 minutes could be put to better use with a few more
slapstick sequences. There's only about three from start to finish.
Count 'em yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson here is that kids care more for looking at pratfalls
than pricey furniture. For that matter, so do some adults.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 and one-half stars; running time: 2 hours, 18 minutes;
PG
</P>
<P>
   Charles Passy writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
