<HEADER>
A7899 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIEREVIEW-NEGOTIATO     07-29 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIEREVIEW-NEGOTIATOR30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Negotiator' patronizes its audience
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Negotiator features a duel of great minds. Too bad they
don't belong to the filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, a Hollywood movie allows its premise to go poof,
wasting two good actors who register average performances. Samuel
L. Jackson and Kevin Spacey play hostage negotiators facing each
other in a psychological tango that could turn deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is Danny Roman, a Chicago cop whose credentials as a
skilled rescuer are established in the first scene. He's a hero to
his buddies. But despite the smiling faces, things aren't kosher in
cop land.
</P>
<P>
   Roman is framed for the murder of his partner, who had told him
that Internal Affairs snoops were looking into the disappearance of
police money. But this policeman is no patsy. The hostage rescuer
takes hostages in the Internal Affairs office. He holds his fellow
cops at bay with threats to kill his captives.
</P>
<P>
   They are a sullen secretary (Siobhan Fallon); a con man with
computer skills (the chameleon Paul Giamatti, who provides comic
relief); Roman's chummy commander (weaselly Ron Rifkin of L.A.
Confidential); and the Internal Affairs chief (the late J.T. Walsh,
whose blandness always hinted at disturbing depths).
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a give-and-take between Roman and colleagues
whose tactics he knows better than they do. He wants to flush out
the real villains. He demands to deal only with another crack
negotiator, Chris Sabian (Spacey). If great minds think alike,
Sabian will get the drift of what's going on. At the very least, he
won't let trigger-happy cops snuff out the truth.
</P>
<P>
   What follows could have been a nimble dance, full of
psychological depth and personal revelation. The strengths and
weaknesses of the pair, their tics and crotchets, might have come
into play in complex and suspenseful ways that would redeem the
thriller sequences.
</P>
<P>
   And the film, opening today, starts in that direction. We buy
into the premise, despite its stretch. But the plot degenerates
into a familiar melange of gunfire and overheated action. The
confusing threads of the mystery are finally woven together in a
confrontation that is both silly and stilted.
</P>
<P>
   The young action director G. Gary Gray (Set It Off) settles for
middle-of-the-road melodrama. Adding to the wimp-out is dialogue
that often doesn't sound right in the context of cops caught in a
corner. Simple words, such as fraud and absurd, and ``people who
set me up.''
</P>
<P>
   People? Why not (expletive deleted)? A naughty word would do
nicely here. Roman has a right to be huffy. In addition, the
repartee too often turns into speechifying.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson gives his rogue cop some emotional complexity, fire and
ice. But he relies on meaningful glares to the point that we start
glaring back. As for Spacey, he's an oasis of calm command in a
crazy situation. But he never comes alive as an interesting foil.
Besides, there's always the hint of a twinkle in his eyes. In this
case, alas, it seems to say he doesn't like where this plot is
heading.
</P>
<P>
   The Negotiator could have talked its way to salvation. But the
premise is held hostage to dumbing down _ the Hollywood fear that
people just don't want to think at summer movies.
</P>
<P>
   2 stars; Rated R: Running Time: 2 hours, 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schwan writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
