<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7900 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-PARASITES30-COX     07-29 1535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PARASITES30-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Health experts seeking Brushy Creek outbreak's precise cause
</P>
<P>
   By Christian Davenport
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN -- As an outbreak of a parasitic infection worsened _
five more people tested positive _Austin Mayor Kirk Watson promised
help to those affected by the sewage spill in the Brushy Creek area
and began demanding answers about how well the city responded.
</P>
<P>
   The additional positive tests means that nine of 12 people who
submitted samples to health officials were found to be infected
with Cryptosporidium, a relatively rare and highly infectious
parasite that apparently has spread to drinking water in the Brushy
Creek area west of Round Rock. State and local health officials
said the number of positive tests qualified as an ``outbreak.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the July 14 spill at a City of Austin pumping station that
sent 170,000 gallons of raw sewage into Brushy Creek, 13 wells have
been contaminated and more than 150 people have called the
Williamson County and Cities Health District to report stomach
ailments. Late Monday, the Brushy Creek Municipal Utility District
ordered children out of the water and closed its two public
swimming pools.
</P>
<P>
   The rash of activity this week is in stark contrast to the first
week after the spill, when officials gave repeated assurances that
the effects of the spill were minor and the water in Brushy Creek
was safe. The first seven days after the spill, during which
numerous local, state, health and private agencies tried to update
each other, was marked by miscommunication, misinformation and
delayed action.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the five public wells at Brushy Creek MUD were closed
July 21, and the neighborhood of 10,000 people began buying extra
water from Round Rock. But because it can take 10 days for symptoms
of the disease to appear, officials said the number of infections
could continue to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has severe symptoms is urged to see a doctor, but the
outbreak of Cryptosporidium appears to be confined to residents of
Brushy Creek MUD and to users of nearby private wells, said David
Bergmire-Sweat, a Texas Department of Health epidemiologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence of a widespread outbreak throughout
Central Texas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And while the sewage spill appears to be the culprit in the
outbreak, work continues on pinpointing the exact cause so health
officials can assess whether a health risk remains, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Watson said Tuesday he wanted to determine whether the city
responded adequately to the spill, and said he was particularly
interested in how city officials identified and warned private well
users.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want someone to tell me what happened and why,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is not the only one.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Russell, a Brushy Creek MUD resident, said, ``I'm not
sure that they let on how serious the problem could be.'' The
incident began July 13, when a thunderstorm knocked out power to a
City of Austin pump station at 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the 103 pump stations the City of Austin owns, the
station just west of the Round Rock city limits does not have a
backup generator. The storm also knocked out the phone line the
emergency alarm system was hooked up to, meaning city officials did
not know of the spill for almost 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The odds of this happening are very rare,'' said Randy Goss,
director of Austin's Water and Wastewater Utility. By 4 a.m.,
officials estimated, the sewage had backed up to a manhole next to
Brushy Creek, erupted out of the ground and into the creek.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours later, A. J. Olson, the operations manager for the
Brushy Creek MUD, drove by on his way to work and smelled the
sewage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was shooting about six inches off the ground,'' he said.
``It was flowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson was the one to notify the company that operates the
pumping station for the City of Austin. Forty-five minutes later,
crews were at the scene, and by 9 a.m. the spill was stopped.
</P>
<P>
   But not before 170,000 gallons of raw sewage had spewed into the
creek.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, crews pumped as much sewage as they could
out of the creek. Then they flushed the creek with water from a
nearby fire hydrant. And when the rain came that afternoon, they
said that would help move the contaminants downstream.
</P>
<P>
   But it apparently didn't move the sewage fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   While state officials told people that the spill would have no
lasting effects, scores of dead fish floated in the creek, and the
contaminants began to seep down to where wells suck up water.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, four homeowners who live on Sam Bass Road about a
mile downstream from the spill began to worry about the quality of
the water coming from their private wells. So as the news of the
spill spread, they called the City of Austin and asked the city to
test their wells.
</P>
<P>
   The results came back two days later: Their wells were
contaminated, and they were told to drink bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   When Tony Bennett, of the water utilities division of the Texas
Natural Resource Conservation Commission, heard that their wells
were contaminated, he called Brushy Creek officials to make sure
they were thoroughly testing theirs.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't.
</P>
<P>
   The district was testing the disinfected water coming out of its
wells and going into homes. But it didn't begin testing the water
before treatment until three days after the spill.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the lab processed the water samples that MUD
officials had collected. By July 20, Olson got the test results
back, showing the water was contaminated, and he called Bennett's
office at the conservation commission. But Olson didn't tell him
how severe the contamination was until the next day.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, July 21, one week after the spill, Bennett
ordered the wells shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he said the MUD should have been testing the water going
into its wells sooner after the spill.
</P>
<P>
   During the delay, contaminants like Cryptosporidium apparently
slipped past the wells' disinfectants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have begun testing the raw water immediately,'' MUD
director Jimmy Griffith said at an emergency meeting last week. ``I
think we learned that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet many households near the spill have their own private wells,
which are not regulated, required to have a permit, or, as far as
any state or city official can tell, even located on any map.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go out in your back yard and dig a well if you want
to,'' Goss , of the Austin water department, said. ``There is
nobody stopping you from that.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of any complete list pinpointing the location of wells
owned privately made it particularly hard for officials to find
them. So the Austin utility depended on citizens contacting the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Some did. And last week, City of Austin crews tested 10 more
private wells. Five came back contaminated, and more people
switched to bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Edmiston a Brushy Creek resident, said he thinks MUD
officials should have tested the water more extensively sooner
after the spill happened, but he's not interested in assigning
blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're doing the right thing now by shutting down the
pool, by testing it or treating it,'' he said. ``They're starting
to take the steps necessary that should be taken, and I guess
that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmiston, 34, said he, his wife and two sons have all felt
symptoms of the parasite in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   As residents near the sewage spill continue to worry about their
health, officials are trying to assure residents they are doing
everything possible. Will Hampton, a City of Round Rock spokesman,
said Tuesday that the city has been testing the water going into
and out of its wells every day since July 6, and that no
contamination has been detected. Owners of private wells should
continue to drink bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials have recommended that those in the Brushy Creek
area wash their hands frequently, and throw out any ice or drinks
made before July 22, the day after the wells were shut down. And
the Williamson County and Cities Health District is compiling a
database that will pinpoint specific clusters of people infected
with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting reports of illness,'' said Karen Wilson, the
director of the health district. ``So we know what the magnitude of
the illness is and where the people getting sick live.''
</P>
<P>
   Reassurances have not eased all of the concerns of those
affected by the spill.
</P>
<P>
   At least 20 people went to a special meeting of the Brushy Creek
MUD board of directors Monday night, and many had questions during
the 90-minute meeting. One of those was John McLemore, who along
with Edmiston signed up to speak at the meeting. McLemore said
Tuesday that officials should have done more testing earlier to
detect parasites.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``There's been a real failure to respond out here.''
American-Statesman staff writers Chuck Lindell, Dylan Rivera and
Harry Thomas contributed to this report. Read more about the Brushy
Creek Municipal Utility District spill at www.austin360.com/news
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-29-98 0029E
