<P>
   BLACK-HAIRSHOW _ ATLANTA _ An advance on the Atlanta-based
Bronner Brothers annual mid-summer black hair show at the Georgia
World Congress Center featuring interviews with stylists and a look
at trends. Expected attendance: 100,000. A show highlight will be
the ``Hair Battle Royale '98'' on Aug. 2, a contest for
hairstylists who do fantasy styles. The winner takes home a 1998
Jeep or $10,000. (Johnson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ ATLANTA _ Veterans of the Second World War II and
high school students just learning about it are venturing onto
America Online's Saving Private Ryan area (Keyword: Saving Private
Ryan) to remember, exchange stories and just talk. AOL spokeswoman
Janine Dunne says that since the area opened Friday, more
than10,000 messages have been posted. Dunne says the only time
there was such a large response to a topic was after the death of
Princess Diana. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 7/28.
</P>
<P>
   MUSTACHE _ There's something about Matt Dillon's mustache. It's
smarmy. Seedy. Oily. Just the crayon-type scrawl for a not-so-stiff
upper lip. Before Dillon's character, Healy, says a word in There's
Something About Mary, the summer's hottest comedy, you can tell hs
a sleaze. (Anna, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STATESCHOOL-BUS _ AUSTIN _ Throughout this fireball summer,
nearly 40 people with mental retardation were forced to endure bus
rides on the Austin State School campus in an unair-conditioned bus
where temperatures soared to 110 degrees. State inspectors deemed
the situation life-threatening, particularly because some of the
disabled residents have seizure disorders and take anticonvulsant
drugs that put them at high risk for heat stroke. (Gamino, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   GARFIELD _ Garfield, the fat cat created by artist Jim Davis, is
celebrating his 20th birthday, prompting the International Museum
of Cartoon Art in Boca Raton, Fla., to stage an exhibition
featuring the feisty feline through Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   It's as good an excuse as any this summer to check out Boca, the
booming Palm Beach County resort that is steadily gaining a
reputation for brainy as well as beachy attractions. (Patureau,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 7/28.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN-HOSTEL _ AUSTIN _ If hostels are, as one veteran traveler
said, the windows through which a city is viewed, then the Austin
hostel is a one-way mirror. The modest building on Lakeshore Drive
is tucked away on the southeast side of Town Lake, unseen by most
of the city's bustling downtown and university populations. Our
hostel is so nondescript even neighbors stop to ask what it is
(''It's what?'' they reply. ``A hotel? A hospital?''). Looks can be
deceiving. Inside this small hostel, more than 9,000 visitors from
every corner of the globe each year make a temporary home in 40
beds. (Hibberd, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LOW-AIRFARE _ DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ The Travel Company of Delray
Beach is installing computer software that quickly searches all
airfares available to find the lowest rate, the company announced
at its first annual meeting recently. The system, called Flight
Attendant, ``does what a perfect travel agent would do: searches,
searches, searches'' until it finds plane tickets that fit the
customer's needs, Chairman Joseph Vittoria said. The installation
of the system, which will occur at its subsidiary Travel 800, is
central to The Travel Company's intention of offering one-stop
shopping for travel. (Plunkett, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
