<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `I wish I had a pencil-thin mustache' . . . why?
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's something about Matt Dillon's mustache.
</P>
<P>
   It's smarmy. Seedy. Oily. Just the crayon-type scrawl for a
not-so-stiff upper lip.
</P>
<P>
   Before Dillon's character, Healy, says a word in There's
Something About Mary, the summer's hottest comedy, you can tell
he's a sleaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been told to beware of people with a mustache,''
says Richard Vachon, owner of Richard's Barber Shop in Palm Beach.
``The shady character always wears a mustache.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? It comes from the old silent elodramas, guesses Stephen
Charla, assistant curator at the International Museum of Cartoon
Art in Boca Raton. The mustache, the black cape, the sinister
smile, the woman tied to the railroad tracks ... all ``incredibly
cheesy'' stuff, Charla says.
</P>
<P>
   The mustache was picked up by the cartoon world, which
introduced us to Snidely Whiplash of Dudley Do-Right and Dishonest
John of Beany and Cecil, among others. Now, Charla says, the
pencil-thin mustache is just a cliche.
</P>
<P>
   The skinny worm of fur across the upper lip means you're not
courageous enough to make a full statement, says Ruth Rubinstein, a
sociologist at the Fashion Institute of Technology in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not really committed,'' she says. ``You're trying to
get away with something.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds about right. John Dillinger had one. Wayne Newton had
one, for Pete's sake.
</P>
<P>
   What about old movie stars? What about Clark Gable?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a rogue,'' Rubinstein said. ``But a beautiful rogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna is the fashion writer for the Palm Beach Post, West
Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
