<P>
   CSIBLEY-COLUMN _ Some people draw celebrities like magnets. I
spent a week in Thomasville, Georgia once and the most famous
person I met was a well-regarded gentleman who sold peanuts on the
main street. Now I hear from my friend Pat Gainey that
Thomasville's celebrated ancient oak tree is a natural attracter of
the eminent and celebrated. ``Your article about the old oak tree
in Mobile(Ala.) reminded me of one of Thomasville's landmarks, our
vintage live oak tree, corner of Monroe and Crawford streets,''
wrote Miss Gainey. ``Visitors to our town are always shown the oak.
Each time I drive by, I wonder how much longer its wide, low, heavy
branches will stay intact.'' (Sibley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED 7/28.
</P>
<P>
   MINOR-OPERA _ The kids are sitting at a big, round table, doing
their Rob-Buddy-Sally routine a la The Dick Van Dyke Show. They're
writing. An opera. About a gang. One of the characters is in a
wheelchair, shot in the back by some nasty street kid. Gang
warfare, it appears. Huge, long pause. ``Man,'' says some kid named
Pedro. ``This is hard.'' And instructor Karen Long-hofer stands
there and smiles. Her little scheme is working. These kids are
actually thinking. Ava Coleman, director of development for Palm
Beach Opera, says she's wanted to do this camp for a while. She saw
her first opera when she was 7 years old, growing up in France. She
went with her grandmother, her godmother and two cousins. She wore
a pretty dress. (Minor, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
