<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTING Q&AMP;A/DAVID EINSTEIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   Trashing Hard Drive's Cyberjunk  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I was told that to quickly rid my hard drive of the mass of
cyberjunk it has accumulated, the way to go is to reformat. If
feasible, how do I reformat and then put Windows 95 back onto my
computer? I have a Pentium 120, a 2.1 gigabyte hard drive and 32
megs of RAM.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Reformatting indeed will quickly remove your cyberjunk.
Unfortunately, it also will erase everything else on the drive. So
if you decide to do it, make sure to first save every document,
graphic and other piece of information that you want to keep on a
floppy disk or a Zip disk. Also, write down the account numbers,
phone numbers and settings for your online accounts, including
Internet and home banking. You'll also need copies of programs that
you'll want to reload, such as Microsoft Office, Norton Utilities
or America Online.
</P>
<P>
   If your PC came with an emergency recovery CD, you probably can
use it to reformat and reinstall Windows. If not, you'll need two
things: a Windows Startup Disk and a copy of Windows 95 (full
version, not upgrade). To make a Startup Disk, go to
Start/Settings/Control Panel, then double-click Add/Remove
Programs. Tab over to Startup Disk, and follow the instructions.
</P>
<P>
   To reformat your hard drive, start the PC with the Startup Disk
in the floppy drive. Then type c: /s at the prompt and hit Enter.
</P>
<P>
   Before you reformat, make sure to save the driver files and
configuration information for your CD-ROM drive on the Startup Disk
or on a separate floppy. You may need them to get the CD-ROM drive
working again after reformatting. (If the CD-ROM drive doesn't
work, you won't be able to reinstall Windows 95 from its CD).
</P>
<P>
   Consult the documentation that came with the CD-ROM drive, or
contact the manufacturer for information about installing the
CD-ROM drive software. Some companies let you download automatic
installation programs from the Web.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I would like to know how to receive and send e-mail while
traveling in Europe. I want to use my laptop and modem, but I don't
want to have to make a long-distance call to my Internet service
provider in the United States. Any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; What you need is an ISP that offers ``roaming.'' This
feature lets you connect to your Internet account through foreign
ISPs. Many larger ISPs now offer roaming. To find one, check with
www.ipass.com or www.gric.com, which are run by companies that
provide roaming services to ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
Q:  &LR; My Windows 95 desktop is getting cluttered, and I'd like to
remove some of the icons, especially the ones for programs I no
longer use. What's the best way to do this, and are there any
dangers to be aware of?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; The easiest way to remove an unwanted icon is to
right-click it and choose Delete. However, as we saw in a column a
few months ago, some Microsoft icons can't be deleted this way. For
them, you need a program called Tweak UI, which you can download
for free from Microsoft at www.microsoft.com/windows
/windows95/info/powertoys.htm. Tweak UI lets you customize your
desktop, including dumping icons like MSN.
</P>
<P>
   As for possible dangers in removing desktop icons, yes, there is
one. Most icons are ``shortcuts,'' so removing them doesn't affect
the actual program. But the desktop also can contain bona fide
program icons. And if you delete one of those, the program is
trashed.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, you can tell when an icon is a shortcut because it
features a tiny arrow. Also, Windows will display a warning box if
you're about to get rid of a program.
</P>
<P>
   Header Update: Last week, I described how users of Netscape
Communicator can eliminate unsightly headers in e-mail messages.
That sparked a barrage of requests from America Online users who
also would like to do away with headers.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, guys, it can't be done. Says an AOL technician: ``We
are sorry, but unfortunately we do not support that ability at this
time. However, we do rely on our members' feedback, and all
comments submitted to us are forwarded to the appropriate
department for consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to register your opinion directly, go the Member
Services in AOL's Members menu. Choose E-mail, then click on Ask
the Staff.
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE WEEK &QC; Don't like your keyboard? Get a new one. There's
no hassle involved. Just plug it in and go. A wide variety of
keyboards with different levels of sensitivity are available
starting at under $25. And ergonomic and wireless keyboards also
can be had for under $60.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computerssfgate.com.
</P>
