<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHTOOLS29-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Tech Tools: Checking quality of your phone line a matter of a call 
By Jack Warner  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As expected, I got a number of e-mails after the
column in which I tried to help a correspondent with his concerns
over whether his telephone line would be acceptable for 56k bps
modems.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, most of them corrected me on several points, the
simplest thing being that I got an acronym wrong. It should be
ADSL. Not ASDL.
</P>
<P>
   The most helpful info came in messages informing me there is
indeed a way Bob Wildaus can check the quality of his telephone
line. I'm going to give primary credit to Jerry A. Smith of Smyrna,
because his message had the most details.
</P>
<P>
   3Com, now the parent company of U.S. Robotics, has a telephone
number you can call to check your phone line's acceptability for
56K operations. You can find out a lot about X2 technology and v.90
at 3Com's Web site at http://www.3com.com. However, I had to do a
lot of poking around to find details on the line checker, so to
save other folks the necessity of all that, I'm going to repeat the
routine here.
</P>
<P>
   First off, you don't get to this function through the Internet.
You'll need to use an ordinary communications program (remember
them?) to accomplish the task. HyperTerminal, the program built
into Windows 95's accessory package, will work fine.
</P>
<P>
   The number to call is 847-262-6000. This is not toll-free.
</P>
<P>
   This will connect you to a bulletin-board type of system. It
will ask you if your system supports graphics. I made the mistake
of answering yes, and the result was not pretty. Just hit enter,
which conveys a ``no'' to the system.
</P>
<P>
   Then it will ask you for your first name. Type: line and press
enter.
</P>
<P>
   Logically enough, it will then ask for your last name, which
should be: test and press enter. Got it? If you want a line test,
your name is line test. I have no idea what will happen if you give
it your right name.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, that's all you need to do. Some invisible
diagnostics will be run, and a report will come back. If your line
is adequate, it will say so, and if you want to see a lot of
statistics about your line, press enter. When you're done, press g
for goodbye and hit enter.
</P>
<P>
   If you get ``Your line does not support 56k technology,'' hit g
and enter. 3Com recommends making several calls over a period of
time to be sure of an accurate report.
</P>
<P>
   If the report is ``Cannot determine 56k capability, test must
run in v.34 mode,'' this indicates noise or static on the line, a
good reason to complain to the telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   There are other possible responses, but these are the ones that
would appear to pertain to home telephone lines. For more
information on using the test, point your Web browser to http://
</P>
<P>
   www.3com.com/56k/need4_56k
</P>
<P>
   /linetest.html.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for another persistent query, this from folks trying to
make calls within the Atlanta area's overburdened phone system. I
think I've answered this before, but here goes again:
</P>
<P>
   To set up your fax calling, or whatever kind of calling, to dial
within an area code such as 404 or 770 without the software
insisting on sticking a ``1'' in front of it, simply enter all the
digits in the space for the number, like this: 4045551212.
Disregard the space for the area code; leave it blank.
</P>
<P>
   This works on every system I've tried.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-28-98 1037EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
