 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
MindSpring is investors' darling 
By Frances Katz  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's always nice to watch David beat Goliath. Watching the
soaring stock prices of Atlanta-based Internet service provider
MindSpring elicits a similar feeling.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which provides dial-up Internet access to some
393,000 subscribers, just posted its third profitable quarter
operating in the volatile Internet industry. The stock closed
Friday down 50 cents at $148.50 after hitting a record $157.12 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring founder and Chairman Charles Brewer cut his vacation
short to appear on CNBC. When asked what was the secret to the
Internet service provider's success, Brewer replied with what is
becoming the MindSpring mantra: Keeping costs down and customers
happy is the key to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   And Brewer seemed to hint in a Wall Street Journal Heard on the
Street column that he wasn't averse to selling the company.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring's national media attention has captured the
imaginations of small investors like Atlanta resident Edie
Friedman. Friedman is impressed by the stock's performance and what
friends say about the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love it. They say it's very easy to use. It's going to be
another Microsoft. I have a gut feeling,'' Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   However, several investment firms warn MindSpring's wild ride is
a short-term phenomenon. But they still believe MindSpring is an
excellent long-term investment for those with the money and the
patience to ride out the company's ups and inevitable downs.
Robinson-Humphrey research associate Jeff John believes MindSpring
has long-term potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, these dial-up providers were all supposed to go
broke because the big boys like AT&AMP;T were supposed to come along
and steal all their customers, and that hasn't been the case,''
John says. But MindSpring, along with America Online and the
aggressive Internet service provider Earthlink are still alive and
kicking. ``MindSpring is one of the highest-quality ISPs out
there,'' John says. ``They've proven that an ISP can be
profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Earthlink, the one national provider most similar to MindSpring
in size and scope, hasn't seen its stock prices climb to
MindSpring's dizzying heights. Part of the reason could be the 28
percent share telecommunications company Sprint has in the company,
which could be off-putting to potential investors.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a difference in company strategies. MindSpring has
opted for steady growth and profitability. Marketing is almost
exclusively word of mouth and customer retention rates are good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earthlink is not a profitable company, and they won't be for
about four years, which is why it's trading at a discount,'' John
points out. Earthlink's plan is to spend as much money as it takes
to acquire subscribers and become the No. 2 provider behind AOL,
which has 12 million subscribers worldwide. Earthlink has 710,000
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Investors like service providers because, unlike some other
Internet companies, they use a recurring revenue model. They charge
a monthly fee that allows analysts to make more accurate
projections. ``It takes away some of the uncertainty you have with
some Internet companies right now,'' John says.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies like Amazon.com are hard to put a value on
because it's hard, if not impossible, to predict how many books the
company will sell from quarter to quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say MindSpring is a solid company, whose fortunes have
been greatly increased by Wall Street's overall enthusiasm for all
things Internet. ``There are very few (Internet) companies to
invest in, and even fewer that have the profitability to back up
some of those valuations,'' John says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
