<SLUG> BC-CPT-ALTAVISTA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB ADDRESS SELLS FOR $3.35 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By Julia Angwin   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. has agreed to pay a San Jose man $3.35
million for the Web address www.altavista.com, which is believed to
be a record amount paid for a domain name, according to a source
close to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction settles a well-known two-year dispute between
Compaq, which owns the popular Alta Vista search engine, and Jack
Marshall, who owns the Alta Vista Web site name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is the largest known figure for a domain name
transaction,'' said Edwin Hayward, who runs www.igoldrush.com, a
Web site that tracks such purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The buying and selling of Web site addresses _ or domain names _
has become fairly common on the Web, but most fetch price tags in
the tens of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Speculators buy popular names such as www.mcdonalds.com or
www.television.com for $100 and then sell those addresses to
corporations for much higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   The practice has been somewhat curbed by a 1996 court ruling
that prevents cyber-squatters from buying trademarked names, but
generic names are still fair game.
</P>
<P>
   The Alta Vista name, however, was not trademarked when
electrical engineer Jack Marshall bought cyber-rights to it in
January 1994 for his Campbell startup, AltaVista Technology.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Marshall sold $49.95 software that let users build
multimedia postcards that could be displayed on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1995, Digital Equipment Corp. _ which now is owned
by Compaq _ launched a search engine called Alta Vista. Because it
didn't own the Alta Vista address, Web surfers had to find it at
www.altavista.digital.com.
</P>
<P>
   But that address confused Web surfers, and many looking for the
Alta Vista search engine ended up on Marshall's site, overloading
his computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We noticed it immediately,'' Marshall said. ``So we put a link
on our page to the search engine and frantically did a bunch of
things with our servers to keep the thing running.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he had to upgrade his computers to handle the
half-million visitors per day, the increased traffic allowed
Marshall to lure big advertisers to his site as well.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Equipment Corp. offered to buy the Alta Vista trademark
from Marshall. He agreed to sell the trademark, but kept the right
to use it on software packages and his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But by Halloween 1996, Digital Equipment Corp. decided it wanted
more _ and it sued Marshall for the rights to www.altavista.com on
grounds that Marshall had violated the previous agreement by
failing to disclose that his site was not the Alta Vista search
engine.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, a federal judge in Boston required Marshall to
change his logo, which was similar to Digital's Alta Vista logo,
and to add a disclaimer to his site. But he didn't rule on the
domain name itself.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said settlement negotiations were stalled until Compaq
bought Digital Equipment Corp. for $9 billion in January.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions came to a head Friday during a six-hour
deal-making session in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the negotiations said Marshall won $3.35
million plus a permanent link from the Alta Vista search engine to
his new Web site _ www.photoloft.com.
</P>
<P>
   On August 31, Marshall will shut down his old site and turn the
name over to Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said his agreement with Compaq prevents him from
commenting on the details of the settlement. Compaq officials were
not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In all the frenzy of wrapping up the project, Marshall, 37,
barely made it home in time to witness the birth of his second son
at 5:21 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to appear in bad faith by not coming out to
Boston,'' he said. ``But I'm just so happy I came back before the
baby arrived. It would have been terrible if I'd missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-27-98 2200EDT &QL;
