<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT CALLS ANTITRUST CASE `COMPLETELY GROUNDLESS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first court papers it has filed in its defense, Microsoft
Corp. called the government's sweeping antitrust case against it
``completely groundless'' and offered a glimpse of the legal
strategy it will pursue.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's formal answer to the suit filed in May by the
Justice Department and 20 states is an early step preceding a trial
in U.S. District Court in Washington, scheduled to begin on Sept.
8. Other, more detailed, court filings will be made later. Both
sides are scrambling to take depositions from potential witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The government has informed Microsoft that it wants to take a
videotaped deposition from Bill Gates, the company's chairman and
most prominent founder, according to a lawyer involved in trial
preparation. ``We want to see what kind of witness he makes,'' the
lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Microsoft would only say that Gates has not yet
been deposed.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a deposition from Gates, antitrust experts say, would not
be a surprising tactic. ``It would be just a common-sense strategy
on the government's part, given that Bill Gates apparently has
firsthand knowledge of everything important that goes on at
Microsoft,'' said Kevin Arquit, a partner at Rogers &AMP; Wells, a New
York law firm, and a former senior antitrust official at the
Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The taking of a pretrial deposition from Gates would not
necessarily be followed by his being called as a witness _ a
hostile one _ for the government side. But that option is open to
the government, and the Justice Department did put the chairman of
AT&AMP;T, John de Butts, on the stand in the government's landmark
antitrust case against AT&AMP;T. That case culminated in the breakup of
the company in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said Tuesday that its own trial preparation was being
hindered by a reluctant competitor, Novell Inc. ``We are dismayed
that Novell is resisting a court order to provide information,''
said Mark Murray, a spokesman for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Such delays, Murray said, could present ``significant problems''
for Microsoft as it tried to prepare for a Sept. 8 trial date. But
he added that the company was working with Novell to try to resolve
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing Tuesday, Microsoft denied all of the government's
major allegations. For example, the company said that it had
decided to include Internet browsing software in its operating
system as early as late 1994 and early 1995, before Netscape
Communications Corp. had even been founded.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was not until 1995 that Microsoft licensed from another
company, Spyglass Inc., the technology that became the core of its
Internet Explorer browser. In its defense, Microsoft said it will
argue, with supporting evidence, that the decision to include
browsing capabilities in its Windows 95 operating system was made
much earlier, even though it had not yet acquired the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also denied that it had ever tried to ``illegally
divide the browser market'' in meetings with Netscape, as the
Justice Department contends. Representatives from both companies,
the court papers say, met ``in Redmond, Wash., on June 2, 1995, and
again in Mountain View, Calif., on June 21, 1995, to explore ways
in which the two companies could work together to improve their
respective products.''
</P>
<P>
   Another government allegation is that Microsoft's contracts with
personal computer makers are restrictive, giving Microsoft
tight-fisted control over the main Windows screen that users see
when they start up their machines. These restrictions are important
to the government's antitrust case because, the Justice Department
says, they are intended to allow Microsoft to use its Windows
operating-system monopoly to give the company an unfair advantage
in the newer markets for Internet software and services.
</P>
<P>
   The government contends that the Windows main screen serves as a
crucial gateway to these new markets and that Microsoft is trying
to maintain a chokehold on that gateway.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing Tuesday, Microsoft replied that its Windows
licensing deal with personal-computer makers gives them ``broad
flexibility to differentiate their products in response to
perceived consumer preferences.'' The only restrictions it places
on personal-computer makers are those that ensure the ease-of-use
and reliability of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department issued a brief statement late Tuesday
afternoon, saying that the Microsoft filing contained ``numerous
misstatements and mischaracterizations.'' The Justice Department
added, ``We remain confident in our case and expect to prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also filed a countersuit against the states Tuesday,
asking the Federal court to toss out claims made under state
antitrust laws instead of the Federal statutes.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said the move was mainly intended to streamline the
case, but it also asked that the states pay the company's legal
fees for researching and responding to specific state laws.
Microsoft could not estimate what those fees might be, but they
would presumably be a small share of the company's total legal
costs to prepare for the trial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-28-98 2043EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
