<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, July 29, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;  (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
 &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-US-REAX (San Francisco) _ Local Indonesian Chinese
listened silently in horror as tales of violence aimed at
Indonesia's 8 million ethnic Chinese were told. But when reports
surfaced of brutal rapes of women and girls _ some of the victims
were as young as nine _ they couldn't sit silently any longer. By
JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   SF-HOUSING _ Lengthening the shadows over the administration of
San Francisco Housing Chief Ronnie Davis, the Department of Housing
and Urban Development has suspended his former boss and close
associate Claire Freeman-McCown from U.S. government work. HUD
cited charges that she allegedly used public funds to pay for her
private townhouse while head of public housing in Cleveland. By
ERIN McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   GROAT-CIA (Albany, N.Y.) _ Douglas F. Groat's son Shawn says he
is disappointed that his dad, a former CIA officer who believed in
never backing down, would strike a plea bargain to settle the
espionage charges brought against him. ``But if he thinks he's
doing the right thing, then I'm behind him,'' the son said in an
interview. By EDWARD FITZPATRICK.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE-COMA (San Antonio) _ State District Judge Mike Machado
shows slight signs of improvement from complications associated
with a brain aneurysm, but still is in grave condition. The
74-year-old judge and World War II hero is in a coma. By JAIME
CASTILLO.
</P>
<P>
   BRIBERY-TEXAS (Laredo) _ A former Webb County sheriff's deputy
is charged with helping a defendant facing cocaine charges
allegedly bribe an investigator in the district attorney's office
to keep his record clean. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL-FLAW (San Francisco) _ A security flaw found a month ago
in several popular e-mail programs is shaking up the on-line world.
The flaw, discovered by computer scientists at Oulu University in
Finland, has been confirmed by researchers at Microsoft and
Netscape. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   HOTBOT-ADS (San Francisco) _ Silverstein &AMP; Partners, the
advertising agency that created the ``Got Milk?'' campaign, will be
creating a multimillion-dollar advertising push for the HotBot
Internet search Web site. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WAR-MOVIES (San Francisco) _ One reason ``Saving Private Ryan''
is being talked about so much this summer is that it goes right
after the audience from the start, grabbing people out of their
seats to drag them through a half-hour of combat. It's the first
time a major war film has allowed itself to do that. By EDVINS
BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-MYSTERIES (Undated) _ Charles McCarry's ``Lucky Bastard''
is going to be compared to Richard Condon's ``The Manchurian
Candidate.'' After all, both books deal with a sleeper agent whose
ultimate goal is the takeover of the U.S. government. The
similarities end there. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-BASS (Undated) _ ``Where the Sea Used to Be''
(Houghton Mifflin, $25) by Rick Bass is superb novel about the
search for oil in Montana. Old Dudley, the main character, is Bass'
Ahab in a book that deserves comparison to Melville's symbolic epic
about a hunt for a white whale in ``Moby Dick.'' By MICHAEL
BERRYHILL.
</P>
<P>
   TONY-MORRISON (San Francisco) _ To read the works of Toni
Morrison requires a certain intensity and patience. She will pull
you in on the thread of images that unravel humanity's mysteries
and truths layer by layer, paragraph by paragraph. If you manage to
keep up, the end of the odyssey rewards you with interior sight. It
is not so different hearing her speak. By VENISE WAGNER.
</P>
<P>
   CBS-NIGHTMARE (Pasadena, Calif.) _ CBS should consider changing
its slogan from ``The Address is CBS: Welcome Home'' to ``Hey,
Guys, We're Over Here.'' The network is an audience demographics
nightmare: old and not enough men. As far as advertisers are
concerned, you couldn't do worse. By MARK McGUIRE. (For release
Sunday, Aug. 2)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LONE-STAR (Undated) _ The new racing season is brief and loaded
with family events. Quality horses are set to compete and there
isn't a slot machine to be found for four hours. It could be
Saratoga Race Course in New York on opening day. But this is
suburban Dallas, home of Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie, packing
them in its second year of existence, even as tracks nationwide are
being turned over to dog races, festivals or wrecking crews. By
JANE GOTTLIEB.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Jesus had zip to say about
wifely submission, virginity vs. marriage or lesbians and gays.
What he did say, over and over, is well put in Matthew 25, when he
talks about Judgment Day and who will be shut out of heaven. I
challenge all ``Christians'' to read that one _ and live it. By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Henry Lincoln Johnson committed an
act of conspicuous gallantry in France during World War I. The
French honored him with a Croix de Guerre. But he was a black man,
so America ignored him. He died 20 years later, his heroism only a
memory. But the U.S. government has still not awarded this war hero
a Medal of Honor. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Americans know the important news
that comes out of Washington, and they can distinguish it from the
usual politically motivated junk. The important news was the
slaying of two policemen who died defending the Capitol against an
armed madman. We pay tribute to Jacob Chestnut and John Gibson.
They were our best. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
