<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAFTA-GLANCE-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAFTA SIDE AGREEMENTS AT-A-GLANCE
 &HT;    With NAFTA-ENVIRONMENT-$ADV02.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Aug. 2 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENTAL INSTITUTIONS CREATED BY NAFTA SIDE AGREEMENT
</P>
<P>
   Commission on Environmental Cooperation (CEC)
</P>
<P>
   Based in Montreal, the commission is supposed to review
citizens' complaints that NAFTA countries (Canada, Mexico and the
United States) are not enforcing their environmental laws. The CEC,
however, has no power to sanction a country in response to these
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   North American Development Bank (NADBank)
</P>
<P>
   Based in San Antonio, Texas, the bank is supposed to loan money
to border communities in Mexico and the United States that are
overwhelmed by untreated sewage and insufficient potable water. No
projects have been built yet using bank loans.
</P>
<P>
   Border Environmental Cooperation Commission (BECC)
</P>
<P>
   Based in Juarez, Mexico, the commission is supposed to recommend
which water and sewage treatment proposals the NADBank should help
finance. The commission has no purview over toxic waste, which
threatens to hinder sewage treatment plants being built along the
border.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
