<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8046 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-CADET-$ADV01-C     07-29 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CADET-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRST FEMALE NAVAL CADET BATTLES HEAVY RESISTANCE, HIGH
EXPECTATIONS
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Aug. 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ Savoring the week of her 18th birthday
and the end of first-year exams, Lyudmila Yolshina resembles any
college freshman on her way to a dance club. Nails are polished, a
hint of make-up adorns her face and the mini-skirt is suitably
stylish.
</P>
<P>
   The first woman ever admitted to Russia's vaunted Frunze Naval
Academy, founded by Peter the Great in 1715, has just finished her
hellish inaugural year. August offers a chance to be a civilian
again, just another one of the girls before returning to her
arduous role as a minority of one in a school of more than 1,000
men.
</P>
<P>
   Cadets at the academy, one of Russia's most prestigious military
institutions, refer to her as ``Soldat Zhane'' -- G.I. Jane. Some
intend it as a compliment; others deliver it with a sneer.
</P>
<P>
   Similar to her American counterparts at military academies such
as Annapolis and West Point (who first gained entry in the 1970s),
she has tales of difficult days in an overwhelmingly male domain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think women should have the opportunity, but it is very
hard. Sometimes I feel I want to give it up because it is just too
hard. There are such moments,'' she confessed in a recent interview
with the Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet, I've managed to show them my place and their place,'' she
added with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Yolshina has been acclaimed as a symbol for the new Russia,
representing the transitional role of women in an Old-World society
notorious for male chauvinism. Russian television and newspapers
have featured her in stories, as have news media around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But the blonde-haired, soft-spoken Yolshina is a reluctant icon.
Dealing with demanding classes and hostile classmates is difficult
enough. Her mere presence is bucking tradition daily at the stately
18th-Century academy on the Neva River, which cuts through this
historic city.
</P>
<P>
   Yolshina does not want her success or failure interpreted as
something larger than what it may mean for her naval career. She is
uncomfortable as the litmus test on behalf of Russia's womanhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't try to be the exception. I am doing well. I am
studying hard for myself. There is no such feeling that since I am
the only woman and the first, that I must be the top student,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   And she is not sure she would recommend the experience to other
women.
</P>
<P>
   The odds are against every high-schooler -- male or female --
anxious to enter the demanding, tradition-bound academy; five of
every six applications are refused.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago, Yolshina and her father, a retired naval captain,
were bristling at her rejection. Despite her athletic abilities as
a competitive swimmer and her excellent academic record, the
academy was not prepared to allow her even to take the entrance
exam.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few women officers sent for specialized training,
no woman had ever been admitted to Russia's elite military
academies for the grueling five-year training as a career officer.
</P>
<P>
   Yolshina wrote letters to the navy's high command, the defense
ministry and the Kremlin in her struggle to be accepted. Her
ability to take the exams, and ultimately her acceptance last
August, were finally approved after she wrote letters directly to
President Boris Yeltsin asking him to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively few women in Russia's military -- they comprise
less than 1 percent of the total, compared to about 15 percent in
the U.S. military -- do not serve in combat roles, though tens of
thousands did in the Soviet army during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Yolshina, who has chosen meteorology as her specialty field,
acknowledges that she will likely never rise through the ranks to
command a ship. There are important jobs to be done on land, she
said, and she is prepared to carry out hers when she receives her
commission in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In her first week at the academy, she had no uniform because it
had to be specially designed. She wore civilian clothes and was
treated as a curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told classmates that I was a student and no one believed
me,'' she said. ``In the first weeks I didn't know how to behave
myself. I didn't know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazing, notorious in the Russian military, also takes place at
Frunze. But the word quickly spread among male students that
Yolshina was off-limits. Navy officials, aware of the public
interest in Yolshina and the academy's image, have instructed her
to report even the slightest problem.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the pressure from professors and fellow cadets is
intense, and entrenched attitudes are difficult to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Admiral Boris Popov, head of the academy, told reporters last
year: ``Women are no worse than men, and some are better suited for
certain navy professions,'' adding with a chuckle: ``They are
particularly good at meteorology -- look at the weather girls on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's restrooms existed at the academy for female members of
the administrative staff, but no dormitories. Yolshina commutes to
classes by subway from her parent's home and is exempted from
nightwatch duty, which tends to further alienate her from the
academy's male society.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she is content with the arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Yolshina speculates that the experience could be
even tougher if there were more females in her class, offering a
bigger target for those opposed to admitting women. More female
cadets might force the reluctant administration to make concessions
on boarding and might stir up more resentment among male students
and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be an issue soon. No women applied for the incoming
freshman class this year. Yolshina remains alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they try to find fault with everything I do. But I
think this is natural because I was the first in the school,'' she
said. ``I have to be ready for this now and in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
