<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8053 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-ENVIRONMENT-$A     07-29 1880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ENVIRONMENT-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    (EDS: This is part one of a report on the labor and
environmental side agreements established by the North American
Free Trade Agreement.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NAFTA ENVIRONMENTAL AGREEMENT: A PAPER TIGER?
 &HT;    With NAFTA-GLANCE-$ADV02; MEXICO-NAFTA-$ADV03.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, August 2 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COZUMEL, Mexico _ When huge cruise ships belly up to a new
concrete pier off this Caribbean island, it's a bitter reminder to
Dora Uribe of an opportunity lost.
</P>
<P>
   An opportunity, she says, to use the North American Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA) to mount an 11th-hour campaign to stop the pier
and save Paradise Reef. Environmentalists had long argued that the
reef would be broken to pieces and eventually destroyed by visiting
ships.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1996, Uribe and other Mexican environmentalists were
the first to file a complaint with a special commission established
by NAFTA's environmental side agreement. By arguing that Mexican
laws had been ignored or violated in the pier's planning, the
petitioners had hoped the commission would fine or at least
chastise Mexico enough to embarrass officials into stopping the
pier's construction.
</P>
<P>
   After waiting nearly two years, they received ``a beautiful''
report from the commission last October, peppered with facts to
back up the environmentalists' position, Uribe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there wasn't one recommendation,'' said Uribe, a lawyer on
this small Mexican island 40 miles south of Cancun. ``The only
conclusion you can make . . . is that this is another bureaucracy
with no power.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cozumel experience is one of the hard lessons learned by
environmentalists who have tried to use the NAFTA side agreement to
ensure that laws in each country are followed, not flouted or
downgraded, as free trade spreads in Mexico, the United States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal-based Commission on Environmental Cooperation (CEC)
is charged with reviewing citizen complaints in each country, but
the process doesn't allow the commission to penalize a nation for
failing to enforce its own laws.
</P>
<P>
   Another institution set up to accompany NAFTA, which went into
effect in 1994, is the San Antonio, Texas-based North American
Development Bank (NADBank), established to make or secure loans for
water and sewage treatment projects in Mexico and the United States
that would clean up the troubled border region.
</P>
<P>
   Although NADBank counts 21 projects for which it is actively
helping find financing, not a single water or sewage-treatment
plant has been built using a bank loan.
</P>
<P>
   The NADBank also has a sister institution, the Border
Environmental Cooperation Commission (BECC), a binational agency
based in Juarez, Mexico, that reviews applications for NADBank
assistance and decides if the proposals are well-designed and
financially feasible.
</P>
<P>
   The BECC, critics say, has limited power because it doesn't have
purview over toxic waste, pollution that threatens the operation of
sewage treatment plants built along the border.
</P>
<P>
   At the CEC in Montreal, director Greg Block said, ``I'm very
aware there are mixed and divisive views among the public'' on the
environmental side agreement's efficacy.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, he said, was not granted the power through NAFTA
to take a side when reviewing citizens' complaints, although some
people may have mistakenly believed this.
</P>
<P>
   He said the reviews ``let the facts speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Block defended the CEC, arguing that it is successfully
pursuing a North American-wide program to phase out dangerous
pesticides and funding small environmental research projects and
businesses in each country. And, he added, the CEC has had some
success responding to environmental crises.
</P>
<P>
   When 40,000 migratory birds in Mexico perished in 1995 at a
poisoned reservoir, Block said, the CEC investigated -- ``with a
good deal of cooperation from Mexico'' -- and recommended methods
to curtail pollution.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, the NADBank has found its work stymied, in part,
because private financing for infrastructure projects proved
difficult to secure and Mexican municipalities were virtually
blocked from accepting loans by federal constraints. What's more,
few Mexican cities have experience at instituting user fees to
guarantee that loans for projects would be paid back.
</P>
<P>
   The $400 million that Mexico and the United States have
contributed to the bank so far is insufficient to directly finance
costly infrastructure projects, according to NADBank director
Victor Miramontes.
</P>
<P>
   The bank is still trying to obtain loans, but it has retooled
its mission.
</P>
<P>
   It is now focusing heavily on administering a program offering
$170 million in grants supplied by the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency to help get critical projects built.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without grants, this system doesn't work,'' said Miramontes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're barely beginning,'' he added. ``If we haven't built
anything in five years, I'll be on the critics' side.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hundreds of millions of gallons of sewage are still
flowing into rivers and oceans off Texas and California, along with
toxic chemicals from the growing number of ``maquiladoras,'' or
Mexican export factories.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1 million people living along the border lack basic
water delivery and sewage disposal systems. Environmentalists worry
that without careful planning, projects to address these festering
problems won't keep up with border population growth that's
expected to double by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
   All of the NAFTA environmental agencies enjoy defenders --
including environmentalists -- who say that the institutions are
vital to free and fair trade, and must be given a chance to mature.
</P>
<P>
   The NADBank is working on relaxing Mexican bureaucratic
obstacles that have prevented municipalities from getting direct
loans, said Mark Spalding, a University of California at San Diego
lecturer who wrote a report on the bank called ``Promising
Potential'' for the National Wildlife Federation.
</P>
<P>
   The CEC, Spalding acknowledged, has no power to stop
environmentally-damaging projects, something that is ``one of the
big criticisms.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, media coverage over the CEC probe into the
Cozumel pier ``embarrassed Mexico,'' and has paved the way for more
transparent reviews for other controversial proposals in that
country.
</P>
<P>
   Gustavo Alanis, director of the Mexican Center for Environmental
Law, was among those who filed the citizen complaint over the
Cozumel pier.
</P>
<P>
   He has turned to the CEC to register other complaints, he said,
because the commission's international spotlight provides objective
information that encourages wider debate in Mexico. The CEC's
attention to the pier, he added, forced Mexico to improve its laws
to protect endangered reefs and prompted an environmental plan for
the island of Cozumel.
</P>
<P>
   But he, too, was disappointed that after many months of waiting
-- while construction went ahead on the pier -- ``you end with
this: a report, only facts, and no conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Seligman of the Sierra Club in Washington, D.C. is more
critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public was sold a bill of goods (with the NAFTA side
agreement),'' he said. ``As a general matter, there was more
promise than could possibly be delivered by these institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   The NADBank was a flawed concept, Seligman said, because it was
expected to lure private capital to finance, in Mexico, the type of
infrastructure projects that Americans had to build with government
money.
</P>
<P>
   Another underlying problem, he said, was that border factories
in Mexico -- many of them American _ are not being sufficiently
taxed by Mexico to contribute to water and sewage projects in the
communities where they dump waste and use resources.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Seligman said, United States EPA money, ``American
taxpayers' money,'' is now being used to help finance projects
across the border.
</P>
<P>
   Also worrisome, Seligman and other environmentalists agree, is
the specter that NAFTA-backed infrastructure projects along the
Texas-California-Arizona border with Mexico will suffer because of
toxic chemicals, explosive population and industrial growth.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Diego-Tijuana border region, where millions of
gallons of raw sewage from Tijuana are dumped into the ocean each
day, a highly touted binational sewage treatment plant that opened
earlier this year to dispose of Tijuana's waste is failing acute
toxicity tests.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: sludge from Tijuana contains a toxic stew of various
industrial chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA and other agencies managing the plant, which was started
before NAFTA, are conducting tests to figure out what the poisons
are, and will need cooperation from Tijuana to identify sources and
prevent businesses from dumping chemicals into sewage systems.
</P>
<P>
   The toxic substances ``could be coming from U.S. companies in
Tijuana,'' said Elizabeth Borowic, EPA's project manager for the
plant.
</P>
<P>
   One of the projects supported by the BECC and the NADBank is an
upgraded sewage-treatment center in Tijuana that currently treats
only about half the sewage it receives.
</P>
<P>
   The NAFTA-backed Tijuana project is slated to be connected to
the San Diego binational plant, but the plan will end up a disaster
if authorities in Mexico don't come up with an adequate program to
prevent toxic dumping.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists are upset because they predicted the San Diego
binational plant would be overwhelmed by toxic chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were really expecting to use this as a model for
binational cooperation,'' said Cesar Luna of San Diego's
Environmental Health Coalition. ``It would like a jewel of NAFTA.
Instead, it's like a cubic zirconium.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has no right-to-know laws that require public disclosure
of toxic substances, and in the past it has been reluctant to
reveal that information publicly on the American side of the
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years after NAFTA,'' Luna said, ``this sort of thing
should have been resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Texas-Mexico border, raw sewage is still flowing into the
Rio Grande river despite a sewage-treatment plant inaugurated in
Nuevo Laredo, Mexico, in 1996 with much fanfare from both
countries' governments.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators discovered that the plant, which President Clinton
cited as a NAFTA success story, will require millions of dollars
more in construction costs so that it can capture sludge from
growing communities that were not properly connected to the system
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican and U.S. authorities are trying to determine how to pay
for the costs, given that Nuevo Laredo is financially-strapped.
</P>
<P>
   Other projects planned for the border cities of Juarez, Acuna,
Reynosa and Matamoros could face similar problems if such obstacles
are not anticipated, said Cyrus Reed of the Texas Center for Policy
Studies in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're building things now to take care of problems that have
accumulated for years,'' Reed said. ``But the growth on the border
continues.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
