<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-NAFTA-$ADV03-C     07-29 1685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-NAFTA-$ADV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    (EDS: This is part two of a report on the labor and
environmental side agreements established by the North American
Free Trade Agreement.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NAFTA LABOR AGREEMENT: SO FAR, IT HAS BITE, BUT FEW TEETH
 &HT;    With NAFTA-ENVIRONMENT-$ADV02.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Tijuana is south of San
Diego along the U.S.-Mexico border.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Monday, August 3 And thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIJUANA, Mexico _ Norberto Cordoba says he was fired from Han
Young, a Korean-owned auto parts factory here, for a simple reason:
``They told me I was a 'political man.'''
</P>
<P>
   The 49-year-old welder didn't take his unjust dismissal lightly.
</P>
<P>
   He, and Mexican and American labor activists have taken his
grievance and a range of others alleging unfair treatment at the
Han Young export, or ``maquiladora'' factory in Tijuana, all the
way to Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a high-profile battle that is dampening free-trade
support in the U.S. capital, straining U.S.-Mexican relations and
testing a promise that the North American Free Trade Agreement
(NAFTA) would benefit -- rather than exploit -- laborers in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   When NAFTA was enacted in 1994, a special side agreement set up
offices in the labor departments of the United States, Mexico and
Canada where people could submit complaints charging that member
countries were failing to enforce their own labor laws.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Kantor, former U.S. Trade Representative in the Clinton
administration, promised then that the side agreement would have
``real teeth.'' But NAFTA opponents were skeptical because the pact
-- the North American Agreement on Labor Cooperation -- included
only limited provisions for penalizing a country for refusing to
change bad habits.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Mexican and U.S. labor activists have been teaming up
to submit complaints and use the agreement as a forum for
spotlighting abuses, especially in Mexico's maquiladora industry.
Maquiladoras employ about 1 million people in nearly 3,000
factories that assemble export goods for U.S. consumers. Han Young,
for example, welds truck chassis for Hyundai Precision America, the
automobile manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this doesn't work, if labor rights are not respected, then
this was all a deception and the labor agreement was simply a way
to protect cheap labor,'' said Tijuana labor organizer Enrique
Hernandez, a leader in the Han Young dispute who has been
threatened with arrest for his activities and whose office has been
vandalized.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Labor Department has received nine petitions alleging
unchecked abuses in Mexico, ranging from discrimination against
pregnant women in maquiladoras to reprisal against independent
labor unions attempting to organize in these factories.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's Labor Ministry, for its part, is investigating
complaints filed against the United States, including one alleging
that U.S. officials have failed to protect Mexican apple workers in
Washington state from anti-union intimidation and health and safety
threats.
</P>
<P>
   The Han Young complaint is twofold: It charges that Mexico
failed to enforce laws protecting health and safety, as well as the
workers' constitutional right to organize an independent union.
</P>
<P>
   Independent unions are a sensitive subject in Mexico's
maquiladoras, a sector dominated only by unions that are affiliated
with Mexico's ruling political party, the Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI). Han Young's maquiladora workers are
among the first in Mexico to successfully obtain recognition for
their independent union.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't been easy, according to an ongoing U.S. probe into
Han Young. Today, despite requests from U.S. officials to address
harassment of the Han Young workers, the independent union is still
battling to represent the employees at the factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement depends on cooperation, and the Mexican
government is not cooperating,'' said Mary Tong, director of the
San Diego-based Support Committee for Maquiladora Workers, one of
the groups that filed the Han Young complaint.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year ago, Hernandez and a group of Han Young workers
upset with working conditions and wages as low as $8 a day tried to
organize their independent union. They were foiled, they say, by
the company, which dismissed sympathetic workers and hired and
intimidated new ones. In addition, the Tijuana labor authorities
conducted poorly-run union elections and then refused to recognize
an independent union victory.
</P>
<P>
   A second vote that upheld the independent union's victory was
held after federal government intervention -- and after President
Clinton and Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo discussed the Han
Young dispute at the urging of U.S. House Democratic Whip David E.
Bonior of Michigan, a NAFTA opponent who has seized on Han Young as
an example of worker abuse in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, the independent union, assisted by American labor
activists, filed its complaint with the U.S. Department of Labor.
And in late April, the department issued a diplomatic but
devastating report that criticized Mexico and backed up the
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The report challenged Mexican officials' impartiality and
commitment to enforcement of its laws, and found that
government-affiliated unions enjoyed more legal protection than
independent unions. It also recommended that Mexico's labor
secretary meet with U.S. Labor Secretary Alexis Herman.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's initial response was hostile, according to published
reports, with the Mexican Labor Ministry accusing the United States
of taking sides and a Tijuana labor official calling the report ``a
lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials are silent on the matter now, saying they are
waiting for a second report on health and safety at Han Young to be
issued by the United States before commenting. No meeting between
the labor secretaries has been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the request for consultations, the relationship between
the independent union and Tijuana labor officials has deteriorated
further. Police have clashed with pro-union workers, attempting to
break up a strike that a judge declared was legal under Mexican
law. After a government-affiliated union said it wanted to regain
its hold on the factory, officials held two more questionable
elections whose results were not released.
</P>
<P>
   Labor organizer Hernandez had to obtain a court order to prevent
Tijuana authorities from arresting him. Anti-American banners were
hung up at the plant, urging ``gringos'' to stay out of Han Young.
</P>
<P>
   Bonior issued a blunt statement from Washington, accusing Han
Young management, Tijuana labor officials and the Mexican
government of ``a systematic effort to deny Han Young workers their
right to an independent union through harassment, intimidation and
fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the outcome of the dispute ``a test for the Mexican
government,'' and warned that it ``could have long-term
implications for U.S. trade policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonior also used the Han Young case to defeat President
Clinton's bid for continued ``fast-track'' authority to negotiate
new free-trade deals.
</P>
<P>
   The Han Young case is so sensitive that Irasema Garza, the
secretary of the office that produced the U.S. report, won't
comment on it other than to say that she is concerned and
monitoring developments.
</P>
<P>
   But a U.S. Labor official familiar with the case said despite
the chilly reception from Mexico, the dispute shows how the NAFTA
side agreement is working to pressure Mexico to enforce its own
laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``That union that is currently struggling (in Tijuana) right now
would not exist were it not for the process,'' said the official,
who asked not to be identified. ``I can't say it any clearer than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, Garza said, ``The Mexican government, to be quite
honest with you, has been cautious (about the side agreement). I
think this is not an experience they have enjoyed.''
</P>
<P>
   The second report on Han Young, focusing on alleged health and
safety violations and due to be released before summer's end, could
be even more explosive than the first.
</P>
<P>
   These accusations, if left unaddressed by Mexican officials,
could lead to U.S. trade sanctions against Mexico, including up to
tens of millions of dollars in fines.
</P>
<P>
   The NAFTA countries can only face sanctions if they are found to
have flagrantly violated their own child-labor, health and safety
or minimum-wage laws. There are no provisions for sanctions for
violating the right to unionize.
</P>
<P>
   Garza acknowledged that getting to sanctions could take years of
negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement is designed in such a way to try to convince a
government to do the right thing . . . ,'' she said. ``Ultimately,
that's what this is about. It's not about penalizing governments.
It really is about governments being convinced to enforce their own
labor laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though sanctions are unlikely, Garza defended the NAFTA
side agreement for opening up ``public debate'' in Mexico through
public hearings that have been held to gather testimony on various
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing on union organizing in Mexico City, she said, ``the
workers would come up to me and say, 'Miss Garza, this is historic
. . . We don't have access to our government officials like you do
in the United States. This is an opportunity we've never had.'''
</P>
<P>
   She said Mexico, through a new five-year plan, is addressing
problems that have been raised some complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Alfredo Gualde, who studies maquiladoras at the College of the
Northern Border in Tijuana, said the NAFTA side agreement has
``symbolic import'' and puts companies under pressure to comply
with existing laws or face public criticism, especially bad reviews
in Washington, D.C. and in the American press.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most of the substantial change,'' he said, ``has to come
from within Mexico itself.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
