<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONORING THE HEROES OF A COLORBLIND SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ I went Monday afternoon to see Henry Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Six decades ago, he was a railroad porter in this town. Now,
he's a bronze monument in Washington Park.
</P>
<P>
   That monument is all anybody can find of Henry Lincoln Johnson
these days. He committed an act of conspicuous gallantry in France
during World War I. The French honored him with a Croix de Guerre.
But he was a black man, so America ignored him. He died 20 years
later, his heroism only a memory. He was buried in an unmarked
pauper's grave near what's now Albany International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, he lay forgotten. Then the 369th Veterans
Organization, a group of black vets, began pushing to get Henry
Johnson in death the honors denied him in life.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there's the monument. There's a street named after him.
There's a posthumous Purple Heart. No Medal of Honor yet, but the
369th is working hard to get that done, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, Mr. Johnson,'' I said to the monument, ``what do you
think?''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't answer, of course. But gazing at the bust of the man,
in his doughboy uniform, I wished profoundly that he could. What
would Henry Johnson think about the letter that John Hope Franklin
wrote to President Clinton last week?
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that we should aspire to a colorblind society is an
impediment to reducing racial stereotyping,'' Franklin wrote.
``Given that research has demonstrated that the best way to reduce
racial stereotyping is to be conscious about racial differences, it
is important to present a thoughtful alternative to the colorblind
society concept.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hope Franklin of Duke University is a distinguished
historian and author. He chairs a presidential panel to advise the
president on racial matters. His letter represented an open
repudiation of one of the best ideas this country ever had _
integration.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. summed up the integrationist credo in
a speech shortly before he was murdered. He said he dreamed of a
time when his children could be judged by the content of their
character rather than the color of their skin.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, Medals of Honor were belatedly awarded to
African-American soldiers from World War II. One recipient was Lt.
Johnny Fox, who died in Italy in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   His widow clutched the medal to her chest and said, ``I think
this sends a message ... when a man does his duty, his color isn't
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Arlene Fox understood that her husband and others, like Henry
Johnson, had been denied the honors due them precisely because
their race was deemed their most important characteristic _ more
important than their deeds, more important even than their
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Black Americans have fought and died in all this country's wars
_ the good wars and the bad ones alike _ because they've been half
of the longest unrequited love affair in the planet's history. They
understood that however unrealized, the American ideal was loyalty
to a magnificent set of egalitarian political principles rather
than preoccupation with accidents of birth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at century's end, with racism at a lower ebb than at any
time in our national history, we have a presidential panel openly
rejecting the goal of a colorblind society.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, I don't think that's what Henry Johnson fought for. I
don't think it's what Johnny Fox died for. They did what they did
because they believed that acceptance and inclusion were worth any
sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Unless we somehow get past this idea that blood is everything _
that race matters above all other considerations _ then how can we
ever fully accept one another as full-fledged fellow Americans?
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Dr. King would have put it, as brothers and sisters with
a common birthright of equality.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
