<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIANS VS. CHRISTIAN VIRTUES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The letter was handwritten on nice white
stationery printed with pretty yellow roses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't you know that being gay causes AIDS?'' it began.
``Didn't you know that being gay is unnatural?''
</P>
<P>
   The writer, from Kentucky, was responding to a column of mine
about televangelist Pat Robertson. He'd predicted that the folks
around Disney World ought to fear hurricanes from God because the
amusement park holds ``Gay Days.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter continued: ``I suppose you think perhaps we should
have a commit adultery day, a steal something today day, etc.
America does need to repent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat Robertson is a man of God. I've heard him pray lovely
prayers for sick people to get healed. So quit condemning ministers
like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the column did I condemn Robertson _ condemnation is
his specialty _ or criticize him for praying for the sick. Mostly I
pointed out how much money and political clout the man has.
</P>
<P>
   The letter closed: ``I challenge you to read Romans 1:26-32.
Remember God loves us and He knows what is best for us.''
</P>
<P>
   As letters from Bible-touting readers go, this one was pleasant.
While it was typical in its sweeping (and erroneous) quid pro quo _
``Don't you know that being gay causes AIDS?'' _ it was atypical in
its polite language, its brevity and in the absence of my eternal
soul being consigned to hell.
</P>
<P>
   The nastier mail and the more vile phone messages come from
people who identify themselves as ``Christians'' and tell me to
read the Bible. (Or who fill several pages quoting the Bible.) The
usual subject for such a screed is homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the quotes attributed to Jesus in the New Testament, not
one mentions homosexuality. But the issue of ``unnatural use,''
especially of ``males lying with males,'' sure occupies a big
portion of many contemporary Christians' minds.
</P>
<P>
   From the volume and tenor of mail and calls I receive, one would
have to conclude that the incidence of homosexuality in the world
far outranks that of poverty and injustice _ two subjects that
Jesus frequently weighed in on.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many Christians, the writer from Kentucky told me to
read a passage from Paul's letter to the Romans. Although different
translations make every Biblical passage subject to startling
variation, the most common translations of Romans 1:26-32 promise
damnation for women who ``did change their natural use into that
which is against nature'' and men who ``burned in their lust toward
one another; men with men working that which is unseemly.''
</P>
<P>
   As that passage goes on, a lot of people get a haircut _ from
fornicators (listed ahead of murderers) to ``whisperers'' and
``inventors of evil things.'' (How many Christians wrote to the
scientists on the Manhattan Project?)
</P>
<P>
   In his lifetime, Paul wrote several letters that covered many
subjects. Because it distinguished Jews from Gentiles, circumcision
was one of his regular topics.
</P>
<P>
   When he was at his most cosmic and big-picture, Paul was as good
as it gets in the Bible. His mystical-yet-practical treatise on
love (I Corinthians 13) could stand alone, forever, as the credo
for a people committed to peace, understanding, compassion and
service.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul was human and a man of his time. If we believe in the
equal weight of every word that is attributed to him, we must
``beware of dogs'' (Philippians 3:2), remember that ``jesting'' is
a sin (Ephesians 5:4), command slaves to obey their masters ``with
fear and trembling'' (Ephesians 6:5) and accept that it is better
and easier to be near God if one eschews marriage and remains a
virgin (I Corinthians, most of Chapter 7).
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the woman-thing.
</P>
<P>
   In Ephesians 5:22 Paul says: ``Wives, submit yourselves unto
your own husbands, as unto the Lord.'' In I Corinthians 11:3-7, he
specifies proper head gear in church. Men: Hats off. Women: Heads
covered.
</P>
<P>
   Why the difference? Because ``the head of every man is Christ;
and the head of the woman is the man ... (the man) is the image and
glory of God; but the woman is the glory of the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Where are the angry letters from modern Christians about the
scourge of church-going women with uncovered heads?
</P>
<P>
   Jesus had zip to say about hats, veils, wifely submission, dogs,
jesters, virginity vs. marriage or lesbians and gays. What he did
say, over and over, is well put in Matthew 25, when he talks about
Judgment Day and who will be shut out of heaven.
</P>
<P>
   It's those who encountered the ``least of my brethren,'' the
sick, naked, hungry, thirsty and imprisoned and _ failing to see in
them the person of Christ _ did nothing for these people.
</P>
<P>
   I challenge all ``Christians'' to read that one _ and live it.
Most of my homosexual friends do.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
