<SLUG> BC-CBS-NIGHTMARE-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP WANTED: CBS NEEDS GUYS FOR ITS STODGY NETWORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 2)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ CBS should consider changing its slogan from
``The Address is CBS: Welcome Home'' to ``Hey, Guys, We're Over
Here.''
</P>
<P>
   The network is an audience demographics nightmare: old _ 30
percent of its viewers are 65 and older _ with no males. As far as
advertisers are concerned, you couldn't do worse. CBS is
understandably desperate to get men, especially younger
city-dwelling males, to watch its shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Admittedly we are going after more males and a more urban
audience this season,'' said CBS network head Leslie Moonves. ``We
need to get younger. This effort is partially based on economics,
partly to provide a broad range of programming for our viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. As Moonves said, the folks at Polident don't go to
Fox with their ad dollars. The trick for a network that is as hip
as, well, Angela Lansbury is to start attracting young men without
alienating its female and older viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-five and younger men weren't watching anything on CBS
over the last four years,'' Moonves said. ``We lost that group
almost entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   So what happened four years ago? CBS lost its National Football
League package to Fox. The hit the network took was so sharp the
execs were willing to pony up $4 billion over five years to bring
it back. It's no surprise the network's promo for bringing back
football featured the Who song ``Won't Get Fooled Again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can underestimate how much the loss of
football had hurt us four years ago,'' Moonves said. ``I think the
values that will happen to the network across the board will be
unbelievable in terms of being a platform for promotion as well as
revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Football's real value to the network is serving as a promotional
vehicle for other programs. CBS hopes they will catch ads for the
network's sitcoms and dramas and be inclined to tune in.
</P>
<P>
   The network is trying. ``Martial Law'' will feature Jackie
Chan-like mayhem from famed Hong Kong actor, director and martial
arts expert Sammo Hung. ``Buddy Faro'' will feature Dennis Farina
(``Out of Sight,'' ``Saving Private Ryan'' and the stylish but
brief show ``Crime Story'') as a detective out of circulation for
20 years returning, time encapsulated, to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, returning to the schedule are the Navy lawyer show
``Jag,'' and ``Walker: Texas Ranger,'' both the equivalent of
testosterone in a can. The Hong Kong legend Hung vs. Chuck Norris
could be a fun pay-per-view.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's entire slate of new CBS dramas and comedies did not
survive. And CBS took heat for canceling ``Dr. Quinn: Medicine
Woman'' (which could return next year in the form of a two-hour
movie).
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately it was a decision we had to make,'' Moonves said
of Dr. Quinn. ``This does not mean we are abandoning our loyal,
core audience. CBS continues to serve our female viewers and our
rural audience better than any other network.''
</P>
<P>
   So the network will have shows now for males and well as
females. The question is: Will any of the new or current fare be
able to attract both at the same time? Ray Romano, whose show
``Everybody Loves Raymond'' was worthy of an Emmy nomination it did
not receive, now finds himself in the same bind as the network
after his sitcom was moved from 8:30 to 9 p.m. on Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll lose the women to `Ally McBeal' and the men to `Monday
Night Football,''' he said only slightly in jest. ``I don't know
where the audience is.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS does. The question is, will the guys come over.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
