<SLUG> BC-PROUTS-NECK-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRADITION BY THE SEA 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE HATFIELD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROUTS NECK, Maine _ Half of the people who summer in Prouts
Neck (and ``summer'' is most decidedly a verb in these parts) do so
because their mother and father summered in Prouts Neck, and in
many cases because their grandmother and grandfather summered in
Prouts Neck. The other half summer here because they are lucky
enough to have married into a Prouts Neck family.
</P>
<P>
   Take Cambridge (Mass.) District Court Judge George R. Sprague,
of Boston and Prouts Neck. Sprague concedes that it is his wife
Lee's family that is responsible for the beautiful old wood frame
``cottage'' overlooking the sea and Cape Elizabeth. In a typical
Prouts Neck geneological explanation of its provenance, Lee Sprague
says, ``This house was my grandmother's second husband's first
wife's family _ the May family _ which bought it in 1888. Rosamond
May married Boston lawyer Frank White and when she died in 1940,
she left it to him. He married my grandmother Florence Thorndike,
who lived here with her staff until 1968. In 1968 she had a stroke
and in 1969 we rented the house from her. We moved here permanently
(for the summer) in the summer of 1970.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Which makes us relative newcomers,'' says George Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   The house, with its dark wood interior walls, antique furniture,
bright chintz upholstery, and old photos and maps and histories of
the area on the walls and in the bookshelves, is a treasure. The
few changes the Spragues have made have been to add decks for more
spectacular views of the bay.
</P>
<P>
   Change is exactly what this enclave in the middle of Scarborough
does not want. It is set apart from the rest of the town by the
configuration of land, which juts out from the coastline and
encompasses about 150 acres. A walk around the neck, a very popular
evening activity, takes about 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Prouts Neck is also set apart because half its 400 residents
have summered here all their lives. There are a hundred cottages,
half of them owned by Bostonians, the rest owned by residents of
New York, Philadelphia, Washington, D.C., Texas, and, in one case,
San Francisco (the husband grew up here).
</P>
<P>
   Traditions rule in this community named after Timothy Prout, a
farmer, and the first tradition is that there is never, ever, an
apostrophe in the word Prouts. Don't ask why.
</P>
<P>
   The second tradition is that there shall be lobster cookouts at
the yacht club on Memorial Day and Columbus Day, and there shall be
fish chowder lunches at the yacht club on the Fourth of July, the
first weekend in August, and Labor Day. At the latter, participants
are served _ without variation _ chowder in the club's collection
of old pots, with a chowder cracker on the bottom and a sticky
doughnut on the handle.
</P>
<P>
   Tradition also dictates that Sunday evenings are for picnicking
``on the rocks'' overlooking the ocean, followed by a community
sing-along at the yacht club that begins at 8:15 p.m. and finishes
at 9:30 precisely. Charles ``Chip'' Homer Willauer, an interior
designer in Boston in winter, has directed the sing-along every
Sunday for 42 years with the exception of July 12, when he had
bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   It was Willauer's grandfather who started the sing-along during
World War II, when the village fathers were trying to keep
everyone's blackout shades down for protection from enemy
submarines. ``The elders thought it might be pleasant to gather
everyone in one place which had shades _ back then it was the
country club _ and that they might as well sing while they remained
there,'' Willauer said.
</P>
<P>
   The sing has attracted participants from 2 to 80 and is such a
tradition that villagers published a Prouts Neck song book, and
everyone has a copy. It includes Stephen Foster songs and camp
songs and even an original written by a committee of neighbors,
``The Prouts Neck Song'': ``The atmosphere we love, it's Prouts
we're singing of. The friends we make we'll not forsake the fun
from Prouts Neck Shore''
</P>
<P>
   The Prouts Neck sing-along stopped, briefly, when Willauer's
grandfather suffered a heart attack in 1952, ``but in 1955, a
friend started them up again in his memory,'' notes Willauer.
</P>
<P>
   Willauer, who says ``I have spent every summer of my life in
Prouts Neck, and I'm 60 years old,'' also is president of the
Prouts Neck Association, which calls itself a ``village improvement
society'' and administers such matters as trash collection and
develops guidelines to keep the ``simple little community,'' as he
terms it, simple. He doesn't belong to the country club ``because I
don't play golf or tennis,'' but joined the yacht club because he
likes to sail. The clubs are private and exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you rent a cottage doesn't give you access to the
community,'' warns Willauer. However, the 100 guests staying at the
Black Point Inn, which sits at the entrance to the neck, are
invited to use the golf and tennis facilities of the country club.
</P>
<P>
   It's Willauer's middle name that connects him, and a score of
Prouts Neck residents, to the community's most famous son. Winslow
Homer, the landscape and marine painter, lived and worked in Prouts
Neck from 1884 until his death in 1910, and if you don't bump into
one of his descendants while walking around the point, you're sure
to bump into someone whose relative at least had him to dinner.
They'll tell you the painter wasn't always wealthy, and he used to
give gifts of a painting to his hostess. A generous gift,
considering the recent news that Microsoft owner Bill Gates
purchased Homer's painting ``Lost on the Grand Banks,'' for $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
