<SLUG> BC-STATES-AMTRAK-NAT </SLUG>

 &HT;        AMTRAK REPORTS RISE IN RIDERSHIP
 &HT;        By Jason Lakin
 &HT;       c. 1998 States News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  &QC;  WASHINGTON, July 29 -- Amtrak ridership is up 6.2 percent
over last year at this time, leaders of the federally subsidized
rail line announced Wednesday during the first meeting of its
infant Board of Directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have your ridership up, your on-time performance up and a
newfound love of railroads in America,'' said Tommy Thompson,
Wisconsin's Republican governor and a board member. ``I think
you're on the dawn of a new era.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak's revenues are also $12.7 million higher for the current
fiscal year than had been projected, while on-time performance has
improved to 79.6 percent for the year, up from 75.9 percent at this
point last year.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater, one of four board
members, attributed Amtrak's success in part to legislation passed
last year by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted with the third quarter results, and look to
Amtrak as a vital element in our 21st-century transportation
system,'' Slater said. ``Last December, President Clinton signed
the Amtrak Reform and Accountability Act of 1997 that provided
Amtrak with the three things it needed to succeed: freedom to
operate like a business, financial resources necessary to rebuild a
railroad, and partnership with its employees.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Thompson and Slater, the meeting's board members
include former Massachusetts Governor Michael Dukakis, the 1988
Democratic presidential nominee, and John Robert Smith, mayor of
Meridian, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Dukakis anticipated a successful kickoff of the Northeast
Corridor project, a high-speed rail line set to open next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Northeast Corridor, the kind of capital investment
Congress has been kind enough to provide is going to create
enormous new revenue,'' Dukakis said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said that the board will unveil more plans for
expansion soon, but he did not specify a date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of plans going on right now,'' Thompson said.
``We're going to be revealing a Midwest plan. We have to go to
Congress and get that clarified.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak, created by Congress in 1971, has a payroll of 23,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers threatened earlier this year to take Amtrak subsidies
away, but instead reshuffled the organization, with a goal of
making the company self-sufficient by 2002. Last April, Congress
passed a budget resolution affirming that commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing ridership and improving financial performance show
that Amtrak is on the right track to improve service, modernize its
business and strengthen passenger rail service,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Congress reformed Amtrak's board of directors,
reducing its size from nine members to seven. Three of those seats
currently are vacant.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's transportation secretary holds a permanent seat on
the board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8110 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-NEGOTIATOR-BOS &LR;      07-29 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-NEGOTIATOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE END, `NEGOTIATOR' FUMBLES THE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE NEGOTIATOR 
Directed by: F. Gary Gray 
Screenplay by: James DeMonaco, Kevin Fox 
Starring: Samuel L. Jackson, Kevin Spacey, David Morse, Ron Rifkin,
John Spencer, J.T. Walsh 
Running time: 138 minutes 
Rated: R (violence and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hostage negotiations, almost by definition, are ordeals. So are
movies about them. ``The Negotiatior'' is probably as good a
slicked-up Hollywood version as we're likely to get. Certainly, it
helps that Samuel L. Jackson and Kevin Spacey are on hand to play
Chicago's No.1 and No.2 police negotiators, respectively. The
gimmick is that Jackson is framed for the murder of a fellow cop
and the theft of millions from the police disability fund, forces
the situation, and finds himself on the receiving end of the
expertise he's so good at dishing out.
</P>
<P>
   Real negotiations are low key and deliberate, the idea being not
to detonate any fireworks. But movies about them are invariably
punched up with commando raids, countdowns with guns held to
hostages' heads and tense faceoffs. ``The Negotiator'' is good up
to the point where it begins to resort inordinately to these
cattle-prod devices. Jackson brings dignity and depth to what could
have been the completely stereotyped figure of the framed cop, and
does much to humanize the cop's anguish and anger, until, of
course, the producers cave in and pile on the fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Spacey's way of finding humor in unlikely places continues with
the way we're introduced to his cop, trying to negotiate his wife
out of their bedroom, into which she has locked herself because
their preteen daughter made her feel bad. But excursions into the
offbeat end quickly as Spacey's pro rushes to the the siege
downtown and begins playing cat and mouse with Jackson's reluctant
but desperate hostage-taker, who figures the only way he can
exonerate himself and avoid being assassinated by a police
sharpshooter on the side of the bad guys is to force the truth out
of Internal Affairs and the larcenous precinct house colleagues who
want him dead.
</P>
<P>
   As sniper and commando squads move into position, Jackson's
embattled suspect knows his only chance of succeeding is to
convince Spacey's honest cop to help him find the evidence that
will prove Jackson innocent and nail the real heavies. This
undercuts the mostly phoned-in duel of wits, which is the film's
most interesting aspect, partly because Jackson's expert knows all
the mind games that are being used against him, partly because
Spacey convinces us his character is nimble-minded and
unpredictable enough to know when not to play by the book.
</P>
<P>
   The contrasting hot and cool styles of Jackson and Spacey,
respectively, keep ``The Negotiator'' watchable up to a point. But
then the bullets and explosions and deterministic plotting take
over and shove ``The Negotiator'' from intelligent thriller into
Hollywood formula dumbness, negating the fresh spin the two actors
had managed to put on their otherwise virtually nonexistent
characters. The louder and more frantic ``The Negotiator'' gets,
the more shallow it seems until, by the end, the movie nullifies
the visual interest of its well-used Chicago locales and snatches
preposterousness from the jaws of gritty credibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
