<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8112 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROUTS-NECK-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     07-29 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROUTS-NECK-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 PROUTS NECK, Maine: ... for $30 Million.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Winslow Homer's nephew Charles Lowell Homer was Willauer's
grandfather, and he deeded the modest house and studio, the latter
called ``the factory,'' to Willauer. It is now a registered
landmark and museum, filled with reproductions only, and run
informally by Willauer and whomever happens to be renting the house
for the summer. Down a short path from the studio is Cannon Rock,
from which Homer painted many of his sea scenes.
</P>
<P>
   While Prouts Neck can't strictly be called a gated community
because there is no sentry on duty at the entrance, there is a gate
to the ``hard neck'' part of the colony; the ``soft neck'' is just
outside the gate, where all the roads run down to the beach. The
joke about the gate, according to Sprague, is that every handyman
in Scarborough knows its combination. What most people feel about
the gate, according to Willauer, is that ``it keeps the crowds from
Portland away from the private beaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Prouts is contained because of the configuration of the land and
limited space. There are only a few lots left on which to build,
and it's extremely rare for a family house to go up for sale
because most are passed down. More families now rent their cottages
for part of the summer because assessments changed in the early
1990s, pushing waterfront property six or seven times higher in
value, and raising taxes on the average to about $7,500. Land alone
here is now worth about $600,000 an acre.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``the overwhelming thing about this place is that it's
not like Southampton, it's not glitzy,'' says Sprague. ``Its just
low-key and family. Our kids feel more at home here than they do
wherever they lived in the winters.'' Sprague says when he's in
Prouts Neck he likes to spend his time ``sailing and
decompressing'' rather than socializing. Referring to the change of
renters and family members from one month to the next, he said ``I
see the July people at one party in July and the August people at
one in August. And we'll give a party or two as well. That's it.''
His wife is the village fire commissioner, which means she keeps a
hand-held siren in her red 1973 Cadillac convertible, and must give
a report to the town and post ``No Outside Burning'' warnings in
times of extreme dry weather.
</P>
<P>
   James Rose, a lawyer retired from the Federal Emergency
Management Agency in Washington, grew up in Manhattan and summered
in Maine. ``Prouts Neck was a place to explore the outdoors, meet
kids from other communities, bike anywhere we needed to go, and be
far more on our own that we could have in Manhattan,'' he says.
``What is very significant about Prouts Neck is that many people
today don't live in the community where they grew up. A community
like Prouts Neck is the only place where your children know
everyone and everyone knows them.'' His grandfather built the
summer home in 1911 and Rose now shares it with his sister's
family; he's here in July and she's here in August. Rose was told
by his mother that Winslow Homer presented her with a gardenia when
her mother had the painter to dinner. His parents were married here
in 1925 and his daughter will be married here in September.
</P>
<P>
   Prouts Neck children are often baptized here rather than in
their winter towns. The lovely old shingled St. James Episcopal
Church is open only in summer, but Willauer says it is a vital part
of Prouts Neck childrens' lives. The beloved Rev. Charles Newbery,
he says, runs a lively ``semi-unruly'' service designed to keep
children interested. It is so popular that, with the congestion of
parked bicycles and cars around the church, ``you couldn't drive an
ambulance through that street on Sunday.'' It's also an important
part, many residents say, of their religious training. Like most of
the cottages here, though, it's not winterized, and early in the
season, if the church hasn't been warm for long, there's a chance
that the 100-plus-year-old organ may not work.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the tiny Charles E. Thomas Memorial Library, named
after the man whose home it once was. In the center of Prouts Neck
is 25 acres of open space, given to the village by Winslow Homer
and one of his brothers, named Charles Lowell Homer just as was his
nephew.
</P>
<P>
   Socially, the children usually meet each other as
``periwinkles,'' the 3- and 4-year-olds who spend their summers at
the yacht club beach, and go on to become ``sea fleas'' as 4- and
5-year-olds learning to sail. As teens, they used to dance at the
country club, but more recently the dances were moved to the more
casual yacht club because, in one of the more wrenching changes in
the community in perhaps 100 years, it was decided that young
people today simply will not dress up enough in the summer for the
country club's dress rules.
</P>
<P>
   And if they live elsewhere 42 weeks of the year, this still is
where Prouts people bring fiances and fiancees to meet the
community, where they hold their weddings, and sadly, sometimes,
their funerals. When the Spragues' 30-year-old daughter Lucy, a law
student, was murdered in Chicago in December 1996, it was here, in
the memorial garden behind the church, where her ashes were buried
the following summer, while members of the village sang one of her
favorite songs from the song book, ``Waltzing Matilda.''
</P>
<P>
   The final tradition of each Prouts summer actually happens in
fall, when many villagers return for the Columbus Day weekend.
Then, Doris Homer, octogenarian widow of Winslow Homer's nephew
Charles (Winslow Homer remained a bachelor throughout his life) and
unofficial tour guide of the studio, gives her huge cocktail party
and serves ``Daddy Homer Punch.'' Made from the recipe of Arthur
Homer, the third of the three Homer brothers, it is a combination
of rum, tea, sugar and oranges. Sprague calls it ``lethal,'' and
says ``the judge doesn't drive on that day. Three cups of it and
you're history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
