<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US BASKETBALL HAS NO STARS _ OR A GUARANTEED WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ You think we can drop the Dream Team bit now?
</P>
<P>
   There was really only one Dream Team, anyhow, but now that we've
got Wendell Alexis, Brad Miller, and David Wood representing the
USA instead of Grant Hill, Tim Duncan, and Vin Baker, it's
reasonably safe to say that the only dreams being fulfilled here at
the 13th World Basketball Championships will be those of the
countries who can now once again fantasize about winning a gold
medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was better competition for the other teams when the NBA
players were coming,'' observes Sarunas Marciulonis, the superb
Lithunanian guard who has advanced from the playing to the
executive ranks in his native land. ``But now it is possible to win
a gold.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is likewise possible to win a silver or a bronze. In the
last three high-level international basketball competitions _ the
1992 Olympics, the '94 worlds in Toronto, and the '96 Olympics _ it
was well understood that the gold was simply not available. Now the
likes of Argentina, Australia, and host Greece are feeling better
about the whole thing. They can start thinking seriously about
standing on a podium when the tournament draws to a close a week
from Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beatable,'' explains Donn Nelson, son of Don and once again an
assistant with the Lithuanian team. ``That's what people are saying
about the American team _ beatable.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, who are these guys, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a bunch of hardworking guys who are really proud to be
representing their country,'' says coach Rudy Tomjanovich, who
spikes rumors that he had misgivings about remaining as coach once
the NBA players pulled out because of the lockout. ``There was
never a question in my mind. What I did was offer the USA
Basketball people (the choice) to get a college coach if the entire
team would be comprised of college players. They said it would not
be an all-college team, and so here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy T talks about the playmaking of ex-Celtic Michael Hawkins,
the shooting and veteran leadership of Wendell Alexis, the inside
banging of 6-foot-6-inch Jason Sasser and 6-7 Ashraf Amaya, the
feistiness of Wood, and the surprising inside finesse of 6-11 Brad
Miller. ``I'll be playing all 12 men,'' he vows.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot at stake here for the Red, White, and Blue, who
will open play against Brazil this afternoon. Should the Yanks fail
to bring home the gold, the USA will be placed in the aggravating,
and possibly even dangerous, position of being forced to qualify
for the 2000 Olympics in Sydney. It is assumed that said
qualification will be held at a time horribly inconvenient for the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never talk about that,'' Rudy T insists.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long, long time since the USA has sent such a weird
team into a basketball tournament of this magnitude. We had gotten
used to sending out our best young players. Then came the Dream
Team business in 1992, at which point it was understood that
henceforth, the United States would submit only the creme de la
creme in these competitions. That would have been the case here,
too, but for the intervention of NBA politics.
</P>
<P>
   And so the movers and shakers at USA Basketball have turned the
goo-goo eyes to a fascinating collection of CBA players, assorted
European-oriented expatriates, and a pair of college types in
Miller and Trajan Langdon. They are asking Tomjanovich to make a
smooth basketball team out of The Best Of The Rest of American
basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   No one is really happy about this, even if their medal
possibilities have improved. ``I don'think anyone really
understands why the NBA players aren't here,'' says veteran
Australian broadcaster Phil Lynch, who will be covering his third
world championships. ``It takes the gloss off the tournament. I
think they all want to compete against the best.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help matters that another world power comes here
similarly stripped of its marquee players. Vlade Divac, who has
been playing year round for a decade, is using the excuse of the
NBA lockout to stay away from this event. The Yugoslavians are also
here without former NBA player Predrag Danilovic and veteran guard
Aleksandar Djordjevic. With these players, they would have been the
overwhelming favorites. ``It would have been Yugoslavia and draw a
line,'' says Nelson. Now they are only one of many medal
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at FIBA (the international basketball governing body,
of which USA Basketball is a member), not to mention the local
organizers, were horrified when the NBA players bailed out of this
tournament. FIBA secretary general Borislav Stankovic is the man
most responsible for the introduction of NBA players into this kind
of international competetion. He was rather looking forward to
seeing Gary Payton here, not that he has anything against Hawkins.
And then there are the Greek officials, who were counting on the
Americans to sell some tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our official position,'' says FIBA executive Marcos Beltra,
``is that we have 16 teams here and we cannot base the success of
the event on the presence of one team, or should I say the
composition of one team. And we hear that the American team is
actually pretty strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't you love international diplomacy?
</P>
<P>
   As far as the box office is concerned, the ultimate financial
success of the tournament will depend on the fortunes of the Greek
team. Greece is the lone European country of note in which it can
truthfully be said that basketball is actually more popular than
football (i.e., soccer). The fanaticism of the Greek fans is the
stuff of international legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are lucky to have this event in Athens,'' concedes Beltra.
``The Greek people love basketball and they are very
enthusiastically nationalistic.''
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is that the Greek national team is in
transition. The Greeks have had better squads. They will more than
likely need all the vocalizing and flag-waving they can get.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans won't be getting any help. NBC and Turner have
bailed on them. The prospective American press corps has been
whittled by about 95 percent. You probably didn't even know they
were here.
</P>
<P>
   But they are. For better or worse, they are indeed here. ``You
know what they say,'' Nelson points out. ``Wounded dogs fight
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. ``There will be a lot of emotion and drama here,''
says Tomjanovich.
</P>
<P>
   So light a candle. Place a bet. Help these guys out. You may not
know who these guys are, but if you like basketball, they're all
you've got.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
