<SLUG> BC-STATES-AMTRAK-NAT </SLUG>

 &HT;        AMTRAK REPORTS RISE IN RIDERSHIP
 &HT;        By Jason Lakin
 &HT;       c. 1998 States News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  &QC;  WASHINGTON, July 29 -- Amtrak ridership is up 6.2 percent
over last year at this time, leaders of the federally subsidized
rail line announced Wednesday during the first meeting of its
infant Board of Directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have your ridership up, your on-time performance up and a
newfound love of railroads in America,'' said Tommy Thompson,
Wisconsin's Republican governor and a board member. ``I think
you're on the dawn of a new era.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak's revenues are also $12.7 million higher for the current
fiscal year than had been projected, while on-time performance has
improved to 79.6 percent for the year, up from 75.9 percent at this
point last year.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater, one of four board
members, attributed Amtrak's success in part to legislation passed
last year by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted with the third quarter results, and look to
Amtrak as a vital element in our 21st-century transportation
system,'' Slater said. ``Last December, President Clinton signed
the Amtrak Reform and Accountability Act of 1997 that provided
Amtrak with the three things it needed to succeed: freedom to
operate like a business, financial resources necessary to rebuild a
railroad, and partnership with its employees.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Thompson and Slater, the meeting's board members
include former Massachusetts Governor Michael Dukakis, the 1988
Democratic presidential nominee, and John Robert Smith, mayor of
Meridian, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Dukakis anticipated a successful kickoff of the Northeast
Corridor project, a high-speed rail line set to open next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Northeast Corridor, the kind of capital investment
Congress has been kind enough to provide is going to create
enormous new revenue,'' Dukakis said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said that the board will unveil more plans for
expansion soon, but he did not specify a date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of plans going on right now,'' Thompson said.
``We're going to be revealing a Midwest plan. We have to go to
Congress and get that clarified.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak, created by Congress in 1971, has a payroll of 23,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers threatened earlier this year to take Amtrak subsidies
away, but instead reshuffled the organization, with a goal of
making the company self-sufficient by 2002. Last April, Congress
passed a budget resolution affirming that commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing ridership and improving financial performance show
that Amtrak is on the right track to improve service, modernize its
business and strengthen passenger rail service,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Congress reformed Amtrak's board of directors,
reducing its size from nine members to seven. Three of those seats
currently are vacant.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's transportation secretary holds a permanent seat on
the board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
