<HEADLINE>
ON A COMMUNITY FARM, NUNS HAPPILY REAP WHAT THEY SOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLAINVILLE, Mass. _ The smell of potato bread just pulled from
the oven wafted through the old rambling farmhouse. Outside, along
the gently sloping hill, a farmer was pulling weeds from the ground
as the season's first melons pushed up through the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Barbara Harrington, dressed in blue jeans, a gray
T-shirt, and running shoes, stood smiling by the antique wood
stove. It was the beginning of another glorious day at Crystal
Springs, a 40-acre spread that three nuns have turned into a sacred
celebration of the earth and its bounties.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Springs was created out of the nuns' belief that earth
is the primary revelation of the divine. And food the land provides
is what binds people and the earth.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the project is a community farm carved out of
one acre of the parcel once owned by a 19th century sea captain.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 families from surrounding communities paid $525 for a
``share'' in the farm tended by Jean Claude Bourrut, a native of
France with years of experience in organic farming. In return, each
family receives a weekly harvest of lettuce, potatos, peppers,
tomatoes, and other vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, Harrington said, is to teach people to ``learn to live
in place, to learn to embrace the land they live on and what it
offers.'' The farm, she said, is an alternative means of providing
food in a society in which most people get their groceries from
antiseptic megasupermarkets where the produce may travels hundreds
or thousands of miles.
</P>
<P>
   Community farms, Harrington said, are becoming increasingly
popular across the country among those interested in promoting
locally-grown products and in strengthening the connection between
humans and the food they eat.
</P>
<P>
   Several women's religious congregations have started community
farms, including the Kentucky Dominican Sisters, who have converted
Crystal Springs into a center for ecology, spirituality, and earth
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people can learn to not just eat healthily but in a way
that reverences the land, the soil, then maybe we can better
appreciate that all this has been laid down as an endowment for the
nurturing of all life,'' said Harrington, pointing toward the field
overflowing with kale, Swiss chard, eggplant, and zucchini.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Springs has been in the hands of the Kentucky Dominican
Sisters for nearly 50 years, after it was donated to them by a
family out of gratitude to the nuns for taking care of a daughter
with Down syndrome. The farm has undergone several metamorphases.
It has been a training center for women preparing to become
Dominican sisters, a Catholic school, and a home for retired nuns.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington lives at the farm with Sisters Carole Rossi and Chris
Loughlin. Trading in their religious habits for farmer's overalls,
the woman have embraced a much different way of living. ``We
decided a few years ago that our mission, our charisma was pushing
us toward the notion of earth literacy,'' Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   The three women still have other jobs. Harrington does
administrative work at the Kentucky Sisters local headquarters in
Watertown. Loughlin does individual and group spiritual counseling,
and Rossi is the Roman Catholic counselor at Harvard Divinity
School.
</P>
<P>
   Education has always been at the heart of the Kentucky Sisters,
which is celebrating its 175th ann
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
