<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$800   PER   WEEK FOR A NANNY JOB? THANKS, BUT NO THANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   News that wealthy New York City parents are hijacking nannies
from the slightly less-rich for weekly salaries of $800 plus
benefits landed in my household with sudden impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``About time,'' sniffed the adult parent who considers herself
the ``primary caregiver,'' as it's termed these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmmm,'' murmured the other adult parent, who considers himself
lucky if he can weasel out of most of the many and varied chores
that go with caregiving, especially if the care-receiver does not
want that particular type of care delivered at that particular
time.
</P>
<P>
   I run into that a lot these days. It's still rude shock to a
well-intended duffer of a dad to discover that the wisdom I
accumulated over generations concerning high finance, low behavior,
driving to survive, the value of a good night's sleep, and a diet
that tosses in a few green vegetables along with the marshmallows
is so widely scorned.
</P>
<P>
   But ears perked up at the notion of 800 smackers-cum-benefits
for dealing with someone else's kid or kids. If this is a trend, I
want to know more. I am not making this up. Yes, there are those,
even under my roof, who snicker that I could not spot a trend
unless it backed into my pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Don't take my word for the nanny price war: It's right there in
The New York Times, an outfit that lands on a trend like a load of
sheetrock coming off the top rack at Home Depot. A woman whose
other job was described as a human rights spokeswoman complained
that her nanny left her employ at a ``rather princely'' $550 a week
for the $800 down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, lady; it's called capitalism. Market forces at work. Going
for the gold is not only a human right, it's a human habit. Adam
Smith (the real one) would be proud. Come to think of it, was Adam
a primary caregiver on the domestic front? Did Mrs. Smith do the
grunt work with the little Smithies? Or was there a nanny in the
picture? Probably the latter. I'm guessing, but two shillings a
week and one hour off every other Sunday sounds right for the
times.
</P>
<P>
   Some irate feminists will probably burst into a capella harmony
about how child-rearing was always underpaid labor, that the oafish
males who supposedly run things planned it this way all along, and
that even things like starting times for elementary school are
designed to keep mothers pinned between the breakfast table and the
car pool line, while men rush from the sports section over coffee
to a tee time blessedly free of female golfers. How do they spell
that, anyway: Is it soccer moms, or sucker moms, that do all that
driving?
</P>
<P>
   I am familiar with arguments, if not the spelling. I merely
raise the point to suggest that if nanny work is made more
remunerative, then males will perforce begin to reassess. I know a
lot of guys who do hard work for less money that eight hundred per.
You know them, too, or at least you see them.
</P>
<P>
   They are up on the rooftops, carrying shingles or spreading tar.
They are lugging trash, breaking down tires off dirty rims in auto
shops, welding angle irons in places that are dark, dirty, and
extremely hard to get at.
</P>
<P>
   Would these gents make good nannies? Some would, some wouldn't.
Just like women. But being a nanny is good indoor work. Getting
cold, wet, or dirty is not part of the deal, as a rule. And it's
only a short hop from being, say, a house-husband to a role as paid
professional child-carer. I dimly recall some TV series have used
the role as a takeoff point for a sitcom. (Memo to the deep
thinkers at the Times: Keep an eye peeled for roofers, sanitation
men, or welders job-shifting into nannyhood _ I think it could be a
trend.)
</P>
<P>
   Not to mislead you; no way I'd be good at the nanny thing. It
requires feats of organization and patience that would defeat me. I
figure my DNA track was laid down eons ago, when the first caveman
decided to take his chances with the woolly mammoth over the next
hill rather than argue with his 15-year-old over who had to wash
the rock they used to beat the dinner roots.
</P>
<P>
   My kitchen work for kids is, beyond Spaghetti-Os, nonexistent.
Infants I can handle with no problem. Little kids I love. My
favorite people are 2 1/2-year-olds, on average. The only problem
with little kids is that they become big kids. I am all for kids,
of course; hard not to be. But I warm up to them a bit more again
when they hit their mid-20s. It's those middle years, starting
around 11, when all the important lessons I have learned about
things like bicycle helmets and seat belts, turn out to be the
starting point for disputation.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot list for you even three arguments I ever won with a kid
over 11 or under, say, 24. I'm always stymied by the killer
riposte, such as: ``Well, did you wear a seat belt/bike helmet when
you were a kid?''
</P>
<P>
   When I stammer that, uhh, no, I don't think we even had seat
belts or bike helmets when I was a kid, but statistics do show blah
blah blah, then I get the bitter smirk, the knowing smile, the old
trapped-you-again grin. So obviously a man who cannot win even
three arguments with three different kids over three decades of
being a nonprimary caregiver is a lousy candidate for $800-per-week
nannying. There are plenty of guys who'd do a bang-up job; just
count me out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
