<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA WAS NEVER MEANT TO BE LOCKED DOWN AND SHUT TIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here we go again: another horrendous act of senseless violence,
another hysterical surge of ``security'' improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's shooting at the U.S. Capitol was caused by a lunatic
bent on mayhem, not by a lack of security. Russell E. Weston Jr.
was able to breach the Capitol's security because he cared nothing
for his own safety and because he was willing to gun down anyone
who got in his way.
</P>
<P>
   A security system might be devised to fend off such an
individual _ but it wouldn't be a system that citizens of a great
democracy would welcome in a cherished public building. As
concerned as they are about occasional outbreaks of random violence
in this country, the American people are surely not inclined to
sacrifice even more freedom in continued pursuit of the illusion
that they are safer.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what most of these increasingly cumbersome security
measures add up to _ the illusion of public safety. We can install
metal detectors, X-ray machines, bomb scanners and who knows what
else in hopes of shielding ourselves from trouble, but the sad fact
is that none of it can deter a maniac who is prepared to risk his
life to achieve his goals.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Capitol security is extensive and
sophisticated. But what good are sophisticated security devices
when the police officer monitoring those devices is gunned down
before he has a chance to react?
</P>
<P>
   Weston didn't sneak a pistol past the metal detector at the
Capitol door; he reportedly charged into the building, shot a cop
in the back of the head and started running down a hallway. Then he
shot another cop, who returned fire and ended the incident almost
as quickly as it had started.
</P>
<P>
   The two policemen died, and a tourist was injured. Weston was
seriously wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, although the price was high, the security system
worked. Two cops died in the line of duty, but no member of
Congress was harmed, and the one bystander who got hurt was out of
the hospital the very next day.
</P>
<P>
   This tragedy might have been averted if the Capitol had been
locked up, inaccessible to the public. But that's not what America
is all about; the Capitol is where the people's elected
representatives conduct the people's business.
</P>
<P>
   If the day ever comes that we must wall off and lock down this
symbol of freedom and representative government, we might as well
send our legislators home, for the greatest nation on earth will
have surrendered to the tyranny of fear.
</P>
<P>
   No, all this talk of tighter security at the Capitol is
ill-advised and unnecessary. And it may be nothing more than an
understandable overreaction to a terrible tragedy _ just as
increased airport security was an overreaction to the explosion of
TWA Flight 800.
</P>
<P>
   But in this era of cynicism, it is tempting to suspect a more
cynical explanation for some of these calls for enhanced security.
Some members of Congress, for example, seem to be capitalizing on
the shootings to revive a dormant plan to build an underground
``visitors center'' at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   One bipartisan proposal calls for building the $125 million
center with private funds. But in the wake of last week's violence,
there were rumblings that Congress might see fit to spend
taxpayers' money on the project.
</P>
<P>
   The project is a boondoggle, of course _ one that would do
little or nothing to prevent the Russell Westons of the world from
wreaking havoc if they are so inclined.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Glenn, the onetime astronaut who is currently training
for another trip into space, was asked on one of the morning TV
chat shows about the security situation. He wondered if it wouldn't
be smarter to spend some money improving mental health programs
rather than enhancing security at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's point was that Weston might never have been in
Washington on his mission of murder if he had received adequate
treatment for whatever mental disorder led him to commit such a
mindless act of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting idea. More interesting than a metal detector,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
