<SLUG> BC-MA-POLICE-PROFILING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITIES SEE `ETHNIC STEREOTYPING' IN POLICE SEARCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ZACHARY R. DOWDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts State Police thought they had sniffed out
a big-time drug trafficker when Manuel Espinola of Tewksbury put
his bag through an airport X-ray machine.
</P>
<P>
   There, buried in his luggage, was a bundle of cash totaling
$14,665.
</P>
<P>
   When police questioned him, Espinola became nervous, saying he
was flying to Las Vegas to buy a house. Yet he couldn't give police
his broker's name or employer's telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a specially-trained dog detected cocaine on the money.
</P>
<P>
   Espinola was not arrested at the airport during the incident in
November 1996 because police lacked enough evidence to build a case
against him as a trafficker. But State Trooper Stephen G. Lynch
seized the money under federal drug forfeiture laws, which allows
confiscation of property thought to be gained from or used in drug
deals.
</P>
<P>
   The government has had the money ever since.
</P>
<P>
   But on July 2, US District Court Judge Nancy Gertner ordered the
money returned to Espinola and delivered a blistering critique of
police, saying they may have relied on ``blatant ethnic
stereotyping.''
</P>
<P>
   African-American and Latino civil rights groups say
``profiling,'' the process by which drug agents and police decide
who to stop and search in airports and along highways, has resulted
in unfair use of race and the disproportionate stopping of black
and Latino travelers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   During the last decade, the Supreme Court and lower federal
courts have granted police wide latitude to size up suspects as
part of the ``war on drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gertner, in one of the first major blows against profiling,
said police violated Espinola's rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government's showing of probable cause is completely
inadequate,'' Gertner wrote, ``based on a troubling mix of baseless
generalizations, leaps of logic or worse, blatant ethnic
stereotyping.''
</P>
<P>
   To Gregory Nojeim, general legislative counsel for the American
Civil Liberties Union, the case ``signals to law enforcement that
passengers are not to be treated as if they are criminals unless
there is probable cause of crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the airport, passengers check their luggage, not their
rights to privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   George Festa, &UR;  &LR; special agent in charge of the Drug Enforcement
Administration in New England, said law enforcement would continue
its aggressive patrol of airports. He said such efforts have cut
down on drug trafficking at Logan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy with this decision because the officer did what
he is paid to do,'' he said. ``No one stood back and said, `That
man looks like a criminal! Let's stop him.' The trooper went step
by step to build probable cause. We weren't satisfied with
Espinola's responses.''
</P>
<P>
   Espinola, a salesman for Equinox International, an Amway-like
consumer products company, has declined comment, saying he feared
retaliation from the government. His lawyer, Blaine DeFreitas,
said, ``Just because a young Hispanic male carries a large amount
of money doesn't mean that money was ill-gotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Gertner made her ruling in the midst of a national controversy
on profiling, or what some have dubbed ``DWBs _ Driving While
Black.''
</P>
<P>
   Strip searches at customs at Chicago's O'Hare International
Airport have led to a federal lawsuit by 18 African-American women.
Last week, US Senators Dick Durbin and Carol Moseley-Braun, both
Democrats of Illinois, released data showing black women are the
most singled out group for strip searches.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the ACLU says it has received hundreds of
complaints regarding computerized airport screenings from travelers
to the Middle East, travelers who have Arab names, and
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Profiling is lazy law enforcement,'' Nojeim said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is investigating possible civil rights
violations in traffic stops and the House recently passed a bill to
monitor stops. The bill has stalled in the Senate under lobbying by
police associations.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People announced it would begin studying traffic stops made
by police. In an interview with the Globe this week, NAACP Chairman
Julian Bond said he was approached a few months ago at a turnpike
rest stop between Washington and Philadelphia by a state trooper.
Bond said the trooper's hand was on his revolver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trooper said, `You resemble a suspect in a robbery,' said
Bond, who said he felt ``enormous fear'' at that moment. ``The
trooper looked back at the woman who was with him and asked her if
I looked like the robber.
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman said, `I told you it was a kid.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bond is 58 years old.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, authorities have stopped and interrogated
prominent African-Americans and Latinos such as Harvard Law School
professor Charles Ogletree, former Virginia governor Douglas
Wilder, Texas appeals court Justice Linda Reyna Yanez, and baseball
Hall of Famer Joe Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Air travelers who have been stopped report everything from
having underwear put on display to missed flights and assault.
Wilder was grabbed by the throat by a security guard at the
Raleigh-Durham airport in North Carolina in 1995. Morgan was
awarded $796,000 by the city of Los Angeles after being thrown to
the floor and handcuffed at the Los Angeles Airport in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Ogletree said he has been stopped about 12 times since 1980,
while dressed casually and when wearing a suit, at airports in
Boston, Miami, New York, Newark, and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came back from Jamaica, the only thing consistent was
that all of the people being stopped had dark skin,'' Ogletree
said. ``It is a situation of terror. You're so vulnerable. When
agents start searching and bring the dogs to sniff your bags you
have no recourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the embarrassment of having fellow travelers all around
you who don't know you thinking you are guilty. You go away and the
first thing that happens when you come home is that you are
reminded of your status in this society.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Reyna Yanez and her teenage daughter, Amparo, were walking
through an airport in Harlingen, Texas, in 1995 when a border
patrol agent grabbed her daughter, suspecting her of being in the
country illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried to intimidate me,'' said Reyna Yanez in a telephone
interview. ``I knew that my daughter and I were being singled out
for an immutable trait, our race, so it made me remember when I was
a little girl in school where they used to punish us for speaking
Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Amparo Yanez, now 21, said she could hardly hold back her tears.
She said she has been stopped at least three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tired and harassed and completely terrified,'' Amparo
said, also on the phone. ``I was embarrassed and scared and I felt
discriminated against because of my skin color.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Espinola case, Gertner originally granted police a
warrant to seize the money based on an affidavit Lynch submitted
after the incident. In her 30-page decision, she said she was wrong
to have done so, saying she was misled by the affidavit and did not
have a chance to hear Espinola's side.
</P>
<P>
   She dismissed the fact that Espinola's cash contained traces of
cocaine, citing several studies that show that 90 percent of all US
currency is tinged with the drug.
</P>
<P>
   US Attorney Donald K. Stern disagreed and is appealing Gertner's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't find any basis in the record that the trooper's
decision was based on racial stereotyping,'' Stern said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
