<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8157 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-PUPPETS-BOS &LR;      07-29 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-PUPPETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AHAB'S WIFE TELLS HER TALE IN HENSON PUPPET THEATER FETE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA YUEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Moby Dick,'' author Herman Melville mentions Captain Ahab's
wife all of three times in the 700-odd pages. While the embittered
Ahab slices through waves in his hunt for the white whale that tore
off his leg, his wife remains the nameless woman who quietly sits
at home.
</P>
<P>
   But never mind Melville. Four Boston-area artists have
collaborated to infuse Ahab's wife with a resonant voice, offering
a story Melville never told. Visual artist Ellen Driscoll, poet Tom
Sleigh, and choreographers/directors Amy Spencer and Richard Colton
teamed up to create the new performance work, ``Ahab's Wife.''
</P>
<P>
   The visual production has been selected to be a part of the
prestigious Jim Henson Foundation's fourth biennial International
Festival of Puppet Theater Sept. 17-20 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Initiated by the Jim Henson Foundation, after the late
groundbreaking puppeteer's death, this year's festival _ the only
puppet festival in the United States _ has invited 28 troupes from
16 countries to perform. Despite Henson's brilliant work with ``The
Muppets'' and other children's entertainment, the gathering
presents mostly adult drama, showcasing marionettes, Kabuki, hand
puppets, rod puppets, and other elements of visual theater.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Ahab's Wife,'' the title character steers through a journey
of flashbacks, imagination, loneliness, and longing to arrive at
her own realizations and destiny. The play combines visual objects,
poetic lyricism, shadowbox, modern dance, Jujitsu, slapstick, and
Fred-and-Ginger ballroom dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're expecting to see `Moby Dick' on stage _ it's not
that,'' said Colton, a Cambridge, Mass. poet who wrote the final
script. ``We're only using Melville's book as a springboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three years ago, Driscoll proposed the premise of the
play to the Brooklyn Academy of Music for sponsorship. The academy
turned it down, but one panel juror, Olivia Georgia, a curator of
the Snug Harbor Cultural Center on Staten Island, enjoyed the
proposal so much she had the center commission the play. Snug
Harbor, formerly a sailors' retirement complex, was administered by
Melville's brother in the 1800s. The center will present ``Ahab's
Wife'' for the Henson festival.
</P>
<P>
   The original work for the production was created at workshops at
the American Repertory Theatre in Cambridge and Concord (Mass.)
Academy's Summer Stages over the past two years. The final product
is a &UR;  &LR; blending of ideas pitched by workshop students, who each read
a chunk of the Melville novel to transfer some of its essence to
dance and acting. The play was also performed at the New Bedford
(Mass.) Whaling Museum last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The hour-long production consists of only 14 pages of script _
shorter than, say, the Cliff's Notes to Melville's book. But
interspersed with eclectic music, dance, and shadowplay, the piece
provides enough nonverbal elements to titillate the eyes and ears.
Scenes drift from one to another like seaweed, as do the fluid
modern dance moves. The fragmented mishmash is meant to complement
Melville's patchwork of writing styles, which tumble from technical
jargon of the whaling industry to philosophical ramblings to common
talk muttered by 19th century sailors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason Melville does that,'' Driscoll said of the book's
myriad styles, ``is because the ship is like a world filled with
different kinds of men; it's a little floating universe. Our piece,
too, has multiple layers and fast turns. I think Melville would
love it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the play, Ahab's wife (Randy Danson) mourns the loss of her
husband but learns that all humans are alone, and that a person
cannot be completed by another. She eventually meets the majestic
whale (Robert Langdon Lloyd), who, as in the book, serves as a
collective repository of the character's experiences. Although
central to the novel, the whale also lacked a voice in the novel.
</P>
<P>
   The creators of ``Ahab's Wife'' perused old bookstores and
thrift stores in search of nautical artifacts and documents. In
some scenes, the giant hoop skirt and diving bell are transformed
into the eye and head of the whale. Hoop skirts and corsets, both
which can represent the repression of women, were made of whale
bone in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll and Sleigh found an 19th century diary of a sailor's
wife who accompanied him aboard on his travels. Augusta Penniman's
journal entries are echoed in the monologues of Ahab's wife in the
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women back then were much more adventurous than how we might
think of them today,'' actress Danson said. ``Some women were
traveling to far-flung places and meeting cannibals. (Ahab's wife)
is an adventurous explorer as well. The nautical journey is a
metaphor for her journey to sort out the loss of her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For information about the New York performances, call
212-627-1455.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
