<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PARENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTCOMINGS SNARE NEW `PARENT TRAP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE PARENT TRAP 
Directed by: Nancy Meyers 
Screenplay by: David Swift, Nancy Meyers &AMP; Charles Shyer 
Starring: Lindsay Lohan, Dennis Quaid, Natasha Richardson, Elaine
Hendrix, Lisa Ann Walter, Simon Kunz, Polly Holliday, Maggie
Wheeler, Ronnie Stevens, Joanna Barnes, Erin Mackey 
Running time: 124 minutes 
Rated: PG (some mild mischief) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's nothing cheap or blatantly exploitative about Nancy
Meyer's remake of ``The Parent Trap.'' And newcomer Lindsay Lohan
is as likable as Hayley Mills was in the double role of twins who
meet for the first time at summer camp. Separated at birth when
their parents went their respective ways after an impulsive romance
and wedding, the girls, with the aid of trick photography and an
occasional body double, bond after initial antagonism, then scheme
to reunite their divorced parents. Meyer and her husband, Charles
Shyer have been down this road before, having retooled ``Father of
the Bride.''
</P>
<P>
   But _ and you will have sensed there's a ``but'' _ the film that
worked well enough in 1961 seems as bit hollow today. Ironically,
its shortcomings are exposed by the faithfulness with which Meyer
has replicated the original script as director and co-writer, right
down to timing out the film at a rather too leisurely
two-hours-plus. The new ``Parent Trap'' is slickly crafted _ with
foolproof fairytale settings in London and the Napa Valley _ but
its central premise, that kids can and therefore perhaps should
somehow get their selfish divorced parents back together, generates
more uneasiness than pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer never allows coyness and cuteness to invade the screen any
more than she succumbs to broadness and MTV editing. She even
manages a few sly visual send-ups _ one aimed at Beatle fans. But
the charm of the performers, sparked by Lohan's unaffected
freshness and the warmth and dazzle of Natasha Richardson's single
mom, enjoying a career as a successful wedding gown designer, and
Dennis Quaid's single dad, grown mellow and rich from his winery,
can only carry the film so far.
</P>
<P>
   It's fun to watch Lohan play to slightly different versions of
her English-bred and California-nurtured selves and the siblings'
respective surrogate parents, Simon Kunz's London butler and Lisa
Ann Walker's Napa nanny. But you spend more time feeling prodded
into emotions than actually feeling emotions, which renders all the
technical care and craftsmanship moot. The actors are attractive to
watch as they gambol through what seem their awfully predetermined
moves through the dreamy scenery and through a perfunctory
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The latter revolves around the impending marriage of Quaid's
careless vintner to a blond she-devil played with unrelievedly
steely demeanor by Elaine Hendrix (Joanna Barnes, the vixen in the
original, returns as the vixen's mom here). ``The Parent Trap''
offers gloss and sheen, but it's all exteriors, a shortcoming that
Meyer might have concealed with a crisp-as-lettuce directorial
touch. But the film's pedestrian earnestness keeps reminding us
that while pretty, it's too calculated to be anything but bland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
