<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS, LAWYERS AWAIT EFFECTS OF COLORADO RULING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The delicate dance with the devil has played out in courtrooms
for more than a century, ever since horse thief and train robber
Dick Liddil cut a deal to testify against Jesse James' brother,
Frank, in a Missouri courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   As prosecutor William H. Wallace reminded jurors in his
oft-quoted final argument in 1883, such alliances between lawmen
and outlaws are unsavory, but unavoidable:
</P>
<P>
   ``When the state would break up a band of criminals, it must
depend on the assistance of one of their peers in crime to do it.
Hence, it is the custom, as old as the law, to pick out from a
desperate band one of their own number, and use him as a guide to
hunt the others down.''
</P>
<P>
   So when a three-judge federal appeals court in Colorado this
month ruled that the practice amounted to bribery and was against
the law, prisoners convicted on the word of their cohorts called
their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  And prosecutors cried foul.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning ruling was the first which targeted the linchpin in
most federal prosecutions: offering deals to witnesses to get them
to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``No practice is more ingrained in our criminal justice system
...'' the court said. But, the court added, it's a practice that
flies in the face of a federal law that prohibits giving a witness
anything of value in exchange for testimony.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous decision, the panel ordered a new trial for Sonya
Evette Singleton, a Kansas woman who was convicted of money
laundering and cocaine dealing largely on the testimony of Napoleon
Douglas, a member of the alleged ring.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for Douglas' testimony, federal prosecutors had
agreed not to pursue other drug cases against him, allowed him to
plead guilty to reduced charges, and asked the sentencing judge for
a lenient term _ a fairly standard deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Singleton decision spawned a flurry of motions _ including
at least three in Massachusetts federal courts _ asking judges to
block the testimony of witnesses who have cut deals with the
government. That occurs in nearly all conspiracy cases involving
multiple defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would change everything,'' said Frank A. Libby Jr., a
former federal prosecutor who relied on a half-dozen cooperating
witnesses to crack the infamous ``Code of Silence'' case involving
murderous Charlestown, Mass. drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would shut down large-scale racketeering cases,'' Libby
said. ``You have to have an insider explain what things means, why
telephone calls went from A to B.''
</P>
<P>
   The US Justice Department, calling the decision simply
``wrong,'' immediately asked for a hearing before the full bench of
the Tenth Circuit, which includes Colorado, Kansas, New Mexico,
Oklahoma, Utah and Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   But before the Justice Department could act, the appeals court
withdrew the decision until the full 12-member court could hear the
matter in November _ mindful, no doubt, that it could affect the
pending appeal of Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh.
</P>
<P>
   Both McVeigh and his cohort, Terry Nichols, were convicted in
part on the testimony of former accomplice Michael Fortier, who was
rewarded with a reduced sentence.
</P>
<P>
   With the ruling withdrawn, there is no impediment to business as
usual. And even if the decision had remained in place pending the
review, it would not have been binding in federal courts in the
First Circuit, which covers Massachusetts, Maine, New Hampshire,
Rhode Island and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the federal judge in Boston who is presiding over the
current murder and drug trafficking trial of two members of the
Intervale Posse street gang _ a trial that features testimony by
three former gang members who've cut deals with the government _
rejected a motion to block them from the witness stand based on the
Singleton ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Still, law enforcement officials are plotting contingencies,
such as asking Congress to exempt plea bargains from the bribery
law, should the Singleton decision pass muster before the Tenth
Circuit and the US Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, defense lawyers hailed the first validation of their
longstanding view that deals-for-testimony are inherently suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get out-and-out rank perjury and manufactured stories,''
said Boston defense attorney Joseph Oteri, who won an acquittal
last year for a Legal Sea Foods executive whose chief accusers were
two career criminals-turned government witnesses. ``They call it
`getting on the bus,' down in Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   And when stiffer, mandatory sentences and the abolition of
federal parole are factored in, Oteri said, ``Almost everybody is a
rat. It's the only way out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bargains that are cut have grown by leaps and bounds,''
said Framingham attorney John H. LaChance, president of the
Massachusetts Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers and a former
federal prosecutor. He's among a handful of local lawyers spurred
by the Singleton decision who filed motions to block witnesses who
had made deals in exchange for their testimony.
</P>
<P>
   LaChance represents Robert F. Carrozza of East Boston, a reputed
Mafia member and part of a faction charged with trying to topple
mob boss Francis Salemme during a bloody five-year power struggle
in the late 1980s and early 1990s. The trial is set for September
in US District Court in Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Martin G. Weinberg, who represents co-defendant Anthony Ciampi
seeking to block the testimony of three witnesses, including Sean
Cote, a career criminal who testified before the grand jury that
returned the indictments. Cote, a convicted bank robber, is
believed to have testified to more than a dozen murders and
assassination attempts.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, Cote avoided a life sentence on charges he robbed
13 banks and two jewelry stores. Instead, he will serve 10 to 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   Carrozza's case offers a textbook example of how the system
works _ and how it can cut both ways. Back in 1992, Carrozza
himself received immunity for the attempted murder of Salemme under
a plea agreement that got him 19 years on a racketeering
conviction. He currently faces five charges, but the attempted
murder of Salemme is not among them.
</P>
<P>
   Given the national outcry from law enforcement, it's unclear
whether the literal reading of the law in the Singleton ruling will
stand. Unlike any court before it, the three-judge panel in Denver
decided that the federal bribery statute which prohibits ``giving,
offering or promising anything of value'' for testimony applies to
arrangements prosecutors make with defendants who have ``flipped.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to imagine anything more valuable than
personal physical freedom,'' the court found.
</P>
<P>
   While that interpretation ``is quite literally correct, it
clearly was not intended to apply in this setting,'' said
Christopher Mueller, a professor at the University of Colorado
School of Law. ``There's not a chance it will stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Still others point out that only three more votes are needed to
uphold the Singleton decision in Colorado and send it to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a conservative issue, not a liberal issue,'' notes
Oteri. ``And when this thing gets to the Supreme Court you might
very well see the conservative majority go for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
