<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY MANAGER FOCUSES ON FEW HOLDINGS, GETS BIG RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a city that celebrates money managers, he is
arguably among the cream of the crop _ and a virtual unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Dworsky works by himself in a sparse, two-room office
overlooking Post Office Square. The entire staff of his Mt. Auburn
Management consists of his wife, Suzanne Werber, who keeps track of
administrative duties from an office in their Cambridge home. He
stopped marketing the firm years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mt. Auburn managed $648 million as of March 31, but the vast
bulk of the total represented huge investment gains over a period
of years. Dworsky's nine institutional clients have given him
considerably more modest sums to manage in an unsual,
high-concentration style that has produced extraordinary results.
</P>
<P>
   It is work done in low-tech solitude. Investment bankers touring
through town to raise money rarely knock on his door. The phone
never rang for more than an hour during a recent visit by a
reporter. Dworsky doesn't even have a computer in his office. The
only concession to information technology is a Quotrek machine, a
device the size of a hand-held calcualator that pulls up stock
prices.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Dworksy, who describes himself as a bit of a
curmudgeon, has compiled unparalleled investment results for his
clients over the last 12 years. Mt. Auburn has averaged returns of
32.42 percent a year from March 31, 1986, when the firm acquired
its first real insitutional client, to June 30, excluding fees.
Cumulative total return: 3,019.22 percent, according to Dworsky.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the most successful mutual fund in the world
during the same period, Seligman Communications, averaged 21.62
percent a year for a cumulative 1,000.07 percent return including
fees. The best Boston-based fund, Fidelity Select Home Finance,
averaged 21.33 percent for a cumulative 968.54 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Mt. Auburn's short-term performance isn't bad either. A
composite of its client accounts earned 51.04 percent before fees
in the first half of 1998. The latest Pension &AMP; Investments
Performance Evaluation Report, which tracks private money managers,
ranks Mt. Auburn's 120.1 percent total return for the 12 months
ended March 31 as tops in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Dworsky isn't shy about his numbers or the stock-picking behind
them. But he's cautious about how markets and investment
performance can turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have peaked out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dworsky has generated big investment returns by putting his eggs
in just a few baskets. All Mt. Auburn's money is invested in nine
stocks at the moment, a rare level of asset concentration.
</P>
<P>
   Pick only a few winners, at least enough to outnumber the
losers, and concentration yields a big advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impact,'' said Dworsky. ``What's the point of having a
Dell Computer that quadruples'' if it only represents 2 percent of
assets? ``If you're running a portfolio with 100 names, you need
many more winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Most managers hold scores or even hundreds of stocks in
diversfied portfolios. Fidelity Low-Priced Stock, one of the
industry's most diversified mutual funds, owns 1,165 stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme concentration is considered risky by most managers and
Dworsky agrees it may be an inappropriate strategy for people
investing large portions of a customer's money. Mt. Auburn usually
receives a small sliver of the total assets invested by an
institution and the rest is sprinkled among many other managers.
</P>
<P>
   But Dworsky has only suffered one year in which Mt. Auburn's
composite returns trailed the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500. Even that
year, 1996, generated a return of 14.85 percent. The portfolio has
been larger, but never numbered more than 12 stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as risky as it seems,'' said Dworksy. The Mt. Auburn
portfolio is heavily focused on technology today. Among Dworsky's
selections are Dell, EMC Corp., America Online Inc., Tellabs Inc.,
WorldCom Inc., BMC Software Inc., and Cendant Corp. Dworsky keeps
his stock list close to the vest and discovering any portion
involves dragging it out of him one name at a time. He flatly
declined to name the other two stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine stocks, eight appreciated by at least 25 percent in
the first quarter of 1998, accounting for much of Mt. Auburn's
strong recent performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five or six years ago the portfolio was heavily in the health
care area,'' he said. ``I shifted toward information technology. I
didn't set out to build an information age portfolio, but my nose
and sensibilities have led me there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dworsky began his career in at Putnam Investments, joining the
Boston firm as an analyst straight out of Harvard Business School.
By 1972, he was offered the chance to run Putnam Investors, one of
the most successful funds of its day. ``The preeminent Nifty Fifty
50 portfolio,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dworsky sensed trouble soon after and privately advised friends
to get out of the stock market. He said he wanted his Putnam fund
to adapt a more defensive stance and ran into resistance from
Putnam executives. By 1975, he was removed as manager and returned
to the analyst ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many analysts note the parallels between the current
market and stocks in the Nifty Fifty days. Dworsky saw trouble then
but he's unconvinced about dire events ahead. ``It's not as clear
now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dworsky stayed with Putnam and later managed large pension fund
accounts, but decided to strike out on his own in 1983. ``When
you're at a place for 17 years, they tend to take you for
granted,'' he said. ``I began to think, you only live once.''
</P>
<P>
   He started Mt. Auburn Management with no clients and the
intention of remaining small, a position he still maintains today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided on Day One to limit ourselves to a business the two
of us and a computer could handle,'' said Dworsky. That made it
harder to build a business early and limits the money he could
manage today.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Mt. Auburn Management mutual fund and its unlikely
there will ever be one. Occasionally one of Dworksy's clients will
leave and another will approach him. And that's the pace he prefers
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an organizational man,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
