<HEADLINE>
ASIAN ECONOMIC CRISIS HITS CALIFORNIA PORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Asia's economic crisis seems like an
abstraction to many Americans _ an alarm too distant and faint to
worry much about. But it is a hard reality here amid the screeching
machinery at America's busiest container port.
</P>
<P>
   As ships dock, giant cranes unload 20-foot-long containers
packed with clothing, toys, televisions, and car parts from Japan,
South Korea, Thailand, Malaysia, and China. When the ships are
ready to return to Asia, the cranes fill them with dozens of steel
containers loaded with ... nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Plummeting currencies have made Asian products a bargain as
American stores prepare for the busy back-to-school and Christmas
seasons. At the same time, Asian consumers are rejecting American
goods because the prices, in Korean wan, Thai baht and other
currencies, have doubled and tripled in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   That makes for the irony in booming California at the century's
end; one of the fastest-growing exports to Asia this summer is the
battered containers used to bring back imports.
</P>
<P>
   And what is happening in California, America's leading exporter
and importer, is telling for the rest of the country. This year,
the United States is running a merchandise trade deficit that
averages $20 billion a month _ compared to $16.5 billion a month
last year. Economists expect that the deficit will grow even wider
in coming months. A visit to the bustling Port of Long Beach, which
loads and unloads 5,000 ships a year, suggests that the economists
may be right.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics released here last week underscore the broader story.
In June, the Port of Long Beach handled 10 percent more imports
than it did in June 1997, while exports dropped nearly 18 percent.
Asian shippers are so desperate for containers that last month the
port sent out 89,402 of the empty trailer-truck-sized containers.
It was the first time that empty containers exceeded loaded ones
since the port started keeping statistics in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are similar elsewhere on the West Coast. Thirty
miles to the north, the number of empty cargo containers leaving
the Port of Los Angeles last month was greater than the number of
containers with cargo for the first time in a decade. The backlog
of imports has grown so much that there is a two-day wait for space
on freight trains to the Midwest and the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Just 16 months ago, when Asia appeared to have an insatiable
appetite for Budweiser beer, Caterpillar tractors, and Imperial
Valley hay, the ports here were sending out the same number of
loaded containers as they were receiving.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of this year, California's exports to
Japan, the state's largest export market, fell by 12.3 percent, to
$3.9 billion. The state's exports to South Korea suffered even
more, plunging 42 percent, to just over $1 billion. So far, though,
California has barely felt the pinch because sales of computers,
software, and television programs to Latin America, Canada, and the
rest of the country are soaring. The unanswered question _ for
California and for other states _ is what will happen when and if
those other markets soften.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asian crisis is coming here fast and a lot of Americans
don't realize it,'' said Anthony F. Munoz, director of
international operations at American Racing Custom Wheels Inc.,
which employs 2,000 workers in the outskirts of Long Beach. Munoz
spent several years finding distributors for his company's fancy
wheels throughout Asia. He had especially high hopes for Thailand,
which is the world's second-largest market for pickup trucks after
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Thai baht crashed a year ago, sending waves of
instability to the Philippines, Malaysia, Indonesia, South Korea,
and, most recently, Japan, the world's second-largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Munoz can barely find buyers in Asia, and he worries
that his Asian competitors will inundate other markets, such as
South America, with cheap wheels or that Asia will buy fewer
commodities from South American countries, and in turn those
countries will have less money for luxury products such as custom
wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers are not the only ones looking to the East with
alarm. At Sunkist Growers Inc., president Russell Hanlin has
fretted as the price of a pound of California oranges has doubled
in Japan, to $1.50, in less than four years. Sales of citrus to
Asia are down 15 percent this year, and that translates to a nearly
$50 million loss for Sunkist farmers.
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood, movie producers have already cut profit
projections for fall releases because so many tickets will be sold
in weak overseas currencies. In San Francisco, United Airlines has
suspended daily flights to Seoul, its most important destination in
Asia. And in Anaheim, Disneyland and other attractions have been
hurt as tourists from Korea have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   All this might sound irrelevant to those living and working in
many other states. After all, the United States is enjoying the
lowest unemployment rate in nearly 28 years and the second-slowest
inflation rate in 35 years. Testifying before Congress last week,
Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan said Americans had
benefited from Asia's woes, as the flood of cheaper products kept
prices down and anxious investors moved capital to the US market.
</P>
<P>
   ``A major concern that I have is that it obviously cannot
continue indefinitely,'' Greenspan added.
</P>
<P>
   At Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, a forecasting and consulting company
in Lexington, senior economist Cynthia Latta said the US economy is
healthy in part because exports to Asia and other regions were so
strong in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The economy is still dynamic enough to withstand turmoil in
several Asian countries, she said. ``But if the Japanese economy
doesn't start to come back ... that could have an impact and cause
a mild recession here.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussion of Asia takes on an added urgency in Long Beach,
where construction halted and housing prices tumbled in the early
1990s as military cutbacks jolted the largest employers, McDonnell
Douglas Corp. and Hughes Electronics. Politicians and business
executives formed a partnership and decided to promote what Mayor
Beverly O'Neill refers to as ``the three T's: tourism, technology,
and trade.''
</P>
<P>
   The tactic paid off. The Sumimoto bank building towers over the
Long Beach Harbor. The Boeing Co., which acquired McDonnell
Douglas, employs more than 20,000 people in the city. Asian
visitors became so common that the Westin Hotel here has a copy of
``The Teachings of Buddha,'' in English and Japanese, in every
room.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese banks are expected to lay off some workers. Boeing
has reduced earnings projections, saying that Asia will order 150
fewer aircraft than expected from manufacturers. And the Asian
tourists are rarities.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, many in Long Beach are sanguine. ``It's been a big
hit,'' said Tom Teofilo, executive director of Long Beach's export
development office. ``But when the Asian countries do come back,
they're going to be stronger than ever because they learn from
their mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
