<HEADER>
A8182 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOM-SPORTS-ROGAN-ART-     07-29 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-SPORTS-ROGAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING BACK, AT 90, AT LIFE IN THE FAST LANE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ When her family gathers here Saturday to
celebrate the 90th birthday of Katherine Mearls Rogan, talk will
likely turn to the days when she could run faster, jump farther,
and swim quicker than any other woman in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When Boston newspapers routinely described her as ``America's
finest girl athlete'' and compared her popularity to that of Babe
Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   When she was this country's shining star leading up to the 1928
Olympics, only to fall inexplicably from the heavens when she
should have been glowing her steadiest and brightest.
</P>
<P>
   When it does, the honoree will likely have little to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think very much of it,'' said Rogan of the nine
years, 1924-33, when she competed against the likes of Babe
Didrickson. ``We didn't make a big deal of it.''
</P>
<P>
   She still doesn't. Heck, why make a big deal out of five
straight national championships in the standing long jump from
1927-31? Or US titles in the 40-yard dash (5.4 seconds, 1928) and
50-yard dash (6.0 seconds, 1926)? Or a world record (11.20) in the
100? Or various national and New England championships in the high
jump, hurdles, shot put, and javelin?
</P>
<P>
   Why, indeed, when you were also national champion in the
breaststroke and own gold medals in 12 events in two sports?
</P>
<P>
   Track, field, swimming, whatever. ``I just had a lot of fun,''
is how Rogan, her handshake still strong and calves still muscled,
sums it up. And you believe her.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she competed in anonymity. Far from it: The newspaper
clippings that daughter Kay Paltsios began to gather 20 years ago
from their attic hiding places (``I didn't know much about her; I
was amazed'') were glowing and plentiful, calling Rogan the
``Boston Miss who is the best all-around girl athlete in America''
and ``wonder girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan ``was right at the very start of Olympic track and field
for women, and competing in that time frame where they'd get 10,000
people for a track meet for women in New Jersey,'' explained Louise
Mead Tricard, author of ``American Women's Track and Field: A
History, 1895-1980.'' But trouble was brewing in the background,
and by the mid-1930s, a national organization of female physical
education instructors had persuaded the public that girls were too
frail to compete other than in ``play days'' _ a sentiment that
lingered for decades and dissuaded many girls of Paltsios's
generation from participating in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' she said when asked if she, too, had been an
athlete. ``My friends wouldn't have accepted that.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, on the other hand, recalls seldom feeling out of
place as a teenage athlete living on Fourth Street in South Boston.
``We never seemed to have any trouble, any one of us,'' she said.
Oh sure, the girls were cautioned not to wear their track pants too
short (``Now they almost wear nothing''), and once after a diving
competition at a local theater, Rogan was told not to come back to
school at St. Peter and Paul's unless her mother accompanied her to
explain how she dared appear on stage in a bathing suit. But for
the most part, she was left to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan's athletic career _ although she would laugh at the word _
began casually enough, when she played around in Lake Boone, near
Hudson, where her family had a summer home. But soon she was
discovered by Ben Levias, described in a newspaper account as the
person ``in general charge of all New England girl athletes,'' and
progressed to the Boston Swimming Association, under whose banner
she both swam and ran.
</P>
<P>
   By 16, she was in her first track meet, on Boston Common.
``There were no lanes or anything,'' Rogan recalled. ``You just
ran.'' The one pair of track shoes you owned had to last for years.
The one track suit you owned showed up in photo after photo, year
after year. You spent days on trains traveling to distant meets, or
maybe you even took a boat. Your mother had to chaperone. You
didn't get much coaching. There weren't any hair dryers, so in the
winter after taking the bus to the T to the trolley, you got home
with icicles in your hair.
</P>
<P>
   And you didn't practice for hours every day the way they do now.
``Today they live at the pools,'' said Rogan. ``We went twice a
week, maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years after her debut on the Common, she was being touted
as America's best hope for a medal at the 1928 Olympics, where
women would compete in track and field for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she can show such speed in the Olympics, victory should
crown her efforts,'' assessed one Boston newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But she never made it to Amsterdam, either as a swimmer or
sprinter. Advised by those in charge to enter the swimming trials
instead of track, young Mearls concentrated all her energy on the
pool, only to inexplicably fall apart at the Olympic trials and
fail to earn a spot on the team. ``I don't know what happened,''
she said at the time after making it to the finals before
imploding. ``I couldn't take a stroke. No, I wasn't nervous. Just
couldn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask her now what went wrong and she still shrugs. ``Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Just days after she fell short in swimming, Rogan tried again
for a spot on the US Olympic team, this time in track. But she
hadn't been training and couldn't pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I didn't make the Olympic team in 1928, that's the only
time I was ever sad,'' Rogan said. ``But then I figured, `That's
the way it's supposed to be. I wasn't supposed to go.' There's a
reason for everything, you know. I probably would have got seasick
going across the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the men at the club advised her,'' added Paltsios, who
believes they saw swimming as a classier pursuit. ``I remember her
saying a long time ago she should never have done that. Track was
her first love.''
</P>
<P>
   Track, and Al Rogan. It was 71 years ago, when Katherine Mearls
was 18, that a carload of fellas came up to Lake Boone after a
meet. Rogan, himself a track star in Rhode Island, was one of them,
and four years later, they were wed in Watertown on Patriots Day,
1931.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the fans of running, ``We went from church to watch the
Marathon,'' said Rogan, who barely had time to change out of her
splendid wedding gown. ``Jimmy Henigan won.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, who played tennis until he was 92, died three years
ago at 93.
</P>
<P>
   Although she says she ``must have'' competed for a few years
after marriage, the birth of Kay in 1933 put an end to that, except
for backyard track meets _ complete with pole vaulting and a high
jump pit _ later as Kay and son Al were growing up. ``In 1952, she
would have been 44 and she could easily have made the Olympic shot
put team,'' proclaimed her son, a track champion in the mid-1950s
out of Newton High School.
</P>
<P>
   It will be in that same backyard that Katherine Mearls Rogan
marks her 90th birthday, with memories but without pretense, with
family but without regrets. Some people live on their laurels and
dwell on their disappointments; Rogan has little interest in
either. Why does she need a medal from the Olympics when she has
plenty of others to go around the necks of her five grandchildren
and 11 great grandchildren?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy with my life,'' she said. And you believe her.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
