<SLUG> BC-EXECUTIVE-EXPERTISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE MANAGERS OFFER ADVICE TO PUBLIC-SECTOR EXECUTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   E. B. Wilson never really retired. Nine years ago, the
67-year-old Chatham, Mass. resident ``stopped having to be
somewhere every day at 9 a.m.'' when he left Almay Inc., where he
was chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   But he continued working. Now he offers 35 years worth of
management expertise to area nonprofit groups _ for free.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and 140 other business executives and former top
corporate managers are volunteers for the Executive Service Corps a
Boston group which offers nonprofits hardnosed business advice from
the private sector on such organizational dilemmas as financial
planning, long-term strategy, and fundraising.
</P>
<P>
   As nonprofits face increasing pressure from donors for greater
financial accountability, managers and board members of social
service, cultural, and medical groups are gradually embracing some
elements of the traditional corporate outlook. Strategic plans
offer funding sources a glimpse at where their donation money will
go, and groups are learning to use benchmarks and data gathering to
measure how well their programs help their target population.
</P>
<P>
   Enter ESC, itself a nonprofit organization and the Boston
chapter of a loosely affiliated national network of similar groups.
For a small fee, which can range from about $200 to about $7,500,
depending on how much a nonprofit can afford, a ESC consulting team
will analyze a nonprofit's managerial and organizational problems
and help the group's board of directors come to a solution. The
nominal fee helps cover ESC's overhead costs; consultants work for
free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Critical to the performance of the nonprofit agencies is their
capacity not only to serve their constituents,'' says Wilson, who
chaired ESC's board of directors for three years. ``They must be
business people as well.''
</P>
<P>
   And who better to aid nonprofit managers in their quest to
become business-savvy than former business executives. ESC's
volunteers come from the area's largest companies, including
BayBanks Inc., Polaroid Corp., and The Gillette Co. Others formerly
worked as lawyers or doctors, at smaller businesses, local
universities, or school systems. The group assists about 80 clients
a year.
</P>
<P>
   One such client is the Lowell Telecommunications Corp., &UR;  &LR; a
community group which offers public access television, satellite
downlinks, and a computer lab to Lowell residents. The line to use
the group's computer center in Lowell's historic district runs out
the door, says executive director George F. Preston. &UR;  &LR;  ``We're
suffering from too much success.''
</P>
<P>
   To solve the overcrowding problem, the group spent about $1,000
to hire ESC consultant Ann Dinsmoor Case the former assistant
superintendant of the Wellesley, Mass. school district. She is
helping the Lowell group write a strategic plan.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing nonprofits learn from ESC consultants is the
need to define a problem in specific terms. Each consulting
contract between a nonprofit and ESC includes the nonprofit's
assessment of its problem and a clear statement of what the ESC
consultants hope to accomplish. But it's up to the group's own
board to implement ESC's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are solving their own problems in their own way
with our help,'' says Edmund V. Marshall, 72, a retired group vice
president with Textron Corp. who lives in East Greenwich, R.I. In
his five years volunteering for ESC, Marshall says he's discovered
nonprofits and private corporations have more in common than most
people think. But other ESC consultants say there are many
differences between the two sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them don't think in terms of competitors, but they do
have competitors,'' says consultant Robert E. Ray, 62, a Boston
resident who retired as a vice president of Gillette in 1990. &UR;  &LR; 
Nonprofits also define their customers in a different way, says
John B. Roll, 63, a former manager with Xenergy Inc. Unlike
businesses, nonprofits must satisfy both the clients they help and
the donors whose funds keep their doors open. ``There's a
disconnect between the customer and who pays for (the service),''
says Roll, who joined ESC four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the differences in approach, consultants say the
nonprofit managers with whom they've worked have taken to
traditional business tactics like benchmarking and aggressive
marketing with aplomb. ESC's customer satisfaction surveys reveal
that ``not 100 percent, but 85 or 90 percent'' of nonprofit clients
are happy with the service, Wilson says.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofits say they appreciate the cost-effective help as well.
</P>
<P>
   Action Inc., a Gloucester, Mass. community agency, has used ESC
for five consulting assignments over the past three years with Roll
as lead consultant, says executive director William C.
Rochford. &UR;  &LR; Roll's team revamped the group's fundraising efforts,
convincing the board of directors to send out three targeted
letters to donors instead of one blanket letter. The ESC
consultants also did a needs-assessment survey for the community
and helped Action launch a new program for homeless job training.
</P>
<P>
   ESC's strength, Rochford says, comes from the group's neutrality
and outsider perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hire a planner or community organizer in this
business, they come in already with an agenda, whether it's food or
housing or women's rights or welfare,'' Rochford says. ``ESC is
more open to what the real needs in the community are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
