<HEADLINE>
SOX SHAKE HEADS AS SCHAEFER, KENNEY LOSE CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ On the face of it, Mo Vaughn's recent venting
against the Red Sox and Bob Schaefer's ouster as the team's
director of player development would seem to have little in common.
</P>
<P>
   But at the center of both Vaughn's disaffection and Schaefer's
demotion is general manager Dan Duquette and what some perceive as
his insistence on complete control, even at the expense of his star
slugger and a longtime baseball man who was instrumental in
reversing the fortunes of the farm system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to do the best I could,'' Schaefer said Tuesday from
his home in Connecticut. ``I thought my job was to make the system
look good and the general manager look good. The general manager
got a three-year contract, so I must have done my job.''
</P>
<P>
   The team has not yet made it official, but Schaefer's duties are
being taken over by Kent Qualls and Buddy Bailey. Qualls, 31, began
in player development with Montreal in 1988, the year Duquette was
hired by the Expos, and was the Expos' director of minor league
operations until 1995, when Duquette hired him as trainer for
Boston's Triple A team in Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   Qualls began this season as coordinator of baseball development
and administration; his duties included overseeing the team's
Dominican operation and involvement with its international
scouting.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, meanwhile, managed at Pawtucket, was the major league
advance scout last season, and this season was working as the
team's roving instructor for catchers.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, who will report to Qualls under the restructuring of
duties, is highly regarded throughout the system for his baseball
knowledge. Qualls, who unlike Schaefer did not play professionally,
is viewed more dimly, according to club sources, as a paper-pusher
and Duquette yes man. In fairness to Qualls, however, there are
numerous player development people around the big leagues who did
not play pro ball. ``You can't knock his ability as a baseball
person,'' said Kevin Shea, director of Red Sox communications.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette and Schaefer, according to sources, clashed on numerous
occasions this summer over minor league personnel decisions and
also over what Duquette perceived as self-promotion by Schaefer for
the success of the farm system.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Duquette had broached the subject of Schaefer
taking too much credit, Schaefer hedged. ``I don't know,'' he said.
``Indirectly, I guess. But I'm proud of what we did. It's `we,' not
`me.' We helped upgrade the situation, and Ed Kenney and I worked
together, and we're not done yet. That's what bothers me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette also is known to be unhappy with the stalled progress
of prized center-field prospect Michael Coleman, who recently was
benched for several games because of his attitude. Schaefer, asked
if he were being held responsible for Coleman's problems, said,
``Maybe that's part of it. I've talked to Michael Coleman more than
anybody. Maybe my way didn't work, but Coleman is still a young kid
and he had tremendous talent. Patience is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Schaefer, Kenney's involvement with the minor leagues is
over, which ends his family's long association with Red Sox player
development. Kenney's father, Edward F. Kenney, spent more than 45
years with the Red Sox, and the team's player development award is
in his name.
</P>
<P>
   As in Schaefer's case, Kenney, the director of minor league
operations, was offered a lesser position with the team and
reportedly will leave rather than accept it. Kenney did not respond
to messages left on his voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   Shea denied a report that Kenney had been fired but said
Duquette would not comment on the changes. ``Reassignments are
being made, and the process is still ongoing,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other changes as well. Roving infield instructor
Rafael Santana, the former Mets shortstop who was in his third
season with the Sox, has been fired, according to a source, and
several key minor league coaches and instructors are talking about
leaving if Schaefer doesn't stay. There also are indications,
sources say, that Pawtucket manager Ken Macha will not be asked
back next season in that position. And Pawtucket batting coach
Gerald Perry, who also came under some fire from Duquette over
Coleman, according to one source, also may look to leave, that
source said.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer said he was offered the title of director of Florida
operations but has not been told what the job entails. ``It's just
a title,'' he said. ``I'm a baseball guy. I don't care about the
other stuff. If the job does not include baseball, I wouldn't be
interested. I really don't want to leave the Red Sox, but before I
accept this job, I want to see what the job is.''
</P>
<P>
   The upheaval in the system came after organization meetings last
week at the Providence Hilton. At one point during the meetings,
according to sources, Duquette pulled Schaefer into the hall for a
10-minute discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the shakeup is unusual. This is the time of year
when minor league players are evaluated, when decisions are made
about which players will be asked to play winter ball, which
players will be assigned to the instructional league, and which
players will be promoted to the Red Sox in September, when rosters
can be expanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very surprised it came out like this,'' said Schaefer, who
came to the Red Sox in 1993, when he was hired by then GM Lou
Gorman as a special assignment scout. ``I told Dan last year that I
didn't want to do this job forever, but that doesn't mean I didn't
want to be involved in the baseball part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could help Buddy, I could help Kent, I could do a little
scouting, I'm pretty close to the players. Jimy (Williams) and I
had a good rapport. No one knows the system better than I do. But
it's almost like they don't need you anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer was asked if he thought of going over Duquette's head
to CEO John Harrington, as one source said he was contemplating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan's my boss,'' said Schaefer. ``He's the one calling the
shots. I'm not going to be changing anybody's minds. He has the
authority to do what he has to do. So I accept it. I'm not happy
about it, but what can I say? Life goes on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
