<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN ROBERT GREEN ADDS EXPERIENCE TO YOUNG PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Drew Bledsoe dumps the ball off in the right
flat to the Patriot wearing No. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The running back makes a quick little move, slipping a hit by
Chris Slade, and turns what might have been a loss into a gain.
</P>
<P>
   A Patriot training camp flashback at Bryant College: Bledsoe to
David Meggett? Nah. Just Bledsoe to the newest Patriot running
back, who happens to be a little Meggett-like.
</P>
<P>
   He wears the same number _ and did for his four years in
Chicago, by the way. He's built somewhat the same at 5 feet 8
inches, 202 pounds. He gets around the football field in somewhat
the same manner. Like Meggett, Robert Green made his first marks in
the NFL on special teams. And like Meggett did in recent years
before being released in the spring, he would like to make his mark
with this team as a special-teams player and third-down specialist.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, differences. Green brings none of the Pro
Bowl honors that Meggett brought. He brings only a small percentage
of the thousands of yards Meggett gained on rushes and catches and
returns in his career.
</P>
<P>
   But he does bring something otherwise lacking in what shapes up
as an extremely young Patriots running game: experience.
</P>
<P>
   This is his seventh year in the NFL since he joined the
Washington Redskins as a free agent out of William &AMP; Mary in 1992.
He'd love to run the ball all the time but figures he's more likely
to be called upon in third-down situations as well as on special
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could look into a crystal ball or something, I think
basically I'd be a third-down back here,'' Green said, ``and show
some of the younger running backs some of the things they need to
to do to be successful in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Running back things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when to get out of bounds, when to get down,'' Green
said. ``When to juke and when to run over a guy. All of that stuff
that only comes with experience. I think that's something I can
definitely bring to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, he was beginning to get a little concerned about
whether he would get the chance to bring his experience to any
camp.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, things got a little close. Green had been released
by Chicago in March and didn't sign with Minnesota until two days
before camp.
</P>
<P>
   That was nothing compared to this year. He played in only three
games with the Vikings last year and was looking for work again.
And was still looking when NFL camps started.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, the Patriots, looking for some experience to go
with the young legs of Robert Edwards and Sedrick Shaw, Derrick
Cullors and Harold Shaw, brought him in.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it gets closer to camp, you get a little more anxious
waiting to get that call,'' Green said. ``You try to think
positively. If you don't, it's tough to go work out with really no
reason to.''
</P>
<P>
   And yes, it did occur to him that this might be the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It crosses your mind,'' he said. ``It's the first time I've
ever actually been late for camp. The first time in seven years.
There very definitely was a point where I thought maybe this is it.
You never know.'
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't want to get caught up in one of those
six-years-and-out situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People start to tail off around the sixth year,'' Green said.
``I want to get this one in and go past that hurdle, and hopefully,
that will keep things going all right for me for the next couple of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Green was here Friday and scored a touchdown on a 12-yard
reception from Tom Tupa in Sunday's scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Reviews on the newest Patriot have been mixed thus far, said
Pete Carroll Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been up and down so far,'' the coach said. ``He missed a
couple of meetings. I think he and I have come back together and
(Ernie Zampese) has been letting him know what we're looking for.
He stuck the ball in pretty good today. I think he has made a
pretty good impression so far. He's very quick and instinctive.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's here, said Green, he plans to make the most of the
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never worry about that kind of stuff,'' he said of making
the team. ``When I'm in camp, I let my work on the field talk for
me. It's never let me down to this point. I've got to keep on doing
the things I need to do and let them worry about who's going to
stay and who's not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
