   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEWINSKY _ WASHINGTON _ Both publicly and behind the
scenes, the White House is working to counter a week of legal
setbacks for President Clinton. His legal team is weighing options
including appeals, a possible constitutional challenge and even
deposing independent counsel Kenneth Starr's own team. As always,
Clinton remains free to simply describe to the public the nature of
his relationship with former intern Monica Lewinsky, an option
aides say has not received much attention in the Oval Office.
(Deans, Cox News Service 900).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Monica Lewinsky's immunity deal has
sent a new tide of anonymously sourced stories into print and over
the air, but prominent journalists defended them Wednesday as the
only way to get information to the public. While the sources refuse
to be identifed, they are reliable, the journalists said. ``They're
not anonymous to us,'' said NBC-TV's Claire Shipman. (Dart, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SATELLITES _ WASHINGTON _ A Senate Governmental Affairs
subcommittee holds a 2 p.m. EDT hearing on the impact on industry
of satellite export controls. (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-WASTE _ WASHINGTON _ The House voted 305-117 on
Wednesday for a compromise bill to create the Sierra Blance
low-level nuclear waste dump in Texas near the Mexican border. The
measure now goes to the Senate, where opposition is expected
because a House-Senate conference committee deleted provisions that
would have limited the number of states that could send waste to
the dump and allowed local opponents to file ``environmental
justice'' lawsuits. (Abulhassan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-BLACKS _ A new census report on the black population.
(Shook, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-US _ MIAMI _ Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello heads to
Capitol Hill on Thursday to make one last-ditch push for passage of
a bill in the Senate that would allow Puerto Ricans to vote on
their island's future this year. The bill, which already passed the
House, would allow Puerto Ricans to choose between statehood,
independence, and commonwealth status. Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott has said there isn't enough time left in the current session
to consider the issue. Still, many Republicans have seized the
issue as a way to reach Hispanic voters, and are pushing for
passage. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: To move by 1 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-BOX-0730 _ Facts and figures about Puerto Rico, and
its choices for statehood. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BLACKLAWYERS _ MEMPHIS _ Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas
plans to speak to the nation's largest organization of black
lawyers at the National Bar Association's national convention.
(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   AUS-BISHOP-HOSPITAL _ The Roman Catholic Bishop of Austin is
walking a tightrope with the Vatican over sterilizations and
contraceptive programs offered at Brackenridge Hospital, the city
hospital managed by the Catholic-owned Seton Healthcare Network.
The unique public agreement is being watched closely by Catholic
hospitals nationwide. Conservative Catholics in Austin have sent
their complaints to the Vatican; Bishop John McCarthy is caught in
the crossfire. (Perkes, Austin-American Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   STATESCHOOL-BUS _ AUSTIN _ Throughout this fireball summer,
nearly 40 people with mental retardation were forced to endure bus
rides on the Austin State School campus in an unair-conditioned bus
where temperatures soared to 110 degrees. State inspectors deemed
the situation life-threatening, particularly because some of the
disabled residents have seizure disorders and take anticonvulsant
drugs that put them at high risk for heat stroke. (Gamino, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AUS-GANG -INJUNCTION _ The state wraps up its case today in
Texas' first-ever gang injunction lawsuit. If Judge Wil Flowers
approves the injunction _ which he seems inclined to do _ the group
of six would be prohibited for life from hanging out at businesses
and apartment complexes at Cameron and Broadmoor in Northeast
Austin. While ACLU and defense attorneys say such injunctions are
unconstitutional, state attorneys say they are an effective legal
tool helping police keep neighborhoods crime-free. If Flowers
approves this first one, lawyers say it is likely that the Travis
County district attorney's office, along with every other
prosecutor's shop in the state, will begin to use injunctions.
(Shah, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   GANGBOX _ List of some of the restrictions that would be placed
on the six people. (Shah, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
