<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-MOVIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIELBERG'S `RYAN' IS THE MOTHER OF ALL WAR MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS and G. ALLEN JOHNSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One reason ``Saving Private Ryan'' is being
talked about so much this summer is that it goes right after the
audience from the start, grabbing people out of their seats to drag
them through a half-hour of combat _ no jokes, no breathers, no
chance to relax. It's the first time a major war film has allowed
itself to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Other war movies have tried to be graphic about wounds and
killing and the cruelty of everyday combat. Other films have
broadcast the anti-war message, offering realistic dialogue and
shattering images. But ``Saving Private Ryan,'' with long,
teeth-grinding battle scenes that begin and end the movie, breaks
new ground _ it makes things uncomfortable for the audience from
start to finish, its idea of a breather being the haunted sound of
Edith Piaf playing from a gramophone before the final German
attack.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the bite-sized, bloodless combat in Audie Murphy's
``To Hell and Back'' becomes a comic book. Ditto for all the John
Wayne epics, from ``Flying Tigers'' to ``The Green Berets.'' That's
to be expected _ propaganda films like ``The Fighting Seabees,''
``The Purple Heart'' and ``Green Berets'' weren't meant to be
realistic.
</P>
<P>
   But in its commitment to unrelenting battle scenes, ``Saving
Private Ryan'' also breaks tradition with anti-war films, which
tend to parcel out their pain. It goes further than the original
``All Quiet on the Western Front,'' further than ``Platoon'' and
``Stalingrad,'' ``Attack!'' and ``The Bridge'' and ``The Hook.''
Further than ``The Bridges of Toko-Ri'' or ``Steel Helmet,'' and
much further than the smug ``Apocalypse Now.''
</P>
<P>
   Director Steven Spielberg said he felt a duty to World War II
veterans ``to finally acquit them of their experience in a
non-Hollywood way, if I possibly could pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   After talking with them, Spielberg said, ``The signal they were
giving me was, `Look, we're 80, we're 70, we're 75 years old. Tell
our stories. The way we experienced it. Not the way we're used to
telling it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drew my own line in the sands of Omaha Beach. I just
couldn't sugarcoat what happened in Normandy,'' Spielberg said.
```Saving Private Ryan' would therefore fall into a long line of
WWII films that have simply used World War II as an excuse for
action and adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg, who extended the original D-Day scene from five to 35
pages, said, ``I made it about a 24-minute sequence because I
wanted to initiate the audience the way these boys were initiated
when they hit those beaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Historian Stephen E. Ambrose said that, compared to ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' movies such as ``The Longest Day,'' ``A Bridge Too
Far'' and ``Patton'' ``are kindergarten films.''
</P>
<P>
   The history of war films, said Ambrose, is ``that every time a
GI gets hit, he's dead ... but in the vast majority of cases, he
suffers. He knows he's been hit, and he knows he's dying, and he's
trying to put his guts back in his stomach ... and that's what you
get with Spielberg. You do not get that in another American war
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous war films committed to degrees of realism, such as ``A
Walk in the Sun,'' ``Pork Chop Hill,'' ``Paths of Glory'' and ``Das
Boot,'' have to step aside for ``Saving Private Ryan.'' And formula
movies like ``The Victors,'' ``Midway,'' ``The Big Red One,''
``Patton'' and ``Catch-22'' become soap operas in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Fuller, director of ``The Big Red One'' and ``Steel
Helmet,'' acknowledged pulling his punches. In a recent documentary
he said, ``I lied with the camera. I lied like hell. I didn't want
people to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike those films, ``Saving Private Ryan'' doesn't take
periodic detours to preach at the audience or give people a chance
to say, ``Whew, that was pretty rough'' as they get up to go buy
some popcorn. Spielberg's movie keeps coming at you, from that
first moment when the ramp of the assault boat hits the water and
machine guns open up on the men crowded inside, the sound of
bullets hitting flesh and metal filling the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Think about the beach-invasion movies you've seen, how the ramp
comes down and men run off, one falling over here, another over
there, some blips of sand exploding to show how close the bullets
are _ a kind of ``Aw, that's too bad'' sense of watching soldiers
die.
</P>
<P>
   You think of ``Beachhead'' and ``Battle Cry,'' of ``Guadalcanal
Diary,'' with a helmet rolling through the sand, a photo of a
family tucked inside. They're all shallow and serene, compared to
the blood-letting in the first few minutes of ``Saving Private
Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's Normandy scenes show up ``D-Day: The Sixth of June''
and Darryl Zanuck's ``The Longest Day'' for the contrived and
Hollywoodish movies they are. Robert Mitchum shouting ``Let's go!''
can't hold a candle to the confusion and slaughter that Tom Hanks
faces as he staggers and crawls to find one spot free from bullets.
</P>
<P>
   When Hanks falls to his knees on the beach, suddenly deaf,
turning through metallic silence to see a man casually pick up an
arm blown off by artillery, another clutching at an ooze of guts,
another, legless, thrashing at the sand, the audience is trained to
think, from past movies, that the slaughter will end in a minute or
two. It doesn't. Hanks leads an attack on a bunker that descends
into butchery, emotional breakdowns and the random killing of
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   It marks perhaps the first time an American film has been able
to make war a truly gruesome experience for those sitting in the
safety of the theater _ an unrelenting attack on the senses, a
tension marathon, an endurance race toward the night air outside.
</P>
<P>
   Whether ``Saving Private Ryan'' will make any difference in the
way people see war _ World War II in particular _ remains to be
seen. But at least Spielberg tried. At least he didn't take it easy
on his audience, the way so many war films have done in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
