A8213 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-HNS &LR;      07-29 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LUCKY BASTARD,' THE BEACH BOOK OF THE SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles McCarry's ``Lucky Bastard'' (Random House, $24.95, 385
pages) is going to be compared to Richard Condon's ``The Manchurian
Candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, both books deal with a sleeper agent whose ultimate
goal is the takeover of the U.S. government. Both books are
political satires _ ``Manchurian'' wickedly sophisticated,
``Lucky'' devilishly politically incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   The similarities end there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucky Bastard'' begins with Soviet agent Dimitri, the book's
narrator, trying to recruit students in New York during the Vietnam
War. A professor suggests Dimitri take a look at young John
Fitzgerald Adams _ a political science major from Ohio who believes
he is the illegitimate son of John Fitzgerald Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   And young Jack is the perfect candidate _ he's amoral, a coward,
a draft dodger, a womanizer (he always carries a jar of Vaseline in
his pocket), a charmer, and everyone who meets him likes him.
Dimitri tells his control, Peter, about Jack, and the two rogue KGB
agents set in motion a plan to make Jack the president of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   First they get Jack a fellowship at the University of Heidelberg
in Germany, then get him into law school at Harvard, where he meets
the strong-willed Morgan, another sleeper agent who will become his
wife. Jack returns to Ohio and sets up a law practice with his best
friend from childhood, Danny, a crippled Vietnam veteran. And of
course, Jack runs for office, beginning with district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   What Jack's handlers don't know about and therefore can't
control is Danny's wife, Cindy, who has always hated Jack.
</P>
<P>
   This thriller is funny, well-crafted and, unfortunately, very
believable. You can't read it and not think of Clinton and the
Kennedys. McCarry goes a bit overboard with the sex scenes, but it
works.
</P>
<P>
   Love it or hate it, ``Lucky Bastard'' is this summer's must-read
beach book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dog Who Bit a Policeman.'' By Stuart M. Kaminsky. $22. 288
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Kaminsky's 12th Moscow police procedural featuring one-legged
Inspector Porfiry Rostnikov is a worthy addition to the series.
</P>
<P>
   In the new Russia, a mafia member is found floating naked and
face down in the Moscow River and others turn up equally dead in
hotel swimming pools. Rostnikov must track down each mob's leader
and try to halt an all-out mafia war.
</P>
<P>
   As wild dogs roam Moscow streets in search of food, other
mobsters are setting up dog fights, and the profits are huge.
Rostnikov sends in an undercover team to track down the leaders and
close the fights down. Meanwhile, he sends his son and another
detective off to track a missing high government official who is
needed for a key vote and is assumed to be off on a long drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Rostnikov and his team of officers are dedicated, loyal even
when the paychecks are often delayed. From the mob bosses to the
underlings, the prostitutes to Rostnikov's family and friends _ all
the characters are well-defined and believable. My only quibble is
the too-cute title _ Rostnikov and gang deserve better.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Gatekeeper.'' By Philip Shelby. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $25. 331
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby offers up a gutsy heroine facing life-threatening
situations in a fast-paced, first-rate international thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago during a lawn party at the U.S. Embassy in
Paris, a sniper known as the Handyman killed the parents of
11-year-old Hollis Fremont. However, he wasn't supposed to kill
Hollis' mother, so he's been hiding out in Marseilles all these
years.
</P>
<P>
   Now grown up, Hollis moves to Paris as a U.S. Foreign Service
officer. She falls madly in love with Paul McGann, a high-ranking
embassy official. He asks her to escort a white-collar criminal
back to New York. Unfortunately, the criminal kills a man in the
subway and forces Hollis to continue with him to New York. There
more killings occur, and special government agent Sam Crawford
saves Hollis when the killer goes after her. Crawford, whose main
task is hunting down assassins, at first believes Hollis was an
accomplice, but then realizes she was McGann's pawn. Crawford tells
her the killer is the notorious assassin Handyman, and now Hollis
must come to terms with the fact that the man she loves used her
and set her up to be killed.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford enlists Hollis' help in trying to stop Handyman before
he completes his assassination. But Handyman goes after them,
nearly kills them, and gets them put on all the most-wanted lists
after a SWAT team tracking them gets blown up.
</P>
<P>
   There are enough plot turns in ``Gatekeeper'' to make you dizzy,
as Shelby keeps you guessing right to end. He's crafted a wild
assortment of interesting characters, drops in realistic dialogue
and moves the storyline along at a brisk pace. A fine addition to
the genre.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
