<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8214 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TONI-MORRISON-HNS &LR;      07-29 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONI-MORRISON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONI MORRISON EXPLORES A NEW KIND OF LOVE IN `PARADISE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VENISE WAGNER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ To read the works of Toni Morrison requires a
certain intensity and patience. She will pull you in on the thread
of images that unravel humanity's mysteries and truths layer by
layer, paragraph by paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   If you manage to keep up, the end of the odyssey rewards you
with interior sight. Where you were blind to the weight of love,
joy and pain, she helps you see.
</P>
<P>
   It is not so different hearing her speak. One might be
intimidated by the authority her name, her novels and the title of
Nobel laureate carry, but the weight of her presence, not unlike
her words, lands gently, surely.
</P>
<P>
   So it was last week when she walked onto two San Francisco-area
stages, at the Marriott Convention Center in Oakland and the Palace
of Fine Arts in San Francisco. The audiences responded with regal
welcomes standing almost immediately as they saw her silver and
white crown of neatly wrapped dreadlocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Marriott Convention Center and the Palace of Fine Arts might
as well have been enlarged living rooms when she sat down first
with Marcus Books founder Raye Richardson and later with author
Dorothy Allison. The meandering conversations visited such
ponderous themes as hope in the face of despair and redemption at
the foot of unforgivable acts, both of which have re-emerged in her
latest novel ``Paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is also a light side to Morrison. A thick giggle
emerges when she talks of the upcoming movie-version of her 1987
book, ``Beloved,'' or even the recent publication of Modern
Library's 100 Best English-language novels of the century.
</P>
<P>
   That list, which came out earlier this month, placed James
Joyce's ``Ulysses'' in the number one slot and boasted only eight
women authors, none of whom were African American.
</P>
<P>
   Raye Richardson, former chair of black studies at San Francisco
State University, called the list ridiculous for not including at
least two Morrison titles. And Dorothy Allison balked that
``Beloved'' wasn't at the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that says 100 of anything, you know that's
marketing,'' Morrison said, laughter streaming between her words.
``Those are their (Modern Library's) books. I am in (published by)
the `Everyman' line that includes Proust and some international
writers. So there was never any way that Modern Library was going
to put me on that list since I was already in Everyman.''
</P>
<P>
   Intimately familiar with the publishing game _ she was a senior
editor for Random House for 15 years _ she has witnessed the
industry becoming consumed with multimillion dollar deals and big
money gambles. But Morrison said she was not discouraged by the
trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very energized by people telling me no, I can't do it. And
when something seems to be falling apart it makes me more eager to
do it well. ... You have to husband your work. You have to just
hold and feed it and cultivate it. The interesting thing about
novel writing is protecting it, cultivating it and at the same time
making it the one part of your life that's totally public.''
</P>
<P>
   This seems to be one of the aspects that Morrison loves about
her work; bringing her literary themes to the community table to
chew on.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Paradise,'' Morrison said she wanted to shift the public
discourse from one focusing on the legal to one exploring the
moral; from a fascination with crime to an examination of sin; from
an obsession with guilt to an openness to contrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paradise'' is the third tome of what Morrison calls a trilogy
that includes ``Beloved'' and ``Jazz.'' She said when she first
began ``Beloved'' she thought she was writing one book with three
parts exploring the many types of love that, if indulged too much,
can overwhelm and destroy.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Beloved,'' the story of an escaped slave who kills her
child to keep the child out of slavery, Morrison explores interior
love, one that emerges in a mother for her child, that turns
destructive when it becomes excessive.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Jazz,'' she examines the romantic love between a married
man and an 18-year-old woman. It is a love that consumes him so
that he kills her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paradise'' looks at spiritual love, the love of God. ``It too
can be excessive, dictatorial and very all-knowing,'' Morrison
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The book, which some critics have described as a parable, takes
readers to the fictional all-black town, Ruby, Okla., started by
nine families whose ancestors had been shunned from other black
towns because they came with nothing, breaking the rule, ``Come
Prepared or Not at All.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, the families literally carry their history in
stone and in their unbending, righteous view of themselves as the
chosen ones, until they begin to turn in on themselves and on a
nearby ``Convent'' of dispossessed women.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the creation of paradise you have a clear example of having
the privilege of a chosen people; that God is guiding and talking
to you, which is lovely and desirable,'' she said. ``Of course
within that phrase `chosen people' is the seed of destruction
because paradise is about the unchosen. Paradises tend to be
exclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   The story ``Paradise'' grew out of a question Morrison asked
while reading the history of 200 freed men who walked from
Mississippi to Oklahoma trying to settle in one of the black towns.
They had no money, few possessions and were turned away because
they did not come prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to those people who were told by ex-slaves you
can't come in? ... that must have been a blow,'' she said. ``That
would have been a knock-out for me to walk from Mississippi to
arrive there and some other black people say, `You can't come
in.'''
</P>
<P>
   Both ``Paradise'' and ``Beloved'' were placed on Oprah's Book
Club list, boosting sales by 3,000 percent at some major chains.
Now Oprah Winfrey has just finished co-producing and starring in
``Beloved,'' the movie.
</P>
<P>
   The story is set in Ohio after the Civil War, with Winfrey
playing the main character, Sethe, backed by Danny Glover, Thandie
Newton and Kimberly Elise. Jonathan Demme directs.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said she sold the complete rights and had no say in its
production. But she has seen two versions of the movie and said she
was impressed with Winfrey's portrayal of Sethe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I don't know how to make movies,'' she said,
emphasizing that she writes books, not movie scripts. ``Even if I
could do that well, it's a complete life. You give a year over to
it and they don't let you fire anybody. So I can't say get off the
set. You have responsibilities without power and I don't like those
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Her laughter was light but the point as resonant as her
presence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
