<SLUG> BC-LONE-STAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSE RACING STRUGGLES TO COMPETE IN AN ERA OF SLOT MACHINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GOTTLIEB  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The setting is an entertainment haven. The new racing season is
brief and loaded with family events. Quality horses are set to
compete and there isn't a slot machine to be found for four hours.
</P>
<P>
   It could be opening day at Saratoga Race Course in Saratoga
Springs, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But this is suburban Dallas, home of Lone Star Park at Grand
Prairie, packing them in its second year of existence, even as
tracks nationwide are being turned over to dog races, festivals or
wrecking crews.
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star relies on a formula heavy on atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you a couple of things we have in common with
Saratoga: Saratoga is an afternoon of entertainment and it just so
happens the core product is world-class racing,'' said Corey
Johnsen, vice president and general manager at Lone Star. ``We
pride ourselves in the same philosophy of entertainment. That's
what sells.''
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga Race Course opened for its 130th season Wednesday, once
again becoming the main event of a resort atmosphere that reaches
well beyond the hard-core gambler. That is an environment the
nation's oldest racetrack shares with its successful counterparts,
such as Churchill Downs in Kentucky and Del Mar in California.
</P>
<P>
   As weaker tracks founder, these strong thoroughbred-racing
venues share other key virtues: they are situated in areas largely
uncluttered by other forms of gambling, and they schedule brief,
defined seasons that leave enthusiasts looking forward to the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the novelty of it,'' said jockey Richard Migliore, who
was the second leading New York Racing Association jockey last
year. ``Coming upstate is beautiful, you have the historical town
of Saratoga, the product is just fantastic and it's condensed into
six weeks. Sometimes, less is better.''
</P>
<P>
   In Saratoga, the season stretches to Sept. 7, with the $750,000
Travers Stakes scheduled for Aug. 29. Last year 991,000 spectators
wagered an average $3.7 million a day, according to the New York
Racing Association, ranking Saratoga among the nation's most
successful tracks.
</P>
<P>
   New York Racing Association chief executive Terry Meyocks
cautioned that the success at Saratoga relies on a delicate balance
of marketing and atmosphere, which could be thrown off by
competition. Periodic efforts to introduce off-reservation casino
gambling in New York state are among perennial concerns to the
track. The state Legislature last year turned back a proposal to
allow gambling halls near Lake George, in the Catskills and western
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to keep the competition out of our doorstep,'' Meyocks
said. ``I hope people in New York realize what would be lost.''
</P>
<P>
   With betting on thoroughbreds up slightly nationwide, racing
analysts say the tracks themselves are on a Darwinian course.
Thoroughbred Racing Communications, a New York City-based industry
group, said the total handle was $11.6 billion in 1996, up from
$9.3 billion in 1990. But nearly 80 percent of the bets are placed
off-track, making the tracks themselves a less integral part of the
equation than they once were.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general there is too much product out there,'' said Tom
Merritt, executive director of Thoroughbred Racing Communications.
``I think you're already seeing the fittest survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent casualties include Atlantic City Race Course, which
concluded live racing last spring; Detroit Race Course, scheduled
to close this year; and Birmingham Turf Club, which now runs dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Arlington International Race Course, outside Chicago, remains in
a suspended state, with no racing this year and no certainty that
the horses will be back in 1999. Like others that have foundered
before it, the track is being crushed by nearby competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the country's most profitable riverboat casinos is 10
miles from us, and we're seeing just a continual erosion of horse
racing as more and more casinos opened and feed off the Chicago
marketplace,'' said Scott Mordell, chief executive of Arlington.
``The horse racing just isn't as attractive anymore in Illinois.
What do we do?''
</P>
<P>
   One approach has been tried in Delaware, where a track decided
to join forces with gambling. Delaware Park benefited from state
legislation that enabled it to add slot machines at the track. The
move quickly boosted attendance and racing. However, some observers
wonder if the success of the slots might prove too much of a good
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What scares people now is the scenario that has mangers
saying, `Gee we don't need the water trucks and the barns and the
starting gates to simply run slot machines,''' Merritt said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
