<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PUERTO RICO FACTS AND FIGURES
 &HT;    With PUERTORICO-US-0730.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Puerto Rico By -The-Numbers
</P>
<P>
   POPULATION: 3.8 million, although about another 2 million Puerto
Ricans live in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   SIZE: 100 miles by 35 miles, an area smaller than Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE: Both Spanish and English were made official languages
in 1993; but only a quarter of the population speak English
fluently.
</P>
<P>
   UNEMPLOYMENT RATE: 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNOR: Pedro Rossello, who took office in January 1993 and
was re-elected last year, is pro-statehood.
</P>
<P>
   PER-CAPITA PERSONAL INCOME: about $8,500.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY: Manufacturing-based. Produces electronics, apparel, and
about half the prescription drugs in the United States. Currency is
the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT: Puerto Rico is a self-governing commonwealth in
association with the United States. The chief of state is the U.S.
president. The head of government is an elected governor. There are
two legislative chambers: the House of Representatives with 51
seats and the Senate with 27 seats.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS: Local parties are neither Democrat or Republican, but
instead favor statehood, independence, or commonwealth. Puerto Rico
has one non-voting representative in Congress, who is currently
Carlos Romero-Barcelo. Residents can't vote in U.S. federal
elections, nor do they pay federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE: Puerto Rican government.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico's Choices:
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-Puerto Rico Political Status Act calls for a referendum
before Dec. 31, 1998. Puerto Rico residents would be asked to pick
from the following three options for the island's future:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Commonwealth: Puerto Rico would continue as a U.S. territory
and maintain local self-government. Puerto Ricans still wouldn't be
allowed to vote in U.S. federal elections, nor would they pay
federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Separate Sovereignty: Puerto Rico would become an independent
nation. Puerto Ricans would have their own citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Statehood: Equal standing as a U.S. state with guaranteed U.S.
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
