</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUERTORICO-US-0730-CO     07-29 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-US-0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PUERTO RICO MAKES LAST-DITCH PUSH FOR STATEHOOD ON CAPITOL HILL
 &HT;    With PUERTORICO-BOX-0730.
 &HT;    EDS:Contains optional trim.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Democratic governor of Puerto Rico will be knocking
on a lot of Republican doors in Washington Thursday during a
two-day visit to Capitol Hill, part of a last-ditch push for a
chance for his island to become the 51st state.
</P>
<P>
   The visit comes on the heels of a call by pro-statehood Gov.
Pedro Rossello last Saturday for a non-binding vote in December on
whether the commonwealth should apply to become a state, request
independence, or remain a U.S. territory.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the U.S. House of Representatives breathed new life
into the issue of statehood by voting 209 to 208 for the first-ever
federally authorized plebiscite allowing Puerto Ricans to vote on
their future. Under the legislation, the vote would be held by the
end of this year. If a majority opted for statehood, the measure
would give Congress 10 years to decide whether to grant statehood
to Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   But similar legislation in the Senate has been stalled this
summer, mostly by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Republicans don't pass this, it will show an
anti-Hispanic strain in the Republican Party that will eventually
hurt them with Hispanic voters,'' said pro-statehood Puerto Rican
Sen. Kenneth McClintock. ``This bill won't cost the U.S. government
anything, so the only thing that could be at play is an
anti-Hispanic sentiment among Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., a leading proponent of the plebiscite,
said he has enough votes in the full Senate to pass the
legislation, which is currently before the Senate Committee on
Energy and Natural Resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``I urge that we not become the victims of decision by
indecision,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Even President Clinton has pushed passage of the measure this
year, the 100th anniversary of U.S. control over Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   But persuading Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., to
bring it to the floor this session has become an uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has said there are more pressing matters to deal with this
session than Puerto Rico, such as lingering appropriations bills,
and that there simply isn't time to take up the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that most Americans would agree that it's more
important to make sure the FBI is fully funded and the military is
fully funded, and that the budget is worked on than it is to deal
with Puerto Rico,'' said John Czwartacki, a spokesman for Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ``My suspicion is that Puerto Rico is not the biggest concern
among Hispanics in the United States,'' he added. ``I believe they
share concerns over law enforcement, education, and the budget with
all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview last March, Lott also relayed concerns
that Democrats would gain two senators and six representatives if
Puerto Rico became a state.
</P>
<P>
   But Xavier Romeu, executive director of the Puerto Rico
governor's office in Washington, said Republicans shouldn't
automatically assume that Puerto Ricans would vote democratic.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico's society is a conservative one, a place where
schools allow students five minutes for prayer and capital gains
taxes were cut from 20 percent to 7 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Romeu added that Senate Republicans will send a dangerous
message if they don't act on legislation this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans are sending a message that they are a party of
exclusion, not inclusion,'' he said. ``Eventually, Puerto Rico will
become a state, and you can bet Puerto Ricans won't forget.''
</P>
<P>
   By announcing a non-binding plebiscite, Romeu said that Rossello
hopes to give momentum to the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, Rossello also hopes that a decisive victory for
statehood could sweep aside fears that the Spanish-speaking island
might become the U.S. equivalent of Quebec, the restive
French-speaking Canadian province.
</P>
<P>
   ``If after 100 years, the U.S. Senate does not possess the will
to put an end to a century of colonialism, Puerto Rico does,''
Rossello told tens of thousands of cheering statehood supporters at
a rally marking the anniversary of the U.S. invasion of July 25,
1898.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico's legislature will hold a special session Aug. 12 to
determine whether to authorize the referendum on the island's
future.
</P>
<P>
   Spain ceded Puerto Rico to the United States in 1898 following
the Spanish-American War. Congress granted U.S. citizenship to
Puerto Ricans in 1917 and made the island a commonwealth in 1952.
Puerto Ricans are exempt from federal taxes and receive limited
federal aid -- some $10 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But Puerto Ricans can't vote for president and have only one
nonvoting representative in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Ricans maintain strong ties to the U.S. mainland, but
have retained a very real sense of sovereignty: they have their own
Olympic team and a beloved flag. And the population of 3.8 million
is a Spanish-speaking one, with only about 25 percent of islanders
able to speak fluent English.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Puerto Ricans voted on their future was in 1993,
during a non-binding referendum, when voters decided 49 percent to
46 percent to remain a commonwealth, with 5 percent choosing
independence.
</P>
<P>
   A San Juan Star newspaper poll in June showed Puerto Ricans are
still deeply divided over the issue, with 40.9 percent favoring
statehood, 40.2 percent a commonwealth, and 7.6 percent
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the U.S. Congress will ever agree to statehood
for Puerto Rico unless there is a clear consensus on the island
that this is what they want,'' said Max Castro of the University of
Miami's North-South Center.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   One problem that looms over future referendums centers on the
definition of ``commonwealth.'' In 1993, commonwealth supporters
pushed for a broad definition that would guarantee American
citizenship, in addition to other things.
</P>
<P>
   But the House rejected that guarantee in drafting new
definitions this year, and now commonwealth backers say they will
boycott any referendum that doesn't include the guarantee of
citizenship under commonwealth status.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some senators are now pushing for a scaled-down
version of the original legislation that would call for a
referendum without pushing Congress to implement the results within
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   They say it's important to get something -- even a watered-down
version -- passed.
</P>
<P>
   The House-approved measure was the culmination of three years of
hearings, a mountain of work that would be wiped away if the Senate
fails to act before the 105th Congress ends this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``A scaled-back version is better than nothing because,
otherwise, we have to start all over again next year,'' said
Cuauhtemoc Figueroa, director of policy and communications for the
League of United Latin American Citizens, which supports a
plebiscite. ``And we've got no idea at all what kind of a ballgame
we'd face with a whole new slew of legislators.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
