<HEADLINE>
INTERNET SEARCH SITE PLANS MAJOR MARKETING PUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Got HotBot?
</P>
<P>
   Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners, the San Francisco advertising
agency that created the ``Got Milk?'' campaign, will be creating a
multimillion-dollar advertising push for the HotBot Internet search
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will be a catch-up move for HotBot
(www.hotbot.com), which is owned by Wired Digital, a Web-based
technology news and information company.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement also represents one of the first corporate
initiatives for San Francisco-based Wired Digital since it split
from its Wired magazine counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Wired magazine was sold to Advance Magazine Publishers
Inc., a holding company owned by magazine mogul S.I. Newhouse.
Advance publishes such titles as GQ, Vogue and the New Yorker.
Wired Digital is now owned by a board made up largely of past
investors in Wired magazine.
</P>
<P>
   According to Andrew de Vries, Wired Digital's director of
marketing communications, the Goodby ad campaign is designed to
make HotBot a widely known Web search resource, instead of a
``word-of-mouth'' site used by information professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to ramp it up to take it to the next level,'' de
Vries said.
</P>
<P>
   HotBot's campaign launch will make it a latecomer to the Web
search engine party, and the hot Web ``portal'' craze fueling
astronomical stock prices of on-line companies such as Yahoo
(www.yahoo.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't really reached the scale or popularity of other
search sites, like Excite, Lycos and Infoseek,'' said Bridget
Regan, an analyst with the Giga Information Group, a research and
advisory group. ``And in the race to become a portal, HotBot hasn't
really geared up.''
</P>
<P>
   A portal is a Web site designed to be starting point for
Internet users. They can attract millions of users, along with
millions in advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say the sale of the magazine helped this push,'' de
Vries said. ``It gave us a healthier balance sheet and a focus. Now
that we're a pure Internet company, we can make a pure Internet
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The budget for the advertising campaign is confidential, de
Vries said. But he added that Wired Digital expected to launch
about a dozen more ad campaigns showcasing Wired Digital
properties, at a cost of between $10 million and $15 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't consider ourselves starting late,'' he said.
``There's still plenty of the Internet pie left to go around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
