<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-COMA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS JUDGE REMAINS IN A COMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAIME CASTILLO  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ State District Judge Mike Machado showed slight
signs of improvement from complications associated with a brain
aneurysm but still was in grave condition, according to a son of
the judge.
</P>
<P>
   The 74-year-old judge and World War II hero has been in a coma
since undergoing emergency surgery Sunday afternoon and remained in
an intensive care unit at Santa Rosa Hospital here.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Machado Jr. choked back tears several times as he read from
a brief statement Tuesday with his brother Marc standing nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Machado Jr. said that only a few minutes earlier his father
``showed improvement in his ability to breathe on his own, and his
heart is strong. ... He's in no physical pain at this juncture, and
we're very grateful for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge's wife of 41 years, Rosa Elia, did not attend the news
conference at the hospital, choosing to stay by her husband's side.
</P>
<P>
   Machado Jr., a local lawyer, said his father was responding to
some stimuli from doctors. ``I really don't know exactly what it
means other than the doctors are encouraged by that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to speculate about his father's political future.
</P>
<P>
   Machado, who must retire from the bench on his 75th birthday
Sept. 4, is the Democratic nominee for Bexar County district
attorney in the November general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, it's too soon and it's too painful to speculate
as to what's going to happen in the near future,'' Machado Jr.
said. ``My father's life is now in God's hands, and all we ask from
those who are concerned (is to) please pray for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in a phone interview, Machado Jr. was asked about
speculation that he would seek to replace his father on the ballot
if the veteran jurist couldn't make the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, in my mind he is still the leading candidate in
the race,'' he said. ``If things change and the climate is right,
I'll consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Machado, who has been a municipal and state district
judge for 41 years, is known for his toughness, which enabled him
to survive severe burns in World War II that put him in a military
hospital for three years.
</P>
<P>
   While in the Army Air Corps, the plane he was in crash-landed
after being hit by enemy fire. As he was rescuing two other men
from the downed plane, Machado received the burns that left him
with limited use of his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Machado Jr. said if anyone can pull out of a coma, it would be
his father. ``Fighter doesn't even come close to describing him,''
he said. ``Nothing fazes him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
