<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8386 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARENTTRAP-AZR &LR;      07-29 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTTRAP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'VE BUILT A BETTER `PARENT TRAP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - What girl can resist the fantasy that she really
deserves a fabulously rich secret father and a wonderfully wealthy
secret mother, plus a fun secret twin sister who will be her best
friend forever?
</P>
<P>
   Not many girls turned down ``The Parent Trap'' fantasy the first
time around in 1961, and today's girls will fall for ``The Parent
Trap'' remake all over again.
</P>
<P>
   They should because, in the land of endlessly tired Hollywood
remakes, this one is actually more fun than the original.
</P>
<P>
   The star, young Lindsay Lohan, in her first _ two _ roles, is
cute as two buttons and twice as funny.
</P>
<P>
   Lohan plays Hallie Parker and Annie James, two delightful
11-year-old girls who dislike each other instantly when they meet
at summer camp. Then the girls discover that they actually have a
lot in common, including the same mother and the same father.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Annie's English mom (Natasha Richardson) and Hallie's
American dad (Dennis Quaid) divorced when the girls were babies,
each taking one daughter and never telling either about her twin.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask why, the filmmakers have no excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, when summer camp ends, the girls decide to switch
places, so Annie can meet her long-lost father and Hallie can meet
the mother she never knew.
</P>
<P>
   The twins then decide to bring their parents back together, but
they'd better hurry because Dad is about to marry a conniving gold
digger who despises little girls.
</P>
<P>
   This second-time-around ``Parent Trap'' uses the same story as
the first. Usually, that's the kiss of boredom for a remake,
causing people who enjoyed the original to ask themselves: Why am I
watching this all over again, when it's not as good?
</P>
<P>
   This time around, it is. Director Nancy Meyers, part of the
writing-producing team behind such comic hits as ``Baby Boom'' and
``Father of the Bride,'' makes a zippier, peppier, spunkier
``Parent Trap.''
</P>
<P>
   This one has more laughs, more high jinks and more fun than the
original. It also has Lohan, who is doubly terrific. As endearing
as Hayley Mills was, Lohan is even more winning.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you treasure the original as an important event
from your own childhood, you may not want someone messing with your
memories.
</P>
<P>
   But that won't affect your own daughters. If they're under 12,
they should love ``The Parent Trap.''
</P>
<P>
   You may wonder why the producers simply didn't hire twins to
play twins, instead of the complicated procedure of filming each
scene twice, then compositing the two images together.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers like to play around with their special-effects
gadgets. Cloning two girls from one creates a buzz. With twins,
you'd have to rely on acting alone.
</P>
<P>
   As much fun as ``The Parent Trap'' is, it does strike some odd
chords:
</P>
<P>
   - As a society, we've had 35 years of parenting lessons since
Brian Keith and Maureen O'Hara were considered good parents despite
each one abandoning a beloved baby and treating twins so cruelly as
to deny one the other.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that Hollywood would promote as '90s role models
parents who make the same dumb mistakes is a stretch to all but
actual Hollywood parents, where the idea of raising a child right
means conducting the nanny interviews personally.
</P>
<P>
   - Quaid (``Switchback'') has some trouble creating a dedicated
dad who would be smart enough to marry the girls' mother, yet dumb
enough to fall for the gold digger.
</P>
<P>
   - As for Richardson (``Nell''), she's oddly done up to remind us
of that other fantasy of English nobility: Princess Di.
</P>
<P>
   - Despite its comic energy, the remake does sag and at precisely
the same point as the original: during the efforts to reunite the
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``The Parent Trap'' remains a fun family film, if for no
other reason than to watch a really talented young actress at work.
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG, ``The Parent Trap'' contains nothing offensive. 3
stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1530EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
