<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8395 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASTEROID-AZR &LR;      07-29 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTEROID-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILEWIDE ASTEROID COMES INTO VIEW  
 (ART ADV: GRAPHIC IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BySTEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. - A milewide asteroid that could some day
collide with Earth was discovered recently by Arizona scientists
using a new device specifically designed to search for potential
killer space rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed ``1998 MQ,'' the asteroid is the first near-Earth space
debris discovered by Lowell Observatory's Near-Earth Object Search,
or LONEOS, which began scanning the night skies from Flagstaff in
March.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers calculated that the asteroid is no immediate threat,
and that in its current orbit it likely will pass no closer than 10
million miles to Earth, or about 40 times the distance between the
Earth and the moon.
</P>
<P>
   However, the orbits of asteroids are chaotic, and their paths
can change over time because of the gravitational influence of
planets and collisions with other asteroids, said Ted Bowell, a
Lowell astronomer who discovered the asteroid with researchers
Brian Skiff and Bruce Koehn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that at some point in the distant future
(perhaps as long as 100 million years) it could hit the Earth,''
Bowell said.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers will continue to track its movements along with
about 500 other known near-Earth objects, more than 100 of which
are larger than 1 kilometer across, or five-eighths of a mile, the
size that not only could penetrate Earth's atmosphere, but cause
catastrophic damage and mass extinctions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such an asteroid, or perhaps a comet, is believed to have caused
the extinction of dinosaurs 65 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell researchers employ an electronic camera attached to a
telescope that can scan the entire visible night sky once every
four months. This year, the device will be improved so that it will
scan the sky once a month and detect asteroids as small as a
football field.
</P>
<P>
   The device uses a computer to compare electronic images. These
comparisons are used to detect the slightest movements and alert
astronomers to anything that does not appear to be a star, a planet
or a previously detected asteroid or comet. It eliminates the
time-consuming process of comparing night sky photographs by hand.
</P>
<P>
   LONEOS automatically notified researchers of 1998 MQ on June 18
after comparing three images taken over the course of an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Located high in the western sky after sunset, just above the
bright star Arcturus, the asteroid is moving at more than a mile
per second. But at 60 million miles from Earth, it is too small and
dim to see with the naked eye.
</P>
<P>
   The asteroid travels in an elliptical path once every 2.4 years
that takes it from the massive asteroid belt between Mars and
Jupiter to near Earth's orbit around the sun.
</P>
<P>
   LONEOS is part of a larger project funded by NASA, which has the
goal of discovering at least 90 percent of all near-Earth objects
within the next decade, thereby providing an early warning system
for any objects in space that could pose a threat to human
survival.
</P>
<P>
   The positions of less than 10 percent of the estimated 2,000
potential killer asteroids are known.
</P>
<P>
   This month, NASA established a near-Earth object coordinating
office at California's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are objects that are difficult to detect because of
their relatively small size, but are large enough to cause global
effects if one hit the Earth,'' said Donald Yeomans, director of
the new office. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1534EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
