<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DAVIDOW-INTERVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 An Interview with JEFFREY DAVIDOW, U.S. ambassador to Mexico  
 &HT;     (Editors: See also BC-MEXICO-HEROLES-INTERVIEW-NYTSF. To
publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.  By DAN DIAL  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    WASHINGTON, D.C. _ The United States and Mexico are neighbors
with a historic and dynamic relationship that is pulling them
closer every day. But the road to the future has some bilateral
bumps: illegal immigration, consumption and trafficking of illicit
drugs, trade and border issues are just a few. They provide fodder
for political rhetoric in both countries. Yet, in spite of this,
the relationship remains strong.
 &HT;    In separate exclusive interviews, Dan Dial, editor of The News,
in Mexico City, spoke with the two men most knowledgeable on the
subject: JEFFREY DAVIDOW, U.S. ambassador to Mexico, and JESUS
REYES HEROLES, Mexico's ambassador to the United States.
 -0- 
 &HT;    DAN DIAL: You are a respected career diplomat with nearly 30
years experience, including considerable time in Latin America.
Does your posting to Mexico reflect the importance of Mexico to the
United States?
 &HT;    JEFFREY DAVIDOW: Well, I wouldn't put it that way, because I
think Mexico is perceived as being extraordinarily important to the
United States. The contacts that we've had over the last few years,
such as President Clinton's trip to Mexico, were very important. A
very high level of coordination of contact that we've had with
Mexico has been building _ all of this indicates that Mexico is
extremely important to the United States.
 &HT;    Now, in terms of my appointment, I'm just very honored to have
been chosen for the job and to be able to follow people like Jim
Jones and John Negroponte and others who have done a good job
there. I want to do as well as I can.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: During your May confirmation hearing before the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee you demonstrated a broad knowledge on
Mexican and bilateral issues. Once you assume your post, what will
be your most pressing objective?
 &HT;    A: There are multiple objectives which reflect the fact that our
relationship with Mexico is so multifaceted. The obvious thing: We
have a number of areas of focus of concentration, trade being one;
making NAFTA work _ and I do believe NAFTA does work for both
countries.
 &HT;    But obviously, there's continuing trade issues that have to be
confronted. I suspect probably there will always be continuing
trade issues.
 &HT;    Certainly, the issue of immigration is extremely important for
Mexicans. And, in this regard, I pay a lot of attention to how we
as a government deal with Mexicans who want to visit the United
States. We give out over 600,000 visas a year.
 &HT;    We have a new program that we're putting into action, as you
know, the new border crossing cards, the laser visas, which is a
major undertaking.
 &HT;    All issues relating to the frontier and the border are important
to me. Of course narcotics and what I see as improving what has
been a very positive development in terms of increasing levels of
coordination and cooperation over the last few years.
 &HT;    And then there's a multitude of other issues.
 &HT;    Q: One issue that's very important to me is service to the
American community. I do believe that the American embassy has as
its primordial role being responsive to the American community,
protecting American citizens, helping American citizens when
they're in difficulty.
 &HT;    A: This is something I've always taken very seriously.
 &HT;    Q: Operation Casa Blanca, the drug-money laundering
investigation, is still in the news. Given as it was conducted on a
``need-to-know'' basis _ in both countries _ it still strained
bilateral relations. Will the accords signed last week in
Brownsville by Attorneys General Jorge Madrazo and Janet Reno help
avoid this kind of incident in the future?
 &HT;    I think so. I think, though, that agreement was very important.
Actually, the agreement that was signed _ which talks about
increasing levels of coordination or cooperation of information
passing _ is far more reflective of the kind of relationship that
has developed over the last couple of years than Operation Casa
Blanca was.
 &HT;    We have said, and I've said personally, that I think Casa Blanca
was useful in that it caught crooks. And it was going to put people
in jail who have been breaking the law.
 &HT;    And this is important because the money trail is one of the most
sensitive and important elements of the whole narcotics trade. That
goes without saying.
 &HT;    Yet, at the same time, I think mistakes were made. I believe
there could have been better coordination between the government of
the United States, the government of Mexico. There could have been
better coordination (ital) within (end ital) the government of the
United States.
 &HT;    We are addressing those issues. I think the agreement between
Reno and Madrazo is a very important step in that regard.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Recently U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's answer
to a question regarding Chiapas was misunderstood because of a
simple translation error _ ``pressure'' versus ``press'' _ again
causing some allegations of U.S. lack of respect for Mexico's
sovereignty. What is the U.S. position on Chiapas?
 &HT;    A: Well, our position on Chiapas has been a steady one. We do
not pressure the Mexican government. And the Mexican government
knows that. And we have had conversations, many of which have been
introduced by officials of the Mexican government, in which they
talk about Chiapas.
 &HT;    We believe that the problem in Chiapas is one that has to be
resolved through peaceful means. Dialogue, negotiation,
communication is the way to move ahead in resolving an issue which
has both political factors, but this also relates to issues of
social and economic development in the Chiapas region.
 &HT;    We believe that the government of Mexico is making a serious
effort to find a peaceful resolution. We believe that the
government of Mexico is making a serious effort to promote social
and economic development in that part of Mexico, as it is
elsewhere.
 &HT;    The Chiapas problem is, above all, a Mexican problem. It's not a
U.S. problem or a French problem or an Italian problem. And it will
have to be resolved by Mexicans working together in a peaceful way.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: You are a strong supporter of free trade. Some people _ in
Mexico and the United States _ say signing the North American Free
Trade Agreement (NAFTA) was a mistake. What are your views on
NAFTA?
 &HT;    A: Well, I think those who think NAFTA was a mistake are just
dead wrong. Everything that I've been able to witness indicates to
me that both the Mexican and the U.S. economy has profited from
NAFTA.
 &HT;    The flow of trade now is _ I don't have the exact figures, but
it's well over a $150 billion a year. The percentage increases
since NAFTA have been quite striking.
 &HT;    Mexico's ability to recover from the shock of the peso crisis
was immeasurably enhanced by NAFTA, and by the fact that this new,
stronger trading relationship with the United States has made it
easier for Mexico to work itself out of the difficulties caused by
the peso crisis.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: For our readers, Mexicans and Americans, property and
personal crime is so rampant that many of them have been forced to
alter their lifestyle. In fact, former Ambassador James R. Jones
told us last year that truck hijackings pose a serious threat to
future investment in Mexico. Is there anything the United States
can do to help Mexico, particularly regarding U.S. citizens living
there?
 &HT;    A: Well, I think you have to look at this in a couple of ways.
Certainly, the U.S. Embassy and our various consular sections have
an obligation to provide up-to-date information to people visiting
Mexico and living in Mexico.
 &HT;    And we've done that. We have, on a permanent basis, through the
consular information sheet, which is available on the Internet,
available at the embassy or the consulates, and which talks about a
number of these issues of personal security.
 &HT;    Ultimately, personal security, of course, becomes the
responsibility and primary concern of the individual involved. But
we can provide information. We can, it seems to me, help American
citizens when they do get in difficulty, either difficulty with the
law or difficulties with their cars.
 &HT;    I'd like to see the embassy be as responsive as possible in that
regard.
 &HT;    In the larger context, the problem of crime in Mexico is a major
one. I mean, it's one that I think all Mexicans in the Mexican
government understand. There are no easy answers, but it does seem
to me that improving the efficiency of police forces, improving the
efficiency of judicial systems, so that when criminals are
detained, they are quickly judged and prosecuted and sentenced.
 &HT;    All of this requires, on the part of Mexican authorities and
Mexican society, it seems to me, the dedication and even greater
efforts, greater levels of resources, greater focus on the need for
institutional reform in both law enforcement and the judiciary.
 &HT;    And, as I say, it's not an easy problem. I mean, it's not one
that's unique to Mexico. But I think a concerted effort on the part
of the Mexican authorities on the issue of crime is something that
would bring results.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: When discussing Mexico-U.S. bilateral issues, drugs and
corruption always seem to enter the picture. What are your views _
from both sides of the border _ on these issues?
 &HT;    A: Well, on the drug front, this is obviously a major issue in
the relationship, because such a high percentage of the drugs
entering the United States come through Mexico. This is a
development of recent years. Again, it has had significant effect
on the bilateral relationship.
 &HT;    What is important is that we see drugs as a shared problem. I
think to a degree this is happening. The dual concept of divisions
based on supply and demand, divisions based on rich and poor,
divisions based on the United States really being the only cause of
the problem is something of an innocent victim.
 &HT;    I think those kinds of ways of looking at things are changing.
It does seem to me that, in all countries of the region, we're
seeing increased problems of consumption. And I would say probably
in Mexico itself there are in increasing levels of consumption.
 &HT;    It is not an issue that can be dealt with without significant
levels of cooperation _ for long-standing, long-lasting approaches
that will lower the level of the drug trade. Both countries have
got to assume responsibility. Both countries have got to cooperate
with each other and with other countries, and confront the problem
at all levels.
 &HT;    That includes eradication, interdiction, following the money
trail, fighting against money laundering, levels of cooperation
among judicial authorities and police authorities.
 &HT;    And I'd have to say that for, you know, even with all the press
coverage and some of the negative things that we hear on both sides
of the border, having worked on this very closely now for
two-and-a-half years, it does seem to me that the level of
cooperation that we have today, and interaction and understanding
between the U.S. government and the Mexican government is higher
than it's ever been.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: While U.S. President Bill Clinton and his administration seem
to be understanding toward Mexico on major bilateral issues,
Congress seems to take pleasure at ``Mexico bashing.'' Is there
anything you can do about this?
 &HT;    A: First, I think one has to distinguish between the easy
rhetoric and polemic of members of Congress and the really
substantive issues that Congress can deal with. It's quite easy to
give a speech. It's quite easy to take a vote on a subject that is
probably on a bill that is probably never going to get to the point
where it will become law.
 &HT;    It's always easy to talk to the press and sound tough. And this
is a particular feature of political life, and I would dare say on
both sides of the border.
 &HT;    I think if I had to spend all my time correcting the
inappropriate statements of American congressmen and Mexican
congressmen, I'd have to work about 26 hours a day. There's just
not enough time to do that. It's one of the features of democratic
life.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Former Amb. Jones said one of the important tools for an
effective ambassador is ``access'' (which he had) to the top
person. Have/Has President Clinton and/or Secretary Albright
assured you of this kind of access?
 &HT;    Well, you know, I've been working in this job as head of the
Inter American bureau for two-and-a-half years. My relationship
with the secretary of state is, I would say, a close one. We are in
permanent, sometimes almost daily, contact. I've traveled with her
on a large number of trips and I consider her not only my boss, but
my friend. She is a friend I'm proud to have.
 &HT;    With the president, I've traveled with him three times to the
hemisphere _ just in the past year. That was, I think, one of the
most important developments in the U.S. hemispheric policy. And, of
course, I have sat in on numerous meetings with him, have been with
him when he's met with President Zedillo, was with him up in New
York not long ago when he met with President Zedillo up at the
United Nations.
 &HT;    So I feel comfortable that I will have access to those
authorities in Washington who are very much concerned about Mexico.
 &HT;    And I think this will be important and will be a factor not so
much of my personal qualities, whatever they may be or not be, but
the fact that there is a very heavy focus here on our relationship
with Mexico.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Do you think you will have the same level of access to
President Ernesto Zedillo and Secretary of Foreign Relations
Rosario Green?
 &HT;    A: Well, of course, you know, that's a decision for President
Zedillo and Foreign Secretary Green. I've met both of them on
several occasions.
 &HT;    Again, having worked in my current position for two-and-a-half
years, I've had a lot of opportunity to have contact with numerous
Mexican government officials, including both the president and the
foreign secretary. There are many others in the Mexican government
whom I consider colleagues and friends. And I hope we can deepen
that relationship.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: We would like to shift focus now. Can you tell us a little
about you and your family: hobbies, likes, dislikes, etc.?
 &HT;    A: (LAUGHING) It's hard for me to talk about myself. But, you
know, my life has been, for the past 30 years, very much wrapped up
in both my family and my career.
 &HT;    I got married the same year I entered the foreign service, which
was 1969. And our life together as a family has been one of moving
around the world. We've served in seven different foreign countries
in Latin America, in Guatemala and Chile _ twice in Venezuela.
 &HT;    I'm very excited about going to Mexico. We had two daughters.
One was born in our first post, which was Guatemala. The other was
born at our second post, which was Chile. They're both now pursuing
graduate studies and leading their own lives.
 &HT;    And it's a very close family. I think foreign service existence,
where one transports a family from one country to another, promotes
closeness. And that's been great.
 &HT;    My career has been just something that has given me a great deal
of pleasure. I've gotten to travel around the world, meet all sorts
of interesting people and lived in fascinating places. And I get
paid for it! Which I actually appreciate that part of it too.
 &HT;    We're looking very much forward to Mexico City. My wife is an
active participant in community affairs. She always has been,
wherever we've been. We're looking forward to coming to a greater
understanding of Mexico: its art, its culture, its people. We're
very excited.
 &HT;    Q: Once you assume your official duties in Mexico City, do you
plan to carry on with some of the extra-official duties, honorary
president of the American Society and sponsorship of the Annual
Golf &AMP; Tennis Charity Classic for examples, as well?
 &HT;    A: (LAUGHTER) We intend to continue with very active
participation in community affairs. You know, we'll have to talk to
people once we get there to see what we would be involved in.
 &HT;    But we've always felt that the embassy and the ambassador and
the ambassador's spouse not only has a responsibility to be active
in the American community, but it can be a lot of fun too, and
interesting. And so, I think people can assume that we will be
active and visible and participatory.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Is there any message for our readers you would like us to
take back to Mexico?
 &HT;    A: No. No, I don't give messages. We're looking forward to it.
We'll be in Mexico on July 22. And I'll be ready to go to work July
23 in the embassy. And then, of course, I have to wait until I
present my credentials to President Zedillo before I can become
publicly active in Mexico. But I hope that will happen quickly.
 &HT;    We intend to do a lot of traveling in Mexico as well, you know.
We have our consulates that perform an extraordinarily important
function. I want to visit them. I want to visit the major cities. I
want to get around.
 &HT;     c.1998 Dan Dial  
