<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-HEROLES-INTERVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 An Interview with JESUS REYES HEROLES, Mexico's ambassador to the
United States  
 &HT;     (Editors: See also BC-MEXICO-DAVIDOW-INTERVIEW-NYTSF. To
publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.)  By DAN DIAL  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    DAN DIAL: You have been here for eight months now. Is the job
what you expected? I expected an intense, complex and dynamic
bilateral relationship and great interest about Mexico in the U.S.
government. Even with enormous diplomatic challenges to improve
understanding, there have been a few crises along the way.
 &HT;    JESUS REYES HEROLES: What has surprised me is the magnitude of
the relationship and the speed of events, the degree of
misinformation about Mexico in the United States in general, and
the difficulty to reverse an unfavorable situation and prevent it
from becoming a setback for the relationship.
 &HT;    Let me start with the issues that surprised me. The first one,
with which basically you can see the magnitude of the relationship
in terms of intensity and the speed of events, and secondly the
misinformation about Mexico in the U.S. in general, and third, the
difficulty to reverse an unfavorable situation.
 &HT;    Let me dwell on the last two of them very quickly. I have been
very surprised about the lack of enough strategic thinking in the
United States about the relationship with Mexico. If you see what
happened in the eighties and even the early nineties, when NAFTA
(North American Free Trade Agreement) was crafted, there was a lot
of thinking in the United States about why Mexico was important to
the United States, why something like NAFTA was needed to cement
the relationship and to give a different kind of spin to that
relationship.
 &HT;    I think that helped to get NAFTA passed, and that made a lot of
people think about the relationship for quite some time. But now,
if you go around asking think tanks, going over the literature,
asking the people in the universities or in the critical offices of
the administration _ my perception, my very personal perception _
is that they have been doing very little thinking about Mexico, the
relationship, what's going on in Mexico and what does it mean for
the future of this relationship with the United States.
 &HT;    So, I'm trying to enhance and induce more strategic thinking in
the United States about Mexico as much as possible. I think now, as
compared with the past, we have been doing more strategic thinking
about our relationship with the United States in a cooler, more
objective, more academic, more intellectual way than what the
United States has been doing about Mexico.
 &HT;    In that sense, there has been a reverse on those two things
where I think there is a need to do more here, in terms of the
relationship. So that's one point about the misinformation about
Mexico which is stated right there.
 &HT;    Now, regarding the last point, I want to mention _ in relation
to Casa Blanca _ it is very easy to enter into today's world of
almost a virtual reality, where information flows instantly. When
you have something that is a surprise, something, an event that is
surprising, unexpected _ and then with the role of the media,
governments are really handicapped in terms of their capacity to
react. It is expected for them almost to react in the same
information cycle when the original news was announced.
 &HT;    And that's really very complicated, because within the
government, first, there's a fact-finding period that has to be
done. You really need to know exactly what happened, and you don't
want to react to things you thought had happened. You want to react
to things that really happened. So, that fact-finding period takes
some time.
 &HT;    Second, even if you, when you know about the facts that happened
_ take the case of Casa Blanca _ still you need to go and do some
coordination, interagency coordination in any government. That
applies to the U.S. government or to the Mexican government, in
terms of saying, `Well, we have this very, this extraordinary
situation.'
 &HT;    Let's try to figure out what would be the response to this which
would be acceptable for everybody, acceptable or at least so that
it's adequate to the circumstances that we're in right now. Once
you take care of these two periods, fact-finding and internal
coordination, what happens is that you're already missing the
initial information cycle. And it's inevitable for public opinion
to come out and say the government reacted late to the event that
happened.
 &HT;    I find that extremely worrisome. It's not easy to figure out how
to get out of that, not only in terms of what happened in the past,
but even the surprises that we might get in the future. It's
complicated to figure out a mechanism, a strategy to react
instantly or even more speedily to unforeseen situations. And that
is what makes it very complicated, to reverse the unfavorable
situation and to become set up for the relationship. That's a
comment I wanted to make on that.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: How has your experience _ both in the public and private
sectors _ helped you as ambassador, or is this a whole new ball
game?
 &HT;    A: It is a new game in the sense that no other position I have
held, either in the public or private sectors, has been as
challenging or complex, requiring such a diverse array of skills
and resources. At the same time, having been in the private sector
has helped me understand the dynamics of the non-governmental
relations between Mexico and the United States. It has given me
another perspective to better understand this country.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: While U.S. President Bill Clinton and his administration seem
to be understanding toward Mexico on major bilateral issues,
Congress seems to take pleasure at ``Mexico bashing.'' Is there
anything you can do about this?
 &HT;    A: In general terms, your perception is correct. But it is not
that simple. There are some agencies in the Executive branch that
join, or even foster, attacks on Mexico. Just as well, in Congress
there are several congressmen and senators that very openly try to
better understand the issues and avoid easy and irresponsible
positions that blame Mexico.
 &HT;    The real problem is those who want to reap political benefits
from blaming others for their own problems. For them,
Mexico-bashing has become profitable.
 &HT;    We are trying to better inform both Congress and the
administration while at the same time increase the cost of bashing
Mexico. There are several groups in this country, from businesses
to Mexican-American communities, who can take action in that
regard.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What is your biggest challenge here?
 &HT;    A: I think my response follows up from my previous answer.
Promoting a better understanding of Mexico, preventing crisis in
the relationship and dealing with those on Capitol Hill and other
places that extol in attacking Mexico.
 &HT;    I want to institutionalize relations with Congress. The relative
weight of Congress in shaping foreign policy decisions in this
country has been rising rapidly over the past few years. And
everything indicates that it will continue to do so over the next
few years.
 &HT;    And that means that an embassy like the Mexican Embassy has to
have more capacity to be present in Congress, to share information
with them, to respond to the information needs, and, when invited
to do so, to participate in the public debates in topics that
affect Mexico's interests.
 &HT;    And that is simple to say, but it's a complicated thing to do,
because you're talking about 435 congressmen, and 100 senators, all
of whom are constantly up for election. That's maybe another thing
I could add to the surprises. I mean, I thought that they, the U.S.
Congress, was a little bit more stable, if I may use that word. But
that's not the case, they have elections every two years.
 &HT;    It's really a continuously changing, reshaping, reconstituting
body. And that requires an additional effort in that regard. So I
``institutionalized'' relations with Congress, to figure out a
mechanism that could work at being a continuous presence of the
embassy. The goal is to provide them information, to share our
views about the issues with the congressmen, the congressmen who
are interested, so that we can not only anticipate what kind of
legislative decisions might be taken that could affect our
interests and our rights, but even more to actually make them aware
of the areas of opportunity there are if we work together. So I
would give a lot of weight to this as one of my biggest, our
biggest, challenges here.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: You and the SRE consular offices seem to be taking a more
active role in protecting the human rights of Mexican citizens in
the United States. How do you explain this higher profile of an
important bilateral issue?
 &HT;    A: The protection of civil, labor and human rights of Mexicans _
irrespective of their migratory status _ is one of the highest
priorities of Mexican foreign policy. We have tried to better
coordinate the efforts between the consular offices throughout the
country and the Embassy here in Washington.
 &HT;    We have established liaison mechanisms at the border to increase
communication and understanding at the local level while doing the
same with federal authorities here in Washington.
 &HT;    A recent example of this was the establishment of a liaison
mechanism between the embassy and the U.S. attorney general's
office to deal with high visibility cases of police brutality.
 &HT;    We must also defend rights of workers. On the migration issue,
one has to start by making a very blunt distinction between the
issue of undocumented migration, immigration into the United
States, and the issue of legal migration to the United States.
 &HT;    To try to defend or talk on behalf of any kind of undocumented
migration, it's a non-starter. And we never do it. And that's
important, because in Mexico sometimes this is not adequately
understood. The United States has a right to enforce its migration
laws on the border exactly the same way we have the right to
enforce our migration laws on our borders. That's what we do on our
Northern border. That's what we do on our Southern border. Let's
not forget that last year we repatriated to Central America about
100,000 persons from Mexico to Central America.
 &HT;    So that is an area that we have to separate from the area of
legal migration to the United States. And if we don't separate
those two aspects, it's very difficult to talk about the second
one, based upon a more objective, intellectual basis.
 &HT;    On the first issue, undocumented migration to the United States,
what we do is precisely what we stated here. Our worry is to make
sure that when the United States applies its migration law, at the
same time the civil and human rights of our Mexican nationals are
fully respected in the United States. All of these activities of
protection are being spelled out in elements to be answered.
 &HT;    On the other aspect _ legal migration _ that's where we have a
big opportunity to work together. From issues as simple and
important as the change of the border crossing guards to the new
laser visas, where Mexico has been very active in promoting the way
it's done. The U.S. State Department does it in a way that
minimizes the problems to the population in Mexico and that it does
it at the minimal cost for the Mexicans so as to minimize the
negative impact into the border communities.
 &HT;    As for more complicated issues, for example, let's consider
programs of temporary guest workers in the United States. As long
as they fulfill conditions that are required both by the Mexican
government, some of them, and some others by the United States
government and public opinion _ like in our case that Mexican
workers are not exploited.
 &HT;    That means that they are being paid and treated according to the
corresponding laws in the United States. And from the United
States, that any kind of guest worker program warrants that the
people who come work here will return to Mexico and will not stay.
 &HT;    By the way, we have a program like that with Canada, which has
been working very well for the last 12 to 15 years. And there are
no complaints, either of exploitation or about Mexicans staying in
Canada. So this is simply an example of the kind of things that we
would have, of opportunities we have on the legal migration area.
 &HT;    But to be able to discuss this in the way we're talking about
now we have to make sure that we never suggest _ I mean this is
essential _ that we are not in any sense making a case for
undocumented migration to the United States. It's in the best
interests of Mexico to make sure that at no moment is there an
interpretation that we are proposing undocumented migration to the
United States. Although we want the rights _ the civil and human
rights of all our migrants _ to be respected when the United States
actually applies its laws at the border.
 &HT;    And in that regard, we are taking, sort of backing some actions
by the civil society of the United States to protect the workers'
rights of Mexican nationals who are legally working in the United
States, they are documented workers. A very brief example is the
filing of the class action suit against the De Coster Egg Farm.
This is an example of the kind of things that we have to be aware
that exist. We have to act on them and we are acting on them.
Because if we want to move in terms of legal migration, we also
have to make sure that the Mexican workers who come to the United
States are going to be respected in terms of workers' rights.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: How would you sum up the state of bilateral relations between
Mexico and the United States?
 &HT;    A: I think that at this point we are undergoing a very difficult
stage in the relationship. Casa Blanca did a lot of damage to the
spirit of trust and cooperation we had built for several years. At
the same time, it is clear that nobody benefits from a sour
bilateral environment. I would say that currently we are in a
``damage repair'' mood.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What will it take to recover from the damage to relations
caused by Operation Casa Blanca?
 &HT;    A: We can only return to the previous cooperative environment if
we can recover mutual respect and mutual trust. I have said that we
need three things for a good bilateral relations: full disclosure,
total cooperation to search for joint solutions and no surprises.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Recently U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's answer
to a question about Chiapas was misunderstood because of the
translation and caused an uproar in Mexico. Do you think the
Mexican press and/or politicians are overly sensitive to what they
perceive as ``foreign intervention''?
 &HT;    One of the negative consequences of Casa Blanca was it created
an unfavorable environment for Mexico-U.S. relations. It increased
our sensitivities and at the same time stirred anti-Mexican
sentiments here. In this atmosphere, any misunderstanding tends to
be magnified.
 &HT;    On the other hand, we must stress that domestic questions, such
as Chiapas, can only be dealt with by Mexicans ourselves.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What is your opinion of U.S. Ambassador-designate Jeffrey
Davidow?
 &HT;    A: I have established an excellent personal relationship with
him. I am sure he will be a very successful U.S. ambassador in
terms of contributing to better communication and cooperation
between our governments.
 &HT;    I offered a farewell dinner for him. We had a very interesting
group: (Jesus and Regina Reyes Heroles, Jeffrey and Joan Davidow,
Thomas and Donna McLarty, Jim and Toril Dobbins, Paul and Diane
Begala, Leon and Lynn Fuerth, Kay Bailey Hutchison, Xavier and
Carolina Becerra, Jim and Olivia Jones, John and Diana Negroponte,
Jorge Castro-Valle, Charles and Kathleen Manatt, Lee H. and Nancy
Hamilton and Christopher Dodd). We also had several congressmen.
 &HT;    We see his nomination as a positive sign. After more than a year
without a U.S. ambassador in Mexico, his arrival is very important.
His previous position makes him very knowledgeable about Mexican
issues. He has worked with several Mexican officials from that
position.
 &HT;    He also has knowledge of contemporary Mexico, sensitivities and
a sense of humor. I think any future ambassador to Mexico needs to
have those three basic characteristics. He has to have a good
knowledge of the bilateral relationship.
 &HT;    And he has it, as undersecretary of Inter-American Affairs he
knows that very well. He speaks Spanish and that's very useful. And
there are very few individuals in the United States who have such
as good a knowledge of the bilateral issues right now as does
Davidow.
 &HT;    The second characteristic the next ambassador to Mexico has to
have, is to be aware of our sensitivities, especially on some
topics that are very, very key to Mexicans. Jeffrey Davidow has
shown over time that he has that sensitivity. He's very careful in
terms of the way he presents his ideas.
 &HT;    That doesn't mean he compromises on the issues, that kind of
thing. But he knows how to go, what kind of terrain he's stepping
on, and on that he's very good.
 &HT;    So we are lucky because he's a sensible man.
 &HT;    And third, I think that any ambassador, the next ambassador to
Mexico needs to have a good sense of humor. And he has an excellent
sense of humor, because it's magical to really, you know, cope with
the stress and cope with the kind of criticism that any U.S.
ambassador to Mexico gets. You need to have a good sense of humor,
and Jeff Davidow, among other qualities, has a very good sense of
humor. So that will help him. That will help Joanna, his wife, and
that will certainly help everybody to really have a smoother
relationship. So I couldn't be more pleased about the nomination of
Jeff Davidow. Not the nomination now, the appointment of Jeff
Davidow as the next ambassador to Mexico.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: If asked, what advice would you give him?
 &HT;    A: I would not give him any advice. I want to be very sure that
I never have some ``advice.'' But I think that he coincides on the
three principles that I have been repeating, the basic operation of
... having a good relationship between the United States and
Mexico. Which are basically that we need to have full disclosure of
all our areas.
 &HT;    We need to know exactly what the other party thinks about each
and every issue of the bilateral agenda. If we keep some things to
ourselves, it complicates things. We don't get to have a real,
direct communication.
 &HT;    We need to prevent surprises as much as possible, not to have
surprises, which is a very important exercise. There are two kinds
of surprises: There are surprises which are preventable and there
are others which are not. We will, therefore, have some surprises
in the future, because we cannot foresee everything with full
precision. Therefore, there will be some things that will happen in
the future which we didn't have the capacity to anticipate.
 &HT;    But it is our responsibility to try to anticipate as many events
as possible _ future events that could become a surprise _ because
surprises damage the relationship very, very much.
 &HT;    And the third principle is that we _ with the kind of problems
we face _ require that we look for joint solutions to these
problems. I mean, the United States is not going to solve the
problem of drug trafficking by themselves. We have to do it
together. It's a problem for the U.S.; it's a problem for Mexico.
And we have to come out to solve it together.
 &HT;    The problem of poverty in Mexico requires the cooperation of the
United States as a country, as an economy _ within the NAFTA
context _ to actually make the North American economy grow.
 &HT;    Solving the problem of migration; that's something we can't
solve by ourselves. That's something the U.S. can't solve by
themselves. It's something that requires a joint solution. So this
is the third point. We have to go out and search for joint
solutions to our problems, and also to face the challenges and the
opportunities that we have.
 &HT;    The best example of it was NAFTA. And in the case of NAFTA, we
really came out, sat down at the table and discussed how to get the
most benefit out of our neighborhood, in terms of trading, with
each other.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Under the new Dual Nationality Law, Mexican citizens living
in the United States can vote in the year 2000 elections.
Considering the sheer numbers, how are you preparing for this?
 &HT;    It is ``non-loss'' of Mexican nationality, not ``dual
nationality.'' There is an important difference between nationality
and citizenship. This will have an effect once the possibility for
Mexicans to vote abroad is enacted, since people will not be able
to vote in two countries. So far, the possibility to vote abroad
has not been enacted, since Congress has not passed legislation in
that regard.
 &HT;    Some groups are pressuring for Congress to deal with this issue
as soon as possible, but apparently technical obstacles may not be
solved in order for us to have the legislation and its
implementation ready for the elections in 2000.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What has been your most satisfying moment as ambassador here?
 &HT;    A: Well, in terms of my most satisfying moment as an ambassador
here, I think there has not been just one moment. But it has been
related with some letters that I have been getting from different
people. Some of them important.
 &HT;    After my visit to the border where we were working to resolve
some of the issues there, like helping to make the U.S. government
realize it was not convenient to establish the exit, the pilot case
for exit controls. And they decided to move it away. I got several
very helpful letters from people on the border saying they didn't
think when I visited them there that something like that could
happen. But at the end of the day we were successful.
 &HT;    Or, especially letters _ letters from some Mexicans who have
been helped by us _ it's not my merit by the way. I want to make
that very clear _ that I have been helped. I have received
assistance from our consulate personnel and our diplomatic
consulars when they are in trouble in the United States. That's
part of our protection and duties.
 &HT;    I think that's how to be motivating and encouraging. It's always
a very human thing to see. If you go to the border, you see these
people who are being caught every day _ captured every day by the
border patrol, and how frightened they are, and how much they are
willing to risk because they want to get to the United States to
get a job. And then, the perils that they go through when they are
actually repatriated to Mexico.
 &HT;    Then when some of them actually write you and tell you they
really appreciated the help of our consular personnel, it's
gratifying to me and it's especially gratifying to the personnel of
the Mexican Foreign Service, who are working so hard on these
issues. And thirdly, I have been getting some communiques from
people in Congress that do appreciate sometimes the efforts we make
to overcome this gap of information, and this problem of
misinformation that I mentioned in response to other questions.
 &HT;    They realize that it is the worst enemy to the bilateral
relationship, for the future of the bilateral relationship, this
misinformation and incorrect perceptions. Anything that we can do
to actually know each other, to talk to each other more directly,
more candidly _ that would be, that would be indeed _ in the best
interests of the two nations.
 &HT;    So it's not one single moment. It's this kind of moment, I have
one every week, or something like that, that are really very, very
rewarding from the position of being ambassador to the United
States.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Washington, D.C., is quite different from Mexico City. How do
you and your family find life here?
 &HT;    A: Washington is a very, a very, _ first of all _ an interesting
city. I hadn't had the chance to know Washington by coming here for
business before. So I sort of didn't know the downtown area. And I
hadn't had the chance to explore the suburbs of Washington. That
has been a very pleasant discovery.
 &HT;    Washington is a city where you can combine both a very intense
and challenging professional life with family life. I mean, you
have more control about your time schedules in general. It's not
that you don't work a lot; you work a lot everyday. But you know,
more or less, at what time you are going to end your day. That's
with few exceptions. That's one thing.
 &HT;    Second, you can do some family life during the week _ that's
very pleasant. People do that; people get together; people visit
each other. You have the chance to stay with your family or to do
things with your family during the week. Washington in that regard
is a very warm and very humane city. We are certainly enjoying it
in that regard.
 &HT;    I think we have only seen the tip of the iceberg now. Everyday
we come out with the assurance that we will find something else
that is going to make it even more enjoyable to be here. And this
is a very convenient combination a top job which requires hard work
and, at the same time, the capacity to have some time for
ourselves, personally and in terms of the family.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Do you have children here?
 &HT;    A: Yes, we have three kids _ a daughter who's 16 years old, a
son 14, and a daughter 8 years old. So we have the whole array of
ages, from teen-agers to quasi teen-agers and to a little kid that
can cope with the other quasi- and full teenagers. (LAUGHING) So we
have the full array.
 &HT;     c.1998 Dan Dial  
