A8451 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     07-29 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL-TOWN COOKBOOKS OFFER BIG FLAVOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every city and town in Texas has its own cookbook. I think it
goes along with getting a charter.
</P>
<P>
   The garden club or the Junior League or a bunch of guys with big
smokers on wheels put together pages of recipes, get them published
and sell them to buy new uniforms for the cheerleaders, or maybe
new hooks for the hook-and-ladder truck down at the volunteer fire
station.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, these books are genuinely fascinating, full
of good food, or at least good intentions.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem is finding them. Some find their way to big
distributors that sell to the Barnes &AMP; Nobles of the world, but
most just sit around on dusty shelves at the chamber of commerce or
the downtown bank.
</P>
<P>
   I like what the Community Garden Club of Johnson City did.
Members painted a sign extolling the virtues of their book and put
it right there on U.S. 281, near the city limits.
</P>
<P>
   The new book is called ``Second Helping, Potluck on the
Pedernales.''
</P>
<P>
   The first helping was served up in 1981 and won the McIlhenny
Company's Tabasco Community Cookbook contest for the Southwest
region. When the members of the garden club cookbook committee
entered the contest, they promised to do another book if they won.
</P>
<P>
   One thing they apparently wanted to get out of the way first was
the geography of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pedernales River is one of the last free-flowing rivers in
Texas with no major dams,'' the book explains. ``The river bisects
the LBJ heartland, rising in southeast Kimble County, flowing
eastward for 106 miles through Gillespie County, central Blanco
County and onward to northern Hays County, finally joining the
Colorado River in western Travis County.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedernales, the book explains, is pronounced ``Purd'nalis.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the joys in these kinds of cookbooks is the simplicity of
the recipes. There is no shame in opening cans. If you need a
sauce, Campbell soups work just fine.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of unusual chapters in this newest book.
After the normal sections on appetizers and soups and sandwiches,
main dishes and vegetables, is ``Look Who's Cooking? Macho Meals
Men Make, Including Wild Stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an additional chapter on ``Tried-and-True Recipes Fifty
Years or Older,'' and ``Jarring Ideas, Puttin' Up Advice, Hints,
Proverbs and a Few Lies.''
</P>
<P>
   The real charm of the book is in the small notes the
contributors sent along with their recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Ola Matus, for example, wrote this note above her chicken
enchilada offering: ``My daughter, Suzanne, won first place at the
District 4-H Food Show in Austin with this recipe. She was 13 years
old and received this recipe from her Aunt Sharon Matus in Texas
City. Gov. Ann Richards was the speaker at the food show that day.
She was then Commissioner Richards. We were very impressed with her
speech; she said, `I am going home this very night and make these
enchiladas.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that Penny Mengers sent in the same recipe.
She said: ``I served this to Billy's family and friends when he
graduated from the Air Force Academy in 1987 when I was still Penny
Liles. It has become a family favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the recipe:
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN ENCHILADAS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 6 _ 6 chicken breasts _ 2 cans cream of chicken soup _
16-ounce container sour cream _ 2 4-ounce cans green chiles _ 1
onion, chopped _ 1 cup chicken broth _ 1 pound sharp Cheddar
cheese, grated _ 12 flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   Boil chicken in water to cover until fork-tender; reserve broth.
Cool, chop into small pieces. Combine soup, sour cream, chiles,
onion and 1 cup broth. Line 13-by-9-by-2-inch casserole with small
amount of soup mixture. Dip tortillas in chicken broth, fill with
small amount of chicken and cheese. Roll. Place in casserole. Cover
all with rest of soup mixture. Bake at 350 degrees for 30 minutes.
The last 10 minutes, add the rest of the grated cheese on top.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 975 calories, 59 grams fat, 54
grams carbohydrates, 56 grams protein, 193 milligrams cholesterol,
2,172 milligrams sodium, 54 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman is a food columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Write him at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort
Worth, TX 76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web site:
www.star-telegram.com/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1552EDT &QL; 
