<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8453 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     07-29 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKSTONE HOTEL'S BLACK-BOTTOM PIE, CHOCOLATE MOUSSE ANGEL FOOD
CAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Services clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am always amazed at what readers come up with from their
recipe boxes.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, a reader called looking for the recipe
for the black-bottom pie that was once served at the old Blackstone
Hotel in Fort Worth. (The Blackstone is under renovation and will
reopen next year.)
</P>
<P>
   Since the hotel has been closed for at least 10 years, I was
sure this was an impossible request. But no.
</P>
<P>
   Bertha McAfee of Fort Worth used to live near one of the mothers
of one of the Blackstone's chefs. In the early 1950s, she gave
Bertha the recipe for the pie. Bertha writes that everyone loves
the pie _ one friend said he thought it had medicinal properties.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE BLACKSTONE HOTEL'S BLACK-BOTTOM PIE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 2 pies (Serves 12)
</P>
<P>
   Black layer:
</P>
<P>
   2 (9-inch) baked pie shells
</P>
<P>
   2 cups scalded whole milk
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 egg yolks, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar, flour, cocoa and salt. Add to the scalded milk;
blend well. Cook and stir constantly over medium heat until thick.
Remove from heat and add beaten eggs. Return to heat and cook,
stirring constantly until thick, about 2 minutes. Add butter and
cool, stirring often. Add vanilla. Pour into the two pie shells.
</P>
<P>
   Rum layer:
</P>
<P>
   2 envelopes Knox unflavored gelatin sprinkled over 1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups scalded whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 egg yolks, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   6 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Rum extract, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar, flour and salt and slowly add to the scalded
milk. Cook and stir constantly over medium heat until thick. Remove
from heat and add egg yolks. Return to heat. Cook and stir about 1
minute. Remove from heat and add gelatin mixture. Stir well to
blend gelatin into pie filling. Cool, stirring often to keep
mixture smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Beat 6 whites until stiff but not dry. Add 1 cup sugar, 2
tablespoons at a time, just as you would with meringue. Fold pie
filling into egg whites. Add rum flavoring.
</P>
<P>
   Pile onto chocolate layer and chill.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish:
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate curls
</P>
<P>
   Top with whipped cream and chocolate curls before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 442 calories, 18 grams fat, 62
grams carbohydrates, 10 grams protein, 117 milligrams cholesterol,
361 milligrams sodium, 36 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An angelic dessert: Gail Beathard saw our request for a
refrigerated angel food cake/chocolate mousse confection and
e-mailed the recipe she uses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE MOUSSE ANGEL FOOD CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
<P>
   Cake:
</P>
<P>
   1 angel food cake mix
</P>
<P>
   Follow instructions on box for making the cake. Turn cake pan
upside down on a bottleneck and leave an hour to cool. Remove from
cake pan and with a serrated knife, slice horizontally to make two
layers. (Or the cake can be cut into squares to be layered in a
trifle bowl with the mousse.)
</P>
<P>
   Mousse:
</P>
<P>
   2 (4 ounces each) bars German Chocolate
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream, whipped
</P>
<P>
   Melt chocolate with water. Beat until smooth and add vanilla.
Cool only to room temperature. Fold into cream whipped firm, but
not too stiff.
</P>
<P>
   Put half of the mousse on bottom layer (the top of the cake
turned over, making the bottom layer). Put on top layer and cover
both top and sides with remaining mousse. Or, the cake can be cut
into large squares, and layered with the mousse in a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 373 calories, 22 grams fat, 43
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 55 milligrams cholesterol,
285 milligrams sodium, 53 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Request:
</P>
<P>
   Bill Harris of Richland Hills, Texas, bought some sugar-free
peanut brittle while on vacation in Ohio from some Amish vendors.
He'd like to make some at home. Does anyone have a recipe?
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
column appears each Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy,
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
