<SLUG> BC-SUMMERDRINKS-TEX </SLUG>
 
fROM KAVA SODAS TO SNAPPLE SMOOTHIES TO EXTREME SPORTS DRINKS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have one advantage this summer over the heat wave of 1980. We
have a whole new segment of drinks with which to quench our thirst,
from organic sodas to flavored iced coffees to a super-macho sports
drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really identified the alternative beverage audience about
10 years ago,'' says Gary Hemphill, vice president of Beverage
Marketing Corp., a consulting and information group for suppliers
and manufacturers of soft drinks. ``Colas, while still growing as a
category, are losing some share to sports drinks, premium waters,
bottled tea, premium and natural soda, nutraceuticals.''
Nutraceuticals are beverages souped up with herbs or extracts, such
as Saint Johnswort, kava or ginseng.
</P>
<P>
   Demographically, Hemphill sees the market for alternative drinks
as 20- and 30-somethings, generally college-educated with a little
higher-than-average income. They prefer to buy the drinks cold.
Women, particularly, like the ``health halo'' of many of the new
drinks.
</P>
<P>
   David Podeschi, vice president for food for Southland Corp.,
sees the market as broad and growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something for almost everyone in some segment of the
market,'' Podeschi says. ``I would say that women buy the sports
bottles of water. Men like the larger sizes, and they prefer the
wide-mouth bottles. The segment has experienced explosive growth
since 1990 and 1991, and I think it's going to continue to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a toast to the hot cool drinks this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Cruz Sparkling Ginger Ale: Certified organic (no
artificial flavor, no preservatives, no caffeine), about $1.19.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's Premium Ginger Brew: Jamaican style (strong) ginger ale,
about $1.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Total Sport: ``Extreme thirst quencher'' fortified with
vitamins A, C, E and ginseng extract and lemon-lime, about $1.39,
supermarkets and convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   Cappuccino Coolers: Flavored powders turn cold milk into French
vanilla or hazelnut coolers, about $1.99 in supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Kogee Iced Latte: Certified organic, decaffeinated coffee blend,
about $1.39.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal Tonics: Herb-infused drinks include a Relaxation Cocktail
with kava and an Energy Elixir with ginseng and guarana,
$1.29-$1.79, General Nutrition Centers.
</P>
<P>
   Whipper Snapple: Fruit smoothies in orange dream, peach mango
and strawberry banana flavors, approximately $1.25 for one, $4.19
for four-packs, supermarkets and convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   V8 Splash: Vegetable drink brand branches out to combinations
including strawberry kiwi, about $1 at supermarkets and convenience
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Twister: Tropicana combinations include ruby grapefruit and
tangerine juice, about $1 at supermarkets and convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   Mega Mountain Twists: Kool-Aid branches out with
strawberry-flavor lemonade, about $3 supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Light Tropical Passions: The powdered-drink basic
punches up its line with flavors such as watermelon-strawberry,
about $3, supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Country Time Lem'N Berry Sippers: Lemonade gets a shot of
strawberry, about $3, supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Sky's Dr Becker: Organic knockoff of the Texas favorite,
about 39 cents.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
