<P>
   MEDITATION-SPACES (Undated) _ ``You don't need a separate room
for meditation,'' Diane von Furstenberg said recently. ``I meditate
every morning in my bed for a half hour before I get up.'' Still,
when the designer moved her showroom and offices to an enormous
carriage house in the West Village last year, one space became her
yoga room. Ms. Von Furstenberg is one of many people of means who
has recently dedicated a room to pursue meditation. By Bob Morris.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE-MAN-APARTMENT (New York) _ Balls of blue paint sail and
splatter. The players catch marshmallows in their mouths and spit
chewed sandwiches onto the stage of the Astor Place Theater in New
York during a typical Blue Man Group performance. It's art as a
kind of graduate-level kindergarten. But when head Blue Man, Chris
Wink, gets home, the scene changes dramatically. Wink, with his
wife Jen Graffam-Wink, a painter, have made their new 800 square
foot apartment in a landmark building on Lafayette Street a
peaceful escape: a holiday from Mr. Wink's work. Call it
light-Blue, like the tones of much of its pacific palette. By
Kimberly Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   STILGOE-LANDSCAPE (Undated) _ John Stilgoe, professor of
landscape history at Harvard, is part of a new flowering of
interest in looking at how culture shapes the wide, mundane world
around us. His evocative new book, ``Outside Lies Magic: Regaining
History and Awareness in Everyday Places'' (Walker), is a clarion
call to what he calls, almost mystically, ``exploration'' _
wandering on foot or bike, in search not of cardiovascular fitness
but of mental agility. Ultimately, it's about becoming the
proverbial person on whom nothing is lost. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-KITCHEN (Undated) _ Ten years ago, I brought my family to
rural Nebraska and built a farmstead from scratch. We bought an
abandoned house for $350 and moved it onto the land, but some
things we had to build: a machine shed, a garage and _ a summer
kitchen. The reason our little building in the backyard is called a
summer kitchen is that it's the perfect place to make tomato sauce
and at the same time enjoy the rattle of cottonwood leaves while
dozing in a hammock. By Robert Welsch.
</P>
