<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA WALKS A TIGHTROPE BETWEEN TECHNOLOGY AND SAFETY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until recently, whenever I heard the word ``recall,'' I thought
of cars. My dad would never buy a new model during the first year
of production. He said that they needed time to work the bugs out.
Quite often, he was right. More frequently than we like to
acknowledge, new cars are recalled for things as minor as a gauge
not working properly or as major as the brakes locking up or the
fuel tank exploding on impact.
</P>
<P>
   But now, when I hear the word ``recall,'' I think of the Food
and Drug Administration. It's gotten so bad that some critics have
proposed that the new FDA slogan should be: ``What doesn't kill you
makes you sicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Viagra and its potentially dangerous side effects for heart
patients is just a Popsicle on an iceberg. A recent Associated
Press article on the subject said: ``Almost as many prescription
drugs were yanked off the U.S. market in the past 10 months as were
banned in the entire previous decade. One longtime FDA
pharmacologist told The Associated Press that she just left the
agency in frustration with pressure to skim over safety concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that's just a little different than Mama blowing on your
soup to make sure it's not too hot, isn't it? If Mama doesn't blow
long enough, you burn your tongue, but if the FDA approves a drug
with serious safety concerns, people could die.
</P>
<P>
   Every drug has potential side effects. Many people are allergic
to the widely used antibiotic penicillin, for example. However,
four patients died and eight others required liver transplants
before the painkiller Duract was banned. Granted, the FDA issued a
warning with its approval, but there were many safer competitors on
the market. Was Duract worth approving in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   The blood-pressure drug, Posicor, caused hundreds of problems
and several deaths. The diet medications Fenfluramine and Redux
caused heart damage in many patients. The antihistamine Seldane
interacted negatively with the commonly prescribed antibiotic
erythromycin. It is not clear that any of those drugs was clearly
superior to proven drugs on the market. Each of them was recalled
after thousands of patients had received prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are under a lot of pressure from patients to prescribe
the latest ``wonder drug.'' Pharmaceutical companies target
patients with aggressive advertisements touting the benefits of
their new drugs. Patients ask for drugs by name now, instead of
simply depending on the doctor's recommendations. Being an informed
consumer is good, as long as you have ALL the information.
Obviously, there are some things that those ads aren't telling us.
</P>
<P>
   Medical science is rapidly evolving, and far more people are
being saved than killed by legal drugs. Still, it only takes one
fatality to be statistically significant if you're the one.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they shouldn't even use the word ``recall'' for drugs.
After all, how do you return a swallowed pill?
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
