<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THENEGOTIATOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU'LL LONG FOR A `NEGOTIATOR' TO GET YOU OUT OF THIS ONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Samuel L. Jackson is the most insolent of actors. Even his
softest statements are peppered with the venom of threat, so it
makes all the sense in the world to cast him as a man whose talent,
and whose job, is talking people out of something.
</P>
<P>
   That's what he does in ``The Negotiator.'' And outside of his
work in ``Pulp Fiction,'' it would be hard to imagine a better role
for Jackson. Imagine if Sylvester Stallone, who walked away from
the role, had done it; odds are that a hostage-taker would come out
of the building just to get a clearer idea of what words were
trying to force their way out of Stallone's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when you see the poster for ``The Negotiator,'' with
Jackson and his co-lead, Kevin Spacey, sporting matching bad
hairpieces, you kinda wonder when the star of the movie is going to
show up. Despite their gifts, Jackson and Spacey haven't exactly
lit up the screen like leading men. They are sublime character
actors, but the generic action-movie setting of ``The Negotiator''
is unlikely to earn them a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that ``The Negotiator'' isn't nearly a
good enough movie for either of them. Few actors understand the
weight and power of language as Jackson and Spacey do. (If you
close your eyes, you can actually hear the smirk on Spacey's face.)
The most enjoyable scene in ``The Negotiator'' plays to the actors'
strengths. After Jackson humiliates a befuddled negotiator _ you
can see the guy's eyes spinning like pinwheels _ Spacey expertly
glides into the movie and takes over. Spacey's gleaming confidence
leads him to bask in his own magnificence.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is Danny, the best negotiator on the Chicago police
force, who is so crudely set up as the fall guy in a
police-corruption investigation that you wonder how the cast
managed to keep a straight face while he's booked and indicted.
Faced with the prospect of prison, Danny flips the script and
stages a hostage situation of his own. He barges into police
headquarters and points a gun at the lead investigator on his case
(J.T. Walsh, wasted in the last performance before his untimely
death) and demands that Chris Sabian (Spacey) come in and negotiate
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Danny wants Sabian because Sabian is not a member of his own
precinct; he doesn't trust any of the cops that he works with. If
only ``The Negotiator'' had been made on a smaller scale, so that
real tension could have been generated. Perhaps in a lower-budget
movie, we might have been forced to wonder whether Danny really
were on the take. But ``Armageddon'' has more ambiguity than ``The
Negotiator.'' We know that Danny is too heroic ever to have
considered taking a payoff. (A dawdling opening in which he
outfoxes a sweaty, stubbly kidnapper spells it out for us.) But the
only question in this movie is which of the weaselly co-stars will
be tricked into confessing by the leads, who have such fluency and
command that they seem to be members of a better, smarter race.
</P>
<P>
   Director F. Gary Gray's talent is manufacturing chemistry.
Certainly, no one who has seen ``Friday'' can accuse him of being a
filmmaker _ to his credit, you probably paid more to get in than he
spent making it _ but the performers connected in a likably raw,
lowdown way. And in ``Set It Off,'' the actresses rise above the
shamelessness of the concept; when they fired up a joint on a
rooftop, there is a true warmth and affection that the script never
provides. But in ``The Negotiator,'' Gray seems to be auditioning
to direct the next ``Die Hard'' rip-off. It has the faceless
hackery of a Richard Donner movie and, like those films, it feels
way too long. (At nearly two hours and 20 minutes, it is too long.)
</P>
<P>
   Gray does get in a few good scenes, particularly an early one in
which a bunch of happy, drunken party animals stumble through a
step-dance version of the old Electric Slide. There's also a sense
of resentment of Danny's skill which, in a better movie, might
register as a rationale for setting him up. (Danny may be a decent
man, but he's not humble.) The assemblage of undistinguished stunts
is just boring, and a propensity for this explosion-by-the-yard
stuff may suggest why Warner Bros. has had such a surfeit of
clunkers; the flying shards of glass could be from ``Batman &AMP;
Robin'' or ``Lethal Weapon 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Spacey triumph where they can, but the sad fact is
that a movie of this kind wastes actors who have pride, wit and
aplomb. They are crushed beneath an anonymous juggernaut such as
``The Negotiator,'' crushed like the broken glass under the
stuntmen's Vibram soles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Negotiator'' is rated R for violence and adult language.
</P>
<P>
   Film: The Negotiator
</P>
<P>
   Score: 2 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Samuel L. Jackson, Kevin Spacey
</P>
<P>
   Director: F. Gary Gray
</P>
<P>
   Length: 139 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
