<HEADLINE>
BOOKS TO READ ON SUMMER VACATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Good Fences''
</P>
<P>
   By Erika Ellis
</P>
<P>
   Random House, 216 pages, $22
</P>
<P>
   THE AUTHOR: First we had the Cosbys and the Jeffersons. Now,
Erika Ellis introduces us to the Spaders _ Tom, Hilary, Stormy and
Tommytwo _ an.MDNM/ upwardly mobile black family from Lovejoy, Ill.
Ellis lives in Santa Monica, Calif., with her husband. This is her
first book.
</P>
<P>
   THE PLOT: Tom Spader, an ambitious black lawyer, propels himself
to fame and fortune when he successfully defends a white slumlord
who has committed arson, killing two sleeping black teen-agers. The
price: his soul.
</P>
<P>
   MOST MEMORABLE CHARACTER: Tom's dutiful wife, Mabel, goes about
hiding the ``Jet'' magazines because Tom thinks it best. She makes
sure, with one exception, that all the maids are minority,
preferably black, because that's what Tom wants. She stands by her
man even after he commits arson to prevent white flight.
</P>
<P>
   APPROXIMATE READING TIME: If triple-digit heat doesn't lull you
to sleep, can be read in one sluggish weekend.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by GRACIE BONDS STAPLES
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
