<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-US-REAX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHNIC CHINESE URGE ACTION IN INDONESIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Chinese and Indonesian organizations in the San
Francisco area are urging the U.S. government and the United
Nations to condemn violence against ethnic Chinese in Indonesia,
including the reported gang rapes of women and young girls.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the economic crisis and democracy demonstrations in
Indonesia made world headlines, the upheaval culminating in
hundreds of deaths and the downfall of President Suharto after 33
years in power.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the violence was aimed at Indonesia's 8 million
ethnic Chinese. During weeks of looting, rioting and arson attacks,
hundreds of Chinese women and young girls were gang-raped,
survivors and human rights observers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were silent when they looted our businesses and burned our
property,'' said John Oei of San Francisco. ``But we can't stand it
when our sisters have been raped.''
</P>
<P>
   Oei, who works as an insurance broker, helped organize the
Indonesian Chinese American Network (Icanet) earlier this month to
bring attention to the ethnic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Icanet is leading a petition drive urging Congress and the
United Nations to condemn the rights violations. The group also is
calling on the United States to cut off military aid to Indonesia,
an Asian nation of 210 million people, until conditions improve.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-Chinese violence has resonated beyond the estimated
12,000 to 15,000 Indonesian Chinese in the San Francisco area, Oei
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has created a furor among the overseas Chinese all
over,'' said San Francisco attorney Edward Liu, who helped start a
Web site (www.huaren.org) to keep track of developments. ``We're
getting hits from Mauritius, Norway, South America and, of course,
Southeast Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty Chinese organizations in the San Francisco area are
helping to collect signatures for the petition and the topic has
dominated Chinese newspapers and radio shows, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Board of Supervisors passed a resolution last
week, co-sponsored by Supervisors Mabel Teng and Leland Yee, urging
Congress to call for an investigation into the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Although the worst violence took place over a three-day period
in May, Oei said reports of rapes persist. Chinese continue to live
in fear as the political situation remains unstable.
</P>
<P>
   ``My relatives live in terror,'' Oei said. ``If they go out in
the street and look Chinese, they could be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of Indonesia's economy sparked violence, both
against the government and prosperous ethnic Chinese
businesspeople.
</P>
<P>
   An Indonesian government agency has said it was investigating
468 reported rapes of ethnic Chinese women after riots erupted in
May.
</P>
<P>
   The National Unity Development Board said it had interviewed
many victims, their families and witnesses. Some victims testified
that they had been raped in front of their parents, said Rosita
Noer, chairwoman of the board. A number had been hospitalized, many
had been traumatized, and at least one later committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has given Indonesia more than $1 billion in
military aid in the last 25 years, according to Ben Terrall, San
Francisco coordinator of the East Timor Action Network, a
human-rights organization.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries have shared close trade relations despite
human rights problems in Indonesia, and the Clinton administration
has supported International Monetary Fund efforts to stabilize the
Indonesian economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1613EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
