<SLUG> BC-BRIBERY-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER LAWMAN ADMITS BRIBERY, AGREES TO HELP PROSECUTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Robert Rodriguez, 32, a former Webb County
deputy sheriff here, pleaded guilty Wednesday to helping a suspect
who was facing cocaine charges bribe a district attorney's
investigator in an effort to keep the accused's record clean.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors cleared the way for Rodriguez to tell a
grand jury all he knows about alleged criminal activity at the Webb
County DA's office.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, outlined in a hearing before U.S. District Judge
George Kazen, follows recent guilty pleas by a former state
district judge who bribed DA officials to fix the outcome of drug
cases and a sheriff's department employee who sold crime
information illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors could recommend leniency in sentencing the
defendants, depending on how well they cooperate with a federal
probe of the district attorney's office and the Webb County
sheriff's department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dead serious about pursuing this investigation as
expeditiously as we can,'' James DeAtley, U.S. attorney for the
southern district of Texas, said after attending Wednesday's
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But he declined to say where his investigation was headed other
than to focus on corruption among law enforcement officials in this
border city.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, accompanied by Laredo attorney Jeff Czar, stood
quietly before Kazen as the judge explained that Rodriguez faced up
to 20 years in prison and a $150,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is reserving the right to say whether you have
cooperated or not,'' Kazen told Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a done deal _ the government is leaving the door open
for you to cooperate,'' Kazen continued.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plea bargain, Rodriguez could get as little as
probation if he fully cooperates with federal investigators. He is
to give them any documents or other information he has that would
further their probe.
</P>
<P>
   If he lies or withholds information, he faces a longer prison
sentence and perjury charges, the judge warned.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who was a deputy sheriff from August 1985 to January
1997 when he was fired, was a go-between for a defendant arrested
in 1996 by Laredo police for possession of cocaine, according to
court documents.
</P>
<P>
   He had conversations on the phone and in county offices during
which he crafted a deal that involved paying $2,000 to the district
attorney's office investigator to shape the outcome of the case.
</P>
<P>
   The identities of the defendant and the investigator have not
been made public.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a promissory note for $2,500 was signed as part of
a bribe that would give the defendant six months' probation instead
of two years' probation and would keep the cocaine possession
charge from being recorded against him, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez told the judge he was unemployed after being fired
from the Sheriff's Department in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
