</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBBINS-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors, attention obit, entertainment editors:
</P>
<P>
   The choreographer Jerome Robbins has died. We will move a 3,500
word obituary within 30 minutes. This will be followed by a shorter
version of under 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-ROBBINS (New York) _ Jerome Robbins, who simultaneously
became one of 20th-century ballet's greatest choreographers and a
towering innovator in Broadway musicals, died Wednesday at his home
in Manhattan. He was 79. Robbins joined the City Ballet in 1948 and
helped shape the company's creative profile with daring and brio
for half a century through his often startling, always experimental
choreography in ballet's classical idiom. At the same time, he
enjoyed phenomenal success on Broadway. From 1944 to 1964, Robbins'
golden touch was evident in musicals as disparate as ``On the
Town,'' ``The King and I,'' ``Gypsy,'' ``West Side Story'' and
``Fiddler on the Roof.'' By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
