<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PICKLING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOOK ON PICKLE-PICKER-UPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvard Common Press is starting to make quite a name for itself
in the cookbook world. First, the little press published the hefty
barbecue trilogy written by Bob and Cheryl Alters Jamison. Harvard
also published the couple's award-winning ``The Border Cookbook.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the publisher has produced ``The Joy of Pickling,'' by Linda
Ziedrich ($14.95).
</P>
<P>
   The book is an intense look at pickles from the sweet to the
half-sour to the dilled guys we all know and love. There are fresh
pickles, fermented pickles, pickled cabbage, quick pickles, freezer
pickles as well as chutney, salsa and other relishes. It's a big
ole brining party.
</P>
<P>
   Ziedrich takes the fear out of the processing, and for those who
don't want to process with boiling water, there are lots of
alternatives. Making pickles does not have to mean buying lots of
special equipment you'll only use once, and Zeidrich tells you how.
Following are two alternate ways to put up pickles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIME-MINT FREEZER PICKLE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 4 pints
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 pounds of pickling cucumbers
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons pickling salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sliced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 small red bell pepper, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup minced mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups distilled white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Gently wash cucumbers and slice them thin, discarding a slice
from both ends of each cucumber. You should have about 8 cups. In
large bowl, toss cucumber slices with salt. Let cucumbers stand for
2 to 3 hours, then drain them.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl, stir together remaining ingredients. Pour
mixture over cucumbers and stir well. Refrigerate mixture for 8-10
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Pack cucumbers and syrup in freezer bags or rigid containers and
freeze the containers.
</P>
<P>
   Thaw pickles for about 8 hours in refrigerator before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per 1/4 cup: 18 calories, trace fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 184 milligrams
sodium, 2 percent of calories from fat.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POLISH PICKLED MUSHROOMS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 pint
</P>
<P>
   1 pound mushrooms, wiped clean with a damp cloth
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon whole allspice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons pickling salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   In nonreactive saucepan, bring all ingredients to a boil. Reduce
heat and simmer 15 minutes. Place mushrooms and their liquid in a
pint jar. Let the jar cool.
</P>
<P>
   Cap the jar. Store it in the refrigerator for several days
before eating the mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerated, the mushrooms will keep for about 3 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per 1/4 cup: 23 calories, trace fat, 4
grams carbohydrates, 1 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 229 milligrams
sodium, 12 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
