<HEADER>
A8535 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-BOOKS-2T     07-29 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-BOOKS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMYSTIFYING ALL THAT MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 20 years ago, when America was awakening to its puppy love
for personal computers, there was much talk about how digitized
data would start to replace books. Anyone remember the paperless
office?
</P>
<P>
   Much like the shelves overstocked with software in computer
stores, shelf space in stores, offices and homes is increasingly
being crammed with books _ old-fashioned paper books _ about
computers and all things digital.
</P>
<P>
   Some publishers today say that encyclopedias and other reference
books on CD-ROM are starting to spell doom for their printed
predecessors. But over all, the proliferation of computers in the
last decade has instead spelled boom for the publishers of books
that explain, support and demystify computers and all that they do.
</P>
<P>
   With the Microsoft Corp.'s Windows 98 operating system only two
months old, stores already offer scores of books _ ``Windows 98 for
Dummies,'' ``Learn Windows 98 in a Weekend,'' ``The Windows 98
Bible'' _ that promise to guide users through the program's
installation and use. More are on the way, publishers say.
</P>
<P>
   In total, 3,000 computer books were released last year,
according to industry statistics. And while some come bearing
companion CD-ROMs to run on multimedia computers, most of these
books are so low-tech that Gutenberg wouldn't have had trouble
using them.
</P>
<P>
   And these books are not just dry users' manuals from
manufacturers. IDG Books Worldwide, publisher of the ``For
Dummies'' series for general users (``DOS for Dummies,''
``Upgrading and Fixing PC's for Dummies'' and more than 300 other
computer-related titles) has sold more than 50 million books,
translated into 38 languages.
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 to 1997, computer book publishers recorded a 40
percent increase in sales, said Peter Breen, managing editor of
Computer Publishing &AMP; Advertising Report, a biweekly newsletter
that tracks the computer book industry. In the same period, he
said, overall book sales grew by 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mirroring the growth of the computer industry, the computer
book business saw a big boom in the early and mid-80s and then
trailed off for the rest of the decade,'' Breen said. ``It started
picking up in the early 1990s and has grown ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   So many publishers are rushing so many computer books to market
that one company, Wiley Computer Publishing, decided that it would
focus its books on more experienced computer users, at intermediate
and expert levels. For years, Wiley has been cranking out titles
like the popular ``Data Warehouse Toolkit'' and its forthcoming
follow-up, ``The Data Warehouse: Lifecycle Toolkit.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies like IDG, Jamsa Press and Macmillan Computer
Publishing U.S.A., the world's largest producer of computer books,
also publish some titles for those more knowledgeable users.
</P>
<P>
   But any brief inspection of a book section of a computer store
indicates that many books, most of them costing between $19.95 and
$49.99, are aimed at the broad lower middle tier of computer users.
</P>
<P>
   Even with rising sales, the computer publishing world has its
own particular problems. One is the difficulty of getting computer
books reviewed. Another, Breen said, is that computer books seldom
sell fast. They tend to build a following slowly, often by
word-of-mouth.
</P>
<P>
   And because computer books are tied to the rapid changes in
computer software and hardware they try to explain, they are more
subject to revisions or to simply disappearing in a matter of
months. Player guides for popular computer games are particularly
vulnerable to the extremely short life span of computer games. Once
a game ends up in the discount bin, so does the book about it.
</P>
<P>
   The three computer books reviewed here are each different and
reflect deepening trends in the computer publishing marketplace.
All three are self-help guides.
</P>
<P>
   One is aimed at general computer users who simply want to know
how their computers work, another is a primer for users of
Macintosh computers, and the third is a strategy guide to help
players get the most from a popular new computer game. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOW COMPUTERS WORK, THIRD EDITION, WITH INTERACTIVE CD-ROM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Ron White (Que, $39.99). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For many computer users, the notion of probing beneath the
covers of these expensive machines and noodling with their innards
is not appealing. Even if someone works up the nerve to look around
in there or dares to make some useful upgrades, poking around
motherboards and expansion cards will probably feel like a perilous
walk in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   But if knowledge is the light of the world, then the contents of
the 292-page book ``How Computers Work,'' which comes with a
complementary CD-ROM, will certainly illuminate much about the
inner workings of today's home and business computers _ without
requiring the user to look under the hood.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike instruction manuals that often come with computers and
are either so laden with jargon or so simplified that they read
like maps without street names, this large, well-illustrated book
strikes a good balance between the needs of the beginner and those
of the more experienced user.
</P>
<P>
   Its author, Ron White, a senior editor at PC Computing magazine
and founder of one of the first PC online user groups, is an old
hand at these kinds of books. A patient teacher, he writes in a
clear and well-informed voice that says, ``You, too, can understand
this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   In the opening of chapter six, ``How Windows Uses Memory,'' for
example, White writes, ``Memory is the staging area for the
processor, the place where the processor receives the instructions
and data it needs to do its job.''
</P>
<P>
   And yes, this book, while conveying some information that is
universal to practically all computers, is more or less aimed at
explaining the ins and outs of Windows-based PCs with Intel chips,
commonly known as Wintel computers.
</P>
<P>
   There is no mention, for example, of Macintosh computers.
Windows 95 and Windows NT figure prominently in the book's
explanations of software, and Intel's Pentium Pro chip gets its own
chapter.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, the book covers some of the most common computer
peripherals, like printers, scanners, joysticks and even digital
cameras. And ``How Computers Work'' delves into the unseen world of
what is actually going on inside, say, a transistor, the building
blocks of computer chips _ the kind of exploration that is a must
for any computer book worth a tree's life and limbs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Interested in the interplay of electrons on P-type silicon?
White tries to make it seem oh so simple _ most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The generous use of large, colorful illustrations practically
turns ``How Computers Work'' into a picture book. And the CD-ROM
that comes tucked in a pocket inside the back cover is an
imaginative interactive guide into the hardware of multimedia
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Through sound and animation, the CD-ROM offers a 3-D vision,
rather than the book's X-ray vision, of how computers work _ for
example, what happens when a floppy disk is formatted.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of this book-and-CD-ROM combination, the computer
might have a tough time holding on to the mystery of its inner
workings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRIMA'S OFFICIAL STRATEGY GUIDE: UNREAL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Joe Grant Bell (Prima Publishing, $19.99). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has ever played even a mildly engaging computer game,
especially multimedia, 3-D challenges like Quake 2, Mech Warrior 2
and Warcraft II, knows that it takes only a few minutes to learn
how to play but dozens of hours to learn to play well.
</P>
<P>
   Who has the time? It didn't take hard-core game players long to
realize that they could considerably shorten their learning curves
by trading tips and secrets about popular computer games.
</P>
<P>
   It also didn't take the publishing world long to realize that
there was a growing need among the millions of computer game
players for well-written, easy-to-follow help in navigating the
spooky digital domains of, say, Myst, or the temples of Tomb Robber
II.
</P>
<P>
   Prima Publishing, among others, took up the challenge, and the
result is a long line of official as well as unauthorized guides to
computer games. Joe Grant Bell's guide to Unreal, an intense,
fight-your-way-through-a-hostile-alien-world game, is one of the
latest.
</P>
<P>
   Like all the Prima guides, the book has numerous but rudimentary
illustrations in black and white. But what makes the books such hot
sellers (Prima's ``Myst: The Official Strategy Guide'' sold more
than a million copies) is the apparent depth of knowledge they
impart about the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unreal'' is broadly organized into four sections: first, the
many weapons and devices, like flak canons and antitoxin suits, and
the myriad capabilities a player must know about them.
</P>
<P>
   Next there is a detailed discussion, bordering on the
anthropological, about various enemies a player is likely to
encounter. What constitutes the bulk of this 193-page guide is a
step-by-step tutorial in how to survive and win in the game's
creepy labyrinths of terror and sudden game-ending mayhem. That
includes a section on advanced combat techniques like circular
strafing, which is the constant circling of a target while firing,
inflicting maximum damage while making it difficult to get hit by
enemy fire. The last section is for players who wish to enter the
game's multiplayer matches on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the guide, Bell effectively maintains an air of
authenticity about the elements of the Unreal environment. Whole
passages never hint that all the firepower specs and tactics
concern a world that is only a game, a game that exists only on the
shiny surface of a CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Bell writes about the flak cannon that it ``fires
high-velocity metal shards that rip a hole in your enemy in seconds
flat. It isn't the prettiest weapon, but it makes up for its lack
of beauty with raw power.'' Or consider his advice about fighting
on the go: ``Never stop. Even the weakest alien in the galaxy is
capable of hitting you if you stand still.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing the aliens can't read Prima's guides. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE LITTLE MAC BOOK, FIFTH EDITION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Robin Williams (Peachpit Press, $19.95). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THIS is a book for beginners that, in many editions over the
years, has become a classic among users of Apple Macintosh
computers. More than 350,000 copies of the book are in print in
eight languages.
</P>
<P>
   When ``The Little Mac Book'' was first published, in 1990, it
actually was a little book. Reflecting the growing complexity of
Macs and their uses, Robin Williams' fifth edition of her book is a
softcover tome of 369 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Williams, who has written more than a dozen best-selling
computer books, says in this book's opening pages that all the
extra words were unavoidable. She writes that while the Mac is
still the easiest computer on the planet to use, ``it is a fact
that there are some things that are now a little more confusing to
use than they used to be.'' Progress obviously has its price.
</P>
<P>
   But much of ``The Little Mac Book'' stays close to the basics.
In a friendly, downright chatty tone, Ms. Williams guides Mac users
through some of the most fundamental functions, like opening files
and using the keyboard's numeric pad.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a section on ``important keys'' on the keyboard,
like the asterisk (readers are told that the word is Greek and
means ``little star''). Helpful additions to this book include a
light discussion of Macintosh's OS 8 operating system and three new
chapters on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There is little trace of geekspeak jargon. Chapter 14 is titled
``Word Processing (also known as `typing').'' Ms. Williams is
apparently much less concerned about telling her readers how
something works and more intent on explaining to them how to get
something to work. She also carries the Mac banner high and more
than occasionally takes all-in-fun shots at PCs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally believe the World Wide Web would not have
happened if the Macintosh computer had not been invented,'' she
writes deep into the book. She says the Mac's pioneering use of
graphics, sound and animation helped open minds to what could be
possible on a vast network of computers.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Microsoft Corp., she writes that it ``copied'' (the
words ``ripped off'' are crossed out in the text) Macintosh
technology, so that PCs now ``clumsily'' mimic Macs.
</P>
<P>
   Further reflecting the Mac's ethos, ``The Little Mac Book'' is
peppered with clear and clever black-and-white illustrations and is
easy to follow. To make sure readers are getting it, Ms. Williams,
a former teacher, placed quizzes at the ends of chapters.
</P>
<P>
   There are also helpful sections near the end of the book _ one
is titled ``Aaack!! HELP!'' _ crammed with tips and
trouble-shooting solutions.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a page of handy Web sites like www.amazon.com and
www.apple.com. Hmmmm. ... looks as if www.microsoft.com didn't make
the cut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1623EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
