<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8541 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-CHINA-INTERNET-NY     07-29 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CHINA-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET-FLUENT MIT STUDENTS TEACH BASICS IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (af)  
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dan Dwyer, a sophomore at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, knew that spending last summer hooking up a high school
in Beijing to its first Internet connection was not going to be
easy.
</P>
<P>
   But his biggest obstacle was not tussling with the Chinese
bureaucracy or outmaneuvering government restrictions on Internet
access. It was the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   When he tried to call the high school's computer director at
home one evening, ``the person who answered the phone said, `You'll
have to call right back,' '' Dwyer said. ``It was one phone line
that was shared by two families living in adjacent apartments.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharing the wonders of the Internet with the rest of the world
is a noble pursuit, but bringing thousands of dollars' worth of
equipment and all that cutting-edge knowledge to a country where
phones are still party lines, computers are scarce and few have
even heard of the World Wide Web might seem laughable.
</P>
<P>
   Not to the students who volunteer for the China Educational
Technology Initiative, an MIT program that sends college students
overseas to teach high school students about the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, two graduate students, Jake Seid and Ron Cao, not
only persuaded MIT to let them go, basically unsupervised, to set
up the first Web site at a high school in China, they later
persuaded the school to talk big-name companies into sponsoring
them. Last summer, the program sent 13 students.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, 24 new interns have traveled to 9 high schools.
They go in teams of two or three, including at least one student
who speaks either Cantonese or Mandarin and at least one who speaks
the more exotic languages of Java and HTML. Together they set up a
server and teach the students to create Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Seid and Cao (pronounced Sow) came up with the idea as an
alternative to the typical graduate-student project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it important that two MIT students write a report on
telecommunications that nobody is going to read?'' said Seid
(pronounced Sayd). ``It really made us think, what do we want to
accomplish?''
</P>
<P>
   And where? News articles they read in 1996 described China as
extremely cautious in its exploration of the Internet. Those who
did have Internet accounts had to register with the police, and
those who applied for accounts had to sign an agreement to abide by
Chinese law and not endanger state security.
</P>
<P>
   The MIT students soon learned, however, that they could set up
sites on the Chinese Educational Research Network, which connects
all the universities.
</P>
<P>
   True, some schools are hesitant to encourage access to sites
outside China, not because of censorship but because most are
charged for every such site they call up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago there were a lot of questions about who should
be hooked up to the Internet,'' Seid said. ``I think they took a
chance on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the student-built Web sites are written in both English
and Chinese. The Fudan High School site has pictures of the school,
names of award-winning students, even a photo of Cao Tianren, the
headmaster. Another school's site offers a practice test for the
college entrance exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than just connecting the wires or getting a computer
into the school,'' said Robert Yung, Sun Microsystems' director for
technology in Asia and a project mentor. ``This is about how do we
teach, how do we show people how to use the technology?''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Sun Microsystems and other companies have donated more
than $250,000 worth of hardware and software. Each team has to
figure out a strategy for its project, from getting the hardware
shipped to figuring out how to teach Java programming to 40 ninth
graders in six weeks, a commitment that impressed Yung.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed at their energy level,'' he said. ``It was finals
week at MIT this week, and I still get e-mail from them at 3 in the
morning. I look at them and say, `Why don't I take care of this
problem? You go and study.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The months leading up to the trip are filled with incessant
e-mails, faxes and phone calls. (The translators have the worst of
it, they agree, because they have to deal with the 12-hour time
difference.) Another first _ setting up a wireless Internet
connection to a Chinese high school _ required days of back and
forth.
</P>
<P>
   The five-floor high school building did not have telephone
wires, so the volunteers used antennae to connect it to a
university, and its dedicated line, about a half-mile away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never even saw the buildings _ it was all through e-mail,''
said Roger Hu, who went to Shanghai as a freshman. ``We needed to
see what buildings were in the way, if they would interfere with
the line of sight. They would go up and on the roof and say, `Oh,
yeah, I can see the building from there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The MIT students' Chinese hosts were eager to help. Some of the
schools updated their computers or bought new ones. So many people
were interested in their progress that last summer the American
students held a conference about the Web in education that drew
corporate chief executives, school principals and Chinese
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   The China Education Technology Initiative inspired another MIT
student, Ameet Ranadive, to start a similar program in India last
year. The population there is approaching one billion, but only
100,000 have Internet access. Ranadive, who will be a graduate
student in the fall, said he planned to have the Indian students
start pen-pal relationships with the Chinese students using e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start with small steps like that, at least it's
promoting connections with the two sides,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The interns have their share of concerns about nuclear testing
in India, human rights violations in China and civil war in Africa,
where yet another MIT student is looking to start a similar
program. But they manage to keep their corner of cyberspace
apolitical.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I heard about China was all very negative things,'' Seid
said. ``You'd hear about issues like Taiwan, you hear about the
Dalai Lama and Tibet, you hear about Tiananmen. Then you hear about
the people. It's a very different perspective than what you hear
about the government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1624EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDITATION-SPACES-ART     07-29 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDITATION-SPACES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDITATION AND DECORATION: OM FOR THE HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By BOB MORRIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You don't need a separate room for meditation,''
designer Diane Von Furstenberg said. ``I meditate every morning in
my bed for a half- hour before I get up.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when she moved her showroom and offices to an enormous
carriage house in Greenwich Village last year, she created a yoga
room. She painted it sea green (``for serenity and calm'') and
installed a regal-looking nomadic-style tent. It's made of
banana-fiber panels, edged with antique ribbons from India. With
each current of air, the panels waft gently like sheets hanging on
a clothesline in summer. The effect is calming, and so is the sound
of trickling water in the mosaic-tile pool below.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the Chinese, moving water brings good luck and
serenity,'' Ms. Von Furstenberg said. Of course, money often brings
serenity, too, and she is one of many people of means who have
devoted a room to pursue it through meditation.
</P>
<P>
   The serene Madonna has a yoga room in her Miami home. Donna
Karan has a rock garden in East Hampton, N.Y. Her husband, Stephan
Weiss, a sculptor, has installed a Balinese teak temple on the
terrace of his studio in Greenwich Village. Around the corner,
Deneen and Raymond King own an indoor pool, which they say has a
meditative effect on their lives, while in Bedford, N.Y., John
Fowle and Gina Sharpe have converted the dining room and guest
cottage of a house once owned by Giancarlo Menotti into Buddhist
meditation spaces. Although they find that having a room with an
altar is helpful, the discipline of stilling the mind through
meditation remains a challenge. After all, they're both former
lawyers. ``Once a lawyer, always a lawyer,'' Fowle said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, when Mircea Eliade wrote in ``The Sacred and the
Profane'' that ``cosmic symbolism is found in the very structure of
the habitation,'' popular awareness of the ceremonial use of space
in the home was limited largely to Christmas trees and Sabbath
candles.
</P>
<P>
   A poll in House &AMP; Garden last winter showed that more than 80
percent of respondents believed that having a quiet place in the
home for meditation is a necessity. For many of these people, such
spaces are more about esthetics and therapy than about faith;
others take their spiritual pursuits seriously. But most mix and
match their disciplines to taste.
</P>
<P>
   In West Hollywood, for instance, Rick Rubin, a founder of Def
Jam records, once the powerhouse of rap music, and president of
Sony's American Recordings, uses a room he designed specially in an
old mansion for transcendental meditation, yoga, tai chi and other
practices. The room has air purifiers, sheepskin yoga mats and a
stained-glass Buddha etched in the door.
</P>
<P>
   And that's nothing compared with the much-publicized yoga house
that Lynda Guber built behind her Bel Air mansion. A ``working
spiritual environment,'' she calls it, where the Dalai Lama once
spoke. It has a kitchen for boiling greens, sofas that can
accommodate people sitting in the lotus position and a guest room
for enlightened visitors. It's a far cry from meditating in a cave.
</P>
<P>
   ``In India, holiness is still associated with poverty and
homelessness,'' said Brad Gooch, who was there in the spring to
research ``Travels in Spiritual America,''a book scheduled for next
year. ``So the interface in the United States between yoga,
spirituality and upscale design seems a little strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Who would have guessed that the spiritual would require so much
of the material?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can meditate everywhere because this whole house is about
ritual,'' said Hedy Klineman, an artist who practices an amalgam of
Eastern ritual. She has a meditation room in a spectacular Fifth
Avenue triplex, which she and her husband, a venture capitalist,
renovated then filled with shrines, Buddhas, Krishnas, Shivas and
prayer tables. ``I call it my home in the sky. In a sense, it's a
temple.''
</P>
<P>
   So is the Park Avenue apartment of Alice Harris, who is not a
practicing Buddhist. ``My apartment is so Zen that when people
first see it, they plotz,'' she said. Ms. Harris, author of ``The
White T'' (HarperCollins, 1997), and her husband, Stanley Harris, a
magazine publisher, enlisted the decorator Robert Metzger to give
their home a theatrical Zen makeover. The yoga room floor is
covered with black sisal, and there's an 18th-century Japanese
screen of Buddhist tranquillity gods. Over the kitchen table, a
wooden sculpture of Daikoku, the Japanese kitchen god, presides
near a bowl of oranges on a marble counter lighted with a pin spot.
It's very Shinto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make pot roast and chicken soup in here,'' Ms. Harris said,
adding that she hired a ``feng shui guy'' to help her find out
where the spirits were moving in her home, but she warned him that
she wouldn't move any furniture because she just finished
redecorating. ``All that over-the-top spirituality stuff makes me
nauseous,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Marian McEvoy, the editor in chief of Elle Decor feels the same
way, especially when she's asked to remove her shoes before setting
foot in someone's Zen palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, your shoes are part of your outfit,'' she said.
``And if you ask me to mess up my outfit by taking them off, that
isn't a spiritual experience. It's torture. If I'm going to be a
pleasant and chatty guest in your home, don't expect me to ruin my
stockings on your floor. If we're in Japan, that's another story.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Ms. McEvoy doesn't think you need a Zen overhaul to
establish a serene space for reflection in your home. ``Just clean
out your bedroom,'' she suggested. ``Get rid of some of those books
and the clutter and light some candles. That should calm you way
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those who don't have the resources to devote a whole room
to meditation, can transcend their earthly concerns as successfully
as the rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need a million dollars to have a space,'' said
Gurmukh, a kundalini yoga teacher in Los Angeles, who has
instructed David Duchovny, Madonna, Tim Burton and Courtney Love,
among others. ``You just need a place to return to, to remember who
you are on a daily basis. A home is a spiritual metaphor for the
self. Anyplace in it can be sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Hindu tradition requires that every home, no matter how
humble, has a place for the family to pray, meditate and make
offerings of food. ``Many Americans find having this kind of sacred
space meaningful,'' said Dvendra Patel, a Hindu scholar who teaches
at the Swaminarayan Temple in Edison, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good. But what we believe is that after you pray, you
still have to be humble in life and you still have to control the
senses.'' Still, he takes no offense at the way some less than
humble Americans are mixing rituals to taste. ``If it's good for
people, they should do what they like.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Books have been published about creating sacred spaces in the
home, including ``Altars Made Easy'' (HarperCollins, 1997) by Peg
Streep. It details how a physical place can be set up in the home
where ``the divine or supernatural can be glimpsed or experienced,
where we can get in touch with that which is larger than
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Sarasohn, a vice president of the Corcoran Group real
estate company, said altars are the next big thing. Her company
will soon install a custom-made glass altar of prosperity in its
office above Barneys, and Corcoran may also put altars in empty
properties to make them more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our clients are concerned with the spiritual
atmosphere of our properties,'' said Ms. Sarasohn, who has brought
channelers in to inspect homes for clients. ``We think working with
altars may also create good publicity for our firm.''
</P>
<P>
   On a late-spring Sunday, when the faithful were gathered at
traditional altars in churches all over town, a single woman was at
home installing a love altar in a corner of her studio apartment on
West 57th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do something mindful with the space,'' she said
about the top two shelves of her built-in bookcase. For help, she
hired Yoanna Da Vinci, an ``interior design and well-being
consultant.'' Ms. Da Vinci designed the Corcoran Group's altar and
has made others for clients like Barbara Biziou, a writer in
Greenwich Village. She helps clients customize their altars for
multicultural rituals as varied as the choices in a food court. If
something's lacking in your life _ job, health, fertility _ it's
likely that Ms. Da Vinci has the right altar for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep in mind how spiritual you are,'' said Ms. Da Vinci, who
would like to supply hip hotels with altars, too. ``If you're a
Wall Street lawyer, you may want to install only a prosperity
altar. If you're more religious, I can teach you a mantra to go
with the altar.''
</P>
<P>
   After a first consultation with her client ($125 an hour), Ms.
Da Vinci returned with a few items: some CD's and red fabrics from
India to drape over the furniture for romantic ambiance. She also
brought complimentary red candles and pink roses.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to feng shui, this is my love and relationship
corner,'' said her client, who did not want to be named lest she
appear to be running a personals ad. In what she calls her
``helpful people'' corner to the north, she had created a shrine of
sorts, with framed photographs of friends, a Nativity plate and a
statue of Lakshmi, the Hindu fortune goddess. Next to that was her
``career'' corner, which, oddly enough, housed her bed. ``It's the
only space where it fits,'' said the woman, a former television
producer, who is now a freelance magazine writer. ``What can you
do?''
</P>
<P>
   After leading a Hindu prayer asking for wisdom, then salting the
shelves (a Chinese tradition), Ms. Da Vinci supervised as her
client arranged her love altar with the care of a child decorating
a dollhouse.
</P>
<P>
   On the upper shelf, she placed things that she said were
symbolic of the higher self: the two of cups tarot love card, a
mandala, a book of Mediterranean love poems, a tiny cherub, some
hard candies wrapped in red and an old wristwatch, so that love
would arrive in a timely manner. On the shelf below, she placed
objects from a more material plane.
</P>
<P>
   These included photocopies of $100 bills, so that money would
not be an issue in her relationship; a book called ``Unleashing the
Sex Goddess in Every Woman'' by Olivia St. Clair (Harmony Books);
her passport and Berlitz dictionaries, so that Prince Charming
would be a worldly guy. She also placed opera glasses on the altar.
``I want my lover to be comfortable in dressy situations,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Da Vinci asked the woman to stick her ring finger on a
red ink pad and make an imprint on the back of her bookshelf, she
demurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too pushy,'' she told Ms. Da Vinci. ``I'm not a ring
person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' said Ms. Da Vinci, who invented the rite herself. ``It's
a ritual that's more popular on the Upper East Side. I guess
they're more ring-oriented over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was time for a closing ceremony. Ms. Da Vinci (who would
return four more times to make sure the altar was properly tended)
had her client walk barefoot on a long red sari as if she were a
bride marching down the aisle. Then she directed her to sit on the
floor and meditate on her ideal. To aid the process, she played a
CD of songs adapted by Ravi Shankar from the Kama Sutra, the Indian
manual of love. A trembling voice soared into the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fill this empty pot with the nectar of love,'' it sang.
</P>
<P>
   There was something wistful about a ritual offering the client
solace but no real solution for what was missing from her life, but
she seemed uplifted when it was over. With a hopeful expression on
her face, she opened her eyes and looked out her window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, it's raining,'' she said. ``I think that's a blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   In life, so many things are. But sometimes it takes a sacred
nudge to see them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1628EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
