<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8560 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-SPEAKERS     07-29 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-SPEAKERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE BEST OF COMPUTER SOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHAEL FREMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hi-fi'' from tiny, inexpensive multimedia speakers plugged
into your computer? Don't count on it _ unless you are willing to
stretch the term hi-fi beyond recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Computer sound cards packed with cheap parts and low-grade
digital-to-analog converters are not designed for quality music
reproduction. The computer environment, awash in sound-polluting
radio frequencies and electromagnetic radiation, doesn't help.
</P>
<P>
   That said, adding a sound system to your computer can enhance
your computing pleasure, whether you're playing games, exploring
the Internet or listening to music as you work.
</P>
<P>
   Most multimedia systems consist of a powered bass unit (woofer)
and a pair of compact speakers (satellites), which handle from the
upper midbass range to the highest frequencies. Getting a seamless
sonic blend between the satellites and woofer is the key to getting
a big, satisfying sound.
</P>
<P>
   The CDs I used to test some of these systems included Olu Dara's
``In the World'' (Atlantic), a new 20-bit remastering of ``Sinatra
at the Sands'' (Reprise) and ``The Fantasy Film World of Bernard
Herrmann'' (Mobile Fidelity). If a system can do justice to complex
music, it should have no trouble with video games.
</P>
<P>
   Though it doesn't include a separate woofer, the $219 Bose
Mediamate system (www.bose.com) offers surprisingly fine midbass
performance from one tiny 2{-inch full-range speaker in each
cabinet. But there is little below about 80 hertz, so you cannot
really feel the bass.
</P>
<P>
   The Mediamate's overall balance is smooth and appealing, though
on the soft side, with a noticeable lack of high-frequency detail,
despite a cannily placed upper-midrange emphasis that greatly
increases clarity and listening pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   The system plays impressively loud without distortion, but the
louder you play it, the more it accentuates the midbass bump that
imparts a chesty quality to things like male voices and violas.
Imaging (the ability of a speaker system to focus, producing a
sonic picture of Frank Sinatra on the Sands' stage, for example) is
satisfactory, though somewhat enlarged directly between the
speakers.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mediamate is impressive, given its size and
portability, pass on it unless you absolutely have no room for a
woofer.
</P>
<P>
   While today's Altec Lansing (www.altecmm.com) has nothing to do
with the company that made movie-theater sound systems during
Hollywood's golden age, the new owners have done the name proud
with the ASC48 Powercube Plus Multimedia Speaker System.
</P>
<P>
   It includes two plastic molded satellites, each 3{ by 5 inches,
with a 3-inch full-range driver, a }-inch tweeter and a 6-inch
woofer in a compact, 14-by-12-by-8-inch wooden cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The Powercube Plus offers a reasonably smooth, extended
top-to-bottom frequency response with moderately deep, though
somewhat thumpy, lows and detailed highs. The tweeter can sound
brash, but careful placement helps.
</P>
<P>
   The Powercube's sound is surprisingly big and well focused, but
it gives instruments like brass and the human voice a harder than
natural edge. An asking price of $300 would be reasonable, but an
Altec Lansing spokesman said the street price for the Powercube
Plus was around $149, making it an even better value.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Kloss, a veteran speaker designer, now creates products
for Cambridge Soundworks (www.hifi.com), a mail-order company,
including the top-of-the-line Microworks multimedia speaker, which
consists of two small, heavy cubes, about 4 inches on a side, and a
6{-inch woofer in a 16-by-8-by-9-inch box.
</P>
<P>
   The Microworks system provides the deepest, tightest bass of any
system in this survey. Although it overemphasizes the
upper-midrange frequencies somewhat, it is the best-balanced, most
dynamic-sounding system of the lot. The Microworks system plays
extremely loud without strain. At $249.99, it offers the
high-frequency clarity, focus and separation usually associated
with far more expensive systems. Effective woofer and satellite
integration creates the illusion of a much bigger system.
</P>
<P>
   The Bose Acoustimass Multimedia system and the exotic Eminent
Technology LFT-11, which each cost $599, are the most expensive
systems surveyed here. The 3-inch satellite cubes of the
Acoustimass are the smallest of the speakers reviewed, so easiest
to place.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But getting a satisfactory blend with the compact woofer unit
(18{ by 8{ by 7{ inches) is difficult because inexplicably, the
Acoustimass system does not offer a bass-level control, something
offered by both the Altec and Soundworks systems, which are less
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The Acoustimass system sounds somewhat thin, especially compared
with Microworks. The 5\-inch woofer's bass response is not as
extended as that of the Microworks system, which is less than half
the price. The small satellites offer good overall clarity, and the
system can play reasonably loud, but it sounds strained when
pushed, at a volume where Microworks is still coasting. It is hard
to justify the Acoustimass' high price.
</P>
<P>
   The boxless Eminent Technology LFT-11 (www.eminent-tech.com)
planar magnetic speakers use flat voice elements etched upon small
sheets of mylar instead of conventional coils and paper cones. The
sheets are stretched and sandwiched between opposing magnets that
are held in place under great force.
</P>
<P>
   The units are dipolar, which means that they produce sound both
in front and behind equally. Less than one inch thick, each Eminent
Technology driver unit is slightly smaller than the 6\-by-9-inch
solid oak panel in which it is set. The disadvantage of such
technology is that the speakers must be aimed at you just so or you
will hear no high frequencies at all.
</P>
<P>
   Eminent Technology's 10-by-15-by-8-inch woofer box, containing
two high-quality 6{-inch drivers and finished in oak veneer and
acrylic, is extremely heavy and well braced.
</P>
<P>
   Both its construction and its nuanced sound put it in a
different league from the other woofers, though it lacks the punch
of the self-powered Microworks unit. Getting a blend is not easy,
but once that is accomplished, you will know you're listening to
something special: a piece of genuine high-end audio.
</P>
<P>
   The LFT-11 system is available unpowered (without an amplifier)
for $499. Add $100 and you get a small Radio Shack Optimus
amplifier, which fits into an attractive oak stand for your
monitor. Of all the systems surveyed, the LFT-11 offers the most
credible, most convincing and least distorted sensation of a
three-dimensional musical performance.
</P>
<P>
   The Eminent Technology system creates a big, rich, creamy
picture you will gladly put your face into _ as if it were the
breeze from an air-conditioner on a hot day. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Setting Up &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Computer listening takes the room out of the acoustics: you're
sitting closer to the speakers than with a normal hi-fi. The result
can be almost holographic sonic imaging if you place the speakers,
also called satellites, equidistant from you and spread them a few
feet apart for a bigger ``sound stage'' and better separation.
</P>
<P>
   Play a good recording like ``Sinatra at the Sands'' and begin
listening with the satellites pointed straight ahead. Vary the
angle at which they face you. One position will create the best
balance of frequency response, image focus and sound stage size,
depending on your tastes and the speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Bass reinforcement is tricky. Depending upon where you place
your woofer, you will either get plenty of good bass, boomy bass or
very little of either.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, most of us have but one option _ under the desk _
but even there, moving the woofer closer or farther away from the
wall can have a big effect. Once the woofer is positioned, blend
its output with the satellites to achieve a seamless sonic
transition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1630EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
