<SLUG> BC-TOURING-COOPERSTOWN-2200(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLIDE INTO COOPERSTOWN FOR A HOME-RUN TRAVEL EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y.:north of Cooperstown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Farmers' Museum ((607) 547-1450) and Fenimore House Museum
((607) 547-1400) vary their hours from week to week, so it's smart
to call ahead. Both have unique charms. The Farmers' Museum
ventures beyond the obvious rusty tools and baling machines; its
quilt collection is considered among the finest in the country. At
Fenimore House, docents wear Iroquois regalia _ it is guaranteed to
brighten the day of any baseball-despising kids (or adults) in your
party.
</P>
<P>
   If you book well in advance, where to stay involves places
within Cooperstown city limits instead of the hundred-mile zone
annually scoured by desperate souls, often without success, in the
latter stages of July.
</P>
<P>
   The bed and breakfasts are uniformly elegant but a bit pricey.
Figure $90 a night, though some $60-$75 bargains are occasionally
available. Even the motels are slightly upscale in appearance and
rates; after all, proprietors realize that you either stay with
them or drive a long way to find alternatives. You do get quality;
many of these places have their own beaches and make paddle boats
available to guests.
</P>
<P>
   The most upscale is the tony Otesaga Resort Hotel, whose rooms
top out at $185 a night but whose porch is mere steps away from the
hall of fame. Convenience combined with elegance always costs a
little more.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide not to stay in Cooperstown, be prepared to search
for accommodations during Hall of Fame Induction Weekend. Room
scarcity is intensified when a so-called name player is enshrined,
and in 1999 Nolan Ryan is expected to be joined in the hall by
fellow superstars George Brett and Robin Yount. Usually,
sportswriters vote in one or two players, at most. An old-timers'
committee also chooses inductees, but generally the honorees are
either deceased or much lesser-known. This anticipated modern-day
threesome means that the always-crazed hotel/motel demand will be
tripled.
</P>
<P>
   After you've booked a place to stay and ensured that
non-baseball fans in your group have plenty of other diversions,
it's time to turn your attention to the hall.
</P>
<P>
   There's no need to worry about induction ceremony tickets per
se: The program, always held Saturday afternoon in front of
Cooperstown's Clark Sports Center, is free. That doesn't assure
proximity; fans shoulder their way into good viewing positions, and
the lawn in front of the center is staked out early by people
spreading blankets or setting up those ubiquitous plastic folding
lounge chairs. The best advice is the most obvious: Get up early to
nail down a choice spot.
</P>
<P>
   The National Baseball Hall of Fame is open daily, with summer
hours of 9 a.m.- 9 p.m. Considering the multitude of treasures
inside and the full day it can take just to give most exhibits a
first look, ticket prices _ $9.50 for adults, $8 for seniors, $4
for kids 7-12 and free for those under 7 _ are not exorbitant. But
during induction weekend, the crowds are egregious. Be there when
the doors open.
</P>
<P>
   Another annual Induction Week highlight is Sunday's hall of fame
game between two Major League teams; the match-up is announced each
spring. The game is played on Doubleday Field, erroneously
identified once upon a time as the spot where Gen. Abner Doubleday
invented baseball. What myths lack in accuracy, though, they often
make up for in comfortable familiarity, and if you're lucky enough
to score a game ticket you really won't care if baseball's genesis
occurred in that converted cow pasture or not. Doubleday Field is
small, perhaps one-fifth the size of The Ballpark in Arlington, and
its cozy confines are perfect for optimum viewing.
</P>
<P>
   Game tickets are $10 for reserved seats and $9 for outfield
perches. They traditionally go on sale in late April; mailed
requests should be sent to Hall of Fame Game Tickets, Cooperstown
Baseball Committee, Box 590, Cooperstown, NY 13326. No checks or
cash, please: The committee does want your letter to include a
credit card type, number and date of expiration. Master Card, VISA,
Discover and American Express are acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Forget buying a ticket on the day of the game; it will have been
sold out for months, and Cooperstown discourages scalpers.
</P>
<P>
   It is traditional for most living hall of fame members to find
their way back to Cooperstown during induction weekend. Especially
if you stay at the Otesaga, you're likely to rub shoulders
occasionally with childhood idols. The hall sponsors a couple of
golf tournaments over the weekend, and many hall of famers compete.
For grown-up fans, this is a good opportunity to ask for
autographs. The hall also sponsors two free autograph sessions for
kids ages 7-12.
</P>
<P>
   There are other activities, notably a minor-league game at
Doubleday Field and a ``town ball'' exhibition, which serve as
secondary treats.
</P>
<P>
   All that remains for Nolan Ryan fans is the hall's announcement
of its 1999 induction weekend dates. July 23-25 or July 30-Aug. 1
are the best bets; call the hall around September or October this
year to find out for certain.
</P>
<P>
   Then, if you want to be with Ryan on his big day, make your next
call to the Cooperstown Chamber of Commerce. Only early birds can
enjoy all the hall of fame worms.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
