r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOURING-COOPERSTOWN-2     07-29 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURING-COOPERSTOWN-2200(2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLIDE INTO COOPERSTOWN FOR A HOME-RUN TRAVEL EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 Takes)-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ A year from now, Nolan Ryan will undoubtedly
become the Deerslayer's neighbor, and area baseball
fans-turned-tourists will want to be there when it happens.
</P>
<P>
   But if they don't plan far ahead, they'll have to settle for
reading about Ryan's induction into the National Baseball Hall of
Fame instead of seeing it. Cooperstown, in upstate New York, home
of the hall and setting for two of James Fenimore Cooper's buckskin
potboilers, is one of America's most delightful country towns.
Besides the hall of fame, Cooperstown has enough other attractions
to make it a good vacation choice for even non-baseball fans.
</P>
<P>
   But during the last week in July, when the annual hall
inductions are usually scheduled, the sleepy town of 2,500 morphs
into the center of the baseball universe. Hotel reservations, let
alone tickets to induction events, are impossible to come by. If
you want to share Ryan's glorious moment, start making arrangements
as soon as the hall announces its induction ceremony dates for
1999.
</P>
<P>
   It is a good idea to make Cooperstown's acquaintance ahead of
time. Begin by realizing that New York state is a whole lot bigger
than New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Too many people assume that Cooperstown is a quick drive from
the Big Apple. In fact, Cooperstown is many miles northwest of New
York City. It takes as long to drive between the two locales as it
does to motor from Fort Worth to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allow at least 3 1/2 hours,'' cautions a Cooperstown Chamber
of Commerce staffer. The New York State Thruway, also known as
Interstate 87, offers a boring multilane route north from New York
City to Albany. But then there is a sharp left turn on State
Highway 20, and you're almost instantly immersed in gently rolling
woodlands. The scenery is lovely, but the driving isn't. Every mile
is lengthened by innumerable twists and turns. It is much like the
Pacific Coast Highway between Los Angeles and San Francisco,
meaning that you might as well relax and enjoy the view.
</P>
<P>
   As befits a sleepy country hamlet, albeit one with a
tourist-driven economy, Cooperstown is long on charm and short on
parking spaces. Forget driving into town and parking at a meter.
Instead, follow the ``Perimeter Parking'' signs to any one of
several lots on the outskirts of town. There is no parking charge,
and for $1.50 a person, you can take a delightful trolley ride to
the town square.
</P>
<P>
   Your first sight of Cooperstown may make you catch your breath.
It is a wonderfully preserved tribute to early-1900s America.
Unlike Colonial Williamsburg, Cooperstown is a real village. Its
shops serve residents as well as visitors. The resulting atmosphere
is delightfully homey.
</P>
<P>
   The area had historic allure long before the hall of fame opened
in 1939. Otsego Lake served as a seasonal fishing camp for American
Indian tribes before the first white settlement appeared on its
shores in the early 1600s. Only after the first century of its
existence did that settlement become known as Cooperstown _ for
William Cooper, whose heir, James Fenimore Cooper, immortalized
Otsego Lake as ``Glimmerglass'' in ``The Deerslayer.'' Cooper also
put his hometown to fictional use in ``The Pioneers.''
</P>
<P>
   Otsego and the surrounding countryside offer ample opportunity
for recreational boating, hiking and other pleasurable outdoor
pursuits. But Cooperstown's distance from outlying metropolitan
areas, in driving time if not in miles, eventually threatened to
turn the Deerslayer's stamping grounds into a ghost town.
Fortunately, Cooperstown also had claim to the title of
``Birthplace of Baseball,'' thanks to a popular myth about Abner
Doubleday and the game he was supposed to have invented there. When
the hall of fame opened up, so did Cooperstown tourism. The town
has thrived ever since.
</P>
<P>
   But part of Cooperstown's ongoing success has been determination
to be something other than homes and shops surrounding the hall of
fame. Besides the venerable hall, Cooperstown has a world-class
opera, two gorgeous golf courses, nearly two dozen motels, a
reasonable selection of restaurants and a half-dozen museums that
have nothing to do with baseball. There are antiquarian book
dealers, antiques stores, art galleries, a pair of glittering state
parks and enough canoe rentals to float the Deerslayer and an
entire Iroquois tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Initial information about these amenities, particularly how to
book in-town lodging a minimum of six months in advance of hall of
fame induction activities, is readily available on the Internet
(www.cooperstown.net/cnatract.html) or by calling the Cooperstown
Chamber of Commerce ((607) 547-9983).
</P>
<P>
   Non-baseball fans often like to call ahead and book tickets for
performances by the Glimmerglass Opera, which cannily focuses on a
summer season during the months when the hall of fame attracts the
most visitors. Glimmerglass offers an eclectic performance mix,
often following tried-and-true favorites such as ``Tosca'' with
lesser-known or quirky works: ``L'Italiana en Algeri'' is a recent
example. Tickets fall into a wide $19-$70 range; information and
reservations are available at (607) 547-2255 or
glimmer\Ntelenet.net. Most performances are held in the lovely
Alice Busch Opera Theater eight miles north of Cooperstown. MORE: &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1640EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
