<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8600 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-ROBBINS-SHORT-NY     07-29 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ROBBINS-SHORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEROME ROBBINS, 79, FAMED BALLET CHOREOGRAPHER AND BROADWAY
LEGEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: This is an abridged version of OBIT-ROBBINS, about 3,400
words) 
 (bl)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jerome Robbins, one of 20th-century ballet's greatest
choreographers and a towering innovator in Broadway musicals, died
Wednesday at his home in Manhattan. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins suffered a stroke Saturday, said Deborah Koolish of the
New York City Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins joined the City Ballet in 1948 and helped shape its
creative profile with daring and brio for half a century through
his often startling, always experimental choreography in ballet's
classical idiom.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he enjoyed phenomenal success on Broadway.
From 1944 to 1964, Robbins' golden touch was evident in musicals as
disparate as ``On the Town,'' ``The King and I,'' ``Gypsy,'' ``West
Side Story'' and ``Fiddler on the Roof.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his acclaim on Broadway, Robbins made it clear that his
first love was dance, and ballet in particular. He briefly returned
to the commercial theater in 1989 with ``Jerome Robbins'
Broadway,'' but even this hit was an anthology of dance sequences
from past shows.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins' association with the City Ballet began when George
Balanchine, the company's artistic director, invited him to join at
the troupe's founding. Balanchine named Robbins associate artistic
director in 1949. After Balanchine's death in 1983, he and Peter
Martins served jointly until 1990 as the company's artistic
directors.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins was a very American choreographer who knew how to
distill the spirit of his time. But unlike others who created
ballets with pioneers and cowboys, Robbins did not indulge in
``Americana.'' He was not concerned with the myth of America but
with its reality.
</P>
<P>
   This genius for capturing the essence of an age was the Robbins
signature. It could be sensationally overt in a landmark Robbins
musical like ``West Side Story,'' with its indelible images of
1950s gang rumbles. But the same gift was even more vividly
expressed in any Robbins ballet, beginning with ``Fancy Free,'' an
evergreen masterpiece about three sailors on the town during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Starting out in Ballet Theater, now American Ballet Theater,
Robbins created ``Fancy Free'' in 1944 as his first ballet. The
score was by a fellow unknown, Leonard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   As the years went by, Robbins said he was more interested in a
world ``where things are not named,'' and his exploration of
ballet's classical idiom became more abstract and profound.
Nonetheless, he never lost sight of the pulse of his times. In the
epic ballets he created to music by Chopin and Bach, he extended
technical virtuosity and the art of partnering but also defined
contemporary encounters.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins' artistic voice was distinctly his own, dazzling in its
originality. Remarkably, and unlike other choreographers, he never
seemed to repeat himself, especially in his 66 ballets. The same
was true to a lesser degree in the 15 Broadway musicals he
choreographed and occasionally directed (he was also production
supervisor for ``Funny Girl''). Shows from ``West Side Story'' to
``Peter Pan'' made Robbins' name familiar to hundreds of thousands
in the 1950s and '60s, and yet all differed in tone and style.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Robbins was born to Harry and Lena Rabinowitz on Oct. 11,
1918, in New York City. Robbins and his parents changed the family
name legally in the 1940s. He grew up in Weehawken, N.J., and
briefly attended New York University.
</P>
<P>
   While at Ballet Theater and in his early years on Broadway,
Robbins was politically active. When called before the House
Committee on Un-American Activities in May 1953, the choreographer
said he had belonged to the American Communist Party's Theatrical
Transient Group between 1943 and 1947. Many in the arts never
forgave Robbins for naming eight colleagues as members of the
group.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, who was very private about his life, never married. He
is survived by his sister, Sonya Cullinen of Wilmington, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, after the City Ballet acquired a hit in ``West Side
Story Suite,'' based on dances from his show, Robbins had a heart
valve replaced. But in 1997, he finished a major work for the
company, ``Brandenburg,'' to the Bach concertos. During rehearsals,
he had said, ``I feel I have one more big ballet in me.'' It was
his last new work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
