<HEADER>
A8609 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLUE-MAN-APARTMENT-AR     07-29 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-MAN-APARTMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HAVEN FROM THE ROAR OF THE STREET AND FLYING GUM BALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By KIMBERLY STEVENS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Balls of blue paint sail and splatter. The players
catch marshmallows in their mouths and spew colored gum balls onto
the stage. At the Astor Place Theater here, during a typical Blue
Man Group performance, it's art as a kind of graduate-level
kindergarten. But when the head Blue Man, Chris Wink, gets home,
the scene changes markedly.
</P>
<P>
   One step in, and the frenetic city itself disappears. The floors
are painted a Creamsicle white. Windowpanes are frosted and cool,
like shaved ice. The ceiling has the faintest tint of blue, like
the gleam of a glacier. Refreshed, one seems to sense a drop in
body temperature of several degrees. Surfaces are rounded and
smooth, as though scooped, not constructed.
</P>
<P>
   Wink and his wife, Jen Graffam-Wink, a painter, have made their
800-square-foot apartment in a landmark building on Lafayette
Street a peaceful escape: a holiday from Wink's work a few steps
away. Call it light-Blue, like the tones of much of its pacific
palette.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theater is dark and industrial,'' said Wink, 37, one of
the three founding members of Blue Man Group, which began
performing 10 years ago. There are now 20 Blue Men in the extended
troupe, which performs nationally. ``I'm proud of that esthetic,
but I didn't want any trappings of Blue Man in the apartment. As
artists, you're sort of anti-materialist, but we wanted a space
that we looked forward to being in.''
</P>
<P>
   Two sculptors who became the Winks' designers helped them set
sail at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set out to create a light, airy, weightless environment,''
said one of them, Blake Moore. ``I think we made it feel like a
cloud.'' He and his partner, Christian Bunce, had both shown in
galleries. In the past year, they have begun to work together on
design projects. The Winks gave them their first full-house
assignment. The designers and their clients _ artists all _
considered the apartment an artists' collaboration as much as
design. That explains the originality of their resources _ from
bass-fishing-boat chairs to wrestling mats _ and their success.
</P>
<P>
   The Winks met when Ms. Graffam-Wink's mother took her to a
performance of Blue Man Group, where she was pulled onstage to eat
Twinkies with the troupe. She met Chris. They were married a year
ago. They rented the apartment below the one they were living in,
planning to renovate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking at a real challenge,'' Wink said. ``It was a
shell, with no kitchen or dining room, not a lot of space and some
odd architectural details.''
</P>
<P>
   But they were open to ideas. They were unafraid of excitement.
And they wanted something new: design as contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   It all began with the cabinets. Bunce's studio was close to Ms.
Graffam-Wink's. She mentioned that they needed someone to hang
kitchen cabinets. Bunce suggested himself and Moore as designers.
</P>
<P>
   Because there were now four artists' esthetics at work, the
designers presented the Winks with miniature prototypes of cabinets
that had interchangeable combinations of materials and colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of my work in theater, it was really important to
visualize our choices,'' Wink said. ``Going to see the prototype
was like going to look at an installation in a gallery. I was
really blown away.'' The presentation sold the work.
</P>
<P>
   What the four chose together managed to surprise everybody:
cabinets with a seamless appearance, made from sheets of
medium-density fiberboard (MDF) and painted with an automotive
lacquer in three delicate shades of blue and cream. The Plexiglas
doors were sanded with plastic kitchen abrasive pads to give them a
soft translucence. All edges of the cabinets were smoothed, to make
them look more molded than built and friendly to the touch.
</P>
<P>
   With the Winks' confidence growing, the job expanded one project
at a time, like a series of installations. During the next eight
months, Bunce and Moore designed the entire one-bedroom apartment
and much of its furniture. The collaborative spirit prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   As a continuation of the serenity that marked the project, the
designers created a dining room within one of two brick-arched
alcoves. With its low lacquered table and leather-seat chairs, it
is like a Japanese dining room _ a style that interested all four
artists. Rounded maple steps that lead up to it echo the alcove's
arch. The windows are frosted glass panes at the bottom half,
allowing light in but shielding an unsightly view. Bunce and Moore
designed and built the furniture. The low chairs are store-bought
stools with the legs cut short.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Graffam-Wink finds the table and chairs practical, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to finish dinner and lean back with your knees up,''
she said. ``It's incredibly comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunce said, ``We were constantly fiddling with scale.'' In these
experiments, playfulness began to creep into the apartment _ like
Blue Men _ in addition to the sophisticated calm spreading across
the walls and floors.
</P>
<P>
   In the bedroom, the designers created a bed the size of two
double beds. Call it the King Ultra. The rounded fiberboard bed
platform was painted a soft lime green. It also sits low, to
accommodate the Winks' two dachshunds, Boone and Thermis _ the
project's other collaborators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dogs were definitely a big consideration in the design of
the apartment,'' Moore said, referring to how low almost everything
is. Not just teahouse, but doghouse.
</P>
<P>
   And why such a big bed?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny,'' Wink said. ``It feels like Alice in
Wonderland. We wanted a bed large enough for us and the dogs.
Something that we could run and jump on.''
</P>
<P>
   The designers ordered wedge-shaped wrestling mats from Resilite,
a wrestling supply company in Sunbury, Pa., to use as dog ramps for
the bed and the couch. They also ordered a flat wrestling mat,
which they painted white, to use in the living room as a supple
area rug, where Ms. Graffam-Wink does her yoga.
</P>
<P>
   As with the wrestling supply company, the designers showed
resourcefulness, to say the least, with their other suppliers. They
spotted bass-fishing stools while leafing through the catalog of
the Bass Pro Shop, a fishing supply company in Springfield, Mo.
They bought them for the kitchen's work island. The air-piston
fishing chairs slide up and down, to eating level or living room
sitting level. They were $80 apiece _ cheap for a design original.
Complementing their functional directness, the kitchen counter tops
are hand-poured concrete.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to high craftsmanship, the designers' knowledge of
the art of sculpture brought an artist's understanding of materials
and a sense of perfectionism to the project, which the Winks
appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't understand something, we were smart enough to try
to figure it out,'' Bunce said. They created their own plastering
tool, for instance, because the smoothness of the finishes was so
important to the way they complemented one another.
</P>
<P>
   The four lived with an artist's risks too. Jobs took hours and
days longer than expected _ because of collaborative
experimentation, no one knew what to expect. There was never a
budget. The sculptors billed for materials and by the hour. The
serene dining corner was once blood orange. Bunce had to be coaxed
into painting the bed lime green. Days were as tiring as if the
work had been their own art, not renovation.
</P>
<P>
   The clients, artists themselves, were happy to deal with
obsession instead of the neglect that is typical in renovation war
stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just kept going over the ceiling over and over again,''
Wink said. ``When it was finally done, I understood. They created
it to feel like you were gazing up at the sky. The moment it had a
crack, it wouldn't have been a sacred place anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time anyone heard a contractor say that?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8613 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-NET-POLITICS-ART-     07-29 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NET-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS WOO VOTERS ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: S.C., Calif., Wis., Ala., Fla.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By REBECCA FAIRLEY RANEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phil Noble, president of Politics Online, a company in
Charleston, S.C., that provides Internet tools for politics, is
betting steak dinners these days on the following prediction: this
fall, he says, ``we're going to see the first candidate who won or
lost an election on the basis of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   He compares 1998 on the Internet to 1964 on television _ the
year Lyndon B. Johnson's campaign pummeled Barry M. Goldwater with
negative television advertising. Candidates who tap the Internet's
potential could be just as successful this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be some 32-year-old first-time candidate in a
statehouse or city council race who unseats an old white guy who's
been sitting there for 20 years and hasn't even heard of the
Internet _ and he'll never see it coming,'' Noble said. ``Every
newspaper in the country is going to do a story, and every
politician in the country is going to say, `I want to get me some
of that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Noble and other political consultants who use the Internet say
this is the first election year in which the Net can be considered
a mass medium. In California, the pioneering state in political
uses of the Internet, a recent Field Poll showed that 41 percent of
likely voters used e-mail and that 67 percent used a computer
regularly at home, work or school.
</P>
<P>
   Many political consultants predict that those proportions of
Internet use among voters will prevail nationwide in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Many others, however, say the Internet has not matured enough to
be an effective medium to convey political messages. The problem,
they say, is twofold: the Internet, unlike television, is not
universally available, and online information reaches only highly
interested voters.
</P>
<P>
   So strategists are turning to television to reach larger numbers
of potential voters, even though those viewers are likely to be
less interested in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``On TV, you decide you want to watch `Seinfeld,' and you get
our ad,'' said Mark Mellman, a Washington political consultant
whose clients have included Sens. Tom Daschle of South Dakota and
Barbara Boxer of California, both Democrats. ``The problem is, not
many people want political information. When you go to the Web, you
have to want to go to a political site.'' Still, he is keeping his
eye on the Internet numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is,'' Mellman said, ``as a tool of political
communication, the Internet today is of marginal value, but
increasing value.''
</P>
<P>
   Some signs of that increasing value are found in research
showing that more people are using the Internet this year to find
political information. Bruce Bimber, a political science professor
at the University of California at Santa Barbara, conducted a
nationwide telephone survey of 1,021 adults in February.
</P>
<P>
   In that survey, he found that 46 percent of adults nationwide
had access to the Internet and that the proportion of people
engaged in political uses of the Internet had roughly doubled since
a similar survey conducted before the elections of November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Bimber found that 17 percent of the respondents used
the Internet to express political views, to learn about political
issues, to browse for political information or to get in contact
with elected officials or candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, he considered 7 percent actively engaged; that group
had either made contact with an official on line or expressed an
opinion. Only 3 percent had done so in 1996. The survey drew from a
random sample that was weighted to reflect the adult population.
</P>
<P>
   The ``wired voters'' that Bimber and others are studying this
year may look a lot like Terry Rolland. Ms. Rolland, 45, is a
federal employee in Hayward, Calif., who is so busy with work and
night school that she had time for an interview only by e-mail. She
first went on line in the last year and says she spent many hours
researching candidates and ballot measures on the Internet before
the California primary.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns' use of the Internet played a critical role in her
decisions. She started by reading the official voter pamphlet and
narrowing the field of candidates based on their statements. After
narrowing the field, she researched the remaining candidates on
line. Here is how her system worked during the attorney general's
race:
</P>
<P>
   ``Using the Web addresses provided in the voter pamphlet,'' Ms.
Rolland wrote, ``I e-mailed each candidate and asked them to
address the 10 top questions that I was concerned with. One
candidate responded within 24 hours. Three others responded within
three days, and the final person did not respond until the day of
the election. My decision was made based on how they responded to
my questions and the time it took them to answer my e-mail.
Obviously, the last candidate was not considered because I had
already cast my ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   Highly motivated voters like Ms. Rolland are clearly rare. And
finding a target audience of likely voters on the Web is nearly
impossible. Doug Thompson, an associate with the Eddie Mahe Co., a
Washington consulting business whose clients have included Sens.
Conrad Burns of Montana and Slade Gorton of Washington, both
Republicans, said: ``There's just no way to know where all of that
effort is going. Right now, I can do more targeting with direct
mail and radio and television advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, few candidates running for high office this year are
neglecting the new medium. Though many campaigns are still
producing dull, static Web sites with only candidates' pictures and
biographies, the spirit of innovation is thriving.
</P>
<P>
   A tactic that is becoming common this year is the electronic
newsletter. From coast to coast, campaigns are attracting
subscribers on their Web sites. People receive weekly updates by
e-mail that keep the candidates' names in the minds of voters.
Aides in several statewide campaigns reported that their
newsletters had attracted 1,000 to 2,000 subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   That concept goes a step further on the Web site of Senator
Boxer. Visitors to her site can sign up others to get e-mail about
the senator. The feature has been used 50 to 60 times at the site
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Garvey, a Democratic candidate for governor of Wisconsin,
lists campaign contributors on line. The tactic furthers his
message on overhauling campaign finance laws. Garvey said
contributors did not mind being identified. In fact, being listed
seems to be an incentive for some to donate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got people saying, `Hey, I sent you $100 and I'm not on
the page,' '' Garvey said. Besides, the risk of listing
contributors is lower in his campaign than it might be in others.
``We're doing a $100 limit, so there's nothing interesting,''
Garvey said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the innovation this year is positive. The Internet's
capacity as a playground for pranks is nurturing dirty tricks as
well. In Alabama, on the day before the June 6 primary, someone
sent anonymous e-mail to 150 of the state's top Republican leaders
that smeared Jim Bennett, the Republican incumbent running for
secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail addresses of the recipients had been gathered from
the state Republican Party Web site. The message presented a phony
news story that said Bennett had switched back to the Democratic
Party. Bennett, like more than 50 officeholders in the state,
switched from the Democratic Party to the Republican Party in 1996,
and the move had been an issue in the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unexpected and disconcerting,'' Bennett said of the
e-mail, whose sender has not been identified. ``I don't know that
anybody took it seriously _ except us. Unfortunately there is no
way to control such things. That's the nature of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of the Internet, in this case, was that creating a
response was fast, cheap and easy. Bennett's aide, Cam Ward, sent
an e-mail to the 150 Republicans within two hours. It was directed
at the sender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations!'' Ward's response began. ``You have won the
prize for the lowest campaign tactic I have ever witnessed.''
Bennett won the primary.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most watched Web sites in politics is for the
campaign of Jeb Bush, the likely Republican nominee for governor of
Florida. Known as the ``Jeb site,'' it is the envy of Internet
political consultants, a $26,000 site in a field where $5,000 is
the going rate.
</P>
<P>
   Information is updated daily with pictures from the road. Bush's
aides carry two digital cameras. They take pictures at every stop,
then pop the disk from the camera into a laptop and post the
pictures on the site. The pictures are one of the site's top draws.
</P>
<P>
   The address for the site is integrated into all campaign
material, from letterheads to television commercials _ a concept
that sounds basic, but one that many campaigns have missed. Adding
features every few weeks has also helped make the site successful.
</P>
<P>
   The latest innovation scheduled to go live on the site sometime
this summer is the Marvin the Dog Chat Room, where visitors can
converse with the Bush family pet. Marvin is also featured in
television ads, and plans for the Web site include adding video
clips of the dog in action.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in regard to the chat room feature, Bush had a
confession. ``I think someone will interpret for Marvin,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
