<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8618 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STILGOE-LANDSCAPE-ART     07-29 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STILGOE-LANDSCAPE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LARGE IN THE SMALL: THE ART OF NOTICING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By PHIL PATTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apple-green paint fascinates John R. Stilgoe, the professor of
landscape history at Harvard. He sometimes finds it inside the
cupboards or broom closets of old kitchens, a token of the 1920s, a
time when that color was thought to be soothing to the soul. Public
schools wore that green; its relative survives in too many halls
under the name ``landlord green.''
</P>
<P>
   Stilgoe's eye for such things begins in the home, strides across
the porch, strolls Main Street, and bicycles breezily past strip
malls to the edge of the Interstates. His evocative new book,
``Outside Lies Magic: Regaining History and Awareness in Everyday
Places'' (Walker), is less a guide than a tool for seeing, like a
pair of binoculars taken on vacation for bird-watching.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a clarion call to what he calls, almost mystically,
``exploration'' _ wandering on foot or bike, in search not of
cardiovascular fitness but of mental agility. Ultimately, it's
about becoming the proverbial person on whom nothing is lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get out now,'' he exhorts readers, ``not just outside, but
beyond the trap of the programmed electronic age.''
</P>
<P>
   Stilgoe is part of a new flowering of interest in looking at how
culture shapes the wide, mundane world around us. The principal
founder of modern landscape thinking and looking was the late J.B.
Jackson, the author of ``The Necessity for Ruins, and Other
Topics'' and the founder of Landscape magazine. He was praised by
the architect Robert Venturi as a prophet who inspired him to look
again at Main Street and Route 66. Stilgoe was Jackson's only
doctoral student at Harvard, and today, his course, nicknamed ``Gas
Stations,'' is regularly oversubscribed.
</P>
<P>
   Stilgoe looks under, behind, beneath and beside what most people
overlook. He explains how the American house tends to have light
and openness on four sides, a legacy of placing the dwelling in the
middle of the property, the better to get to its distant reaches;
European houses sat on the edge of their much smaller plots.
``Letting light and wind strike all four sides of a house remains
peculiarly American,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   He records how a small thing like angled parking can lure
customers to shops on languishing Main Streets. Malls, he says,
have killed the skill of parallel parking. He points out that since
fear arose about electromagnetic radiation, luxury homes and condos
are not built anywhere near power lines. And he explains why
fast-food chains use only dwarf evergreens so that they can
landscape instantly and never prune thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   But Stilgoe's specific observations constitute examples to
illustrate a method, not a thesis; his book is a guide for the
private eye in the public realm. His point about apple green is
less about the specific color _ a neon pink is now in fashion as a
calming hue in police stations and the admitting rooms of
mental-health clinics _ than about the survival of old paint
schemes in hidden places, places that require notice.
</P>
<P>
   Stilgoe's own exploring began as a boy in Norwell, Mass., south
of Boston, where he still lives. When he was 13, his parents gave
him a Raleigh bicycle. He said he acquired his eye and interest
from his mother, who ``had always been someone who noticed
things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a theory,'' he said, ``that noticing is part of what
used to be called feminine intuition. Women were more discerning
than the men, who were so busy doing. They transmitted that to
children.'' This pattern holds less true today, he said, because
more mothers are working.
</P>
<P>
   Being a noticer, Stilgoe said, is a secret to success in many
areas. A former Stilgoe student, now a physician, linked a series
of aches and pains his male patients reported to their wallets:
spending more time in the car, sitting on fatter wallets, they
found their legs growing numb.
</P>
<P>
   He urges, too, the importance of seeing what is absent: no weeds
at the edges of fast-food restaurants (gravel and black plastic
sheeting beneath keep them down); no shrubs more than knee-high,
the better to reassure customers that no carjacker can lurk.
``Discerning what is not in the picture enables the explorer to
make connections,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   A characteristic Stilgoe moment comes in his discussion of
fences. Cedar fences took over suburban backyards in the 1960s, he
notes, marking property rather than providing privacy. By walking
or biking rapidly, one can see through their cracks into the yards
beyond _ the picket-fence effect. This is his method in a nutshell:
the full picture, chink by narrow chink, rendered with the magic of
a nickelodeon _ noticing made dramatic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
