<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BANK-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANYONE CAN DIAL IN FOR YOUR DOLLARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LAURIE J. FLYNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To most people, few things are more private than their money _
such as how much they have and where they keep it. But with the
help of just a touch-tone telephone, some banks permit just about
anyone to learn the approximate balance of a checking account.
</P>
<P>
   Using a decades-old system reserved for small businesses called
merchant check verification, someone with enough curiosity can
simply call the bank's customer service line, input the customer
account number printed at the bottom of a check and input a dollar
amount. (Some banks require a check number as well; some don't.)
</P>
<P>
   The system then tells the caller whether the amount is in the
account. After a half-dozen or so inquiries involving different
amounts, the caller can typically learn approximately how much
money is in the account.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of a handful of banks proved how easy it was. The
automated system at Chase Bank, for example, asks for a check
number, but from there it was easy to guess other check numbers and
request verification of other amounts. Within a few minutes, we had
learned roughly how much money was in the account.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America's merchant check verification system was equally
easy to manipulate, as was that of Wells Fargo Bank.
</P>
<P>
   It proved more difficult to get the same information through the
merchant check services of a credit union, because a live bank
representative handled the call.
</P>
<P>
   To some privacy rights advocates, this is just one example of a
system in dire need of better controls. One concern is that
manipulating such a system will become even simpler as banks move
more of their consumer operations online. Someone could then,
conceivably, write a software program to automatically check the
balance of a certain account.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it quite bothersome because how much money you have is
one of the most private things,'' said Brad Templeton, a board
member of the Electronic Frontier Foundation. ``And then to find
out it's not really a secret at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Mierzwinsky, consumer programs director for CALPIRG, a
consumer watchdog group in Washington, said he thought merchant
check systems could add better controls, such as automatically
shutting down after someone makes more than one entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, companies have the right to reduce their risk,'' he
said. ``But it should be a `go-no go' thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all privacy advocates view the merchant check system as
all that bad. Marc Rotenberg of EPIC, a leading privacy rights
organization in Washington, D.C., said he thought the system
adequately protected privacy rights because it gave merchants the
least amount of information available.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to manipulate it by inputting multiple check numbers was
``a little like trying all possible combinations on a lock on a
suitcase,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, a spokesman for Wells Fargo Bank in San Francisco
said that the phone-in system is quickly being replaced by
point-of-sale technology that automates the check verification
process. In the meantime, the bank isn't aware of abuses to the
system, which it has used in some form for nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, view it as just one example of the need for
better privacy controls in banking. ``That's just one of the flaws
in the banking system,'' Mierzwinsky said. ``This is where things
are headed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1650EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
