<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8625 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SHOPPING-ROBOTS-N     07-29 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SHOPPING-ROBOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROBOTS THAT RUMMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instead of letting their fingers do the walking through the
Yellow Pages to get information from merchants, many consumers now
let a software robot do the crawling to find bargains on line.
</P>
<P>
   So-called softbots, or bots, are software programs that go out
to numerous Web sites at once and come back with search results.
They can reach into the more obscure crevices of the Internet as
well as regular Web pages. Think of it as a wild pack of
investigative reporters doing your bidding at a click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more useful bots is www.acses.com, which will search
about 25 online bookstores for the title you desire. It first
displays how many vendors have been polled and how long your search
will take. Its searches include foreign sites, so users in the
United States have to proceed through an extra screen to indicate
which currency they want their quotes in, but it is probably worth
the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The site provides a comprehensive listing, from cheapest to most
expensive, listing prices, delivery costs and estimated times of
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Jango (jango.excite.com), one of the earliest softbots,
presented quick information on computers and fragrances recently on
this user's first experiments with it. But the results could not be
replicated in later tries because of to snoozing servers or
shifting availability.
</P>
<P>
   Jango, which was developed at the University of Washington, goes
to several hundred stores and several auction and review sites, and
it can search the hidden Web (databases not accessible through the
common search engines).
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really nice about Jango is you're contacting sites in
real time so you can get up-to-the-minute information,'' said one
of Jango's inventors, Oren Etzioni. ``That's important with stores
and essential with auctions. Others get the information once a
night _ every night you send a copy of your catalog to the softbot
_ which means the information will not be as up to date.''
</P>
<P>
   Another softbot, Junglee (www.junglee.com), provides six sites
willing to serve your shopping needs _ Web Market, Yahoo Travel,
Yahoo Visa Shopping Guide, Hotbot, Snap and Compaq, though it can
be hard to tell which one is best for a particular item. The Compaq
site, for example, has searchable categories ranging from apparel
to outdoor gear, as well as electronics.
</P>
<P>
   A downside to the bots: you do not always know if you are
surfing the entire Web or just the merchants who have paired up
with particular search sites.
</P>
<P>
   Jango is working on a version that will allow shoppers to do
one-click ordering from within Jango without having to go to the
store's ordering page.
</P>
<P>
   So where's the superbot that searches all these sites, then
searches your house or apartment to see what you really, really
need?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8626 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WEB-DADS-NYT &LR;      07-29 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-DADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE NEW DADS CAN GO ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a proud first-time father _ one too proud, perhaps, to ask
his partner or own parents about such tricks of the trade as
eliciting the perfect burp _ the shelves of any bookstore can offer
a stack of road maps, yet few written for anyone other than the
mother.
</P>
<P>
   But any new father who chooses, instead, to cruise the Internet
in search of guidance and solace, long after mother and infant have
retired for the night, should be forewarned that the path is muddy.
</P>
<P>
   For example, punching the phrase ``new dad'' into Dogpile.com, a
compendium of various search engines, quickly turns up numerous
sites devoted to fathers seeking to win back custody of children
lost in bitter divorces. Hardly the sort of stuff that should be
occupying the mind of the bewildered parent of a 7-day old.
</P>
<P>
   Forging on, there is A Man's Life (http://www.manslife.com),
which, in its ``family forum'' the other day, posted a message from
a new dad seeking the counsel of others on how long to wait to
circumcise a new son. A thought-provoking discussion, to be sure,
but one that had difficulty competing with the nearby notices from
women advocating that their partners sleep in the nude. (``It
always leads to sex,'' wrote someone named Tahlia. ``And good sex,
at that!'') Again, probably not what the new father should be
thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   The web site of Fathering Magazine (http://www.fathermag.com),
would seem to offer few such distractions. The site contains
articles dating back to July 1995 on topics like ``Long-Distance
Daddy'' and ``Who Are the Child Snatchers?'' but virtually the only
material that is geared strictly to new fathers is poetry written
for them. One entry, ``Our Baby Is a Boy,'' by A.A. Talbert,
begins:
</P>
<P>
   Today we found out that our baby is a boy
</P>
<P>
   In spite of holding back our wish it charged our joy
</P>
<P>
   The doctor took a picture showed his beating heart
</P>
<P>
   And showed the little place at which his manhood starts.
</P>
<P>
   But just when all hope of finding practical help seems lost, two
home pages beckon, like warm bottles of formula.
</P>
<P>
   One, www.babycenter.com, has a special section devoted to ``new
dads.'' Its index includes such topics as ``How to bond with your
baby'' (two suggestions, from a new mother, of course: ``Take a
bath together'' and ``Have a staring contest''), as well as tips on
``Sex after baby.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also a place to relay questions to experts and a huge
online store.
</P>
<P>
   If babycenter.com is like a Wal-Mart for new fathers, then
Raffaelle Borelli's home page is the neighborhood hardware store.
</P>
<P>
   Borelli, an amateur magician and science teacher from the small
Canadian town of Portage la Prairie, 60 miles outside Winnipeg,
writes that ``being a new dad, I discovered there was a variety of
information available for the new father (but you had to look real
hard).''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I decided to do,'' he adds, ``was pool some of this
information together.''
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1995, Borelli, then the father of a new
daughter, Victoria, inaugurated the Web site Dads Den
(http://megamach.portage.net/rborelli/dads.html). On the site,
Borelli has organized his material under user-friendly headings
like ``Colic: how to deal with that dreadful crying'' and ``Diaper
rash: preventing it, and dealing with it.'' Under ``diaper rash,''
Borelli passes on such clinical advice as how to wipe a baby girl,
from front to back, to minimize the spread of germs and infection.
He also suggests using athlete's foot cream for rash relief.
</P>
<P>
   In recommending ways to distract a colicky baby, there are the
usual gimmicks, such as turning on a vacuum cleaner, but also a
recipe: ``Boil a half-cup of water with one bay leaf. Let cool for
15 minutes. Remove leaf and give to baby in bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   Borelli's site has received nearly 21,000 hits _ and 300
questions conveyed via e-mail _ since its debut.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some new mothers out there, at least those with
computer-literate husbands, have been able to get a little sleep
after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
