<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HISTORY-CDROM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MULTIMEDIA ENCYCLOPEDIA OF BLACK HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henry Louis Gates Jr., an academic all-star, chairman of Harvard
University's African-American studies department and a staff writer
for The New Yorker, is rarely short of ideas. But the inspiration
for his current big project _ a comprehensive reference work on
Africa and people of African descent _ goes back nearly a century,
to W.E.B. Du Bois, who first advanced the notion of an
``Encyclopedia Africana'' in 1909.
</P>
<P>
   Du Bois envisioned the project as an act of progressive
scholarship. ``He believed that you could help defeat racism if you
could codify the knowledge of the black experience, undermining all
sorts of stupid myths and prejudices,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   Gates has pursued the Du Bois vision in the same spirit, though
he also has technological and entrepreneurial ambitions. His
encyclopedia, Encarta Africana, is a collaboration between a team
led by Gates and Kwame Anthony Appiah, a Harvard professor of
African-American studies and philosophy, and Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Work on the multimedia encyclopedia began two years ago and
Gates has made no secret of his venture with Microsoft. Encarta
Africana is being formally announced Thursday at the National
Association of Black Journalists convention in Washington. The
CD-ROM encyclopedia will go on sale next January with an estimated
retail price of $50, after a $20 rebate offer.
</P>
<P>
   Later in 1999, a text version of the encyclopedia is expected to
be published by Perseus Book Co. Yet if recent trends in reference
works, especially encyclopedias, are any guide, it will be the
multimedia version played on personal computers that attracts by
far the largest audience and sales.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, the multimedia encyclopedias have overrun their
print predecessors. The early multimedia works were limited and
often shunned as playthings by teachers and librarians. But such
products have improved greatly, partly because of increased data
storage capacity, links to the Internet and the migration of
traditional encyclopedia editors into the new media field.
</P>
<P>
   Encarta Africana will include 2 million words of text in more
than 3,000 articles and more than 2,500 multimedia entries _ video
clips, audio recordings and maps. ``It goes from early humans in
Africa millions of years ago to today, from Lucy to rap music,''
Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   His subject, Gates says, lends itself particularly to the
multimedia format. ``Where African-Americans have excelled,
especially in the 20th century, are in the expressive arts of
dance, jazz and entertainment, which do not lend themselves to
text,'' he observed. ``You can write all you want about Billie
Holliday or Duke Ellington, but the only way to truly understand
what they accomplished is to listen to their music. Ninety years
later, the technology has caught up with W.E.B. Du Bois' dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates also said that he hopes his multimedia encyclopedia will
help draw more African-Americans into the computer age. Several
studies have shown that African-American children are less likely
to use computers or have access to the Internet than other American
children. The main reason, of course, is that a higher proportion
of African-Americans live in low-income families and neighborhoods
than whites. But some research has also shown that even adjusted
for income, black families are less likely to have computers in
their homes than whites.
</P>
<P>
   Gates said he hopes that his multimedia encyclopedia can help
stir technological enthusiasm within the black community, as well
as efforts to put more computers in schools and libraries in
predominantly African-American neighborhoods. ``I want Encarta
Africana to seduce our people further into using computers and help
them become more computer literate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An early glimpse of Encarta Africana was presented to a panel at
the American Library Association's annual conference in June.
Initial impressions were positive. ``What I saw was very
professional,'' said Pam Berger, a librarian at Byram Hills High
School in Armonk, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   In academic circles, questions have been raised about whether
Gates, 47, given his many ventures, would be able to give enough
first-hand attention to the huge reference project. Not a problem,
Gates said during a telephone interview on Wednesday from
Johannesburg, where he was finishing up the filming of a BBC-PBS
documentary series, tentatively titled ``Into Africa With Henry
Louis Gates Jr.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I carry the articles with me on my IBM laptop, take notes and
get back to the writers,'' Gates said. ``I'm through about 1.1
million words by now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
