<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIP TO SHORE E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT, in parentheses, has been used
in the end note instead of the symbol, which is non-transmittable
to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 J.D. BIERSDORFER  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My brother wishes to meet a writing deadline via e-mail while
crossing the Atlantic Ocean by ship. How is this best done from a
laptop, and what are the expected costs?
</P>
<P>
   A. Many large cruise ships have fax machines, telephones and
e-mail access for passengers to use. Your brother should call the
ship's operating company to find out what equipment is available on
board the ship he's taking and what software he might need on his
laptop to use various services.
</P>
<P>
   While most ships don't have e-mail access directly from
passenger staterooms, arrangements can usually be made with the
vessel's radio room to use a satellite modem with a guest's laptop
computer. Connection time will cost from $7 to $10 per minute.
</P>
<P>
   If your brother is taking a ship with fewer technical perks, his
options are much pricier because satellite access and special
equipment are needed. The transceiver that attaches to the laptop
and is needed to send and receive data via satellite, plus the
required antenna, can cost well over $3,000. That price does not
include access to an Internet service provider, and connection
charges can run about $3 per minute.
</P>
<P>
   More information on these marine devices is available on the Web
at www.elec-unlimited.com and www.landseasystems.com.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to QandA(AT)nytimes.com or postal mail to Questions,
Circuits, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St., New York, N.Y.
10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
