<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8633 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TOM-CLANCY-GAME-2     07-29 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TOM-CLANCY-GAME-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CLANCYLAND, A GAME-TO-NOVEL PIPELINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tina, Tom Clancy beat you to it.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, feeling the need to have his motors raced, so
to speak, the all-star author embarked on a new media venture, Red
Storm Entertainment, whose stated mission is ``to develop and
publish stimulating entertainment for multiple media.''
</P>
<P>
   With imperial backing from Pearson PLC, Red Storm produces
digital media projects that morph into all sorts of juicy ancillary
cash spinners: books, movies, board games, strategy guides, action
figures and other globally distributed merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Red Storm will release Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six
CD-ROM (for Windows 95, $49.95), a counterterrorism strategy action
game, with a multimillion-dollar cross-promotional marketing
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the company's mandate for synergy, the PC game
will be released in conjunction with a hardback novel of the same
title, based on the game, also written by Clancy and published
under the Berkley imprint by Penguin Putnam, a book tentacle of
Pearson's media empire. Movie discussions are under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to rely on one revenue stream,'' explained Doug
Littlejohns, a former British submarine captain and longtime Clancy
technical adviser who is now Red Storm's chief executive. ``What
we're trying to do here is approach the market with a broad aim and
establish Rainbow Six as a brand, of which the book is a major
component and probably the biggest money spinner. But there are
many other issues to contemplate. We're certainly going to do a
sequel. Having established the brand Rainbow Six, we'll be able to
extend the franchise even further.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other game-book-merchandise clusters are scheduled for
release in the fall. Behold, the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of the Rainbow Six product line _ the game _ is
a classic piece of Clancyana, a geopolitical action thriller in
which the player leads a counterterrorism task force. Choosing from
a crack team of 20 skilled international operatives, each with a
unique skill, you assign the personnel and plot their military
advances on a blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   The game segues into high-adrenaline real-time action mode, and
you do your best to take out the terrorists, rescue the hostages
and get out alive. As the game progresses, isolated terrorist
incidents form the outlines of a more cohesive and sinister plot of
global proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these episodes is highly interactive, from the blueprint
phase to the crisis decisions and gunplay. But the story _ the
mission sequence and the culmination of events _ moves forward
along a non-negotiable arc.
</P>
<P>
   By stringing these self-contained missions, in which the player
has lots of control, into a modular story, the game creates the
illusion that the player is immersed in an interactive drama. The
enemy plot unfolds. Incidents acquire a critical mass and forward
momentum, and you are carried along.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible to fail _ if you lose your sniper and your
safecracker in an early mission and you need those pivotal people
in mission 10, you're in trouble. But the story never branches. The
challenge is basically to get through it, to barrel through to the
end. It's as linear, in its own way, as a movie or a novel.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of computer game that is easily turned into a
Clancy novel, for the same reason that Clancy novels are easily
translated into films. These stories are not heavily psychological.
They're not scenic. They're not about language. They're about
action. They're driven by strategy and driven by technology _ there
is always something to pick up, fire, launch or drive, and an array
of buttons to push.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And the characters navigate through these gear-laden
environments through a series of action sequences. It's not hard
for them to leap, as the bomb ticks down, from Clancy's literary
universe into the context of a computer game. Or vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Rainbow Six,'' the novel, ``I started off with
the two principal characters, John Clark and Domingo Chavez, and
their thoughts, and how they're developing as characters,'' Clancy
said. ``Which is something you don't put into the game because the
characters are the people playing the game. But generally speaking,
they're faced with the same tactical situations as John and Domingo
are faced with, and they have to find their way out.''
</P>
<P>
   Novelizations are not new, of course, even in the computer game
world. This one just happens to be written by one of the most
bankable authors on Earth and promises to be the first book on The
New York Times best-seller list to be excerpted in PC Gamer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the CD-ROM stands to benefit enormously from the
publicity surrounding a blockbuster book tour. ``I think Penguin's
going to make me do it,'' Clancy said with a sigh. ``It's sort of
the literary equivalent of being held by Abu Nidal.''
</P>
<P>
   The author makes a show of stoically submitting to the ordeal of
it all, but methinks he protests too much. If there is any hostage
here, it's Penguin Putnam because, at this point, Tom Clancy is
running his own media company.
</P>
<P>
   Red Storm is developing other people's content _ Anne McCaffrey
just sold them the rights to develop her staggeringly commercial
fantasy sci-fi universe into a line of products.
</P>
<P>
   The company is releasing a volley of non-Clancy products in the
fall and has struck alliances with IBM, Microsoft and AT&AMP;T
Worldnet; the latter deal delivers Worldnet as the ``preferred,''
instantly clickable Internet provider to Red Storm online gamers.
</P>
<P>
   When your company is leveraging digital content and signing
telecommunications deals, you're not a part of the publishing
economy anymore. You're a part of the Internet economy. Clancy has
reached escape velocity. He doesn't need a publisher. He is a
publisher. He needs a distributor for the dead-tree version of his
product.
</P>
<P>
   But in a concentrated media industry utterly dependent on
name-brand stars, Rainbow Six is Clancy's pie to slice, and Penguin
Putnam can take it or leave it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's probably one of the reasons why Pearson
invested in the company,'' Littlejohns said. ``They can see the
change in media. And here was an opportunity to work right across
the Pearson empire.''
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent tribute to its own media machinations, Red Storm
will be releasing a game entitled Ruthless.com in November. In the
words of Littlejohns: ``Ruthless is warfare in business. The back
story is that you are the CEO of a small electronics company. There
are five other companies in the game. One of them is called Evil
Soft. I'm not telling you where it's based, but it is the largest,
and it's trying to take over the world and crush you. So what you
do in Ruthless the game is all the things that every businessman
would ever like to do but can't because of law. So you can team up
with other CEOs, you can assassinate CEOs, you can burn their
buildings down, you can hack into their equipment, you can steal
their money. It appeals to the most base instincts of the average
businessman.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy was quick to add, ``We're trying to make a movie out of
this one, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
