<HEADER>
A8653 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAR-STOCK30-COX     07-29 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAR-STOCK30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golden Bear stock remains frozen; shareholders file suit
 &HT;    By Danielle Herubin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Trading of Golden Bear Golf Inc. stock
remained halted on the 28th for the same reason that a
shareholders' lawsuit was filed against Jack Nicklaus' North Palm
Beach-based company: The company said former employees falsified a
subsidiary's records, hiding nearly $22 million in losses.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was stopped at 2:45 p.m. Monday, July 27, on the Nasdaq
exchange, with Golden Bear stock (JACK) at $4 a share. It will
remain halted until Golden Bear can satisfy Nasdaq's request for
additional news, according to a Nasdaq statement.
</P>
<P>
   National Association of Securities Dealers spokesman Reid Walker
said it is typical to halt trading in a stock with ''material
news.'' Nasdaq's Stock Watch Department makes the decision, and
typically resumes trading after the news ''has been fully
disseminated over the news wires.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court for the
Southern District of Florida in West Palm Beach, seeks class action
status for all of Golden Bear's investors who wish to join the
lawsuit. It was filed by the Pennsylvania law firm Schiffrin Craig
&AMP; Barroway.
</P>
<P>
   ''The case is simple. They misstated their earnings,'' said
Andrew Barroway, the attorney handling the case. ''We're basically
trying to get back the investors' money.''
</P>
<P>
   The action came one day after Golden Bear announced it would
restate its losses for last year because it had discovered a former
manager had falsified records, hiding nearly $22 million in losses
of its Paragon Construction International unit.
</P>
<P>
   The company had originally reported a net loss of $2.9 million,
or 53 cents a share, on revenues of $67.7 million. The restated
loss will be $24.7 million, or $4.49 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Bear has said it began looking at the projects and the
books of its subsidiary, Paragon Construction International unit,
after it began losing some big deals due to disagreements and
delays. Paragon President John Boyd and three other executives left
the company in April before the review began.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Bear officials did not return repeated calls for comment,
and Boyd could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The company has not named the employees it is accusing of
falsifying records.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
