<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-BJT30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE THURSDAY BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Thursday, July 30, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   PBP-POWER-PLANT-SALE (10 inches) _ Indiantown, Fla. _ Two
leading developers of power plants are close to selling stakes in
Indiantown Cogeneration Ltd., which owns a coal-fired cogeneration
power plant in Indiantown, for an undisclosed price. San
Francisco-based Bechtel Enterprises will sell its entire stake in
the partnership, 10 percent, to a division of Cogentrix Energy,
while Bethesda, Md.-based U.S. Generating Co. LLC will sell
one-fifth of its 50 percent stake to DCC Project Finance Twelve, a
subsidiary of Dana Credit Corp. (Bhatt, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   CASUAL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ If employees at Comerica Bank in Austin
look unlike those at any other bank, you're not imagining things.
Gone are the dark _ some people say somber _ pinstripe suits that
can be seen soaking up perspiration as bankers stroll down Congress
Avenue at lunch hour in triple digit heat. Gone are the tie and
stiff-starched, long-sleeve, white shirt. ForComercia's 60 Austin
area employees it's casual dress day every day, five days a week
(Keefe, Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GM _ Strong folo on the GM-UAW settlement. Workers in Flint
expected to approve settlement, setting stage for local workers to
return to work. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BEAR-STOCK _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Trading of Golden Bear Golf
Inc. stock remained halted Tuesday, July 28, for the same reason
that a shareholders' lawsuit was filed against Jack Nicklaus' North
Palm Beach-based company: The company said former employees
falsified a subsidiary's records, hiding nearly $22 million in
losses. (Herubin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
