<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8665 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COACHWIITA-PLEA30-COX     07-29 1998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COACHWIITA-PLEA30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soccer coach hopes to clear his name with new trial
 &HT;    By Christine Stapleton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH PALM BEACH, Fla. _ At the time _ with his wife's pregnancy
in jeopardy, his brother dying of AIDS and his business on the
skids _ Bruce Brian Wiita figured he was doing the right thing when
he pleaded guilty to having sex with a 15-year-old baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   Wiita, a North Palm Beach real-estate agent, said he is
innocent. But the 1991 plea bargain would let him keep his record
clean if he could complete 10 years probation.
</P>
<P>
   Now Wiita says he didn't get what he'd bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   How could he have known that six years after he accepted the
plea deal, lawmakers would pass a law that required Wiita's name
and photo to be posted on the Internet? A law that required telling
his neighbors and the parents of children he coaches on youth
soccer and Little League teams that he had been dubbed a sex
offender? Wiita, 39, is trying to clear his name. He's hired a
public relations expert and adept lawyers. His lawyer has written
letters to probation officials and neighbors, warning them not to
spread misinformation, he said. And Wiita wants his day in court.
</P>
<P>
   In June, a judge allowed Wiita to cancel his plea bargain,
meaning the case begins again. Prosecutors are appealing, but as
details of Wiita's situation unfold, more questions are being
raised about how Wiita's case has been handled: _ Wiita was twice
arrested for violating his probation, a charge that normally
requires a defendant to be held without bond until a judge
schedules a court appearance. But Wiita was freed within hours of
each arrest.
</P>
<P>
   _ Although Wiita was found guilty of violating his probation, he
still has no felony conviction.
</P>
<P>
   _ For his battle to withdraw his plea, Wiita hired Richard
Lubin, a friend of State Attorney Barry Krischer. After several
phone calls from Lubin, Krischer decided to take no position on
Wiita's request to take back his plea.
</P>
<P>
   _ Krischer, who had defended two of Wiita's brothers in criminal
cases before he was elected State Attorney in 1992, saw no conflict
in getting involved in Wiita's case this year.
</P>
<P>
   If prosecutors lose their appeal and are forced to take Wiita to
trial, they face other hurdles: the he-said, she-said nature of the
case, the victim and the evidence. The woman, now 22, threatened to
sue Wiita after he pleaded guilty. To avoid a lawsuit, Wiita paid
the woman an undisclosed settlement and she agreed not to discuss
the case, according to Wiita and prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The baby sitter and her lawyer declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they would have to get a court order to force
the victim to testify about what happened at Wiita's home on Dec.
29, 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the problem of the evidence. After Wiita pleaded
guilty in 1991, the evidence _ panties the baby sitter was wearing
that night _ were destroyed. Assistant State Attorney Darren Shull
said that shouldn't affect the case because the panties had ``no
evidentiary value'' since no semen was found on them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lubin plans to investigate whether his inability to have
his own experts examine the lost evidence hurts Wiita's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Wiita's decision to withdraw his plea and reopen the case comes
after years of trying to avoid publicity. The only reason Wiita
accepted the plea was to avoid the publicity and stress of a trial,
Lubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Wiita knows that his decision to go to trial now has brought him
more notoriety than if he had stuck with his plea deal and accepted
the notification law. Still, he doesn't regret it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was probably one time in life I rolled over,'' Wiita said
of his plea deal. ``This is a travesty and I'm not going to roll
over anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was arrested in February 1991, his wife had already had
four miscarriages and was pregnant again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met with various doctors and no one could assure us we
wouldn't lose another child from the stress,'' Wiita said in a
recent interview. ``Do you risk that for your wife?'' She later
delivered the baby.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1991, Wiita agreed to plead guilty to lewd assault and
sexual activity with a child. In exchange, he agreed to:
</P>
<P>
   _ serve 10 years probation
</P>
<P>
   _ pay court costs and the baby sitter's therapy bills
</P>
<P>
   _ have a psychological evaluation
</P>
<P>
   _ refrain from unsupervised contact with children unless a
psychologist approved.
</P>
<P>
   Wiita also won a concession: Probation officers would be barred
from contacting him at home or work and would have to rely on Wiita
to contact them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day I went to see my probation officer he said, `I
can't live with this,' '' Wiita said.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1991, Wiita's probation officer said Wiita had
failed to report on time, make a weekly call to his probation
officer while on vacation and pay a fine, court costs and
restitution, according to a probation report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The subject has been arrogant, vindictive and manipulative
throughout his brief and unsuccessful probation,'' probation
officer David Denler wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Denler recommended revoking Wiita's probation and sending him to
prison for 10 years: ``It is clear that he believes society's rules
and court's orders do not apply to himself.''
</P>
<P>
   At 7 p.m. on Sept. 11, 1991, Wiita was arrested on the probation
violation charge.
</P>
<P>
   People accused of violating their probation are not entitled to
bond. Barring a special arrangement, most defendants are stuck in
jail without bond until a judge can schedule a hearing days _
sometimes weeks _ later, probation officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Yet two hours later, Wiita was free on bail. His attorney, David
Roth, made an arrangement with a prosecutor that was approved by a
judge earlier in the day for Wiita to be released on $10,000 bond,
court records show.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1992, the charge was withdrawn. Wiita's probation was
reinstated with new rules: Probation officers could now contact
Wiita at home and get written verification of his travel plans.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year later, Wiita was wrangling with his new
probation officer, Martha Tyndal. Wiita had not done any of the 500
hours of community service ordered for his first five years of
probation.
</P>
<P>
   Wiita was coaching youth soccer and Little League, but wouldn't
claim it as community service because his probation officer would
have to tell team officials of his case, according to probation
reports. Tyndal said she was ``not going to play games'' and set a
court date.
</P>
<P>
   At an October 1992 hearing, Circuit Judge James R. Stewart Jr.
told Wiita that ``he doesn't get to tell the Probation Department
what to do.'' Stewart also told Tyndal to file a violation report.
</P>
<P>
   Tyndal reported that Wiita had been argumentative and combative,
saying, ``He insists on doing things `his way.' '' Witta was
arrested at 2:15 p.m. on Oct. 30, 1992. By 4 p.m., Roth reached an
agreement with another prosecutor to set a $10,000 bond. Wiita, who
had been facing a weekend in jail, was released later that Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judge Edward Rodgers, who has since retired, found that
Wiita had violated his probation. But Rodgers agreed to put him
back on probation and to withhold convictions on the original sex
charges and probation violation. He also ordered that soccer and
baseball team officials be told of Wiita's case.
</P>
<P>
   Krischer wasn't in office when Wiita was arrested on the
probation violation charges. If Wiita were arrested on those
charges today, Krischer said, he never would have gotten out of
jail so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the policy we put in place, everybody has to stay in
jail, go see the judge the next morning, and then we'll talk about
bond,'' Krischer said. Otherwise, ``the rich, white guys with
lawyers get out right away and the poor minorities would be stuck
in jail overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   In December 1993, Wiita received a psychologist's approval to
work, unsupervised, with children. He did well on probation for the
next four years, although he didn't like his probation officer
calling his home.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, Wiita's new probation officer told him to have
his photo taken for the Florida Department of Law Enforcement's Web
site listing of sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   After his photo was taken, Wiita hired attorney Jack Scarola,
who wrote to probation officials. Wiita was not a sex offender,
Scarola wrote, and should not be on the Internet: ``We trust that
you will take appropriate steps to be certain that no mistake
occurs . . . an error would obviously be devastating to Mr.
Wiita.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials disagreed. Wiita's photo appeared on the Internet
and was posted in the North Palm Beach Police Department, where a
den mother escorting her Cub Scout troop saw it. Neighbors and
parents began to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Wiita decided to move out of North Palm Beach and started trying
to clear his name. Wiita's wife, Cinde, said the family moved to
Singer Island primarily because their home was being renovated.
However, Wiita's probation officer reported that Wiita had ``moved
simply while he is in this legal bind, and claims when he untangles
the situation with community notification, he will move back.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiita also hired Richard Lubin, a prominent West Palm Beach
criminal defense attorney, who in turn called Krischer.
</P>
<P>
   Krischer said he decided to get involved because Wiita's case
could set a statewide legal precedent. If Wiita was allowed to
abandon his plea, other defendants could also try to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Although Krischer had defended Wiita's brothers in a petty theft
case and a misdemeanor drug case before being elected, he saw no
conflict in getting involved in Wiita's case now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no conflict,'' Krischer said. ``He was never a client
of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Wiita _ who might have feared Krischer could have
gathered personal information about him when defending his brothers
_ ever ask him to remove himself, Krischer said.
</P>
<P>
   Krischer has requested excusing his office from prosecuting 15
cases this year, according to records from the governor's office.
Most are cases involving relatives of employees at his office. One
involved a former client, but none involved relatives of past
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Lubin planned to argue that the law should not apply to Wiita,
who had pleaded guilty but was not convicted of a sex crime before
the law went into effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a fairness issue,'' Lubin said. ``They changed the
rules mid-stream. It wasn't part of his plea.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true, Krischer acknowledged. But he said he would not
agree that Wiita could withdraw his plea. Instead, Krischer
instructed an assistant, Terry Nolan, to leave it up to the judge.
</P>
<P>
   On June 11, Lubin and Nolan went to court. Lubin told Circuit
Judge Harold Cohen that prosecutors would not block efforts to
withdraw Wiita's plea.
</P>
<P>
   But Darren Shull, another prosecutor assigned to the case,
arrived and objected.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the judge ruled Wiita could drop his plea and set his
trial for Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Wiita said he's confident he'll beat the charges: ``If I thought
there was a chance I'd lose the case, do you think I'd risk this?''
</P>
<P>
   Four days after Wiita withdrew his plea, Scarola sent another
letter to Wiita's probation supervisor, requesting the correction
of ``misinformation which previously has been circulated, and to
assure that Mr. Wiita is not in any way identified as a sex
offender (or predator) in any future communications . . . ''
Wiita's photo has been removed from the Internet because he's no
longer listed as pleading guilty to a sex offense. Wiita has since
moved back to his home in North Palm Beach with his wife and four
children.
</P>
<P>
   He said his business is thriving and he still loves coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hold him in the highest regard,'' said Peggy Rafferty, a
North Palm Beach mother whose son and daughter were coached by
Wiita. ``I think he's wonderful and hope he's around to coach my
third child.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
