r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COWBOY-CAMP30-COX     07-29 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOY-CAMP30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Photographer captures more than football at Cowboy camp
 &HT;    By Tyler Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS _ It was like the summer's mega blockbuster, but
even bigger.
</P>
<P>
   In this red-dirt town, practically all 140,000 locals had
something to say about Dallas Cowboys football. Banners and
billboards everywhere. ``Welcome Jerry and the Boys,'' proclaimed
the sign in front of the Kleen Kar Wash _ pretty much summing up
the feelings across the community.
</P>
<P>
   I spent a week chronicling the Cowboys training in their new
camp. Once, it was a Wichita Indian encampment on a vast grassland
prairie; now it's a modern community with more than 39 fast-food
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The big event was at Midwestern State University, where the MSU
Indians hosted the Cowboys. Bivouacked in my little yellow dorm
room, No. 136 Pierce Hall, I started each day much the same: Wake
up to the sound of ``Mad Mark'' and classic rock on my new Kmart
clock radio. ``Freebird.'' ``Stairway to Heaven.'' I was on
vacation from carpet and cable. Cokes in the microfridge, bathroom
down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   There was more to photograph here than just sweaty athletes. A
whole gaggle of characters _ crazed fans, zealous community leaders
and regular guys _ was caught up in the extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   All geared up, I hit the door. Then POW!, the heat hit back. Not
counting Laredo, the Texoma area, as natives lovingly call this
region, was the hottest spot in the state with the heat index
reaching 110 degrees. Fans gathered at the practice field, piled up
like so many wind-blown tumbleweeds against the chain-link fence.
Nowhere to go.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon they had drifted in from all over. Sun-crazed
stargazers down from Lawton, Okla., and up from Archer City. Three
thousand of them. Carolyn Price-Woods, of Dallas, screamed at wide
receiver Michael Irvin and the Cowboys fans around her laughed.
Like some possessed preacher leading her flock, she screamed,
really screamed, ``Michael, Michael !!'' The playmaker, not 30
yards away, ignored her. Price-Woods' odds on a conversation with
her hero? An ice storm in August?
</P>
<P>
   On the field, the Cowboys' newest big man, second-round draft
pick Flozell Adams from Michigan State, was in trouble. The
335-pound mountain was perched on an orange cooler with little
wheels. It was an uneasy scene. The new millionaire rookie was
spent. Doubled up in pain, ``The Hotel'' hunkered down and tried to
suck in enough air and water to keep from passing out. You have to
be tough, he was learning, to play offensive tackle in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   On the far side of the field, along autograph alley, a jumble of
serious 12-year-old boys was on station. As afternoon practice
broke up and football players walked their way, the grim task of
obtaining autographs began. With Emmitt Smith just feet away, Cody
Henderson's face kinked up as he tried to will the man in his
direction. But the most important sports hero on the planet walked
away.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, Harold Bufford, a skinny, twentysomething working
at the 7-Eleven on U.S. 281, told anybody who would listen how
blasted he got at the big Cowboys pep rally Tuesday night. ``Yeah,
they was charging two bucks a whack,'' Bufford said. ``I should've
packed a couple of beers in my boot.'' Another local who was too
busy working to visit training camp, Bobby Zentgraf, owner and auto
mechanic at Three Sons Auto on Missile Road, had experienced some
of the Cowboys mystique personally. ``Man ... can they dance!''
said Zentgraf, referring to what he considered the best thing about
the Dallas Cowboys _ the cheerleaders, who had performed ``quite a
show'' over at Sheppard Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   At the Wichita Falls Country Club, a different scene prevailed.
Well-scrubbed real estate brokers and attorneys played 18 holes in
the ninth annual Cowboys Golf Classic. That's where I ran into Kay
Yeager, the Wichita Falls mayor and shameless promoter of Cowboys
vibes. On the third tee she talked about the spirit of community,
the excitement and the economic impact of ``a once in a lifetime
opportunity for a town this size to host a world-famous sports
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Back on campus, with practice over, fans gone and calm restored,
Sue Raagas, 43, stood guard.
</P>
<P>
   Her eyes scanned the fenceline around the Clark Student Center
cafeteria where the athletes ate. Raagas watched over the players'
golf carts and talked about her role as a member of the event staff
_ a kind of gatekeeper, crowd controller and mother hen for the
team. Raagas used to be a chaplain at Parkland Hospital in Dallas.
Her job there was to help people die. ``People died in my arms, and
I listened to their last words. Many of these people were so filled
with regret,'' she said. ``They did not think their life would end
so soon; they had left so many things undone.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when Raagas decided to follow her dream. She loved the
Dallas Cowboys and wanted to be involved with them. Now, 10 years
later, she is a fixture with the team, doing a lot of small things
that make a big difference for players and fans _ like helping a
kid with a disability get Troy Aikman's autograph. ``I love this
sport and I love people. It's like being in the ministry,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Johnson is a photographer for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
