<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8686 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLPHINS30-COX     07-29 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLPHINS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dixon elevated, Avery deflated in J.J.'s daily praise agenda
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Steamy summer heat. Two-a-day practices. The
crunching of pads and helmets.
</P>
<P>
   We tend to hear the words ``training camp'' and think of a
grueling, physical test. But this particular pre-season ritual is
more than that. It is a test of body and head. Especially with
Jimmy Johnson in charge.
</P>
<P>
   A reminder of that came on a recent morning when the Miami
Dolphins' head coach strolled off the field and, in his daily
interview session, made a point to pump up Mark Dixon, an offensive
lineman who has spent the past three seasons in the Canadian
Football League, and to tear down running back John Avery, the
team's first-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Let the (mind) games begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about John Avery,'' Johnson said. ``He
can crack jokes with (the media) or do whatever. I'm not real happy
with John Avery right now. ... He doesn't have pads on. And he's a
rookie. And I'm not real happy with rookies without pads. Every
minute that he misses hurts our football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson spent most of the first week of camp praising Avery. He
laughed when the rookie made a joke about his hair at the annual
breakfast. He smiled as he watched Avery burst through holes in
practice. He cut Lawrence Phillips _ and cited Avery's play as one
of the reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Avery, it seemed, had become Johnson's pet player.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Avery lost 6 yards on six carries. Worse, as far as Johnson was
concerned, he pulled a hamstring muscle.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins players had Monday off. And on Tuesday, the rookie
from Mississippi wasn't ready to practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day he misses is going to hurt his contributions to our
season early on,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Avery, who during the first week of camp was easily the most
media-friendly player on the team, wasn't available for interviews
Tuesday. Dolphins media relations officials said he was
rehabilitating his hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Once Johnson's words make it to Avery's ears, the rookie won't
have to look far to find someone to offer a little historical
perspective on the sudden change of favor. All he has to do is turn
to the guy at the next locker, Karim Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago as a rookie, Abdul-Jabbar became a student in the
Jimmy Johnson Motivational Academy.
</P>
<P>
   First, Abdul-Jabbar held out, albeit only for a few days. Then,
once he arrived at camp, he sprained his ankle. He quickly found
himself No. 5 on the depth chart and a target of some Johnson
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't talk about guys who are hurt,'' Johnson said at the
time. ``I talk about guys who are out there and practicing.''
</P>
<P>
   Before one pre-season game, Johnson walked up to Abdul-Jabbar
and said, ``At UCLA, you had a four-year scholarship. Around here,
it's day-to-day.''
</P>
<P>
   The message got across to the rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I learned,'' Abdul-Jabbar said, ``is that you have to
learn to play hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has since admitted that some of the talk, especially the
notion that he might cut Abdul-Jabbar, was part of a motivational
ploy. Johnson, however, is a bottom-line kind of coach. And the
bottom line in this instance was that Adbul-Jabbar played hurt in
pre-season, started the first regular-season game and finished the
year with 1,116 rushing yards _ most ever by a Dolphins rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all motivate people in different ways,'' Johnson said
later. ``I made a mistake on him. I was skeptical about his injury.
I also was frustrated because I knew what kind of talent he had,
and I wanted to groom him to stay in the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, as Johnson was expressing frustration about Avery
dropping into the background of the current picture, he also was
talking about a surprise addition to the photo.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Dixon. Front and center. OK, front and left guard.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that Dixon has moved to the top of the depth chart
at the same position containing Anthony Redmon, the former Arizona
starter that the Dolphins signed last week for a $600,000 salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Dixon) is really a steady player,'' Johnson said. ``He
doesn't say a whole lot. He's fairly quiet. But you look at
performance and start grading every play, and he did a great job
(in the scrimmage).''
</P>
<P>
   This is the flip side of the mind game. A player being built up.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon, 6-feet-4 and nearly 300 pounds, is the second strongest
player on the team, having bench-pressed 315 pounds 17 times. Yet,
he readily admits that his weakness is his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's all confidence,'' he said. ``It's up and down
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, it got a boost from Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't read much into it,'' Dixon said. ``Who knows where
I'll be this afternoon. I might be back to third string or on my
way back to Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
