<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8687 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGE-SPIELMAN30-COX     07-29 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-SPIELMAN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spielman's choice reassuring to us here in Cynic City
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it was The Bridges of Madison County, the wholly
incomprehensible wedding of Clint Eastwood to a weepy chick flick.
Maybe it was Dale Earnhardt's admission that tears welled up in his
eyes on the final lap of his Daytona 500 victory in February.
</P>
<P>
   Something is happening to me, that's certain. Something soft.
Something too sensitive to discuss with strangers.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I'm talking to you, dear friend. Over the years you
have heard me grouse about what's wrong with sports, from the greed
of players to the arrogance of owners, to the epidemic of agents.
You have wondered, at times, who stole my parking space or closed
the elevator door in my face in order to summon up so much venomous
ink.
</P>
<P>
   Bless you for your concern. A lifetime in locker rooms, the most
macho environment this side of Parris Island, tends to shape a
personality. One laughs too loudly at cruel jokes, runs too quickly
to the sounds of a fight, pushes each hint of sentimentality out
into the open so it can be piled upon like a fumble or scored as an
error.
</P>
<P>
   So what is it about the Chris Spielman story that fascinates?
</P>
<P>
   Here is a linebacker no longer on the Buffalo Bills roster. He
counts against no one's salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   This is of Spielman's choosing, right down to the forfeiture of
$1.8 million that was due him this season. The Bills invested $8
million altogether to get Spielman as a free agent from Detroit two
years ago. It was money well spent on an unquestioned leader, a
player so intense that he showed up before the coaches at training
camp and was in full uniform before Bruce Smith was even fully
awake.
</P>
<P>
   Then it all changed last week with a visit to the doctor.
Spielman's neck, surgically repaired last winter, was fine. No
problem there. His wife, Stephanie, however, was in trouble. First,
a miscarriage, then a diagnosis of breast cancer. Sudden surgery
followed, with months of chemotherapy promised thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily this is where the coach steps in and offers that the
thoughts and prayers of the team go out to the player and he can
take as long as he needs _ three days, four days, whatever _ to get
things squared away at home and get back to work.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that Spielman didn't wait to get a second
opinion from Bills coach Wade Phillips. Without hesitation, he
walked away from the NFL and into the real fire. Spielman decided
to sit out this season so he can stand up by his wife and by their
children, too.
</P>
<P>
   What choice did the guy have? According to the long-established
rules of the locker room, there is only one. A player plays the
hand that is dealt him. He plays on through adversity. He plays on
for the team, always for the team, and for the obvious reason that
great sums of money have been dedicated to his contributions.
</P>
<P>
   David Williams had no problem with that picture, earning a
starting spot on the Florida Gators' offensive line as a freshman
in 1985 and never relinquishing it until the conclusion of his
All-America collegiate career 46 games later. The picture changed,
however, when Williams' wife became pregnant in 1993. The big man
blew off his obligation to the Houston Oilers, skipping a game in
order to be present at the birth of his son. One-sixteenth of his
annual salary, Williams figured, was a small price to pay for a
once-in-a-lifetime family miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is out of the league now, cut by the New York Jets in
June. Sooner or later it was bound to happen. Credit him with
knowing that life's other landmarks aren't so predictable.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening to me is a growing desire to run, screaming,
from sordid tales of players losing control of their lives and
toward quiet, calming stories like these. No longer will I
entertain, even for a moment, the boyhood fantasy of being a sports
superstar. The price is too high.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of real men, like Chris Spielman, is too low.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
