<P>
   GEORGE-SPIELMAN _ Something is happening to me, that's certain.
Something soft. Something too sensitive to discuss with strangers.
That's why I'm talking to you, dear friend. Over the years you have
heard me grouse about what's wrong with sports, from the greed of
players to the arrogance of owners, to the epidemic of agents. You
have wondered, at times, who stole my parking space or closed the
elevator door in my face in order to summon up so much venomous
ink. So what is it about the Chris Spielman story that fascinates?
(George, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DOLPHINS _ DAVIE, Fla. _ We tend to hear the words ``training
camp'' and think of a grueling, physical test. But this particular
pre-season ritual is more than that. It is a test of body and head.
A reminder of that came on a recent morning when the Miami
Dolphins' head coach strolled off the field and, in his daily
interview session, made a point to pump up Mark Dixon, an offensive
lineman who has spent the past three seasons in the Canadian
Football League, and to tear down running back John Avery, the
team's first-round draft pick. (Woods, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COACHWIITA-PLEA _ NORTH PALM BEACH, Fla. _ At the time _ with
his wife's pregnancy in jeopardy, his brother dying of AIDS and his
business on the skids _ Bruce Brian Wiita figured he was doing the
right thing when he pleaded guilty to having sex with a 15-year-old
baby sitter. Wiita, a North Palm Beach real-estate agent, said he
is innocent. But the 1991 plea bargain would let him keep his
record clean if he could complete 10 years probation. Now Wiita
says he didn't get what he'd bargained for. (Stapleton, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COWBOY-CAMP _ WICHITA FALLS _ It was like the summer's mega
blockbuster, but even bigger. In this red-dirt town, practically
all 140,000 locals had something to say about Dallas Cowboys
football. Banners and billboards everywhere. ``Welcome Jerry and
the Boys,'' proclaimed the sign in front of the Kleen Kar Wash _
pretty much summing up the feelings across the community. I spent a
week chronicling the Cowboys training in their new camp. Once, it
was a Wichita Indian encampment on a vast grassland prairie; now
it's a modern community with more than 39 fast-food restaurants.
(Johnson, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
