<SLUG> BC-SF-HOUSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBE IN CLEVELAND RAISES NEW CONCERN OVER SAN FRANCISCO HOUSING
CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIN McCORMICK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Department of Housing and Urban Development
has suspended the head of the public housing agency in Cleveland,
raising questions about her former assistant who went on to direct
the housing authority in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, HUD said it was sanctioning Claire Freeman-McCown
over her alleged use of public funds to pay for her own private
townhouse while head of public housing in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Davis, who has headed the San Francisco Housing Authority
since November 1996, was a trusted lieutenant to Freeman-McCown at
the Cleveland agency and Utah corporate records show he was
registered as a manager and member of her private business.
</P>
<P>
   Davis denies ever doing any business with Freeman-McCown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We independently started our own companies,'' Davis said.
``I've never done business with her.''
</P>
<P>
   But records show that, while they worked as the top two managers
of Cleveland's low-income housing in 1996, Freeman-McCown and Davis
signed papers to register a limited corporation in the name of
Claire E. Freeman in Mapleton, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Documents provided by the Utah Department of Commerce list
Freeman and Davis as the only members and managers of the company,
which was suspended from the Utah corporate rolls in March because
no annual report was filed. Davis said he believed the registration
information was a mistake. But even if he did sign the registration
papers, he said, he never did any business with the company.
</P>
<P>
   From the records, it is not clear whether any work was ever done
by the corporation.
</P>
<P>
   However, current and former housing officials say they remember
Freeman-McCown and Davis seeking jobs as consultants to other
housing authorities, including San Francisco's, prior to the time
the corporation was formed.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Supervisor Leland Yee has demanded an audit of the
San Francisco Housing Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they would want to do consulting after they
leave their jobs doesn't bother me,'' he said. ``What raises a red
flag for me is the idea that the two of them had a conflicted
relationship while they were public servants.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Noga, spokeswoman for the Cuyahoga Metropolitan Housing
Authority in Cleveland, where Davis and Freeman-McCown worked, said
she believed their contracts had allowed them to work as
consultants elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' contract with the San Francisco Housing Authority allows
him to work as a consultant, as long as the work does not conflict
with his responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The housing authority Freeman-McCown and Davis managed had been
named the most improved large city housing agency in the nation in
1994, and housing improvements made under Freeman-McCown there were
seen as a model of how to fix the problems of low-income housing.
The agency was touted for its innovative health programs for
residents, improved management systems and spruced-up housing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Freeman-McCown is under investigation by the FBI and a
grand jury in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman-McCown had already been placed on unpaid leave by
Cleveland's housing board in May, after the board learned that more
than $100,000 intended for housing the poor had gone to make
mortgage payments on her townhouse in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hinton, HUD's secretary for public affairs, said
Freeman-McCown's suspension would last until the investigations
were completed and any problems were resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking this action to ensure the wise and efficient
expenditure of public funds,'' she said. ``Secretary (of HUD
Andrew) Cuomo's top priority has been to ensure the funds targeted
for low-income people get to low-income people.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman-McCown's lawyer, Thomas Wilson, declined to comment on
the federal sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Plain Dealer reported this month that
Freeman-McCown and Davis had moved more than $1 million in federal
money into an obscure fund and then allegedly used the money to
give bonuses and pay perks to themselves and other housing
authority employees. Freeman-McCown earned $403,000 in 1997, while
Davis made $368,000 during 1995, his highest-paying year, the Plain
Dealer reported.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Davis has said that all bonuses and incentives paid to him and
other staff members at the Cuyahoga Metropolitan Housing Authority
were authorized by the agency's board of commissioners and
reflected ``a very small percentage of the benefit received by the
CMHA.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he had no comment on HUD's action against
Freeman-McCown, but said he believed his work with the Cleveland
housing agency was exemplary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has no effect on my role in San Francisco as a public
servant,'' said Davis, adding that he did not believe the ongoing
FBI and grand jury investigations touched on his work at all. ``HUD
has not approached me with any questions about Cleveland.''
</P>
</TEXT>
