<HEADER>
A8738 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-KITCHEN-NYT &LR;      07-29 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-KITCHEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEROIC ADVENTURES IN A SUMMER KITCHEN 
</HEADLINE>
   Roger Welsch, the author of ``Diggin' in and Piggin' Out''
(HarperCollins, 1997), does the ``Postcards From Nebraska'' reports
on television for ``CBS Sunday Morning.''  
 (bl)  
 By ROGER WELSCH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten years ago, I brought my family to rural Nebraska and built a
farmstead from scratch. We bought an abandoned house for $350 and
moved it onto the land, but some things we had to build: a machine
shed, a garage and _ a summer kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The reason our little building in the backyard is called a
summer kitchen is that it's the perfect place to make tomato sauce
and at the same time to enjoy the rattle of cottonwood leaves while
dozing in a hammock. But the real reason I cook out there is that
my wife, Linda, won't let me cook indoors. Shortly after we built
our home, through some perfectly reasonable and logical events, I
somehow got fish guts on the ceiling of her new kitchen. It
happens.
</P>
<P>
   She colorfully called them to my attention the next day,
summarizing her commentary with how she would never again repaint a
kitchen because my extra-special barbecue sauce ate the paint off
the cupboards. And cooking utensils that look for all the world
like gardening tools do not belong in a civilized kitchen. And one
cleans fish outside.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to reason with her, suggesting that while it might be
hard for her to understand how fish guts get on a ceiling, it was
no less baffling to me how one would NOTICE fish guts on a ceiling.
I didn't even start explaining how the guys up at the town tavern
think my barbecue sauce is transcendental or that cast-iron pots
are wonderfully efficient.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line was that my days in the house kitchen were over.
</P>
<P>
   Until not very long ago, a summer kitchen was a presumed adjunct
of just about any home. It was a small, one-room building that
stood behind the house, furnished only with a stove and chimney, a
table and some generous-size pots, pans, ladles and stirring
paddles.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional summer kitchen was the arena for heroic culinary
adventures rarely taken on today: canning hundreds of pounds of
peaches, assembling a threshers' dinner, butchering a hog and
rendering the lard or curing four hams and two slabs of bacon, with
room left over for stuffing sausage.
</P>
<P>
   The theory was that a summer kitchen avoided filling a house
with heat and steamy, messy, smelly cooking; that if there should
be a fire from the wood-, coal- or cob-stoked stove, you might lose
the summer kitchen but not the house, and finally, that it was more
convenient to carry water and fuel (let alone hogs) to the summer
kitchen than into the house.
</P>
<P>
   These days I understand that Martha Stewart has a summer kitchen
at her house in Westport, Conn., and I imagine she has it equipped
with a Cuisinart, a fish steamer and a mortar for making pesto. For
most people, a summer kitchen may hold only the barbecue grill,
bags of charcoal and a supply of aprons saying ``A Man's Place Is
at the Grill.''
</P>
<P>
   The design for mine is modest, with decidedly random dimensions:
10 by 12 feet. It has a tile floor, a table, a stove, wood bins, a
cupboard and shelving. There is no need for electricity, and the
spigot at the house is close enough for water. After all, the
fancier it gets, the less it is a real summer kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The advantages of cooking in a separate building are obvious:
</P>
<P>
   1. Wood smoke. Wood smoke becomes part of the charm of cooking _
if you have a summer kitchen. I like the smell of wood smoke. I
like the taste of wood smoke. In my summer kitchen, I have the
smell and taste of wood smoke.
</P>
<P>
   2. Critters. See what happens when you try to store a couple
hundred pounds of hickory, mesquite and apple wood, corncobs and
charcoal briquettes in your household kitchen. Some nitpicker (I
won't mention names) is bound to say something about the dirt and
insects that come in along with such supplies, believe me. Not in
my summer kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   3. Capacity. My Great Depression mentality demands making
quantities of food as if preparing for a Russian winter. While my
indoor kitchen cupboards let me buy no more than two boxes of
Wheaties at a time, my outdoor kitchen has room for me to cook up
50 pounds of ribs at a time, 5 gallons of beans, 30 hams. Sometimes
all at once. And when I'm done, I can hose out the summer kitchen
with a rented power washer. Try that in the indoor kitchen. Which
brings us to . . .
</P>
<P>
   4. Mess. Cooking and eating are as close as I come to a contact
sport. I go at cooking and eating the way some guys approach the
martial arts. I know there is barbecue sauce on at least one of the
windows of my summer kitchen and a few still festering spots of
marinade baked onto the stove. There may even be fish guts on the
ceiling, but I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   5. Cooking odors. In the house, the aftereffects of cooking a
fish dinner seem to linger for days, eventually fading a week later
in the farthest reaches of the guest room. In my summer kitchen,
the aura of a garlic pie is moved somewhere beyond the county line
in at most a couple of hours, depending on the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   In my summer kitchen, I cook things even I wouldn't attempt in
the house. For example, I like lutefisk. You're not likely to see
that in print again: ``I like lutefisk.'' It's not the kind of
thing most people admit.
</P>
<P>
   Lutefisk is a Norwegian delicacy _ cod cured in lye (yes, lye),
then dried, stored until it is geological, or at least
archaeological, and then boiled down to a gelatinous, fishy slime
eaten with potatoes and butter. Believe it or not, it is even
better than it sounds. Problem is, lutefisk when cooking lets off a
certain tang.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never cooked lutefisk but have cooked kidneys, imagine
cooking fish kidneys. I don't cook lutefisk in the summer kitchen
unless the family is safely and well removed _ sort of like
Londoners sending children to Wales during the Blitz. In fact, a
lot like Londoners sending children to Wales during the Blitz.
</P>
<P>
   When everyone is safely upwind, I fire up the stove in the
summer kitchen, cook up a mess and take it up to my pal Eric, who
runs the town tavern. I once made the mistake of bringing some
leftover lutefisk back home from the tavern, thinking my dogs might
enjoy it. They looked at it, circled it, smelled it _ and then
rolled in it, a remarkably candid culinary critique, even for black
Labs, who are noted for their candor. A summer kitchen lets people
like me cook things like lutefisk.
</P>
<P>
   I do not intend to provide ammunition for the gender wars by
suggesting a summer kitchen is a man thing. Nor would I for a
moment suggest that men have no business in a house kitchen (even
though Linda says that just about every time she looks into my
summer kitchen).
</P>
<P>
   But I can tell you this: my summer kitchen is the source of
comfort and joy for me and has resulted in some darned tasty food
over the years. No matter what the dogs think.
</P>
</TEXT>
