</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SILVA-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAM MAKING AS THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ When life gets tough, the tough make jam.
</P>
<P>
   Who could have foreseen that the age-old practice of making jams
and jellies, an art that appeared to be dying on the vine, would
become fashionable again.
</P>
<P>
   But now, instead of a form of sustenance, it would take the form
of spiritual healing.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer's Blue Jelly: Lost Love and Lessons of Canning
(Hyperion, $16.95) was my first inkling of what was to come.
Written by former Rolling Stone writer Debby Bull, I was lulled
into a trance by the cadence and rhythm of the writing as the main
character sought to mend a broken heart after a nasty breakup with
her boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Her therapy?
</P>
<P>
   Making jellies and jams.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes, written in a narrative format, might tempt the
noncook to skip over them, just to get back to the next chance
encounter with the wacky Dr. Ruths of the world who offer advice to
lovelorn. But such wreckless action would take some of the
mesmerizing power away from this tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canning may sound like a strange path out of the dark woods of
despair, but all other ways, from Prozac to suicide, are really
hard on your body,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Why was I surprised when I went to buy Blue Jelly at the
bookstore that it was shelved in the self-help section?
</P>
<P>
   This summer's cookbook crop has yielded yet another
introspective look at the solace one woman finds in jam making.
</P>
<P>
   Well Preserved: A Jam-Making Hymnal (Fireside, $11) by Joan
Hassol is an account of how she uses jam to ``center'' her grief
after the death of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``My relationship to jam, my soul, music and the world in which
I live. When I make jam, I slow down, my actions become more
rhythmical, my thinking clear,'' she writes. ``The repetitive
motions of washing, stirring, pouring, and labeling allow me the
space to think about my life _ what it means to be starting over
and how I can embrace this stage of my life with vitality and
joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, there are recipes, but they are intertwined with the
seasonal ebb and flow of fruit and the labors of life.
</P>
<P>
   Even if droves of brokenhearted souls don't rush into the
kitchen to sterilize jars or strive to learn the nuances of pectin,
I am convinced there is a small, but important trend crystallizing
here.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I now have hard evidence that jam therapy may work for
men who have loved and lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finding that more men are participating in home canning
in part because they enjoy the process,'' according to a recent
press release by Alltrista, makers of home canning equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The company goes on to note that one quarter of today's home
canners are younger men.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? A home canning set may just be good for the soul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
