<SLUG> BC-TELEVISION-UPN-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPN, WB RECAST FAMILIAR FOR FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON BARNHART  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PASADENA, Calif.) _ Whether you're running a big TV network or
a small one, the rule this fall seems to be the same: Familiarity
breeds content.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever accused the Big Three networks of excessive
originality, and certainly no one is doing so this year. NBC is
spinning new sitcoms that are based largely on its old sitcoms, CBS
and ABC are doing the same in the drama department, and all three
networks are cloning their newsmagazines.
</P>
<P>
   What's surprising, however, is that even the No. 5 and No. 6
networks, WB and UPN, have fallen into the same pattern as their
more-established rivals. They are taking their current hits,
crafting careful approximations of them and then hoping viewers
will show up for these ``new'' programs.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of the WB, which seven months ago launched a new
drama called ``Dawson's Creek'' by Kevin Williamson, the creator of
``Scream.'' Praised as fresh and intriguing, the show gathered
months of advance buzz from TV critics and landed like a comet on
Tuesday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Although low-rated in the overall Nielsens, ``Dawson's Creek''
and the WB's other two verifiable hits _ ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' and ``7th Heaven'' _ performed very well among the
network's target audience of viewers ages 12 to 34. These three
shows helped WB this spring to overtake UPN in the ratings for the
first time since the two networks launched in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   This fall the WB is introducing more shows that will remind
viewers of their existing favorites. ``Felicity'' applies the
``Dawson's Creek'' template of young lust and heartfelt talks to a
college setting. It stars Keri Russell, a future heartthrob who has
not actually attended college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charmed'' merges ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' with ``Sabrina
the Teenage Witch.'' Shannen Doherty leads three sisters who
discover they have magical powers, and just as Buffy's powers draw
her into conflict with vampires, these three seem destined to do
weekly battle with warlocks.
</P>
<P>
   Of the WB's two comedy additions, one previously aired on NBC
(``For Your Love'') and ``The Army Show,'' which stars Dave Higgins
of ``Ellen,'' is an obvious attempt to update ``The Phil Silvers
Show'' for the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Over at UPN, where a management shuffle and affiliate problems
have led many to question whether the network will survive this
season, the new fall lineup has a heavy sci-fi skew. Not
surprisingly, so does UPN's highest-rated show, ``Star Trek:
Voyager.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mercy Point'' features a dedicated medical staff caring for ER
patients _ including the occasional space alien _ on a hospital
spaceship. ``Seven Days'' combines the adventure of time travel
with contemporary events. Jonathan LaPaglia (``New York
Undercover'') plays a top-secret government agent who is
transported back one week in time to avert disasters and terrorist
attacks. UPN's Thursday-night movie is also expected to be
dominated by sci-fi features.
</P>
<P>
   As for the new sitcoms, ``Guys Like Us'' is organized around a
precocious child, ``DiResta'' around a stand-up comedian. Nothing
new there. The true wild card on the UPN schedule is ``The Secret
Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer,'' a contemporary political satire
disguised as a historical comedy about Abraham Lincoln's butler.
</P>
<P>
   One WB offering, ``Hyperion Bay,'' is geared more toward
20-somethings and could lift the network out of its reliance on
teen angst. Its creator, Joseph Dougherty, was a writer on
``thirtysomething'' and is a two-time Emmy winner.
</P>
<P>
   It is the story of brotherhood and its potentially tragic
nature. Nerdy, withdrawn Dennis (Mark-Paul Gosselaar, who played
Zack on ``Saved by the Bell'') left town after high school and got
rich in the computer industry. His older and more popular sibling,
Nick (Dylan Neal, last seen on ``Dawson's Creek''), wasn't so
lucky. Now, in a high-school reunion fantasy gone mad, Dennis has
convinced his boss to construct a new facility, which Dennis will
run, in economically bereft Hyperion Bay,.
</P>
<P>
   As with every WB drama, there's a love triangle here _ but the
person in the middle isn't a girl, it's the brothers' father.
Played by Raymond J. Barry, who also had father roles in ``Dead Man
Walking'' and ``Born on the Fourth of July,'' Dad is frugal with
his affections, and his two sons are still competing for them. When
Dennis returns to town, Dad fires up the grill and throws a party.
Nick deeply resents the breaking of taboo. It's the parable of the
prodigal son all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty had been noodling with the idea of writing a TV series
on the relationship between brothers when the WB approached him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them what I wanted in the show: no cops, no lawyers, no
doctors, no detectives,'' Dougherty said in an interview. ``At that
point, they either validate your parking or they're interested.''
</P>
<P>
   WB was interested and for good reason: ``Hyperion Bay,'' showing
at 8 p.m. Mondays, is a nearly ideal alternative to the sitcoms on
NBC and CBS, football on ABC and female-oriented ``Ally McBeal'' on
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   In their fall season previews for the press held last weekend,
executives of UPN and WB differed sharply in their views of the
future of broadcasting _ specifically, their own futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not enough ad revenue to support the production of
seven nights a week for six broadcast networks,'' said Jamie
Kellner, CEO of the WB network. ``Even when we were in sixth place,
I said there wasn't room for six.''
</P>
<P>
   UPN's Dean Valentine, who suffered the indignity earlier this
year of having UPN thrown off affiliate stations in several
markets, including Kansas City, begged to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute WB or NBC or us doesn't have a hit show is the
minute that somebody's not going to be watching,'' Valentine told
critics Sunday. ``And the minute that you do have one, whether
you're coming on through the Internet or through digital (cable) or
through CBS, whatever, people will be watching you and paying for
the privilege of doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
