<SLUG> BC-SNEAK-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNEAK-A-PEEK REVIEWS WON'T BECOME A TREND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PERRY STEWART 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Thursday, the Star-Telegram published a review of ``The
Phantom of the Opera,'' which had its first Fort Worth performance
the previous evening in Bass performance hall.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal, you say? News event happens, newspaper prints
story.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the ``Phantom'' review is significant, because the
performance reviewed was not the one the producers wanted reviewed.
The ``Phantom'' national tour and Casa Manana, the local presenter,
stipulated that no reviewer was to see the show before Friday
evening. That would allow the cast to have one dress rehearsal and
three performances under its collective belt before anyone with a
note pad and an attitude viewed this edition of composer Andrew
Lloyd Webber's handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   (They needn't have worried; the review was a five-star rave.)
</P>
<P>
   What was our hurry? Were we sharpshooting, hoping the show's
vaunted chandelier would fail to crash on cue or that the Phantom
would trip over his cape? No, the Star-Telegram decided that
``Phantom'' is a sufficiently big deal
</P>
<P>
   _ a phenomenon, actually _ that its Fort Worth arrival should be
reported (and, yes, critiqued) immediately.
</P>
<P>
   This was an expensive decision. No press tickets were issued for
Wednesday's show, and none was available for purchase through
normal channels. The newspaper bought my ticket through a broker.
For the cost of that one aisle seat, we could have bought season
tickets for two at most theaters in Tarrant County.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the audience Wednesday or Thursday last week might not
have known they were attending a preview. They saw a polished and
fully realized show, and they paid almost as much for their tickets
as Friday theatergoers did. A news release for the Fort Worth
``Phantom'' run states that ``performances begin Wednesday, July
22'' and that ``the press opening night is Friday, July 24.''
Tickets for the first three performances _ or ``previews,'' if you
like _ ranged from $25 to $65, compared with $27 to $67 for
subsequent shows. Not a major bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Is the instant review a trend? Is there to be a new breed of
outlaw reviewers who sneak into rehearsals? Will sports writers now
write game stories based on scrimmages?
</P>
<P>
   Calm down. Although we note that a production is technically
fair game for criticism if tickets are being sold, we support the
preview concept. Previews help actors sharpen their timing _
particularly in comedies, when pausing for laughter is a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fully a play until it's in front of an audience,''
said Diane Anglim, executive director of Stage West in Fort Worth.
``A production needs that interaction of the audience and the
actors. It gives the director a chance to tweak and change.
Something might work in rehearsal that doesn't work with an
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   However:
</P>
<P>
   ``A preview is not a rehearsal,'' Anglim is quick to clarify.
``At preview, our plays are always ready. They're at performance
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Eastman, artistic director of Jubilee Theatre in downtown
Fort Worth, said he prefers to keep the reviewing press away from a
new production until the third preview.
</P>
<P>
   ``A show needs to be worked in front of an audience to get its
sea legs,'' Eastman said. ``We give the cast notes after every
preview. And I can understand why a touring show like `Phantom of
the Opera' would not want to be reviewed at the first show in a new
city. The production needs to understand the space. Any number of
little things can go wrong in that first performance.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons to have previews. Ticket prices usually
are lower, giving budget-minded theatergoers a break. Circle
Theatre in downtown Fort Worth, for example, charges $12 to $16 for
regular performances and $8 for first Wednesday previews. Jubilee
Theatre charges $5 on preview weekend and $10-$16 thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Discount previews also are excellent marketing devices. If you
score a ticket for half price, you're already in a good mood.
Unless you really hate the show, you tend to talk it up.
</P>
<P>
   (This is not the case on Broadway _ where preview audiences
usually pay full price. Because of that, advertisements must state
clearly that a Broadway show is in preview.)
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the preview strategy backfires. One local reviewer
attended the fourth performance of a new production at a Fort Worth
playhouse. It was a disappointing experience, and the review
reflected that.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the lead actor was ill that night _ missing
lines and disrupting the timing of other cast members. ``If only
the reviewer had come to an earlier show,'' the producer moaned.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
