<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PARENT-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAKE COULD BE EVEN BETTER THAN ORIGINAL `PARENT TRAP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN McTAVISH  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Parent Trap,'' a romantic comedy, opens Wednesday and is
rated PG. Running time is 2 hours 4 minutes. Three out of four
stars.
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ So is the remake of ``The Parent Trap''_ which
originally starred Hayley Mills as identical twins who switch
identities in a kooky plan to reunite their divorced parents _
anywhere near as good as the film that became an instant family
favorite in 1961?
</P>
<P>
   Hold on to your autographed 8-by-10 glossies, Mills fans. The
new ``Parent Trap'' may be even better than the movie you hold dear
to your childhood.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly shouldn't disappoint kids and parents looking for
high jinks, romance and most of all a good time together at the
movies. Such cross-generational appeal alone is a rarity in
live-action family films these days.
</P>
<P>
   While the new version wisely stays faithful to the plot and even
much of the dialogue of the original, it also has more laughs and
heartwarming moments than its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   First-time director Nancy Meyers (who co-wrote the screenplay
adaptation with partner Charles Shyer, just as they did Disney's
``Father of the Bride'' remakes) never falters in bringing an
overall gentle touch to the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this is a kinder ``Parent Trap,'' retooled for the
sensitivities of '90s viewers who might find it just a tad
appalling that a divorcing husband and wife would dare to separate
twins shortly after birth. On top of that _ and here's the really
disturbing part _ they never 'fess up to either kid that the other
exists until years later after the two offspring stumble on each
other at a summer camp and discover their strange family secret.
</P>
<P>
   An attempt to soften the blow is made in the new introduction,
which shows Dennis Quaid and Natasha Richardson (ably handling the
Brian Keith and Maureen O'Hara roles) taking part in a whirlwind
romance, wedding and honeymoon aboard the QE2 cruise ship. The
inference is that, after quickly souring on marriage, the two are
too immature and foolish to come up with a better solution for
raising their infant children.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Still, once you're over that psychological hurdle, ``The Parent
Trap'' easily lures you into its slickly told fantasy of two crafty
11-year-old girls who just want to get their parents back together.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's successful working Mom is more independent and
self-satisfied than O'Hara's stay-at-home variety in the first
film. And Quaid's Dad is more even-keeled than Keith's crabby man
of the house.
</P>
<P>
   But, as in the original, trouble looms when a beautiful and
despicable gold digger (Meredith Black) wants to marry Dad.
Valuable comedy relief is provided by Simon Kunz as Annie's
emotional butler and Lisa Ann Walter as Hallie's intuitive nanny,
who help the kids make their dream come true _ but they have to act
fast.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, where the audience sees two kids there is only one.
Red-headed and freckle-faced newcomer Lindsay Lohan, with the aid
of superb digital effects, is delightfully convincing as the
down-to-earth Hallie, raised by her vineyard-owning father in
California; and the high-toned Annie, raised by her wedding-gown
designer mother in London.
</P>
<P>
   When the girls switch places to see their missing parents for
the first time and find out why they split up, Lindsay's expressive
eyes and lingering hugs say all that needs to be said about the
value of a child knowing and growing up with both parents. Lindsay,
an American, also has her two different accents down _ something
that the British Mills, despite her pluck, couldn't quite master in
the original.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
