r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-NEGOTIATOR-REVI     07-29 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-NEGOTIATOR-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATOR IS A MAZE WHEN IT COMES TO STORY LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Negotiator,'' a drama, opens Wednesday and is rated R for
violence and language. Running time is 2 hours 15 minutes. Two out
of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The makers of ``The Negotiator'' deserve some credit
for trying to stretch the fairly narrow parameters of the action
genre. Here's a film in which palaver tries to be as important as
firepower.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is that director F. Gary Gray (``Set It
Off'') is still making an action movie. Every time the talk starts
to get interesting, he feels compelled to deliver a violent
sequence, lest the audience get restless.
</P>
<P>
   James DeMonaco and Kevin Fox's screenplay centers on Danny Roman
(Samuel L. Jackson), a hostage negotiator for the Chicago Police
Department. Danny is alarmed when his partner confides that fellow
officers have been ripping off a police benevolent fund. Before his
partner can spill the details of this corruption, though, he's
killed.
</P>
<P>
   All the evidence points to Danny as both the killer and the
embezzler who made off with $2 million of his buddies' money.
Looking at certain conviction, the hostage negotiator does
something drastic: He takes hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Danny commandeers the police department's internal affairs
office atop a riverfront office building. Among his hostages are
his chief accuser, an internal affairs bigwig (the late J.T.
Walsh); the man's secretary (Siobhan Fallon); a longtime cop pal
(Ron Rifkin); and a petty crook and police informant (Paul
Giamatti) in the wrong place at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   It's a ``Die Hard'' setup with police tactical teams and snipers
trying to break into Danny's high-rise fortress. Meanwhile Danny
uses the telephone to play mind games with the cops in the command
center, trying to determine which among them are the real villains.
</P>
<P>
   And he demands that he deal only with another hostage
negotiator, Chris Sabian (Kevin Spacey), whose impartiality he is
relying on. Chris will be Danny's eyes and ears in ferreting out
the bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, like two chess masters who can foresee and counter
each other's efforts several moves in advance, the negotiators do a
verbal dance of jabs and feints.
</P>
<P>
   If this brief description sounds a tad confusing, be assured
that the film is knottier still. Indeed even the most observant
viewer is likely to get lost along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence of Jackson and Spacey, both terrific
performers, ``The Negotiator'' isn't an actor's movie by any
stretch. Virtually all the characters are underdeveloped, the
narrative smacks of contrivance, and a lot of the details _ like
the behavior of the crowd that gathers outside the building for an
all-night vigil _ seem patently bogus.
</P>
<P>
   What the film has going for it is a fairly well-developed
atmosphere of suspense. Our hero appears to be in an inescapable
box. How will he ever get out?
</P>
<P>
   Director Gray, who is only 28, knows a lot more about cameras
and editing than he does about human nature or the way the world
really operates. But give him time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1725EDT &QL; 
