<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8770 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HOME-DESIGN-NYT &LR;      07-29 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HOME-DESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING HARD AT PLAYING ARCHITECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that in the writer's e-mail address at the end
of the text, the word AT, in parentheses, has been used instead of
the symbol, which is non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When not working at the computer, I spend my time fantasizing
about renovations to the house my husband and I bought nearly four
years ago. Recently, for example, I began to fret over the mud
room. Knocking down one teensy wall to expose a staircase would
open up that whole portion of the house. It seemed so obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't visualize it,'' my husband said. He had found me
in the mud room, waving a metal tape measure spastically in the
air. But then, I couldn't envision his fantasy home-improvement
plan: Replace the living room sofa with two stereo speakers, each
only slightly smaller than the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe software could save our marriage. After all, the best
programs behave like magic wands. Wave a word processing program at
raw text and, voila! Misspellings disappear. Tap the family budget
gently with a spreadsheet program, and impulse purchases evaporate.
I wonder if there is any problem that software won't eventually be
able to solve.
</P>
<P>
   The program that excited me this time was Sierra's Home
Architect, part of the Sierra Complete Home package. Earlier
generations of home-architect programs forced users to draw many
tedious lines to create a layout. Home Architect, on the other
hand, comes with preformed room icons. Within seconds of naming one
``mud room,'' I would be able to reshape it just by dragging and
clicking on its outline.
</P>
<P>
   But the feature of Home Architect that seemed most promising was
the ``three-dimensional view.'' After I had created a scale layout
of the first floor, my husband and I would be able to ``walk''
through the rooms by dragging the mouse. (I visualized him saying:
``You were so right, as usual. Why didn't I just listen to you?'')
</P>
<P>
   I consulted the 143-page user's manual and saw that I first had
to fit the room icons together to create the layout, then add
appropriately sized windows and doorways. Now, wait a minute.
Unless I was missing something here, I would have to spend hours
walking around my real-life house, measuring and jotting down
dimensions, before using the nifty virtual 3-D view the software
promised. Could this be right?
</P>
<P>
   I called Sierra for help. I tried not to sound too lazy, and the
company's spokesman, Chad Thompson, did not disappoint. Not only
did he assure me that the program was perfect for someone with a
relatively simple project _ ``a lot of folks use it for purposes of
changing around real minor stuff, whether it's just their furniture
or slightly moving a window over a few feet'' _ but he also gave me
a tip. Concentrate on the dimensions only in the area I wanted to
remodel. I could gloss over the rest for now.
</P>
<P>
   Taking Thompson's advice, I guessed at the sizes of most of the
rooms. I used horizontal and vertical rulers on the screen's
margins to size them. After an hour or so, the floor plan began to
look like my house. The only problem was persuading the program to
replicate faithfully the twists and turns of the proposed mud room.
After an hour, I settled for a shape resembling a Z with a wart
hanging off the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Next: doors and doorways. Who knew we had so many? Not to
mention windows _ I counted 31 on the first floor. And those little
window icons were willful, attaching themselves to the wrong walls.
Eventually, I mastered the technique of dragging them around
corners.
</P>
<P>
   By then, I had been working for more than three hours and still
needed to add a staircase. Clicking among suggested styles, I found
a staircase that resembled mine and dragged it over to the mud
room. I lost track of time as I tried to figure out where to click
on the staircase to get it to rotate properly to fit into the
space.
</P>
<P>
   At last, I was ready for the three-dimensional walk-through. I
dragged the mouse a few inches and was accompanied by the sound of
footsteps. The experience was slightly claustrophobic, but I
managed to suppress mental images of the Minotaur in his maze.
Starting in the living room, I moved through the rooms.
</P>
<P>
   I called in my husband. ``Look, if we go down this hallway, we
will be at the foot of the staircase. And then if we turn, we will
walk into a ... ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall,'' he said. ``I didn't know you wanted another wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I didn't. That was no wall; that was the wart. In the
three-dimensional view, it had evolved into an impenetrable dead
end. Frantically, I returned to the two-dimensional view to remove
it. But it seemed to be shared _ how, I don't know _ by two rooms.
I tried to resize the mud room. A second wart grew. If I had only a
few more hours, I was sure I could figure this out. After a while,
my husband got bored and _ ominously _ went downstairs to flip
through a catalog of stereo components.
</P>
<P>
   That was when I realized that Home Architect was not for me. Oh,
I can easily envision instances when this program would be useful:
for designing a dream house from scratch instead of trying to
massage a maze of 50-year-old rooms into a layout. Or maybe for a
full-scale kitchen renovation, for which you might want to
rearrange appliances and cabinets and work islands in a dozen
different configurations before settling on the best. The kind of
person I would recommend this software to would be someone with far
more patience than I, someone who likes to tinker with models.
</P>
<P>
   At the root of the problem wasn't Home Architect itself but the
expectations I had for the software. At $49.95, Home Architect
falls into a nether category of programs, neither toy nor tool. I
am not an architect, so what folly of hubris led me to believe that
mere software could somehow circumvent all the training real
architects must undertake? What would I have turned to next _ brain
surgery software to teach me to perform home lobotomies? If my
expectations seemed high, blame the best software for raising them.
</P>
<P>
   Not that my argument dissuaded my husband, whom I found at the
computer a few hours later, tinkering with the icons. He had placed
two refrigerators in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address:
</P>
<P>
   Slatalla(AT)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
