<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS AGGRAVATE VACATION ONCE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ My goal in life is to go on at least one vacation
without a stock market swoon savaging the Heaster Hoard. It did it
again last week.
</P>
<P>
   Things began promisingly enough. The first two days on the road
were record setters for the Dow Jones industrial average, the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 and the Nasdaq composite index. The thought
occurred that this time would be different.
</P>
<P>
   But, nooooo. Last week's opening session signaled that
hoard-hitting history was about to repeat itself and by the next
day it was obvious the rout was on.
</P>
<P>
   His Gloominess, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan,
exacerbated things by persisting in his lugubrious presentation on
Capitol Hill. Of all the discouraging things Greenspan said, what
analysts considered most critical was what he didn't say.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street was hoping for a hint that a Fed move to cut
short-term interest rates was in the cards to help stimulate what's
expected to be a sluggish economy during the rest of the year. No
flicker of hope was forthcoming from the Fed chairman, and the
market's disappointment translated into a meltdown for a budding
summer rally.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow industrials gave up 196 points Thursday for its third
worst sell-off of the year and the sixth-biggest point loss in
history. Meanwhile, the S&AMP;P 500 and Nasdaq also got hammered,
although not quite as badly as the Dow blue chips.
</P>
<P>
   When the dust settled, the Dow's loss for the week was 4.3
percent, and the S&AMP;P 500 and Nasdaq composite were both down almost
4 percent. The Heaster Hoard? It's impossible to say precisely
because no effort was made to benchmark it before embarking on R&AMP;R.
Calculations using some Kentucky windage, however, lead to the
conclusion that the 401(k) package, which /{is/} the Heaster Hoard,
got hit about as hard as the major market indices.
</P>
<P>
   The thought occurs that a sure-fire way to make a big score in
the stock market is to short everything when the Heasters hit the
vacation trail.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey! Who's complaining? That's what buying into the
American Dream is all about, right? And my experience is probably
not much different from most average individual investors trying to
ensure a measure of future financial security.
</P>
<P>
   The question for everyone shepherding a modest nest egg now is
whether to trim sail in anticipation of a major correction, or hang
tight and wait for the inevitable rebound that repeatedly has
restored investors to health during the roaring bull market of the
past several years.
</P>
<P>
   Rumbles from the experts, it's worth noting, are sounding more
and more cautionary. It's not just that corporate-earnings
disappointments are proliferating, but some market watchers are
wondering whether this is 1972 revisited. That was the time of the
so-called Nifty 50 _ companies that Wall Street viewed as
can't-lose investments.
</P>
<P>
   The slaughter that occurred over the next two years devastated
such conventional wisdom and put stocks out of vogue as popular
investments for the better part of a decade and a half. The
economic fundamentals are much sounder now, but one similarity is
what worries the experts most: Stock valuations are crazy in the
context of what can reasonably be expected in terms of growth.
</P>
<P>
   This has been troubling Greenspan for a year and a half, and
it's finally gotten to the point of troubling Wall Street, too.
Then, as if things weren't bad enough, the Heasters went on
vacation.
</P>
</TEXT>
