<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-BLACKS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BLACK POPULATION RISES TO 12.8 PERCENT OF NATION
 &HT;    By DANIELLE SHOOK
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ African-Americans' share of the U.S. population has
risen to 12.8 percent, the U.S. Census Bureau reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The black population, which totaled 34.2 million as of March
1997, rose from 12.3 of the total population since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In that period, the black population increased in the South, the
Northeast and the Midwest, and declined in the West.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest gain was in the South, where the percentage of black
residents increased from 18.5 percent to 20.1 percent. The only
region where the black percentage decreased was the West, where it
went from 5.4 percent to 4.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Last year, there were about 8.5 million black families. Less
than half, 46 percent, were headed by married couples.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About 74 percent of blacks age 25 and over had at least a
high-school education. About 14 percent had at least a bachelor's
degree.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The income of 2.1 million black families was below the federal
poverty level, which is determined by the size of the family. For a
four-person family, the level is $16,404.
</P>
<P>
   The report was based on random interviews that were analyzed by
computer, according to Claudette Bennett of the Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
