<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERBALL-TESTING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFEGAURDS PROTECT DRAWING POWERBALL NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (WEST DES MOINES, Iowa) _ The Powerball balls are prone to
turning yellow over time.
</P>
<P>
   But they're kept beautifully unpredictable. Any ball is as
likely as the next to fall to the bottom of a rotating drum, roll
down a tube and transform a tramp into a Trump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We test them four times before each drawing,'' said Sue
Dooley, drawing manager for the Multi-State Lottery Association
that runs Powerball. ``Believe me, we check everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's biggest-ever jackpot will turn on a system of
double-checks and safeguards glitzed up in a small TV studio to
make the random selection of a handful of numbers seem almost sexy.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Pace will wear one of his two black tuxedos and stand
between a pair blinking $65,000 machines that will drop the winning
balls into slots. But other than looking handsome and calling out
the numbers in a low, clear voice, he hasn't a thing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Off-camera, Dooley will use a remote control to run one of the
machines while moonlighting Des Moines city detective Brad Wells
will work the other.
</P>
<P>
   They will only push their buttons, however, after Dooley,
auditor Kimberly Hembry and security consultant Wells spend another
evening scripted like numerous Wednesday and Saturday nights
before.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts to keep the fix out of lottery fortune take place
in a bland building of glass and white concrete just off the
junction of Interstates 35 and 80 in an upscale suburb of Des
Moines.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Knox it is not. No guards. No steel bars. Just a small
parking lot and a little landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we keep money in here,'' said Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Just super balls. When not dancing about on Saturday and
Wednesday nights _ they have a $250 million date tonight _ these
hard rubber balls sit in plastic briefcases locked up in, of
course, a vault.
</P>
<P>
   The key to one padlock on the vault _ actually a plywood room
with a garage-style door in the studio _ spends most of the week in
the trunk of an auditor's car. The key to a second padlock jangles
on Dooley's key chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's right there with the rest of my life,'' said Dooley.
</P>
<P>
   The keys open the way to four sets of white and four sets of red
balls, four 6-foot ball-tumbling machines and a few volumes of
paperwork that only an accountant could love.
</P>
<P>
   Each ball bears a single number printed sixteen times. Squeeze
one and it feels like a slightly larger version of what children
play jacks with. They are 2 inches in diameter and weigh from
79.126 to 80.936 grams each (checked once a year at the state
transportation department in Ames, Iowa).
</P>
<P>
   Both balls and machines are picked randomly each night _ Dooley
has Wells pick numbered cards from her hand while Hembry takes note
of the selections _ and are tested to make sure there's no tendency
of one number to show up more than others.
</P>
<P>
   The trio confess to no superstitions. It's a casual affair,
usually conducted in T-shirts and jeans, or shorts and softball
uniforms in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   A small camera crew watches, and sometimes family members come
along for kicks. Last summer two regular players passing through
Des Moines for the Iowa State Fair asked to come and watch. No
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Dooley said, it will be the crew and a few reporters
and TV crews drawn in by the behemoth bonus. Wells sometimes
carries a gun to drawings, but he wouldn't say whether he'll be
packing tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Most of their time will be consumed with paperwork performed at
a small round table, filling out forms and making telephone calls
to confirm numbers with lottery officials in Washington, D.C.,
Arizona, Connecticut, Delaware, Idaho, Indiana, Iowa, Kansas,
Kentucky, Louisiana, Minnesota, Missouri, Montana, Nebraska, New
Hampshire, New Mexico, Oregon, Rhode Island, South Dakota, West
Virginia and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ratings should be high.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has a gambling pot grown so gargantuan. Last year's
Christmas lottery ``El Gordo'' drawing, or the fat one, in Spain
held a $270 million purse, but its grand prize was merely $2
million. Powerball produced a $195 million winner in May that was
the biggest then.
</P>
<P>
   In Powerball, players choose five white numbered balls from a
pool of 49 and a red Powerball from a pool of 42 numbers. A ticket
costs $1.
</P>
<P>
   Seven times out of 10, the winner lets a computer pick the
numbers. So, are you wrong to string together your family's
birthdays with your golf handicap? No. Three in 10 people pick
their own numbers, and three in 10 winners hand-pick their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Word on whether anyone bought a winning ticket will come from
the member lottery states about midnight and confirmed officially
between 3 and 4 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Statistically speaking, the pot should stop growing tonight
because somewhere between 85 to 90 percent of the 80 million number
combinations will be purchased.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people play when these jackpots build up like this,''
said Charles Clotfelter, a professor of public policy at Duke
University and the author of a recent book on gambling. ``There's
no better chance of winning _ that's still outrageously remote _
but it brings people out of the woodwork.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1729EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      07-29 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TALK: `PRIVATE RYAN' REVIVES A GENRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Norman Mailer's ``Naked and the Dead,'' arguably the greatest
combat novel ever written by an American, the reader engages with
Lt. Robert Hearn through hundreds of pages, getting to know all his
real and psychological attributes before coming to this sentence:
``A half-hour later, Hearn was killed by a machine-gun bullet which
passed through his chest.''
</P>
<P>
   In Stephen Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan,'' arguably the
best combat movie ever made by an American, there is the same
brutal, sudden, absurd death _ but in this case concentrated
carnage _ that is, the chaos and reality of combat. Can a novel, no
matter how magnificent, ever have the visceral impact of a greatly
made movie? Will novelists try after this movie's popularity?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the first question is very likely not, but in
``The Naked and the Dead'' and in James Jones' ``Thin Red Line,''
both novels of the war in the Pacific, there are roundelays of the
horrific on the killing ground.
</P>
<P>
   From Jones' book: ``His other hand, which was inside the
stretcher, was submerged to the wrist in an astonishing amount of
drying, almost jellylike blood which all but filled the cavity made
by his buttocks on the canvas.'' The soldier who observed this was
reduced to blubbering.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it's too early to tell whether novelists and would-be
novelists will get back to the graphic slaughter of war, but many
in book publishing believe they will, since the movie will
introduce a whole new generation to the spilled-guts school of war
storytelling. Indeed, there's already a slight indication that book
buyers might be interested again in World War II as it really was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizen Soldiers'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), Stephen E. Ambrose's
nonfiction about the men who fought that war, will be back on the
New York Times best-seller list at No. 15 on Aug. 9. Ambrose was on
the roster as a consultant on the Spielberg movie, and his book was
previously on the list on March 22.
</P>
<P>
   The Mailer and Jones novels, along with Irwin Shaw's ``Young
Lions,'' were the three defining American combat novels to emerge
from World War II, and actually were nearly the last novels about
war (with the exception of a few Civil War and Vietnam novels) to
focus on human beings and the blood they spilled. Although the
combat genre goes back to ``The Iliad,'' in American literature
perhaps only Stephen Crane's ``Red Badge of Courage'' and some of
Ambrose Bierce's short stories approach those three in the
unquestioned truth of combat. Mostly in the 1980s and '90s, their
novels were followed by the surge of what can be called military
novels, which aren't usually about combat, in which technology and
deadly hardware are the real heroes, not men.
</P>
<P>
   Still, realism has different meanings for every writer. In The
New York Times Book Review on May 9, 1948, the reviewer wrote of
Mailer's novel that the vignettes of war depicted in it ``are a
triumph of realism, but without the compassion which gives final
authority in the realm of human conduct.'' Which was precisely a
point of both the novel and the Spielberg movie. On the piece of
land being contested, compassion can be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview the other day Mailer recalled his war:
</P>
<P>
   ``Superrealism. I was in a war in which we never suffered huge
losses in combat like in Europe. I saw a hundred dead Japanese for
every dead American. Fatigue, heat, the oppressiveness of the heat.
We went out on long patrols to see where the enemy might be
located, walked 215 miles in heavy mud, a prodigious physical
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   And this wasn't the war he wanted to fight or write about. He
wanted to fight and write Private Ryan's war. (He hasn't seen the
movie yet, but will.) ``One of the ironies of being a writer is
that I always wanted to be in the first wave that went ashore in
France. And there I was in Fort Bragg on D-day and therefore I
couldn't write the great novel about Europe. I knew we were going
to the Pacific, and I was going to be stuck writing about what I
thought of as a minor war. I never realized I could have died on
that beach in Normandy.''
</P>
<P>
   But looking through his retrospectivescope, Mailer said that
``hoards of people'' read his novel of the ``minor'' war, and those
of Jones and Shaw, adding: ``That's important because if hoards of
people read it, the American consciousness is altered. The Second
World War was a watershed. Everything is of it, before it or after
it. It is a point of reference. It's still my point of reference.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that ``the most powerful way to show death in a novel is
to dispose of a character in a single sentence.'' Hence, Hearn's
death. ``I stole the device from E.M. Forster's `The Longest
Journey.' There was this character, Gerald, as I recall, and I
turned the page from Chapter 2 to 3, and Gerald was killed. It gave
me an enormous shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Shock and reality. The historian, Ambrose, said of the unit in
``Saving Private Ryan': ``I tried to describe what I heard from
Company A in the 116th Regiment of the 29th Infantry Division. The
ramps went down, and 90 percent dead in a minute. That sounds
impossible. I remember crying when I wrote it, just bawling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no possible way I can do in a book what the camera
can,'' Ambrose said. ``A novelist like Mailer or Tolstoy can do it
better than a historian'' and ``it's powerful but not like seeing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's movie has been out there only six days, and
ever-quick book publishers have seen the opportunity and are
already trying to seize it. One executive said he was at a meeting
when someone wondered aloud whether the movie's popularity might
not ``provide a commercial opportunity'' for a gory Civil War
novel.
</P>
<P>
   And over at Doubleday they are popping about like jumping beans
over the dumb luck of having Steven Pressfield's ``Gates of Fire''
ready for publication in November.
</P>
<P>
   The novel is about the Battle of Thermopylae in 480 B.C. when
300 warriors of Sparta held back an overwhelming number of
rampaging soldiers from the Persian Empire for six days before
being wiped out. Now that was bloody. So much so that Doubleday's
advance publicity claims Gen. George Patton would have carried this
novel with him while attending to World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
