<HEADLINE>
ELEPHANT BECOME LONG-DISTANCE PAPA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) _ The Kansas City, Mo., and Indianapolis zoos
are making history by making a baby elephant _ via long distance.
</P>
<P>
   The zoos announced Tuesday they have succeeded in impregnating a
female African elephant in Indianapolis with semen collected from a
male in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time that an African elephant has been
artificially impregnated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be one of the most significant conservation steps for
African elephants in this century,'' said Kansas City Zoo Director
Mark Wourms.
</P>
<P>
   The American Zoo and Aquarium Association, which accredits zoos
and oversees species survival plans, also is excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fabulous thing,'' said association spokeswoman Jane
Ballentine. ``It's a huge leap.''
</P>
<P>
   For two years, the Kansas City Zoo has collected semen regularly
from Dale, a 20-year-old bull. The semen is express-shipped to
Indianapolis, where zookeepers have implanted it in ovulating cows.
</P>
<P>
   An ultrasound on Friday confirmed a 9-week-old fetus within
Kubwa, a 22-year-old virgin cow. Gestation for elephants takes 22
months so it is very early, but officials say the fetus appeared
healthy. The calf will remain with its mother in Indianapolis when
born.
</P>
<P>
   There are only 12 bull African elephants in accredited zoos in
North America, and Kansas City has two of them. Kansas City was the
first zoo in the world to manually collect semen from an African
bull, using a technique developed in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The program is managed by curator Bruce Clark, veterinarian Kirk
Suedmeyer and animal area supervisor Theresa Schawang. Much of the
funding comes from Friends of the Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   The Dickerson Park Zoo in Springfield, Mo., has been working
with Asian elephants and last month announced the first successful
artificial insemination of that species. Veterinarian Dennis
Schmitt of that zoo has been working with both Kansas City and
Indianapolis on this project.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian elephant, now about 26 weeks into her pregnancy, had a
calf before. Schmitt said the African elephant pregnancy is
important for demonstrating artificial insemination can work in a
virgin animal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the cows are in zoos that don't have bulls,'' Schmitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 600,000 African elephants left in the wild. The
current rate of poaching for ivory could wipe them out in just a
few years.
</P>
<P>
   Elephant births in zoos have been rare and not enough to sustain
a genetically viable captive population. Without any change, there
may be no captive females capable of breeding within 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The logistics of moving elephants around to maximize breeding
opportunities are costly. Artificial insemination will allow
conservationists more flexibility in managing the gene pool _ both
in zoos and in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could theoretically go into the field and artificially
inseminate elephants,'' said Wourms. ``That means small populations
can suddenly become viable populations through long-term
management.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City also is working with the Henry Doorly Zoo in Omaha,
Neb., to develop ways to freeze elephant semen so genetic material
can be preserved indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   For the Kansas City Zoo, where a $71 million renovation earlier
this decade included state-of-the-art elephant facilities, the
successful insemination is a validation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is one of the largest contributions we have made to
worldwide conservation,'' said spokeswoman Denise Rendina. ``It is
a huge step forward and something our staff should be very proud
of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
