<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CHIEF-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE MAN WHO WOULD BE CHIEF': A GHANAIAN-AMERICAN CALLED TO LEAD
HIS TRIBE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lb) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can an American human-resources executive and basketball fan
transform himself into a tribal chieftain in Ghana? Such is the
decision facing Sule Issifu, who after 25 years in the United
States is summoned back on the death of his father to the family
village of Nalerigu. His relatives, an extended clan, are demanding
that he keep power over the 250,000-member Mamprusi tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying the Issifus (husband, wife and two daughters) are
Bill Kurtis and his ``New Explorers'' crew. While the camera
provides a travelogue of women with pots on their heads and dancers
in ceremonial garb, of long walks for water and an old slave fort,
Kurtis works at building suspense: ``A wrong decision would haunt
him for the rest of his life.'' ``They are two worlds far apart.''
All right, we get the point.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you can sympathize with the Issifus, faced with a future
in what Kurtis calls ``the simple life of the Middle Ages'': no
electricity but plenty of illiteracy; no sewers and not many paved
roads; five or six wives to a man and no evident means of support.
</P>
<P>
   Issifu is determined to resist such allurements, but pressure
from the Ghanaian side of the family is strong. The program doesn't
throw much light on the hours of closed-door arguments _ ``a roller
coaster of emotions,'' Kurtis assures us _ except for an
observation by Issifu that none of his 18 brothers ``is capable,''
and all appear to be counting on him for some sort of livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   Meetings are held with the elders in ceremonial dress, and there
are horsemen pretending to be warriors; Kurtis changes his safari
suit for a colorful local smock.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, I'm afraid, is a touch anticlimactic. Issifu
agrees to be the chief, but avoids the shock of a return to the
Middle Ages by deciding to rule his chiefdom from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   How will he manage that? He says he will employ his
human-resources training to help his people shape up. Reassured?
Well, the new leader evidences at least one qualification for
leadership these days; he talks, like politicians around the world,
about bringing his people into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `NEW EXPLORERS'
</P>
<P>
   The Man Who Would Be Chief
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Thursday on A&AMP;E
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Kurtis Productions for A&AMP;E; Bill Kurtis, host and
executive producer; Laura Wiessen, supervising producer; Joel D.
Sartori, associate producer/unit manager; Susan Green, producer;
Michael Cascio, executive producer for A&AMP;E; Gayle Gilman and
CarolAnne Dolan, supervising producers for A&AMP;E.
</P>
</TEXT>
