<HEADLINE>
`THE AMERICAN GAME': A LOOK AT LITTLE LEAGUE TENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lb) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beneath the buttoned-down image of the television anchor beats a
little boy's heart. Lucky Peter Jennings, tieless Thursday night in
Hagerstown, Md., not only looks inside the Amvets, a team with a
chance to make it into the Little League World Series, but gets to
play sports announcer for the district championship: ``They go
ahead once more, nine to eight. With Mike Vaverchak at bat again
and runners on second and third, National has a chance to blow the
game wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   No one can begrudge Jennings his outing, but what begins as a
tough look into Little League tensions, particularly between
fathers and sons, turns all soft with puffery about ``an American
rite of passage.'' At its best, when Jennings is at work as a
reporter, the program explores the values behind the cliches.
</P>
<P>
   He finds childish parents, driven coaches, unmannerly managers
and youngsters who are learning that winning is everything. The
program is a revelation as long as it keeps its eye on the people
and off the ball.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `Peter Jennings Reporting'
</P>
<P>
   The American Game
</P>
<P>
   9:30 p.m. ET Thursday on ABC
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
