</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAIN-DUST-HAZARDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGHER STANDARDS SET ON REPORTING HAZARDOUS LEVELS OF GRAIN DUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Federal warehouse inspectors are examining grain
elevators a lot closer in the wake of the June 8 DeBruce Grain
explosion in Wichita, Kan., that killed six workers.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement reached late last month, federal warehouse
inspectors with the U.S. Department of Agriculture's Farm Service
Agency now must immediately report potentially dangerous
accumulations of grain dust to the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration, which can order cleanups and levy fines for
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Two elevators in Minnesota and South Dakota already have been
targets for special OSHA inspections under the new rule.
</P>
<P>
   Farm Service Agency inspectors' findings of unsatisfactory
conditions, including hazardous situations involving grain dust,
previously were handled internally with elevator operators.
</P>
<P>
   Since late 1996, excessive dust was observed twice at DeBruce's
Wichita facility and was noted in reports by agency inspectors. If
such a federal agreement had been in place earlier, those findings
would have been forwarded to OSHA for corrective action and
monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mosteller of Wichita, whose son Scott was burned on 27
percent of his body and may lose some use of his hands, said the
crackdown in reporting might prevent future explosions.
</P>
<P>
   But Mosteller, who operates a farm and garden store in Wichita,
added, ``Grain elevators are not a new business. There have been
many deaths over the years. It's a shame families have suffered
because these problems weren't solved before now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did they have to wait?''
</P>
<P>
   The June 8 explosion ripped through the DeBruce Grain elevator _
one of the largest in the world _ killing six workers and injuring
six others. Flammable, airborne grain dust is strongly suspected as
the cause of the explosion, although no agency has made that a
formal finding yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Farm Service Agency's 58 U.S. inspectors are in Kansas City,
Mo., this week for scheduled annual training sessions, including
newly added lessons in how to apply the new interagency reporting
rule on grain dust.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki J. Hicks, a Farm Service Agency deputy administrator, said
Tuesday that it was difficult to determine when grain dust, which
is always present, reaches unsafe levels.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for North Kansas City, Mo.-based DeBruce said
Tuesday that the company had no comment on the new reporting rules.
</P>
<P>
   Farm Service Agency inspectors routinely visit grain elevators
and other agricultural facilities, but their authority extends only
to reviewing management and financial practices to protect grain
quality and the interests of grain owners.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors' written findings include observations of other
conditions that could affect the value of the stored grain,
including sanitary and safety issues.
</P>
<P>
   Excessive dust conditions at the DeBruce facility were noted by
Farm Service Agency inspectors in November 1996 and again last
August.
</P>
<P>
   Under previous procedures, those findings routinely were
forwarded to elevator owners for voluntary corrective action.
</P>
<P>
   In both instances, Farm Service Agency officials said DeBruce
executives responded satisfactorily with pledges of better
housekeeping practices.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new arrangement, any reports of unsafe grain-dust
conditions must be forwarded immediately by Farm Service Agency
officials to the appropriate regional OSHA office.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're not waiting for the paperwork,'' Hicks said.
Inspectors are instructed to telephone a supervisor, who then will
forward the information to OSHA the same day.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA then is to handle the information as a formal complaint,
triggering a round of special inspections and follow-up monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   The DeBruce explosion also was expected to be a focus of
long-scheduled hearings in Chicago and Washington this week to
review OSHA's 10-year-old safety rules on grain warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Such hearings are required each decade by federal law to weed
out outdated rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Carmichael, OSHA assistant regional administrator in
Kansas City, said his agency's warehouse rules allowed accumulation
of no more than one-eighth of an inch of grain dust on internal
surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Airborne dust is the cause of most explosions, he said. An
initial explosion disturbs layered dust, sending it airborne, where
it explodes in a chain reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You minimize the possibilities (of danger) if you keep the
accumulated dust levels low,'' Carmichael said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Farm Service Agency inspectors examined 3,580
warehouses subject to federal oversight under the U.S. Warehouse
Act and the rules of the Commodity Credit Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly twice that number of elevators are under state
regulation, Hicks said. The Kansas Department of Agriculture last
month also pledged greater cooperation with federal and state
safety offices in investigating worrisome grain-dust situations.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks on Tuesday praised Kansas for its initiative. ``We
certainly encourage other states to follow Kansas' lead,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, a former congressman
from Kansas, pledged last month during a visit to the DeBruce site
to institute the reforms on reporting grain dust.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Howard Goin, the last victim to be found in the
wreckage, isn't convinced that tougher reporting and more
inspections will make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Goin, 43, has worked at the DeBruce site for 24 years. He
was not at work the day of the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``OSHA can investigate to their heart's content,'' he said of
the new rules. ``But I don't personally believe that the dust was
that excessive (that day.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my dad in there. I'm not trying to stick up for the
company or anything. It was just one of those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the explosion happened, (the elevator) was as clean as it
had been in a long time. It was just an accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elevators are that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1731EDT &QL; 
