<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8796 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRUIT-ODD-KANSAS-KAN &LR;      07-29 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRUIT-ODD-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHAPE OF FRUIT IN THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KAREN UHLENHUTH  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There, prominently displayed in the produce
section of a Westport grocery store, was a peach that looked like
it had been sat upon. Flat. Squashed. Majorly compressed.
</P>
<P>
   And apparently it had been done on purpose, because there were
hundreds, if not thousands, exactly like it in the same big bin.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out it's known as a Saturn peach _ or a doughnut peach,
depending on what produce circles you travel in. It's in its second
season in wide distribution and probably available at a produce
department near you.
</P>
<P>
   After you get a good look at it, check out the price: 89 cents
apiece at the Mill Street Sun Fresh market, compared with perhaps
30 cents for the more rotund, and much larger, variety.
</P>
<P>
   And according to Ed Cox, the store's produce manager, ``We don't
brag about the quality of it. They don't have much flavor. They
just taste watery.''
</P>
<P>
   So why buy it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Variety,'' he said. ``People like it because it's something
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are constantly tinkering with what we eat, but change
is a hit-and-miss proposition, to be sure. Take fruit, for example.
Breeders both private and government-sponsored are always crossing
one fruit with another, or different strains of the same, trying to
improve on nature, or on the latest human-made hybrid.
</P>
<P>
   Seedless watermelons, peaches with white flesh and fall-bearing
raspberries have been a few of the results. Plumcots could be
coming soon. Craig Ledbetter, a research geneticist for the federal
Agricultural Research Service in Fresno, Calif., is one of the
breeders who's been marrying apricots and plums for years in search
of a fruit that combines the best of both.
</P>
<P>
   Plums have a nice thick texture, he explained, and apricots are
appealing for their flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could combine the plum's flesh density with the
apricot's aromatics, you'd have something pretty good,'' he said.
``That is my objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite a few offspring have been produced, ranging from ``things
that are very plumlike to things that are very much like
apricots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is one hurdle yet to be scaled before plumcots are likely
to produced on a large enough scale to show up in grocery stores,
Ledbetter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although some of these are very beautiful and very delicious,
unless we have a selection that is able to make a grower some
money, the grower won't be interested.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the plants so far developed simply don't produce enough
fruit, so ``it's just a novelty fruit,'' Ledbetter said.
</P>
<P>
   In the next couple of years a new variety of apricot known as
Robada should be in store produce bins, Ledbetter said. Its special
distinction: It develops its flavor a bit earlier than other
apricots, so that even if picked green, it will have some flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit-breeding has several goals, which are not always mutually
compatible.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're talking about any type of fruit crop, you want to
increase the season of fruit maturity, so there's a longer season
to pick the fruit,'' Ledbetter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second global objective would be resistance to diseases.
Another objective is improving fruit quality, getting higher levels
of sugar, lower levels of acids, more aromatics. The ratio of sugar
is what we perceive as tasting good or bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people prefer a high proportion of sugar relative to acid,
he said, with one marked exception: Asians, for the most part,
prefer fruit without acid.
</P>
<P>
   Catering to that market has recently become a mission of
fruit-breeders, Ledbetter said, and several acid-free varieties
have been developed.
</P>
<P>
   Some breeding efforts are aimed at cosmetic factors, he said,
such as fruit color.
</P>
<P>
   ``White flesh is becoming popular. It's marketing opportunities,
giving consumers choices.''
</P>
<P>
   With such a panoply of goals, however, breeders cannot always
take aim at all of them simultaneously. In fact, breeding for one
trait _ say, durability during shipping and handling _ often
detracts from another, say, taste and texture.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are nectarines that have little spots or freckles that
some people deem unacceptable. Breeders are saying, `We can't have
that.' Yet, it's pretty well-known that when nectarines have those
spots, they have very high eating quality,'' Ledbetter said.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, taste and texture lose out to appearance,
shelf-life and the ability to withstand the rigors of shipping.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, Ledbetter said, ``I don't like buying fruit in
the store. Most of it's garbage. I work in a fruit-breeding
station. I get it here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1732EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
