<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8813 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-RYAN-REALITY-AR     07-29 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RYAN-REALITY-ART-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-DAY, REAL AND RECREATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Corrects location of the ``Bridge too Far.''  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By M. R. MONTGOMERY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walter Zagol, a World War II paratrooper who survived D-Day, the
``Bridge too Far'' at Arnhem, and, as if that wasn't enough, the
siege of Bastogne in the Battle of the Bulge, has seen ``Saving
Private Ryan.'' He's fine. Got bored after the gory part, but
stayed because ``my grandson wanted to see the end of the movie.''
That may be a normal reaction for men who survived the reality
behind the myth of ``Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories and reviews on ``Private Ryan'' have raised concerns
about the opening 20 minutes of the film with scenes so violent and
so accurately evocative of the landings at Omaha Beach in Normandy
on June 6, 1944, and suggested that veterans will attend the film
at their peril. Some veterans will be disturbed: The post-traumatic
syndrome counselors at the Veterans Administration are gearing up
for an increase in the number of vets needing some help in the next
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Very few of those who are truly disturbed by the film will be
veterans of D-Day. Those who have lived this long (the youngest are
over 70) are the men least troubled by memories of carnage. All the
talk about those poor veterans who may go to the movie and be
brought to tears is, well, talk. A few may crack but most will not.
It was that way in the war, too.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Parks, a former Boston school official, spent D-Day on Red
Beach, one of the messier parts of Omaha Beach where the carnage
imagined and re-created in ``Private Ryan'' really happened. Parks
is looking forward to seeing the film later this week and doesn't
expect that the violence will bother him at all. He's been there:
``You have to understand, this was our first combat, we were
unprepared for the noise of the gunfire, the men screaming for
medical aid, all those dead bodies. But it won't bother me now. You
see, you fall into a groove in your psyche after a while, you
accept that it's war, that people are gonna die, you may die, so
you do your job, take your objectives, but with caution. You don't
lose that. You're still in that groove.''
</P>
<P>
   Zagol, a 101st division paratrooper, remembers the beach in
Normandy vividly. His outfit, after the jump, regrouped at the edge
of Omaha Beach. ``Did the violence in the movie bother me? Yeah, it
upset me,'' Zagol allowed. ``I remember the bodies on the beach,
but you know, I was wounded a few days later and sent back to the
beach to be evacuated, and the Germans got some planes over us and
strafed the hell out of the beach; I slept right through it. I
don't think the movie's going to bother anyone who was there.
You've seen so much, how can it really bother you any more?''
</P>
<P>
   Zagol went to the movie because his grandson wanted to see it.
``Actually,'' he recalled, ``after the first 20 minutes were over,
the real part, I wanted to go home. ... I mean, it just wasn't
realistic. They were running around throwing hand grenades into
buildings, they weren't staying behind the tanks when they moved
up. It wasn't the war I fought in.'' As for the movie's basic
premise, that a whole platoon of soldiers would be sent into
disputed territory to find a single soldier and bring him out,
Zagol couldn't think of a better comment than a very audible
snicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell,'' Zagol asked, ``how many vets are going to see it,
anyhow? I go to reunions now, and you don't see anyone you know. I
was young then, the officers, the sergeants, they were older,
they're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Parks, who farms in Southeastern Massachusetts, wasn't
planning to see ``Private Ryan,'' but he got a call from a talk
show host who was planning a call-in about the film. ``I thought I
ought to go,'' Parks related, ``so I'd know what I was talking
about if he does have the show.'' As a film critic, Parks is
generous. ``It was one of the better ones,'' he said, ``at least
not that John Wayne stuff, that Rambo stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part to watch, the worst,'' Parks continued, ``was
the beginning of the movie. My wife was funny, she watched it
through her fingers, and she was really worried about me, she
wondered if it wouldn't bother me that night.'' His experience
parallels that of Paul Parks and Zagol, that everyone has to find
that groove to survive: ``The worst of the invasion was right at
the start. You knew everyone, we'd trained together for years, you
knew the dead. Later on in the war, they were just serial numbers.
You get used to it.'' Ed Parks's war ended at the Battle of the
Bulge. Captured, he spent the rest of the war in Stalag 4B, south
of Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   And he had the same reaction, if milder, as Zagol to the movie
after the realistic violence of the invasion turned into the
psychological docudrama of sending a platoon of Army Rangers into
harm's way to save a single soldier. ``The uniforms,'' he began,
``were realistic. But the middle part was, well, pretty good. I
mean, you never saw anyone dig a foxhole. My God, the first thing
you did when you stopped was dig. Movement brought artillery fire,
guaranteed, so when you stop, you dig. `Dig or die,' that's we
said. Another thing, if you wanted to make it realistic: No one
ever sat down and ate anything. You stopped, you ate. People
bitched about the Army canned rations, but you ate. And you dug.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Parks, although eager to see the movie, is already prepared
not to like, or believe, part of it. ``Everyone tells me it _ the
war footage _ is actual, realistic. The thing they're telling me
that really bothers me is that the movie makes us out to be so
disorganized on the beach. How do you think we got off the beach?
It was the platoon sergeants _ most of the lieutenants got it right
away, they were obvious targets _ and the sergeants are who gets
you up and moving. Now,'' he summed up, ``if there had been
disorganization at that level, the sergeants' level....''
</P>
<P>
   Terence Keane, a psychologist at the Boston Veterans Hospital,
where he directs the National Center for Post-Traumatic Syndrome,
is not surprised that the veterans of D-Day are taking the movie in
relatively well-tempered stride. ``For one thing,'' he explained,
``the veterans that you can still find, still get ahold of, are the
lucky ones. The people who were most severely affected by the war,
well, they die earlier, you can imagine the causes, alcoholism,
heart disease, accidents. The healthier ones, that's who's talking
to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Keane also offered some insight into why veterans and
non-veterans might overlook, or only mildly object to, the film's
banal dialogue and unbelievable story line. ``Beginning the film
with that terrible and accurate footage of death and destruction is
what we call a `prime manipulation.' It's something we've studied,
used, and it affects the way people respond in all ways,
emotionally, behaviorally, cognitively. What Spielberg may have
done is primed them to deal with very serious issues, and then
given them a bad film.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Keane expects that this film, like others before it, will
trigger reactions in veterans suffering from post-traumatic stress
syndrome. ``We can expect something like a 20 percent increase in
our workload, numbers of clients seeking help, over the next few
weeks. This has happened with every very popular, very violent,
film since `The Deer Hunter,' back in 1978. That's the film that
made us aware of the problem. `Platoon' was another one, so was
`Born on the Fourth of July.'''
</P>
<P>
   While films might kick up visits to the VA, they don't hold a
candle to true life. ``The Gulf War,'' Keane recalled, ``we saw a
greater than doubling of patients. That's reality for you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
