<HEADER>
A8834 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH30-COX     07-29 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH GAP WIDENS BETWEEN RICHER, POORER
 &HT;    By DANIELLE SHOOK
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans' health seems to be getting better, but
low-income families or those less educated aren't benefiting as
much, according to a government report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Health and Human Services found record high
life expectancy, with a narrowing gap between whites and blacks;
record low infant mortality rates, and declining death rates for
heart disease, cancer, AIDS and firearm-related casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The life expectancy for all Americans reached 76.1 years, with
males born now expected to live 73.1 years and women 79.1 years.
The long-standing gap between blacks and whites has narrowed to
about six and a half years, or 76.8 years for whites and 70.2 years
for blacks.
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 to 1996, the leading cause of death, heart disease,
decreased 12 percent from 1052 to 134 per 100,000 people. Deaths
from cancer, the second leading cause, declined 5 percent, from 135
to 128 per 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   From 1995 to 1996, deaths from HIV infection, which causes AIDS,
dropped about 30 percent, from 73 to 51 per 100,000 adults aged 25
to 44. It declined from the first to the third leading cause of
death for people in this age group after accidents and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Firearm-related deaths dropped about 20 percent from 14.6 to
12.9 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health is improving in America along many fronts, and our
challenge is to share that progress as widely as possible,'' said
Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala in issuing the
annual report, titled ``Health, United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This comprehensive report shows the progress we're making, but
it also documents the strong relationship between socioeconomic
status and health in the United States for every race and ethnic
group studied.''
</P>
<P>
   The study found those with low incomes or less education have
more health risk factors _ such as a sedentary life style and
cigarette smoking _ were not as likely to have health insurance or
receive preventive care, and were more likely to report unmeet
health care needs.
</P>
<P>
   The report found:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cigarette smoking declined among adults 25 and older between
the years 1974 and 1995, but the decline was greater for more
educated adults. In 1995, roughly one out of four adults with less
than a high school education smoked, compared to one out of seven
who completed college.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Low birth weight and infant death rates were higher among
children of less-educated mothers than more-educated mothers.
Mothers that did not finish high school were about 50 percent more
likely to have low-birth weight children than college-educated
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Young children in low-income families had greater exposure to
environmental lead and elevated blood-lead levels.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Children in low-income families were more likely to be without
a regular source of health care than children in higher-income
families. Roughly 12 percent of children in families with incomes
below the federal poverty level did not have a regular source of
health care compared to 4 percent of children in families with
incomes at least twice the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
