<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTA-RICA:TECH-HUB-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSTA RICA: TECHNOLOGY HUB
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international and ``f'' financial files.) 
 By SERGIO R. BUSTOS 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SAN JOSE, Costa Rica _ Everybody in Costa Rica seems to know the
road to the new location of U.S. technology giant Intel. Of course,
it's hard to miss the massive construction site of a company that
is the world's biggest computer chip maker. A company that
surprisingly chose Costa Rica to locate its latest assembly and
test plant. A company that expects to employ up to 3,500 people and
invest US$500 million by the end of 2002. These days, conversations
about Costa Rica's investment and business climate begin and end
with the same subject: Intel. No doubt, Costa Rica is proud that
Intel, a global US$20 billion dollar company, chose to place its
millions in this Central American nation of 3.5 million people.
 &HT;    To understand the magnitude of Intel's multi-million dollar
investment, consider the following:
 &HT;    The cost alone of constructing the four Intel plants represents
six times the amount the country typically receives annually in
foreign direct investment (FDI). Between 1990 and 1996, FDI
averaged $272 million per year.
 &HT;    Exports from the Intel plants are expected to double the value
of Costa Rica's current $3 billion in exports by the year 2000.
 &HT;    This year alone, the expected $700 million worth of Intel
computer chips to be produced for export will overtake coffee ($544
million) and bananas ($391 million) as the nation's top exports.
 &HT;    The $500 million Intel investment is the single largest
investment ever made in Costa Rica.
 &HT;    Intel's Corporate Vice President Mike Splinter says the company
chose Costa Rica over Brazil, Chile and Mexico because of its
``excellent educational system.''
 &HT;    An independent report detailing Costa Rica's successful effort
in attracting Intel also cited the country's appeal to foreign
investors because of its political stability, a corruption-free
government, its commitment to economic openness and its small size.
 &HT;    ``Intel's decision to invest in Costa Rica serves as a rich
example of how a small country with no domestic market can still
lure a world class, high technology firm,'' says Debora Spar, a
Harvard University Business School professor, who wrote the report
for the Foreign Investment Advisory Service, which is jointly run
by the World Bank and the International Finance Corporation.
 &HT;    Indeed, Costa Rica's size and central location in the middle of
the hemisphere make it an ideal country for all kinds of foreign
investors, including those not tied to the high-tech sector.
Fast-food franchises, car rental companies, video rental outlets,
hotels, designer clothing boutiques and stores selling computer
products opened in recent years have all met with financial
success.
 &HT;    Costa Rica is Central America's top consumer of paper and
paperboard products, while agricultural chemicals are also in high
demand because the agro-industry still represents nearly 20 percent
of the country's GDP. Automobiles, telecommunications equipment and
computer peripherals are also among the sectors with the best
prospects, according to the U.S. Department of Commerce.
 &HT;    The banking sector remains dominated by state-owned banks, but
there is continued talk about privatizating the Banco International
de Costa Rica (BICSA), which was first recommended for a sell-off
in 1995.
 &HT;    The tourism sector bounced back last year following a
disappointing 1996 when the number of tourists dropped for the
first time in a decade. Last year, the number of tourists rose
nearly 4 percent to 811,490.
 &HT;    Although U.S. companies make up nearly 70 percent of all foreign
investors, European and Asian companies are showing growing
interest. For example, Germany-based Veba AG, through its
subsidiary, Wyle Electronics, is building a manufacturing plant
this year and expects to export US$7.5 million worth of
semiconductors.
 &HT;    Among Asian companies, the Taiwanese are most active. The
state-owned Taiwan Sugar Corp. (Taisugar), is investing in the
development of Costa Rican orchids for export. A huge greenhouse
facility will be completed at the end of this year and is expected
to produce more than 700,000 pots of orchids for export to Europe
and the United States, say Taiwanese officials.
 &HT;    The most notable Taiwanese company is computer giant Acer, which
opened its state-of-the-art customer service calling center in
1995. Today, the company employs 420 people and expects to hire at
least 100 more people in the next few years, says Flora Solera,
Acer's site director.
 &HT;    ``We looked at several countries _ the Philippines, Panama,
India _ but we chose Costa Rica,'' says Acer America Corp. Vice
President Max Hung, who says the strong education system, the large
number of bilingual (English/Spanish) Costa Ricans, the low cost of
communications and the high ``computer-literacy'' rate made the
country an overwhelming choice as a place to do business. He
cautions, however, that Costa Rica's pool of high-tech graduates is
growing smaller because of the country's very success in attracting
high-tech industry.
 &HT;    Perhaps the biggest single carrot Costa Rica dangles in front of
foreign investors is the free trade zones. Most newly arrived
foreign companies are locating their offices or plants in the
highly promoted Free Zones, which are comparable to industrial
parks found in the United States and elsewhere.
 &HT;    The parks offer a variety of tax exemptions for companies that
want to use Costa Rica as a base for exporting. Domestic sales of
manufactured products are not allowed. The first Free Zone opened
in 1982, drawing mostly textile companies. Today, there are nine
such parks, most located near San Jose. Nearly half of all Costa
Rican exports come from the free zones, while companies in the
zones last year imported an estimated $500 million in raw
materials. ``The free trade zone legislation has resulted in one of
the better export processing zone systems in the developing
world,'' says a World Bank study.
 &HT;    Despite the interest of foreign companies willing to invest, the
Costa Rican economy is straining under serious financial problems.
Newly elected President Miguel Angel Rodriguez, who took office in
May, promised during his campaign to tackle those problems by
cutting spending and pushing for the privatization of state-owned
companies.
 &HT;    At the top of the list of worries for the new Rodriguez
administration is the internal debt. Currently, the country owes a
whopping $4.1 billion, which represents 40 percent of GDP. Other
sources of concern include GDP growth, which last year registered a
disappointing 2.5 percent, well below the robust regional average
of 5.3 percent. It also had a trade deficit last year of $1.1
billion, according to Costa Rica's Central Bank. The trade deficit
through the first three months of this year is an estimated $184
million.
 &HT;    The consensus among analysts is that Rodriguez is a president
with a pro-business agenda and that he will bring government
spending under control.
 &HT;    ``The new administration has requested members of past
governments known for being market-oriented to form part of the new
cabinet,'' says U.S.-based BancBoston Securities analyst Rodrigo
Diaz. The appointment of former Commerce Minister Roberto Rojas as
Minister of External Relations ``symbolizes Costa Rica's clear
desire to attract international capital and investment,'' Diaz
says.
 &HT;    Another positive appointment is new Central Bank President
Eduardo Lizano, a respected economist. He will likely pursue a
policy of fiscal restraint and will push to privatize several
state-owned companies. Lizano served on a task force of economists
charged with resolving Costa Rica's growing internal debt. Its
recommendations included selling state-owned companies such as the
National Insurance Institute and the National Liquor Factory and
parts of its telecommunications monopoly.
 &HT;    Lizano is ``relatively optimistic'' that the country's economy
will grow, but he says it depends on the government's move to get
its financial house in order. ``With (former) President (Jose
Maria) Figueres, there was lots of talk of privatization, but
little was done.''
 &HT;    Costa Rica must reduce the cost of its high electricity rates,
fix its deteriorated roads and highways, and assure that customs
procedures are more efficient at its ports and airport so as to
attract foreign investors, he says.
 &HT;    Because of the relatively small size of its population, Costa
Rica represents little more than a footnote on the marketing plans
of many multinational companies. To compensate and to get one step
ahead of any future Free Trade Area of the Americas agreement, the
Costa Rican government is leading the drive to form a regional
trading bloc with other Central American countries and the
Dominican Republic. The bloc would create a market of 41.5 million
people with a $112.7 billion GDP.
 &HT;    For now, fiscal worries are overshadowed by the euphoria over
the arrival of Intel. Visit any government office and you will find
a souvenir marking the arrival of Intel. In one office, an Intel
hardhat and a paperweight were on display.
 &HT;    Costa Ricans, both in government and the private sector, say
Intel's arrival will spur other high-tech companies to make Costa
Rica high-tech manufacturing hub.
 &HT;    ``Intel's decision to come to Costa Rica says many things about
our country, but, most importantly, it says that everything and
anything is possible here,'' says Enrique Egloff, CEO of the Costa
Rican Investment and Trade Development Board (CINDE). The private,
non-profit organization that contracts with the government to help
foreign investors in Costa Rica.
 &HT;    ``This is the tip of the iceberg because Intel marks the
beginning of a new era for us,'' says Jose Manuel Salazar, who was
trade minister under President Jose Maria Figueres (1994-98).
``There is now a new wave of interest, especially high-tech, in
Costa Rica.''
 &HT;    A new wave of interest, indeed, is taking hold. U.S.-based
Photocircuits Corp., a circuit board manufacturer, invested $8
million this year and hired 400 workers to staff a new
24,000-square-foot plant outside San Jose. Eventually, company
officials say, it plans to invest a total of more than $30 million
and employ more than 700 employees over the next three years.
 &HT;    Earlier this year, U.S.-based EMC Technology formed a Costa
Rican subsidiary called EMC Tecnologia S.A., investing up to $2
million with a new plant. The company builds electronic components
for satellite communications.
 &HT;    Much of the credit for drawing the interest of high-tech
companies to Costa Rica lies with the government. During the 1980s,
as wages rose, the government shifted from begging textile
companies to chasing after high-tech firms. The strategy paid off
with handsome dividends.
 &HT;    During the last five years, 25 high-tech companies have invested
in manufacturing plants in Costa Rica, according to CINDE. Among
them are such companies as DSC Communications, Panduit Corp.,
Merrimac Industries Inc., Q-Bit Corp., Sawtek Corp. and Reliability
Inc. (all U.S.-based). During the early 1980s, U.S.-based Motorola
and Costa Rica-based Bourns Trimpot Electronicas, S.A. started
manufacturing electronic components.
 &HT;    The high-tech fever is not limited to foreign companies.
Software development is also becoming big business in Costa Rica.
According to the Costa Rican-American Chamber of Commerce, the
industry has 140 companies that employ 4,000 people. By the end of
this year, the sector is expected to export as much as $45 million,
up from about $25 million last year. Next year the figure should
continue to grow _ to $60 million, the chamber estimates.
 &HT;    Despite euphoria over Intel and the ambitious hopes of creating
a high-tech paradise, Costa Rica still must overcome nagging
problems endemic to other Latin American countries. For example,
getting a telephone line can take up to a year through ICE, the
government telecom monopoly. Official figures show that as many as
40,000 customers are waiting for telephone service. And, although
the industry is taking off because of the Costa Rican higher
education system _ which is graduating about 2,000 computer systems
designers each year _ local software developers complain about a
lack of financing and credit.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, nearly every government official interviewed for
this story said Costa Rica would become ``Silicon Valley South.''
 &HT;    But Lizano, the Central Bank president, says such talk is
premature. ``It's a dream that's a long way off,'' he says.
 &HT;    At the makeshift offices of Intel, located in a suburb outside
San Jose, the lobby overflows with young Costa Ricans awaiting job
interviews. Past the security guards, Danilo Arias, the company's
corporate affairs director, keeps busy handling the steady number
of media inquiries from around the world. He says everyone wants to
hear the story of the Latin American Silicon Valley.
 &HT;    Arias doesn't want to disappoint anyone, but he knows his
country's limits. ``A country like Costa Rica cannot draw this kind
of industry without a major public investment. Education, social
services, infrastructure _ all need to be in place,'' he says. ``If
two more Intels showed up in Costa Rica, the airport would collapse
from all the cargo.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SIDE BAR: Catching Multinationals
 &HT;    SAN JOSE, Cost Rica _ The Mexican state of Jalisco last year had
little doubt that U.S. chip maker Intel would choose it as the site
of its next multi-million dollar assembly and test plant. After
all, the Jalisco government had offered the huge multinational
corporation free land, cheap labor and cheap electricity rates. And
as for the mandatory union rules, the government assured the
company it could be granted an exception.
 &HT;    Intel officials refused the offer because they were ``wary of
the way business policy was formulated in Mexico,'' according to a
report put together by a team of researchers led by Harvard
Business School professor Debora Spar.
 &HT;    The researchers documented how a small Central American country
persuaded a major corporation to sink millions of dollars _ US$500
million by 2002 _ into its economy. The report was based on
interviews with Latin American government officials and exclusive
interviews with several key Intel officials involved in
negotiations.
 &HT;    The report, ``Attracting High Technology Investment, Intel's
Costa Rica Plant,'' was issued for a little known non-profit
organization called the Foreign Investment Advisory Service (FIAS),
which is jointly funded by the World Bank and the International
Finance Corporation.
 &HT;    But the report is more than just a portrait of one nation's
success in attracting a big company. It's the perfect textbook for
any Latin American government trying to figure out why a
multinational company chooses one country over another.
 &HT;    For example, Intel was turned off by Chile for a combination of
reasons, including the country's distant location, which made it a
transportation headache, and a perception that Chilean officials
seemed uninterested in high-tech companies. ``(President Eduardo)
Frei spent only two or three minutes with company officials after
being introduced to them,'' says FIAS researcher Damien Shiels.
``The company got the sense that Chile wasn't bending over
backwards for them at all.''
 &HT;    As for Brazil, one Intel company official close to the
site-selection process told Latin Trade that they visited Brazil
several times only to find themselves ``more confused'' after each
visit in trying to understand its laws related to business and
foreign investment. Intel officials were annoyed with Brazilian
government officials who issued a press release to announce that
Intel was interested in building a plant, accodring to Shiels. ``It
was unwanted pressure as far as Intel was concerned,'' he says.
 &HT;    For Intel, Mexico's deal was too good to be true, says Shiels.
``In Costa Rica, what you see is what you get in terms of the legal
side of business,'' he says. ``In Mexico, there is a certain degree
of negotiation attached to foreign investment ... For a
high-profile global company like Intel, it does not want to get
involved with side deals.''
 &HT;    Jalisco government officials were so shocked last year over
Costa Rica being selected that several Jalisco officials visited
Costa Rica this year to try to figure out what Costa Rica offered
that was so enticing to Intel.
 &HT;    ``Costa Rica did not ... grant (any) special favors, no side
deals or firm-specific concessions. But (it) did make major
adjustments _ at the airport, the schools, the free trade zones _
to accommodate Intel's needs,'' says Shiels. ``They had to, or
Intel almost certainly would have gone elsewhere.''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
