A8870 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT &LR;      07-29 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIXES ARE ELUSIVE FOR A SECURITY GAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Texas, Calif.)   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A serious security flaw in recent versions of Microsoft Outlook
98, Outlook Express and Netscape Mail _ three of the four most
widely used Internet electronic mail programs _ is proving more
difficult to fix than initially thought.
</P>
<P>
   Programmers at Microsoft and Netscape were scrambling last night
to devise solutions to the flaw, which could allow rogue
programmers to damage or steal data from a user's computer by
sending a seemingly normal e-mail message.
</P>
<P>
   After posting a software patch on its Web site Tuesday,
Microsoft programmers discovered that the proposed solution did not
fully fix the problem, leaving users vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is deeper and more complicated than was
reported,'' a Microsoft spokeswoman said. ``We hope to have a fix
by the end of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that Microsoft would not post any fixes for the
Outlook 98 and Outlook Express programs until the company was sure
they were fully effective.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem, Microsoft's own network crashed
Wednesday, preventing customers from gaining access to the Outlook
98 security information site. Microsoft has posted information
about the problem with Outlook Express at
www.microsoft.com/ie/security.
</P>
<P>
   To date, there have been no reports of attacks using the method,
which was discovered last month by security researchers in Finland.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail attacks have been possible for years in a slightly
different form, in which rogue programs are sent as attachments to
e-mail. When the recipient opens the attached program, it does its
dirty work. For this reason, users are routinely advised never to
open an e-mail attachment from a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   The new attack also involves attachments but has a nasty twist:
in some cases it can trick the computer into launching the rogue
code when the e-mail program retrieves the mail, without requiring
the user to open the attachment.
</P>
<P>
   The flaw exploits the inability of the affected e-mail programs
to read very long file names. If the attached file has a name
longer than the program can handle in its memory buffer _ longer,
for example, because it contains a string of computer instructions
_ the buffer overflows and causes the e-mail program to crash. The
computer is then tricked into running the rogue code.
</P>
<P>
   The flaw does not exist in the e-mail programs used by America
Online, which has more than 12 million subscribers, or in Eudora, a
popular e-mail program. Both America Online and Eudora have
protections already built in.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape, meanwhile, was working to fix a similar problem with
Netscape Mail versions 4.05 and 4.5b1. Netscape said it would
incorporate a solution in the next version of Netscape Mail,
scheduled to be available for downloading on Aug. 7. Netscape has
posted information about the problem at www.netscape.com/ &QL; 
products/security/resources/notes.html.
</P>
<P>
   Peter H. Lewis &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another computer virus did not cause the sky to fall this week,
despite warnings to the contrary. On July 26, the CIH virus was
supposed to affect computers running Windows 95 and 98, stopping
some machines, keeping others from starting and wiping out files on
yet others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had zero reports, nada, naught,'' said Alex Haddox,
director of the Symantec Anti-Virus Research Center, which had
posted a warning on its Web site though it had said the likelihood
of a problem was slight.
</P>
<P>
   The virus, which first showed up in the Far East, contaminates
32-bit executable files (the files with a ``.exe'' extension).
</P>
<P>
   ``Some program that is popular in the Far East got uploaded to a
popular site and that got a few first-generation infections, and
there were some second-generation infections, but the virus just
died,'' said David Chess of IBM's Thomas J. Watson Research Center
in Yorktown Heights, N.Y. ``People just don't share executables.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Watson antivirus research team remained vigilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever went broke overestimating a virus,'' Chess said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven E. Brier &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IBM's Big Blue computer shocked the chess world last year by
beating the human world champion, Garry Kasparov, in a series of
games. Emboldened, other game-playing computers are now challenging
human experts in backgammon, bridge, Scrabble, Go and poker.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Conference on Artificial Intelligence this week
in Madison, Wis., computer programs are having mixed results
against the humans, said Dr. Gerald Tesauro, a researcher at IBM's
Thomas J. Watson Research Center in Yorktown Heights, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Tesauro's neural network program, TD Gammon, running on a
400-megahertz Pentium II computer, lost Tuesday morning's
backgammon competition to the World Cup champion, Malcolm Davis of
Dallas. But it won the afternoon session, and going into
Wednesday's matches, it trailed by 15 points after about 60 games.
</P>
<P>
   After six games in the Scrabble competition, a program called
Maven, created by Brian Sheppard of the Hasbro toy company, was
dead-even with the human champion, Adam Logan, the top player in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Scrabble players will appreciate the high scores:
</P>
<P>
   Game 1: Logan 389, Maven 280
</P>
<P>
   Game 2: Maven 474, Logan 351
</P>
<P>
   Game 3: Logan 377, Maven 359
</P>
<P>
   Game 4: Logan 380, Maven 365
</P>
<P>
   Game 5: Maven 377, Logan 329
</P>
<P>
   Game 6: Maven 473, Logan 419
</P>
<P>
   The bridge program, GIB, lost narrowly to the human champions.
The Go competition had not yet begun, but the humans were heavily
favored. As for the poker program, Tesauro said he was looking
around the conference for a computer than could smoke cigars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter H. Lewis &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Apple iMac, to be released Aug. 15, got a vote of approval
from Dartmouth College, which placed the computer on its
recommended list for incoming students.
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth started recommending that new students have a computer
in 1984, and made it a requirement in the fall of 1991. The college
is primarily a Macintosh environment, with about 9,000 of the more
than 10,000 users already on Macs.
</P>
<P>
   Steven E. Brier &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE PRICE OF A NAME The San Francisco Chronicle reported this
week that Compaq, which owns the Alta Vista search engine, paid
Jack Marshall of San Jose, Calif., $3 million for the rights to the
domain name www.altavista.com. This is believed to be the most
money paid for a registered domain name.
</P>
