<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PRESS30-COX     07-29 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRESS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    USE OF ANONYMOUS SOURCES NECESSARY, JOURNALISTS SAY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With newspaper headlines and network newscasts
blaring that Monica Lewinsky is ready to testify that she and
President Clinton engaged in a cover-up of their sexual affair, a
White House spokesman warned journalists Wednesday to take what
they hear ``with a grain of salt till you know what the facts
are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And you don't know what the facts are,'' press secretary Mike
McCurry cautioned the White House press corps. ``You don't know
factually anything about what she's going to testify other than
what you've been told by anonymous sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the story broke six months ago, anonymous sources have
fueled the coverage of the alleged sexual relationship between the
president and a young White House intern and independent counsel
Ken Starr's investigation of whether there was a subsequent illegal
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   This week's developments are no different, as virtually all news
organizations quoted anonymous sources _ such as ``lawyers familiar
with her account'' _ in reporting what Lewinsky will tell a federal
grand jury under an immunity deal with Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Correspondents said they are comfortable with the credibility of
informed people who won't talk if publicly identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not anonymous sources to us,'' said Claire Shipman,
White House correspondent for NBC News. ``We know very well'' who
these people are, what their motivations are for talking and what
their past veracity has been, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of us likes to use anonymous sources, but
that's the reality of working in Washington,'' said Shipman. ``It's
an unfortunate fact of this investigation that nobody wants to go
on the record.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel queasy or uneasy at all'' about not identifying
sources, said Scott Pelley, the CBS News White House correspondent.
``I know who the sources are. I know we have multiple sources. ...
I know our reporting has been very solid.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Jonathan Wolman, Washington bureau chief for the
Associated Press, conceded to some misgivings about the reliance of
unnamed sources on such an important _ and potentially historic _
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly are reluctant to use them,'' said Wolman, whose
bureau cited ``legal sources'' in its Lewinsky report. ``Our
preference by a mile is to quote and identify our sources of
information by name.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it would be better to use sources who are on the
record'' publicly, agreed Len Downie, executive editor of the
Washington Post. ``But it's easy to understand why people supplying
us with information'' don't want to be identified. ``I'm satisfied
that our sources are excellent'' on the Lewinsky story, he said.
``I know who they are,'' Downie said, adding that he usually does
know the sources on stories of such magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   Reliance on anonymous sources is ``just the way life works'' in
Washington journalism, said ABC News White House Correspondent Sam
Donaldson. ``We can't get the information that the public wants and
needs without them.''
</P>
<P>
   Periodically, news organizations decree that they won't use
unnamed sources, but inevitably they change because they get beat
on too many stories, said Donaldson. ``In the theoretical world,
everything is on the record. But we're talking about the real
world.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN White House correspondent Wolf Blitzer said, ``You have to
make a judgment call. Are your viewers better off getting
information, attributed to anonymous sources, or better off being
kept in the dark?''
</P>
<P>
   Correspondents have a stake in insuring that their anonymous
sources are truthful, said Blitzer. The reporter's credibility is
on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a perfect science. Most reporters have been burned
from time to time by an anonymous source,'' he said. ``But that
source winds up burning himself'' because he loses his media
outlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viewers are pretty skeptical'' about anonymous sources, he
conceded. `` All of us in the national news media hope to build up
a reservoir of trust with viewers or readers. I'd like to think
that when viewers of CNN see me personally, they believe'' a news
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public makes a choice on which news organizations to
trust,'' said Pelley of CBS. ``You have to have a bond of trust
with the audience that, 'We can't tell you who the sources are but
that we trust these sources'.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
