<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BR5-49's shtick sliding into stale lines
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not a fan of BR5-49? How terribly unhip. At least that's what
the Nashville hype machine would have you think. In its two years
since being signed to a major label, the campy Nashville band has
toured with Bob Dylan, schmoozed with Conan O'Brien and been
featured on MTV. It's probably because these guys are masters at
imaging _ from the cheeky name (taken from a running Junior Samples
gag on TV's ``Hee Haw'') to the throwback string ties to the
plastic-deer yard art on the album cover.
</P>
<P>
   But, on this new album, the posturing is coming at the expense
of the music.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Stray Cats or Big Bad Voodoo Daddy, BR5-49 has plopped
down in a musical era _ in this case, 1950s big-twang,
cigarettes-and-ashtrays country _ which it excavates like an
obsessed college kid in a vintage clothing store. In the past, it's
worked. The band's first two releases were fresh and fun, if a bit
raw. The production is much tighter here, but the joke is wearing
thin. Gary Bennett's twangy lead vocals are so exaggerated that
it's like listening to 14 tracks of Gomer Pyle saying ``Shazam!''
Most of the cuts are swing-based (is this the new marketing
direction?) rather than barroom, making the album extremely
repetitive.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. BR5-49 has proven that it can pull off the retro sound
with style. But peel away the packaging and promotion, and this CD
is more like an aging lava lamp _ the novelty is starting to wear
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Backyard Beat Show''
</P>
<P>
   BR5-49. Arista. 14 tracks
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Cartoonish country falls short of this band's
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
