<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oddball formula carries over to Zippers' latest
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Accidental geniuses of counterprogramming, the members of the
Chapel Hill, N.C., outfit Squirrel Nut Zippers went over big time
on modern-rock radio by being the exception to the rule. The rule
was, and still is, a half-hearted shotgun marriage of Nirvana 'n'
Hootie that goes down as smoothly at the Gap as at the local
college beer barn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell,'' the Zippers' breakthrough novelty hit, worked
precisely because it wasn't like that or anything else. And, though
the band's Dixieland-meets-Cab-Calloway revival was gosh-awful
quaint, it was close enough in retro spirit to the nostalgic
lounge/swing movement to charm any card-carrying member of the
Martini Nation. Shaken or stirred, these Tar Heels were a sleeper
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The band's sophomore album, ``Perennial Favorites,'' is a
cheerfully oddball affair that won't catch any newly won fans
off-guard. Champagne visions of Lawrence Welk and Billie Holiday
bubble through a dozen new tunes, which evoke the antic spirit of
old cartoon soundtracks, the bluster of polka and the brassy tones
of a dime-store Duke Ellington. The lighthearted humor (``The Suits
Are Picking Up the Bill,'' ``Fat Cat Keeps Getting Fatter'') that
makes the music so effortlessly likable also renders it bland,
however, which makes me wonder why the Zippers didn't tinker more
with their formula. The effort's made: For a few seconds, here and
there, the band indulges a music-box dementia that sounds like, oh,
Stephen Foster hijacked by a gamelan orchestra, or Bartok enjoying
a healthy pinch of Red Man. Yo, Beck: Are you up for a remix?
</P>
<P>
   ``Perennial Favorites''
</P>
<P>
   Squirrel Nut Zippers. Mammoth. 12 tracks
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Flashback favorites flirt too closely with formula.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
