<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8915 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS30-COX     07-29 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS30-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Audio reviews: the word on the latest sounds
</P>
<P>
   By Richard L. Eldredge, Doug Hamilton, Al Levine, Sonia Murray,
and Nick Tatec. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   -- POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Gloria!''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Estefan. Epic/Sony.16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   With ``Gloria!,'' Cuban-born Gloria Estefan temporarily leaves
her trademark sappy adult contemporary ballads to Sony sister
Celine Dion. ``Gloria!'' successfully merges Estefan's high-energy
urges with today's top dance mix masters. The result is a nonstop
dance workout as all the Latin-flavored tracks segue into one
another. The first single, ``Heaven's What I Feel,'' has already
made a big club dent in its remixed form, so look for the Wyclef
Jean-penned and remixed ``Don't Release Me,'' also featuring a rap
from Jean, to follow. ``Gloria!'' also represents the first
successful attempt to satisfy both the singer's U.S. and Cuban fan
bases. Four of the album's best tracks come in both English and
Spanish versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dopamine''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Froom. Atlantic. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of producing and arranging, Mitchell Froom steps
out from behind the mixing board to make an album of extraordinary
wit and originality. Cross MTV's ``Liquid Television'' with David
Lynch and you get a feel for this West Coast keyboard whiz's weird
cinematic style. A handful of famous friends, including wife
Suzanne Vega, lend their vocals to this collaborative enterprise,
but in Froom's hands they leave familiar territory behind. Vega's
vocals on the club-friendly title track are menacing and seductive.
Sheryl Crow's piercing ``Monkey Mind'' has a sci-fi appeal. And Ron
Sexsmith's ``Overcast'' is surrealistic Gershwin. ``Dopamine''
covers a ton of musical territory in just 30 minutes. Some of it is
chilling, most of it is quirky and all of it is delightful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small Soldiers'' soundtrack
</P>
<P>
   Various artists.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks Records. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   As aggressive as rap tends to be, pairing it with similarly
powered rock 'n' roll was a virtual no-brainer. The smarts came in
on the ``Small Soldiers'' soundtrack when the creators asked
hip-hop artists Bone Thugs-N-Harmony to match their lulling rhymes
with Flea's muscular guitar on their dynamic re-creation of Edwin
Starr's ``War.'' Rapper-producer Wyclef Jean tag-teaming with the
late Freddie Mercury on Queen's ``Another One Bites the Dust'' is
another heavyweight champ. And that's it. Instead of continuing a
concept that really works, this ebbs into a remix project that
simply checks in.
</P>
<P>
   -- ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the Radar''
</P>
<P>
   Little Feat. CMC International Records. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Of course Little Feat will never be the same without Lowell
George. When the fitfully brilliant writer of such 1970s radio
classics as ``Willin''' died in 1979, he took with him the
critic's-darling status his band had enjoyed. Since the surviving
members regrouped in 1988, Little Feat has become a technically
solid, crowd-pleasingly slick blues/R&AMP;B act. The latest album
boasts more lively jams and adventurous asides than you'd expect
from an act nearly 30 years old. Too bad about the cliched lyrics.
The group's vivid history should inspire more than hackneyed
platitudes such as the title track's ``I'd walk on fire to get back
to you.''
</P>
<P>
   -- COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``What If I Don't Stay the Night''
</P>
<P>
   Mindy McCready. BNA. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   On her second album, Mindy McCready underscores the themes that
marked her debut: female independence and orneriness. But the act
is getting a little old. She scored with ``10,000 Angels'' and
``Guys Do It All the Time,'' and her new lyrics have the same
message. On ``What If I Do,'' she asks, ``What if I do, will he
love me more; what if I don't, will he walk out the door?'' And
then there's ``This is me, take or leave it; my own girl, you
better believe it.'' By the time she coos seductively in ``Only a
Whisper,'' we're tired of the tease.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
