<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Levert sings from heart_ of aches and breaks
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gerald Levert has made a career out of beautifully singing what
some men struggle to say. Instead of an unimaginative come-on, he
coyly asks the object of his affection to ``School Me.'' When his
peers were speaking of relationships as an unnecessary evil,
Levert, in his big, palpable baritone, proclaimed, ``I'd give
anything and everything to fall in love.''
</P>
<P>
   But, obviously, love is a struggle. And instead of a well-penned
metaphor or a primary focus on the hearts and flowers of romance,
Levert's third album is mostly heartbreak and frustration laid
surprisingly bare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing hurts like a woman with dreams that don't involve
you,'' he says on ``What About Me.'' That's clear, because the
conviction Levert once used to describe pleasant matters of the
heart is now applied to songs of infidelity (``Thinkin' Bout It'')
and breakups (``Taking Everything'').
</P>
<P>
   At times, his focus on pain and his frequent use of cliches is
almost distancing, but Levert's storytelling ability lures you in,
particularly on ``That's the Way I Feel About You,'' a duet with
his peer in ache, Mary J. Blige. Next thing you know, tears are
dropping in your ear again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love &AMP; Consequences''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Levert. Eastwest.
</P>
<P>
   13 tracks
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: If this really is Gerald Levert's much-rumored
adieu ... whew.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
