<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Giamatti homes in on a pithy parallel well worth noting
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 2: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a posthumous collection of essays titled ``A Great and
Glorious Game'' (Algonquin, $14.95), the late A. Bartlett Giamatti,
Renaissance scholar, one-time president of Yale University,
one-time commissioner of major-league baseball, wrote that the game
he loved was, above all else, a metaphor for going home. And not
just about arriving, but ``how hard it is to get there and how
driven is our need. It tells us how good home is. Its wisdom says
you can go home again but that you cannot stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Giamatti, as many know, was the game's hymnist, given to
mythopoetic musings far removed from the coarse calculations of Jim
Leyland, the monstrous swings of Mark McGwire, the blithe spirit of
Andruw Jones. There have always been poets in the press box, but
Giamatti discerned in the game's slow progress through nine innings
intimations of something Homeric.
</P>
<P>
   This is, to be sure, ground that has been plowed and replowed to
the point of exhaustion. Yet it's worth asking why the national
pastime should give the idea of home so central a place. Football
has its end zone, sacred ground to be struggled and striven for,
defended like Stalingrad one minute, laid siege to the next. But
``end zone'' strikes no chords. It conjures up the battlefield, not
the place we speak of habitually, even if we must search our hearts
to find it.
</P>
<P>
   An American concept
</P>
<P>
   ``The word home,'' Reynolds Price wrote some years back, ``is an
obsession of the American language, not the English. In four years
of living in England, I never heard an Englishman use the word
hometown,for instance.'' And modern French, Spanish and Italian,
though they have words meaning ``house'' and others suggesting
``hearth,'' apparently have none equivalent to the word Americans
find need for many times a day: homemade, homemaker, home breaker,
homecoming, home free, homebound, homeless, homesick ... home.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same notion that Witold Rybczynski developed at
greater length in his book ``Home: A Short History of an Idea.''
Rybczynski, an architect-turned-social historian, didn't draw upon
the baseball diamond for evidentiary support, but his book could
have been a brief against the sterility of the steel-and-beam
structures built in the '60s _ stadiums that Turner Field and
Camden Yards are reactions against.
</P>
<P>
   Where Giamatti's was a metaphorical (and perhaps metaphysical)
view, Rybczynski's was an apologia for simple human comfort
(``During the six years of my architectural education, the subject
of comfort was mentioned only once.'').
</P>
<P>
   People have been living in houses for eons, but they've been at
home for a comparatively short time. When Europe was emerging from
the Middle Ages, a middle-class household accommodated not just an
immediate family but also a gaggle of servants, apprentices,
friends and proteges, everyone eating, cooking and sleeping
together like vagabonds. Not until the 16th century did dwellings
acquire anything resembling furniture: a bed, stiff-backed chairs,
a cushion or two, a rude table for eating. It would be still
another century, in the Netherlands, before separate rooms were set
aside for meals and sleeping, but at least people had begun to live
in houses and not simply camp in them.
</P>
<P>
   A yearning for domesticity
</P>
<P>
   In time, the French would produce overstuffed furniture, built
with comfort consciously in mind. And the English, in the Georgian
period, would carry developments further with interior designs that
continue to influence modern living. But for humble domesticity we
thank the broom-whisking Dutch, who, as Rybczynski wrote, ``brought
together the meanings of house and of household, of dwelling and of
refuge, of ownership and affection. ... You could walk out of the
house, but always returned home.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the idea of home was born, corollary notions of convenience
and efficiency, leisure and ease took shape also. Yet, true as all
this is, most of us understand by ``home'' something more than
day-to-day comfort. We understand something of what Reynolds Price
described. In the United States, a person may have several homes in
a lifetime _ stops along the way to somewhere else, each invested
with the emotions (not to mention toil and sweat) that yearn for
permanence.
</P>
<P>
   Home, in so mobile a society as ours, thus means many things,
from place of birth to wherever we're hanging our hat at the
moment. But if it means anything, it means a bulwark against
rootlessness. And once we are uprooted, it becomes another place we
left behind, the cold ground in which our past remains. There's
comfort even in that, but only when secured by the warm hard earth
of home underfoot.
</P>
<P>
   When it is not, as Giamatti wrote in ``A Great and Glorious
Game,'' ``the journey must always start once more, the bat an oar
over our shoulder, until there is an end to all journeying.'' Until
we've reached home, one day for good.
</P>
<P>
   -- E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
