<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Camp meeting a tradition worth keeping
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 2: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's almost camp meeting time in Georgia. Those crops that the
heat and drought haven't burned up are, in the poetic phrase, laid
by. It's almost time to put the chairs in the wagon, hitch the milk
cow to the tailgate and head for Old Salem or New Hope or blessed
Shiloh campground.
</P>
<P>
   But until camp meeting starts, there are decoration days at
small churches all over the state. I have been to a few, and I can
report that the time spent decorating old graves and remembering
the departed is only a part of it. There's food and singing and
reunioning to sustain body and spirit for another year.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Monroe ``Buddy'' Stamps, who calls himself my banker
emeritus (he left Roswell(Ga.)'s Citizens and Southern Bank, where
he was manager, soon after we moved out there), had the advantage
of growing up where camp meeting and decoration day were major
summertime events.
</P>
<P>
   He writes: ``My grandmother had been a dyed-in-the-wool
foot-washing, hard-shell Baptist in her younger days, so my mother
and dad would make the annual pilgrimage to the old home place each
summer, somewhere around Bowdon Junction in west Georgia, so that
Mama could visit with her old friends. It was a joyous occasion
beginning early on the appointed Sunday morning and lasting until
sunset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Families would begin arriving early, some in trucks, a good
many in one- or two-horse wagons with kitchen chairs set in the
beds, and all loaded with baskets and boxes of food, some of which
had been in preparation all week long. Enough fried chicken,
country ham, fried pies and cakes to feed the whole 7th Cavalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old country church was situated in a beautiful grove of
hardwood trees, and soon the entire grove would be crowded with
wagons, trucks, cars, mules, dogs and people, all dressed in their
Sunday best, as the men set up tables and the womenfolk sorted out
the food. The small fry ran in and out, playing tag and other games
and occasionally snatching a fried pie left momentarily
unguarded.''
</P>
<P>
   He continues: ``Inside the little church could be heard the
sweet sound of `fa-so-la' singing, replaced periodically by real
down-home, pulpit-pounding preaching. At some point, the
foot-washing would take place. This went on much of the day, with
people moving in and out of the church at will, and outside would
be heard the cries of recognition as friends found each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The reunioning isn't remembered so happily as the food,
according to Mr. Stamps. Every small child was ``fair game to every
lady on the grounds,'' he reported. They were scooped up,
``enveloped in a pair of strong motherly arms, clutched to a soft,
billowy bosom, and hugged near to asphyxiation amid the acrid fumes
of `Evening in Paris' dusting powder.''
</P>
<P>
   When the preacher announces that it's dinner time (lunch is
unknown in the country), ``the feeding frenzy begins among the
trees,'' Buddy tells us. ``Children are fed and admonished, July
flies abound, hound dogs beg and receive chicken bones. ... Teenage
girls and boys shyly find each other amidst giggles and flaming
cheeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The after-dinner preaching and singing end as the sun begins to
go down. ``It's all over. Collection is collected, benediction is
given, final goodbyes said, and everyone promises to meet again
next year.''
</P>
<P>
   It strikes me as a country fete worth preserving, better by far
than television and maybe even the Sunday papers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
