<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Dark City' a hellish haven for intrepid sci-fi fans
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dark City'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   This mesmerizing sci-fi labyrinth from the makers of ``The
Crow'' unfolds with the creepy (il)logic of a nightmare. Rufus
Sewell plays an amnesiac who wakes ups in a bathtub with a dead
woman nearby. He doesn't know who he is, or for that matter where
he is.
</P>
<P>
   This city is a sunless place of neo-noir detectives (William
Hurt, for one) and voluptuous retro girls, personified by Jennifer
Connelly as the woman Sewell thinks may be his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and there are these creepy bald aliens in black trench coats
with the power to put all the city's humans (except Sewell) into a
trance and morph the entire skyline into a new shape.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing science fiction, pulp mysteries and existential dilemmas
into one attractive package, ``Dark City'' is that rare movie that
makes you believe in a different world. It deserves to become a
cult classic. One drawback: Kiefer Sutherland almost kills the
flick with his freak-show performance as a toady of the evil ETs.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
