<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views: Short reviews of new video releases
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``The Gingerbread Man'' (R) _ Yes, it has Robert Altman's
distinctive jazzy touch, and good performances from Kenneth
Branagh, Robert Downey Jr. and even Daryl Hannah. And it captures
the weighty, moist mood of Savannah 10 times better than Clint
Eastwood's awful ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil.'' But
all these pluses can't overrule one major minus: The John
Grisham-based screenplay (cocky lawyer falls for femme fatale)
plays out like a subpar TV movie from the 1970s. Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Live Flesh'' (R) _ Spanish director Pedro Almodovar isn't
having the same day-glo fun he used to have in movies like ``Women
on the Verge of a Nervous Breakdown.'' In fact, this adaptation of
a novel by mystery writer Ruth Rendell plays it relatively
straight, though the colorful art direction still flirts with camp,
and the director's fascination with sex remains. But here it
results in serious consequences. The enjoyable, melodramatic love
quadrangle includes Javier Bardem, Francesca Neri and Angela
Molina. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Hard Rain'' (R) _ All wet. Christian Slater plays a guard
whose armored car is ambushed by bad guys (led by Morgan Freeman)
in a flooded small town. The result is an endless progression of
shootouts, chases and big waves of water. It's an action film
written so by-the-numbers that it radiates pure contempt for the
audience. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   -- ``A Brother's Kiss'' (R) _ This gritty New York drama, which
didn't get an Atlanta theatrical release, stars Nick Chinlund and
Michael Raynor as brothers who survive a rough upbringing by their
alcoholic mother (Cathy Moriarty) but grow apart as adults. Raynor
becomes a cop, Chinlund a junkie. With a cast that includes Rosie
Perez, John Leguizamo and Marisa Tomei, the movie's dead-end tale
is sometimes too familiar. But first-time director Seth Svi
Rosenfeld and the actors bring conviction to the drama. Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Little Men'' (PG) _ This adaptation of Louisa May Alcott's
novel takes place at an enlightened school for boys run by Jo
(Mariel Hemingway) and her professor husband (Chris Sarandon).
Respectful, handsomely done and a bit dull, this Canadian
production has that Sunday school-lesson sheen. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
