<HEADER>
A8922 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MEMOIRS-COX     07-29 1527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MEMOIRS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reaching a destination is not nearly as important as the
journey, memoirs reveal
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 2: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A memoir recaptures place as much as the past. The geography _
psychological and physical _ that the writer travels is often a
major character in a life story.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Lopez, visiting Antarctica in ``About This Life: Journeys
on the Threshold of Memory,'' describes the importance of locale:
``Over the years, one comes to measure a place ... not just for ...
the sublime pleasures it offers, but for what it teaches. The way
in which it alters our perception of the human.'' The writer of a
memoir, perhaps more necessarily than a novel's protagonist, comes
to a new understanding. Self is remade, often in the course of
writing.
</P>
<P>
   A memoir is frequently an odyssey, with motion specific or
implied in titles. So important is motion that its absence is
noteworthy. ``Still Me,'' the title of the best-selling memoir by
the suddenly paralyzed actor Christopher Reeve, has double meaning.
Though he can no longer sail or ride horses or feed himself, his
essence forges on in an internal odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   If place, as Lopez holds, alters our perception of the human, a
memoir chronicles the human alteration of perception. In the life
stories reviewed here, writers come to terms with parents and home.
As Natasha Tarpley notes in her family tale, ``Girl in the
Mirror'': ``You're constantly negotiating between where you come
from and where you think you're going.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Slow Motion: A True Story.'' By Dani Shapiro. Random House.
$23. 245 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing slow-motion about Dani Shapiro's memoir is the
title. A few paragraphs in, most readers will be so caught up in
this tale of a prodigal daughter that the pages will practically
flip themselves. Shapiro grew up in an Orthodox Jewish home in New
Jersey, but by age 23 she had ``strayed far from that home,''
dropping out of Sarah Lawrence College to become the pampered,
alcoholic mistress of Lenny, a wealthy New York lawyer. Her life
evolves into ``a series of random events that have no logical
connection.'' New York City is less the locus of her existence than
the terminus for a jet-set life.
</P>
<P>
   A phone call divides her life into before and after: Her parents
have been gravely injured in a car crash back home. As she watches
her brain-damaged father fade and her broken mother struggle to
walk, Shapiro wants to recover her old self but doesn't know how.
Hebraic prayers echo in her head, but cocaine and vodka are too
tempting, and she lives at Lenny's beck and call. His life is built
on lies, and the gradual revelation of his character, petal by
petal like an artichoke, is magisterial.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of Shapiro's characters resists caricature a la
``Portnoy's Complaint.'' This memoir, like Kathryn Harrison's ``The
Kiss'' (minus the incest), comes to terms with a sexual past, and
was written after the author married and turned to writing. But
``Slow Motion'' is notable in that religion and culture _ home _ so
patently form the desire and basis for reformation. Though
Shapiro's conversion is not religious, her confession, like St.
Augustine's, is a magnificent testament to victory over nothingness
and going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Skating to Antarctica: A Journey to the End of the World.''
By Jenny Diski. Ecco. $23.95. 250 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Writing, too, is Jenny Diski's salvation in this icily titled
memoir about coming to terms with a British childhood. ``The will
to live was not strong in my family,'' she writes. Her father was a
suicidal con man who deserts wife and daughter and dies. Her mother
at first dotes on Diski with skating lessons. ``My mother dreamed
of making me into an ice princess,'' like Sonja Henie, Diski
writes. ``What she got ... was an ice maiden.'' An instance of
sexual abuse by her mother instigates Diski's suicide attempt and
hospitalization. Helped by a foster family, she painfully
reconstructs her life, though she battles lifelong depression.
Diski marries, has a daughter, Chloe, and writes novels. She does
not see her mother for 30 years, has no idea whether she's alive
and doesn't care. Chloe, nearly an adult, decides to find her
grandmother. This angers and frightens Diski, who craves oblivion
in her entirely white bedroom, which she wants to extend ``beyond
reason.'' She decides to visit Antarctica, which represents ``a
place of absolute peace and quiet.'' As she prepares to sail toward
her geographical goal, much like Ahab searching for the white
whale, she also delves into her past, looking not for her mother
but for herself. Aboard a ship of fools and sages in the Antarctic,
she discovers that reaching the destination is not nearly so
important as the journey. Chloe, on her own odyssey, uncovers the
fate of Diski's mother. Diski's triumph over her unloving parents
lies in the book's dedication: ``For Chloe without whom.'' The
circle of hatred is broken.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Rebuilding the Indian.'' By Fred Haefele. Riverhead.
$24.95. 210 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Even readers who don't give a dang about motorcycles will enjoy
this tale in Montana, a home of the Unabomber and the Freemen.
Muses Haefele, ``When you live in a state with 800,000 people, how
often do you hear the CNN anchor say, `Elsewhere in Montana today
...'?'' Haefele, who came of age in the 1960s, has not been notably
successful except as an arborist and in his 16-year relationship
with Caroline. His first marriage long ago went kaput, he
communicates with his grown daughter but not his messed-up son, no
one will buy his novel and his teaching job at Stanford University
dried up. Then he comes into $5,000 and decides to rebuild an
Indian, a motorcycle that went out of production in 1953. A couple
of days after he buys the basket case, Caroline finds out she's
pregnant. As the child grows within her, the Indian grows in
Haefele's garage. So does his Gold Card balance. And so does his
circle of friends, to include Bootsy, Magoo and Bummy. But
especially there's Chaz, a sort of Parts Father for motorcycle
rebuilders, with a troubled marriage and finances. Haefele would
like to get him out of his life, but they share a commitment to
Indian rebuilding and the same antidepressant. Baby Phoebe arrives
long before the Indian is ready to ride to a big meet. But much,
much more is rebuilt than a motorcycle in this rich, all-American
memoir that is as off the beaten track as Missoula.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Tea That Burns: A Family Memoir of Chinatown.'' By Bruce
Edward Hall. Free Press. $25. 308 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Though the opening pages may recall Maxine Hong Kingston's
``Woman Warrior,'' Bruce Edward Hall's voice soon overcomes any
echoes. This re-imagined family history tells the interwoven story
of the Hor family, Manhattan's Chinatown and the Chinese in
America. Hall's great-grandfather emigrated from China in 1873,
leaving behind two wives to set up an American family on Mott
Street. Hor Poa kept his hairstyle and his connections to home, but
he also was influential in Chinatown politics. Over the decades,
the family becomes Americanized. Hall's grandfather, a bookie who
enjoys Tea That Burns (bootleg Scotch), marries a Chinese woman and
lives most of his life on Mott Street. But Hall's father weds a
Caucasian from Oklahoma, changes the family name to Hall and moves
to the suburbs. Bruce, ``a Connecticut boy ... who could eat with
chopsticks,'' feels like an insider/outsider when he attends family
celebrations in Chinatown. Yet he is powerfully attracted to the
locale, where ``I could almost smell the beginning of time,'' and
he yearns to be a tourist to the past. Hall re-creates the past so
admirably that readers will mourn a culture's diminution.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Girl in the Mirror: Three Generations of Black Women in
Motion.'' By Natasha Tarpley. Beacon. $22. 181 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Tarpley's memoir about her grandmother, her mother and herself
gloriously challenges the boundaries of the genre, using novel
techniques, poetry and even a newspaper obituary to tell the
generational tale. In the 1940s, Tarpley's grandmother Anna leaves
Alabama to join her husband in Chicago, after some fine
conversations with emptiness. Tarpley's mother, Marlene, moves from
Chicago to Boston after her husband dies, and Tarpley travels with
her mother to visit Africa in one of the book's ironic highlights.
Home, a safe place, is what Tarpley seeks. Though the memoir is in
three sections, one for each woman, it is often not chronological.
It is, however, a puzzle well worth putting together. Tarpley tells
her grandmother the reason she's writing the book: ``I'm looking at
glimpses of your life and Mom's life to see how they overlap with
and impact my own. How the past informs the present.'' If Tarpley
is more successful in rendering her mother's and grandmother's
lives than her own, it may be because the present can be more
elusive than the past. But this book reinvents memoir, infusing it
with a heartbeat you can hear and feel.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
