<HEADER>
A8923 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEW-RECIPES-COX     07-29 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEW-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Long-cooking labor of love says you care
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 2: DO NOTR USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henrietta Stanley Dull's recipe for Brunswick stew was anything
but dull. In her 1928 book, ``Southern Cooking,'' the longtime food
editor of The Atlanta Journal began her stew with directions that
seem closer to pioneer times than ours:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thoroughly clean pig's head and feet. From the head remove the
teeth and gums, upper and lower. Place head, feet, liver and heart
into boiling water and cook slowly until meat falls from the bones
and will come to pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   At least she didn't throw in eye of newt.
</P>
<P>
   We quote Mrs. Dull because, while the following recipes are
time-consuming, at least they aren't gruesome. Making stew, burgoo
or hash isn't easy. As Ray McLees, a hash man in Tryon, N.C., says:
``To go to this much trouble, you want to be making it for a good
cause, or at least for people you know _ preferably blood kin.''
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Brunswick Stew
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 3 quarts Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes, plus 3-6 hours
</P>
<P>
   This is a domesticated version of the stew my family has been
making since the 1800s. For a small batch, you can use a crockpot
and not have to worry about stirring. If you want to multiply the
recipe and make a larger batch, you'll have to use a pot and, as my
father says, ``Stir, stir, stir!''
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2pounds chicken pieces (weight includes skin and bones)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2pounds lean ground beef (round or sirloin)
</P>
<P>
   3/4pound ground pork
</P>
<P>
   1can (28 ounces) whole tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1can (14 3/4 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   creamed corn
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons ( 1/2 stick)
</P>
<P>
   butter
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3/4teaspoon red pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt (or to taste)
</P>
<P>
   Remove skin and excess fat from chicken pieces. Place in a pot
and cover with water. Bring to a boil, then lower heat and simmer
until meat falls off bones, 20 to 30 minutes. Drain broth. After
the chicken has cooled, pick the meat from the bones, shredding
into small pieces.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, cook the beef and pork together, stirring
often and breaking into fine pieces, until the meat is just gray.
Drain excess fat. Add chicken to beef and pork.
</P>
<P>
   Put meat mixture into a large pot or crockpot. Add the tomatoes,
corn, ketchup, vinegar, butter, black pepper, red pepper and salt.
Mix well. Cook over low heat for 3 hours, stirring from the bottom
of the pot often. (Or, if using a crockpot, cook for 5 to 6 hours
at a low setting.) Taste after an hour or so to fine-tune
seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1-cup serving: 333 calories, 29 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 50), 13 grams carbohydrates, 105
milligrams cholesterol, 547 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Brunswick Stew
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 1 1/4 gallons Preparation time: about 45 minutes
Cooking time: 2 1/2-3 hours
</P>
<P>
   The stew of Brunswick County, Va., is different from Georgia's
in that it usually contains more vegetables and fewer meats _
chicken, but rarely pork. John D. Clary, a businessman in the
county seat of Lawrenceville, cooks this often at community
fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   2 3/4pounds boneless chicken
</P>
<P>
   3ounces fatback, ground
</P>
<P>
   2pounds potatoes,
</P>
<P>
   peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4pounds onions (about 4 medium), diced
</P>
<P>
   Black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   128-ounce can crushed tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   5cups small butter beans, frozen or canned
</P>
<P>
   3cups shoe peg corn, frozen or canned, drained
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons ( 1/2 stick)
</P>
<P>
   butter
</P>
<P>
   Red pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Sugar to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a large stockpot, cover chicken and fatback with water, about
1/2 gallon. Bring to a boil and cook over medium heat until chicken
starts to fall apart, about an hour. Add potatoes and onions,
pepper to taste, and boil until potatoes are soft. Add tomatoes and
more pepper and simmer 10 minutes. Add butter beans, bring back to
a boil and cook until they're soft, about 20 minutes. Add corn and
simmer another 30 minutes. Turn off heat and stir in butter until
it melts. Season to taste with pepper, salt and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1-cup serving: 512 calories, 37 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 35), 48 grams carbohydrates, 109
milligrams cholesterol, 587 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Moonlite Burgoo
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 1 1/2 gallons Preparation time: 30-40 minutes
Cooking time: about 4 hours
</P>
<P>
   Burgoo is to Kentucky what Brunswick stew is to Georgia _ the
communal dish that used to grease the skids at political barbecues
and now shows up at church picnics and the like. The burgoo capital
has to be Owensboro, an Ohio River city that specializes in mutton
barbecue. Owensboro's numerous Catholic parishes stage enormous
fund-raising dinners; at St. Pius X's gathering in June, they
cooked 7,000 pounds of barbecue and 700 gallons of burgoo. Most
burgoo cooks in Owensboro use a recipe similar to this one from the
Moonlite Bar-B-Q Inn, the city's best-known barbecue restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   2pounds lamb shoulder
</P>
<P>
   (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2pounds chicken pieces
</P>
<P>
   2cups finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   cabbage
</P>
<P>
   1cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2pounds potatoes,
</P>
<P>
   peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2cups corn,
</P>
<P>
   canned or frozen
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups tomato puree
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons distilled
</P>
<P>
   vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4tablespoons salt
</P>
<P>
   (or more to taste)
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   In a large saucepan or kettle, cook lamb in water to cover until
tender, about 2 hours. Discard broth and bones. Chop meat fine and
set aside. Meanwhile, in large stockpot, cook chicken in 1 gallon
of water until tender, about 30 minutes. Remove chicken and set
aside. Add cabbage, onion, potatoes, corn, ketchup and an
additional 1/2 gallon of water to the chicken broth. Bring to a
boil over medium-high heat. Reduce heat to medium and cook until
potatoes are tender, about 20 minutes. Meanwhile, chop chicken
meat, discarding bones and skin. When potatoes are tender, add
chicken, lamb, tomato puree, lemon, vinegar, Worcestershire sauce,
salt, pepper and cayenne. Return to a boil. Reduce heat to
medium-low and simmer 2 hours or more, stirring occasionally from
the bottom as it thickens.
</P>
<P>
   Burgoo is often served with bread, but crackers or corn bread
are also good.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Our tester used lamb shoulder, which is more readily
available than mutton. Some cooks add dried or frozen lima beans,
tomatoes and a little boiled shredded beef or wild game.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1-cup serving: 239 calories, 18 grams protein, 5 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 19), 31 grams carbohydrates, 48
milligrams cholesterol, 941 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Barbecue Hash
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 quarts Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 6
hours
</P>
<P>
   Brunswick stew is found from Virginia to Georgia with one big
exception: South Carolina. The equivalent there is hash. It appears
to be an adaptable concept. A few years ago, I judged a barbecue
contest with a hash category; the cooks brought everything from a
reddish gravy to a yellowish soup to something with diced apples in
it. The classic hash is a simple dish made from cooked-down pork or
beef leftovers. Dan Huntley, a columnist for The Charlotte Observer
and all-around foodie, gave us this version of a beef hash.
Properly cooked, it should have the consistency of baby food, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   5pounds beef (not counting the bone _ any cut)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2pounds onions, diced
</P>
<P>
   1pound butter
</P>
<P>
   1to 2 tablespoons salt
</P>
<P>
   Black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Place the beef in a large pot, cover with water, bring to a boil
and simmer for 3 hours, replenishing water as needed. Turn off the
heat. Once the meat has cooled, tear it off the bone. Reserve
stock. Process meat and onions in a food processor. Return mixture
to the pot. Add butter, salt, pepper and reserved stock. Simmer for
3 hours, stirring often.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1-cup serving: 790 calories, 35 grams protein, 70 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 80), 6 grams carbohydrates, 217
milligrams cholesterol, 1330 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
