<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stew wars: Brunswicks do battle
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the longest-running debates in Southern food concerns the
genesis of Brunswick stew.
</P>
<P>
   Virginians say it originated in 1828 on the banks of the
Nottoway River in Brunswick County when a slave named Jimmy
Matthews threw together some squirrel, onions and stale bread to
feed a hunting party. The Virginia Legislature endorsed the tale in
a 1988 proclamation, and markers went up around the county
declaring, ``Other states have made similar claims, but Virginia's
is the first.''
</P>
<P>
   The other states are North Carolina, which also has a Brunswick
County, and Georgia, where the city of Brunswick is no less attuned
than Virginia to the value of publicity. Brunswick, Ga., claims to
have created the stew in 1898 and displays the sacred birth caldron
at its visitors' center.
</P>
<P>
   Who's right? Food historians give more credence to Virginia's
boast, although they point out that the dish probably descended
from camp stews that Indians and pioneers had improvised for years.
</P>
<P>
   But that's almost beside the point. When you've got a
good-natured public spat going, what's the sense in settling it?
Says John D. Clary, a prominent Brunswick County, Va., stewmaker:
``We're going to ride this thing for all it's worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
