<SLUG> BC-STYLE-SHEENA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia teen gets royal treatment as magazine modeling finalist
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 2: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Right now, there's not a cloud in the sky for future
meteorologist Sheena Lutes.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old from Acworth, Ga. spent five days in New York
last month as one of eight national finalists _ selected from
20,000 entries nationwide _ in the Seventeen magazine and Chanel
New Model of the Year Contest.
</P>
<P>
   While her friends back home shopped at area malls, Sheena
modeled a pricey Chanel outfit, had a makeover at the trendy
Frederic Fekkai salon and ate pasta at the Fashion Cafe in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   It was a heady experience for the green-eyed blonde, who saw the
contest advertised in the March issue of Seventeen and sent in two
pictures. In May, she learned she was a semifinalist. ``I was
ecstatic,'' recalls Sheena. ``I screamed and cried at the same
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When looking at pictures, we look for diversity and
uniqueness,'' says Jennifer Shapiro of Seventeen. ``We also look
for self-confidence, which came through loud and clear in Sheena's
pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Sheena and the seven other finalists must wait until the end
of this month to find out who snagged the top prize _ an appearance
on the November cover of Seventeen. Other winning perks: a five-day
trip to Paris, including tickets to a Chanel fashion show, and a
$1,000 shopping spree. Runners-up will appear as models in the
issue. And all eight will be featured in segments of
``Entertainment Tonight'' and ``Extra.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheena is an old hand when it comes to entering magazine model
contests. She was a recent semifinalist in the YM model contest but
has not yet heard if she placed in a Teen magazine competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheena just began testing with us and so far, so good,'' says
Cathleen Gehling of Elite Models Atlanta. ``She has lots of energy,
moves well in front of the camera and has a classic look _ with an
edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheena has a good feeling who will win the top prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think I have a pretty good shot,'' says the teenager,
who likes to wear jean shorts, tank tops and metallic gray nail
polish when hanging out. ``Everyone who saw my pictures said I had
potential, and I felt comfortable during interviews with model
agency representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheena is certainly a winner in the eyes of her parents, Cindy
and Mark Lutes, and her 5-year-old sister, Calee. ``Sheena has
already won over 20,000 other girls. It (the contest) was an
eye-opening experience for her and a great opportunity, but I would
prefer for her to finish school,'' says her mom.
</P>
<P>
   Whether she becomes the cover girl or not, Sheena wants to
continue modeling. She hopes to be in front of the camera for 10
years, become famous and make lots of money. Then she plans to turn
her eyes toward predicting the weather _ which can prove almost as
fickle as a modeling career.
</P>
<P>
   SNIPPETS ABOUT SHEENA
</P>
<P>
   WEARS: A size 4-6 and is 5 feet, 8 inches tall.
</P>
<P>
   LOVES TO: Swim, play basketball and draw pictures of animals: a
school project done in eighth grade _ a pencil drawing of horses _
exhibited in a Japanese museum.
</P>
<P>
   ADMIRES SUPERMODEL: Claudia Schiffer.
</P>
<P>
   LIKES TO SHOP: At Old Navy
</P>
<P>
   SO FAR: No boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ON NEW YORKERS: ``They dress really neat. And they aren't rude.
They just move faster and talk faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
