<HEADER>
A8926 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TABOO-TV-COX     07-29 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TABOO-TV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Television mores have been replaced by a new rule: Forget the
rules.
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 2: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Comedian George Carlin's old trademark routine is ``The Seven
Dirty Words You Can't Say on TV,'' a classic bit from the '70s that
has him rattling off a string of unprintable obscenities.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer, bizarro comic Bobcat
</P>
<P>
   Goldthwait is hosting a new game show on the cable network FX
that includes one of Carlin's once-forbidden phrases in its title.
And, no, we still can't print it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite chronic complaints about the lack of ``family-friendly''
programs and the adoption of a content ratings system intended to
alert viewers to potentially offensive material, Taboo TV is upon
us.
</P>
<P>
   From the profanity-laced 'toons on Comedy Central's ``South
Park'' to the syndicated slugfests on ``Jerry Springer,'' the
rigidly enforced television mores many adults grew up with have
been replaced by a new rule: Forget the rules.
</P>
<P>
   As the fall season approaches, the broadcast and cable
television schedule is liberally sprinkled with pedophilia, drug
use, hard-core violence, foul language, nudity and other topics
viewers rarely discussed 20 years ago, much less watched on the
family television set.
</P>
<P>
   There are still plenty of safe havens for viewers who prefer
shows that are more like a warm glass of milk than a shot of
battery acid. Later this month, PaxNET (touted as a wholesome
alternative with reruns of old shows) and Fox's revamped Family
Channel will join Nickelodeon, TV Land and the Trinity Broadcasting
Network in programming shows exclusively for small children, teens
and impressionable grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, however, television is no place for the faint of
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A is ``Lolita,'' a film version of Vladimir Nabakov's
novel about a tortured love affair between a middle-aged college
professor and a young girl (she's 12 in the book, 14 in the movie).
</P>
<P>
   Oscar winner Jeremy Irons stars as the lovesick Humbert Humbert
pathetically obsessed with teenager Dominique Swain in the title
role.
</P>
<P>
   Completed two years ago, the movie was orphaned by its studio
and barred from U.S. theatrical release because the subject matter
was considered too risque for moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but tonight's debut of ``Lolita'' on the premium channel
Showtime is shaping up as the first, and splashiest movie event of
the fledgling TV season.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Lolita'' contains no sexually explicit scenes, Irons
and Swain share several onscreen encounters that are disturbing
even by the more relaxed standards of cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Is Showtime programming chief Jerry Offsay nervous about getting
calls from cultural conservatives or protests from outraged
parents' groups? Hardly. At the recent television critics
convention in Pasadena, Calif., Offsay said viewers seem less
uptight about what's considered appropriate fare for television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some radio stations gave out my office phone number as a joke
thinking I would get flooded with calls,'' Offsay said. ``I got
just one call from a concerned person who said they were praying
for me. I'm sure there will be some people who will be unhappy, but
we invite people who want to criticize (`Lolita') to see the film
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Showtime executives don't discuss Nielsen ratings,
Offsay expects the lusty ``Lolita'' to be one of the most watched
and talked about movies on the network this season, and with good
reason.
</P>
<P>
   HBO, which fancies itself the gold standard of pay cable
networks, is known for high-quality movies and high-minded programs
that consistently win industry awards and critical acclaim. A quick
look at its Nielsen ratings reveals that HBO viewers are fond of
documentaries, especially when they're about sex.
</P>
<P>
   The top-rated show on HBO for the period ending in June was the
documentary series ``Real Sex 19,'' followed by ``Real Sex 20.'' A
documentary about prostitution, ``Pimps Up, Ho's Down,'' was a
not-so-distant third, beating out more expensive, heavily promoted
original movies such as the Emmy-nominated ``A Bright Shining
Lie.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO's highest-rated series is ``Sex in the City,'' about a New
York newspaper columnist who covers the mating habits of horny
yuppies.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why so many of the network's highest-rated shows have
sex in their titles, HBO chairman Jeff Bewkes answered, ````Real
Sex'' has been a real draw for years. I guess that's what people
want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   And they're not just seeing Taboo TV on pay cable. Even on
commercial television, which relies on skittish advertisers for
revenue, subjects that were considered scandalous just a year ago
are being greeted with ho-hum acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ABC sitcom star Ellen DeGeneres' decision to reveal her
homosexuality on national television created a media frenzy and a
brief ratings spike before the show was canceled, as she put it,
for being ``too gay.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, ``Ellen'' might not have been gay enough. NBC is
introducing ``Will and Grace,'' a sitcom about a male-female
friendship that raises the stakes with suggestive banter and
multiple gay characters.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to this exchange on the phone between good-looking gay
lawyer Will and gorgeous, straight, best friend Grace during the
pilot episode:
</P>
<P>
   Grace (while lying in bed with her boyfriend): ``Are you
jealous?''
</P>
<P>
   Will (while watching the NBC drama ``ER''): ``Honey, I don't
need your man, I got George Clooney.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace: ``Sorry, baby, he doesn't bat for your team.''
</P>
<P>
   Will: ``Well, he hasn't seen me pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   While there are still no openly gay lead characters on CBS, the
network's new cop drama, ``Martial Law,'' has plenty of openly
violent ones. The show features a kung-fu-fighting detective
transplanted from China who might have a higher butt-kicking
quotient than ``Walker: Texas Ranger,'' the network's other
Saturday night punch-happy do-gooder.
</P>
<P>
   CBS spokesman Dana McClintock insists the network is not pushing
the limits of good taste to keep pace with edgier entertainment on
cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of cable channels are narrowcasting and going after a
certain niche of the audience,'' McClintock said. ``We are trying
to reach a broader section of viewers. We are _ and will always be
_ broadcasters.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC spokeswoman Susan Sewell said her network hasn't been
influenced by cable or the content ratings that some feared were a
veiled attempt at censorship by politicians and television watchdog
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used the same standards we have always used when it comes
to making the fall schedule, which is basically `Is it a good
program?''' Sewell said. ``Our goal is always to put the best shows
on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   At TNT, taboos die hard, or most of them anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the network refused to broadcast Anjelica Huston's
``Bastard Out of Carolina,'' a television movie that showed brutal
scenes of child sexual abuse. The movie was later picked up on
Showtime, where it won an Emmy. Still, Terri Tingle, vice president
of standards and practices for TNT, has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing unusual about `Bastard' was that it was a very
public decision, but there are very many times when we look at a
show and say, `This is not for us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Tingle admits the network has been having second thoughts about
professional wrestling shows such as ``Monday Nitro,'' which are
among the most violent, and popular shows on cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think everybody understands that wrestling is not a sport;
it's a drama more like a soap opera, with characters and continuing
stories,'' Tingle said. ``But we are looking into the question
right now about whether it's too violent. There's been a lot of
publicity about wrestling, and we wouldn't be responsive if we
weren't listening to what was being said.''
</P>
<P>
   But TNT's rude-and-crude wrestlers are no match for the
profanity-spewing third-graders on ``South Park,'' a show
ostensibly for adults (it's rated TV-MA) that has attracted a huge
following of viewers under 18.
</P>
<P>
   The show features wrestling matches between Jesus Christ and
Santa Claus, the ritualistic killing of a main character in every
episode, and more swear words than comedian Carlin ever bothered to
count.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there's also one of the show's most beloved characters, Mr.
Hanky. He's a talking feces.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central President Doug Herzog faced a group of television
critics recently who wondered if the cable network's biggest hit
has ever been censored.
</P>
<P>
   ``What doesn't get on the air?'' Herzog said. ``You don't want
to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
