<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8928 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-CROMWELL-COX     07-29 2522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-CROMWELL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pistol-packing author's dreams are just as grisly as her
thrillers
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 2: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charleston, S.C. -- On the afternoon of her book signing here,
Patricia Cornwell is unusually nervous for an author with 10 best
sellers under her Armani belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wonder if anybody's going to show up,'' she says as
the black stretch limousine navigates the streets of Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   Or if the wrong person will show up.
</P>
<P>
   Cornwell's fame _ and the grisly crimes she writes about in her
novels featuring medical examiner Kay Scarpetta _ has left her so
cautious that she travels with at least two bodyguards and hires
armed, off-duty police officers for book signings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have the books for the security guys?'' she asks. A
female staffer nods and shows her a stack of Cornwell's latest
Scarpetta thriller, ``Point of Origin'' (Putnam, $25.95), No. 1
this week on The New York Times Best Seller list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good,'' Cornwell says, checking the time on her expensive gold
Breitling pilot's watch. She is wearing no makeup, a simple white
gold necklace and a pinkie ring designed from an ancient seal that
reads, ``Don't tell.'' She smiles and ignores the warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I'm paranoid, but that's the way it is out there.
In New York the other night at a signing, a guy showed up with a
knife on his belt. He was told to get rid of the knife or leave, so
he left. Maybe it was nothing, but look at what happened to
celebrities like John Lennon and Monica Seles.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the two stalkers in Richmond, not to mention
Eugene Bennett, the FBI agent who accused Cornwell of breaking up
his marriage after she had an affair with his wife _ also an FBI
agent. Days after a bizarre incident in which Bennett attempted to
ambush and kill his wife at a Manassas, Va., church in the summer
of 1996, his rented car was found parked in Richmond, Cornwell's
hometown. The author is convinced that he was there to hurt her.
(Bennett was convicted of attempted murder and is serving a 23-year
prison term.)
</P>
<P>
   All the details of the 1992 lesbian affair and its repercussions
were discussed in numerous articles last year, including a lengthy
piece in Vanity Fair that described Cornwell as a control-obsessed
woman with anorexia, drinking problems and a bipolar disorder who
jettisons longtime friends in the wake of her success.
</P>
<P>
   Cornwell admits that she was ``devastated'' by the Vanity Fair
article.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would try to sneak out of my house and get the newspaper
without my neighbors staring out the window and saying something
awful. But you know what? People don't really care. They only care
if you don't write another good book.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently she is right. Inside Books-A-Million in Charleston,
more than 300 Cornwell fans stood in a line that snaked around the
store. Many carried multiple copies of her novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her personal life is her business. It has no bearing on the
books,'' says Leslie Stall, 27, a forensic scientist for Charleston
County. ``I really like the technical aspects of her writing
because that's the kind of things I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Bridges, 51, a nurse who drove more than 400 miles from
Thomasville, Ga., just to get Cornwell's autograph, remains an
unabashed fan. ``I love her books,'' Bridges says. ``As for what
she does in her personal life, I think everybody is entitled to
find happiness where they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the autograph table, Cornwell patiently poses for
pictures with fans and graciously accepts a Beanie Baby from a
6-year-old girl. The roped-off area behind her is off-limits,
however, and lingering admirers are ushered away quickly once their
books are signed.
</P>
<P>
   When the last customer leaves three hours later, Cornwell stands
up, flexes her writing hand, slips into a navy Armani jacket and
heads for the limo. Lean and petite with blond-streaked hair,
Cornwell, 42, is a real-life model for Kay Scarpetta, the
brilliant, always-in-control medical examiner who has tracked
serial killers and psychopaths through nine novels.
</P>
<P>
   Both she and Scarpetta are fighters, Cornwell says, and both are
armed and dangerous. The fictional Scarpetta totes a Glock 9 mm;
Cornwell is never far from her .357 Colt Python, .380 Walther
semiautomatic or .38 Smith &AMP; Wesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't sit around cowering,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Cornwell has been obsessed with the dark side of life since
1979, when she began work as a police reporter for The Charlotte
Observer. Two years later, determined to become a novelist, she
took a job as a computer analyst in the Richmond morgue and wrote
three books about a male detective. After all were rejected,
Cornwell's agent suggested that she write about her experiences in
the medical examiner's office. The result was ``Postmortem,'' her
first Kay Scarpetta novel, which netted her a $6,000 advance and
launched a career that earned her more than $17 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Author Frye Gaillard, who worked with Cornwell at the Observer,
isn't surprised by her success.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had an incredible drive, and she was very focused,'' says
Gaillard, 51. ``She worked hard at what she did. To me, that's been
the key to her success as a mystery writer.''
</P>
<P>
   She also was well-liked and always willing to help, Gaillard
says. He recalled an incident in which Cornwell overheard him
complaining about not being able to get in touch with evangelist
Billy Graham for an article.
</P>
<P>
   ``This intern who I had never had contact with said, `Would you
like me to call him for you?' When I asked her if she knew him, she
picked up the phone and dialed the number from memory. I heard her
say, `Ruth? This is Patsy. Is Billy there?'''
</P>
<P>
   Gaillard later learned that Cornwell's relationship with the
Grahams began in 1965, when her mother _ divorced, desperate and
nearly broke _ left her and her two brothers with the Grahams in
Montreat, N.C. The Grahams placed the children with Christian
missionaries who had just returned from Africa, but over the years
they offered emotional and financial support.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was working my way through Davidson College as a
waitress, Ruth would send me letters with a $100 check in them. She
was like a mother to me,'' Cornwell says. That relationship was
broken when Cornwell wrote an authorized biography of Ruth Graham
in 1981. Through a misunderstanding, Cornwell says, the two did not
speak to each other for eight years. ``It was just a tempest in a
teapot,'' the novelist says. ``We joke about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   As her fame grew, other friendships suffered. Dot Jackson, a
former columnist for the Observer, was Cornwell's best friend for
years. The friendship ended soon after Jackson's son committed
suicide by hanging himself. According to last year's Vanity Fair
article, Cornwell flew in to see Jackson and, in the midst of her
grief, began grilling her about details of her son's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the things that appeared in print were taken out of
context,'' says Jackson, 66, who lives in upstate South Carolina.
``She was very interested in his cause of death, but I saw this as
just an example of how intense she is. Nothing distracts her from
her pursuit of gruesome details. I wasn't angry with her about it.
That's just the way Patsy is.''
</P>
<P>
   What destroyed the friendship, Jackson says, was a dispute over
a screenplay treatment that Jackson had written at Cornwell's
request.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later on, she wanted me to relinquish any claim to the
screenplay. She said I was an employee at the time, and this was
work for hire. I had been her oldest friend, and for her to treat
me like an employee was intolerable. I still love her dearly, but
she's a master manipulator. She has to be in control.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornwell wasn't always that way, says Jackson, who remembers her
as fun-loving and spontaneous when she worked at the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was precious before she became famous. What was ironic is
that when she was a cop reporter, she was very anti-corpse. She
didn't want to be around dead people. And she was terrified of
lesbians. A lesbian cop followed her home one night and scared her
to death.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does Jackson explain why her former friend ended up
working in a morgue and having a lesbian affair?
</P>
<P>
   ``As Stephen King says, very often we are drawn to the very
things that frighten us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornwell has a different version of the breakup of the
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day I don't know why she turned against me. I went to
see her after her son's death and spent several days with her, and
she wanted to talk about the pathology report. Then later she told
the press that I wanted to learn more about hanging for my next
book. I loved her like a mother. You think that didn't hurt me,
really badly, to have somebody think that I would go visit somebody
in grief like that, and I only did it for information?''
</P>
<P>
   Cornwell shakes her head and sighs. Jealousy is the only
explanation, she says. Friends hate you for your success.
</P>
<P>
   Old friends, maybe, but not new ones. Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah)
has only praise for Cornwell. ``She's a heckuva nice person,'' says
Hatch, who admits he had never heard of the author before they met
at a California hotel a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the hotel gym to exercise, and there was this young
woman on the Stairmaster next to me. `I know you from somewhere,'
she said, and I introduced myself. She said, `I'm Patricia Cornwell
and I'm a novelist.' I said I wasn't aware of her books. She was
surprised, but the next day she gave me three of her novels and I
loved them.''
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely pair struck up a friendship later when Cornwell
popped into Hatch's office to lobby for an upgrading of the FBI's
police academy in Quantico, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that what she was saying was absolutely true, that
she had really done her research,'' Hatch says, ``so I went to bat
for the facility. After that, we became good friends. She's a very
strong personality, and when she wants to get into a subject, she
really gets involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornwell acknowledges that almost everything she does is related
to her writing. Obsessed with learning about technical details
firsthand, she often spends months in research. For ``Point of
Origin,'' a novel about a fatal fire at a thoroughbred horse farm,
she investigated dozens of arson cases with ATF agents in
Philadelphia and Washington and learned to fly a helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to show readers what can be done with fire and how it
can be used to disguise a homicide,'' Cornwell says. ``In this
case, what Scarpetta has to figure out is not that it was used to
disguise a homicide, but that the killer is disguising what he does
to the body. And what he does is horrific.''
</P>
<P>
   So horrific, in fact, that Cornwell's nightmares have become
even more disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to have nice dreams,'' she says. ``Now my dreams are so
bad I don't even want to remember them. Usually I don't, and I'm
thankful for that, because they're always, always awful. Because
I've seen what some of these murders look like, my dreams are
always anatomically correct ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The nightmares started shortly after Cornwell began working in
the Richmond morgue in 1981. ``I was separated from my husband and
living alone,'' she says. ``And there was a series of women being
killed _ a neurosurgeon, a bookkeeper, a lawyer _ women who were
not in high-risk crime areas. These were terrifying, but then I saw
other things that had happened to women who ended up in the morgue.
The one thing they had in common was that they all thought it
couldn't happen to them. That's when I went out and bought my first
revolver.''
</P>
<P>
   The cases that she saw were the basis for ``Postmortem,'' her
chilling first novel about the rapes and murders of Richmond women.
The book introduced Scarpetta as a no-nonsense medical examiner who
uncovers the maniac's identity.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewers were enthusiastic about the first few Scarpetta
novels, but more recently they have been less kind. Entertainment
Weekly's Mark Harris, who gave ``Point of Origin'' a lukewarm
review, bemoaned the ``overworked and predictable'' plot.
Scarpetta, he wrote, ``who was initially compelling, well-rounded
and keenly intelligent, seems depressed and adrift, all charred
corpses and no play.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornwell dismisses the bad reviews as more examples of jealousy.
``When you've had really big success, critics are just looking for
a chance to blast you out of the water. I think my characters are
colorful, and I think my fans agree. They wouldn't keep buying my
books if they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   She just as quickly discounts criticism of the gory details she
includes. In ``Point of Origin,'' for example, Scarpetta boils the
remains of a young woman in a 40-quart pot to complete an autopsy.
In other books, Cornwell meticulously describes what serial killers
did to their victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that Scarpetta sees are not pretty,'' Cornwell
says. ``If you're going to tell people about death and violence,
don't make it pretty. It's real and you've got to face it. The
reason I feel my books are helpful is that they come from the
perspective of a very humane woman who fights the good fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cornwell is giving Scarpetta a rest while she
finishes ``Southern Cross,'' her sequel to ``Hornet's Nest,'' a
tale of crimefighters, reporters and rednecks in Charlotte that was
published last year to savage reviews. Cornwell says the reviewers
didn't understand what she was trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't realize that an author can have two
different voices. I have a very, very dark, brooding, melancholy
side that is like Scarpetta's. But I was a cartoonist for my
college paper, and I also have a `Far Side' sense of humor. I knew
it would be hard for people to accept that the same person wrote
both of these books.''
</P>
<P>
   To research ``Southern Cross,'' which is set in Richmond,
Cornwell worked with the ATF on its bombing range, blowing up cars
and analyzing explosives. ``It's amazing how many pennies and
quarters you can find in old cars they get from junkyards. They're
always finding coins under the seats of these blown-up vehicles.
It's this type of minutiae that give reality to my fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornwell doesn't expect ``Southern Cross'' to win her many
friends in Richmond, but she says she is already persona non grata
in some circles because she's a descendant of Harriet Beecher
Stowe, author of the 1852 novel ``Uncle Tom's Cabin.'' In a way,
Cornwell sees herself as the same type of crusader as her famous
ancestor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harriet Beecher Stowe was fighting an abuse of power, and I'm
fighting an abuse of power, too,'' she says. ``But there's a
different war going on. It's a kind of slavery we have, with the
violence in America. When you think about the way we have to live
with alarm systems, or the fear we feel in a parking lot or at an
ATM machine, that's a kind of enslavement. For a country that
values freedom, it's unconscionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
