<SLUG> BC-BLACK-HAIRSHOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hair show to be more than just a big tease
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- It's always a heady experience. A time when weaves,
locs and straw set dos mingle gracefully among China bangs, French
twists and basic bobs.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, if there's a do that can be done, it will show up at
the Bronner Bros. Mid-Summer International Hair Show _ right down
to Janet Jackson's red-hot curls.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Saturday at the Georgia World Congress Center and
running through Tuesday, stylists from around the world, including
Africa and the Netherlands, will learn about hairstyling and
business techniques and new hair care products.
</P>
<P>
   But the highlight is sure to be Monday night's ``Hair Battle
Royale '98,'' where 12 stylists (including three from Atlanta:
Felisha Gatlin, TEE White, and Maurice Beaman) will compete for
$10,000 cash or a 1998 Jeep Cherokee. Their challenge: in 10
minutes create the most out-of-this-world statement in hair since _
well, the last time these hair-raisers came to town.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronner Bros. hair show, now in its 51st year, expects
75,000 to 100,000 attendees, making it one of Atlanta's top five
conventions, according to Brandy O'Quinn, spokeswoman for the
Atlanta Convention and Visitor's Bureau. The show could pump more
than $50 million into the city's economy, O'Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   For stylist Gatlin, 27, of Unique Styles in College Park, Ga.,
the show will be a nerve-racking experience. She's got her sights
set on taking home the prize money. Her plans are to buy a pair of
black Gucci boots and invest the rest. She plans to do futuristic
styles for the year 2010 during the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very nervous, but I work better when I'm nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
