</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTEOPOROSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drug that increases bone density may help osteoporosis sufferers
 &HT;    By Ellen Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   People who have osteoporosis because they take steroid
medications for other illnesses might benefit from a drug that
increases bone density.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 million American women and men take steroids for such
diseases as asthma and arthritis, but the medication can cause bone
thinning.
</P>
<P>
   A study in today's New England Journal of Medicine says the drug
alendronate, marketed as Fosamax by Merck &AMP; Co., may help prevent
and treat steroid-induced osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   Women and men taking medications with steroids increased their
bone density when they took alendronate in combination with calcium
and vitamin D, said lead researcher Kenneth Saag, assistant
professor of internal medicine at the University of Iowa. Calcium
and vitamin D are currently recommended for preventing and treating
steroid-induced osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   Men and women have already used alendronate to prevent fractures
and post-menopausal women have already been treated with
alendronate for osteoporosis, but alendronate may be the only
FDA-approved drug that can help those with steroid-induced
osteoporosis, Saag said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important message is that this is a common, but
under-recognized problem, and we now have a proven, effective
therapy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which involved nearly 500 women and men who were
given an oral dose of alendronate or an inactive placebo, should
especially help post-menopausal women who are also taking steroid
treatments. Because of the combination of estrogen deficiency and
the effect steroid medications have on their bones, these women are
among those at the highest risk for steroid-induced osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
