<HEADER>
A8936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS30-CO     07-29 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE STANDS BY TO CONSIDER IMPEACHMENT PROCEEDINGS
 &HT;    By MARK SHERMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wary about upcoming elections, the man who would
lead impeachment proceedings against President Clinton said
Wednesday his staff is ready and waiting for whatever independent
counsel Kenneth Starr may send their way.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, said he had no idea when a report from Starr might
arrive or whether he would convene his committee for immediate
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get a tight document, with points A, B, C, that's one
thing,'' Hyde said. ``But if it's War and Peace. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Hyde said, ``We're ready for any eventuality.''
With Clinton agreeing Wednesday to testify Aug. 17, it is unlikely
any report from Starr would reach the House before it returns from
its summer vacation after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, only about a month will remain in Congress's work
schedule before lawmakers head home to campaign for the November
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The deals reached by Starr with Clinton's attorneys and lawyers
for Monica Lewinsky for the former White House intern's testimony
about her alleged sexual relationship with the president have
started a new round of speculation on Capitol Hill about the
prospects for an eventual move against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats said that Congress is having too much trouble
passing the spending bills that provide money for government
operations beginning Oct. 1 to consider Starr's report before
adjourning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This already crowds out discussion of important issues,'' said
Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., also a member of Hyde's panel, who said
he thinks it's already too late for Judiciary Committee hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., said the House should not hold a
post-election session on the report, but rather wait for the new
Congress to begin in January. ``It seems to me a lame-duck Congress
shouldn't deal with this issue,'' Fazio said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde and other Republicans were not willing to forgo
hearings either just before or after the election. Conceding that
the timing of a report by Starr, if indeed he sends one, is
``awkward'' because of the election, Hyde said, ``I'm loathe to let
political considerations interfere with the orderly process of our
responsibilities. On the other hand, there are problems of timing,
like the need for members to campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that he would have his critics whatever he
decides. ``That's the problem. Whatever you do, you're accused of
political motives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two former prosecutors on Hyde's committee, Republicans Bob Barr
of Georgia and James Rogan of California, said the House should be
ready to act whenever Starr sends a report of his findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to make time for it,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Rogan: ``A prosecutor files his case when he's damned good
and ready.''
</P>
<P>
   To get ready for the possibility of impeachment hearings, Hyde
recently added eight people, led by a veteran Chicago lawyer, to
his staff.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman, who repeatedly cautioned that discussion of a
report from Starr is speculative, said he would be working with
Speaker Newt Gingrich to determine if and when to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   But Gingrich had no comment on the report of Clinton's agreement
to testify, and his aides referred all questions about a report
from Starr to Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
