<HEADLINE>
CONCEDING THE GRIM PAST, GERMANY INVITES JEWS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Half a century after the world learned the
full horror of Hitler's campaign to extinguish Jews, few countries
have worked harder than Germany to atone for past evil.
</P>
<P>
   Nazi concentration camps like Dachau and Bergen-Belsen have been
preserved as museums and draw tens of thousands of visitors every
year. Every major city has its memorials and museum exhibits, from
``The Topography of Terror'' at the Berlin Museum to the Frankfurt
Jewish Museum's immense model of the city's old Jewish ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of historic synagogues have been meticulously
reconstructed from rubble, though most are devoid of actual
worshipers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there is something jarring about the new brochure
from the German National Tourist Board: ``Germany for the Jewish
Traveler,'' a 40-page pamphlet written in full recognition that
many Jews still recoil at the mere mention of this country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The brochure's stated purpose is to attract foreign Jews,
particularly Americans, to explore their historical and cultural
roots in Germany. The authors took pains to review the horrors of
the Third Reich. The first paragraph of the introduction notes that
the ``vastness, ruthlessness and near success of the Nazis' stated
goal of annihilating the Jews of Europe was, and remains,
unparalleled in human history.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It then describes a full catalogue of sites that speak to both
the accomplishments of German Jews and the genocide waged against
them. It also points out that Germany is one of the few European
countries where the Jewish population is now increasing. That is
because the country has accepted thousands of immigrants from
Central Europe and Russia under a policy that offers citizenship to
people with documented German ancestry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the vast majority of German tourist sites of
Jewish interest resonate with tragedy and death. For all the
efforts to unearth and reconstruct the Jewish heritage in Germany _
and there are many such efforts _ there aren't many Jews left in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 400,000 who lived here before Hitler took power in 1933,
all but a few either escaped or were killed or deported. Jews now
account for about 75,000 of the 80 million people who live in
Germany. That may be part of the reason that American Jews avoid
the country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no Jewish tourism to Germany,'' said Ignatz Bubis,
president of the Central Council of Jewish Communities in Germany,
who wrote a message of welcome in the new pamphlet. ``It doesn't
exist.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five decades Germany's federal and local
governments have spent countless millions to resurrect or at least
honor the Jewish culture that evolved here for many centuries. The
re-establishment of Berlin next year as Germany's capital has added
fresh energy to the old efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the massive reconstruction of what used to be East
Berlin involves Jewish historical sites, such as the immense
Oranienburger Strasse synagogue, beautifully restored and reopened
in 1995 as the Centrum Judaicum museum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is also trying to build a massive new
Holocaust memorial near the old Berlin Wall, though that effort
remains tangled in political disputes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But most other big cities in Germany have sites commemorating
Jewish history. Frankfurt's Jewish Museum, housed in a palace that
once belonged to the Rothschild family, contains artifacts that
date back to the 12th century. The highlight is a huge model of
Frankfurt's old Jewish ghetto, complete with streets and 194
buildings built at one-fiftieth scale.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a new museum has been opened on the site of the old
Jewish ghetto, which burned down in 1711. There archeologists have
unearthed the foundations of five houses and two ritual bathhouses.
Among other things, the museum exhibitions depict everyday life of
Jews in Frankfurt during the past 300 years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there are an amazing number of museums and museum
exhibits devoted to Jewish history. Berlin alone boasts the Centrum
Judaicum and the Martin-Gropius-Bau, part of the Berlin Museum, and
a separate Berlin Jewish Museum is under construction. Museums in
Cologne, Dusseldorf, Braunschweig and other cities maintain
exhibitions on Judaica as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Worms, which was a center of Jewish scholarship in the Middle
Ages, the city has carefully preserved the houses and cobblestone
street of the medieval Jewish alley. Trier, which in ancient times
was a central administrative city in the Roman empire, has also
preserved its Jewish alley, as well as the home of one of Germany's
most prominent Jews, Karl Marx. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bubis said he welcomes the effort to attract Jewish tourists.
Beyond the established attractions, he said, Germany offers rich
opportunities for people to explore their roots in the towns of
their ancestors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But will Germany's new overture persuade many Jewish travelers?
``I rather doubt it,'' Bubis said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
