<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD ALLOW SUITS AGAINST HMOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the Senate expected to delay consideration of
a managed-care bill until September, a bipartisan group of senators
proposed Wednesday a compromise measure that would allow patients
to sue health plans for monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John Chafee, a Rhode Island Republican, offered the
alternative to the leading Democratic and Republican versions of
legislation that would impose national rights and benefits for
people using managed-care health plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unacceptable for a debate on managed-care reform to be
stymied by the gridlock of politics as usual. What is needed now is
the politics of the possible,'' Chafee said.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was unclear whether Senate majority leader Trent Lott
would allow a vote on his compromise measure, and it was becoming
increasingly clear Wednesday that the Senate would not have time to
take up any managed-care bill before its month-long summer recess
that begins Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The House narrowly passed a health-care bill on Friday that
would cap awards from lawsuits against physicians and insurance
companies at $250,000 for non-economic and punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   With Senate action likely postponed until September,
election-year pressures may make the compromise more attractive to
some lawmakers, its sponsors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally, we want to solve a problem,'' said Senator Max
Baucus, Democrat of Montana. ``We are not here to score political
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Arlen Specter, Republican of Pennsylvania, said, ``If
there is to be legislation, it has to come from the center.''
</P>
<P>
   The so-called centrist bill, backed by Chafee, Baucus, Specter,
and Senators Bob Graham of Florida and Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut, both Democrats, is closer to the Democratic proposal
than the Republican measure.
</P>
<P>
   The centrist and Democrat bills would cover all 161 million
privately insured individuals. The Republican bill would apply to
the 48 million enrollees in self-funded plans. The centrist and
Democrat bills would also allow access to specialists and guarantee
continuity of care with the same doctor, access to prescription
drugs, and direct access to obstetrician-gynecologists and
pediatricians.
</P>
<P>
   The centrist bill proposes a significant alternative on the
issue of lawsuits. The Democratic bill would allow patients to sue
in state courts and seek damages for non-economic damages, that is,
awards for pain and suffering from an injury, as well as economic
damages that typically cover job loss and actual medical costs. The
Chafee bill would limit lawsuits to federal court and would not
allow non-monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill would allow consumers to purchase medical
savings accounts, an IRA-type account to pay for medical costs, and
allow 100 percent deductability of health care costs for the
self-employed.
</P>
<P>
   The centrist bill would also give the Departments of Health and
Human Services and Labor the right to levy harsh penalties on
managed-care plans that fail to abide by the law.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy called the Chafee bill ``a welcome new
sign'' and a ``major improvement'' over the Senate Republican plan.
``But it lacks many of the most important protections'' in the
Democrat bill, said Kennedy, one of the co-sponsors. Kennedy said
the Democrat bill includes minimal hospital stays for breast cancer
patients who undergo mastectomies and need reconstructive surgery,
protection for whistle-blowers in the health-care community, and
the ability to file medical malpractice lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Later Kennedy held his own news conference to criticize the GOP
health bill as inadequate for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican bill should have a warning label: Dangerous to
Your Health,'' said Senator Barbara Mikulski, a Maryland Democrat
who backs the Democratic bill.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate moderates said their bill was the only
legislation that could pass Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see happening in the next few weeks is a train wreck,''
said Graham. Lieberman said, ``If our colleagues want to do
something this year, here it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
