<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT RYKODISC TO BE SOLD TO ISLANDLIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rykodisc, a feisty independent record label that rose to fame
through catalog sales of Frank Zappa, Elvis Costello, and David
Bowie albums, is expected to be sold within a week to Islandlife, a
New York company owned by music mogul Chris Blackwell.
</P>
<P>
   Islandlife is Blackwell's re-entry into the music business,
after leaving Island Records, where he reigned for 20 years and
signed such mega-stars as U2 and Bob Marley.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Rykodisc is expected to top $30 million. ``It's
the right thing at the right time,'' said Rykodisc co-owner Don
Rose. ``With all the merging going on, we needed a broader reach,
and this way we will have more muscle behind us. Chris is also a
real music lover and we feel it's a great fit.''
</P>
<P>
   The 15-year-old Rykodisc issues 100 records a year. It employs
70 people in Salem, Mass. and 130 worldwide, with offices in
Philadelphia and London. It's a privately held company known for
its spiffy catalog reissues, but which also has put out new music
by Kristin Hersh, Morphine, Bob Mould, Jeffrey Gaines, and Medeski,
Martin &AMP; Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Ryko, as it's commonly known, also owns a number of smaller
labels that are attached to the Islandlife deal. They include
Hannibal (with Cubanismo!, Kate &AMP; Anna McGarrigle, and the catalogs
of Sandy Denny, Fairport Convention, and Nick Drake); Slo River
(with the Future Bible Heroes, Charlie Chesterman, and Josh Rouse);
Tradition (an historic label with the catalogs of Odetta, Woody
Guthrie, Ledbelly, and Louis Armstrong); newly launched imprints
Candescence (a new age label) and Rykolatina.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell was unavailable for comment and a spokesman said he
preferred to delay talking until the deal was officially closed.
His Islandlife company also just started a record label called Palm
Pictures, which recently issued its first two albums: Baaba Maal's
``Nomad Soul'' and Ernest Ranglin's ``In Search of the Lost
Riddim.'' Both are world-music releases and will be marketed by
Rykodisc under the new agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The imminent sale of Rykodisc is not expected to result in major
operational changes, Rose says. ``We'll still be who we are and do
it from where we do it. I'm not expecting anything dramatic to
happen in the transition. For me, I'll go from ownership control to
something else, but I think it will be a good something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Rykodisc grossed more than $70 million last year
through its labels and publishing, Rose conceded that the record
business has become a tougher business in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record business has been flat. It's gotten to be more
expensive to get the same result,'' he says. ``This new merger is
going to allow me to focus on making records again rather than on
capital structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose and the Philadelphia-based Arthur Mann are the current
co-owners of Rykodisc. They were introduced to Blackwell by
producer Joe Boyd, who came on the Rykodisc board when the label
acquired Hannibal Records in 1991. Boyd had produced albums by
Fairport Convention, Sandy Denny, and Nick Drake when all of those
artists were on Blackwell's Island Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aesthetically, we share a lot with Chris,'' says Rose. ``In
fact, when we get together, we always listen to music. Chris is a
totally uncynical individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Rykodisc has shunned outside ownership before, but the Blackwell
offer was just too attractive to pass up, Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell also owns considerable hotel and resort properties in
the Caribbean and on Miami's South Beach, where he has spearheaded
the art deco revival. One of his South Beach hotels, the Marlin, is
where Boston band Aerosmith did pre-production for its last album,
``Nine Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell has also started a video company, a music publishing
company, and is seeking to get into films. Rykodisc is expected to
market any soundtracks that evolve from the film business, Rose
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
