<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUR RACERS PROTEST DRUG-TESTING POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIX LES BAINS, France _ The most famous bicycle race became the
most infamous one Wednesday when the 133 riders in the Tour de
France tore off their numbers and merely rolled slowly along the
149-kilometer course, refusing to race. In addition, three teams
got off their bikes and piled into their team cars in protest of
the drug controversy that has surrounded the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   After the bike ride _ it could hardly be called a race _ Tour
director Jean-Marie LeBlanc announced that the stage will be
negated and that racing will resume Thursday, minus the riders who
dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   But a sour taste remained, both among the fans who jeered the
slow-moving riders and the riders themselves, who are still
spurning the press.
</P>
<P>
   The ride on the Tour's final day in the Alps was not filled with
chases and attacks, but rather with stops and starts. Just a
half-hour after leaving Albertville, the pack stopped as the riders
tore the numbers off their jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't race in this climate of permanent suspicion where we
are taken for criminals,'' Laurent Jalabert said on France Info
radio. Jalabert apparently led the protest, and he and his
German-based ONCE team stopped riding entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the ride, 1996 Tour winner Bjarne Riis slowed to talk
with LeBlanc, and other riders talked to journalists on
motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   Former champion Stephen Roche, speaking on the Eurosport
network, said, ``Some riders were in tears. They were saying, `I'm
only doing my job. Please leave me alone.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although one team was ousted from the Tour last week after the
team masseur was allegedly caught with drugs in his car, no rider
has been accused of, or tested postive for, drug use. But the
riders have become increasingly annoyed over the drug controversy
that has overshadowed the race, and this was the second time they
threatened to end the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the riders put down their bikes and staged a sitdown
strike that delayed the start of a race for two hours. Then came
Wednesday's action, when at times it looked doubtful that the race
would make it to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a World Series being played with both teams getting so
angry at the officiating and the ensuing media coverage that by the
fifth game, all the players walk off the field.
</P>
<P>
   That's what in effect is happening in the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   The three-week, 2,400-mile race around France, which attracts
the most elite cyclists in the world every summer, has been
unraveling to the point of all but negating this year's results.
Even if the race does reach its scheduled conclusion in Paris
Sunday, it's been so decimated that even the finishers will have
glaring asterisks next to their names.
</P>
<P>
   The drug story began even before the Tour did, when Festina team
trainer Willy Voet was arrested by customs officials and charged
with carrying drugs in his car July 8. The Tour began under a cloud
three days later, and at the end of the first week, the Festina
team was banned. The riders are accused of using the hormone EPO, a
drug that can be used to increase red blood cells and enhance
endurance. Five of the team's nine riders have confessed to taking
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Festina rider Christophe Moreau had been charged with steroid
use three weeks before the Tour, but since it was under appeal, he
was allowed to start the race. He finished fifth in a time trial,
but it was a moot point after his team was thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, four members of the Dutch TVM team were taken
by police to a hospital, where they were required to give blood and
hair samples. The riders returned to their hotel at midnight and
Wednesday morning started the stage with the other riders. In
addition, the police Tuesday seized suspect medication in a van
driven by officials of the French Bigmat team.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the arrests and allegations has led to evidence of
drug use on the Tour, prompting riders to question the emphasis on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Tour, riders voiced anger that the press, often
camped out at team hotels, ignored the racing action and focused
instead on the drug controversy. ``The riders are disgusted. Nobody
is interested in the sport side of the race,'' Jalabert said at
last week's sitdown strike.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, the riders directed their anger not at the media
but at the police.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, when word spread through the pack of the treatment
of the four TVM riders who were tested the night before, the riders
decided to go into low gear. The riders on ONCE, led by Jalabert,
were the first to get off their bikes and get into the team cars;
three hours later, the Spanish-based Banesto team did the same. The
three remaining riders on the Italian Risso-Scotti team quit, too.
</P>
<P>
   When the ride finally ended 2 1/2 hours after its scheduled
arrival here, the four TVM riders rode to the front and raised
their hands in victory as the pack behind them applauded.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little doubt that the drug controversy and ensuing
protests have put a damper on the racing action. The richest and
most prestigious bike race, held since 1903, has come to be seen
not just by the French but by the world as an extravaganza and
intense show of power.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thinks Wednesday's action means the end of the Tour,
Johnny Weltz, general manager of the US Postal Service team, ``At
the moment, I realy don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand it's a difficult situation, but we are here to
race and we want to go to Paris. The only thing to do is to go
on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't commented because honestly, it doesn't affect me,''
said American Bobby Julich before Wednesday's race when asked about
the drug scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But it does now. After all, if Julich, now in second place, does
reach the podium in Paris, both he and the fans will most likely
remember the Tour for its drug controversy rather than his stellar
ride.
</P>
</TEXT>
