<HEADER>
A8961 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-PATIENT-RIGHTS     07-29 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-PATIENT-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPEARS DEADLOCKED ON PATIENTS' RIGHTS LEGISLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., S.D., R.I., Fla., Pa.)  (th) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republican and Democratic leaders deadlocked
on patients' rights legislation Wednesday, all but guaranteeing the
Senate will not debate the contentious, but politically popular
issue until September, if then.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks now, Senate Republican and Democratic leaders, whose
proposals differ greatly in scope and detail, have been unable to
agree on how many amendments could be offered when a Republican
bill is taken up.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want to allow three amendments on each side, arguing
that there is not enough time for limitless debate. Democrats want
to offer as many as 20, saying the issue warrants a full-fledged
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Without an agreement, Republicans will not bring the bill up for
debate. The House narrowly approved a Republican patients' rights
bill on Friday, leaving it up to the Senate to act.
</P>
<P>
   Each party's Senate leader blamed the other for delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't take up the health care reform legislation dealing
with HMOs it will be because the Democrats would not agree to take
it up,'' said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. ``It's
their fault. I want the record to be clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., disagreed. ``What are they afraid
of?'' he asked. ``Why not have a good debate. What's stopping them
from giving us the full opportunity to debate this issue as we are
each of the appropriations' bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by the stalemate, Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., and four
other senators unveiled their own compromise patients' protections
bill Wednesday. Chafee said the partisan logjam over the two main
bills is jeopardizing the prospects for legislation this year,
despite its grass-roots appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe, as I said before, that each side will press
forward with their legislation and that neither side will have the
votes to enact legislation,'' said Chafee, who co-sponsored the
compromise bill with Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla. ``Here's a bill that
contains what we believe is the best of both plans, and if we want
to get something done this year, here it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats adamantly disagree on the issue of a
patient's right to sue, among other things in the two bills. While
the Democrat's bill would permit patients to sue a managed care
company in state court for the denial of benefits, something most
consumers cannot do, Republicans prefer to allow an outside review
panel to handle the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The Chafee-Graham plan tries to breach the gap, although it
skews more towards the Democrats' approach. It would allow
consumers to sue their managed care companies for lost wages and
other economic damages, and not for emotional or punitive damages,
as the Democrats' bill would permit.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who supports Chafee's bill, said that
the Republican leadership's bill ``provides no incentive at all''
for managed care company's to respond to patient concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not sure we go far enough,'' he said, referring to
the lawsuit measure in the compromise bill. ``We have a system of
400 years of experience where liability is based on fault.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
