<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REGS-ECONSCENE-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: REGULATORS BEWARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With anti-tax Republicans in charge of Congress and a New
Democrat eager to distance himself from his party's welfare-state
excesses in the White House, big government is on the wane.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes and no. While much of the New Deal heritage _ the
safety net, progressive taxation, market regulation _ has been
rolled back, Washington has more and more to say about health,
safety and environmental issues. And the cost of that regulation,
as my grandmother never said, isn't chopped liver. At the last
reckoning by the Office of Management and Budget, private outlays
to comply with social regulation topped $200 billion, and they are
rising rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   This is not necessarily bad, as people who have breathed the air
in Denver lately or taken a swim in Lake Erie can attest. But ask
an economist who follows regulatory issues, and you will hear that
federal regulation is a hodgepodge of the smart and the perverse,
the elegantly precise and the miserably flat-footed, the
extraordinarily cost-effective and the grotesquely wasteful.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the new Joint Center for Regulatory Studies fits
in. The center, sponsored by the American Enterprise Institute and
the Brookings Institution, will act as a nonpartisan watchdog,
assessing big-ticket initiatives and producing an annual report on
the effect of regulation. ``The real purpose is to keep the
regulators _ and the legislators who regulate the regulators _ on
their toes,'' said Robert Hahn, the center's director.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has been struggling with questions of how much social
regulation is enough since the early 1970s, when the government's
role in health, safety and the environment began to mushroom.
Presidents Nixon and Ford made modest attempts to coordinate
executive agency rule-making and to review proposed rules.
President Carter established two permanent oversight groups within
the executive branch to formalize the process.
</P>
<P>
   But as the effect of social regulation grew in the years of
Presidents Reagan and Bush, oversight took on a more partisan cast.
And though the adversarial atmospherics have largely cleared since
the election of President Clinton, regulatory review remains a game
that only insiders play. ``The only comments regulators generally
get are self-interested comments,'' said Robert Litan, co-director
of the joint center.
</P>
<P>
   A decidedly mixed bag has resulted. At one end of the spectrum,
the rules phasing out lead additives from gasoline are widely
viewed as a model of efficiency, flexibility and solid science. At
the other, inconceivably expensive Superfund rules require the
government to make every toxic waste site as clean as it was before
human beings populated the planet. Meanwhile, bipartisan efforts to
anchor rule-making in good economics and good science _ for
example, a measure sponsored last year by Sens. Carl Levin,
D-Mich., and Fred Thompson, R-Tenn. _ have gotten nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   The tension between those who fear the quiet accretion of social
regulation and those who see regulatory change as a plot to roll
back a quarter-century of progress won't be easily resolved. But
the American Enterprise Institute and the Brookings Institution are
trying to narrow these differences by opening the regulatory
process to the light of day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Congressional Budget Office routinely analyzes budgets,
and think tanks routinely second-guess them,'' Litan said. ``But
we'll be the first to look systematically at federal regulation,
which now costs consumers more than total discretionary government
spending costs the taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   The joint center, which just opened solely on the strength of
foundation grants, says it will release in-depth analyses of a few
proposed big-ticket rules each year. It will also publish an annual
assessment of the costs and benefits of all federal regulation,
backstopping the once-over-lightly assessments by the Office of
Management and Budget, which have been required by law since 1997.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As important, the center will assess the effect of existing
regulation. At the moment, neither Congress nor the White House has
the stomach to evaluate hugely expensive rules that may have
outlived their usefulness but are still defended by entrenched
interests. Hahn cites the example of the corporate average fuel
economy standards for cars, which add billions of dollars to the
nation's transportation bill with questionable effect on energy use
or the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Attitudes toward regulation expose the gulf between the way
economists and just about everyone else thinks. To economists,
rules are undesirable unless the benefits _ tangible and intangible
_ exceed the costs. Otherwise, there must be some other way to
organize the world that leaves everyone better off. But to many,
the cost-benefit analysis that forms the bedrock of regulatory
analysis is just a fancy way to rationalize self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   The joint center project probably won't change many minds. But
in Hahn's view, it is a promising place to start. ``We're not going
to have a real debate over regulatory reform until people have a
source of information they can really trust,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
