<HEADER>
A8971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPAIN-BASQUES-675&AMP;ADD     07-29 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-BASQUES-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH OFFICIALS SENTENCED FOR 1983 KIDNAPPING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ A divided Supreme Court panel on Wednesday
sentenced two high-ranking officials in the 1980s government of
Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez to 10 years in prison after finding
them and 10 lower-ranking officials guilty of kidnapping in a
shadowy struggle against Basque separatist terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   By 7 to 4, the court found the former Interior Minister Jose
Barrionuevo and his director of state security, Rafael Vera, guilty
of having a French furniture dealer, whom they mistook for a Basque
terrorist, kidnapped from his home across the border in France in
December 1983.
</P>
<P>
   With Julian Sancristobal, the former civil governor of Vizcaya
province, and some of the other defendants, Barrionuevo and Vera
were also found guilty of misappropriating government money to pay
thugs to carry out the crime. Sancristobal also received a 10-year
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict in the seven-week trial was so keenly awaited that
various versions of it began leaking to Spanish newspapers last
week, and the conservative prime minister who defeated Gonzalez in
national elections two years ago, Jose Maria Aznar, said under
public pressure that he would not try to use the verdict to score
political points.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict rekindled a long-smoldering national debate about
whether Gonzalez, one of the fathers of Spanish democracy after the
long dictatorship of Francisco Franco, has been telling the truth
over the many years in which he has denied having any knowledge of
illegal actions against Basque terrorists. He denied it again last
month under oath during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict, Gonzalez, now talked about as a possible
candidate for the presidency of the European Union's Executive
Commission two years from now, hurried back to Spain from a
vacation in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The target was Felipe Gonzalez and the Socialist Party,''
Vera, the security official, told a Spanish radio station, and he
said he would appeal to the Constitutional Court or the European
Court of Justice in Strasbourg, France, to clear his name. He and
Barrionuevo have denied approving the kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   But the seven judges in the majority, in an opinion read by
Judge Joaquin Delgado Garcia, said Wednesday, ``It does not seem
credible to us that high officials in Vizcaya could act without the
knowledge and approval of the highest officials in the Interior
Ministry charged here.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Socialist Party said Gonzalez's camp was
heartened by the dissenting opinions, including one signed by the
panel's chief judge, Jose Jimenez Villarejo, that found the
prosecution case against the two top government officials not
proved.
</P>
<P>
   None of the defendants were present when the sentences were read
in court Wednesday afternoon, and lawyers said it was unlikely Vera
or Barrionuevo would face jail before September.
</P>
<P>
   The armed separatist struggle by the underground Basque group
ETA, whose initials in the Basque language stand for the words
``Basque Homeland and Liberty,'' continues, three decades after it
began. Spanish authorities say it has taken about 800 lives.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez and his supporters charge that prosecutors now looking
into government actions in the 1980s are playing into the hands of
Aznar's conservatives. But at least 27 people are believed to have
died as a result of activities of the Anti-Terrorist Liberation
Groups, whose first publicly acknowledged action was kidnapping
Segundo Marey, the victim in the trial that ended Wednesday. And
prosecutors are investigating at least half a dozen other cases
that could lead to trials.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, the majority verdict on Wednesday said, Basque
terrorism was ``a political and social problem of the highest order
in the Basque country and all of Spain, singularly aggravated
because the French authorities were not collaborating with the
Spanish authorities, so that the south of France had become a
refuge for ETA members who carried out various crimes on our
territory and could later cross with impunity into France.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Marey, 51 at the time, told the court that he was sitting at
home in Hendaye, France, watching Benny Hill on television at 8
p.m. on Dec. 4, 1983, when two burly kidnappers burst in and
dragged him out into the wintry night in his socks into a car. The
kidnappers were looking for Mikel Lujua, a suspected ETA terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   Alerted to the mistake after the victim was bundled into Spain,
Vera contacted Spanish police and civilian officials in Bilbao by
telephone, the judges in the majority found. The police chief, one
of his top aides and Sancristobal then called in the top Socialist
official for the province for advice, according to the court.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the verdict said, Sancristobal got approval from
Barrionuevo, the interior minister, to keep Marey prisoner to use
him as a bargaining chip to get the French authorities to release
four Spanish policemen who had been arrested after botching an
attempt to capture yet another Basque terrorist two months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   After the Spanish Red Cross received a note on Dec. 6
threatening Marey's death within 48 hours unless the demand was
met, the four Spanish policemen were released. Marey was held
blindfolded and lightly clad in a cold mountain hut, and by the
time he was freed on Dec. 14 he had lost more than 15 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   In his pocket was a note the court said had been approved by
Sancristobal. ``You will have more news from GAL,'' it said,
referring to the initials for the Anti-Terrorist Liberation Groups
in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   A dissenting opinion by Villarejo and Judge Gregoria Garcia
Ancos said, ``It is a secret to no one, in effect, that the case
was profusely used by some political parties to attack the
government of which Barrionuevo was a part, and has continued to be
used in the political confrontation after the elections that
brought a new government to power.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority on Wednesday did not find, however, that the
prosecutors had proved GAL was a terrorist armed group under
Spanish law ``in this concrete case,'' a key element in the
prosecution's attempt to show that the government of the day was
conducting a ``dirty war'' against the ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of membership in an armed group as well as the
other crimes, Sancristobal, Vera and Barrionuevo could have
received jail sentences of up to 23 years, as the prosecution had
requested.
</P>
<P>
   All 12 of the defendants convicted Wednesday were ordered to
share payment of a $200,000 indemnity to Marey, who still lives in
France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1850EDT &QL; 
