<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIA'S POST-ELECTION CAMPAIGN IS IN FULL SWING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By SETH MYDANS c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ One of the three main candidates climbed
a tree and shouted through a bullhorn. One threatened to amend the
constitution so that he could stay in office. One fell suddenly
silent and dropped from sight.
</P>
<P>
   The post-election campaign for power in Cambodia was in full
swing Wednesday, three days after the nationwide parliamentary
vote. A preliminary official announcement of results is not due
until the weekend, but the maneuvering and bargaining had already
begun.
</P>
<P>
   The man with the bullhorn, Sam Rainsy, who was expected to get
the fewest votes, held a news conference here to denounce the
election as rife with fraud, though few independent observers
supported that view. He demanded a new vote in several selected
areas as a sort of test of whether the nationwide count had been
rigged.
</P>
<P>
   The man who currently holds power, Hun Sen, said he would simply
stay on if his opponents did not like the election result. If
necessary, he said, he would amend the constitution to do so.
</P>
<P>
   As the man who was expected to win the most votes, according to
early projections, he was in a position Wednesday to say: ``I wish
to call on all political parties to honor the determination of our
people. Winning or losing is normal as far as democracy is
concerned. No one wins all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The third candidate, Prince Norodom Ranariddh, who had earlier
joined Sam Rainsy in threatening to boycott the new Parliament and
block the formation of a government, was nowhere to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Most political analysts expected him to agree to let his
royalist party, known as Funcinpec, become the junior partner in a
new government, after a suitable period of protest and bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   With none of the parties expected to win the two-thirds majority
of Parliament's 122 seats needed to form a government, two of the
parties would need to join to form a coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hearing the opening salvos,'' a European diplomat said.
``The two sides are each telling the other they are needed and
can't be ignored. I suspect Hun Sen and his party will let it ride
out and then start working on individual Funcinpec members. The
coffers will be open.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he and other analysts said, the Prince and his party
would not be able to resist their chance at sharing in the spoils
of power, which in Cambodia's corrupt system include wealth as well
as political position.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Rainsy, he said, would probably continue doing what he is
doing now, and what he has done for years: act as Cambodia's chief
gadfly and political spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   The list of dozens of complaints about election irregularities
that Sam Rainsy presented today to the National Election Commission
was longer than that of any of the foreign and domestic observer
groups that have flooded Cambodia in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   But in a country that is still recovering from decades of mass
killings and civil war, his complaints, compiled from various
polling stations, seemed only to emphasize the peacefulness of
Sunday's election:
</P>
<P>
   _``Overcrowded and disorderly. Staff cannot control normal
procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Ballot box has no number on it.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Doorkeeper is delaying by asking unnecessary questions,
inspecting voters. Voters are complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Ballot papers are being torn off from the bottom instead of
the top.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Chief of polling station went into the polling booth with a
voter, carrying a pen in his hand, and she came out and put a
ballot in the box. He said that she was deaf.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Ballot box loosely closed, lid is so loose you can stick your
fingers in the sides.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Saw two cases of people who were allowed to dip their middle
finger instead of their index finger, although they had one (into
the bottle of indelible ink). One was a policeman who felt it would
be dirty when he picked up food to eat. The second was the wife of
Siem Reap's governor, Toan Chay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
