<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELA-GUARDA-THEATER-N     07-29 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELA-GUARDA-THEATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER AS JUICE, DREAM AND CATTLE PROD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ROAR OF THE CROWD: This article is the first in an occasional
series describing cultural events through their audiences'
experiences.) 
(bl) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's not likely that the theater of the future will
exactly mirror the antics of the crazed Argentine ectomorphs
whizzing around like window washers on amphetamines in the former
bank building between Toys ``R'' Us and Starbucks across from Union
Square.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe there's a signal or two to be found in the soggy,
hyperactive scene that's evolving this summer around the show
``Villa Villa'' by the ensemble called De la Guarda.
</P>
<P>
   The show has no seats, no plot, no dialogue and a predominantly
young, casual clientele. It plays out like an acrobatic New Year's
Eve in a surreal, strobe-lit, rain forest mosh pit where the
performers race around the walls on ropes and pulleys and the
audience gets to dance, soak, bat around balloons, scramble for
baubles and in some cases fly along with the cast.
</P>
<P>
   But along the way it is becoming one of the most talked about
and puzzled over off-Broadway productions of the year, one that has
raised in a particularly fevered way one of the theater's enduring
obsessions: how to get a generation raised on MTV interested in
seeing live theater.
</P>
<P>
   The show's audience has been getting older as publicity and good
reviews have filtered out. But the core constituency that regularly
fills up the 499 spaces at what used to be Union Square Savings
Bank, and is now the Daryl Roth Theater, remains people in their
20s and early 30s, many of whom have heard about the show through
word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a dream, only more intense,'' said Feliz Skamser a
27-year-old art student who walked out into the night with a damp,
disheveled, wild-eyed look entirely appropriate for a production a
reviewer from The Guardian in London described as ``theater as good
as sex.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Guarda, of course, hardly invented nontraditional,
participatory theater, taken in different directions by the Living
Theater, La Fura dels Baus or Cirque de Soleil. And its production
is only one of a handful of shows like ``Rent,'' ``Stomp,'' ``Blue
Man Group,'' or ``Bring In da Noise, Bring In da Funk'' aimed
squarely at the Gen X and younger audience.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Villa Villa'' (it's pronounced VEE-shuh and roughly
translates as ``by the seat of your pants'') may be the most
extreme example of the appeal of a show that goes way beyond the
borders of conventional theater.
</P>
<P>
   John Arendt, who builds props and sets, and Sarah Murphy, a
graduate student in art education at New York University, both 23,
had seen the show once already and brought along their friend
Joseph Cahill, a 21-year-old who had just graduated from Alfred
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come out of this totally alive, totally awake, thrown off
balance,'' said Arendt. ``There are enough things that are like
sitting in front of a television and letting your brain vegetate.
This is a lot more refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeal to the ``Friends'' and younger crowd is no accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it for the first time in Montreal, and I was so crazy I
couldn't sleep; it was everything I ever wanted to do,'' said David
Binder, a 30-year-old producer who brought De la Guarda to New York
along with Daryl Roth, who had produced ``Three Tall Women,'' and
Jeffrey Seller and Kevin McCollum, two of the producers of
``Rent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who've gone over the top, who love this show the
most passionately, are people who don't go to the theater very
often, who believe the theater has nothing for them,'' Binder said.
</P>
<P>
   Pichon Baldinu and Diqui James, the show's creators, said De la
Guarda was largely a reaction to the pessimistic theater and
audience apathy in Buenos Aires after the return to democratic
government in 1984. After coming up with productions meant to evoke
the apocalyptic chaos and fear that came in the wake of the
dictatorship, they came up with ``Villa Villa'' as a nonpolitical
way to jump-start audiences' emotions like an injection of
adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   But Baldinu said the show's cattle-prod intensity was also a
reaction to what he called the stale conventions of conventional
theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 600 years, the theater has been based on the audience
believing things that no one really believes,'' he said. ``Now
young people don't buy into that anymore, so they find theater
boring. In Argentina no one goes to the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're trying to break through all that and make a statement
that's so strong you have to pay attention. If you want a storm, we
make water and wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, flogging the dying beast of the theater has a long
history, and for now, with record Broadway box offices and
innovative productions like ``Rent,'' ``Cabaret'' or even ``The
Lion King,'' the beast seems pretty vital.
</P>
<P>
   And whether ``Villa Villa'' is theater or spectacle is open to
debate. California Burrito up the street bills itself as ``extreme
food,'' and its huge posters of ``Villa Villa''-ish mountain
climbers and surfers raise the issue of whether De la Guarda is
just ``extreme theater,'' more off-Broadway's answer to mountain
skateboarding than the theater's next big thing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, though a flood of ``Villa Villas'' are unlikely to
replace ``Cats'' on Broadway or on the road, even theater series
outside New York are increasingly including at least one
nontraditional production, according to the League of American
Theaters and Producers.
</P>
<P>
   And just as Stephen Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan''
escalates the intensity level to almost unbearable levels in its
depiction of World War II, or ``Cabaret'' puts its audience in the
Kit Kat Klub, ``Villa Villa'' in a very different way hooks into a
broad-based desire for emotional juice and immediacy that clearly
goes beyond the young.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely edgier than Mary Martin in `Peter Pan,''' said
Bob Fox, of Oradell, N.J., who came with his wife, Anita, and gave
their ages as ``over 70 and under 80.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We go to a lot of plays, but Broadway is mostly revivals that
we saw the first time around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Their only bow to age was the pair of white plastic earplugs
both brought along. ``We brought them when we saw the Rolling
Stones at Giants Stadium, too,'' Fox said. ``We were the oldest
ones, there, too. But then the Rolling Stones are almost as old as
we are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
