s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ST.-FRANCIS-OPERA-$AD     07-29 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ST.-FRANCIS-OPERA-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESSIAEN'S `FRANCOIS' HAS STAYING POWER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Permanence, these days, comes electronic. Even in the world of
what was once ``classical'' music, the most a composer can expect
for a big work is a run of performances leading to a recording,
after which the score might as well be dropped in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   But there are exceptions. In the 15 years since its premiere,
Olivier Messiaen's opera ``St. Francois d'Assise'' has, like a
classic of older times, gone on growing through repeated
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Its demands _ an orchestra of 120 (including 3 players on ondes
martenot, the 1930s electronic instrument that Messiaen's music has
preserved) and a choir of 150 _ mean that it will never be a
regular repertory item, but it has had two full-scale productions
and a good number of complete or partial performances in the
concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   For an emergent classic like this, recordings have the value not
only of making the music available but also of documenting its
performance history. The original production at the Paris Opera in
1983, conducted by Seiji Ozawa, was recorded on CD, as was a
concert version that was given in the Netherlands soon after, with
Kent Nagano in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Now Orfeo presents the concert performance of four of the
opera's eight scenes that took place at the 1985 Salzburg Festival
(C 485 982 1; two CDs).
</P>
<P>
   This was a major event. It introduced the work to Salzburg,
where it was to have its second production, in 1992, a production
to be revived there this month.
</P>
<P>
   It also proved the viability of a concert made of selected
scenes, and led to a run of other such performances, often with the
same four scenes on the program. Such was the case three years
later in London, where Messiaen attended a performance on his 80th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   This mini-``St. Francois,'' just over two hours long, starts
with the scene in which Francis cures the Leper with an embrace and
is himself cured of the disgust that had kept him from full
sympathy with the suffering. Then comes a jump to the three final
scenes. Francis preaches to the birds, prays for and receives the
stigmata (the five wounds of Christ on the Cross), and dies in the
company of his brother monks, the Angel and all of heaven.
</P>
<P>
   But quite apart from the function this 1985 Salzburg performance
had in promoting the opera, it was evidently a great musical
occasion. You can hear it growing in intensity. The Vienna Radio
Symphony Orchestra, conducted by Lothar Zagrosek, seems at first to
be speaking a slightly foreign language: it has problems with
rhythm, accentuation and ensemble. But these rapidly fall away, and
the music starts to sound as it should, full of exuberance, color
and glory.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the Angel and the Leper, whose roles are relatively
small, two kinds of creatures are depicted in the score: monks and
birds. Both sing as they are accustomed to sing in life: the monks
in chant and the birds in shrieks, calls and liquid songs. For the
most part, Messiaen alternates between the two.
</P>
<P>
   Francis and his brothers sing their lines with warm harmonic
accompaniment from string or wind groups, then the whole
magnificent assembly of the orchestra is set free for the birds.
Fittingly for a portrait of a man who loved Creation, the opera
places Francis's drama _ which is, as Messiaen put it, ``the
progress of grace'' in his soul _ in a context of nature music,
brilliant, loud and agile.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the time the birds are there to represent heaven on
earth: the perfection that human beings will have to wait to
achieve and that Francis is shown achieving. But Messiaen's birds
can also be sinister (the hooting owl at the start of the stigmata
scene), hieratic (the Pacific bird that each time announces the
arrival of the Angel) or weird (the New Caledonian bird songs on
ondes martenot in the bird sermon scene). Whatever the expressive
mode, the performances by the Vienna players, as soloists or in
small groups, soon become lustrous and exact.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderful, too, are the contributions of the Austrian Radio
Chorus and the Arnold Schoenberg Choir. Messiaen uses his huge
chorus to sing as the voice of the unseen God, addressing Francis
in the scene where he receives the stigmata, or of the heavenly
host surrounding God in the final scene, where Francis dies and is
_ out of direct view on the stage _ reborn.
</P>
<P>
   But choral voices also appear without words to add to the
atmosphere of violence and unease in the scene where Francis
summons the spiritual strength to embrace the Leper. All through
this performance the choral singing is strong and vividly present.
</P>
<P>
   In the central role, Messiaen said he wanted the vigor of
Golaud, in Debussy's ``Pelleas et Melisande,'' combined with the
``declamatory solemnity'' of Mussorgsky's Boris Godunov. Here he
has those qualities in abundance, for he has Dietrich
Fischer-Dieskau.
</P>
<P>
   It is moving to hear Fischer-Dieskau, who retired four years
ago, take on, at an advanced point in his career, a big new part
outside his normal repertory. He rarely sounds strained; for the
most part he is robust and majestic, providing the sureness with
which Francis is to be seen taking his spiritual steps forward and
upward.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the bird sermon scene he mounts with strength
and total authority to the high note on ``Croix'' (``Cross''), a
gesture he repeats at the end of the scene, where the same sound is
contained in ``surcroit'' (``excess'').
</P>
<P>
   But with all the power and grandeur, and the vehemence almost on
the edge of anger, he can also be gentle when Francis has the
opportunity to reflect rather than declaim, and so to become, for a
moment, a human being as well as a saint.
</P>
<P>
   There is an example in the scene with the Leper, where, in
response to the latter's reproaches about his treatment by the
young Franciscan community, Francis comments, ``Poor brothers, they
do all they can,'' and Fischer-Dieskau inflects the line with a
wise sadness.
</P>
<P>
   He has some excellent supporters. Kenneth Riegel repeats his
blistered, expostulating but thoroughly musical performance of the
Leper from the first performance; Rachel Yakar is magically serene
as the Angel, and Sebastian Vittucci makes a special, beautiful
moment of Brother Bernard's prayer to Francis not to die.
</P>
<P>
   As the opera has it, he both dies and does not die. It is good
to have this performance in its own resurrection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
