<HEADLINE>
`MOSTLY MOZART': WELCOME RESPITE WITH HIGHS AND LOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A city that regularly suffers the dog days of July
and August needs its palliatives. There is ice cream for the
palate, air-conditioning to placate the body and for the ear,
Mostly Mozart.
</P>
<P>
   The monthlong festival returned to Lincoln Center for the 32nd
year on Tuesday night. Once again its programs are friendly, and
once again its concert halls will serve as refuges from the
streets. Mostly Mozart concerts are gratefully received by those
overloaded and overstimulated by the summer days of New York. In
the well-cooled climate of Avery Fisher Hall, with steamy urban
chaos held momentarily at bay, listeners on Tuesday could sit back
and let their spirits snooze for an hour or two.
</P>
<P>
   This opening event offered Richard Strauss and Mozart, with
Gerard Schwarz conducting the Mostly Mozart Festival Orchestra,
Andre Watts playing the piano and Angelika Kirchschlager of Austria
offering us her first-rate mezzo-soprano voice.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the festival's expected amenities this season come
some splashes of inventiveness, especially the start of a two-year
survey of Haydn's string quartets, to be played in hourlong
early-evening events. Haydn invented the quartet medium and was its
most successful practitioner (Mozart, Beethoven, Schubert and
Bartok notwithstanding). The chance to hear these wondrous pieces
in concentrated and consecutive form is a considerable gift of the
festival to its public.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere this summer, the Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment
and the Concerto Koln will speak for the early-music movement.
Gidon Kremer and his Kremerata Baltica will arrive to stir
otherwise calm waters, performing pieces by Arvo Part, Nino Rota,
Astor Piazzolla and 20th-century Russians. Vivaldi's ``Four
Seasons'' will be Kremer's antidote for the faint of heart.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's concert was a long and laborious throat-clearing that
started badly and ended well. The excerpts from Strauss'
``Bourgeois Gentilhomme'' were ragged affairs, vaguely together and
clearly underrehearsed. The Strauss segment was rescued by Ms.
Kirchschlager, an articulate and committed singer in songs like
``Das Rosenband,'' ``Morgen'' and ``Muttertandelei.''
</P>
<P>
   The young mezzo was also strong in two examples of the operatic
Mozart: ``E giunge a questo segno'' from ``La Finta Giardiniera''
and ``Parto, ma tu ben mio'' from ``La Clemenza di Tito.'' Here was
the composer at the very beginning of his opera career and at the
very end. Tuesday's audience, if it was not terribly concerned
about such historical matters, clearly loved the singer's work.
</P>
<P>
   Watts was soloist in Mozart's E flat Concerto (K. 271), a big
work in every way and an anomaly in the composer's early and
otherwise genteel repertory. It was a comfortable glide of a
performance and disturbing for that reason. Careless passage work
hid behind a lovely blur of sound. Trills aimed for speed rather
than clarity. The finale became an out-of-breath footrace in which
the pianist was not always in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Possessed of so much inherent musicality, Watts chose to coast,
ignoring the weight of a mighty piece and relying on a creamy
legato to get by. It was distressing to observe that which once
promised so much musically operating in such a state of regression.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz and his players did have a parting gift for their
listeners: a performance of Mozart's ``Jupiter'' Symphony that
truly worked. The tempos of the first movement made space for
articulation. The yearning melodic lines of the Minuetto were
beautifully paced and very touching. The finale was a delight.
</P>
</TEXT>
