<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9013 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUCLEAR-WASTE-HNS &LR;      07-29 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-WASTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OKS CREATION OF NUCLEAR WASTE SITE IN WEST TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Maine, Vt.) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House gave its overwhelming approval Wednesday
to legislation authorizing the creation of a low-level nuclear
waste disposal site in west Texas.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 305-117, members endorsed the claim by the states
of Maine, Texas and Vermont that the site would pose no health or
environmental risks to the community of Sierra Blanca, where
construction on the dump site could begin this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate must vote on the final bill as well before sending it
on to President Clinton for his signature. But the tally there is
expected to mirror the House's show of support for the three-state
compact.
</P>
<P>
   The facility would be the final dumping ground for radioactive
materials from electricity generating plants, hospitals and medical
clinics in Maine, Texas and Vermont. But the site, to be built with
$25 million from each state, will also be allowed to accept
radioactive materials from other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill argued that the site would never be
opened to other states looking to dispose of nuclear garbage. But,
at the request of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the House and Senate
versions were stripped of an amendment that would have prevented
the site from being used by other states.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the three states in the compact free to turn the
dump into a money-making venture by allowing wastes from other
states to be buried there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the people of west Texas deserve better treatment
by this House than they have received,'' said Texas Rep. Silvestre
Reyes, D-El Paso, an opponent of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-San Antonio, another opponent, warned his
colleagues that approval of the site could damage U.S.-Mexican
relations. The Mexican government has complained that placing the
dump site at Sierra Blanca, just 15 miles from the Rio Grande,
could constitute a violation of treaties and border agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition from Mexico is understandable, Bonilla said. ``We
wouldn't want them dumping nuclear wastes within a few miles of the
border.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the controversial bill pitted Texan against
Texan, with six members of the state's congressional delegation
voting against it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill drew strong support from the Houston- and Dallas-area
members, many of whom represent the interests of the state's huge
medical industry. The state has more than 3,500 hospitals, clinics
and medical research facilities, and most of the radioactive waste
generated by them would be buried in deep trenches at Sierra
Blanca.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas medical industry joined with utility companies in all
three states to lobby for the bill and against any amendments that
might derail it.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Eddie Bernice Johnson, D-Dallas, said she understood the
opposition from the mostly Hispanic Sierra Blanca residents, who
are concerned that the site, scheduled to open in 1999, could pose
a serious health and environmental risk to the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we must put the waste somewhere,'' she said, contending
that it could not be left to pile up in heavily populated areas
like Dallas and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much safer to put it in a less-populated area ... If I
thought for a moment that it would endanger the lives of people, I
would not be standing here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the measure said that if Johnson and other
supporters weren't concerned about health risks, they should vote
to build disposal sites where most of the Texas radioactive waste
is generated _ in Houston and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are simply trying to do the right thing for the people of
Sierra Blanca,'' Bonilla said. ``The threat to the environment is
real.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to take up the bill soon. But Sen. Paul
Wellstone, D-Minn., has vowed to use ``every parliamentary tool
available'' to kill it.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone opposes the compact bill because amendments
prohibiting it from becoming a national dumping ground for
radioactive wastes were stripped out of the final version and
because it does not include ``civil rights'' legal protections for
local residents who might be harmed in some way by the location of
the site in Hudspeth County.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
