<HEADLINE>
BBC TO PROVIDE NEWS PROGRAMS TO PBS STATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eager to get its 24-hour world news service onto U.S.
television, the British Broadcasting Corp. announced a three-year
contract yesterday with WLIW/Channel 21, a PBS station based on
Long Island, to provide three half-hour BBC World news programs,
live from London, every day to WLIW and about 25 other public
television stations.
</P>
<P>
   BBC Worldwide chief executive Rupert Gavin said at a news
conference in New York that the BBC had chosen WLIW because of the
station's interest in international news and because WLIW could
immediately offer access to a 26-station partnership covering about
30 percent of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For six years, WLIW has carried an evening newscast from ITN,
another British network, but that contract ends Nov. 1, the day
WLIW will broadcast the BBC World programs. They are scheduled at 6
a.m., 7 p.m. and another time slot later in the evening to be
determined.
</P>
<P>
   WLIW leads a group of 26 stations that are each the
second-licensed PBS station in a market, and together work to
acquire programming to distinguish themselves from the primary
stations. Having acquired the American rights to BBC World, WLIW
will receive a fee from other stations who carry the broadcasts,
according to WLIW president and general manager Terrel Cass, who
said he expected most of his 25 partners to buy the BBC programs,
replacing ITN.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Neither WLIW nor BBC World would disclose financial terms of
their contract.
</P>
<P>
   Although its radio news service is world-renowned, the BBC was
slow to get into the 24-hour television news business, and is
trying to catch up. It began BBC World, a television news channel
distributed outside Britain, in 1991 in Asia and the Middle East,
and has since expanded to Africa, Europe, India and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   It is available now in 53 million homes in 187 countries and
territories _ compared with the potential audience of CNN at 200
million homes in 210 countries and territories, including about 73
million in the United States).
</P>
<P>
   ``The North American market was such an obvious miss for us,''
Gavin said Wednesday, explaining that getting distribution in the
United States as quickly as possible ``is critical to our
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that BBC World had discussed an alliance with
WNET/Channel 13, the primary PBS station in the New York area, but
that WNET did not have ``an early opportunity'' to fit the news
programs into its schedule.
</P>
<P>
   WNET president and general manager William Baker confirmed that,
but also said he believed that the BBC news programs, while ``a
high-quality service for viewers,'' would not ``yield a large
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Cass said he believed there was an audience, among
``discriminating viewers'' who wanted to see news reported from a
global rather than just an American perspective. He said WLIW had
had positive responses from viewers to the ITN news programs. ``The
popularity of the BBC World Service on radio is well known,'' he
said, noting that National Public Radio carries some of its
programs in this country. ``But this will be the first time its
television service is available in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, BBC news programs also appear on the BBC's own
fledgling cable channel, BBC America, co-owned with the Discovery
networks, but that channel is available in 300,000 homes and is not
likely to get wide distribution for several more years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1918EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
