<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-MAGS-AD-COLUMN     07-29 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-MAGS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: CANADA EASES CURBS ON U.S. MAGAZINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ In Canada's latest attempt to balance free trade
against cultural protection, the government said Wednesday that it
would lift prohibitions against the Canadian editions of U.S.
magazines but would prevent Canadian advertisers from buying ads in
those magazines.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. trade officials quickly rejected Canada's new approach.
``This new policy is the same old story,'' said U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barshefsky said Canada's new approach seemed to be just as
inconsistent with its international trade obligations as its
current practices, which the World Trade Organization has rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barshefsky will send a team of U.S. officials to Canada next
week to review the magazine issue and the new advertising ban in
detail. Her spokesman, Jay Ziegler, said that if the team found
that the new measures discriminated against U.S. publishers, the
United States would not wait until the enabling legislation was
passed in the Canadian Parliament to challenge it.
</P>
<P>
   While Canadian magazine publishers energetically embraced the
government's actions, some Canadian advertisers strongly objected,
saying the measures amounted to ``affirmative action or
protectionism'' for the magazine industry and might even violate
Canada's constitution because they would deprive advertisers of
access to an important market.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian officials said they believed the advertising ban would
meet any constitutional test and would also satisfy World Trade
Organization standards. They said that limiting Canadian
advertising to Canadian magazines was necessary to protect the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot allow foreign publishers with publications that are
already paid for to strip away and skim away advertising dollars
that rip away at our capacities to tell our own stories,'' said
Sheila Copps, minister of the Canadian Heritage Department.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian magazine publishers have said they cannot compete with
Canadian editions of big U.S. magazines. They argue that if allowed
to produce Canadian editions, U.S. publishers would simply include
some mention of Canada and then, with their editorial costs already
covered, undercut domestic publishers with discount advertising
rates.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. publishers deny that their rates would be substantially
lower than in comparable Canadian magazines. The only
general-interest U.S. magazine exempt from the prohibitions is
Time, part of the Time Inc. unit of Time Warner Inc. which has been
in Canada for 55 years. Donald Brown, president of Time in Canada,
said the price of advertising in the Canadian edition of Time was
about 9 percent more, on a cost-per-thousand circulation basis,
than in Maclean's, Canada's top news weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The circulation of Time's Canadian edition is 320,000. Maclean's
has a circulation of 512,000.
</P>
<P>
   The United States filed a formal complaint with the World Trade
Organization in 1996 challenging Canada's magazine protections.
While upholding Canada's right ``to take measures to protect its
cultural identity,'' the international trade group sided with the
United States last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Canada announced Wednesday that it would comply with the trade
group's decision by revoking several measures by Oct. 30. They
include an existing tariff that keeps the Canadian editions of U.S.
magazines _ sometimes called split runs _ from crossing the border.
Canada will also end an excise tax of 80 percent, imposed after
Sports Illustrated tried to avoid the split-run prohibition by
transmitting copy across the border via satellite and printing a
local edition in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The trade organization also rejected the way the government had
subsidized Canada Post _ the national post office _ in order to
lower the cost of subscriptions for Canadian magazines. Government
officials said Wednesday that the subsidy would now go directly to
the magazines and that all magazine publishers would pay the same
postal rates.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising ban, also scheduled to take effect Oct. 30,
requires an act of Parliament. Officials said U.S. publishers who
ignored the law could be fined the equivalent of $35,000 to
$165,000 in U.S. dollars for each violation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Copps, the heritage minister, said the new prohibition would
not restrict U.S. access to the Canadian magazine market, provided
U.S. publishers did not solicit Canadian advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is not about competing for readers,'' Ms. Copps
said. ``The issue is about selling advertising services.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
