<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SUSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITOL SUSPECT HAD MORE AMMUNITION IN TRUCK, FBI SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mont., Calif., Va.)   (bl)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Russell E. Weston Jr., charged with shooting two
Capitol policemen to death Friday, had additional ammunition for
his .38-caliber revolver in his truck as well as in his pocket,
according to affidavits unsealed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavits, filed by the FBI in U.S. District Court here
Saturday, supported warrants to allow searches of Weston's cabin in
Montana, his room at his parents' home in Illinois and his pick-up
truck, which was parked on Pennsylvania Avenue near the Capitol at
the time of the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress on Wednesday, Republican party leaders and the
chairmen of several Senate and House committees agreed that a new
visitors' center should be built at the Capitol to improve the
building's security. But no decision was made about what the center
should contain, where it should be situated or how much it should
cost.
</P>
<P>
   In the affidavits, federal agents said they believed that a
search of Weston's belongings in Montana and Illinois would turn up
letters and other material documenting Weston's fear of the federal
government. Weston, 41, has a long history of mental illness, his
parents have said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the affidavits, Weston's parents told the
authorities that a letter to him from an unspecified federal agency
had been forwarded this month from his cabin in Rimini, Mont., to
their home in Valmeyer, Ill. The letter was a response to a letter
he had written ``concerning his belief that there were land mines
on his property that were placed there by the federal government,''
an affidavit stated.
</P>
<P>
   His parents, this affidavit continued, said Weston did not
believe the government's assurances that no such mines had been
placed and that he was probably frightened by the letter.
</P>
<P>
   The matter of a visitors' center was discussed at a meeting in
the office of Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott. ``The House and
Senate want to move in tandem,'' said Sen. John Warner, R-Va.,
chairman of the Rules Committee, which has jurisdiction over the
matter in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Congress has considered building a center to funnel
tourists into a central point before they enter the Capitol, but
there has never been agreement on cost or scope. In 1991, Rep. Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., who was then the Republican whip and is now
speaker of the House, called a Democratic plan ``madness.''
</P>
<P>
   It called for a three-story underground center beneath the East
Front parking area. The most recent cost estimate was $121 million.
</P>
<P>
   Warner and Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., chairman of the House
committee with jurisdiction, said that new plans might or might not
resemble the ones drawn in 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
