<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-KNESSET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNESSET BACKS EARLY ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Reflecting its dissatisfaction with Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's handling of the peace process, the Israeli
parliament voted Wednesday for a bill calling for early elections.
</P>
<P>
   While largely symbolic at this point, the message was a reminder
to Netanyahu that his already thin political margin is diminishing.
The vote was significant as well for its timing, days before the
Knesset adjourns for a three-month recess, and just as Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators work to break the impasse in talks over
further Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is symbolism intended to cast a dark cloud over Netanyahu's
government,'' said Daniel Ben-Simone, who covers politics for
Israel's leading daily, Haaretz. ``They are sending him a
warning.''
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary approval of the bill will have no immediate
effect on Netanyahu's government. Two more votes by the full
parliament are required for it to become law. But as Netanyahu
marks the midpoint of his four-year term in office, he confronts
increasing Israeli fears that the gains of the Oslo peace accords
are slipping away, as well as concern that rising unemployment and
a drop in economic growth presage hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration is mounting as well in the Palestinian- controlled
areas, where Palestinian leaders warn that they will not be able to
control outbreaks of violence if the impasse continues. Washington
is growing impatient, too, and is retreating from its role as an
active mediator.
</P>
<P>
   The stumbling block has been the amount of land Israel will hand
over to the Palestinians. While the difference of a few percentage
points may sound minuscule, each percentage point represents more
than 20 square miles, the approximate size of Tel Aviv, Israel's
largest city.
</P>
<P>
   A US proposal calls for a further 13.1 percent turnover of West
Bank land to the Palestinians before the start of the final stage
of peace talks. The Palestinians accepted the US proposal, although
it is far short of the 30 percent withdrawal they had expected. The
Israelis have rejected it, arguing that they can accept no more
than a 10 percent withdrawal without sacrificing their security and
the protection of their water resources.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli negotiators have recently offered a ``10 plus 3'' plan
in which 3 percent of the land to be ceded would be a park under
Palestinian control which could not be developed by Israelis or
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the land issue is resolved, most analysts believe that
potentially irreconcilable differences between the two sides will
emerge in final talks on the status of Jerusalem and control of
water resources.
</P>
<P>
   With each setback, the original May 4, 1999 deadline of the
peace agreement looms larger. Palestinian President Yasser Arafat
has vowed to declare unilaterally a Palestinian state at that point
if no agreement has been reached. Such a declaration could lead to
another military conflict in the Middle East, many Israeli and
Palestinian experts believe.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli economy is beginning to fade along with hopes for
peace. Since Netanyahu took office, unemployment has risen over a
third from 6.5 in 1996 to 9.3 according to the most recent figures.
The rate of growth of the economy has declined some 300 percent
during the same period, from 4.5 percent two years ago to a
projected 1.0 to 1.5 for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and investors have hailed Netanyahu for his tight
fiscal policy and expansion of Israel's potent high tech sector.
And Netanyahu maintains that recovery is imminent. ``There is
simply a gap between the halting of the deficit and the beginning
of growth,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Economists also add that the rising unemployment can be
attributed to Israel's shift from a job-intensive industrial
economy to a high tech one which will employ fewer people.
</P>
<P>
   But if the economy continues its slide, it could pressure
legislators to push for new elections, currently scheduled in 2000.
And if this happens, Netanyahu and his rightist Likud Party would
be forced to face angry voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investment is in drastic decline, growth is at a low point,
construction is in collapse, companies are in crisis, thousands of
businesses are closing monthly,'' said David Levy, who quit as
Netanyahu's foreign minister in January after accusing him of
failing to move on the peace process or do enough for working-class
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Levy's departure from the fragile coalition government left
Netanyahu with a razor-thin majority of 61 votes in the 120-member
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having the peace process move forward would certainly help the
economy. There is no question about that,'' said a Hebrew
University political science professor, Yehezkel Dror. ``There is a
groundswell of dissatisfaction with the government. It increases
the odds that the government could fall. But it is unclear by how
much.''
</P>
<P>
   The hawks of Netanyahu's government, like Cabinet minister Ariel
Sharon, have threatened to bolt his coalition if he cedes too much
land to the Palestinians. The more moderate members have vowed to
leave if he fails to seal a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He remains trapped,'' said Gideon Doron, a political science
professor at Tel Aviv University. ``The walls are closing in on him
and eventually he will have no way out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Netanyahu continues to confound the experts and Israeli
journalists who relentlessly predict his demise. On Monday, he
defeated the 61st attempt by the Labor Party opposition for a
recall vote aimed at toppling his administration.
</P>
<P>
   And many Israelis still support him. Yaacov Vanunu, 60, is a
Moroccan immigrant to Israel who voted for Netanyahu and now
struggles to get by on the meager salary of a parking lot guard.
``People blame Bibi for everything,'' he said, ``for unemployment
for failing peace policies. He's not guilty. He wants what is good
for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But others are as weary of the lack of progress in the peace
talks as they are frightened by the potential repercussions of
their failure. Liat Shpaizman, 18, who is about to begin her army
service, said that her friends took her Wednesday to the shopping
districts where two large terrorist bombs exploded last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very disappointed with the state of the peace process. I
didn't feel safe here today. The country is losing hope,'' she
said. ``We still have some hope, but something has to be done
really soon in order to save the country.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Correspondent Bonnie Rochman contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
