<SLUG> BC-DISABILITIES-WORK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISABLED PEOPLE URGE SENATE TO LET THEM WORK AND RETAIN BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Witnesses in wheelchairs urged Congress Wednesday
to pass a bill that would let disabled people take jobs without
losing federal benefits.
</P>
<P>
   They backed a measure introduced by Sens. James Jeffords, R-Vt.,
and Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., earlier this year that would allow the
disabled to make more money than the law currently permits and
still receive Medicare or Medicaid funds.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, the disabled cannot earn more than $500 a
month for more than nine non-consecutive months without losing the
aid they receive from Social Security. Once they lose that money,
they can continue to receive Medicare or Medicaid for up three
years, but after that they must pay a premium of about $300 a month
to keep the health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 7.5 million persons on federal disability programs, fewer
than 37,500 are employed.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Becker Kennedy of Los Angeles, who was paralyzed in a
diving accident, told the Senate subcommittee on social security
and family policy that she cannot work as a lecturer. The reason,
she said, is that the average $2,000 payment she receives per
speech would eventually makes her ineligible for Medicare, which
provides her with home health care as well as her electric
wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without (the Jeffords-Kennedy) bill we are trapped in a cycle
of poverty and shame,'' said Nancy Kennedy, who is no relation to
the Massachusetts senator. ``We are beached on the sidelines. If we
can figure out how to contribute productively without being paid,
we still feel handicapped. Cap in hand, trapped in poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   She said if she would earn a decent living if she could afford
the health care coverage that she would lose.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bob Dole, the unsuccessful Republican nominee for
president in 1996, also testified. Dole, whose right arm was
severely damaged in World War II, said the government is sending
the wrong message to the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``To access basic care, prescription drugs or personal
assistance services through Medicare or Medicaid, we say to
individuals with disabilities, `Stay home, don't work,''' Dole
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords, a subcommittee member, told his colleagues that
``without coverage, a person with a disability will be unable to
even leave the house.'' He added, ``Millions are trapped in a
system that forces underemployment of unemployment upon people who
want to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Irish of Burlington, Vt., who is also wheelchair-bound,
said he cannot afford to work full-time because his salary would
make him ineligible for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to choose not to work although I can work, want to work,
but can't afford to work,'' he testified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
