<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-VOTE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARLIAMENT EXPRESSES DISPLEASURE WITH NETANYAHU 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a parting shot before a long summer recess, the
Israeli Parliament issued a sharp and potentially weighty new
protest Wednesday over Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's handling
of Middle East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, which was boycotted by most of the members of
Netanyahu's governing coalition, set in motion a process that could
force the prime minister to face an early election.
</P>
<P>
   While that prospect remains distant, at least for now, the
passage of the measure, by a 60-6 margin, struck a clear blow to
Netanyahu's prestige, and it underlined the depth of
dissatisfaction at the lack of progress toward a further accord
between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to members of the Labor-led opposition, four members
of his governing coalition sided against Netanyahu, including Dan
Meridor, who quit as finance minister last year.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister, who had called the bill ``an empty ploy,''
remained dismissive Wednesday of the prospect that his government
might be brought down before its term ends in 2000. His government
still holds a 61-59 majority in the 120-member Parliament, and his
opponents have proved unable as recently as the beginning of this
week to garner the 61 votes necessary to topple the government in a
vote of no confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But Netanyahu and his aides had clearly sought to defeat the
measure, and they had called for the boycott only late Tuesday
night after it became clear that they could not muster enough votes
to win.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's vote marked only preliminary approval of the
measure, which would dissolve Parliament and force new elections.
In order to become law, it needs committee approval and three more
parliamentary votes _ procedures that could take weeks or months
and could not begin until Parliament returns from its summer
recess, which began Wednesday night and is expected to last for
three months.
</P>
<P>
   Final approval would require 61 votes, one vote more than the
measure received Wednesday. But even so, the former Labor Prime
Minister Shimon Peres said Wednesday's vote would lead to ``the end
of the present government.''
</P>
<P>
   Since last week, when a renewal of talks between Israel and the
Palestinians gave rise to a flurry of hope, there has been little
indication that the two sides are any closer to resolving the
differences that have kept them at odds in the 16 months since
their negotiations broke down.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, an Israeli team led by Danny Naveh, a top aide
to Netanyahu, has met several times with a Palestinian team led by
Saeb Erekat, but neither side has reported progress.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has pledged to convene a special session of Parliament
to review and vote upon any accord reached during the summer
recess. But the stalemate has already prompted Netanyahu's
opponents and some within his own party, like Meridor, to despair
ever more vocally at what they have regard as his overly rigid
approach.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For now, the main focus of those complaints remains Netanyahu's
refusal to accept an American package, endorsed by the
Palestinians, that would include an Israeli withdrawal from another
13 percent of the West Bank. Members of the centrist Third Way have
already threatened to leave the government if Netanyahu fails to
reach a deal with the Palestinians on the handover of land, and
that stance was underscored Wednesday by three Third Way members,
who joined with Meridor in breaking with the prime minister in the
protest vote.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu is also facing pressure from the opposite end of his
government spectrum, among more hawkish members who have threatened
to abandon him if he gives away too much land to the Palestinians.
That may make it difficult if not impossible for him to accede to
the moderates' complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Netanyahu has proved adept at overcoming crises during
his 25 months in office, and even Wednesday, he was quick to seize
on an opportunity to turn attention away from his own controversial
stands. He devoted most of a speech to Parliament to remarks made
by a prominent Labor Party legislator, a former major general, Ori
Orr, that were seen as offensive by Sephardic Jews, those of North
African and Middle Eastern descent.
</P>
<P>
   Orr quickly apologized for his remarks, including a suggestion
that Jews of Moroccan origin did not have the curiosity to know
what was going on around them. But the remarks became the subject
of intense coverage on Israeli television and radio, and Netanyahu
made the most of the political moment, charging in his speech that
Labor Party governments had long shown a pattern of discriminating
against Sephardic Jews.
</P>
</TEXT>
