<SLUG> BC-PROBE-POINTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TALKING POINTS' VITAL TO STARR'S CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Though the source of Monica S. Lewinsky's
now-famous ``talking points'' became the focus of a heated dispute
Wednesday, the document could still be a key piece of evidence in
independent counsel Kennth W. Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in a case noteworthy for its ``he said, she said''
element, the talking points document is one of the few pieces of
independent evidence that could show that a cover-up took place.
</P>
<P>
   The talking points have been considered a central focus of
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr's investigation into whether
President Clinton had a sexual relationship with Lewinsky and urged
her to lie about it. Lewinsky gave the document to her one-time
friend Linda R. Tripp, who was instructed to say, ``I have never
observed the president behave inappropriately with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, some news organizations have quoted sources who
indicate that the talking points were written by someone within the
White House. Officials at the White House officials have denied
this.
</P>
<P>
   The story took a twist Wednesday, when some news organizations
quoted anonymous sources saying that Lewinsky told investigators
that no one at the White House had written the talking points.
Various reports said Lewinsky had written the points herself or
that she had help from Tripp or someone outside the White House.
</P>
<P>
   If these reports are correct, it would hamper an attempt to show
the White house participated in a coverup. But whoever helped draft
the cocument, the talking points remain vital to Starr's case. They
could demonstrate Lewinsky's frame of mind around the time that she
swore in an affidavit early this year that she did not have sex
with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky on Tuesday received a grant a immunity from Starr in
exchange for testimony that she did have an affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she produced this entirely on her own, it would still be
evidence that would corroborate Lewinsky's testimony today that she
concluded it was in her best interest to concoct a story in order
to protect the president, and she thought it was really important
that Linda Tripp not say anything harmful to the president,'' said
Benito Romano, a former US attorney in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp Wednesday said she had nothing to do with the talking
ooints and ``anyone who testifies under oath that I authored or was
involved in preparation of the talking points would in my view be
committing perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, after completing her last day of testimony before the
grand jury investigating the case, later appeared to imply that
Lewinsky was urging her to commit perjury with the talking points.
``Imagine how you would feel if someone you thought was a friend
urged you to commit a felony,'' Tripp said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked who wrote the talking points, Tripp told reporters: ``I
wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's report that no one at the White House participated
in writing the talking points has not been confirmed on the record.
Moreover, it remains unclear whether someone outside the White
House who is connected to Clinton helped write the talking points.
</P>
<P>
   All of this left White House spokesman Michael McCurry with his
own set of talking points. As reporters Wednesday asked McCurry
about reports that no one in the White House was involved in
writing the points, he chastised news organizations for reporting
earlier that a White House official had helped write them.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry told reporters in his office Wednesday: ``You said
sources in Starr's office and close to Linda Tripp say they believe
the instructions came from the White House, which is a fairly
damning statement which means for weeks and weeks we've been living
with what is now apparently something untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a press briefing, McCurry repeated his qualms about
the early reports and said the press should stop quoting anonymous
sources who give conflicting accounts about the talking points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another useful reminder to all of you to be very careful
and cautious as you report because, you now, we've had some pretty
serious allegations raised on national television.'' He added about
Lewinsky: ``You know, you don't know factually anything about what
she's going to testify.''
</P>
<P>
   In the talking points, Tripp is instructed to recant her earlier
statements that she had seen another woman, Kathleen Willey, emerge
from the Oval Office after an alleged sexual encounter with
Clinton. Willey said earlier this year on CBS's ``60 Minutes'' that
Clinton made an unwanted advance.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp is instructed to say in the talking points: ``Kathleen and
I were friends. ... She came to me after she allegedly came out of
the Oval Office and looked...very happy. I did not see her go in
and out.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripp Wednesday said it would defy logic for her to help write
the talking points. Her comments about perjury appeared to be aimed
at Lewinsky. While Lewinsky has received a broad grant of immunity,
that does not exempt her from being prosecuted if she lies to the
grand jury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
