<SLUG> BC-LA-DNC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNC PANEL MEMBERS PRAISE L.A.'S PRESENTATION
</HEADLINE>
 
(Col., Pa., Mass., Minn., La., Fla. ATTN) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Moving in the ``a'' national news file and in the ``n'' California
news file.) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles won high praise from Democratic
National Committee members Wednesday for its bid to host the party
convention in 2000 as their three-day tour closed with another hard
sell.
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast at the Biltmore Hotel, where the 52 committee
members stayed for free, they were reminded of the city's
diversity, its union and labor peace and _ yet once again _
California's 54 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was the best presentation we've seen by any city,
including my own,'' said Ben Jeffers, of New Orleans and who is
chairman of the Lousiana Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Renee Walker of Detroit echoed Jeffers' sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles certainly showed they are capable and have the
facilities,'' Walker said. ``It was a very impressive three days.
And the fact California has 54 electoral votes isn't lost on
anyone. It's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   It was exactly the message Los Angeles officials and the LA2000
committee wanted to get across.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can stress it enough,'' said Bill Wardlaw,
one of LA2000's co-chairman who organized the three-day
extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is competing with Denver, Philadelphia, Boston,
Minneapolis, New Orleans and Miami for the right to host the
convention, expected to bring in some $137 million to the city,
with an estimated 30,000 voters.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate estimate on the cost of this week's
events, with most of the expenses _ air fare, hotel rooms and meals
_ covered by contributions from various firms.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trip, the delegates were wined, dined and feted
as if they were royalty: from the opening Olvera Street welcoming
ceremony to the reception hosted by actor Jimmy Smits at the Conga
Room on Tuesday night where he danced with nearly all the female
committee members.
</P>
<P>
   In a demonstration of the city's technical capabilities, the
committee members were shown a five-minute video _ complete with
musical scoring _ that recapped their stay, including pictures
taken at the Conga Room.
</P>
<P>
   George Kirkland, head of the Los Angeles Convention Center, also
reminded the committee members of the city's 93,000 hotel rooms _
and the fact that each of the major downtown hotels are unionized.
Democratic party events, by policy, can be held only in unionized
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Staples Center sports arena, he said the
Convention Center will provide some 1 million square feet of space
to accomodate the national media and all the state delegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other city that can offer the amount of space and
quality space that Los Angeles has,'' Kirkland said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
