<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANGSTER, AGENT DISAGREE ON MAFIA INDUCTION TIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Last summer, mobster Angelo ``Sonny'' Mercurio shuffled
into court in prison garb and admitted that he was the one who told
the FBI where a secret Mafia induction would be held so agents
could record the blood oaths.
</P>
<P>
   His dramatic unmasking of himself as an informant was the first
chapter in a year-long saga that has exposed the FBI's often
dubious dealings in its war against organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Mercurio was back in federal court in Boston, but in a
different courtroom, in a different case, the first sign that the
controversy uncorked last summer is spilling over to a second tier
of Mob prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   And he offered markedly different testimony than another key
witness, former FBI organized crime supervisor James A. Ring, as to
who in the FBI he told about the induction ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Mercurio was the lead witness called by defense attorney John H.
LaChance, who represents reputed Mafia capo regime Robert Carrozza.
Carrozza is challenging the legality of the first-ever recording
made possible by Mercurio's information: the October 1989 Mafia
induction ceremony in Medford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The recording underpins generations of Mob cases, including the
landmark 1995 case which has been dissected for months in another
federal courtroom before US District Judge Mark L. Wolf. Those
pretrial hearings, which are scheduled to resume next week, have
exposed the cozy, and potentially criminal, relationship between
FBI agents who ignored the criminal activity of Irish mobsters
James ``Whitey'' Bulger and Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi in
their quest to bring down their Italian rivals in the Mafia,
including reputed New England Mafia boss Francis P. ``Cadillac
Frank'' Salemme.
</P>
<P>
   The case before US District Judge Nathaniel M. Gorton stems from
the April 1997 indictment of 15 mob associates allegedly involved
in a bloody, five-year struggle to topple Salemme, beginning with a
botched assassination attempt in June 1989 outside a Saugus pancake
house.
</P>
<P>
   While the hearings before Wolf also involve the legality of the
induction ceremony tape, the testimony there has been wide-ranging,
dictated, in large part, by Flemmi's claim that he was promised
immunity from prosecution in exchange for information he provided
the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings that began Wednesday before Gorton are expected to
be much narrower, focusing solely on the legality of the induction
ceremony bugging.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing the parallel proceedings do share is the claim by
defense lawyers that the recording should not be used as evidence
because key information was withheld from the judge who authorized
the bugging. For one, the judge was not told that the FBI had a
top-level informant like Mercurio, who shuttled inductees to the
ceremony from drop-off points in Medford and Boston's North End.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the judge told that the FBI knew two days before the
ceremony where it would be held and when. Instead of seeking
permission to bug that location, prosecutors asked for a more
liberal ``roving bug'' which is only supposed to be sought when the
specific location to be bugged is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Mercurio, who has been offered a reduction in the nine-year
sentence he is serving in exchange for his testimony, said he and
several Mob associates drove by the house at 34 Guild Street in
Medford on Friday, Oct. 27, 1989, two days before the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day Mercurio said he phoned his FBI handler, John
Connolly, and gave him the time and location of the planned
ceremony. And later that night, Mercurio said he met with Connolly
and Ring in a room at the Sheraton Hotel in Boston to discuss the
upcoming ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   But Mercurio's version of events was contradicted by Ring, who
said Mercurio had phoned him, not Connolly, that afternoon. Ring
also testified that he had not met in person with Mercurio that
Friday. Ring, as he had testified earlier in the Wolf hearings,
said Connolly was not around in the week leading up to the
induction ceremony bugging.
</P>
<P>
   Mercurio also denied what has become part of local lore: that he
had turned down the television set in the room where the ceremony
was held so FBI agents listening in could hear better.
</P>
<P>
   Ring testified that Mercurio phoned him several hours after the
induction ceremony and bragged that he had turned down the
television. Ring said Connolly said the same thing the following
day.
</P>
<P>
   But Mercurio testified that he told Connolly he hadn't lowered
the volume on the television, to which Connolly reportedly
retorted, ``That's okay, we'll give you credit for it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercurio also denied knowing that Jeremiah O'Sullivan, former
head of the organized crime strike force, had asked the US Parole
Commission in 1988 to end his parole early because of the help he
had given the FBI. Had he known about the request, ``I wouldn't
have allowed it,'' Mercurio said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
