A9086 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-HEALTHCARE-H     07-29 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTHCARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTISAN BICKERING DELAYS MANAGED HEALTH CARE REFORM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite promises by congressional Republicans to
move quickly on managed care reform, the hot button issue is not
likely to be resolved before this fall, a victim of partisan
squabbling and vacation plans.
</P>
<P>
   Although the House narrowly passed a measure last week that
placed a number of restrictions on managed care plans, the Senate
has been slower to move on the matter. And with only a few days
remaining before they are scheduled to depart for August recess,
senators are predicting they will not act on the measure before
they return in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will not be a vote on it this week. That is clear,''
said Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., who joined with several colleagues,
Republicans and Democrats, on Wednesday in offering a compromise
health care proposal they hope will break the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Republican leadership has introduced legislation that
would give consumers access to both internal and external appeals
processes for decisions made by their HMOs. It would require some
managed care plans to provide easier access to gynecologists and
emergency room care.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said earlier this
week that Republicans wanted to move on the health care bill before
senators left for vacation. But Democrats have balked at placing
restrictions on the amendments that could be offered. Without such
limits it would be all but impossible to complete work on the bill
in the next two days.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also suspect that Democrats do not want to vote on
the issue before the summer break, and instead hope to make it a
campaign issue when they are back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't seem to want to take up the health care package,''
Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats say that the Republican plan does not go far
enough because it does not lift the prohibition on consumers suing
their HMOs if they belong to federally regulated health plans.
</P>
<P>
   They also note that many of the GOP mandates, including access
to gynecologists, would only apply to the minority of health plans
that states do not regulate.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich.,
have introduced legislation covering all health plans that permit
states to give consumers the right to sue their HMOs and gives them
access to a variety of specialists .
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan compromise measure, developed by Sen. John Chafee,
R-R.I., and Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., would cover more health plans
than the Senate GOP plan but would not give consumers as broad an
ability to recover damages against HMOs as the Democratic plan.
Consumers could go to federal court to recover economic damages _
but none for pain and suffering _ resulting from a decision by
their health providers.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee warned the Senate appeared to be headed for gridlock on
health care because neither Republicans nor Democrats had enough
votes to pass their respective plans.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Republicans are confident that they have been
inoculated politically on the managed care issue after pushing
through a bill last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   However, that bill, which was approved 216-210 with the support
of only three Democrats, was attacked as inadequate because it does
not give consumers the right to sue their HMOs. Critics of the
House bill also say its appeals procedure is weak because it is
nonbinding, meaning consumers would have to go to federal court to
force HMOs to abide by any arbiter's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the House bill should be dead,'' said Connie Barron,
an official with the Texas Medical Association, which has joined
with its parent, the American Medical Association, in trying to
derail the Republican-sponsored managed care legislation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barron said the doctors will use the August break to lobby Texas
lawmakers to oppose the House bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas doctors are afraid that the legislation will undermine
state reforms approved by the Texas Legislature in 1997, including
the right to sue HMOs and an appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   The Aetna Insurance Company is challenging in federal court in
Houston some of those changes approved by the Texas Legislature,
including the right to sue HMOs. The insurance company has argued
that the federal law bars states from interfering in employer
sponsored managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, acknowledged that the Texas
reforms, including the right to sue, appear to be working. So far
there have been no lawsuits involving HMOs, contrary to predictions
that the law would spur expensive and protracted legal action.
</P>
<P>
   But Hutchison said she was not prepared to back federal
legislation giving states the ability to open the courts to
lawsuits against HMOs. She said such lawsuits would ``increase
costs so much that it would deter coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
