<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The following is a proposed two-day package on the
controversy surrounding the side agreements to the North American
Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA):
</P>
<P>
   DAY ONE (SUNDAY)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ENVIRONMENT _ COZUMEL, Mexico _ When huge cruise ships
belly up to a new concrete pier off this Caribbean island, it's a
bitter reminder to Dora Uribe of an opportunity lost. An
opportunity, she says, to use the North American Free Trade
Agreement to mount an eleventh-hour campaign to stop the pier and
save Paradise Reef _ a reef environmentalists had long argued would
be broken to pieces and eventually killed by the thrust of the
ships. In January 1996, Uribe and other Mexican environmentalists
were the first citizens to file a complaint with a special
commission established by NAFTA's environmental side agreement. The
Cozumel experience is one of the unhappy lessons learned by
environmentalists who have tried to use the NAFTA environmental
side agreement to ensure that laws in each country are followed,
not flouted or downgraded, as free trade spreads in Mexico, the
United States and Canada. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
</P>
<P>
   With NAFTA-GLANCE _ A short description of the entities involved
in the NAFTA side agreements. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   DAY TWO (MONDAY)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-NAFTA _ TIJUANA, Mexico _ Norberto Cordoba says he was
fired from Han Young, a Korean-owned auto parts factory, for a
simple reason: ``They told me I was a 'political man.''' The
49-year-old welder didn't take his dismissal lightly. Cordoba,
Mexican and American labor activists have taken this grievance and
a range of others alleging unfair treatment at the Han Young
export, or ``maquiladora'' factory, in Tijuana all the way to
Washington D.C. (Ferris, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by noon Tuesday, July 28 in both the (i)
International and (f) Financial categories for Sunday, August 2.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-HUSSEIN _ AMMAN, Jordan _ The soveriegn of this small
country for 45 years, King Hussein is the emblem of his nation and
its guarantor of stability and security. Even among those who feel
he has been dictatorial and let his country languish in an economic
recession, Jordainians breathed a sigh of relief to see him
apparently in control of his recently found lymphoma cancer. ``This
is not the time for the king to be sick, you know,'' said car parts
retalier George Naber, after watching the King on television
Tuesday nigh. ``The situation in this country is very bad. He is
the only one who can control everything.'' The King's illness calls
into question the future of a small country that plays a huge role
in protecting the stability of the Middle East. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move Thursday, July 30 for Saturday, Aug. 1
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-US-$ADV02 _ MIAMI _ Conservative president-elect Andres
Pastrana takes office in Colombia on Friday, Aug. 7, bringing a
rare burst of optimism to this violent and dangerous South American
country. Already, Pastrana has initiated talks with leaders of two
rebel armies to end the hemisphere's longest-running civil war, in
which more than 35,000 people have been killed. And he's worked to
build better relations with the United States. Even the country's
right-wing death squads promised this week to stop attacking
civilians. But Pastrana, the charismatic former mayor of Bogota,
has his work cut out for him. Colombia is the cocaine capital of
the world and one of the most-violent places on earth. More people
are kidnapped for ransom, or because they work for foreign oil
companies, in Colombia than anywhere else. And previous government
have held peace talks with the rebels and achieved little. So, why
should Pastrana be any different? (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With COLOMBIA-US-BOX-$ADV02 _ MIAMI _ Facts about Colombia,
President Pastrana, and the Florida/Colombia connection that will
include the number of Colombians and Colombian-owned businesses in
Florida. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move Thursday, July 30 for Saturday, Aug. 1
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTIONS _ OAXACA, Mexico _ Mexico continues to test its
transition to peaceful and pluralistic elections this Sunday, Aug.
2. Jubilant from its first gubernatorial victory in Zacatecas state
in July, Mexico's left-center Party of the Democratic Revolution
(PRD) has another strong candidate running in Oaxaca state on Aug.
2. In many ways, Oaxaca's election is more meaningful for the PRD
than Zacatecas' (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CADET _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ The first woman ever
admitted to Russia's vaunted naval academy, founded by Peter the
Great, has just finished her first hellish year. (Holmes, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by noon Tuesday, July 28 for Saturday, Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TOWN-CRIER _ ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ In the upstairs ballroom of
Gadsby's Tavern, where George and Martha Washington waltzed in the
late 1700s, today's denizens were discussing the unique problem
facing this picturesque riverfront community where history is as
omnipresent as haze on the Potomac. ``You can't just run an ad in
the Washington Post saying 'Wanted: Town Crier,''' explained
Redella S. Pepper, a member of the city council. (Dart, Cox News
Service 1000).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moved Monday for release Sunday, Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: The following is a Dayton Daily News package for Sunday,
Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   MORELAND _ Regina Moreland wanted 10 children, just like her
mother. She bore only two. But wanted more. So over the years, she
and husband, Phillip, filled their house with other kids _ foster,
adopted, a mentally retarded grandchild. Regina also opened her
arms to a passel of great nieces and nephews who visited the
Moreland home at 633 Homewood Ave. But in less than nine months,
four children have died while at the Moreland home _ three
grandchildren, and a great-niece, ages 3 and younger. Montgomery
County Coroner James H. Davis has ruled the deaths homicides by
aphyxiation and suffocation. A child in the Moreland household has
emerged as the main suspect _ a revelation that has split family
loyalties between those who want cooperation with police and those
who reject authorities' suspicions. (Lyles, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   LEGAL _DAYTON, Ohio _The growing number of children accused of
serious crimes is confounding the juvenile justice system in Ohio
and elsewhere. A plan to overhaul Ohio laws governing young
offenders is being drafted and may be presented to the legislature
as early as September. But until new laws replace ones drafted in
the 1960s, Ohio's juvenile justice system is severely limited in
how it can handle young offenders, especially those under age 12
(Hundley, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL _ DAYTON, Ohio _ We talk to a former FBI profiler, who
says while the suspect in the Moreland case doesn't fir the
traditional serial killer profile, authorities are having to
re-think such profiles give the recent school schootings in
Arkansas (Grieco, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   CHRONO _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Updated chronology of the Moreland
deaths. (Hundley, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   UNDERGROUND _ DAYTON, Ohio _ With all the focus on underground
railroads, we'll tell people how they can get their homes on the
register being put together in Washington. (McKelvey, Dayton Daily
News)
</P>
<P>
   FLADEM _ Just when it should be gearing up to try to hang on to
the Governor's office in the November elections, Florida's
Democratic Party is in a shambles, victim of an eroding voter base
and a nasty racial controversy that has splintered its traditional
support among blacks. Last week the party's legislative leader
resigned and announced she won't run for reelection, leaving the
party rudderless. Tweaking the party in its misery has been State
Rep. Willie Logan, a black Miami Democrat who was to have been the
party's top legislative leader last year until he was deposed by
whites who said he wasn't raising enough money. (Williams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCHIZOPHRENIA _ WASHINGTON _ Scientists are coming up with a
deeper understanding and new treatments for schizophrenia.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: To move Thursday for release Saturday, Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   THREATS _ WASHINGTON _ As U.S. military forces moved to prepare
for a possible attack on Iraq last February, President Clinton
received a top-secret briefing at the White House. For much of the
month, he learned, military computer systems around the country had
been penetrated. While the computer commandos eventually proved to
be a couple of California teenagers, the incident helped push
Clinton to announce a new national effort against not only
cyber-attacks but also ``nuclear, but also chemical or biological,
to use disease as a weapon of war.'' (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   THREATS-Q&AMP;A _ WASHINGTON _ A Q&AMP;A with Richard Clarke, the
``national coordinator'' recently appointed by President Clinton to
prepare the country for the possibility of new kinds of terror
attacks. (Deans, Cox News Service 1500).
</P>
<P>
   THREATS-COMPUTER _ WASHINGTON _ It starts with an unexplained
power blackout in a major southeastern city. As utility workers
struggle to restore service, telephone systems across the country
become paralyzed. Quickly, the problems spread to oil refineries,
banking and financial systems, communications networks and even the
military. This scenario, outlined in a recent report by the Rand
Corp. for the Defense Department, provides a chilling picture of
how the Information Age has left the United States vulnerable to a
``digital Pearl Harbor.'' (Glass, Cox News Service 1000).
</P>
<P>
   THREATS-GERM _ WASHINGTON _ In the spreading chaos that could
develop if terrorists deliberately started an epidemic of smallpox,
ebola or another deadly disease in America, the country's first
line of defense would be the doctors, nurses, hospital personnel
and public health workers who would care for victims and try to
figure out what was going on. Yet the Clinton administration, which
plans to spend about $1.3 billion next year to defend the country
against chemical or biological warfare attacks, would invest only
about 3 percent of that amount _ $42 million _ to reinforce an
underfunded and poorly equipped network of state and local health
departments. (Nesmith, Cox News Service 1050&AMP;add).
</P>
<P>
   THREATS-GERM-POX _ WASHINGTON _ The doctor who headed the World
Health Organization's successful effort to eradicate smallpox warns
that the United States needs a $50 million effort to stockpile
vaccine in case of a terrorist attack using stolen medical stores
of the virus. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   THREATS-GERM-LIST _ Here are some of the diseases considered to
be prime threats for use in a terrorist attack. (Cox News Service
480).
</P>
<P>
   THREATS-GRAPHICS _ The following graphics are available with the
THREATS package. All elements will be placed in a Threats folder in
the National folder on the Cox server.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Thursday for release Sunday, Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-LOBBYING _ WASHINGTON _ Last fall, the high-tech industry
lost a legislative skirmish in its multi-year battle with the FBI
and U.S. spy agencies over who will control encryption of messages
on the Internet. Scared and enraged by a loss that threatened the
growth of their industry's profits, high-tech rivals stopped
dissing each other long enough to chip in more than $5 million to
form a lobbying coaltion called Americans for Computer Privacy and
convince a lot of their customers, suppliers and sympathizers to
sign up. Launched in March, the $5 million lobbying alliance of
more than 90 companies and 40 associations already has won some
early rounds in its fight against the FBI and U.S. spy agencies.
Who formed Americans for Computer Privacy, why, how they grew it,
how they run it, and what it does. (Mollison).
</P>
<P>
   With art and data for a graphic showing the founding, inner
circle and rank-and-file companies and associations in the
coalition, together with lobbying and political expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-ENCRYPTION WASHINGTON _ What the coalition wants and why
its foes don't want to give it to them.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Thursday for release Sunday, Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   LOGGING _ Slide Hollow is a place that time forgot, where
streams tumble pure and ancient trees stand tall. This enclave of
forest primeval in the Tennessee mountains is the poster child for
the fight for the last remaining unprotected areas of the South's
national forests. And nowhere in the National Forests is that more
important than in the Southern Appalachians, where more than 6
milion acres in six states comprise the largest block of public
land east of the Rockies. Slide Hollow is also a place where winds
of change are buffeting the Forest Service, slowly and reluctantly
evolving from a timber-cutting overlord to a group of men and women
more concerned about protecting these last vestiges of the nation's
natural heritage. Main story 40 to 50 inches. (Harmon, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/LOGRAGE _ James Sullivan has spent the last 15 years hounding
the Forest Service in the northeast Georgia mountains. Profile on a
volunteer who is part of a band of environmentalists who monitor
Forest Service-sanctioned timber cutting. Sullivan has documented a
disturbing trend of overharvesting in parts of the national forests
seclued from public view. (Harmon, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/LOGLIFE _ A profile of a mountain logging family who for years
have made their living felling trees in this rugged landscape. We
explore their unique perspective in the battle for the mountains,
as they struggle not to become endangered species of the 21st
century. (Harmon, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
