<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALCONS-CHANDLER-COX     07-29 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-CHANDLER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No one felt worse than me not being able to play'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   AJC: The first question is obvious: How are you? Are there any
lingering effects from your concussion?
</P>
<P>
   Chandler: No. If I had a concussion bad enough where there were
any lingering effects, I wouldn't be playing. You would think
somebody would have enough of an intelligence level to know that. I
feel great, really good. If I can just stop getting my head bounced
off the turf, I'll be all right.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Does the constant fuss about your injury situation irritate
you?
</P>
<P>
   Chandler: Any question that gets repeated gets tiresome. I will
always talk. I won't go out of my way to do things for an
interview, but if it's set up and done right, I have no problem.
But I've never had problems with not talking. Once in a while, I
try to make the media's job harder. (Chandler smiles.)
</P>
<P>
   AJC: But you do recognize the reason for all the questions,
don't you? The team was 7-3 with you, 0-6 without you.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler: I understand all that, but it just gets kind of
foolish after a while to keep so much attention on something like
that, when there's so many other things that are important. I took
every snap the second half of the season, and a lot of guys didn't
do that. It all depends on ... the spin you want to put on
something. No one felt worse than me not being able to play.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Your contract with the Falcons ends this year, and the
Falcons say they want to extend it. You say you want to extend it.
Any progress in that direction?
</P>
<P>
   Chandler: I just leave that up to (agent) Frank Bauer. He's
handling the whole thing, and when he thinks there's something
worth looking at, he'll talk to me.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Have you given him any framework, like length of contract,
how much you want, a deadline for getting it done?
</P>
<P>
   Chandler: No. I haven't even gotten to the point where I know
how long I'll play, although I know I'll play a long time.
Everybody wants stability, so you don't have to move around every
few years. I want what's fair. I can't tell you what that is, but
Frank knows the market. I'd like it done sooner. Once the season
starts, I'm not really going to be in the mood to hassle with it.
Even if it doesn't get done, though, I'm assuming something will
get done after the season.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Coach Dan Reeves and general manager Harold Richardson both
say they want to extend your contract, but they make it clear the
Falcons will want ``protection.'' That is to say they want a deal
laden with incentives tied to your health. Does this annoy you?
</P>
<P>
   Chandler: The injury thing is always annoying. Steve Young has
had a lot of concussions. So has Troy Aikman. I've had more
touchdown passes than Troy Aikman the last (three) years (53 to
47), and he's missed some games because of concussions. But people
are kind of like, ``I don't want to mention that about Troy, but I
will about Chris.'' OK, he's won a few Super Bowls, and he's Troy
Aikman, so we can let all that (injury talk) slide. But if you're
not him, people don't care if you had a great season last year.
It's, ``What are you going to do this year?''
</P>
<P>
   AJC: You'll be throwing to some different receivers this year,
chief among them Tony Martin, who was acquired by trade to replace
the departed Bert Emanuel. What's your early read on Tony?
</P>
<P>
   Chandler: You can just see in one-on-one drills, his technique
in running routes. He doesn't tip off things. He won't look back
early on a curl route. And you can just see his speed. He's got at
least the speed Bert has, with a little extra height (6-foot-1 to
Emanuel's 5-10). His ability to make big plays is evident, and it's
just a matter of me being able to get the ball to him.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: How are things better in camp this year?
</P>
<P>
   Chandler: I understand the offense better; we all understand
things better; we're more confident, more comfortable. Everything
goes pretty well, except when there's a rookie in (the offense).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
