A9099 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-EXPLOSION-NAT     07-29 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-EXPLOSION-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        NEVADA COMPANY BLAMED FOR EXPLOSION THAT CLAIMED FOUR LIVES
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Mark D. Preston  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 29 -- Dismissing a sabotage theory Wednesday,
federal investigators placed blame on the Sierra Chemical Co. for
two blasts that killed four workers and leveled its explosives
plant just east of Reno last January.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators told the Chemical Safety and Hazard
Investigation Board (CSB) that a combination of human error, poor
management and lax safety procedures most likely caused the Kean
Canyon Plant to blow up in the early morning of Jan. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The plant made explosive boosters that are used in the mining
industry. Boosters provide the energy necessary to detonate less
sensitive blasting material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sierra provided over 100 pages of documents and wanted us to
consider a theory of sabotage,'' said Paul Hill, chairman of the
CSB. ``When our investigators looked at their report ... they were
unable to find any factual evidence to support it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Laxalt, attorney for Sierra Chemical, disputed the CSB's
findings and said he thinks investigators disregarded facts
gathered from their independent investigation. He said the CSB also
rebuffed requests many times for face-to-face meetings with company
representatives to discuss the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gone to great efforts to offer our expert input to the
board and they were not interested,'' Laxalt said. ``They reached
their results ... and we feel they are inaccurate as far as the
cause of the blast.''
</P>
<P>
   After narrowing down four possible scenarios, the investigators
said the cause of the explosion was probably due to friction from a
mixing pot's blade that ignited volatile chemicals left overnight
in a pot.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility investigators would not rule out was that
chunks of the explosive materials were pinched between the mixer
blade and pot wall causing the detonation.
</P>
<P>
   Debris from the first blast, investigators said, most likely
penetrated an adjacent building that housed highly flammable
chemicals causing a second explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said many essential elements of process safety and
management were missing or deficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the evidence and testimony safety precautions were
not being taken,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also chastised the Department of Defense for
selling recycled explosives materials that sometimes contained
foreign objects and are dangerous to use.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators report is preliminary draft and the final
version is expected to be adopted within the next six weeks.
Although the CSB has no power to enforce any of its
recommendations, other state and federal agencies may use the
recommendations to aid their investigations.
</P>
<P>
   While not officially adopting the report, Hill described it as
``very thorough,'' and said he is comfortable with its conclusions
and recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra, which is fighting a $997,000 fine from the Nevada
Division of Industrial Relations because of 38 safety violations,
has submitted construction plans to local authorities and plans on
opening another explosive plant on the site, Laxalt said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
