<SLUG> BC-PILOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pot plot: Pilot spots drug crop
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Somewhere, a drug dealer is fuming that the cops
didn't find Eric Robert Rudolph on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That's because a pilot on his way home from the Rudolph manhunt
spotted the dealer's pot plants and called the law. The marijuana,
found growing in a vacant Cherokee County field, was worth
$323,000, according to narcotics agents who launched a manhunt of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia State Patrol helicopter pilot was returning to Cobb
County Airport-McCollum Field in Kennesaw after spending most of
the day combing the North Carolina mountains for Rudolph, who is
the only named suspect in the deadly Jan. 29 bombing of a
Birmingham abortion clinic and is wanted for questioning in three
metro Atlanta bombings in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip W. Price, who commands Cherokee's Multi-Agency Narcotics
Squad, said the pilot had changed course after encountering rough
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Flying low over Ga. 92 and Wade Green Road, the pilot happened
to glance out the window. The field below was teeming with 294 dark
green marijuana plants.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators first thought about hiding near the field to try
to catch the grower, but decided that the low-flying chopper might
have tipped off the culprit, so they destroyed the crop. Price said
the landowners live elsewhere in metro Atlanta and probably did not
know about the plants.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month Cherokee authorities have seized marijuana
worth more than $1 million, Price said, including plants worth
about $900,000 in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, county police confiscated marijuana worth only about
$130,000. Price credits this year's increase to more tips and
flyovers by helicopters from a statewide anti-drug task force.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
