A9103 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-WALLEYE-LADN     07-29 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-WALLEYE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA'S LAKE OKOBOJI PLENTIFUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKOBOJI, Iowa _ Query Midwest anglers about their favorite
species. If they aren't targeting panfish or bass, or gambling on a
rare bite from big-game muskie or Northern pike, they are probably
after walleye _ the bread-and-butter fishery here.
</P>
<P>
   Walleye are the trout of the heartland, and the similarities
between the two fish are enough to attract Western trout lovers who
venture into region.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are fairly easy to find. If you've got rocks, you're
going to find walleye eventually,'' said Jeff Morrison, a
conservation officer for the Iowa Department of Natural Resources
in recreation-crazed Dickinson County, home of the Great Lakes of
Iowa. ``You can catch them any time of day or night.''
</P>
<P>
   And, often, in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   He was talking my lingo; I'll take quick success and quantity
over quality anytime. I wanted lots of hookups, as I have come to
expect of the Eastern Sierra's bountiful trout lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Though not particularly fabled fighters, trout and walleye are
staples of stocked waters, and their human pursuers enjoy
much-ballyhooed season openers.
</P>
<P>
   But these fish have their differences. While trout are
cold-water dwellers, walleye are quite at home in the tepid
temperatures of Northern Iowa's natural lakes, where summer highs
can exceed 80 degrees. Trout fall into the salmon family. The
walleye is the largest member of the perch clan. And while the case
can be made that nothing surpasses the taste of trout, many
Midwesterners would argue that walleye are the caviar of freshwater
fare.
</P>
<P>
   To break this trout connoisseur into the world of walleye, two
knowledgeable Iowa anglers would serve as my initiators on the
Okoboji Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Casual but frequent fisherman Warren Vanden Brink of neighboring
Spirit Lake and guide Jim McDonnell from nearby Royal are polar
opposites in angling technique. Vanden Brink prefers still-fishing
with gear he's trusted for decades. McDonnell is a troller who
likes his tackle cutting-edge with all the bells and whistles. They
would show me vastly different bodies of water. It was just the way
I wanted _ an array of methods to land walleye on the one day I had
set aside to fish while visiting family in Iowa in the first week
of June.
</P>
<P>
   Vanden Brink would keep me busy in the a.m. dunking live minnows
on 6- and 8-pound line to the bottom of East Okoboji Lake in an old
Alumacraft that might never have seen a vacuum. He anchored in the
middle of the murky, runoff-fed waters and handed me an antiquated
closed-face spinning reel the likes of which I hadn't seen since
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have $500 or $600 worth of tackle but always catch my fish
on $3 or $4 worth of gear,'' said the 73-year-old former shipyard
welder and sewing-machine repairman who lost an arm in a hunting
accident nearly a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Vanden Brink put us on the right spot and was surprised to find
such a windfall of strikes following a three-day cold snap that set
record lows around the Midwest and dumped 10 inches of snow onto
the Black Hills of South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   We brought nine walleye to the boat in the first hour; the
initial two exceeded the legal size minimum of 14 inches. (The
limit is three keepers per rod. A mountable Iowa walleye is 8
pounds; the state record is 14{ pounds.)
</P>
<P>
   As soon as I would inquire about the finer points of Vanden
Brink's angling routine, he would be pleasantly interrupted by a
strike. ``We got business here,'' he would spout.
</P>
<P>
   Walleye have dramatic, oversize eyes _ hence the name _ that are
impossibly opaque but help them feed at night, their preferred
supper time. But runoff-fed East Okoboji is murky and its depths
are dark enough to stimulate daytime foraging instincts.
</P>
<P>
   A split-shot pinched onto the line 12 to 18 inches above a size
No.6 hook keeps the bait on the bottom, and a sliding bobber with a
stopper above it indicates a strike. The simple set-up is deadly _
and much easier than trolling for Vanden Brink, whose fattest
walleye was 6{ pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got one hand and it's easier for me to still-fish,'' he
said. ``I can handle it better. Driving a boat and setting the hook
is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   He has everything on his boat placed just so and appears quite
systematic in his coveralls as he uses his knees to hold the fish
for dehooking and measuring. Shorts were released and the next
minnow was quickly pinned on the hook. As he attended a separate
suspended panfish line, the whole process began anew as I would
yell out, ``Warren, I don't see your bobber.''
</P>
<P>
   The morning action seldom slowed, as evidenced by our 28 walleye
hookups and three keepers in three and a half hours. Back ashore,
Vanden Brink again impressed me with his adeptness, filleting the
fish with the aid of a contraption composed of a clamp, chain and
barn-door hinge that would anchor the walleye to a cleaning board
and act as a second hand.
</P>
<P>
   By 1:30 I was trolling with McDonnell on adjoining West Okoboji
Lake aboard a flashy vessel befitting an ``ambassador'' to the
Berkley fishing line and tackle manufacturer headquartered in
Spirit Lake. When McDonnell isn't guiding his own customers 100
times a year, he is ferrying Berkley clients another 20 days.
</P>
<P>
   Considered a blue-water lake because of its spring sources, West
Okoboji is markedly clearer than its twin to the east and its
predators are accordingly much warier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lake has been a tough old brute,'' said McDonnell, 61,
who taught middle school for 35 years. ``Fishing is always good;
catching is a little iffy.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell trolls to find the fish that are most active and least
heedful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also the most effective way to find some type of fish
biting when you have any type of extreme weather conditions, which
throws them offbeat a little bit,'' he said. ``Anytime you have a
cold front, it gives the fish the flu.''
</P>
<P>
   He prefers 10- and 14-pound line with sinkers that submerse both
live bait _ night crawlers and leeches _ and plastic worms on two-
and three-hook harness rigs. The hooks are set up behind in-line
spinner outfits: A rotating blade _ the flashing part of a spinning
lure _ is combined on 40 inches of leader with beads in varying
colors, sizes and quantity.
</P>
<P>
   The consummate fishing technician, McDonnell steadfastly altered
the troll speed, adjusted lengths on lines, changed weights,
experimented with color patterns, checked for weeds and made sure
the bait was swimming OK.
</P>
<P>
   As predicted, however, the west lake was slow. We hooked six in
four hours, mostly on ribbon leeches and plastic worms.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell said something to the effect that if you can't catch
them where you think they are, you fish for them where you know
they are. Then he whisked us off to East Okoboji. There our luck
picked up dramatically; 10 walleye were nailed in less than an
hour, including the afternoon's only keeper on the lucky thirteenth
hookup.
</P>
<P>
   All tallied, three anglers caught 44 walleye and four keepers in
about 8 hours. Now I know why bumper stickers read, ``Paris ... New
York ... London ... Tokyo ... Okoboji.'' Must be walleye anglers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
