<SLUG> BC-DOWN-DETECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTS COULD ALLOW EARLY DETECTION OF DOWN SYNDROME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAR HARBOR, Maine _ If new prenatal screening test methods under
study are validated, a woman could learn as early as the 11th week
of pregnancy if her risk was great of carrying a fetus with Down
syndrome, instead of waiting until the second trimester when the
deadline for abortion looms, a researcher said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If so, couples would have more time for the agonizing process of
weighing their options for continuing the pregnancy or terminating
it. However, the woman would still have to undergo an invasive test
_ chorionic villus sampling or amniocentesis _ to know for certain
whether the fetus was affected.
</P>
<P>
   With current tests, screening for Down syndrome and other birth
defects is done at 16 to 18 weeks' gestation. If it is positive, an
amniocentesis is needed to make a diagnosis, and by the time those
results are available, it's often not until 21 or 22 weeks that an
abortion is performed, said Dr. Laird G. Jackson of Thomas
Jefferson University in Pennsylvania. This is uncomfortably close
to deadlines of 22 to 24 weeks after which most abortion providers
will not terminate a pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The new test, said Jackson, ``if properly applied will exceed
the present rate of detection in the second trimester (tests) and
will move it into the first trimester when people can be more
comfortable'' under less time pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The tests combine an ultrasound scan that requires intensive
training, and a set of blood tests that measure human chorionic
gonadotrophin (hCG) and pregancy-associated placental proteins
(PAPP-A), said Jackson, a professor of medicine, pediatrics and
gynecology.
</P>
<P>
   The ultrasound, developed in England, looks for an abnormal
swelling of tissues in the back of the neck of the fetus, which is
a strong indication of Down syndrome. But the difference is subtle,
and the test did not work well when tried by US ultrasound
specialists in a study several years ago, said Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   However, the ultrasound in combination with the blood tests is
about to undergo a new study sponsored by the National Institutes
of Health, he said, with improved training of ultrasound operators.
Jackson spoke to reporters Wednesday at a briefing during an annual
genetics meeting held at Jackson Laboratory here.
</P>
<P>
   If validated, the combination of ultrasound and blood tests
``could make it possible for a woman to have a single appointment
at an obstetrical center, wait 20 minutes'' for outcomes of the
tests and know then and there whether she has a high risk of
carrying a fetus affected by Down syndrome, said Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Down syndrome is caused by a chromosome abnormality and results
in retardation and characteristic physical abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   If the tests were positive, the woman would be assigned an
estimated risk based on the findings and her age. She would still
have to undergo an invasive test, either chorionic villus sampling
(CVS) or amniocentesis, to make certain of the diagnosis, and doing
either test early in pregnancy carries some risk of fetal damage or
miscarriage.
</P>
<P>
   George Knight, director of the prenatal diagnosis laboratory at
the Foundation for Blood Research in Scarborough, Maine, said that
CVS has become less available in recent years because of concern
over fetal damage, and therefore a woman getting the new test might
have to wait a significant amount of time or go elsewhere for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first-trimester test has a lot of appeal because it's
early,'' said Knight in a telephone interview, ``but the concern is
these other issues, such as having to have an invasive test'' that
may not be immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   Knight said that the blood tests for hCG and PAPP-A that go
along with the ultrasound are not yet widely available.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said that he and other obstetricians would like to see
the combination test closely studied for accuracy before it becomes
widespread. He said a study is being conducted by obstetricians at
New England Medical Center in Boston, but the investigator heading
the research could not be reached Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Screening tests currently used in the second trimester include a
blood test to measure a substance called alpha-fetoprotein in the
mother's circulation: an abnormally low level signals the
possibility of a fetus with Down syndrome.
</P>
</TEXT>
