<SLUG> BC-OUT-BOOKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-AROUND STATEGY ESSENTIAL WHEN ENCOUNTERING BEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH MARTIN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No North American land animal evokes primal fear
like the grizzly bear; those who have seen the recent flick ``The
Edge'' will agree.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for humans, encounters with the humpbacked bruin are
avoidable, according to ``Backcountry Bear Basics'' (The
Mountaineers, $10.95).
</P>
<P>
   Author Dave Smith, an Anchorage, Alaska, naturalist who has
lived in grizzly territory for nearly three decades, places the
blame for deaths and maulings by bears on humans; ignorance and
misinformation are the major contributing factors.
</P>
<P>
   Smith does not have any magic bullet. For example, carrying a
gun is hardly a safety guard since a near-perfect shot with a
large-caliber weapon is required to bring down a charging
!ital!Ursus horribilis!off!. That's common knowledge for hunters,
but the subtitle of this 110-page book is ``The Definitive Guide to
Avoiding Unpleasant Encounters,'' because most backpackers can't
afford the weighty luxury of a rifle. A wound from a handgun
usually only enrages the beast.
</P>
<P>
   Running from a grizzly is just as useless; it can move almost
twice as fast (35 mph) as the speediest human. Pepper spray can be
helpful in some situations provided the user can get to it in time,
but Smith advocates a comprehensive strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Hikers should find out the bear situation before going into the
woods. Smith says specialty items, such as bear-resistant food
containers, resealable plastic and garbage bags are essential.
</P>
<P>
   Some advice seems like common sense, until you see tourists
actually approaching bears, feeding them and carelessly leaving
food around their campsites. Smith suggests taking only cold food
into bear country. Cook in the open and away from the campsite.
Camp away from streams, in a forest or in the open, but not where
the timber and meadows meet. Hanging food can help, at least to
deter ``novice'' bears.
</P>
<P>
   Some tips seem more difficult to follow. It would be tough to
stand ground when a griz approaches suddenly in a close-up
encounter. (You're supposed to hit the dirt and play dead _ hands
behind head _ if contact is imminent.) And good luck trying not to
yell out when under attack.
</P>
<P>
   In most case, Smith writes, it is better to stand and face the
grizzly, because it might oblige the creature to back off, as
grizzlies usually do in confrontations with others of their
species. Most charges are bluffs anyhow. Speaking softly (without
carrying a big stick) to the animal might also help ward off
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest dangers on the trail is surprising a bear.
The author recommends that trekkers clap while going around a bend
and say, ``Hey, bear,'' rather than tying bear bells to their
packs.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has pieced together the only bear book anyone would ever
need. His advice is flawlessly logical. But who could summon a
calm, quiet voice to reassure a grizzly or resist screaming bloody
murder if the former isn't effective? I hope Smith's tactics work
the next time I'm in grizzly country. If not, he might be hearing
from my estate. Our rating: 3 1/2
</P>
<P>
   Norman Clyde is a legend in the annals of Sierra Nevada hiking
and climbing. He climbed Mount Whitney 50 times. In 1925 alone, he
undertook 48 high-country climbs _ half of them first ascents. When
he first fell in love with the mountains, ``free climbing'' was the
norm, with ropes seldom employed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Close Ups of the High Sierra,'' (Spotted Dog Press, $14.95),
edited by Wynne Benti, is a collection of Clyde's writings and
descriptions of many of his climbs. Most of the 169 pages, which
include forewords, are straightforward narratives of ascents. But
among them is an emotional account of one trip when his partner
didn't come back; a skiing partner died of a heart attack during a
snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   It's really too bad Clyde, described as a ``vanishing
Victorian,'' didn't write more about himself and his adventures,
and not merely climbing tales. Not only was he a world-class
climber, he plucked injured, lost, stranded and _ too often _ dead
climbers and skiers from various locales during winters. He had a
nose for finding wrecked planes, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde initially turned to climbing after his wife died four
years into their marriage and spent much of the rest of his life in
the mountains. One foreword notes that he was principal of a high
school in Independence until he was fired for shooting warning
shots at youthful pranksters.
</P>
<P>
   This candid look at Sierra hiking should be engaging for the
casual reader, and Clyde's accounts of early ascents might be
especially fascinating to hard-core mountain climbers. Our rating:
2 1/2
</P>
<P>
   Dad takes a fishing trip with his 7-year-old daughter as he
attempts to get over his divorce and his father's death a year
earlier. A sentimental family story set in the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a perfect idea for a teary-eyed ``chick flick.''
As a book, well, it will not rival Clancy or Follett for thrills.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Faithful Travelers'' (Bantam Books; $22.95) is not a bad
read. Author James Dodson is a solid writer, and his anecdotes and
connecting facts are poignant if not always funny.
</P>
<P>
   The 279 pages meander and rarely seem to get anywhere in
particular, but the journey is fairly entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Those with families will find ``Faithful Travelers'' more
interesting than others, and it has a decidedly Christian
viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The outdoors as therapy rather than as proving grounds? Makes
sense. Our rating: 2 1/2
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
