<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-ROBBINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEROME ROBBINS, 79: LEGENDARY CHOREOGRAPHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerome Robbins, the legendary choreographer whose work straddled
the worlds of ballet and Broadway, died of the effects of a stroke
in his home in New York Wednesday. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   A visionary known for his synthesis of popular culture and high
art, he brought his signature theatricality to classical ballet and
brought virtuoso movement to the Great White Way. Known to
balletomanes for his long association with the New York City
Ballet, he was best known as the quintessential choreographer of
the modern American musical. His 1957 collaboration with Leonard
Bernstein and Stephen Sondheim on ``West Side Story'' remains a
timeless landmark in theatrical history: His finger-snapping,
high-kicking choreography defined the essence of cool, and the
dances captured the rare combination of youthful abandon and
controlled emotion that unfolds in an urban conflict on a hot,
sweaty night.
</P>
<P>
   His prolific Broadway career began in 1945with the light musical
comedy ``On the Town'' and spanned several decades and included
many commercial hits. He created the landmark ballet ``The Small
House of Uncle Thomas'' in ``The King and I'' (1951); he directed
Mary Martin as she flew across the stage in ``Peter Pan'' (1954);
he brought the bump-and-grind to the Broadway stage in ``Gypsy''
(1959); and he captured life in a Russian village in the historic
production of ``Fiddler on the Roof'' (1964). A retrospective of
his work, ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway'' received popular and
critical acclaim in 1989, when it won the Tony Award for Best
Musical. He also won two Academy Awards for the 1960 movie version
of ``West Side Story.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time he was capturing the hearts of theatrical
audiences, he maintained a long-standing relationship with the New
York City Ballet, which he joined in 1949 as associate artistic
director so he could work with ballet master George Balanchine; he
shared the title of balletmaster-in-chief with Peter Martins from
1983 to 1990, until Robbins resigned to pursue other interests,
which ranged from theater to film to opera. In May, the ballet paid
tribute to him at its spring gala, which included a performance of
his ballet ``Les Noces.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerome Robbins's death truly represents the end of an era and
leaves us in deepest grief,'' balletmaster-in-chief Martins said
Wednesday. ``He was the last of the titans in the world of dance.''
</P>
<P>
   The last of the titans was born Jerome Rabinowitz in New York,
the son of Russian-Jewish immigrants who had fled the pogroms of
Eastern Europe. He changed his name in the early '40s, after he had
begun his career as a dancer in musical comedy and then joined the
newly formed Ballet Theatre (now called the American Ballet
Theatre). His affinity for both ballet and Broadway sprouted early
on: His first ballet, the light-hearted, loose-limbed ``Fancy
Free,'' became ``On the Town.''
</P>
<P>
   A taskmaster who drove himself as hard as he drove his dancers,
Robbins rarely gave interviews. He was known to be exacting both in
and out of the theater: When he did grant an interview, he would
pull out a tape recorder and record the session himself. ``I am
enormously demanding,'' he once said. ``I ask for a great deal, but
no more than I give myself.'' In one famous theatrical tale, after
a day of grueling rehearsals, the cast of ``West Side Story''
watched him back off the stage and fall into the orchestra pit
without warning him of his precarious position.
</P>
<P>
   If Mr. Robbins was mercurial, however, it was because he
possessed an uncompromising commitment to his art. Dancers, he
often said, ``have to be passionate.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Pelzig, associate artist at Boston Ballet, was a young
dancer in the 1980 Broadway revival of ``West Side Story.'' ``He
could be prickly one moment and have the most amazing sense of
humor the next,'' Pelzig recalled. ``But you accepted the package
because he was such a great visionary.''
</P>
<P>
   He may have pushed and prodded but he did it to instill that
vision in his dancers. Even though he underwent heart surgery two
years ago, he debuted his last ballet, the critically acclaimed
``Brandenburg,'' last year in New York. ``Robbins made you aware
that as a dancer, there is a context,'' Pelzig said. ``It's not
about feet pointing or the leg straightening: It's about being in a
time and a place and being in touch with your humanity. He was a
master at that.''
</P>
<P>
   That sense of humanity extended from the high jinks of ``Gypsy''
and ``The Pajama Game'' to the heartbreak of ``West Side Story''
and ``Fiddler.'' Like the gang members in the unforgettable number
``Cool,'' Robbins was a passionate artist all the way, from his
first Broadway show to his last dying day.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins leaves a sister, Sonia Cuollines, a niece and nephew.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway theaters will dim their lights Friday night just before
curtain as a tribute to Robbins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
