A9124 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-BUDGET-NAT     07-29 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BUDGET-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        PEOPLE WOULD USE SURPLUS TO PAY NATIONAL DEBT, REPORT SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Elliot Zaret  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 29 -- The government is about the right size.
The budget surplus should be used to pay off the national debt.
Social Security should be reformed to include individual savings
accounts. And if taxes need to be raised, bump up sin taxes and
corporate income taxes first.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way average citizens would tackle the federal budget,
according to a report by the Committee for a Responisible Federal
Budget, a bipartisan Washington-based nonprofit research group.
</P>
<P>
   About 850 people in five cities, including Denver, took part in
the group's day-long budget exercises, working through some of the
decisions lawmakers face in making the $1.7 trillion federal
budget. The other cities were Norman, Okla., Long Beach, Calif.,
Cincinnati, Ohio, and Greensboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The participants looked at the size of the federal government,
considered possible balanced-budget rules, examined Social Security
and Medicare reform, contemplated other programs such as defense
spending, and decided what to do with current taxes and the
expected budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   They then broke into groups of eight to 10 to come up with
answers. Staff members from the congressional budget committees
helped them with questions that arised.
</P>
<P>
   Among the results:
</P>
<P>
   89 percent of the groups wanted to use the projected $63 billion
budget surplus to begin paying off the $5.5 trillion national debt,
while only 4 percent wanted to use the windfall to cut taxes.
Virtually none wanted to use it to increase spending.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to Social Security, which is expected to go
bankrupt by 2030, more than three-fourths of the groups wanted to
include some sort of individual savings account in the solution. 13
percent wanted to make gradual changes to the program, such as
raising the retirement age to 67 for people born after 1949 and
decreasing the cost-of-living adjustments. Only 1 percent wanted to
keep the current program.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the groups, 61 percent, wanted to maintain a
lean government in relation to the GDP, keeping the government at
19 percent of the GDP as mandated in the 1997 Balanced Budget
Agreement. A third of the groups would increase the federal
government slightly -- to 23 percent of the GDP -- in order to
anticipate the expected increase in demand for Medicaid and Social
Security when Baby Boomers retire. Few, though, would increase the
government more than that.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to taxes, the participants said they didn't want
them raised, but if they had to be raised they wanted alcohol and
tobacco taxes increased first. After that, they said they would
raise corporate income taxes, and Social Security payroll taxes
before hitting individual income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Both Sen. Wayne Allard, R-Colo., and Diana Degette, D-Denver,
who took part in the Denver session in April, praised the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The responsible budget was a tremendous success in Denver
where local citizens contributed their time to help shape the
economic future of our country,'' said DeGette. Allard agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress should take a very close look at the results of these
exercises,'' said Allard. ``Especially the section concerning what
Congress should be doing with the budget surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Allard, who introduced a bill in February that would set a
30-year payment schedule to repay the national debt, took the study
as validation for his plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When 90 percent of folks believe we need to start paying down
the debt, that is a strong message that Congress needs to start
doing something to put our fiscal house in order,'' Allard said.
``As I have said in the past, we do not have a budget surplus as
long as we have more than a $5.5 trillion debt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
