<HEADER>
A9125 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKLAWYERS-COX     07-29 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKLAWYERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thomas sharphy defends conservative views
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ In a highly personal address to the nation's
largest association of black judges and lawyers, Clarence Thomas,
the only black justice on the U.S. Supreme Court, said Wednesday
his judicial views are influenced by his own reasoning and that
race should not be the basis for his decisions.
</P>
<P>
   He addressed head-on controversy surrounding his appearance at
the National Bar Association meeting and efforts by some members to
rescind his invitation because, they claim, he has hurt the cause
of civil rights with his opinions.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 850 in the main ballroom of the Peabody Hotel, and
300 more who watched a television feed in a nearby room, gave
polite responses throughout the 35-minute speech. Thomas at times
struck sharply at critics, drawing gasps from the crowd when he
wondered whether his detractors were ``illiterate or fraught with
malice.''
</P>
<P>
   A rumored walkout never materialized, although a handful of
protesters picketed at two separate locations outside. Thomas joked
about the controversy in his opening remarks _ ``I have heard all
the arguments and will take them under advisement'' _ but he ended
his speech with emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pains me deeply, more deeply than any of you can imagine,
to be perceived by so many members of my race as doing them harm,''
Thomas said. ``All the sacrifices, all the long hours of
preparation were to help, not to hurt. But what hurts more, much
more, is the amount of time and attention spent on manufactured
controversies and media sideshows when so many problems cry out for
constructive attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia native, appointed to the nation's highest court in
1991 by President George Bush, harked back to the assassination of
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. in Memphis 30 years ago as a
turning point in his life that caused him to leave seminary and
abandon his calling as a Catholic priest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, this cataclysmic event ripped me from the moorings
of my grandparents, my youth and my faith,'' Thomas said. ``It was
this event that shattered my faith in my religion and my country.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas recalled that a fellow seminarian had ``hoped the SOB
died'' after King was shot. Gone was the life Thomas had dreamed
about during summers on the farm in Georgia or on the oil truck
with his grandfather. Thomas said his dream ``expired as Dr. King
expired.''
</P>
<P>
   In his address to the NBA, formed 73 years ago because the
American Bar Association did not allow black members, Thomas kept
returning to the theme of oppression, a history he told the group
he shared with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a man, a black man, an American. My history is not unlike
that of many blacks in the Deep South,'' said Thomas, 50. ``And in
many ways it is not that much different from that of many other
Americans. It goes without saying that I understand the comforts
and security of racial solidarity. ... Only those who have not been
set upon by hatred and repelled by rejection fail to understand its
attraction. As I have suggested, I have been there.''
</P>
<P>
   On a picket line outside the hotel, one protester wore a
sandwich board bearing the legend, ``Uncle Thomas an Insult to
Thurgood Marshall and Dr. King.'' James Stewart, an appeals court
judge in Louisiana, said many in the NBA see Thomas' votes against
affirmative action as a ``wasted opportunity.'' Stewart said Thomas
has a ``duty to follow the views put forth by Thurgood Marshall,''
the first black member of the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he never would apologize for his conservative views
and would continue ``to refuse to have my ideas assigned to me as
though I'm an intellectual slave because I'm black. I come to state
that I am a man free to think for myself and do as I please. I came
to assert that as a judge I will not be consigned to the
unquestioned opinions of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
