<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PRISONER-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO DENY PRISONERS THE VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For the first time in the state's history, the
Legislature moved Wednesday to take away a group's right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   But this being an election year, and the group being prisoners,
the House and Senate overwhelmingly passed an amendment to the
Massachusetts Constitution taking away inmates' ability to cast
absentee ballots from behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   To finalize the decision, the Legislature must vote in favor of
the amendment again next year, which is likely, and then the
measure would be put on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the state would fall within the norm across the
country. Currently, only three other states allow prisoners to
vote: Utah, Maine, and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm told other states place restrictions,'' Senate President
Thomas F. Birmingham said. ``I think it's within that context, in
terms of constitutional issues, that we're on very solid ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Prisoners have had the right to vote under the state
constitution and, in the 1970s, the Supreme Judicial Court upheld
that right.
</P>
<P>
   However, the issue came to the fore last year when Acting
Governor Paul Cellucci discovered that Norfolk County prisoners had
formed a first-in-the-nation political action committee to urge
fellow inmates to vote and lobby lawmakers on the transfer of
convicts to cells in Texas and on cuts in rehabilitation and
substance-abuse treatment in correctional facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci issued an executive order banning inmate fund-raising
and vowed to take away their voting rights. Wednesday, the
Legislature followed Cellucci's lead, approving an amendment to the
constitution, 155-34.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of prisoners' rights said the Democratic Legislature
was acting cynically, to avoid giving Cellucci an inflamatory issue
in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the Republicans mostly,'' said Represenative Byron
Rushing, a Boston Democrat, who voted against the measure. ``And a
lot of people not giving due consideration would feel uncomfortable
voting green (yes) in an election year. No one could tell us how
many prisoners could vote.''
</P>
<P>
   David Elvin of the Massachusetts Prisoners Assocation _ the PAC
that Cellucci tried to quash _ said that at least 2,000 prisoners
out of 24,000 in state and county facilities registered to vote
using their most recent address in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main activity over the last year has been to increase
voter registration,'' Elvin said. ``There aren't that many
prisoners that vote on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, usually more liberal than the House, voted with
similar support Wednesday to take away a prisoner's right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate on the House floor during the joint session
spanned a range of opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Represenative Benjamin Swan, a Springfield Democrat, said his
grandfather was born a slave who could not vote and he argued
against taking the ``very serious'' step of taking away the rights
of any disenchfranchised group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it abhorrent that we would vote to take away the
franchise rights of individuals, the right to vote, especially in
this election year,'' Swan said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Businger said he was concerned about making any change
to the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, we're fiddling with it because we want a headline,''
said Businger, a Brookline Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Paul Frost, a Republican from Auburn, argued those who
have committed crimes have impinged on the freedoms of others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murderers have taken the voting rights of their victims,'' he
said. ``They forfeited their rights in cases of murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis Marini, a Republican representative from Hanson, filed
the constitutional amendment in January, 1997. It bans voting for
the span of inmates' sentences, then restores their rights once
they are released. In 13 states, according to Elvin, convicts never
get that right back.
</P>
<P>
   Marini predicted that the amendment would win wide popular
support. ``People who oppose this measure, know the public will
approve this,'' Marini said.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci spokeswoman Ilene Hoffer praised the Legislature's
move. ``Those people who can't obey our most basic laws forfeit
their right to participate in the law-making process,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
