<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIPS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORTILLA-CHIP MAKER SQUEEZED BY GIANT FRITO-LAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN CRENO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's hard for Bob Murillo to keep the frustration from
boiling over. He's trying to stay upbeat about his company's
chances for survival while he watches it slowly die.
</P>
<P>
   Murillo has to keep a happy face for the grocery store
executives and buyers who decide what foods you see in stores. He's
pitching hard to keep his company's tortilla chips in enough stores
to let his business stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Murillo is seething. His company, Mi Ranchito, has been
dropped from one grocery chain after another and may have to close
if it's removed from any of the last three it does business in.
</P>
<P>
   Murillo says his chips are selling, but he's still losing store
space.
</P>
<P>
   He says it's tough to compete with a giant like Frito-Lay,
Pepsico Inc.'s snack food division, which offers stores
compensation for increased space, including premium spots at the
ends of aisles, ``slotting fees'' for new displays, and marketing
deals his company could never afford.
</P>
<P>
   Frito-Lay says it's doing nothing wrong and is merely an
aggressive player in a very competitive business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not our intention to drive small, regional companies out
of business, but the business environment probably has been
difficult for small companies,'' Frito-Lay spokeswoman Lynn Markley
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our single focus is on growth, and you get that growth through
quality, innovation, and technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Stores say that when Mi Ranchito, or any product is dropped,
it's due to sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a customer wants a product, we won't discontinue it,''
Safeway spokeswoman Debra Albery said.
</P>
<P>
   Fry's spokesman Mike Donnelly and Marsha Gilford, spokeswoman
for the Smitty's-Smith's stores, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really dictates to us what products we carry,''
Donnelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Mi Ranchito is trying to overcome one of the biggest obstacles
confronting small, independent retailers: Big companies and big
brands rule the marketplace and can spend huge amounts of money
promoting their products.
</P>
<P>
   Local or regional companies often operate on a shoestring and
don't have the money for a big marketing push to establish or
promote their brands.
</P>
<P>
   Mi Ranchito, for instance, has bought ads on the announcement
board at the Fiesta Bowl. Frito-Lay now sponsors the game and
renamed it after its Tostitos chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have been trained that if it's a name brand, it's
OK,'' Bashas' spokeswoman Becca Anderson said. ``It's that habit
that really works against a small company until someone is used to
their product and tells other people about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported in 1996 that the U.S. Justice
Department's antitrust division was looking at whether Frito-Lay is
buying shelf space to keep out competitors. Markley said
investigators contacted Frito-Lay a year ago, but the company
hasn't heard anything since.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never been accused of any wrongdoing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mi Ranchito - Spanish for ``my little ranch'' - operates out of
a 15,000-square-foot office and production facility in Phoenix. It
has a staff of 18, including 14 who work on the production floor.
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded more than 20 years ago by Espiridion
Murillo, 82, who said he picked up the nickname Pancho years ago
when a man logging bets for a boxing match couldn't spell his name
and scribbled Pancho on the sheet instead. Espiridion Murillo is
the company's president and his face is on the side of the bag as
its trademark, ``Senor Pancho.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Murillo is the son of the founder, as is company treasurer
Rudy Murillo. As of 1991, Mi Ranchito was in every major grocery
chain in the Phoenix area with prominent shelf space and end-caps,
the coveted display space at the ends of aisles.
</P>
<P>
   The brand recently was taken out of Southwest Supermarkets and
is down to three chains: ABCO, Fry's and Bashas' Food City stores.
Mi Ranchito says its sales have fallen from $3.5 million six years
ago to $1 million last year, even though the company has added
revenue by taking on distribution for another snack-food company.
</P>
<P>
   Mi Ranchito's production is sporadic, and some employees' hours
have been cut to 32 a week. The Murillos say some employees left
for more stable jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Mi Ranchito has complained to the state Attorney General's
Office, and has asked a private lawyer what it can do. The
prospects seem dim.
</P>
<P>
   Frito-Lay said it faces plenty of competition from such chip
companies as Mission and Poore Bros.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have succeeded for decades by being totally open honest and
fair,'' Markley said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilford, of Smith's-Smitty's, said stores face huge pressure to
find space for the avalanche of new products introduced every year.
</P>
<P>
   She said her company depends on vendor research to assess how
well those products will be received, and watches sales of
merchandise that's already on the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult when there are so many new products out there
that grocery stores cannot be the test arena for them,'' Gilford
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Murillo acknowledges that Mi Ranchito has grown, but says
that growth hasn't come at the expense of other companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not getting rich here,'' he said. ``We're just trying to
make a living. We're not flaunting anything because we don't have
anything to flaunt.'' &QL; 
Glen Creno can be reached at glen.creno(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
