<HEADLINE>
MEGGETT'S BROKEN FOOT INJURED DURING SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Former Patriots running back David Meggett may be out
for the entire 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Agnone, his agent, said Wednesday that Meggett sustained
further injury to his broken foot during surgery at Brigham and
Women's Hospital in Boston this week.
</P>
<P>
   Meggett suffered a broken right foot during the Patriots' 7-6
playoff loss in Pittsburgh Jan. 3. The Patriots released Meggett
May 29, some three months after he was charged with sexual assault
and robbery in Toronto. The assault charges were dropped; the
robbery charge is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Agnone said Meggett returned to Boston for the removal of a pin
that had been placed in his foot to stabilize the break. However,
during surgery, a tendon in his foot detached from the bone and had
to be reattached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave thought he would be ready to come back to play in
October,'' said Agnone, ``but that is doubtful now. The doctors
told him this (setback) would add another six weeks to the recovery
process, and that would take him close to the end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Meggett is still a free agent, but several teams had maintained
interest in him and were considering him as a possibility once he
was cleared medically to play again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
