u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-ART-345&AMP;ADD     07-29 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-ART-345&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BOTH GM AND UAW WERE HURT BY STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ind., Ohio, Wis., N.J.)  (With GM-LABOR, a news analysis) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on recent and imminent plant openings is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ Strikes against two General Motors auto parts
factories ended here Wednesday after nearly eight weeks as workers
ratified a settlement and trooped back into the plants, but the
showdown has harmed GM and the United Automobile Workers while
appearing to produce limited gains for either side.
</P>
<P>
   The strike cost GM about $3 billion in after-tax losses, the
nation's costliest strike ever before adjusting for inflation, yet
produced a deal that mainly calls for a few small changes in work
rules at the factories here and other parts factories in Ohio and
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has left GM dealerships with few popular models, so
GM's market share in July and possibly August most likely will fall
below Ford Motor Co.'s for the first time since a national strike
against GM in 1970. And GM could have serious problems producing
enough 1999 model cars and trucks in time to compete with rival
automakers' 1999 offerings this autumn.
</P>
<P>
   UAW leaders have praised the agreement since it was announced
Tuesday, but they have relatively little to show for the $1 billion
in paychecks that their members gave up. The strike mostly
maintained the status quo, but at the cost of giving the union a
national image for taking workers out on long strikes. That could
hurt the UAW's planned push over the next several years to organize
workers at independent auto parts makers.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's strikes also cost GM nearly half a year's worth of
earnings, which will reduce workers' profit-sharing checks at the
end of the year. And the further erosion of GM's market share
during the strike means that the world's largest automaker may need
even fewer workers in the future.
</P>
<P>
   GM could probably rebuild the factories here from the ground up
for less than $1 billion, so Wall Street analysts questioned what
the company and the union had achieved after fighting each other to
a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, they both are suicidal _ nobody won,
but you can conclusively say both sides lost a little,'' said
Maryann Keller, an auto analyst at Furman Selz.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The final details of the settlement, presented to workers before
their ratification votes Wednesday, include some small adjustments
in work rules. Seeking to rally public opinion against the UAW, GM
often painted the walkouts as a struggle over whether decades-old
work rules would continue to allow about 600 welders to draw a full
day's pay for four to six hours of work. The welders, who labor in
a hot factory with no air-conditioning and must move 55-pound
engine braces with their bare hands because there is little
automation available, must produce a certain number of parts during
a shift. Once they have met their quotas, they can stop work,
although they are not allowed to leave the factory until eight
hours have elapsed.
</P>
<P>
   The final settlement maintains these work rules but raises the
number of parts a welder must produce before stopping work. Yet
even the increases in required parts are fairly modest and will be
phased in gradually. Welders producing engine braces for the
Chevrolet Astro van, for example, will be required to produce 800
braces during an eight-hour shift by next March, compared with 768
now.
</P>
<P>
   One of these welders, Kim Cramer, said he would still be able to
finish work early. ``I'll get done in five hours or six hours, it
depends on how hard I work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The accord protects GM against further strikes for a year at
some of its most important auto parts factories here and in
Indianapolis and Dayton, Ohio. In exchange, GM promised that, at
least through the end of next year, it would not sell or close a
spark plug factory here or brake factories in Dayton, a distinct
possibility that had worried workers in both cities.
</P>
<P>
   But the fate of these factories will be on the table again when
GM and the UAW start bargaining next summer on a new national
agreement. The current accord will expire in September 1999, and
many workers and UAW officials said here Wednesday that they were
already bracing for another possible strike then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be just as hard fought as this one,'' said Dennis
Savage, 55, who operates parts-making equipment. ``Better start
saving now.''
</P>
<P>
   GM and UAW leaders agreed Tuesday to talk more regularly to head
off future strikes. But the two sides continued to aim barbed
remarks at each other, suggesting that the peace may not last long.
The two sides may also have a tacit understanding not to engage in
further showdowns of this sort for a while, although neither party
would confirm this.
</P>
<P>
   In the first sign that restarting production may be a long, slow
process, GM announced Wednesday that it would reopen just four of
its 25 closed assembly plants in North America on Friday. The first
assembly plants to reopen will be a highly profitable sport utility
vehicle factory in Janesville, Wis., two small-car factories in
Lansing, Mich., and a Cadillac factory in Hamtramck, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   GM officials have said they would like to reopen all of their
assembly plants within a week, but outside experts predicted that
it could take 10 days to return to full production..
</P>
<P>
   Frank Ursomarso, the chairman of the GM section of the National
Automobile Dealers Association, said that many dealers might not
have a full selection of cars and trucks again until September.
Ursomarso's Pontiac and GMC dealership in Wilmington, Del., has
only 27 vehicles in stock, compared with a typical inventory of 125
vehicles before the strike. He predicted that once the assembly
plants reopened, it would be three weeks before he started to
receive new vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Jacobs, an automotive sales consultant in Rutherford,
N.J., said that GM's short-term market share, which was hovering
around 31 percent before the strike began, would not recover until
October. The company will announce its July sales next week.
</P>
<P>
   GM's long-term market share will most likely continue to drop
because of the automaker's inability to find a way to cut costs
more quickly. Ms. Jacobs said, ``I think they'll drop below 30 next
year and just trend down over the coming years.''
</P>
<P>
   GM's board is scheduled to meet Monday to consider the company's
latest plans to improve its competitiveness by eliminating
unprofitable car models, closing factories and streamlining the
separate bureaucracies at divisions like Chevrolet, Buick and
Oldsmobile. But the odds of a drastic move affecting thousands of
workers seem to have faded. GM and UAW officials said that they had
not discussed factory closings, and GM has also promised to start
working more closely with the UAW, making any sudden move unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   GM could stop production of some unprofitable models, like the
Buick Riviera, without closing factories or affecting employment.
The UAW has expressed no opposition to such a limited move. GM may
also cut further its white-collar staff, much of which is not
unionized.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts were generally unimpressed with Tuesday's
settlement and predicted that GM would continue to lag behind more
efficient rivals like Ford and Chrysler, to say nothing of low-cost
producers in Japan and South Korea. Shares of GM edged down 12.5
cents today, to $74.125.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM doesn't get one step closer to where it needs to be on cost
and competitiveness,'' Ms. Keller, the analyst, said. ``If this is
what they get in two factories after 54 days of strikes, how are
they going to get this across the country?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
