<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: BIG PIPES; BIG STARS IN VENICE; BIG-SCREEN
BEATLEMANIA; BIGGEST POSTER IN THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Italy)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 90, many pipe organs are totally worn out or in a state of
advanced decrepitude. In Ocean Grove, N.J., on Thursday, there will
be a cake and a concert to celebrate the 90th birthday of the still
vital Hope Jones Pipe Organ, installed in the 6,000-seat Great
Auditorium in the Victorian days when the seaside resort was
established as a spiritual retreat. The organ has 10,000 pipes, 600
stops and 40,000 feet of pine and weighs 20 to 25 tons. The
resident organist, Gordon Turk, and the harpist Kathleen Bride will
play works by Bach, Handel and Grandjany.
</P>
<P>
   Twinkle, Twinkle
</P>
<P>
   The stars will be out again this year at the Venice
International Film Festival. After shunning the luminaries last
year, Felice Laudadio, the director of the event, is bringing them
back, although he continues to insist that commercialism is not his
motive. ``Venice is not a festival of stars,'' he said. ``There's
no change of direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, many stars are aligned in films competing for the
Golden Lion from Sept. 3 to 13. Warren Beatty's ``Bulworth'' is in
the running, as are Tony Drazan's ``Hurlyburly,'' with Meg Ryan and
Sean Penn; Meryl Streep in Pat O'Connor's version of the hit play
``Dancing at Lughnasa''; Emmanuelle Beart and Sandrine Bonnaire in
Yves Angelo's ``Voleur de Vie,'' Catherine Deneuve in Nicole
Garcia's ``Place Vendome,'' and Emily Watson as the cellist
Jacqueline Du Pre in Anand Tucker's ``Jackie.''
</P>
<P>
   Comeback Kids
</P>
<P>
   The Beatles &UR;  &LR; are coming back, all of them, in their youth and
glory. And with a little something extra. Miramax Films has
acquired ``A Hard Day's Night'' and plans to release a restored
version of the 1964 Richard Lester film with digitally remastered
six-track stereo sound and additional scenes for its 35th
anniversary next March.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute black-and-white feature, which was nominated for
two Academy Awards, tells a fanciful tale of a day in the life of
the Fab Four. Among the songs in the film are ``A Hard Day's
Night,'' ``Can't Buy Me Love,'' ``All My Loving,'' ``I Should Have
Known Better'' and ``She Loves You.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kicks
</P>
<P>
   ``Tosca'' is big in Rome. Literally. What is trumpeted as the
world's largest advertising poster has been unveiled by the
advertising agency Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi in the circular Piazza del
Popolo in the heart of Rome. The poster is 913 feet long and 6 1/2
feet high and promotes the Teatro dell'Opera's summer staging of
the Puccini work.
</P>
<P>
   What's behind this outsize gesture? This ``Tosca'' is being
staged in Rome's Olympic stadium, more often home to soccer
partisans. Therefore, the poster, created by the Italian Pop artist
Marco Lodola and consisting of 30 panels that tell the story of the
opera, also shows opera devotees displaying their enthusiasm as
soccer fans do, with banners emblazoned with slogans like ``Support
Puccini'' and ``100 Percent Tosca.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
