<HEADER>
A9143 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     07-29 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; TINA BROWN JUMPED GUN ON MURDOCH MEMOIR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tina Brown &LR; 's final New Yorker issue, which was last week's,
included a much-talked-about excerpt from  &UR; John Bayley &LR; 's memoir
about his wife  &UR; Iris Murdoch &LR; 's Alzheimer's disease. The English
novelist Murdoch is a well-known intellectual, and the piece caused
much buzz in literary circles. Its publication in the New Yorker
may also have cost the author $100,000, says the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   The Times of London had bought rights from the London publisher,
Duckworth, to be first to publish an excerpt. Brown had bought
rights from the book's American publisher, St. Martin's, which was
to publish the book in January, four months after it would appear
in England. When Duckworth heard that Brown, apparently looking for
some final splash, was going to publish the piece last week rather
than in the fall, as planned, the publisher threatened legal action
to stop her.
</P>
<P>
   The threat was unsuccessful. Last week, after the New Yorker
came out, the London Telegraph ran a 1,500-word summary of the
excerpt, pretty much ruining the Times's plans. ``It would be fair
to say this will cost John Bayley something,'' Duckworth's
 &UR; Robin Baird-Smith &LR;  told the Post.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's said that American publication might be rushed
ahead, &LR;  and that the author is ``delighted with the piece. ... He's
not at all upset at the New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMILLA THROWS A PARTY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prince Charles &LR;  has revealed that  &UR; Camilla Parker Bowles &LR;  will
host his 50th birthday party in November, with his sons,
 &UR; William  &LR; and  &UR; Harry &LR; , as ``honored guests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is testing the waters for an eventual morganatic
marriage,'' royalty expert  &UR; Tony Ridley &LR;  told the Philadelphia
Daily News, ``such as occurred in many royal families, but never
before in the British royal family.''
</P>
<P>
   In a morganatic marriage, the rank of the ``inferior'' partner
does not become elevated after marriage, and any children from the
union do not inherit the title of the ``superior'' partner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT'S WRONG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Headed downtown on a San Francisco bus Wednesday morning,
passengers became impatient when the driver remained stopped at
Sutter Street to chat with another Muni driver who'd strolled over
from across the street. The light changed a couple of times while
the conversation continued and the passengers fumed, and finally
one woman complained. ``If you're in such a hurry,'' the driver
told her, ``take a cab.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers at the Boston University School of Medicine say
smoking can reduce the size of a man's erect penis, and promise to
say more at next month's meeting of the International Society of
Impotence Research in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   _ An e-mail now whizzing, unwanted, into mailboxes around the
country is a spam asking users to vote on whether they want to be
spammed. ``Is this adding insult to injury, or what?'' asks  &UR; Flash &LR; 
 &UR; Gordon &LR; . The message gives a 95-cent 900 number.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Frank Williams &LR; , intrigued by Tuesday's San Francisco
Chronicle headline ``Army's Rules on Dating Under Attack,'' was
hoping to learn ``how to kiss properly and fire a gun at the same
time.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In Bodega Bay last week,  &UR; Jim Adams  &LR; bought a 49er scarecrow
he'd spotted on a woman's lawn and was carting it away when he came
upon former coach  &UR; George Seifert &LR; , chatting with some fishermen.
Seifert opined that the scarecrow looked just like some of the team
members.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vacation snapshots:  &UR; Keith Howell &LR; , just back from Madagascar,
faxes the image of a 1994 stamp that pictures  &UR; Bill &LR; 
 &UR; Clinton &LR;  with  &UR; Louis Armstrong &LR; , both playing their instruments;
 &UR; B.S. &LR; , just back from Miami, says  &UR; Gianni Versace &LR; 's house on
Collins Avenue has become a tourist attraction, with many
sightseers stopping to pose for jolly holiday photographs.
</P>
</TEXT>
