<HEADER>
A9146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNDAY-UPDATE-BUDGET-     07-29 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-UPDATE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has moved the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Aug. 2,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (`e' category)
</P>
<P>
   FEATURE STORIES
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-FILMS (Hong Kong) _ As recently as eight years ago,
Hong Kong was second only to Hollywood in exporting movies, and
Hong Kong films were among the most exciting things happening in
cinema. Talented directors were casting charismatic stars in movies
that were by turns stylishly violent, breathtakingly magical,
beautifully tender or silly kung-fu comedies. Slowly, Hong
Kong-style art direction, action choreography and even plot
elements began to appear in American films. Today, audiences here
are flocking to Hollywood films, especially ones filled with
special effects, and ignoring ones made in Hong Kong. By Neil
Strauss. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM-DIRECTORS (Undated) _ Attendance at American art museums
is skyrocketing, but upstairs in the director's office, the desk
chair is often unoccupied and an eerie silence prevails. At last
count, there were about 20 openings for directors at prominent
museums, and trustees are insisting, with only partial
exaggeration, that they can't find anyone for the job. By Deborah
Solomon. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   FILMS and VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   RYAN-FILM-VIOLENCE (Undated) _ Though the landmark film event
that is Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan'' opened last
weekend to strong attendance and critical cartwheels, it also set
off a flurry of talk-show trepidations. Worries spread about the
violence level in this already famously harrowing World War II
epic. By Janet Maslin. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BENOIT-JACQUOT-FILMS (New York) _ Benoit Jacquot is not about to
write his autobiography. ``I'm not interested in recounting my life
through my films,'' the famously reticent French director said
recently. ``I'd rather they teach me something about my life.'' His
presence in his work is close to transparent: a finely tuned eye
and intelligence, focused on the intricate, oblique entanglements
of human beings. By Leslie Camhi. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MINNIE-DRIVER-FILMS (New York) _ Minnie Driver is equally at
home telling an off-color joke or spelling Aeschylus correctly on a
crossword puzzle, as she did recently in a rare moment of repose at
a midtown Manhattan hotel. The British actress, 27, who has made a
career for herself in the United States in hit movies like ``Big
Night,'' ``Grosse Pointe Blank'' and ``Good Will Hunting,''
displays a dizzying array of attributes: she's intellectual and
earthy, statuesque and spirited. By Laura Winters. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   FILMS4KIDS (Undated) _ Some film reviews and their suitability
for children. This week: ``Mark Twain's America in 3-D''; ``The
Parent Trap''; ``There's Something About Mary''; ``Mafia!''
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   THEATER
</P>
<P>
   VIEWPOINTS-DANCE (Undated) _ Invented in the 1970s by two dance
choreographers, Mary Overlie and Wendall Beavers, Viewpoints has
recently become part of the contentious debate currently going on
in America about actor training. In the last five years, there has
been an explosion of interest in new ways to train American actors.
Some people in the theater believe the itch to explore different
theories is a reaction to the longtime dominance of the Method,
preached by the controversial teacher Lee Strasberg, who died in
1982. By Rachel Shteir. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-SYMPHONY (Undated) _ Many things about the Russian
Symphony Orchestra seem to resonate of formative youth. The
ensemble was organized just six years ago, and the average age of
its members is 25. But to judge from a collection of exceptionally
well-produced recordings, the sapling Russian Symphony might be as
old as its musical roots. Indeed, the youth of its players is
belied by an intensity, insight and precision that usually come
with more years on stage than most of these musicians have lived.
By Lawrence B. Johnson. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   DON-GIOVANNI-OPERA (Aix-En-Provence, France) _ Peter Brook's
production of ``Don Giovanni'' is at the Festival Internationale
d'Art Lyrique this summer. Brook gives us not much of a production
at all: a few benches on the big courtyard stage of the
Archbishop's Palace, the Don in a vanilla suit and Panama hat, his
colleagues in street clothes and party dresses. Yet Mozart has been
treated exceptionally well: not with visual effects or theatrical
coups that draw us into the events, but by an attempt to look at
the opera's people from the inside out. By Bernard Holland.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ST.-FRANCIS-OPERA (Undated) _ In the 15 years since its
premiere, Olivier Messiaen's opera ``St. Francois d'Assise'' has,
like a classic of older times, gone on growing through repeated
performances. By Paul Griffiths. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   POP MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ-DRUMMER (New York) _ In barely a decade, the percussionist
Leon Parker has gone from stints with the pianist Kenny Barron to a
chair in the pianist Jacky Terrasson's fine trio to a major label
contract. By Adam Shatz. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-COMPOSERS (New York) _ The last quarter century has seen
the emergence of female composers as serious professionals. Opera
and the bigger forms of `serious music' require both practical
experience and real opportunity to learn (and earn) from
performance, as Ellen Taaffe Zwilich, the Pulitzer Prize winning
composer of large scale instrumental works, points out. It has been
easier for women to compose pop. But successful women are often
more readily co-opted by commercial forces than men. By Albert
Innaurato. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-FILMS-ANTIQUES (Undated) _ Hollywood-crazed collectors
have long been willing to pay handsomely for original props like
Dorothy's red shoes. But reproductions of collectibles? Chronicle
Books, a medium-size San Francisco publishing house, is betting
that there is a market out there for such items, and somewhat
closer to earth than the Tatooine desert. Chronicle has just issued
``Star Wars Scrapbook: The Essential Collection,'' by Stephen J.
Sansweet, a former reporter for The Wall Street Journal who is
revered by other collectors for having one of the world's largest
collections of ``Star Wars'' memorabilia. By James Barron. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ART
</P>
<P>
   SHOCK-ART (New York) _ With art, there are three forms of shock:
the shock of recognition, the shock at something merely appalling
and the shock of the new. By Michael Kimmelman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   ITALIAN-GESTURES-TV (Undated) _ In the documentary ``The
Italian-Americans II: A Beautiful Song,'' which has its premiere on
Tuesday at 8 p.m. on WLIW, Nick Stellino, a New York cookbook
author of Italian descent, describes the way he and family members
used hand gestures when speaking to one another. By Warren Berger.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
