<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDSUPPORT-COX     07-29 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDSUPPORT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parental Bounty Hunters
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Candy Williams used to hound her ex-husband about
child support. Even so, the money sometimes didn't come.
</P>
<P>
   Then in May 1996, the 28-year-old Decatur hairstylist saw a
television ad for Child Support Network, a collection agency in
Phoenix, and gave the company a call. Within a month CSN had begun
collecting payments.
</P>
<P>
   Now Williams gets monthly checks for $162.50 like clockwork.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a catch.
</P>
<P>
   Like other private agencies that specialize in tracking down
deadbeat parents, CSN takes a hefty cut of what it collects _ as
much as 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Williams doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Them taking out something, to me, is better than me not
getting anything at all,'' she says. ``They took the pressure off
of me. I don't have to even question him about whether he's going
to send me anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is one of many parents who have resorted to collection
agencies to enforce child support orders. Local governments have
departments to do the job, but with huge caseloads and a limited
number of workers, they end up letting many nonpaying parents
slide. In DeKalb County, where Williams lives, child support
prosecutors have up to 1,500 cases apiece.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, collection agencies take only cases that will
likely turn a profit for them. Austin, Texas-based Child Support
Enforcement Co. won't even bother with monthly payments, limiting
its services to tracking parents who owe at least $5,000 in back
support. Its collectors handle no more than 350 clients apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The collectors pursue nonpaying parents with the diligence of
bounty hunters.
</P>
<P>
   They conduct background checks to determine where the nonpaying
parent works, how much he earns, what kind of car he drives, what
assets he holds and where he banks. Armed with that information,
they approach the wayward parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we make that first phone call we don't have to listen to
the nonsense excuses,'' says Casey Hoffman, CSE's founder and
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work the cases ... consistently. We work them efficiently.
You really don't have to be a rocket scientist to determine why we
are successful,'' adds Hoffman, who ran the Texas child support
enforcement agency before founding CSE.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Jacobson, president of CSN, says his company locates 90
percent of the nonpaying parents in its case files and collects
from half of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tenacious,'' Jacobson says. ``It's not a matter of if
they're going to pay, it's when they're going to pay.'' When the
company fails, he says, it's because a parent has no job, no
unemployment benefits and no property.
</P>
<P>
   He cites another metro Atlanta case: In February, a Stone
Mountain woman complained that her son's father had given her only
two $150 checks in the past 15 years. Three months later, CSN sent
her a check for $27,000.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone's applauding, however.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Collins, coordinator of the Georgia chapter of the
Association for Children for Enforcement of Support, thinks parents
are better off collecting through the government, no matter how
long it takes. She thinks collection agencies are a rip-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not concerned about the children. If they were, they
would only charge 5 (percent) to 10 percent,'' Collins says.
</P>
<P>
   (That criticism might also apply to parents who get behind in
their payments until collectors force the issue. For his part,
though, James Williams doesn't seem to mind that his ex-wife
receives only $162.50 of the $250 he sends CSN each month for his
son.
</P>
<P>
   (``I don't have a problem with it,'' he says. ``That's what she
chose to do, so she'll have to live with it.'')
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Collins' solution is that, though governments
do in fact charge only small fees to enforce child support orders,
the wheels of officialdom move slowly. In 1996, more than $1.2
billion in uncollected support was owed to 788,000 Georgia kids,
according to the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.
Nationally that year, 30 million children were owed more than $41
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has enacted several recent measures to make it easier
for parents to collect. One mandates that states take monthly
payments directly from a noncustodial parent's paycheck, even if
there is no history of late or delinquent payments. The only
exceptions: if both parties agree to waive the deduction, or if it
would be in the child's best interest to collect the money some
other way.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent law requires businesses with more than 25
employees to put the names of all new hires in a nationwide
computer system, making it harder for noncustodial parents to hide
their income.
</P>
<P>
   And a federal law that went into effect this year requires
states to enforce child support orders granted in other states. In
the past, if a noncustodial parent moved to another state, a new
court order had to be issued from that state.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the new enforcement tools, 80 percent of clients who
turn to government to collect child support never receive a dime,
creating an opportunity for private collection agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies seem to have friends in Congress, which is
dominated by Republicans, many of whom support privatization of
government functions. CSE's Hoffman got a favorable reception in
May when he testified before a House Ways and Means subcommittee,
arguing that businesses such as his should have better access to
government records on nonpaying parents.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Johnson, managing attorney of the Clayton, DeKalb and
Gwinnett offices of Atlanta Legal Aid Society, thinks that for some
parents, private collectors fill a need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have occasionally told clients you might as well try one of
those places,'' Johnson says. ``I view that as sort of a last
resort, because I think in a perfect world a person shouldn't have
to give up a third of the money that was awarded to their kids just
to get it collected.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
