<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REJECTS BID TO KILL SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House turned back another attempt to kill the
international space station Wednesday, with 323 members voting to
continue funding the NASA-run project, now costing more than 12
times the original $8 billion estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Only 109 members voted to eliminate the $2.1 billion budgeted
next year for the orbiting laboratory. But many more members who
ended up voting against the amendment that would have killed it
said they were running out of patience with the cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   The project includes 16 nations, spearheaded by the United
States and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to President Clinton, Rep. Kevin Brady, R-Texas,
complained about Russia's lack of a substantial financial
commitment and its failure thus far to build and deliver on time
the propulsion module for the project. He called on the president
to support the removal of Russia as a full partner in the space
station, saying that ``inaction'' by NASA and the administration in
addressing the problem would only increase the costs to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   When it was authorized in 1984 by President Reagan, the cost of
the space station was estimated at $8 billion. Today the estimate
is $98 billion and growing, according to critics such as Sen. Dale
Bumpers, D-Ark., and Rep. Tim Roemer, D-Ind. Both men have been
offering annual amendments for several years in attempts to kill
the project, which supporters insist is needed to conduct important
``medical and disease-curing research'' and other work that would
lead to advances in new technologies and products.
</P>
<P>
   A killer amendment offered by Bumpers was defeated by the Senate
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   During debate in the House on the project, Rep. Nick Lampson,
D-Texas, summed up the view of supporters by arguing that Americans
are willing to spend the money necessary to continue manned space
flight and research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe it to millions of Americans who could benefit from
future medical advances to continue funding, rather than gutting,
the international space station,'' Lampson told his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, however, say that the same research supporters talk
about can be accomplished just as well on Earth They say the cost
overruns would be better spent on more earth-bound research
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody had told us that the space station was going to
cost this much, we wouldn't have voted for it,'' said Rep. Barney
Frank, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
