<SLUG> BC-BBO-PLAYERS-SUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL UNION GETS BOOST FROM SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a proposal that would help reduce the possibility of a
strike, Major League Baseball players would, for the first time
since 1922, have the right to sue owners under legislation unveiled
in the US Senate Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement among Senate leaders and Major League Baseball
owners and players would be a major change in baseball's
controversial 76-year-old antitrust exemption. It would put
baseball players on the same footing as athletes in other major
sports when it comes to the ultimate legal recourse in settling
disputes with owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress may not be able to solve every problem or heal
baseball's self-inflicted wounds,'' said Senator Patrick J. Leahy,
a Vermont Democrat. ``But we can pass legislation that will declare
that professional baseball can no longer operate outside the law as
it applies to others.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement on the proposal became possible when both the
players' union and commissioner Bud Selig sent senators a letter of
agreement on the proposed language in the legislation. It was also
boosted when it was agreed among the parties that the minor
leagues, represented by the National Association of Professional
Baseball Leagues Inc., would continue to be exempt from antitrust
laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress adopts this agreement,'' said Donald M. Fehr,
executive director of the Major League Baseball Players
Association, ``it will be a significant step toward minimizing the
labor discord and disruptions in play that have plagued our
national pastime.''
</P>
<P>
   Players have long complained that they had no leverage if the
owners moved, as they did in 1994, to unilaterally impose the
provisions of an expired contract. In both the National Football
League and the National Basketball Association, players can sue
under antitrust law when such conditions are imposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball players have never had that,'' said Steve Fehr, chief
legal counsel to the Major League Baseball Players Association.
``Not having that recourse has exacerbated the tensions many of us
have always felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Fehr, Donald's brother, said that in 1994, for example, if the
baseball owners had succeeded in breaking the union, the players
could then have taken the owners to court under antitrust law, with
fairly easy access to remedies like injunctions and back-to-work
orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is enacted to law, this is a big step forward,'' Steve
Fehr said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee has been considering changes in
baseball's antitrust exemption since the bitterly divisive players'
strike of 1994 that resulted in the cancellation of the World
Series for the first time _ a strike that resulted in lower
attendance and television viewership, which baseball continues to
recoup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear to me that the existence of an antitrust exemption
contributed negatively to those developments,'' Leahy said. ``That
was a low point in the history of baseball and one from which it is
only now recovering.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Orrin Hatch, a Utah Republican who chairs the Judiciary
Committee and announced the accord in Washington with Leahy, has
for years pushed for changes in the exemption. Hatch has sponsored
the so-called Curt Flood Act, named for the late major leaguer who
pressed an assault on Major League Baseball's reserve clause, which
had bound players to teams for life.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed agreement would remove one of the last obstacles to
passage of the legislation, which has been pending for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As fans are returning to the ballparks, they deserve to know
that players will be on the field, not mired in labor disputes,''
Hatch said. ``I am pleased that Congress will, it now appears, be
able to help guarantee that this is the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch and Leahy, the ranking Democrat on the committee, said
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi has indicated that
he favors the proposal, and they expressed confidence Congress will
pass it in September after returning from the summer recess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
