<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERBALL-GREENWICH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TONY GREENWICH, A WEALTH OF COMPLAINTS AGAINST POWERBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENWICH, Conn. _ In a tony town where many residents have
already won life's lottery, a Powerball frenzy has drawn flocks of
out-of-state optimists bearing not just traffic jams and litter
piles, but a world that locals say has gone from novel to scary.
</P>
<P>
   As the first Interstate exit and the first train station over
the Connecticut border for New Yorkers hoping to buy their slim
chance at the world's largest jackpot, Greenwich became ground zero
this week for a pastime that is thoroughly alien to most well-to-do
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until this morning, I thought it was PowerBOWL,'' Lisa C.
Gentil confessed as she headed for her architect's office in her
silver Mercedes-Benz sport-utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Greenwich is a place where the wrong side of the
tracks means new money instead of old. Many of the taxis are
Mercedes-Benzes, wallpaper is sold not in a store but in a gallery,
and the main drag is regulated by white-gloved officers instead of
stop lights.
</P>
<P>
   And then came Powerball. The six-number tickets are sold in the
District of Columbia, Connecticut and 19 other states _ but not in
New York or New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Each night this week, the boutique-lined streets of Greenwich
have been packed with clunkers from the boroughs _ with some
drivers going the wrong way, forcing the Land Rovers to screech and
dodge. The previously pristine sidewalks now resemble the floor of
a theater after a double feature, and the restaurants have been
empty because regulars have been afraid to go out or have not be
able to find a place to park. After the lottery machines are shut
off at 11 p.m., scalpers roam Greenwich Avenue, hawking their
tickets with come-ons like, ``How many? Got plenty.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, in the hours before the drawing for the
quarter-billion-dollar jackpot, which if unclaimed would balloon
further, the town fathers wrote to state officials to ask that
Greenwich be allowed to secede from Powerball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Town of Greenwich has been under siege from an
uncontrollable force,'' First Selectman Tom Ragland, who is the
equivalent of mayor, wrote to state lottery officials. ``If there
is not a declared winner, the Town of Greenwich is respectfully
requesting the Connecticut Lottery Corporation to shut down all of
the lottery machines in Greenwich no later than 7 a.m. Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   If the state refused, Ragland said he would shut the game down
himself, using his emergency powers in the interest of what he
called ``the health, safety and welfare of the residents of the
Town of Greenwich.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there has been cause for concern among town officials.
Town police said they responded this week to 300 reports of
disorderly conduct, plus a smattering of people urinating in public
or causing fender-benders by gawking at the Powerball lines. A
roving squad of 15 officers has moved from store to store at
closing time to make sure the disappointed people who were left in
line kept their disappointment to themselves. When a shoving match
broke out at Greenwich Cigar and Stationery, sirens wailed and two
dozen officers rushed to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The toll is fiscal as well as emotional. Town officials have
estimated Powerball has cost Greenwich nearly $100,000, most of it
for overtime for police officers and sanitation workers. The
Greenwich Police Department said every one of its 158 officers was
assigned to Powerball duty, with many working double shifts. The
Connecticut State Police sent 20 troopers to help keep order. Gov.
John G. Rowland announced Wednesday night that the state would
reimburse Greenwich for what he called its ``extraordinary costs,''
with details to be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   But it is very likely that the town will have some time to
simmer down. Powerball officials said 94 percent of the possible
combinations were represented among the 200 million tickets sold,
making it likely that a winner was among them. Officials of the
Multi-State Lottery Association, which runs Powerball, said they
would know by early Thursday whether anyone had won. If not, the
jackpot would roll over to Saturday night and would grow by tens of
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Greenwich's Powerball problem is not going away.
Powerball officials say their computer models indicate that under a
new game design introduced in November, a jackpot of at least $250
million can be expected to come up every two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   And very much against its will, Greenwich, population 58,000,
has become the Powerball capital of America: Connecticut was the
top state in sales for this drawing, and Connecticut's top eight
Powerball retailers are all in Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   The Powerball invasion may be the most action Greenwich has seen
since the Revolutionary War, when British troops raided homes and
farms for seven deadly years. With the construction of a rail line
in 1848, the town became a summer resort for rich New Yorkers, who
built huge estates and entertained lavishly. The population swelled
again after World War II with corporate types who made the town
their home.
</P>
<P>
   According to the 1990 Census, the per-person income of $46,000
in Greenwich was more than twice the figure for the state. Now,
residents say they fear becoming known as ``the North Bronx.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can these people ignore it when it's $20 million, and then
be so retarded as to line up here in the 98-degree heat?'' asked
Melissa J. Bariere, 33, the owner of a furniture gallery called
Painted. ``I just want to drive by and scream, `You're not going to
win!'''
</P>
<P>
   Few residents of Greenwich admit to playing the game. No one,
though, is more eager for a winner to be declared. Curvin O'Rielly,
an advertising consultant who lives and works in Greenwich, was
approached by one of the ticket buyers flooding the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said in a New Jersey accent, `Where's the nearest Powerball
outlet?''' O'Rielly recalled. ``I said `Exit 14' _ way up the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles F. Strutt, the executive director of the Multi-State
Lottery Association, which is based in Iowa, acknowledged that
Greenwich was in a tough situation, although he did point out, ``A
wealthy population wanting a sleepy town next to New York City is
an odd mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Strutt said the association's board would meet soon to consider
caps on jackpots, self-service lottery terminals and other ways to
tame Powerball-mania.
</P>
<P>
   Such gestures are unlikely to quell the Powerball backlash in
Greenwich, however. Signs urging residents to ``Boycott Powerball
Stores'' have sprouted around town, and a State Representative and
the Chamber of Commerce held a packed forum at Town Hall tonight so
business owners could vent their fury.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Trilnick, the owner of Cafe Rue, a French-Argentine
restaurant, sent a call-to-arms to fellow merchants that included
the declaration: ``Invaders from neighboring states are swarming
our streets. They are tireless and determined, overwhelming our
public servants with their persistence.''
</P>
<P>
   These desperate times call for desperate measures. Until last
week, the Police Department would dispatch an officer to
investigate a stolen lawnmower, broken window or toppled mailbox.
Because of the Powerball strain, the police have begun asking
residents to go to the station to lodge such reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2002EDT &QL; 
