<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMAS-LAWYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS DEFENDS CONSERVATIVE STANCE TO LAWYERS GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS _ Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas, in an
extraodinary, sweeping attack on his critics, defended Wednesday
his right to hold conservative views, and dismissed as ``silly''
the idea that his opinions are molded by some ``ideological Pied
Piper'' among his white court colleages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come to state I'm a man, free to think for myself,'' Thomas
said in a speech to the nation's largest association of black
lawyers and judges, the National Bar Association. ``I'm a judge not
consigned to assert the opinions of others.''
</P>
<P>
   The justice, who appeared at the convention despite the open
hostility of some of its most prominent members, also made an
emotional appeal for reconciliation between the association and the
nation's most prominent black jurist and conservative _ Clarence
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it time to move on...to realize that being angry with me
is no solution?'' Thomas said. ``Isn't it time that we respect
ourselves and each other as we have demanded respect from others?''
</P>
<P>
   But even as he sought an end to animosity, Thomas offered an
unapologetic defense of his controversial court opinions on
affirmative action and other subjects as the product of his
reasoning rather than his race.
</P>
<P>
   He emphatically rejected the notion that ``I have no right to
think the way I do because I'm black.'' And he caustically wondered
if some who criticize his views have ever read his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but wonder whether some of my critics can read,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Describing a political climate where ``some go so far as to all
but define each of us by race and to establish the range of our
thinking and our opinions by our color,'' Thomas said he had long
been free of ``racial identity problems'' and had no need for
blacks or ``anyone telling me who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said some whites, in particular, had ``elevated
condescension to an art form by advancing a monolithic view of
blacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly offensive in that regard, Thomas said, is the
notion that he doesn't think for himself but merely echoes the
views of the white conservative justices, particularly Antonin
Scalia, whom he frequently votes with.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stench of racial inferiority still confounds my olfactory
nerves,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, only the second black man ever to serve on the high
court, did not disarm his audience _ there was little applause but
also few boos. He did, however, earn the grudging respect of some.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spoke from the heart,'' said National Bar Association
President Randy Jones, a federal prosecutor in San Diego. ``He's a
man who's not afraid to come into the lion's den and face his
detractors and critics. I think we all have to respect him for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   And Thomas, who joined the court in 1991, did provoke a few
chuckles when he noted that the Supreme Court is ``not infallible,
just final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not one of us can claim infallibility, even from the
overwhelming advantage of hindsight. This makes it all the more
important that fallible ideas be examined in a resonable manner and
not as some doctrinal or racial heresy.''
</P>
<P>
   His appearance at a luncheon meeting of nearly 1,000 black
lawyers, judges and law professors had triggered opposition from
the time the event was announced. After an effort to disinvite him
failed, some were believed prepared to walk out on his address.
</P>
<P>
   Few did. Before his speech, hecklers in the ornate lobby of the
Peabody Hotel were making placards branding Thomas as a
``traitor.''
</P>
<P>
   As Thomas was finishing his lunch, he heard Judge Shelvin Hall
of Chicago,the new chairwoman of the group's judicial conference,
say that the National Bar Association was ``offended'' by the
presence of a guest who ``would willfully destroy the purposes'' of
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., who was murdered a few blocks from the
convention hotel 30 years ago, and Thurgood Marshall, Thomas' black
predecessor on the court. Referring to the invitation to Thomas,
she said, ``The NBA has broken my heart and the heart of the NBA
has been broken.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an effort to defuse the situation, D'Army Bailey, a local
judge who originally extended the invitation to Thomas, drew a
metaphor from Memphis in the days following the King assassination.
In the midst of racial turbulence, he said, ``We learned the
importance of talking to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey invited those who might want to leave to do so before
Thomas began his speech. Only a half-dozen departed. The vast
majority who stayed in the ballroom gave Thomas a respectful
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The culture in Washington encourages ``the tendency to
personalize differences,'' Thomas told the group, ``and I have been
singled out for particularly bilious and venomous assault.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he welcomed ``constructive'' arguments, but warned that
``criticism of the court goes beyond the bounds of civil debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas did not address his opposition to affirmative action
except to say that ``any effort, policy or program'' founded on the
presumption that ``blacks are inferior is a non-starter with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he elaborate on any of ther other positions,
particularly on criminal justice topics, that have drawn the ire of
much of the black legal community.
</P>
<P>
   But he did object strenuously to those who took his dissent in
one case to imply that ``I supported the beating of prisoners.''
Thomas said his opponents had to be ``either illiterate or fraught
with malice'' to make that argument.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who rarely makes public appearances, described his
passage from an angry black militant in the days following King's
death to become a jurist embracing conservative beliefs he once
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   He said he appreciated ``the comforts of racial solidarity,''
the feeling by blacks that they must stick together in the face of
bigotry and ``frustrations with the system.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has moved to his own destiny, Thomas said. Referring to a
fictional character in Richard Wright's novel, ``Native Son,''
Thomas said he had ``contained his anger'' as a black man to avoid
``suffering the fate of Bigger Thomas,'' the novel's protagonist
who is consumed by racial animosity and dies in a rampage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
