<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NIGERIA-OPPORTUNITY     07-29 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NIGERIA-OPPORTUNITY-ART-847&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARBLE MOGUL CATERS TO NIGERIAN CAPITAL'S ELITE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photo note)   (ART ADV: Photo of Theodore Luttwak is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria _ ``Look, the human rights here in Nigeria are
terrible,'' Theodore Luttwak says, ``but the opportunities are just
fantastic. Tell me, where else in the world do you have so much
money?''
</P>
<P>
   Good question. Abuja, Nigeria's capital-under-construction, is
full of the whiff of oil money, and not just at the exclusive golf
course said to absorb 25 percent of the city's water supply just to
keep the greens smooth. Luttwak _ ``just call me Teddy'' _ is out
to get his share of the $10 billion that Nigeria earns each year
from oil.
</P>
<P>
   His logic is simple enough. The military officers who have ruled
Africa's most populous nation for two decades, and siphoned off a
good share of its oil revenue, are busy building vast mansions on
their Abuja real estate. They want gold-inlaid basins for their
bathrooms and Jacuzzi baths, sophisticated water purifiers and huge
quantities of Italian marble that Luttwak is busy importing.
</P>
<P>
   ``One man from the national petroleum company just gave me
$100,000 only for the marble in his house,'' Luttwak said. ``My
company started three years ago, and I'm now the major importer of
Italian marble. This is Africa's land of opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow it is a surprise to find the older brother of Edward
Luttwak, a former defense policy adviser to the Reagan
administration and a senior fellow at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies in Washington, hustling imported marble in
Abuja, Nigeria. But then this place is full of surprises.
</P>
<P>
   There is, for example, the National Human Rights Commission _
``created by presidential decree.'' It is just off Sani Abacha Way,
a prominent avenue named after the late dictator whose flouting of
human rights, including the wholesale imprisonment of journalists
and execution of writer Ken Saro-Wiwa, turned Nigeria into an
international pariah.
</P>
<P>
   Or, not far from Luttwak's premises, the Sani Abacha Foundation,
a palatial enterprise whose aim, its prospectus says, is ``to
immortalize the name, ideas and achievement of Gen. Sani Abacha in
relation to his efforts in promoting peace, unity, conflict
resolution and the universal brotherhood of mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Abacha plundered Nigeria with single-minded zeal during his
nearly five years in power before his abrupt death, apparently from
a heart attack, in June.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Maryam, was recently stopped trying to leave the
country on a flight bound for Saudi Arabia with eight suitcases
full of cash. Western officials estimate that the late general may
have more than $3 billion stashed away in overseas bank accounts,
the sort of sum that Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire took decades to
accumulate.
</P>
<P>
   All this, for Teddy Luttwak, is no surprise. He deals every day
with ``the Nigerian factor'' _ the bribes needed to get anything
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abacha was tremendously corrupt, more than than any mafia you
can imagine,'' he said. ``The general took a share in every
contract, everybody, everything. He was a ruthless warrior. But the
fact is, you probably do need a soft-spoken dictator here.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Transylvania in 1939, Luttwak has a scar on his head
from the years of Nazi oppression. A postwar move to Italy brought
fortune and fame in the plastics industry, notably in the
production of plastic beach balls, but the good times ended when he
was kidnapped and held for ransom in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   While his brother Edward made his way in Israel and the United
States, Luttwak, an Italian citizen, eventually washed up on
Nigeria's shores, where he has been wheeling and dealing for two
decades. A day spent at his company Pated _ ``mirror polished
granites and marbles at very, very, very, very competitive prices''
_ is instructive in the ways of this country.
</P>
<P>
   As Luttwak, sweat glistening on his brow, blue eyes gleaming,
rushes around his premises looking for a driver to make a huge
marble delivery to the northern city of Kano, in walks Ahmud
Agberankhe. He is 34 and has a university degree in physics. He
works for Nigerian Radio for a monthly salary of about $40.
</P>
<P>
   Agberankhe's assignment for the day is to work on a jingle for
an advertisement for Pated, which is looking to hire salesmen to be
paid on commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1980s a graduate like me could have a car,'' Agberankhe
lamented as he played a proposed jingle focused on the ``very,
very, very, very competitive prices'' for Luttwak. ``But now it's
difficult to make ends meet. You have the knowledge, but there are
no openings. If you strive, you should be given a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   There are millions of downwardly mobile Nigerians like
Agberankhe whose chances of making it have evaporated as this
potentially rich country has succumbed to sweeping decay,
mismanagement and corruption on a scale so vast that it has made
people despair of a fair reward for a fair day's work. Per capita
income here is now a quarter of what it was a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why work for a pittance when you see a military man making $10
million a month because he has the power to award contracts?'' an
architect in Luttwak's office said. ``What's the motivation?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The architect was particularly unhappy because he had just spent
a substantial share of his monthly salary of about $400 on
black-market gasoline, often the only kind available in a country
that is one of the world's largest producers of oil and the
fifth-largest supplier to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Luttwak, 59, is used to bending the rules to get ahead in his
adopted land. He once spent several days in prison for refusing to
pay a bribe and has learned his lesson. He has a 28-year-old
Nigerian wife named Patience, who, formally speaking, is the owner
of the company. Under Nigerian law, majority ownership of
corporations must be in Nigerian hands.
</P>
<P>
   Handing out a Pated bill for about $100,000 to a messenger, he
let drop a few crumpled Nigerian naira notes. ``We are of course
aware of the `Nigerian factor,' and please tell your boss that we
are waiting for payment as soon as possible,'' Luttwak said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking on in admiration, and mild dismay, was Marino D'Ermo, a
major Italian marble producer, visiting Nigeria to examine the
business possibilities. ``Teddy is fantastic,'' D'Ermo said, ``and
the potential in this town is crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the town in question is supposed to be home to a
democratic government by May 1999, under commitments made this
month by Nigeria's military rulers. If so, the boom in
marble-bedecked mansions could evaporate, but Luttwak is not
alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   As he sees it, a northern, Muslim ruling caste controls the
country through the military and is unlikely to be budged.
Disciplined, God-fearing and determined, this caste, for Luttwak,
stands in contrast to what he sees as an impossibly unruly south.
He is unconvinced that change is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, he is wasting no time. ``There is no tomorrow at
this company!'' he shouts at a worker who has made the mistake of
saying something will be done tomorrow. ``Tomorrow does not
exist.''
</P>
<P>
   To a sign maker, Luttwak complains that his proposals are not
gargantuan enough. ``I want this corner of Abuja to be called Pated
Marbles Plaza,'' he said. ``Whatever goes up has to be enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria has huge reserves of marble and granite. But, as in the
oil industry, mismanagement has led the domestic industry to ruin.
State-owned factories are idle. So Nigeria imports marble and
granite, just as it imports petroleum. And disaster for the
majority translates into opportunity for a few.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
