<SLUG> BC-MA-TAX-CUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS ANNOUNCE AN ADDITIONAL $200 MILLION TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Take an election year and a brimming state economy and
the tax cuts keep on coming.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders Wednesday announced a surprise $200 million
one-time tax break to give another $50 back to every taxpayer in
the state, according to preliminary calculations.
</P>
<P>
   The latest round follows a $160 million reduction already agreed
upon, and a historic $770 million taxcut expected to be signed into
law Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At a hastily called press conference late Wednesday, House
Speaker Thomas M. Finneran and Senate President Thomas F.
Birmingham said they had just struck a deal on how to spend the
$1.1 billion state revenue surplus and decided to take a ``blended
approach'' to ``sop up extra cash.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan: To give another $200 million back to taxpayers; put
$60 million in a so-called best and brightest education fund for
teacher signing bonuses and other professional development; add
another $150 million to the state's rainy day fund; and spend an
unspecified amount out-of-pocket on capital improvements across the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we'll look back on these days as being quite
responsibly led,'' Finneran said. As for the surplus, he said it
``makes little or no sense to hold onto it when it was productively
earned'' by taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear last night whether Acting Governor Paul Cellucci
will sign off on whole agreement or whether either branch would be
willing to override a veto after the legislative session adjourns
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci spokeswoman Ilene Hoffer said the acting governor has
line-item veto power over leftover budget matters, from which
Wednesday's proposal came, and he could veto spending items while
approving tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a step in the right direction but it's not enough,''
Hoffer said. ``He will have his veto pen poised to veto excess
spending and get even more money back to the taxpayers...he's going
to fight for the whole enchilada.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, lawmakers passed the largest budget in state
history which includes the $770 million tax cut, expected to be
signed by Cellucci today. That tax cut will double the exemption
for personal income taxes -- saving between $131 for a single filer
to $262 for joint filers -- and cuts in half the 12 percent tax
rate on interest and dividend income.
</P>
<P>
   This additional $200 million tax cut could add another $50 in
exemptions to single filers and $100 to joint filers on this year's
tax returns, according to what leaders called ``back of the
envelope'' calculations.
</P>
<P>
   The previous plan also increases the size of the stabilization
or rainy day fund from 5 percent of current revenues to 7.5
percent, allowing reserves to grow from $950 million to a maximum
of $1.42 billion. At Wednesday's announcement, Finneran and
Birmingham said they had allocated $150 million from the surplus to
go into that fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every part of the Commonwealth will benefit,'' said Stanley
Rosenberg, chairman of the Senate Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He said the state will pay cash -- rather than borrow money --
to fix up tourist destinations, cultural centers, environmental
retreats and historical sites.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham said more of the surplus will also be used to pay for
environmental cleanup legislation known as Brownfields, a tax cut
for the insurance industry, and other ``boring items'' such as
collective bargaining issues.
</P>
<P>
   State Treasurer Joseph D. Malone, a Republican gubernatorial
candidate, is asking for the full $1.1 billion to be returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're told this surplus is better off in the hands of state
bureaucrats than in the hands of the people who earned it. I will
always fight to make sure surpluses get back into the hands of the
people of Massachusetts, where it belongs,'' Malone said. ``This is
people's money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be someone like Joe Malone who will burp and
say `more,''' Birmingham said. ``We are taking a more rational,
more reasonable, more blended approach. There are other needs that
need to be addressed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
