<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAWLEY PLAINTIFF GETS ONLY FRACTION OF DAMAGES HE SOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ After an eight-month trial that revived the
racially divisive Tawana Brawley case, a Dutchess County jury
Wednesday set $345,000 as the total damages that Steven Pagones, a
white former prosecutor, can recover from three advisers to Miss
Brawley, a black teenager who said Pagones abducted and raped her
in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The sum was sharply lower than the $150 million Pagones had
sought in the damages phase of the case. The same jurors had
decided July 13 that he had been defamed in 10 instances by the
advisers, the Rev. Al Sharpton, C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's award was approximately what Pagones has said he
spent waging what became an emblematic struggle by a man to clear
his name.
</P>
<P>
   Although in their original verdict the jurors found that
Sharpton slandered Pagones more times than the other two
defendants, in Wednesday's decision they assessed lower damages
against him. Two jurors said they thought Sharpton had been duped
and that he did admirable work.
</P>
<P>
   They set Sharpton's total damages at $65,000. Maddox's damages
were $95,000. Mason's damages were $185,000.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews after the verdict, three of the jurors adopted a
tone of reconciliation, saying they had respect for all the
participants in the case and several took issue with the media's
portrait of the trial as an unruly circus.
</P>
<P>
   Several jurors said Pagones had been wronged, but they did not
want to hurt the three advisers, who had portrayed their fight on
behalf of Ms. Brawley as a singular battle in the decades-long
civil rights struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors said they had taken a cue in settling on the amount
from the message that Pagones gave them in 25 days of testimony .
``He did not want to destroy them,'' said jury foreman Patrick
Cody, a warehouse worker. ``He wanted them held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve said it himself, he didn't want to hurt these guys,''
said Mark Urbin, another juror at a news conference, with Pagones
watching from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial Pagones had repeated his version of a legal
mantra _ ``it's not about money'' _ to summarize his position that
he was taking on the advisers because they had crossed the bounds
of civilized behavior with accusations that he said came out of the
blue and altered his life. In their remarks Wednesday, the jurors
said they agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones appeared dazed after the verdict and he did not display
the celebratory mood he showed after the July 13 verdict. But he
said the jurors had been right. ``I didn't want to destroy anybody,
ironically, because they didn't care about destroying me.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said, his long battle was over. ``It's time to heal. It's
time to move on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The three jurors who spoke at a news conference here said they
did not know what happened to Miss Brawley when she disappeared for
four days in November 1987, but they said it was clear that Pagones
had not attacked her.
</P>
<P>
   But the jurors, who were never told by the court of the damages
that Pagones sought, said they were surprised when reporters told
them the amount. One of the jurors, Glen Heinsohn, who said he
earns $20,000 a year, said the jurors thought the amount they
assessed was a lot of money compared with what they earn.
</P>
<P>
   But reaction to the verdict in the metropolitan area indicted
that its size came as a surprise and prompted supporters of the
advisers to say Pagones had only won a symbolic victory.
</P>
<P>
   One of those was Sharpton, who said he was stunned by the small
amount and that the size of the verdict would negate its impact as
a political symbol. ``As I run for mayor in 2001,'' he said after
th verdict, ``it's now going to be very difficult for anybody to
raise the issue because of the size of the award.''
</P>
<P>
   The jurors who spoke were three white members of the panel,
which included two black jurors who did not join the news
conference. One of the black jurors who did not appear at the news
conference, Althea Williams, a post office clerk, had been the
subject of intense scrutiny since the verdict July 13 because she
did not sign the verdict sheet, indicating that she disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   There had been reports in recent days that she expressed deep
disagreement with some of the white members of the panel. And
deliberations were interrupted Tuesday after a court officer
interceded in an emotional argument between Ms. Williams and a
white juror. Only five votes were required to reach a verdict.
Wednesday's verdict sheet included the signatures of all six
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   At her Dutchess County home after the verdict, Ms. Williams
denied that her opinion of the case had anything to do with
prejudice. But she said, ``I have a right to my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the award was a fraction of the damages that could have
been assessed, several members of the defense team immediately
claimed that they had won the case. When the trial began last Nov.
18, Pagones was seeking $395 million. The amount went down to $150
million because the jurors only found 10 of 22 statement in the
original complaint were defamatory in their July 13 verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hardy, Sharpton's lawyer, declared the verdict was a
major victory, reminding reporters that Pagones' lawyer, William
Stanton, had asked the jurors to hit the advisers with a large
damage award to ``shut them up.''.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox, who was often the most combative of the advisers, said:
``This was the greatest comeback in American jurisprudence. Pagones
was looking for $395 million and we ended up getting only a slap on
the wrist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
