<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARRACK-MARKETPLACE-A     07-29 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARRACK-MARKETPLACE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: CONFLICT OVER CONFLICTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.J., Minn., Fla., La., Wis., Calif., Conn.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
( rm ) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leonard Barrack, a prominent fund-raiser for Democratic causes
and the finance chairman of the Democratic National Committee, has
been a generous contributor to the campaigns of Mayor Ed Rendell in
Philadelphia and Carl McCall, the state comptroller in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Barrack, a prominent securities class-action lawyer, represents
the Philadelphia and New York state public pension funds in huge
class-action cases against companies whose stocks have tumbled
because of undisclosed setbacks or accounting irregularities,
earning substantial fees in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Did the contributions influence officials who hired him? Not at
all, Barrack says. ``I'm not sure that there's anything wrong with
political contributions like these, as long as we have vigorous
representation and the best recovery for the shareholders,'' said
Barrack, a partner in the Philadelphia firm of Barrack, Rodos &AMP;
Bacine. The firm represents McCall's fund and two others in a
securities case against Cendant Corp., potentially one of the most
lucrative class-action cases in history.
</P>
<P>
   But with the number of securities class-action cases up sharply
this year, some people think there is something very wrong here,
something that runs counter to the goals Congress had in 1995 when
it enacted a law giving pension funds and other institutional
investors an enhanced role in class-action litigation.
</P>
<P>
   One critic is Howard Sirota, a veteran class-action lawyer in
New York. ``There is a non-arm's-length arrangement between Len
Barrack and the politicians hiring him,'' Sirota said. ``And what
is wrong with that is that it puts last the economic interest of
the people in whose name the cases are being filed _ all the small
shareholders in the class.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrack and Sirota will be battling on Tuesday in federal court
in Newark, N.J., over whether campaign donations by Barrack and his
co-counsel disqualify their firms from adequately representing
Cendant shareholders. He wants the legal work to go to whichever
qualified firm will to do it for the lowest fee.
</P>
<P>
   Another critic of lawyers who cultivate public business by
contributing to politicians _ a practice known as ``pay to play'' _
is Harvey Goldschmid, the new general counsel of the Securities and
Exchange Commission. ``If we allow wild political contributions to
be made to get public benefits,'' Goldschmid said, ``we're going to
create questions about the integrity of the people and the
integrity of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldschmid was a member of an American Bar Association task
force that last week called for new professional rules that would
sharply restrict, and fully disclose, the contributions lawyers
make to politicians who award them business. On Tuesday, as Sirota
argues in Newark, the bar association's delegates will be debating
the task force's recommendations at their annual convention in
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Leading class-action lawyers are offended by Sirota's complaint.
``The pejorative implication is that one cannot be appropriately
appointed if one is politically engaged _ and that would be a sorry
state of affairs,'' said Samuel D. Heins, who represents the
Minnesota pension fund and who has supported two Democrats on the
fund's bipartisan five-member board.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sirota's challenge and the bar association's debate are
being watched carefully by executives at the large pension funds
that have become active in the class-action arena since 1995. The
general counsel of the $13 billion Florida state pension fund plans
to fly to Newark to observe the courtroom arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The funds insist their lawyer-selection procedures are immune to
political influence. Yet interviews with dozens of lawyers and
pension executives show that in most states the hiring of a
class-action lawyer is protected from politics by little more than
an honor system. Indeed, questions about a law firm's political
contributions have rarely been raised in the selection process
until now. And some funds do not even try to use their clout to get
lower fees from lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   This was not how it was supposed to work under the 1995
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Before then, the class-action arena was dominated by a handful
of giant firms _ Barrack, Rodos prominent among them _ considered
by critics to be quick-draw lawyers who kept ``pet plaintiffs''
handy so they could sue at the drop of a stock and settle quickly
for substantial fees. The passive plaintiff whose lawyer got to the
courthouse first was likely to be named ``lead plaintiff,'' even if
his actual loss was minimal, and his lawyer got the bulk of the
fees awarded by the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a process that hadn't been working particularly well,''
said the SEC chairman, Arthur Levitt Jr., with his typical
understatement.
</P>
<P>
   To improve it, Congress decreed that the investors with the
largest financial losses had a presumptive right to be lead
plaintiff, an arrangement that was expected to put powerful,
sophisticated institutional investors _ like mutual funds, money
managers and state and city pension funds _ in the driver's seat.
Congress expected public pension funds and other institutional
investors to take the reins of the securities class-action process
out of lawyers' hands, demanding lower fees and larger recoveries
for shareholders. But that model does not exactly match what is
happening in, say, Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The staff of the Florida State Board Administration has elected
officials on its board, but they are not involved in the selection
of counsel in the handful of cases the fund has filed. But then, no
one really is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't choose them; they choose us,'' said Horace Schow II,
the board's general counsel. ``It's first come, first served,
really.'' As for fees, any law firm representing the fund ``is
entitled to whatever the court will award them,'' Schow said,
adding, ``We haven't gotten around to negotiating them yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's approach to the class-action challenge also bears
little resemblance to the congressional vision, so far as anyone
outside the city solicitor's office can tell. Barrack acknowledged
that he represents the city pension fund in several cases, but he
did not identify them. The fund's chairman could not identify them
either, explaining that all litigation is ``the exclusive domain''
of the city solicitor, who is appointed by the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   And Deborah Butler, the chief deputy city solicitor, refused to
discuss any aspect of the city's securities class-action
procedures, including what steps are taken to insulate them from
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Barrack also filed numerous class-action cases on behalf of the
state of Pennsylvania's public pension funds, after being hired in
1996 by the state treasurer, who has since left office. But the
cases were filed without the required approval of the pension
fund's board and the treasurer was not authorized to hire outside
counsel, said Paul Tufano, the governor's general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   After learning accidentally of Barrack's work, Tufano protested.
Barrack balked at dropping the cases, Tufano said, and was
ultimately allowed to proceed with one or two cases that were too
far advanced to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Barrack described the dispute as ``a misunderstanding.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Louisiana, William T. Reeves, general counsel for the
Teachers Retirement System, said all his class-action work so far
had been done by I. Walton Bader, a partner in a two-member law
firm in White Plains, N.Y. Despite its tiny size, the Bader firm
has done extensive work for the Florida pension fund as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bader was selected after he got in touch with the fund six years
ago, Reeves said, but the fund is exploring other ways to handle
its class-action legal work. And while Bader's fees are left to the
discretion of the court, Reeves said, ``If we ever do anything with
anybody else, we're not going to do it that way.'' Typically,
court-awarded fees in such cases can be as much as 30 percent of
the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, the New York state comptroller, has retained three firms
to handle class-action cases on behalf of the state's various
pension funds. Besides Barrack's firm, they are Bernstein,
Litowitz, Berger &AMP; Grossmann and Milberg, Weiss, Bershad Hynes &AMP;
Lerach, both in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Bernstein firm is co-counsel with Barrack in the Cendant
case. The firms agreed to a sliding scale of fees that range from 3
percent of any early settlement exceeding $400 million to 20
percent of a post-trial award up to $150 million, a McCall
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported Wednesday that that the three firms
and their lawyers have contributed more than $165,000 to McCall's
campaign since they were retained in June 1997. McCall denied any
impropriety, saying that the contributions are completely unrelated
to the decision to retain the firms for the state's class-action
work. Lawyers in his office chose the firms after rigorously
reviewing the qualifications of 14 applicants, and he merely
approved the selection, McCall said.
</P>
<P>
   The role played by the State of Wisconsin Investment Board,
which manages that state's $55 billion pension fund, seems to be a
little closer to what Congress had in mind. The board is the lead
plaintiff in the class-action cases against Cellstar and Physician
Computer Network, said Keith Johnson, assistant legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the outside lawyers were selected after a
competitive review by a four-member panel made up of Johnson, an
in-house investment manager, a representative of the attorney
general, and a local lawyer, recruited for his litigation
expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Fees are negotiated in advance and are always ``way, way below''
the 30 percent that is the norm in class-action cases, Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   In California, the California Public Employees Retirement
System, called Calpers, has so insulated its procedures from
politics that one of its board members _ the state controller,
Kathleen Connell _ has actually sued to overturn a new fund rule
that bars her from accepting campaign contributions from anyone who
does business with the fund, including the lawyers it hires.
</P>
<P>
   Most other states active in class-action cases fall somewhere in
between.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Silvester, the state treasurer in Connecticut, is ready to
become active in appropriate cases, he said. And a state law
prohibits him from awarding business to anyone who has contributed
to the treasurer's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Silvester's outside lawyers are selected by Richard Blumenthal,
the state's elected attorney general, who is not barred from hiring
firms that have contributed to his campaign. But Blumenthal said
this week that he had an internal rule against hiring campaign
contributors. ``So the practical effect is to insulate the
selection from politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This growing dispute could discourage pension funds from getting
involved in the class-action arena, as Congress hoped they would,
said Michael Perino, a law professor at St. John's University in
New York and co-author of a recent study that shows a sharp
increase in class-action filings.
</P>
<P>
   Sirota's challenge provides further evidence that lawyers must
change their campaign contribution practices, said Michael A.
Cardozo, a former president of the New York City Bar Association,
who supports curbs on campaign contributions. ``I think many major
firms realize this is a bad practice and should be stopped,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But many lawyers, including Barrack, see such restrictions as
irrelevant and unnecessary. ``There are serious problems out there
in the campaign financing area, but this isn't one of them,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
