<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WHITE HOUSE, JULY IS NOT NEARLY AS BAD AS JANUARY
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-TRIPP) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nothing, White House aides insist, could be as bad
as late January, when the Lewinsky accusations first crashed over
them.
</P>
<P>
   To the rest of the country, or at least that fraction of it that
is paying attention, the last couple of days of revelations and
reversals in the investigation of Kenneth Starr surely looked like
a nightmare for the White House. But the people living through them
just shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no comparison between late January and late July,''
said a senior administration official, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``There is no shock value in anything anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Another said: ``This is not the first six days.'' He added, with
the deadeye accuracy of a prisoner or a hostage marking time,
``This is after 6 months and 11 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of President Clinton's political advisers had been
pushing White House lawyers for him to testify and not fight the
subpoena by Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel. They were
clearly relieved on Wednesday by the president's decision to do so.
``I told you,'' crowed one. ``Clinton wants a quick resolution. Get
this done.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, such strategic decisions are out of the hands
of all but a half-dozen officials at the White House, mostly in the
counsel's office. Those officials have had a more panicky couple of
days. Late on Tuesday evening, one was telephoning reporters to
question them about what they had learned of the immunity deal
between Starr and Monica Lewinsky, the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the staff, to a remarkable degree, has gone on with
business as usual _ for better or for worse. On Tuesday afternoon,
after the news of Ms. Lewinsky's deal was announced, an internal
memorandum rocketed through the building from the president's
famously aggressive communications office.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a directive on how to discuss the deal or to describe
the president's negotiations over his own testimony. Instead, it
was a stern memorandum stating that certain words were off-limits
to speech-writers and others, because they were reserved for the
``millenium project,'' an administration effort led by Hillary
Rodham Clinton to herald the change of century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language of the Millenium, and the logo (until we hear
otherwise), is for millenium use only,'' warned the memorandum, a
copy of which was provided to The New York Times by an amused staff
member, who like others wondered if he was now allowed to refer in
conversation to the 21st century. It added that ``it is very
important to the overall strength and infrastructure of the
millenium project'' for it to remain distinct from ``our day-to-day
messages and words that we use.''
</P>
<P>
   Under current circumstances, talking about talking about an
event two years' hence might seem like a remote endeavor. But life
has a strange way of going on in this White House, despite all the
buffeting by prosecutors or pundits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're inured to it,'' said another a White House aide, who is
not involved in the day-to-day damage control effort. But, he
added, he had been startled by the abrupt acceleration of Starr's
investigation in recent days. ``That's what everyone's amazed by,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president went resolutely about his business on Wednesday,
much as he has done since January.
</P>
<P>
   He met with a task force he convened on adults with
disabilities. And in a speech on Wednesday morning to an
international meeting of educators, he laid out lofty goals,
calling for a guarantee of ``universal, excellent education for
every child on our planet.'' He criticized Republicans for not
embracing his education agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at a White House briefing about the president's mood, Mike
McCurry, the president's press secretary, said, ``He seemed to be
enjoying all the work he is doing today. He's giving a speech on
education, which some of you may or may not report.''
</P>
<P>
   Many White House staff members express a certain fatalism or
resignation about the investigation. ``One, this president's done
nothing wrong, and if the facts get out it'll be fine,'' said one.
``And two, this will never end.'' The reason that scandal will
continue to dog the White House, he said, was that ``It's a
politically charged opposition, and it's set out to destroy this
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Other aides acknowledge harboring private doubts about Clinton's
truthfulness. But they say they are convinced that Starr's
investigation is doing much more damage than any lie he might have
told. One adviser said that anger at Starr has intensified since
his decision to subpoena Secret Service officers in the
investigation. ``The Service subpoenas made everybody furious,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been energized in the last two days by press
reports that the so-called talking points, which Ms. Lewinsky
apparently gave to Linda Tripp, were no longer believed by Starr's
team to have come from the White House. The talking points appeared
intended to coach Mrs. Tripp, a former White House secretary, on
possible testimony about the president. They were repeatedly
reported to be central to Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Gleeful White House aides fed reporters their own words,
compiling lists of quotations from news organizations and sending
them out. And they brandished the story of the talking points as a
talisman; other news reports about Starr's accumulation of
evidence, they said, may also prove flimsy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
