<SLUG> BC-NH-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE BRINGS ADMINISTRATION EDUCATION MESSAGE TO NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDONDERRY, N.H. _ She was a refugee asking a favor of an
American Vice President, but Beata Umugwangwali wasn't nervous,
saying: ``I went through so many things in my life that I wasn't
afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Umugwangwali is a nurse who fled the war ravaging her native
Rwanda with three children and a niece three years ago. She now
works in a rehabilitaion hospital in Dover, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore was on a swing through New Hampshire, a
state where the first presidential primary of the milennium will be
held. The visit marked his fourth trip to the state since the last
election and the 12th of his vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's trip included a meeting with Governor Jeanne Shaheen and
Democratic stalwarts, but he began his day talking to business
leaders, educators and people who have benefited from federal
education programs. He held a town hall meeting at Insight
Technology, a manufacturer of night-vision goggles and laser sights
for weapons that has grown from three to 140 employees since its
founding in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted so much to say something to him and I am so happy
that they put education on top and are pushing everyone to go back
to school'' Umugwangwali said after asking Gore's help in getting
American licensing boards to recognize college degrees earned
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Gore repeatedly praised President Clinton for his education
initiatives and made no secret of the fact that his trip was also
meant to chastize Congress for stalling education and environmental
programs pushed by the Clinton adminstration.
</P>
<P>
   Budget cuts proposed by the Republican majority would cost New
Hampshire $8.5 million in lost federal funds for education alone.
</P>
<P>
   Gore talked about continuing education and skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now there is a big controversy in Congress about lifting
the immigration limits for people with higher skills to come in and
fill these jobs. ... Yes, that's something that needs to be debated
but, why don't we at the same time make a commitment beyond
partisanship to invest what is needed to give the skills to
Americans so they can fill those jobs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, on the banks of the Oyster River in Durham,
Gore told a group of some 150 UNH students and faculty that the
state would soon get $1.6 in federal funds to help restore the
state's polluted esturaries and reopen long closed shellfish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now, I think, past the old mistake people used to make
of having to choose between the economy and the environment.'' In
tourist dependent N.H., as in many other states, they are one and
the same, Gore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
