<HEADER>
A9203 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEONE-ATROCITIES-ART-     07-29 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEONE-ATROCITIES-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WEST AFRICA, A GRISLY EXTENSION OF REBEL TERROR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A rebel movement dislodged early this year from
a brief period in power in Sierra Leone is waging a campaign of
butchery against civilians, human rights groups and government
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   By the hundreds, poor farmers and villagers _ men, women and
children _ have been shot, disemboweled or mutilated by having
limbs hacked off, survivors report. Thousands are thought to have
died, many in a rebel campaign code-named No Living Thing.
</P>
<P>
   Some victims have been turned into messengers of death,
disfigured then sent away bearing letters warning President Ahmad
Tejan Kabbah and the African peacekeeping troops who restored him
to office in March that armed resistance, led by remnants of a
former military junta, will continue and that no one is safe.
</P>
<P>
   A refugee who reached Guinea, his arms hacked to stumps, told
his story to a representative of Refugees International, a
Washington-based advocacy group that videotaped his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want a military government,'' the refugee said the
rebels told him. ``You say you want a civilian government. Then we
will have to cut off your hands. Then go to Tejan Kabbah and he
will have to give you more hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Another refugee, with bandaged stumps where his hands had been,
shook with fear as he repeated again and again that he would never
be able to use a toilet without help.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are doing really is atrocious,'' said Fode Dabor,
Sierra Leone's representative at the United Nations. ``I've never
seen it before. This is one of the most vicious rebel organizations
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred thousand people have fled their homes in recent
months for government-controlled areas or refugee camps in Liberia
and Guinea. Hospitals in Sierra Leone and in the camps are treating
a steady stream of mutilated victims.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the United Nations is to convene a special
conference on Sierra Leone to discuss how to begin rebuilding a
country that has endured decades of civil war and ruthless military
leaders since its independence in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan met with Kabbah,
who is in New York for the conference. Annan said later that Kabbah
had told him that Nigeria on Wednesday turned over Foday Sankoh,
the rebel leader, to Sierra Leone to stand trial on charges of
treason and crimes against humanity, including atrocities he has
been associated with for more than seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh, who was arrested in Nigeria last year while trying to
buy weapons, told his followers in a televised message after his
return to Freetown, Sierra Leone's capital, that they should end
their terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not support the cutting off of people's hands and feet,
and when I heard about this I felt sick,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kabbah, a civilian and Sierra Leone's first democratically
elected president, served for only a year before being overthrown
in May 1997 by the Armed Forces Revolutionary Council and the
Revolutionary United Front.
</P>
<P>
   The Front is now trying to regain power even as Kabbah's
government begins to re-establish shaky institutions and repair a
ravaged capital. Political power and economic spoils have been the
object of this struggle and those that have gone before, though the
rebels have no political platform, according to experts on the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups came to the United Nations this week in
force to press participants in the Sierra Leone conference to mount
an international drive to insure that trials are held and
punishments meted out to the rebels. Officials from Sierra Leone
say the country may need international help to hold such trials.
</P>
<P>
   Dabor, Sierra Leone's representative, said in an interview that
the rebels are strongest in eastern Sierra Leone, where they have
been selling diamonds to buy weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem has been the diamonds,'' he said. ``We have a lot
of people who want to lay their hands on our diamonds. I know that
the rebels finance their operations by the diamonds they recover
from this mining area. That's why they don't want to give up these
places.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Campbell, who recently completed a report on violence in
Sierra Leone for Human Rights Watch, said that the rebels had been
using brutal tactics for years but that they now appear to be more
desperate because of the presence of the Nigerian soldiers, who
make up the majority of the peacekeeping force sent by the Economic
Community of West African States Monitoring Group (ECOMOG).
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``Sowing Terror,'' was published Wednesday. Written
by Campbell and Jane Lowicki, both consultants to the organization,
it says children and women have also been singled out for sexual
abuse. Accounts of gang rapes and kidnappings for purposes of
sexual slavery are common.
</P>
<P>
   The report includes accounts of abuses by civilian defense
forces supporting Kabbah, in particular a group known as the
Kamajors, which it describes as ``responsible for the majority of
the most serious abuses committed by those fighting on behalf of
the Kabbah government since February 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch says child soldiers have been used by these
forces, but the Kabbah government has promised to end that
practice.
</P>
<P>
   The most brutal offenses seem to have been committed by the
rebels, however, especially the Revolutionary United Front, the
report says.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Since 1991, when the RUF got going, in one of their first
attacks they allegedly decapitated administrators, put their heads
on sticks,'' Campbell said in an interview Wednesday. ``In order to
make statements of power, political statements, in 1996, they would
mutilate people. They would write things like `No election' or
`Don't vote' on peoples' backs _ they would burn it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of chopping someone's hands off allegedly came from
rebels saying to people: We're going to cut your hands off so you
can't vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's changed now,'' Campbell said, ``is that the military
balance has changed, with ECOMOG there. ECOMOG is really powerful.
They control the urban centers and the rebels have become more
desperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their new strategy to put themselves back on the political
chessboard is to do these horrible things to civilians. That does
two things: It makes the civilian population subservient, and it
makes them somebody you have to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   The report included transcripts of testimony from survivors of
rebel attacks. One was from a farmer in Koidu, in the Kono
district, identified as Sam R., whose home was attacked twice. This
is his story:
</P>
<P>
   ``At about 4 a.m. I heard bombs and gunshots outside my house,''
he said of the first attack. ``The rebels came and banged on the
door. They said they would kill us all outside. My wife took five
of the six children outside. I stayed inside with one. My wife
threw herself on top of two of the children to protect them. They
shot my wife, killed two of the children, shot my 7-year-old
through the stomach and cut one on the buttocks. Two got away.''
</P>
<P>
   There was another attack in June. ``They accused me of being a
Kamajor,'' he said. ``When they want to kill you, they accuse you
of anything. There is no reason. I am a farmer. I don't vote. I
have no money. They burnt my house.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
