</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWGUINEA-TSUNAMI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAVE VICTIMS TO GET U.S. AID FOR RESCUE, PREVENTION
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT MORESBY, Papua New Guinea _ Government rescue workers said
Wednesday that they had given up hope of finding large numbers of
additional survivors from a series of giant waves that crashed into
the northwestern coast of the island of New Guinea on July 19,
killing an estimated 3,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The search for bodies continued as Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright arrived here to announce a package of more than $1 million
in aid from the United States to help pay for the rescue effort and
to install a seismic early-warning system to help prevent loss of
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only begin to imagine the horror of what took place,''
said Albright, who viewed the devastated area from the air as she
flew to Port Moresby, the capital of this western Pacific nation of
4 million people. ``It simply staggers the imagination. Words can
only begin to describe the sorrow we feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Whole villages along an 18-mile stretch of the northern coast
disappeared, their residents pitched into island lagoons or swept
out to sea after an earthquake about 30 miles offshore unleashed
three huge waves, or tsunami, the largest of them reported to be
about 30 feet high. The bodies of about 1,600 victims have been
recovered so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Papua New Guinea is grieving over the loss of human life as a
result of the tidal-wave disaster,'' Prime Minister Bill Skate said
at a ceremony to mark the arrival of Albright, the highest-ranking
American official to visit Papua New Guinea since it gained
independence from Australia in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Her visit, which lasted about two hours, was scheduled long
before the recent disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has already sent about $400,000 in relief
supplies to the Papua New Guinea government. In announcing an
additional $650,000 in aid, Albright said that while ``it's hard
not to feel helpless before the awesome destructive power'' of
nature, ``we are not powerless to help those who are suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials here described a desperate situation in the
coastal area where the waves struck, with hundreds of bodies
decomposing in a central lagoon near the village of Sissano, about
400 miles northwest of Port Moresby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, people had used that water for washing, for fishing,''
said Cecilia Sangul, a spokeswoman for the Department of Foreign
Affairs. ``Now it is completely contaminated. The bodies decompose
so fast.'' She noted that the Sissano lagoon was created by a huge
tsunami in 1907.
</P>
<P>
   While the government had originally planned to dynamite a sand
spit at the mouth of the lagoon to allow it to drain into the
ocean, officials said the idea had been abandoned out of fear that
corpses and debris would contaminate hundreds of miles of coastline
near the border with Indonesia. News reports from Indonesia said
that nearly 200 bodies had already been sighted by fishermen in
Indonesian waters.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials here said the largest number of victims
were children, who lacked the strength to fight the pull of the
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sangul, who met with reporters traveling with Albright, said
the government wants to reopen the schools in the area quickly, if
only to determine through student rosters how many children are
missing and presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6,000 people have been left homeless by the waves.
Most of them are subsistence farmers and fishermen, and many are
frightened to return home. Ms. Sangul said that some are afraid
that another wave might be imminent, while others are terrified
that the ghosts of the dead now haunt the coastline.
</P>
<P>
   Although Albright's visit took on a somber tone as a result of
the disaster, she was still greeted on the tarmac of Port Moresby's
airport with a raucous display of traditional dance, which in many
remote regions has changed little since the Stone Age.
</P>
<P>
   As she stepped from her government jet, she was met by a troop
of scantily clad dancers from the country's central Mekeo region.
Each wore a necklace of dogs' teeth and a headdress adorned with
feathers from chickens, parrots and birds of paradise. Their skirts
were made from pulverized tree bark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
