u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDGE-COMA-1STLD-WRIT     07-29 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-COMA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DISTRICT JUDGE MIKE MACHADO, 74, DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Complete writethru, adding death, details)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAIME CASTILLO and GLORIA PADILLA  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Mike Machado, a Depression-era child who rose from
poverty to become a revered war veteran and judge, died at a San
Antonio hospital Wednesday from complications associated with a
brain aneurysm. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime jurist, who spent 41 years as a judge in the
municipal and district courts, died at 3:30 p.m. with friends and
family by his side at Santa Rosa Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Machado, the Democratic nominee for Bexar County
district attorney, sends party officials into a scramble for to
find a replacement candidate for the November general election
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Machado was looked upon by many as a godfather who took young
defense lawyers and prosecutors under his wing while they learned
their trade.
</P>
<P>
   During his long career as a judge, Machado performed marriage
ceremonies for hundreds of couples and gave them all an open
invitation to his chambers. Many took them up on it.
</P>
<P>
   Until the end, friends and colleagues held out hope that the
gritty Machado would conquer his latest challenge.
</P>
<P>
   District Judge Sid Harle said that in recent weeks he had
encountered a confident Machado who was looking forward to his bid
for district attorney in the November general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was typical Mike Machado _ giving 'em hell and talking to
everybody he saw,'' said Harle, who first met Machado when he was a
county prosecutor in the mid 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow District Judge Mary Roman, who was sworn in by Machado as
a new lawyer in 1984, said she often spent hours in Machado's
courthouse office discussing politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was strong in his beliefs,'' she said. ``He was passionate
about everything. If he thought I didn't agree him, he'd proceed to
try to persuade me and he wouldn't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1940 Lanier High School graduate, Machado often referred to
himself as ``La Garra Kid,'' said Ronnie Waiters, the judge's
longtime court coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was from the West Side and I'm from the East Side and we
put our experience to work downtown,'' Waiters said. ``That's a lot
of experience from two old fools.''
</P>
<P>
   Machado joined the U.S. Army Air Corps after high school and
soon found himself shooting at enemy targets as a nose-gunner
aboard B-24 bombers during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   On June 13, 1944, a B-24 carrying Machado and others was strafed
by enemy fire while flying a mission over Munich, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of intelligence reports that captured American flight
crews were being tortured by German soldiers, those aboard the
damaged bomber decided not to bail out.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they guided the failing aircraft to a crash landing in
northern Italy. A resulting fire badly scarred Machado's upper
body, forcing him to spend 36 months in the hospital to receive
skin grafts.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries left him with limited use of his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was every man for himself,'' Machado told the San Antonio
Light in 1991. ``I pulled two boys out. That's how I burned my
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the war, Machado went back to school and began an
ascent in the San Antonio legal community.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from St. Mary's School of Law in 1952, he
served as an assistant district attorney and then as a municipal
court judge for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Machado became a state district court judge where he
remained until his death. He was set to retire from the bench on
Sept. 4 _ his 75th birthday _ which is the mandatory retirement age
for judges in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife of 41 years, Rosa Elia; sons Mike Jr.
and Marc; and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
