u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FED-WAGES-BOS &LR;      07-29 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-WAGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE FED, THE BOOM MEANS INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Cahill recommended nine friends to come to work for his
employer, Citizens Bank of Massachusetts _ the bank paid him $2,700
for his help finding good recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Shelley re-entered the job market with some trepidation
after 25 years with one company and soon learned how valuable her
skills were. She received three job offers in one day, and took one
as a store manager for Best Buy, a retailer opening stores in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Haan, a software systems manager, can top that: 13 calls
in one day, after posting his resume on the Internet. ``I
constantly got jobs,'' the Haan said while standing in the computer
``control room'' of his employer, OrderTrust of Lowell, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   It is easier to get a job than it has been in decades. With
unemployment at its lowest level since the 1970s, employers report
that the job market is so tight it is driving up wages and bonuses.
But there is a downside: Rising wages often trigger greater
consumer demand and price hikes, which in turn can spur inflation.
That hasn't happened so far, but the Federal Reserve Board and many
investors will be anxiously watching today for any spike in what
has been an obscure measure of quarterly wage changes, the
government's Employment Cost Index.
</P>
<P>
   The index has already shown an acceleration in wages, which rose
3.3 percent during the year ending March 1998, up from 2.9 percent
for the year ending March &UR;  &LR; 1997. A big increase in the index report
could heighten fears of inflation on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Whatever the numbers are today, the pressure on employers to
hike wages continues. ``If you're not competitive on pay, you might
as well hang up your hat,'' said Joann Laipson, director of human
resources for Lotus Development Corp., an IBM Corp. subsidiary in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do employers feel compelled to raise basic wages, they
also are passing out more bonuses, rewarding emplyees who help with
recruitment, more employees to justify pay hikes, and responding
more aggressively with raises for employees who receive job offers
from other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Though most acute in the high-technology industry, the labor
shortage is also occurring in retail, consulting, and financial
companies and healthcare organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Whether higher wages will be reflected in the Consumer Price
Index, the main inflation gauge watched by the Fed, is unclear. So
far, despite strong growth in the US economy, inflation has
remained calm: The Consumer Price Index, rose 0.1 percent in June,
even less than the scant 0.3 percent May increase.
</P>
<P>
   But Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman said in recent
testimony before the Senate Banking Committee that he is worried
that a tight job market means ``increasingly confident workers
might place gradually escalating pressures on wages and costs,
which would eventually feed through to prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Although wages push up inflation, other forces are working
against it. Asia's economic crisis has lowered the cost of goods
imported from the Pacific Rim, and US companies are responding by
lowering their prices. Commodities prices, notably oil, a key
component of the CPI, are falling.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation ``would be with us today, were it not for Asia,'' said
Nicholas Perna, chief economist for Fleet Financial Group Inc. in
Boston. ``If Asia had continued to jump along at the rate it was
growing, oil prices wouldn't be running $14 a barrel _ they'd
probably be closer to $20. The dollar exchange rate would probably
be weaker rather than strong _ and US interest rates would be
higher rather than lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is ample cause for Greenspan's concerns about labor
costs.
</P>
<P>
   An estimate by Watson Wyatt Worldwide, a Wellesley, Mass.
consultant to coroporate human resource departments, based on a
survey of 180 companies in New England, said 1998 raises were 4.1
percent, about the same as the average in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not take into account other costs of keeping and
hiring workers. In Watson Wyatt's survey, 75 percent of employers
said they use counter-offers to keep their best employees, more
than 60 percent use incentive plans to reward employees for good
performance, and half gave raises to prevent people from quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's Perna said, ``These hidden costs that don't show up in
wages affect the total level of costs.''
</P>
<P>
   A separate study by Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, a Lexington, Mass.
research firm, found that wages and salaries for Massachusetts
workers in all industries increased between 4.6 percent and 4.8
percent in each of the past three years. That is a sharp rise from
wage increases of below 2.5 percent in 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both locally and nationally wages have been accelerating for
the past three years,'' said Sara Johnson, chief regional economist
for Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI. ``Eventually this will surface in the
general price inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The tight job market gives employees confidence to demand
more in job interviews and in seeking pay raises from current
employers. ``It is definitely a job applicant's market, and
employers have to move very, very quickly,'' said Heidi Toppel, a
consultant for Watson Wyatt in the eastern region.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Shelley, for example, who had worked for Montgomery Ward
for 25 years, most recently as a store manager in Portsmouth, N.H.,
had many offers she didn't really even consider. After several
interviews, she chose Best Buy, she said, in part because the
retailer offered better pay than other retailers _ and much better
than Montgomery Ward.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all. ``Best Buy's benefits were by far the best. Best
Buy offered a 401k after six months,'' Shelley said. ``You can get
into stock options after a year. Their discount is 5 percent over
cost.''
</P>
<P>
   When he makes an offer to a job applicant, Chris Coffin,
director of human resources for Citizens Bank Massachusetts, said
that potential recruits sometimes respond with ``irrational
counter-offers'' from their existing employers. ``It feels like the
mid-80s where it really heated up.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffin said he resists costly bidding wars. But the bank in
December boosted pay for tellers by 50 cents an hour, to $8.50 an
hour, to help fill the difficult-to-fill positions.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals can often secure better pay by changing jobs. Lisa
Carroll, one of the nine employees that coworker Cahill helped to
recruit, said she got a ``moderate increase'' in pay when she
switched from Fleet to Citizens, where she is now a manager of its
branch on West Broadway in South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether pervasive stories about the tight labor
market turn up in the US Department of Labor's wage index.
Economists have forecast a rise in the Employment Cost Index for
the April-June quarter ranging from 0.5 percent to 1.0 percent.
That would boost the cost index for the year ending June to 3.4
percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anecdotal stories make you confident the acceleration you
see is real. You could argue it could be worse than what we're
seeing'' in the numbers, said William Dudley, the chief US
economist for Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. in New York. But, Dudley
concluded, ``we need more data.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
