<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9220 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-LABOR-NYT &LR;      07-29 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: GM STRIKE NOT A BIG BOOST FOR ORGANIZED LABOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (with GM-STRIKE) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The General Motors strikes will certainly not give the nation's
labor movement the shot in the arm it received last year from the
Teamsters strike against the United Parcel Service.
</P>
<P>
   Unions trumpeted the UPS strike as an unequivocal victory that
gave part-time workers a big raise, but labor can describe the GM
strikes as, at best, an ultimately successful but extremely costly
goal-line stand.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks on the picket line, the striking auto workers can
boast that they achieved their main but modest goal: GM agreed to
proceed with a $180 million investment at a metal stamping plant in
Flint, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   But the United Automobile Workers achieved that small victory
for a huge price: workers who went on strike at two plants in
Flint, as well as workers at dozens of other GM plants that were
forced to close, lost $1 billion in wages.
</P>
<P>
   Though the labor movement used the UPS strike as a rallying cry
to tell nonunion workers there was a reason to join a union, the
results at General Motors are likely to send a different message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not want to be a UAW organizer,'' said Dale Brickner,
a professor of industrial relations at Michigan State University.
``How do you go out and tell people they should join a union that
has had people out for 50 days, 190,000 of them, and gained
absolutely nothing?''
</P>
<P>
   The auto workers may not have made significant gains, but union
officials say they did prevent a pivotal loss. GM precipitated the
strike at the metal plant by removing some valuable stamping dies,
which are like large molds used to shape metal, over the Memorial
Day weekend, a move that caused union members to fear that the
plant's days might be numbered. Anxious to protect their jobs, the
workers at the plant struck, and they now insist workers at the
plant struck, and they now insist they were victorious because they
persuaded GM to return the dies, which will be used to produce a
vaunted new pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the union achieved what they set out to achieve _ to
bring the dies back, which were the catalyst that started this
whole thing,'' said Daniel Hoffman, a former GM factory worker who
is coordinator of the Labor Studies Center at the University of
Michigan. ``The fact that they got the corporation to follow
through on the investment in the plant, that's going to be looked
upon as a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   But certainly not as a major victory.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Katz, a professor of labor relations at Cornell
University, expressed more skepticism about how much the union
achieved. ``In the grand scheme, I'd call it a lose-lose draw. If I
had to say who lost more _ not in the dollar sense, but in the
symbolic sense _ GM lost more. The UAW did get at least partially
what they fought the strike over.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because the strikes began locally and grew to national
proportion, they never captured the public's attention the way the
UPS strike did. Moreover, officials at other unions often said that
UAW leaders did a poor job framing the issues to win public backing
for the strikers, a weakness considered especially important
because these strikes, while national in impact, focused on local
issues. That was one reason many Americans saw the strikes as yet
another example of some Brahmins of blue-collar labor biting the
hand that feeds them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even though the UAW achieved its main goal in the strikes,
the result has so few implications outside of Flint that it will be
hard for the union to convince the nation this was a big victory.
That is especially so in light of the staggering losses the union
and the company suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM lost, but the UAW didn't win,'' said Harley Shaiken, a
professor of labor relations at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes could hurt labor in ways that go beyond the loss of
$1 billion in wages. Fearing a costly stoppage like the General
Motors strike, an employers who wants to keep out a union can be
expected to fight unionization all the more. And though the main
goal of the strikes was to protect job security, the results might
end up causing some unionized employers _ perhaps even General
Motors _ to accelerate plans to move jobs to other countries with
more pliant workers and less obstinate unions.
</P>
<P>
   For labor, Shaiken saw a silver lining: after the number of
strikes has declined nationwide to its lowest level in 50 years,
the GM walkouts certainly demonstrated that labor could still
muster plenty of muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, this was a strike in which two local unions
paralyzed the world's largest industrial corporation,'' Shaiken
said. ``If anything, this shows that strikes still pack a wallop.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two decades, labor has been trounced in some
highly visible strikes, including those by the air traffic
controllers and workers at Phelps Dodge and Caterpillar. Labor's
losses in those showdowns discouraged other unions from walking
out, and, the GM strikes, some labor experts said, might prove more
encouraging to workers thinking of striking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all the dust settles from this one,'' said Hoffman of the
University of Michigan, ``the auto workers come out of this very
supportive of their union. I think the average auto worker will
have the resolve to say, `I either stand now and strike or there
may be no tomorrow.'''
</P>
<P>
   But labor experts said the GM showdown might cause other unions
to think hard about striking because what seemed like a minor
dispute mushroomed into a conflagration.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts said the strikes turned out to be at least as much
of a loss for GM as for the union. Company officials said GM's
biggest gains _ which many industry analysts said were modest _
were getting the union, first, to agree to regular meetings to
improve labor relations and, second, to promise to improve
productivity at the Flint metal stamping plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM lost because it lost close to $3 billion and 50-odd days of
lost production in obtaining a settlement that it likely could have
had without a strike,'' Shaiken said. ``You have to ask how does
what GM gained transfer to any other plant and what did they
accomplish other than antagonizing the union. I think the strike
was a miscalculation for GM. If this strike was a car, it would be
a Corvair.''
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts said that considering how modest the issues were
and how much the two sides lost, GM and the union would have been
far wiser to have intensified its negotiating efforts before the
strikes erupted.
</P>
<P>
   If any person emerged stronger in the dispute, it was Richard
Shoemaker, the UAW vice president for General Motors issues. By
playing field commander and chief negotiator, he burnished his
credentials as an eventual successor to union president Stephen
Yokich.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the eyes of the UAW leadership and the rank and file, Dick
Shoemaker comes out of this looking like a very strong leader,''
Hoffman said. ``He was able to mobilize everybody and pull it
together when it came to crunch time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
