<HEADER>
A9223 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY30-CO     07-29 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON AGREES TO TESTIFY BEFORE STARR'S GRAND JURY
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton agreed Wednesday to answer
questions from independent counsel Kenneth Starr, setting the stage
for a late summer climax of Starr's investigation into perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony is expected to pit the word of the nation's chief
executive against that of former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky, who reportedly is ready to change her story and testify
that she had sexual relations with Clinton and that they discussed
concealing the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than appearing in person before a grand jury, Clinton
will give his testimony from the White House. It will be videotaped
and later played for grand jurors, the president's personal
attorney, David Kendall, announced.
</P>
<P>
   In a second concession to Clinton, Starr will allow attorneys to
be at the president's side as he testifies, Kendall said in a
statement read outside the White House. Normal practice is for
witnesses to undergo grand jury testimony alone and behind closed
doors.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton agreed to testify Aug. 17, delaying a New England
vacation, after receiving a court order requested by Starr seeking
his testimony. The counsel's office then withdrew the subpoena,
which had been issued after months of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony from Clinton and Lewinsky are the final elements
needed by Starr to complete his investigation. If the probe turns
up evidence of impeachable offenses by the president, Starr is
required to report them to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers believe that a Starr report could be sent to
House Speaker Newt Gingrich by September, presenting Congress with
a politically delicate decision just a month before it is scheduled
to adjourn to allow members to campaign for the fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   While many lawyers say perjury and obstruction of justice would
warrant removal of a president, recent opinion polls suggest that
most Americans do not now believe a president should be removed
from office for lying about a private affair.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision to testify voluntarily heads off a potential
constitutional clash over whether a sitting president can be forced
to appear before a federal grand jury. If the courts ruled against
him, Clinton would have become the first chief executive in history
required by subpoena to go before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky has previously stated in a sworn affidavit in a civil
sexual harassment lawsuit brought by former Arkansas state employee
Paula Jones that she never had a sexual relationship with Clinton.
The president has said the same thing, under oath, in a deposition
in that case.
</P>
<P>
   Senior administration officials indicated that in his testimony
Clinton would insist, as he first did six months ago, that he never
had sexual relations with Lewinsky and did not urge her to lie
about it under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president, back in January, leveled with the American
people, and he said what he had to say about this matter, and
nothing has changed about that in the time since,'' said White
House spokesman Michael McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing to testify, Clinton rejected a list of other legal
options, including asking the U.S. Supreme Court to rule on the
undecided question of whether a president can be forced to testify
against his will.
</P>
<P>
   That tactic might have delayed Starr's investigation by another
two or three months, but in the end, both failure and success would
have posed risks for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Failure _ meaning the Supreme Court might, in the end, order
Clinton to go before the grand jury _ would have been a historic
setback for the presidency and personally embarrassing for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Success _ meaning he would escape by the will of the court _
would have been politically damaging, in the view of many of his
top domestic aides.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these aides have grown openly weary of an investigation
that has sapped enormous resources from the administration and
taken the focus away from an ambitious policy agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sooner we get this behind us, the better it is for the
country and, therefore, the better it is for the president,'' said
White House political counsel Paul Begala.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no denying this is an aggravation,'' Begala said.
''It's no fun.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry conceded there had been lively debate within the
administration this week over whether to continue a strategy built
around delaying on the issue or whether to confront it head-on.
McCurry said he and others wanted Clinton to address the matter
sooner rather than later, a position opposed by some members of
Clinton's legal team.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think sometimes we acknowledge the wisdom of their position;
sometimes they acknowledge the wisdom of our position. And, no,
they don't always win out,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has no plans to address the American public on the issue
in the near future, McCurry said, adding that he didn't know
whether Clinton would go public with his testimony after he gives
it to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he wanted to talk about it he could talk about it,''
McCurry said. ''But remember, grand jury proceedings, for all the
reasons we've talked about in the past, are conducted in secret,
first and foremost to protect the rights of the innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has not given up his Fifth Amendment right to remain
silent on any questions he believes could incriminate him.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking that right, however, would also carry a high political
cost.
</P>
<P>
   ''While legally that's viable, politically it's not,'' said
Clifford S. Fishman, law professor at the Catholic University of
America in Washington. ''For the president of the United States to
plead the Fifth Amendment ...it's a tacit admission of guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
