<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9226 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALCONS-NOTES30-COX     07-29 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-NOTES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons Notebook
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Atlanta Falcons haven't quite hit the wall yet,
but the shadow was looming as the first week of training camp ended
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one practice, for just under two hours in the
afternoon, and more than half of it was spent working on various
special teams and group drills. The 10th practice of camp was not
one of the most intense.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are guys getting tired physically, and tired of doing
many of the same things over and over, but they're getting tired of
each other.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is they'll scrimmage twice against the Jaguars
Saturday in Jacksonville. The bad news is it won't be a true
scrimmage, but rather almost the exact same drills they've been
doing, minus much of the special teams work.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know the tendencies of each other, and sometimes it
doesn't give you a very good look (against teammates),'' left
tackle Bob Whitfield said. ''So it's exciting to go up against
somebody you haven't seen in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Shane Dronett and running back Jamal Anderson
viewed the road trip with different kinds of indifference.
</P>
<P>
   ''In training camp you got to keep the same attitude whatever
they ask you to do,'' Dronett said. ''It doesn't really matter to
me. It's the same work. It's good competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said, ''I hate training camp, period. The whole thing
is a pain I could do without. I'm glad we're not going down there
for four or five days, but I wish they were coming here so I
wouldn't have to get on a plane.''
</P>
<P>
   What's next?
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons today will practice at 9 a.m. and 3 p.m., and at 9
a.m. Friday. After meetings Friday afternoon, the team will fly to
Jacksonville for Saturday's 8:15 and 2:15 scrimmage-practices.
Actually, the Falcons will take the field a little earlier than the
Jags in order to get in extra special teams work.
</P>
<P>
   Turning up the heat
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was the first time Reeves had the first offense run a
hurry-up drill against the first defense. It was the last part of
practice. Quarterback Chris Chandler and the starters had a minute
and five seconds to go 70 yards with one timeout. Chandler was very
sharp, hitting on all five of his passes, including a perfect throw
down the middle to Terance Mathis even though cornerback Ray
Buchanan had tight coverage. Generally, the ball was spotted a few
yards past where it was caught. That 30-yarder moved the ball to
about the 15, and after Chandler downed the ball on the next play,
he hit receiver Kevin Thornal on a look-in to move it to about the
7. But time ran out. The second unit did not fare well. Backup QB
Tony Graziani misfired on a few passes, and the backups barely made
it across midfield. ''Things went pretty well for it being the
first time,'' Reeves said. ''Chris had a really good grasp of it.
Usually the first unit does. Defensively, that's something we have
to work on. When your offense moves it like that you feel good, but
then you worry about the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   QB watch
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at what's going on with the quarterbacks:
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chandler -- In addition to the above, he took turns
throwing passing drills, include extra work with receivers and
defensive backs after practice.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Graziani -- See above, and also worked with kickers for the
first time as a holder. Did not throw well.
</P>
<P>
   Steve DeBerg -- Didn't get to go in the hurry-up offense drill,
but did run the No. 1 offense in a 9-on-9 running drill while
Chandler was working passing drills on the next field.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Brennan -- Used only in passing drills, and a couple
running drills.
</P>
<P>
   The good, bad, and ugly
</P>
<P>
   Good: The Falcons for the first time worked on a drill where the
outside coverage men on the punt team streak downfield to try to
keep a punt from bouncing in the end zone. Rookie Elijah Williams
caught a kick on the one-foot line.
</P>
<P>
   Bad: Rookie Octavus Barnes made a nice catch on a deep route
down the middle when receivers were working against defensive backs
without linemen and linebackers. But he ran into secondary coach
Ron Meeks after the grab. Way to make an impression, er,
indentation.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly: Falcons president Taylor Smith's shorts and T-shirt.
They're old. In fact, it is believed they once belonged to former
Falcon and Georgia running back Preston Ridlehuber, who played for
Atlanta in the first year of the franchise: 1966. The gray shorts
and white shirt are riddled with holes and creased by wrinkles. But
Smith has a good story. He was working out before he walked out to
practice.
</P>
<P>
   What they said
</P>
<P>
   ''It'd be really nice if we could get one of them to block.'' --
Reeves, on the possibility of running backs Jamal Anderson and
Bryon Hanspard in the lineup at the same time. Anderson's response:
''Dan's comment was very accurate, and that's why I tell people it
will never happen. Actually, I can block for Byron in some
situations. I'm not going to be running in there and iso-ing
anybody . . . at all. And Byron's not going to be lead-blocking for
me, unless it's a cornerback or something. But really, man, it's
like having two tailbacks back there. Tailbacks aint blockers.''
</P>
<P>
   Did you know?
</P>
<P>
   This is remarkable. Reliable sources say one of the players'
absolute favorite foods in the dining hall is steamed cabbage. On a
day when it is served, cooks typically go through 40 pounds of the
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Close book on Davis
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Davis, who was waived by the Falcons Tuesday, cleared
waivers without being claimed by another team. That means the
6-foot-5, 326-pound defensive tackle is a free agent. He will count
$245,700 against the Falcons' cap this year, and $220,700 next.
These numbers pale to the $1.1 million former center Roman Fortin
will count against the cap after being waived in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Aches and pains
</P>
<P>
   If we were to list every player that has something wrapped,
iced, taped or strapped, you'd be reading until opening day. But
the three players who missed both Tuesday's practices missed
Wednesday as well. CBs Randy Fuller (ankle) Ronnie Bradford
(hamstring) and DE Barry Mitchell (quadriceps) were out. Wednesday,
LB Jessie Tuggle (mild back strain) and WR Keith Crawford
(hamstring) came up lame. DE Chuck Smith (back spasms) also was
limited. Fuller looks worst. He's wearing a removable cast with an
electrical stimulation pack as a constant companion. G Scott Adams
(ankle and hamstring) practiced, but continues to limp badly. He
too wears a removable cast -- when he's not practicing.
</P>
<P>
   The boss talks
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Taylor Smith didn't look so good, but he had good things
to say after practice.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last year there was such a newness to everything (in Reeves'
first year),'' he said. ''The coaches didn't know the news players,
or even the players we already had. The players didn't know the
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no worrying about switching from the run-and-shoot,
and no worrying if we can understand the new defense. Everybody
just seems much more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Loving life
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Swayda is a happier man these days. He was drafted in the
sixth round last year by the Bears after playing defensive tackle
at Arizona State. But the 6-foot-5, 290-pounder played only at end
in Chicago's camp, and got cut. He started out at end in the
Falcons' camp, but since switching to tackle Saturday, he's made
some plays and is working at No. 2 right tackle behind Shane
Dronett.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm better suited to play inside,'' he said. ''(The Bears) . .
. didn't give me a chance inside. I wasn't very happy. I can handle
not making it as long as I get a fair shot at where I think I
should play.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
