<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACING-BRICKYARD-COX     07-29 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACING-BRICKYARD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trading Places
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ When the green flag waves for Saturday's
Brickyard 400, a large contingent of local fans will tell you that
this is Indianapolis' biggest sporting event of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, even bigger than the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the Brickyard 400 is the race now,'' said
Curt Cavin, who covers motorsports for the Indianapolis Star. ``The
demand for everything surrounding this race is much higher than the
Indy 500. People here have acquired a taste for Winston Cup
racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the break between the Indy Racing League and CART,
support for the Indy 500 has declined the past two years. And
NASCAR, which began racing here in 1994, has more than filled the
void.
</P>
<P>
   The fans' hunger for speed and competition is being supplied by
such drivers as Jeff Gordon, Dale Jarrett, Dale Earnhardt, Rusty
Wallace and Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners around the track have noticed the change, and
some have made adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   George Harrison, who owns a racing collectibles store outside
Turn 1, points to the shelves in his store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around here,'' he said. ``It used to be all Indy stuff.
Now we have a little shelf for that, and the other 99 percent of
the place is NASCAR. The fans are fed up with the IRL-CART split.''
</P>
<P>
   But you won't find many Winston Cup officials or drivers who
will jump into the middle of the fray. They love racing Indy, but
they respect the history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Indy 500 still is one of the most prestigious
races in the world,'' said Dale Jarrett, the 1996 Brickyard
champion. ``I don't think there ever was any illusion that any of
us as NASCAR drivers had a thought of trying to replace that, and
(I) still don't think we're going to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the Brickyard has grown in stature in a short
period of time, as NASCAR races go,'' Jarrett said. ``It's
certainly one of the two or three that every driver here wants to
win. It's a huge, huge race for us in a lot of ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Irwin, who drives the No. 28 Taurus for Robert Yates and
grew up in this area racing the USAC open-wheel circuit, says
die-hard Indy fans will always be die-hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been coming to the 500 for years, have season tickets,
suite privileges and call the drivers by their first names,'' Irwin
said. ``But I think the people outside of Indianapolis and the
casual Indy-car fans would probably say the Brickyard is bigger
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Rawlings lives 54 miles from the speedway and has seen
every 500 since 1982. He wonders if the two factions ever will be
one again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy watching the Winston Cup boys, and they've filled some
of the void,'' Rawlings said. ``But I'm an open-wheel fan. I can't
see NASCAR ever being No. 1 here. I hope it's not wishful
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   IMS officials don't want to say which race is bigger, but it's
clear they're thrilled with the enormous success of the Brickyard
400, which will have a sellout crowd of 307,000 in the stands and
50,000 more in the infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those big dances. Everybody brings their best
stuff,'' Bobby Hamilton said. ``Win at Indy, and you know you've
beaten the best. I don't know if the Brickyard is surpassing the
Indy 500. I don't usually pay attention to stuff like that. But if
this Kodak Chevrolet is sitting in victory lane at the end of the
day, you can rest assured I believe the Brickyard 400 is bigger
than the Indy 500.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
