</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memorial funds set up in honor of killed fans
 &HT;    BY Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Families of two spectators killed in last weekend's
CART U.S. 500 at Michigan Speedway have designated charities for
those who want to make memorial contributions in their names.
</P>
<P>
   The designated charities are for Sheryl Ann Laster of the
American Cancer Society, 1599 Clifton Road NE, Atlanta, 30329, and
for Michael Terry Tautkus the National Kidney Foundation, 2350 S.
Huron Parkway, Ann Arbor, Mich. 48104. No requests have been made
yet for the third victim, Kenneth Dale Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Speedway has set up a national counseling ``hotline''
for spectators who might have been affected by the accident, at
800-253-2182.
</P>
<P>
   NHRA
</P>
<P>
   Like the fine wine from the vineyards that surround Sears Point
International Raceway in Sonoma, Calif., NHRA Pro Stock driver
Warren Johnson of Duluth just keeps improving with age. The
55-year-old GM Goodwrench Service Plus Pontiac driver scored his
fifth win of the season and the 68th of his career Sunday at the
Autolite Nationals. Johnson's victory tied him with Funny Car
driver John Force for the No. 2 spot on the list of all-time NHRA
winners and put him 210 points ahead of No. 2 Jeg Coughlin with
1,098. Son Kurt Johnson of Lawrenceville is No. 3 with 780 points.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta native Whit Bazemore made it to the Funny Car finals
before his Team Winston Camaro Z28 was defeated by Cruz Pedregon.
Heavy on Bazemore's mind is the impending loss _ in 1999 _ of his
Winston sponsorship. ``It's an emotional weekend, and to finish it
on the upside is good,'' Bazemore said. ``I have six weeks to land
a corporate sponsor that's willing and has the ability and the need
and recognizes the benefits of going out there and really competing
for a Winston championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia Tech star Tom Hammonds keeps getting better at
drag racing. The Minnesota Timberwolves power forward made it to
the second round of the Autolite Nationals in his Winnebago/Mac
Tools/ Kendall Camaro Z28, the second time in four races. Hammonds
debuted his Camaro in Columbus on June 12, qualified and won the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   Road Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Joe Foster has been named chief driving instructor for the Panoz
Racing School and the Panoz Performance Driving School, replacing
Jeff Purner, who was named Road Atlanta's manager of new business
development.
</P>
<P>
   Motocross
</P>
<P>
   Ezra Lusk of Bainbridge finished third in the AMA Mazda Truck
Motocross at Troy, Ohio. Jeff Emig of Riverside, Calif., won the
event, taking first place in Moto 1 and 2. Lusk finished 4-3, and
second-place finisher Doug Henry of Oxford, Conn., finished 5-2.
Henry remains points leader after eight events with 316. Lusk and
Emig are tied for fifth with 262
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
