<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Donnan: At least 6 recruits should play
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. -- Georgia football coach Jim Donnan said at
least six freshmen from the Bulldogs' highly regarded recruiting
class will play this season.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jasper Sanks of Columbus and quarterback Quincy
Carter of Decatur could have the best shots at extensive playing
time. Sanks, a Parade All-American at Carver High in 1996, attended
Fork Union (Va.) Military Academy last season. But Sanks, who
rushed for 5,043 yards during his prep career, reported to Athens a
few weeks ago a little heavier than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been disappointed that he's been in Athens this summer
and hasn't worked like our other players have worked,'' Donnan
said. ``I'm disappointed that he's not further along in his
conditioning. For him to be the kind of player we need him to be,
he needs to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanks reported at 230 pounds; Donnan wants him at 220.
</P>
<P>
   Sanks' emergence could be a key for the Bulldogs, who might be
forced to run early while developing an inexperienced quarterback.
Also returning in the backfield are senior Olandis Gary, junior
Patrick Pass and senior Ronnie Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good that we're going to build our offense around what
our quarterback can do and not what he can't do,'' Donnan said.
``We've always been pretty balanced, but we might be a little more
stubborn about running the ball even if it's not working.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia already has received a big boost, because freshmen
offensive lineman Jon Stinchcomb of Parkview High and linebacker
Boss Bailey of Charlton County High, who suffered serious knee
injuries as high school seniors, both appear ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan said freshman cornerback Tim Wansley of Buford and
first-year linebacker William Witherspoon of Panama City, Fla.,
also could receive extensive playing time.
</P>
<P>
   He's a Champ
</P>
<P>
   Donnan said junior cornerback Champ Bailey of Folkston would
probably play ``25 to 30 percent'' of the time on offense this
season. Bailey, an All-America candidate on defense, had 12 catches
for 234 yards last season, including two clutch receptions in
Georgia's 27-24 win at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best big-play guy that we've got,'' Donnan said.
``You need to have a guy like that when you've got a young
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   First commitment
</P>
<P>
   Georgia received its first verbal commitment, from defensive end
Shedrick Wynn of Lincoln County High. Wynn, 6-4, 235 pounds, is the
cousin of former Bulldogs running back Garrison Hearst. He also was
recruited by Tennessee, Clemson, Louisville, Georgia Tech and South
Carolina. Wynn had 76 tackles and 11 sacks as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
