<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mumme keeps QB out of spotlight
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. -- The conspicuous absence of quarterback Tim
Couch from SEC Media Days on Wednesday could be just the first of
several gestures from Kentucky coach Hal Mumme to bring attention
to other players and to lend some normalcy to what figures to be an
increasing spotlight for the junior quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Couch, who will have his own conference call with reporters next
week, was left home in favor of one of his main blockers, offensive
tackle Kris Comstock, and free safety Willie Gary.
</P>
<P>
   It underlined Mumme's assertion that the Wildcats, who were a
surprising 5-6 in his first season, have to present more than a
one-man show to build on the excitement of a high-flying passing
attack. Even if that one man threw for 3,884 yards and 37
touchdowns, and led the nation in pass attempts, completions,
yardage and a completion percentage of 66.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought never really crossed my mind that you guys would
want to talk to him,'' Mumme deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the questions were about Couch anyway, especially
about his candidacy for the Heisman Trophy. ``It's a great honor,
but football's a team sport,'' Mumme said.
</P>
<P>
   Strange feeling
</P>
<P>
   Since he got the Arkansas job in December, new top Razorback
Houston Nutt estimates that he has spoken to about 79 booster clubs
and groups around the state to drum up support for the program. But
it's nothing like the lengths he went to to get students to turn
out for games when he was at Division I-AA Murray State 1992-96.
</P>
<P>
   There, students were noticeably absent from games, until he
started making his rounds on fraternity row, at one house in
particular. ``They invited me to come at 12 midnight, even though I
thought 7 p.m. was more reasonable,'' Nutt said. ``They said,
'Coach, we don't get started around here until midnight.'''
</P>
<P>
   When Nutt arrived at the house, he was instructed to enter
through a window and then onto the roof, where he was handed a
bullhorn to invite students to a game the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was great,'' he said. ``It broke the student record. I
think we had about 3,000 students come out. I'd do it at Arkansas,
if I had to. But I don't think I'll have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
