<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tennessee turnout pleases officials
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though a massive downpour diminished the gate, the 3,757
spectators in Chattanooga on July 22 for a quarterfinal
doubleheader of the U.S Open Cup sent an encouraging signal about
interest in soccer as a spectator sport in the South.
</P>
<P>
   That's the opinion of a high-ranking U.S. Soccer Federation
official who is seeking the group's presidency next month. Current
executive vice president Larry Monaco, who attended the
doubleheader at Finley Stadium, said that outside of the Major
League Soccer markets, little has been done to attract soccer fans
to major competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reasons we came here,'' he said. ``We've got
to spread the game around. We can't keep going to MLS cities and
over-saturating them.''
</P>
<P>
   The figures in Chattanooga to see four MLS teams stacked up well
with those the same night in Dallas, an MLS city, where only 3,812
showed up at the Cotton Bowl for the other quarterfinal matches,
including one with the hometown Burn.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament semifinals will be held next week at a
10,000-seat stadium in New Orleans, and the finals are scheduled
for Aug. 26 in Virginia Beach, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Five figures again
</P>
<P>
   Women's World Cup organizers got some better news from the
Goodwill Games this week than the 2-0 win by the U.S. over China
would indicate. The crowd of better than 11,000 on Long Island
Tuesday is the sixth five-figure crowd the women have played in
front of this season at home, a positive sign about attendance
projections for next summer.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150,000 tickets have been sold for the Women's World
Cup, which will be played in seven cities. All first-round matches
will be played in a doubleheader format to ensure a healthier gate,
although there are concerns about the draw for games not involving
the U.S. or other favorites _ Germany, Norway, China, Italy and
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey kicks it around
</P>
<P>
   Anyone doubting Disney's interest in attaching itself to soccer
should tune in the MLS All-Star weekend in Orlando. The typical
all-star fare that includes a Celebrity Rock 'n' Soccer game is on
tap at Disney's Wide World of Sports Complex.
</P>
<P>
   It starts at 8 p.m. Friday on ESPN2, which will show a highlight
program of the first half of the MLS season Saturday at 10 a.m.
ESPN will air a players' skills challenge Saturday at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The all-star game is taking a page from the National Hockey
League, featuring MLS stars from the U.S. against the league's best
international competitors. The game at the Florida Citrus Bowl
begins at 2:30 p.m. Sunday on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   MLS and Disney recently extended a television contract with
ABC/ESPN/ESPN2 through the year 2000. Disney also is interested in
pursuing a possible expansion franchise in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo has no regrets
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's 3-0 loss in the World Cup finals was considered
``disastrous'' enough for coach Mario Zagallo and his entire staff
to get the pink slip Tuesday. But the white-haired veteran of all
four Brazilian World Cup triumphs, either as a player or coach,
insists he'll hold his head high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not walking away distraught. I've been to five World Cup
finals, with four wins and a runner-up finish. I'm very proud of
what I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Valderrama fined
</P>
<P>
   After the Miami Fusion fired coach ``Cacho'' Cordoba last week,
Colombian center Carlos Valderrama sulked, missing two practices
and getting left out of Sunday's win over New England. On Tuesday,
he received an MLS record fine of $10,000 for his absences.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
