<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tyson snaps during hearing
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ In his quest to show that he now has``good
character, honesty, integrity and responsibility,'' as mandated by
the statutes of the New Jersey Athletic Commission, Mike Tyson made
one fatal mistake Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He failed to go the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, appearing before state officials in an attempt to regain
the boxing license he lost last year after biting Evander Holyfield
twice, was on his best behavior for 3 1/2 hours at the Hughes
Justice Complex.
</P>
<P>
   Then he snapped. After Anthony Fusco, the fighter's attorney,
asked the commission rhetorically, ``How many times should one man
have to (answer), `Are you sorry for what you did?'''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson nodded approvingly and vented, ``You know what I mean,
man? Why do I have to relive my (bleeping). ...''
</P>
<P>
   Fusco immediately put his hand on Tyson's shoulder and cautioned
him to ``relax.'' The lawyer then said he felt too frustrated to
read a statement he intended for his closing remarks and told the
commission, ``It's one thing to criticize (Tyson), but you don't
want to look for a crucifixion, and that's the frustration that you
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Tyson's outburst, it would be surprising if New Jersey
rejected his application. He has maintained a relatively low
profile in the past year and the amount of dollars he generates for
the sport and any local economy hosting one of his fights is
unparalleled.
</P>
<P>
   Three board members of the New Jersey commission will meet in a
closed session Aug. 6 to determine Tyson's fate and will announce a
decision within two days.
</P>
<P>
   Even Holyfield, who has the greatest reason to hold a grudge
against Tyson, thinks that Tyson has been ``sufficiently penalized
over the past year,'' according to a brief letter signed by him
that Fusco entered into evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson had his license revoked by Nevada for at least one year
and was fined $3 million after his disqualification loss to
Holyfield in June 1997 in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson camp members deny they are trying to circumvent Nevada and
made the same claim to New Jersey officials. Tyson has said he
always enjoyed fighting in Atlantic City but hasn't had a bout
there since a December 1990 win over Alex Stewart. Then came the
rape trial, three years in prison, a lucrative deal with the MGM in
Las Vegas upon his return and promoter Don King's inability to
obtain a promoter's license in New Jersey because of legal
problems. If the license is granted, Tyson figures to fight a
non-ranked fighter before the end of the year and at least one more
warmup bout before possibly pursuing a title fight. A third fight
against Holyfield remains a long shot for financial and logistical
reasons. Holyfield is interested in only three bouts: mandatory
defenses against Vaughn Bean and Henry Akinwande to retain his IBF
and WBA belts, and a unification fight against Lennox Lewis next
spring or summer.
</P>
<P>
   However, some people still find repulsive the idea of Tyson
making millions again. Bear Atwood, one of 10 members of the New
Jersey chapter of the National Organization for Women picketing
outside the judicial building, wore a button that read, ``Stop
honoring and rewarding violent athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't even make it through a hearing without losing it,''
Atwood said. ``We're suppose to believe that he's now under
control? How does he meet the criteria of having good character?''
</P>
<P>
   Fusco tried to portray Tyson as an angelic creature, lining up
seven character witnesses to testify. All were either Tyson's
friends or had financial ties to him.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Rotman, a New Jersey psychologist, asked if he would be
compensated for his court appearance, replied, ``I hope so.'' Asked
how much, Rotman said, ``I have to go back and work out a bill,''
drawing laughter from an audience of approximately 200 people.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, who wore a dark gray suit and a black shirt, wasn't
quizzed until nearly three hours into the hearing and answered
questions for 45 minutes. He appeared to grow irritated as Haas
went over every detail of his rape conviction and the ear-biting
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the ear bite, Tyson reiterated that he thought that
Holyfield head-butted him in their two fights. ``I don't even know
why I bit Mr. Holyfield. I don't even know how I did it. I went
berserk.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the head-butts, Tyson said, ``I was blacking out. I
was getting light-headed. I snapped. ... I'm very sorry. My life
has been devastated by this.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the rape conviction and Holyfield fight had
changed him, Tyson said, ``Both of those ordeals ruined my life
internally. Do you think I want to do it again?''
</P>
<P>
   The character witnesses said he felt remorseful. Shelly Finkel,
Tyson's new adviser, said the boxer rejected multiple offers ``in
excess of $10 million each'' for Tyson to fight in Russia,
Scandinavia, Germany and the Middle East in the past year because
he wanted to serve the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
