<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACING-IRL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Speed is name of IRL game
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eddie Cheever Jr. was cruising around the speedy, asphalt
Atlanta Motor Speedway quad-oval Wednesday afternoon. On a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   This was a guy who was going to zoom around later at speeds of
220 mph or better, but the bike served a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for bumps,'' the 1998 Indy 500 winner said,
``and working on race strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheever and some of his Indy Racing League (IRL) competitors
were in Atlanta on Tuesday and Wednesday, practicing for the Aug.
29 Atlanta 500 Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, while IRL drivers practiced on a track used
primarily by stock cars, NASCAR drivers were at Indy getting ready
for the Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   For the stock-car drivers it was a trip to America's hallowed
racing mecca.
</P>
<P>
   For the IRL drivers, it was a chance to really feed that need
for speed.
</P>
<P>
   The good ol' boys will probably be the bigger draw this year.
AMS general manager Ed Clark said, ``I'll be pleased if we can have
about 50,000'' attend the IRL race. That many were at Charlotte
last week.
</P>
<P>
   It's a getting-acquainted process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' Cheever said. ``That's the future for you. Race
fans will have more types of racing available.''
</P>
<P>
   And the speed. Last week, IRL drivers averaged 214 mph.
</P>
<P>
   At Atlanta, it will be faster, Cheever said, because of the
smoother surface _ ``flat as my mother's pancakes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It don't get no better than this,'' said the American, who was
raised in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   It will be something racing fans this far south normally don't
see or hear _ open-wheel racing under the lights at lightning
speeds. Cheever predicted that the driver who can average 218 mph
will win.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred and eighteen mph. Stock cars might get in the 190s
at AMS on a test run, but IRL drivers will go into the turns at
220, three abreast.
</P>
<P>
   Clark compared the IRL cars' swiftness to F-16s. They swoop
around the track with their trademark throaty roar, reeking of raw
power, produced by four-liter, 32-valve Oldsmobile Aurora V-8
engines. A.J. Foyt, who has raced everything and won almost
everything, had his team here and was enthusiastic about the
renovated AMS. ``These cars work a lot better than stock cars,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Michigan 500 tragedy last weekend _ when three
spectators were killed by hurtling debris _ safety is a big factor.
AMS' track is surrounded by a sharply angled safety fence.
</P>
<P>
   As for fan turnout, Foyt has this to say: ``Atlanta is like
Houston. If you don't come up with something special, they won't
come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
