<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SOFT-CELLUCCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI WON'T RELEASE SOFT-MONEY LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In his first public comments on the issue Wednesday,
Acting Governor Paul Cellucci declined to release the list of large
corporate and individual donations he solicited for a Republican
Governors Association fundraiser.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, who has denounced the use of such soft-money donations
in campaigns, referred all inquiries to the governor's association,
saying only the Washington-based group can release the names.
``That's up to them,'' Cellucci said. ``It's their list.''
</P>
<P>
   Association officials would only point to their filings at the
Federal Election Commission, but those lists do not indicate which
donations were solicited by Cellucci or his fundraising team.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have charged Cellucci skirted state campaign finance
laws that require disclosure by raising the money. The donations,
which ranged up to $40,000 for the June 26 Boston event, were to be
deposited into a national Republican fund that is used to
distribute money back to state campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Democratic gubernatorial candidate Patricia McGovern
joined the chorus of candidates and others who are demanding
Cellucci release the list of donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``To hide it, to launder it....is a disgrace,'' McGovern said.
She said much of the national GOP's soft-money funds are from
controversial special interests groups like the gun lobby, tobacco
industry, and major polluters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to know, did the gun lobby give to Paul Cellucci?''
McGovern told reporters at a State House press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Democratic candidate, Attorney General Scott
Harshbarger and former US Representative Brian J. Donnelly, have
also called on Cellucci to release the list. So has his Republican
rival, state Treasurer Joseph D. Malone.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci lashed back at McGovern and the others, saying they
must first get a commitment from the state Democratic Party that it
will not use the soft-money donations that it has already and will
continue to pour into Massachusetts. ``Then come back to me,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci cited a statement by Democratic national chairman Steve
Grossman that the party is going to use soft money to win back the
governorship in Massachusetts. ``What is she going to do about
that?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern has said that if she wins the nomination she will call
on the state committee not to use any soft-money donations whose
source is not made public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
