<SLUG> BC-TRW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRW MAY CUSHION ARIZONA WORKERS FROM JOB CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER AND CRAIG ANDERSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. - One of Mesa's biggest private employers said
Wednesday that it will cut 7,500 workers worldwide and close up to
21 factories in its automotive division.
</P>
<P>
   But the growing use of automotive air bags may cushion the blow
to TRW Inc.'s 3,500 workers in east Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be looking primarily at where our sales are and
aren't,'' company spokesman Jay McCaffrey said. ``Air bags are a
very good product for TRW.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked which workers or plants will be affected, McCaffrey added,
``At this point, it's impossible for me to say.''
</P>
<P>
   The company plans on announcing details of the cutbacks, which
amount to 14 percent of its workforce, later this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland-based conglomerate, which makes a wide variety of
products for space, defense and information systems, is targeting
its automotive products group based on ever-shrinking profits.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few growth areas in the division has been air bags,
especially those used for side-impact crashes. TRW, the largest
maker of U.S. air bags, produced 19 million air bags worldwide in
1997, up from 13 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But growth in the business doesn't guarantee jobs for TRW's Mesa
employees, who make parts for inflatable air bags used in both the
driver and passenger side of automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, TRW laid off about 20 workers in Mesa as part of a
1 percent North American workforce reduction in the inflatible
restraint division. And last week, an additional 100 employees took
a voluntary one-month layoff with health and other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   TRW spokeswoman Linda Ellerbusch said there are no indications
that employees who voluntarily left now would be cut permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're anticipating the return of all our employees,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   TRW built its first factory in Mesa in 1989. It expanded in the
Phoenix area with a second facility two years later. The area has
the largest of TRW's six U.S. air-bag manufacturing plants.
</P>
<P>
   In the past several years, the company has been fined for
multiple safety violations after an explosion of sodium-azide
propellant resulted in the death of a construction worker in 1994.
Several others also were injured.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the labor dispute between the United Auto Workers
and General Motors Corp. prompted the company to ask for volunteers
to take a month off without pay. It also eliminated 400 jobs at a
seat-belt plant in Mexico, and its second-quarter earnings slipped
6 percent due, in part, to the strike.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown has led to rumors that more cutbacks were in the
works.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't surprise me at all,'' said a former manager laid
off in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were originally going to trim 1 percent on the
engineering side,'' he said. ``I was in that 1 percent. Then I
heard they were going to trim the manufacturing side 10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   TRW CEO Peter Hellerman has said that cost cutting is his top
goal for the year.
</P>
<P>
   TRW will take a pre-tax charge of $125 million to $150 million
in the next year to cover the plant closing and severance packages
for affected workers.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street anaylsts applauded the move. Its stock closed at 54
and 7/8, up 3/8 for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something they need to do and if they don't do it,
they're goisng to continue to suffer,'' said Brian Eisenbarth, an
analyst with Collins &AMP; Co. in San Francisco. ``They need to get
costs down.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Casey, an analyst with Midwest Research in Cleveland,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably better that they take a hard swallow and follow
through on the actions that they announced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Casey and Eisenbarth said they forecast continued growth in
air bag sales, especially in side-impact units.
</P>
<P>
   Both also agreed that problems with worker safety and explosions
will not make either TRW factory in Mesa more of a target than
other facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll look at it from more of an operating-cost
perspective,'' said Casey. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kerry Fehr-Snyder can be reached at kerry.fehr(at)pni.com via
e-mail. Craig Anderson can be reached at craig.anderson(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
