<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMAS-SPEECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARENCE THOMAS RESPONDS ANGRILY TO HIS CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., La.)  (mk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ In an explosion of pent-up anger, Justice
Clarence Thomas on Wednesday lashed out at his critics, both black
and white, saying they were racists who have been unable to accept
the notion that he is able to think for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I refuse to have my ideas assigned to me because I am black,''
he told an audience of several hundred black judges and lawyers.
His critics, he said, have subjected him to particularly ``bilious
and venomous assaults'' because his conservative views and judicial
opinions since he joined the court in 1991 do not conform to what
is expected of a black man.
</P>
<P>
   Up until Wednesday, Thomas has generally confined his public
speeches to small and friendly audiences. But in speaking before
the National Bar Association, the nation's largest group of black
lawyers, Thomas was facing a very mixed group, some of whom had
openly protested his invitation to address the convention.
</P>
<P>
   His critics, Thomas said, have engaged in what he called silly
speculation that he must be taking his cues and ideas from other
conservative justices on the court who are white. ``What else could
be the explanation when I fail to follow their ideology or
anti-intellectual prescription,'' he said. ``The stench of racial
inferiority still confounds my olfactory nerves.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' troubled relationship with his fellow black Americans
was on vivid public display in his appearance before the annual
convention of the bar association. It was an event to which he had
been invited months ago, only to have a large and prominent group
of members attempt to have the invitation rescinded. He told the
audience of more than 2,000 that it had become a wearisome ritual
that when he is invited to speak publicly, people seek to deny him
that opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But he suggested that his acceptance of Wednesday's invitation
was like when he was younger and ``tired of turning the other
cheek.'' As for those who have said he has forgotten his black
roots, he said they were engaging in ``psychosilliness'' and
probably had too much time on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Although his delivery was calm, his words Wednesday were harsher
than ever before. At one point he said his critics were
``illiterate'' and that many of them had been ``half-steppers'' in
earlier times, a black expression meaning they were craven
appeasers of white people.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his speech, Thomas said, ``Despite some of the
nonsense that has been said about me, I am a man, I am a black man,
I am an American.'' He added, ``Isn't it time to move on? To be
angry with me solves no problems.''
</P>
<P>
   About half the audience applauded, some standing, while the
other half remained silent.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following the speech, several hundred lawyers and
judges went into an adjoining room to hear Thomas' critics analyze
his work and compare him unfavorably to the man he replaced on the
court, Thurgood Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Leon Higginbotham, the former chief judge of the 3rd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, based in Philadelphia, and one of Thomas'
most consistent critics, said Thomas was deceptive in his speech
Wednesday. He had said his critics purposely misinterpreted his
dissent in a 1992 case in which he wrote that it was not a
violation of the Constitution's proscription against ``cruel and
unusual punishment'' when a black prisoner was beaten by guards. He
described the injuries as minor, but Higginbotham said that the
shackled prisoner was beaten so badly his dental plate was broken,
his lips were burst and some teeth were loosened.
</P>
<P>
   Higginbotham had argued before Wednesday's event that it was a
mistake to have Thomas be the bar association's keynote speaker
because that would bestow an undeserved honor on someone whose
rulings on the court ``have done more to turn back the clock of
racial progress than any other African-American public official in
the history of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernette Johnson, a member of the Louisiana Supreme Court and
chairwoman of the bar association's judicial council, said she knew
the choice of speaker would be controversial. But Ms. Johnson said
that she did not view extending the invitation as an honor to
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, she said, ``It gives us a chance to interact with a
Supreme Court justice and dialogue is always good.''
</P>
<P>
   But like most of those who supported the invitation , Ms.
Johnson said she disagreed strongly with Thomas' views and his
writings on the Supreme Court. ``I'm not an apologist for him,''
she said. ``I'm just saying he has a right to say what he says.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Bar Association opposed Thomas' confirmation to the
court when he was nominated in 1991, largely over his conservative
views and outspoken opposition to affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas offered a fervent defense of his views against
affirmative action programs Wednesday, telling the audience that
such programs are inevitably based on black inferiority and are
``non-starters in my view. I do not believe kneeling is a position
of strength and I do not believe that begging is an effective
tactic.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' opponents have said his views on affirmative action are
particularly galling since he was a major beneficiary of such
programs, including his admission to Yale Law School under an
explicit set-aside program for minority students. Keith Watters, a
Washington lawyer and a former president of the National Bar
Association, said that he decided at the last minute to picket the
speech outside the hotel because he found Thomas' views so
hypocritical.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
