<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRIPP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPP DEFENDS TAPING HER CONVERSATIONS WITH LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-MOOD, CLINTON-TALKINGPOINTS) 
(sw) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Linda Tripp, the woman whose secret tape recordings
of Monica Lewinsky started the sex-and-perjury investigation of
President Clinton, emerged on Wednesday from her eighth and final
day of grand jury testimony and told America to think of her as
Everywoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm you,'' Mrs. Tripp said in a bitter apologia outside the
federal courthouse. ``I'm just like you. I'm an average American
who found herself in a situation not of her own making. I'm a
suburban mom, who was a military wife for 20 years, and a faithful
government employee for 18 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The 48-year-old Pentagon assistant complained that she had been
vilified by middle America for tape-recording the confidences of
her close friend and colleague, mocked by late-night comedians for
her physical appearance and attacked as untruthful by the
president's personal lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   But in her dramatic statement before reporters and
photographers, Mrs. Tripp portrayed herself as a victim of
circumstances, a reluctant witness to wrongdoing and a nonpartisan
patriot who is without malice or a political agenda and whose only
motive is the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This investigation has never been, quote, `just about sex,' ''
she said, her hands shaking, her voice halting as she struggled to
catch her breath while reading from a prepared text. ``It has been
about telling the truth, the truth matters.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I have been vilified for taking the path of truth.
I've been maligned by people who have chosen not to tell the truth,
and who know that they are not telling the truth. That's a pretty
frightening thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Banished in 1994 from the White House to a basement cubicle in
the Pentagon, Mrs. Tripp quietly laid plans two years later to
write a tell-all book chronicling what she believed were the
secrets and lies of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   She hinted at those events on Wednesday, saying, ``I became
aware between 1993 and 1997 of actions by high government officials
that may have been against the law.'' Knowledge of those events,
she added, ``made me increasingly fearful that this information was
dangerous, very dangerous to possess.''
</P>
<P>
   The day last January when she approached the Office of the
Independent Counsel was the day she decided that ``fear would no
longer be my master,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She did not explain exactly why she turned on a friend and began
tape-recording their telephone conversations. But she praised Ms.
Lewinsky for her decision to testify before the grand jury about
her sexual relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am encouraged that it appears from press reports that Monica
has decided to cooperate with the independent counsel,'' Mrs. Tripp
said. ``The facts will show that, time after time, I urged her to
tell the truth right up until the end.''
</P>
<P>
   With her son, Ryan, and daughter, Allison, her two lawyers and a
press spokesman standing behind her, Mrs. Tripp used the occasion
not only to proclaim her own innocence but to point fingers at
others, including Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I am just like you, I ask you to imagine how you would
feel if someone you thought was a friend urged you to commit a
felony that could jeopardize your job, potentially put you in jail
and endanger the well being of your children,'' Mrs. Tripp said, an
apparent reference to a suggestion by Ms. Lewinsky that Mrs. Tripp
deny any knowledge of a sexual relationship between Clinton and Ms.
Lewinsky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine how you would feel if your employer illegally released
your confidential records to the media, then demoted you and cast
you aside for daring to tell the truth,'' she said of her bosses at
the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon insists that it did not demote Mrs. Tripp from her
$88,137-a-year job, but had changed the job description to
acquiesce to her request to work at home after the scandal broke.
But the Pentagon did tell reporters that Mrs. Tripp may have lied
on a security clearance form in 1987 when she said she had never
been arrested. (She was arrested when she was 19 on a charge of
grand larceny; the case was dismissed).
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine how you would feel if your boss' attorney called you a
liar in front of the whole country,'' she said of a statement last
year by Robert Bennett, Clinton's personal lawyer, that she was not
believable. ``And imagine if that boss was the president of the
United States.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Mrs. Tripp expressed anger about the way in which she
has been publicly portrayed. She charged ``people'' whom she did
not name with enlisting `'legions of paid prevaricators'' to attack
her. And she expressed hurt that entertainers had chosen to
ridicule her, ``going so far as to even make fun of my appearance
in a manner so mean and so cruel that I pray none of you is ever
subjected to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
