<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING TICKETS GO UNCLAIMED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Maybe you watched the Powerball drawing last night,
like I did, checked the winning numbers against your tickets and
cursed your rotten luck.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you'd made a special trip to the convenience store on your
way home from work in order to buy the tickets. Maybe that caused
you to be late and your family ate dinner without you and by the
time you got home they were all watching TV or talking on the
telephone or out somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you didn't even tell them you'd bought the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   You wanted to surprise them.
</P>
<P>
   You pictured yourself sneaking into the living room in the
middle of the night and blasting ``For the Love of Money'' by the
O'Jays on the stereo until they all woke up wondering what the heck
was going on and found you out there holding the winning ticket
above your head shouting ``WE'RE RICH!!!''
</P>
<P>
   But, you didn't win.
</P>
<P>
   You never win, except in your dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you pictured yourself buying news houses and new cars for
family and close friends.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you even made a secret pact with God concerning the many
charitable deeds you planned to perform after winning Powerball.
You genuinely believe a person with money has that kind of
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Also, you figured having the Big Guy on your side could go a
long way toward improving your luck.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   So, you tore up the tickets and tossed them in the trash and
told no one. When asked, you said you didn't buy any tickets
because lotteries are for saps who have never won a thing in their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Like you.
</P>
<P>
   Today, you'll leave work and drive straight home.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose that means you have a job and a car and a place to
live. And, if you drive, you must be relatively healthy. If you
weren't, the lottery would be the last thing on your mind.
</P>
<P>
   When you get home your kids will be there.
</P>
<P>
   And a spouse.
</P>
<P>
   They're healthy too.
</P>
<P>
   You have food on the table and telephone service and a TV.
</P>
<P>
   You have a few extra bucks in your pocket, or did, until you
stopped by the the convenience store to buy lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of winning were 80 million to 1 but you laid your money
down anyway, thinking you might get lucky.
</P>
<P>
   You had a 5,000 to 1 chance of being killed in a car crash on
your way to buy the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   You weren't.
</P>
<P>
   You had a 2 million to 1 chance of being sucked up by a tornado
before you got home.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen, either.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the drawing, you could have fallen out of bed
and died. The odds of that happening also were 2 million to 1. The
same as getting killed by a wild animal.
</P>
<P>
   Life is a crap shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone's life.
</P>
<P>
   I'm wondering what the odds were that my grandfathers would make
it out of hill towns in Italy all those years ago, onto boats and
over to America.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't know each other in the old country. Imagine the
probability that each of them would wind up in Pittsburgh working
in the same steel mill.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, it was a long shot for the children of poor
families to survive, but the babies who would become my mother and
father did.
</P>
<P>
   Then I came along, and by the wildest chance bumped into a
beautiful brown-eyed girl.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you have two kids and a house and a car and a few extra
bucks in your pocket to blow on games of chance, which you never
win because you're unlucky.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe the unlucky ones aren't those with the wrong
Powerball numbers, but those who hit the lottery a long time ago,
and still don't know it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
