<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   CORRECTED WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 216.
WASHINGTON, July 29 -- The following chart shows how senators and
house representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the
last week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: GUNSAFETY
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, July 21, the Senate voted, 61-39, to table, or set
aside, an amendment that would have required handguns to be sold
with child-proof safety devices. Supporters of the amendment said
it would protect children from handgun accidents. Opponents said
the amendment was an unnecessary federal regulation and would not
accomplish its purpose. A ``yes'' vote favors setting aside, or
rejecting, the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: GUNOWNERS
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, July 22, the Senate voted, 69-31, to table, or set
aside, a measure that would have allowed federal prosecution of gun
owners whose weapons were used by children in a crime, if the guns
were stored insecurely. Supporters of the measure said it would
have kept guns out of children's hands by requiring people to keep
their guns out of reach. Opponents argued that innocent people
could be held responsible if children found a way to access the
guns, even though they were properly stored. A ``yes'' vote favors
setting aside, or rejecting, the measure.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
<P>
   --- ---
</P>
<P>
   THERE ARE NO HOUSE VOTES THIS WEEK.
</P>
<P>
   The attendance record tracks the cumulative attendance of
members to date when they are physically present for roll call
votes.
</P>
<P>
   ------------------
</P>
<P>
   SENATE ATTENDANCE Present and Voting
</P>
<P>
   ------------------
</P>
<P>
   ------------------
</P>
