<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-STATEMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPP DISMISSES CRITICS AS `PAID' LIARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Linda Tripp, who secretly recorded telephone
conversations with Monica Lewinsky, bitterly dismissed critics of
her role in the investigation of President Clinton as ``paid
prevaricators.''
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional statement following her final day of grand jury
testimony in the sex and cover-up probe said she is not the villain
portrayed by her detractors.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp described herself as a former military wife, a mother and
federal employee with no political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am you, I am just like you,'' Tripp said, looking into a
forest of TV cameras outside the U.S. District Courthouse. ``I am
an average American who found herself in a situation not of her own
making.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been vilified for having taken the path of truth,'' she
said. ``I have been maligned by people who have chosen not to tell
the truth and who know they are not telling the truth. That is a
pretty frightening thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To cast me in the role of the villain, they have enlisted
legions of paid prevaricators,'' Tripp said. ``Not surprisingly,
many in the entertainment industry have chosen to ridicule me as
well, going so far as to even make fun of my appearance in a manner
so mean and so cruel that I pray none of you is ever subjected to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripp said that during her tenure as a secretary in the Clinton
White House she ``became aware ... of actions by high government
officials that may have been against the law.'' This knowledge made
her ``increasingly fearful'' and she decided ``this information was
dangerous, extremely dangerous to possess.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in January, she contacted independent counsel Kenneth Starr,
who already was investigating Clinton's Arkansas business dealings.
Within days, Tripp agreed to turn over her tapes of Lewinsky's
conversations and cooperate with Starr as he expanded his inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided that fear would no longer be my master,'' said
Tripp, who was transferred in August 1994 from her White House job
to a position at the Pentagon, where records from her personnel
file were leaked to a reporter after the Lewinsky matter became
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine how you would feel if your employer released your
records to the media, then demoted you,'' Tripp said, her voice
quavering and her hands shaking as she read her statement.
``Imagine how you would feel if your boss' attorney called you a
liar in front of the whole country. Imagine if that boss was the
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripp did not discuss her grand jury appearances except to say
she told the truth and was glad her testimony is over. She took no
questions, thus leaving unanswered why she made the tapes, whether
anyone put her up to it, and exactly what _ other than ``fear'' _
prompted her to go to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
