<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-MIYAZAWA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN PICKS EX-PREMIER AS FINANCE CHIEF TO GUIDE IT IN CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Kiichi Miyazawa, a veteran politician who only five
years ago was forced out of office as prime minister, was named
finance minister Wednesday and charged with steering Japan out of
its worst financial crisis in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa is a familiar face to U.S. officials, who have worked
with him for more than four decades, as he held a variety of senior
posts. And he is a veteran of the Finance Ministry, the powerful
institution that in recent years has fallen into disgrace in a
series of scandals and accusations of mismanagement of the world's
second-largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also Miyazawa, serving as finance minister in the
late 1980s, who oversaw the growth of the Japan's ``bubble
economy,'' and starting this week he will be charged with cleaning
up the enormous mess that the bursting of that bubble has caused.
</P>
<P>
   Although Miyazawa, 78, appeared hesitant to accept the post in
recent days, he was persuaded to do so by Keizo Obuchi, the new
president of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party who is to be
confirmed as prime minister Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   According to Japanese news reports, Obuchi has also chosen his
deputy, Masahiko Komura, to be foreign minister, Deputy Chief
Cabinet Secretary Fukushiro Nukaga as defense minister and former
Education Minister Kaoru Yosano as trade minister.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi has little expertise in financial engineering himself and
needs a powerful finance minister to give his administration
credibility in a skeptical world. Many consider the choice of a
finance minister to be more important than the selection of the
prime minister, and in many ways, the next finance minister will in
fact be a more pivotal and powerful figure than Obuchi. But while
Miyazawa is well known internationally, and negotiated the Clinton
administration's first major trade accord with Japan, he has not
been considered politically powerful at home.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa will take the ministry's helm at a critical juncture.
The economy has stalled, unemployment is climbing to unheard of
levels and the banking system is seriously ill.
</P>
<P>
   More and more economists are drawing comparisons to the Showa
Depression of the late 1920s, which lasted more than a decade. The
Japanese press has compared Miyazawa with Korekiyo Takahashi, a
politician and financial expert of the time, whose suspension of
the gold standard and increase of government spending helped combat
the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what Miyazawa will do to fix Japan's economic
woes. He has reportedly been involved in the ``total plan'' to
clean up the banking system, which will be debated in the special
session of Parliament that begins Thursday and which is generally
regarded as a step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   World financial markets have so far greeted rumors of Miyazawa's
appointment with cautious optimism. The yen has traded in a narrow
band ever since his name first appeared in the press as the
favorite candidate, and the Nikkei Stock Average has climbed as his
appointment has seemed more certain.
</P>
<P>
   A concern about Miyazawa is his age. He initially declined the
job for that reason.
</P>
<P>
   But his years of experience dealing with Japan's carefully
orchestrated government financial system, including a stint as
finance minister in the 1980s, as well as his outspoken support of
Obuchi in the recent party election, made him an obvious choice for
a job that few people seemed to want.
</P>
<P>
   He will inherit the task of weeding out the banking system,
which is suffocating under bad debt, and of fashioning policies to
drag Japan out of its doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa did speak out last fall, when the banking and
securities industries seemed on the verge of a meltdown, urging
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto to commit to using public funds to
bail out the financial system.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa is regarded as one of the more globally minded of the
senior ruling party members. He speaks English well, one of the few
Japanese politicians of his generation to do so, and his daughter,
Keiko, is married to Christopher Lafleur, deputy chief of mission
at the U.S. Embassy in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   He worked closely with Nicholas Brady, the Treasury secretary
during the Bush administration, in putting together a bailout for
Latin American nations.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier this year, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin sought
out Miyazawa while the Japanese politician was on a trip to New
York to suggest some ideas Japan might want to consider for pumping
up domestic demand and jump-starting its economy.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa was forced to resign as finance minister in 1988 after
being implicated in a scandal surrounding Recruit Co. efforts to
buy political influence.
</P>
<P>
   He is also remembered in some quarters for his economic
prescriptions in the mid-1980s, when he was a high-ranking party
official jockeying to become a candidate for prime minister. His
views helped create the ``bubble'' that defined Japan in the 1980s
and became the root of its problems Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa will be the first former Japanese prime minister in the
postwar era to take a job in the Cabinet after serving as prime
minister. He was prime minister from 1991 until 1993, when he
resigned after the Liberal Democrats lost control of Parliament, a
setback from which they have yet to fully recover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
