</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TALKINGPOINTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LAST, MYSTERY OF `TALKING POINTS' APPEARS TO BE SOLVED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-TRIPP, CLINTON-MOOD) 
(sw) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In Kenneth Starr's six-month investigation of
President Clinton and the former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky, few subjects have fueled more speculation than a
three-page document known as ``the talking points.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the authorship of the document remained a mystery until
this week, the talking points had always been portrayed as an
important piece of physical evidence in Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Ms. Lewinsky provided at least a partial solution to
the guessing game that has consumed Washington. As she began talks
with the office of the independent counsel as part of an immunity
deal, Ms. Lewinsky said she was prepared to testify that she wrote
the talking points, said lawyers familiar with her account. While
someone else may have helped her, she has also said no one at the
White House was involved, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky gave the talking points to her former friend and
Pentagon colleague, Linda Tripp, on Jan. 14, after both women were
summoned to testify in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct suit
against Clinton. Unknown to Ms. Lewinsky, Ms. Tripp was already
cooperating with Starr, and she later gave him the talking points.
</P>
<P>
   The document appeared intended to coach Ms. Tripp to give benign
answers to potential questions in the Jones case, especially
involving Clinton's alleged encounter in a hallway just off the
Oval Office with Kathleen Willey, a former White House volunteer.
The document contained suggested language for Ms. Tripp, including,
``You never observed the president behaving inappropriately with
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation that someone in the White House _ perhaps Bruce
Lindsey, the presidential aide and confidant _ helped write the
talking points was published and broadcast widely by the news
media. The speculation persisted after both the White House and a
spokesman for Lindsey denied any involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The news that Ms. Lewinsky had claimed authorship and exonerated
the White House was greeted with elation there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talking points were the basis of Ken Starr's
investigation,'' said Rahm Emanuel, senior adviser to the
president. ``They were the only venue of legitimacy. And now that's
been stripped away.''
</P>
<P>
   The talking points were one area of Starr's investigation into
possible obstruction of justice and subornation of perjury. But
they were not the only basis for the investigation. The independent
counsel is also investigating whether efforts to help Ms. Lewinsky
get a job were part of an attempt to shape her testimony in the
Jones case, lawyers familiar with the investigation said.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution of the talking points mystery may have sparked
even more ill will between Ms. Lewinsky and Mrs. Tripp. On
Wednesday, Mrs. Tripp angrily denied news reports that she had
helped Ms. Lewinsky prepare the document.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had nothing, let me repeat, nothing to do with preparing the
so-called talking points,'' she said after completing her eighth
and final day of grand jury testimony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
