<HEADER>
A9293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENDANT-NYT &LR;      07-29 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENDANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENDANT SHARES UP 8 PERCENT AFTER BOARDROOM CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Fla.) (jw) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cendant Corp., which is struggling to emerge from an accounting
scandal that erupted in April, saw its shares rise by more than 8
percent in heavy trading Wednesday, as investors reacted to
sweeping boardroom changes announced after the market had closed on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The shares closed Wednesday at $18.375, up from $17, on volume
exceeding 16.4 million shares, making it the most active New York
Stock Exchange issue.
</P>
<P>
   Trading on Tuesday had been buoyed by early reports that
auditors did not expect to make more revisions to estimates of the
scandal's financial impact on the company, which is a direct
marketer and franchiser that owns brands like Avis car rentals and
Ramada hotels.
</P>
<P>
   All told, shares of Cendant, formed in December from the merger
of HFS Inc. and CUC International, have gained more than 16 percent
since Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's advance followed the announcement the night before
that Walter Forbes, Cendant's chairman and the founder and former
chairman of CUC, had resigned, along with eight other former CUC
directors who sat on Cendant's board. His resignation was the
latest in a series of events that began on April 16, when Cendant
announced the discovery of serious ``accounting irregularities'' at
businesses formerly operated by CUC.
</P>
<P>
   In resigning, Forbes insisted he had been unaware of the
accounting irregularities, which are under investigation by
Cendant's audit committee, federal prosecutors and the Securities
and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional investors had been pressing for Forbes'
resignation, and their demands intensified after Cendant disclosed
July 14 that the accounting irregularities were considerably more
pervasive than it had originally reported. The company expects to
revise its financial statements for the last three years, and it
substantially reduced its reported 1997 operating profits as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   The company's shares, which have traded as high as $41.6875,
fell 46 percent when the accounting problems were first disclosed
and weakened further when the bad news worsened. This week's rally
is only a small respite for Henry Silverman, Cendant's chief
executive, who added the title of chairman after Forbes resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Additional hurdles remain between now and the company's annual
stockholders meeting, scheduled for Oct. 1. Sometime early next
month, Cendant expects to release audited revisions of its
financial statements for 1995 through 1997, giving Wall Street
analysts their first close look at the damage done to the company's
track record.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman has already disclosed that the damage will reduce
Cendant's operating profits, originally reported as $900 million,
or $1 a share, to between $648 million and $702 million, or between
72 and 78 cents a share, before extraordinary merger-related
expenses. Downward revisions in those expenses will largely offset
the impact of the reductions on the bottom line, however.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after those revised results are released, Cendant, based in
Parsippany, N.J., will report on its financial performance in the
last three months. Given the upheaval in operations during most of
that period, and the impact on franchisers and employees, those
results may be an additional source of surprise or disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   The company has already indicated to analysts that the current
year's financial results will probably be affected slightly by the
problems under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But the most significant hurdle for investor confidence will
come around Aug. 17, when Cendant's audit committee expects to
receive a report from its independent counsel, Willkie, Farr &AMP;
Gallagher. The law firm has engaged a forensic accounting team from
Arthur Andersen to investigate how the accounting irregularities
occurred and who may have been responsible.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary report on the irregularities was made at the
special board meeting on Tuesday, but did not assign any blame.
</P>
<P>
   The Arthur Andersen report, besides clarifying the mystery that
has plagued the company since April, is essential to Cendant's
ability to proceed with its proposed acquisition of American
Bankers Insurance Group, a credit-card industry insurer based in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Dowdell, legal services director for the Florida
Department of Insurance, asked Cendant, in a letter released on
Tuesday, to provide information about the company's efforts to
identify who was responsible for the irregularities, or who knew of
them. It also asked Cendant to indicate whether any of those
individuals currently served in any capacity that could influence
the operations of American Bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are apparently optimistic that state regulators will
be satisfied with Cendant's investigative efforts. Shares of
American Bankers, which fell when Cendant's troubles were
disclosed, rallied Wednesday to close at $60.1875, up $1.3125.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
