<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADCAST-AFFIRM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME BIG BROADCASTERS VOLUNTARILY ADHERE TO AFFIRMATIVE ACTION
RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some of the nation's biggest broadcasters,
including the four major networks and several of the largest owners
of radio stations, have agreed to continue following the Federal
Communications Commission's affirmative action guidelines even
though they are no longer required to do so under a recent court
decision, the industry's chief regulator said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   FCC Chairman William Kennard said he had received commitments
from several of the radio and television companies to voluntarily
continue outreach and recruitment programs specifically designed to
increase the number of minority employees. Such efforts had been
required by the FCC until a federal court declared this spring that
the agency's mandate would inevitably lead to quotas and was
therefore unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies that have agreed to continue following the
FCC guidelines are ABC, CBS, NBC, the Fox network, Time Warner
Inc., which includes CNN, Tribune Co. and Clear Channel
Communications Inc., the owner of 183 radio stations and 18
television stations. Kennard also received commitments from cable
companies Cox Communications, Cablevision, the TCI Group and
Comcast Inc. In all, the companies agreeing to follow the
guidelines earn one-third of the annual advertising revenue in the
broadcast industry, the FCC said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the companies comes after a three-judge panel of
the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit
ruled April 14 that the FCC could no longer require broadcasters to
follow such guidelines. In their opinion in the case Lutheran
Church-Missouri Synod vs. FCC, the judges ruled that the agency's
affirmative action program did not serve a compelling public
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel strongly that we can't allow three judges to dictate
what is important to the country as a policy,'' Kennard said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The decision sent shock waves through many civil rights groups,
since the FCC requirements did not mandate quotas, preferences
based on race, or set goals for particular companies and timetables
for when they should be met. The rules essentially required that
broadcast companies, as a condition of maintaining a license, make
good-faith efforts to recruit and hire minorities, which even some
critics of extending preferences based on race say they could
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not think it matters whether a government hiring program
imposes hard quotas, soft quotas or goals,'' Judge Laurence
Silberman wrote at the time. ``Any one of these techniques induces
an employer to hire with an eye toward meeting the numerical
target. As such, they can and surely will result in individuals
being granted a preference because of their race.''
</P>
<P>
   The FCC has petitioned for a review of the three-judge panel's
decision by the full Court of Appeals. The Clinton administration
has not decided whether it would appeal an adverse ruling to the
Supreme Court. Some civil rights leaders have been lobbying the
administration not to bring the case to the Court, fearing that it
might issue an even more sweeping prohibition against affirmative
action efforts in employment.
</P>
<P>
   Since the ruling, however, Kennard has been lobbying
broadcasters to maintain efforts to increase the number of minority
employees. The announcement of the agreement with the broadcasters,
which he will formally make in a speech Thursday in Washington at
the convention of the National Association of Black Journalists,
represents Kennard's first success in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know our rules work,'' Kennard says in a draft of his
speech, which was provided by his office. ``And we know how
important they are in giving minorities a start. Employment is not
just an end unto itself. For some it can also be a path to
ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Kennard has also met with owners of media
conglomerates to see if ways could be devised to increase the
number of minority station owners. Since 1995, when Congress
repealed a tax break for companies that sell television and radio
stations to minorities, the number of stations owned by minorities
has declined slightly to 322.
</P>
<P>
   As an incentive , Kennard is proposing a trade-off in which he
would support the broadcasters' efforts to increase their media
holdings if they helped increase the number of minority-owned
stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these companies have come to me and said, `We want to
get bigger,''' he said. ``My question is, you're asking me to relax
ownership rules so you can get bigger. But what does that do for
the goals I am interested in, in terms of ownership?''
</P>
</TEXT>
