<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-ARMSTRONG-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS SCOLD EXECUTIVE FOR U.S.-CHINA ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Miss., N.M.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A current and a former top executive of the
nation's largest satellite maker urged a Senate panel Wednesday not
to subject the industry to a more restrictive licensing review by
the government.
</P>
<P>
   But senators Wednesday criticized one executive, C. Michael
Armstrong, the former chairman of Hughes Electronics Corp., for
lobbying President Clinton too aggressively, and for acting as an
unofficial envoy between the United States and China to lift
sanctions that blocked Hughes from launching two satellites aboard
Chinese rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``American corporations should not serve as mini-State
Departments,'' Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., who heads the
Governmental Affairs Committee, scolded Armstrong at a hearing
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is weighing whether to revert the licensing control
over satellites to the State Department, which had that
responsibility until 1996, from the less restrictive Commerce
Department. Lawmakers fear that engineers from Hughes, which is a
unit of General Motors Corp., and from Loral Space &AMP; Communications
gave Chinese officials sensitive information after a failed
launching of a Loral satellite on a Chinese rocket in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who became chairman of AT&AMP;T last fall after running
Hughes for five years, and Steven Dorfman, Hughes' vice chairman,
told senators that they did support giving the State Department
authority to approve any technical exchanges in a disaster review.
</P>
<P>
   But the executives said transferring licensing authority to the
State Department would hurt American companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we raise unnecessary barriers to satellite exports,''
Dorfman said, ``we will jeopardize the continuing U.S. pre-eminence
in this critical technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., said he favored shifting
jurisdiction to the State Department and insuring that the
department's ``processes are more responsive to industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Wednesday's hearing focused on Armstrong, 59, a
hard-charging executive and motorcycle buff, who has headed
Clinton's advisory panel on exports since it was created three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1993, when the administration imposed sanctions on
China for shipping missile technology to Pakistan, Armstrong thrust
himself into the dispute that grounded two Hughes satellites, and
threatened company profits and thousands of jobs in Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   Documents released by the committee Wednesday, and by the White
House in the last two weeks, showed how Armstrong worked to free
his satellites from the sanctions and, two years later, how he
pushed the White House to shift the licensing jurisdiction to the
Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter on Oct. 29, 1993, Armstrong reminded Clinton that he
had supported the president's economic package and the North
American Free Trade Agreement. ``I am respectfully requesting your
involvement to resolve the China sanctions,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   A Dec. 8, 1993, internal White House memorandum to Clinton's
national security adviser, Anthony Lake, said, ``Armstrong is now
fairly directly threatening to wage a more public campaign against
the administration's sanction.'' Armstrong, the memorandum said,
was threatening to ``write op-eds and/or spur union opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said Wednesday that he and Hughes never compromised
national security. But senators voiced concern that Armstrong's
blunt approach pushed the limits of corporate advocacy expected
from any industry chieftain.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a bare minimum, you need some help in letter-writing,''
Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., told Armstrong. ``That's not any way to
write the president.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In seeking to have the sanctions lifted, Armstrong mixed
diplomacy with business by passing messages between senior Chinese
and American officials. ``I hope this information is useful and can
be used to resolve the situation,'' Armstrong said in a Nov. 16,
1993, letter to Samuel Berger, Clinton's deputy national security
adviser, relaying his conversation with China's vice premier, Qian
Qichen.
</P>
<P>
   By early 1994, Clinton reached a compromise that allowed Huhges
to modify its satellites and refile its applications with Commerce.
The administration ended the sanctions in November 1994.
</P>
<P>
   With the sanctions issue resolved, Armstrong still was waging a
war to shift licensing authority over all commercial satellites to
the less restrictive Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   By March 1996, Armstrong got what he wanted by enlisting
Berger's help in reversing the State Department objections. ``It
was indeed some battle, two and a half years and more politics than
a textbook,'' Armstrong told Berger in an Oct. 17, 1996,
``thank-you'' note.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
