<SLUG> BC-BKO-WORLD-BLINEBURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Dreamers must &QL; 
grow up in a hurry
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ Zorba the smiling waiter put down a menu on the
table and quickly realized he had made a mistake when a pair of
would-be diners looked at the pages as if they were covered by the
random scribblings of a chicken with ink on its claws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' he said. ``It must be all Greek to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ba-da-boom!
</P>
<P>
   ``It is actually a very easy language to learn,'' said Zorba.
``How long will you be here?''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, it sinks in about the third week,'' he replied with a
grin.
</P>
<P>
   Ba-da-boom! Rim shots and jump shots.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Tomjanovich will have to hope the learning curve for his
ragtag band of Dreamers at the World Basketball Championships is a
little faster. For in spite of a final score that was a lopsided
83-59 over Brazil, the debut of the American team had more lurches
and stops than a ride in an Athens taxi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can attribute a lot of what you saw out of us in
the first half to nerves,'' said Trajan Langdon, the Duke star and
the only collegian on the team. ``We've been working to get ready
for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard a lot of the talk about what people at home think
we can't do, and I think everybody was pushing a little bit extra
at the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed shots. We didn't make plays. But in an international
tournament like this, that's what the first day can be all about.
Calming down. Sorting things out.''
</P>
<P>
   South Koreans fade fast
</P>
<P>
   At two locations on opposite sides of Athens, the 16 teams
finally kicked off a tournament that had received a kick in the
teeth when the NBA stars who would have made up Dream Team IV
bailed out as a result of the current labor discord.
</P>
<P>
   Over at the Peace and Friendship Arena, one of the favorites,
Yugoslavia, came out of the blocks sprinting with an impressive
thumping of Puerto Rico, and Russia beat up on Japan.
</P>
<P>
   At the Olympic Stadium, there was an intimate gathering of
family and the custodial staff on hand to see the opening game,
which had South Korea giving a first-half scare to Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
   The Koreans took spreading the court to extremes, set up about
10 yards apart, were hotter than kimchi in burying a raft of
3-pointers and crisply executed a half-court offense.
</P>
<P>
   Listen, when you see Sang-Min Lee and Dong-Hee Kang run the
pick-and-roll, you have flashbacks to Cousy and Russell.
</P>
<P>
   The Koreans led for a long while, trailed by only six at
intermission, but were done in by the small matter of a 48-8 burst
by the Lithuanians to start the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, by comparison, were never in that much trouble,
though they fell behind 22-17 with about seven minutes left in the
first half before settling down and resembling a team that can walk
and dribble a basketball at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to rely on our defense in this tournament,''
Tomjanovich said. ``It will be the foundation of everything we hope
to accomplish. This isn't a team with a lot of big offensive
weapons. So we're going to have to be persistent with our defense
and hang in until the offense follows.''
</P>
<P>
   Fundamentals over flash
</P>
<P>
   The offense started to come around when Rudy T put Langdon into
the game as his 12th man in the final minutes of the first half,
and Langdon responded with a pair of treys that seemed to boost the
U.S. confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The no-name Americans rode a solid-if-unspectacular game by
point guard Michael Hawkins, who played last year in the Greek
League for Olympiakos of Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins made all but one of his shots to finish with 12 points,
dealt a U.S. tournament-record 10 assists and grabbed seven
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently on the receiving end of Hawkins passes was forward
Wendell Alexis, formerly of Syracuse, a half-dozen NBA tryout camps
and a handful of pro leagues in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis scored inside on feeds and opportunity hoops and made one
crushing block on a Brazilian layup attempt that led to a layup by
Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   This is how the Dreamers will have to do it. By choking off the
middle with team defense, by taking advantage of their overall team
depth and beating opponents down the floor in the running game.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. was 10-for-11 in converting fast breaks, and with the
exception of David Wood, every player on the roster scored.
</P>
<P>
   Next up is Lithuania. The learning process must accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people back home don't think we can even medal,
let alone win the gold,'' said Langdon. ``But I think this team
will surprise you. We're learning who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   It will have to be faster than Zorba the waiter says we can
learn the language.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
