<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Struggling Wohlers puts team in bind
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ While the Braves continue to try publicly to
maintain a forward spin on the Mark Wohlers situation, it has
become clear the club is going to have to make a move to remedy the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Even manager Bobby Cox, who has tried to remain positive as his
former closer fights for his control, was astounded by Tuesday
night's five-walk, five-run outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't good,'' Cox said Wednesday. ``What more can I say.''
</P>
<P>
   But there, the team is stuck. It could ask Wohlers to accept
another optional assignment to the minors (Wohlers has declined
comment on that possibility). It could wrangle a way to place him
on the disabled list and let him work in the minors (remember the
New York Mets had Pete Harnisch on the DL much of last year with
anxiety).
</P>
<P>
   Or the Braves could release him, which is highly unlikely. Even
with control trouble, Wohlers is still a prized commodity and the
club is liable for his contract. Wohlers would be owed $7.375
million if released based on pro-rating the remainder of his $4.125
million salary this season, the $5.2 million he has coming next
season and an $800,000 buyout clause.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the club would prefer the first option, since it costs
the Braves nothing and Wohlers can work on his problem on his own
terms. Keeping him in Atlanta may prove a burden to the bullpen. In
his six appearances, three times the club has had to scramble
another pitcher to finish Wohlers' innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll keep finding him opportunities,'' said Cox.
</P>
<P>
   But those opportunities are not never-ending. His progress, to
judge by his results, is indeterminable. In his six outings,
Wohlers has pitched 3 2/3 innings, allowed 10 runs on five hits and
11 walks. He has not struck out a batter since June 9. Of the 25
men he has faced since rejoining the team after the All-Star break,
he has retired 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be, he would come in and say, here it is, see what
you can do with it,'' said Cincinnati's Reggie Sanders. ``Now, it's
like he's saying, I don't really know what I'm doing and I hope
it's there. He's a little more timid,''
</P>
<P>
   Skinning the Cat
</P>
<P>
   After being plunked for the 17th time Tuesday night, Andres
Galarraga is within four of breaking Jeff Blauser's record, set
last year, of being hit by pitches 20 times. Adding insult to
injury, Galarraga's arm shield isn't helping. He has been hit six
times since he began wearing a padded sleeve guard and only once
has the device stopped the ball. Cincinnati's Scott Sullivan caught
him Tuesday where he has most often been struck _ in the left
triceps above the guard.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga has not been so successful this month driving the
ball. While he came into Wednesday's game with six July homers, he
has hit just one double this month. He hit 15 in the first three
months of the season. The ``Big Cat'' cannot explain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it,'' he said. ``They catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   See how he runs
</P>
<P>
   Of Andruw Jones' 13 stolen bases, seven have come this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby gives me the opportunity to run,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   He has only been caught once this year and that was on a
pick-off by Florida's Jesus Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
