 &HT;    On Deck: Cincinnati Reds
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: 12:35 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV, radio: TBS, WSB 750-AM.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: LHP Denny Neagle (10-9, 3.60; 7-3,
4.67 lifetime vs. Reds) vs. LHP Rick Krivda (0-1, 7.62; first
appearance vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Neagle and his changeup were much improved last time out.
Although he lost at Pittsburgh on Saturday, he only gave up two
runs while striking out six, a vast improvement over his nine-run
debacle against Chicago on July 20. He has not faced the Reds this
year, but Cinergy Field has not been one of his favorite stops. He
is 3-3 in eight career appearances in Cincinnati, where his ERA is
5.40 and the Reds have a .300 average against him. Krivda, acquired
by the Reds from Cleveland on June 16, will be making his first
National League start. In five Cincinnati appearances, he has given
up 18 hits, including three homers, and six walks in 13 innings,
but he is being tried as a starter after the club returned Scott
Winchester to the minors. After seven years in the Baltimore
organization and going 9-14 in 45 games with the Orioles, he was
cut during the winter and signed by Cleveland. After 20 appearances
and one start with the Indians (2-0, 3.24), he was dealt to
Cincinnati for pitcher Eddie Priest and outfielder Christian Rojas.
Although the Braves are unfamiliar with him, Danny Bautista will be
glad to see him. One of his 19 career home runs came off Kridva in
1994, when Bautista was a Detroit Tiger.
</P>
