<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PROBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO TESTIFY TO GRAND JURY VIA VIDEOTAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will provide videotaped testimony
to the independent counsel investigating the Monica S. Lewinsky
allegations on Aug. 17, Clinton's attorney announced Wednesday,
marking the first time a president will testify for a grand jury as
the presumed criminal target.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Linda R. Tripp, who triggered the Lewinsky
probe, defended her actions in her first extended comments on the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement on Clinton's testimony, announced by David
Kendall in an appearance on the White House driveway, came after
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr bowed to Clinton's insistence
that he testify from the White House with his lawyers present. In
return, Clinton, under apparent pressure from a federal judge,
abandoned his attempts to postpone the testimony until
mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   The timing still allows Clinton to testify after Lewinsky,
giving the president some knowledge of Lewinsky's version of events
as he provides his own detailed account of their relationship for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   As events continued to tumble toward an uncertain conclusion,
Tripp, the former White House worker who secretly tape recorded
Lewinsky, said she had no political agenda when she approached
Starr with the tapes in January and instead was trying to conquer
her own fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of simply trying to earn a living, I became aware
between 1993 and 1997 of actions by high government officials that
may have been against the law,'' Tripp said from the steps of the
US District Court, after completing her eighth and final day of
testimony before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``For that period of nearly five years, the things I witnessed
concerning several different subjects made me increasingly fearful
that this information was dangerous, very dangerous to possess,''
Tripp said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, her hands and voice shaking, Tripp added: ``I bear no
malice toward anyone in this case. I have never had any political
agenda. I still don't. I have been honored to serve presidents of
both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   It was another in a string of eventful days in the capital, the
image of Lewinsky's lawyers announcing Tuesday's immunity deal
still fresh on television news shows when Kendall stepped before
the microphones Wednesday to make his announcement. And just
minutes after Kendall disappeared without taking questions, Tripp
appeared at the courthouse and seemed ready to burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall addressed reporters after meeting privately with Clinton
to inform the president of the testimony arrangement. On Tuesday
afternoon, Kendall pleaded with US District Judge Norma Holloway
Johnson to have the president's testimony postponed but was rebuked
in a closed-door hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an effort to achieve a prompt resolution of this entire
matter, the president will voluntarily provide his testimony on
Aug. 17, 1998, to the office of independent counsel, as he has on
prior occasions,'' Kendall said. ``The president's testimony will
be videotaped at the White House with lawyers present.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said Wednesday that Starr had
agreed to withdraw the July 17 subpoena after Clinton had agreed to
testify. That move, while largely symbolic, allows Clinton to
answer prosecutors' questions without the stigma of being under
subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   That official, speaking under the cloak of anonymity, strongly
hinted that the testimony would be concluded in a single day.
Clinton is delaying his departure to Martha's Vineyard for vacation
at least two days to stay in Washington and testify, officials
said, and is likely to clear out blocks of his schedule before then
to prepare. He will now leave for Massachusetts either the night of
Aug. 17 or the morning of Aug. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday's deal was reached, defense lawyers and
analysts had been increasingly speculating that Clinton would
somehow back out of his plan to testify, largely because they saw
no clear legal benefit for Clinton in presenting his case to the
grand jury. It is extraordinarily rare, lawyers said, for a
criminal suspect to appear before a grand jury investigating him.
</P>
<P>
   A grand jury appearance, those lawyers and analysts said, might
only serve to provide more legal ammunition to Starr to pursue a
perjury allegation. Clinton had already said under oath in January,
in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, that he did not have
a sexual affair with Lewinsky, and further testimony would either
exacerbate his legal plight or force him to confess to a prior lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing you can do is after the fact, after you've
been called to a grand jury, is lie,'' said Mary Cheh, a professor
at George Washington University Law School. ``Prisons are filled
with people who have lied and burned files. When there's even the
hint of risk, you tell people not to testify.''
</P>
<P>
   The sparring Lewinsky and Clinton grand jury appearances will
create a climactic summertime showdown in a case that was launched
in the coldest days of January and has lurched forward, to
considerable criticism, ever since. Under the current plan, Starr
could not conceivably present the House of Representatives with a
report of his findings by September.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky is prepared to testify that she had a lengthy sexual
relationship with Clinton while she worked as an intern at the
White House and after she was transferred to the Pentagon,
according to sources familiar with her account. She also told Starr
that she would testify that Clinton discussed with her a strategy
to keep their affair secret, the sources said. At least part of
that discussion occured after Lewinsky was named on a witness list
in the Jones lawsuit, but before she was actually subpoenaed, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky also plans to testify that she typed the now-famous
so-called talking points herself, under Tripp's guidance, the
sources said. The talking points describe ways for Tripp to tailor
her testimony in the Jones suit so as not to implicate Clinton in
illicit relationships with other women. Lewinsky handed the sheet
with the talking points to Tripp on Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Tripp dismissed Lewinsky's account as ``illogical''
and ``patently false.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had nothing _ let me repeat: nothing _ to do with the
so-called talking points,'' Tripp said on the courthouse steps.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, ABC News resurrected the issue of a
semen-stained dress, reporting that Lewinsky told Starr this week
that as part of the immunity deal, she would now turn over clothing
to prosecutors that could prove her version of a sexual affair with
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Over the winter, reports of the dress were widespread in the
news media. But at one point, Lewinsky's former lawyer, William
Ginsburg, said explicitly that no such dress existed.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Lewinsky also expressed private concern last
night that White House officials had launched what they described
as a ``smear campaign'' against the former intern.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the whirlwind events, it was Tripp, silent since the
investigation was launched in January, who appeared the most
forceful, with a vivid recounting of her role and a dramatic
defense of her efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Her face seemed to quiver as she spoke, her eyes darting from a
page of text to the battery of reporters and cameramen who stood
before her in the summer sun. Villified by pundits for seeking a
book deal and by administration officials for pursuing a partisan
agenda and pushing the White House toward a political crisis over
allegations of a sexual affair, she started with a simple apology
for being a mediocre public speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that there has been a great deal of speculation
about just who I am and how I got here,'' Tripp said, her son and
daughter behind her. ``Well, the answer is simple. I'm you. I'm
just like you. I'm an average American who found herself in a
situation not of her own making. I'm a suburban mom who was a
military wife for 20 years, and a faithful government employee for
18 years. I never asked to be placed in this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Tripp, a former employee in the Bush White House, said,
``I have been villified through taking the path of truth. I've been
maligned by people who have chosen not to tell the truth and who
know that they are not telling the truth. Not surprisingly, many in
the entertainment industry have chosen to ridicule me as well,
going so far as to even make fun of my appearance in a manner so
mean and so cruel that I pray none of you is ever subjected to
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
