u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDMAN-SACHS-NYT &LR;      07-29 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-SACHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN SETS PAYMENT CHOICES FOR RILED PARTNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The top executives of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. have
promised that when the firm, Wall Street's premier private
investment bank, sells shares to the public, everyone at the firm,
from general partners to janitors, will get a share of the
multibillion-dollar payoff.
</P>
<P>
   The first test of that pledge came at a meeting in New York on
Wednesday, when Goldman's co-chairmen and chief executives, Jon
Corzine and Henry Paulson Jr., tried to salve a wound that opened
when the firm decided to go public in June: how much 111 limited
partners, who built Goldman into a powerhouse in wholesale banking
but have retired or left the firm, should get.
</P>
<P>
   Indications are that the payoff will be less than some limited
partners hoped, but more than many feared. The limited partners,
who retain cash stakes, were given a choice of investing in the new
Goldman shares or cashing out now. They would earn premiums on
their current investments of 25 percent to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The offer was not enough to appease all elder partners. Among
the most vocal critic was John Whitehead, a former senior partner.
Whitehead, also a former deputy secretary of state, led a group of
disgruntled retired partners who complained that their lifetime
contributions to Goldman were being played down at a time when it
mattered most, according to people who attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead did not return telephone calls to his office
Wednesday. But people present at the meeting of the limited
partners Wednesday said he argued forcefully that Goldman's current
partners had a moral obligation to reward their predecessors, some
of whom worked at the firm for nearly half a century to create the
blue-chip Goldman brand name.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the limited partner settlement appears to be enough to
placate others. ``I would characterize the reaction as mild
disappointment,'' said one limited partner who asked to remain
anonymous. ``They should have been more generous. But are people
really upset? No. We can live with this.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute shows how difficult it will be for Corzine and
Paulson to satisfy soaring expectations. Many analysts expect a
public offering will value Goldman at $30 billion or more, creating
windfall profits with thousands of claimants. One Goldman executive
described his colleagues' dreams of wealth as ``off the charts and
through the roof,'' even before plans for the share offering are
complete.
</P>
<P>
   A misstep could prove damaging. The two Goldman chiefs have to
figure out how to shore up the firm's capital base for future
expansion, reward people who have contributed to its success over
the years and keep current partners and senior employees committed
to working long hours even after their net worth increases by three
or four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly why some people, including Whitehead, told
them not to go public,'' said another limited partner who attended
Wednesday's meeting. ``You get into all these delicate issues where
peoples' egos are at stake, and you potentially wreck Goldman's
formula for success.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the risks, Goldman is proceeding apace toward a public
offering, most likely in October. The 190 current partners are
expected to vote on Aug. 10 on details of the offering plan,
including which other investment banks will help underwrite Goldman
and the schedule for dividing shares among employees.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest winners will be the 190 general partners, the firm's
owners, who will see the value of their stakes increase as much as
four times. Senior partners are likely to get shares valued well
over $100 million, although they would not be able to sell those
shares for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Limited partners will not receive such exalted premiums for
their stakes. But Corzine and Paulson have gone some way toward
appeasing their demands for a bigger and more flexible cut.
</P>
<P>
   After tense negotiations in recent weeks, Goldman agreed to
offer the limited partners both more choice in how their
investments are handled and a greater premium whichever option they
choose. They can elect to have their ownership stakes exchanged for
cash, choose a debt instrument that would pay a fixed rate of
interest, accept new Goldman shares, or a mix of the three.
</P>
<P>
   Taking shares would bring the biggest premium, estimated to be
55 percent over the current value of their investments. But those
who accept this plan would also take a risk that the shares would
drop in value, and they would have to agree not to sell during a
``lock-up'' period, perhaps a year, after the public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Limited partners would get a 25 percent premium if they elected
to cash out entirely. If they chose the debt option, they would
earn a fixed rate of return from a debenture that matures over many
years, an option considered attractive for limited partners who are
retired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
