<HEADER>
A9359 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MOON-HNS &LR;      07-29 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MOON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moon considering retirement
</P>
<P>
   Rift with Seahawks over pact has ex-Oiler mulling end of career
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
If the Seattle Seahawks do not increase their one-year, $1.8
million offer, quarterback Warren Moon says he will retire after 20
seasons in professional football, including 14 in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Moon, 41, is under contact to the Seahawks and holding out for
the first time in his career. The two sides are as far apart as
Seattle and Houston, and Moon says he will not let the stalemate
continue into the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've given it a lot of thought, and if the situation doesn't
change, I'll retire,'' Moon said after returning to his home
outside Houston. ``First, I'd ask for my release, but I don't think
they'd give it to me. Then, yes, I'll just retire.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Seahawks and Dallas Cowboys kick off the NFL's
preseason schedule Friday night at Texas Stadium, Moon won't be
playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very surprised it's come to this,'' Moon said. ``What
bothers me the most is that it wasn't addressed seriously until a
couple of weeks before camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not asking for a ton of money. Two years ago, my base
salary with Minnesota was $4.3 million. Last year, it was $550,000.
Now, my situation's changed. I'm just asking to be paid like a
starting quarterback. I still believe I'm one of the better
quarterbacks in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon, who played the first 10 years of his NFL career with the
Houston Oilers, signed a two-year contract with the Seahawks in
1997. At the time, John Friesz was the starter. Moon accepted base
salaries of $550,000 and $600,000 and a lot of incentives. Seattle
assured him that if he became the starter, the second year of his
contract would be redone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never complained about my salary last year,'' he said. ``I
accepted my situation. But they said they were going to pay me more
this season since I was the starter. They said I'd be taken care
of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks, who paid Moon a $150,000 roster bonus this year,
are willing to give him a new one-year deal for $1.8 million, a
$300,000 increase from their initial offer. They also are willing
to add $1.6 million in incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll have to have the most unbelievable season of my
career to earn those incentives,'' Moon said.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Leigh Steinberg has made several proposals, but the
Seahawks say no new offers will be made.
</P>
<P>
   Moon says he wants a two-year deal so he can get a large signing
bonus that would provide a 1998 income of $3.5 million to $4.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they don't want to give me a two-year deal because
they're afraid I won't play next year,'' Moon said. ``They're
afraid I'll retire after one season and they'll have that portion
of my prorated signing bonus count against the 1999 cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll play as long as I can. I'll sign an agreement
guaranteeing I'll play the second year.''
</P>
<P>
   When Friesz was injured in the first game last season, Moon
became the starter. He finished with 25 touchdown passes and set
team records with 313 completions and 3,678 yards passing, but
Seattle finished 8-8 and missed the playoffs for the ninth
consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very fired up before camp,'' Moon said. ``I was as fired
up as I've ever been. When you look at the talent they've acquired,
it reminds me of our old Oiler teams.''
</P>
<P>
   In free agency, the Seahawks signed running back Ricky Watters,
center Kevin Glover and guard Brian Habib for the offense and
outside linebacker Darrin Smith for the defense. They used their
No. 1 pick on linebacker Anthony Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to be in camp watching everything come together,''
Moon said. ``We've got a great combination of speed and athleticism
and youth and experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in quite a while the Seahawks have
depth. I think it's going to be a very good season. I think we can
compete for the AFC West title, and we play in the toughest
division in the league. I definitely think we're a playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes this so frustrating. This team has a chance
to be very, very good. I hate not being in camp. Not only am I the
quarterback on the field, but I'm the quarterback off the field,
too. That extends into the dressing room and meeting room. We've
got a lot of young players, and I try to help them as much as I
can. I spend an awful lot of time with the younger guys. I try to
help take care of them. There are times when we have some
mini-crisis like every team, and I help take care of them. I can't
do that sitting home in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon earned a lot of respect last year when he had the best
season of any quarterback in his 40s in NFL history. Not only did
he throw 25 touchdown passes and establish Seahawks passing
records, but he won the Most Valuable Player award at the Pro Bowl
for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if holding out while he is under contract will hurt
his reputation with fans, Moon said, ``I think it might if people
didn't understand the dynamics of the deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
