u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANTITRUST-NYT &LR;      07-29 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL REACHED ON ANTITRUST LEGISLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Vt.)  (th) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In baseball parlance, the Senate Judiciary Committee for the
first time Wednesday moved into scoring position with a bill that
would alter the antitrust exemption Major League Baseball has
enjoyed since 1922.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the committee, and Sen.
Patrick Leahy of Vermont, the committee's ranking Democrat,
announced an agreement on the bill, which would affect players'
rights in labor relations. For the first time, owners, players and
the minor leagues support the same legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch called the step ``a truly historic milestone'' in baseball
history.
</P>
<P>
   The joint support of the bill by owners and players arose from
the collective bargaining agreement that ended the most devastating
work stoppage in sports history. The legislation would give
baseball players the same rights as players in other professional
sports, allowing them to challenge owners' actions in a labor
dispute with an antitrust lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The bill does not affect the status of antitrust law with
respect to the minor leagues, franchise expansion or relocation and
the amateur player draft.
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate and then the House pass the bill, known as the
Curt Flood Act, by the end of this year, it will affect the
termination date of the current labor agreement between the players
and the owners.
</P>
<P>
   If the bill becomes law, the termination date will remain Oct.
31, 2000, which the owners prefer. If Congress does not pass the
legislation, the date will change to Dec. 31, 2000, which the
players prefer.
</P>
<P>
   The owners have long wanted the earlier date because it would
affect contract negotiations for the following season. Players who
become free agents, for example, would not gain that status until
after Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement on dates was part of a compromise under which the
owners agreed to join the players in seeking a change in the
antitrust exemption as it applies to labor relations.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Washington, Hatch, holding a baseball
bat, said it was unlikely that Congress would have time to act on
the bill in the current session _ the Senate is trying to adjourn
for the summer by Saturday _ but he added that it would probably be
approved in September.
</P>
<P>
   If the act becomes law, Hatch added, ``the owners will not have
an unfair advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Leahy alluded to the cancellation of the 1994 World Series, a
victim of the last labor dispute, and said, ``Sometimes a
near-death experience is an enlightening thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee initially approved the Flood Act a year
ago by an 11-6 vote, but it stood little chance of passage because
the minor leagues opposed the language. Their concerns, however,
have been allayed by new language.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Brand, vice president of the National Association, the
umbrella organization of the minor leagues, wrote a letter to Hatch
earlier this week saying the amended bill assures ``the continued
survival of minor league baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig, using his title of commissioner formally for perhaps
the first time, and Donald Fehr, the players' labor chief, wrote a
joint letter to the two senators acknowledging that they agreed
with the bill's new language.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate statement, Fehr said passage of the bill would
``be a significant step toward minimizing the labor discord and
disruptions in play that have plagued our national pastime.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
