<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 7/29/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) BASKING RIDGE, N.J. -- July 29, 1998 --
CONGRESS-ARMSTRONG, 7-29 -- C. Michael Armstrong, the former
chairman of Hughes Electronics Corp. - the nation's largest
satellite maker - urged a Senate panel Wednesday not to subject the
industry to a more restrictive licensing review by the government.
But senators criticized Armstrong for lobbying President Clinton
too aggressively, and for acting as an unofficial envoy between the
United States and China to lift sanctions that blocked Hughes from
launching two satellites aboard Chinese rockets. (Norman Y.
Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) TRENTON, N.J. -- July 29, 1998 -- BOX-TYSON, 7-29 --
Mike Tyson, center, is flanked by his two lawyers, Raymond Reddin,
left, and Anthony Fusco, while testifying before the New Jersey
State Athletic Control Board. Efforts to portray him as a changed
man who deserved the right to fight again may have been undercut by
a moody appearance that ranged from a near-tearful apology to an
angry outburst laced with an expletive. (Norman Y. Lono/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- July 29, 1998 -- CLINTON-STARR-2, 7-29 --
Linda Tripp after appearing before the grand jury Wednesday; her
son, Ryan, left. Mrs. Tripp, the woman whose secret tape recordings
of Monica Lewinsky started the sex-and-perjury investigation of
President Clinton, emerges from her eighth and final day of
testimony and asks America to think of her as Everywoman. ``I'm
you,'' she says. ``I'm an average American who found herself in a
situation not of her own making. I'm a suburban mom, who was a
military wife for 20 years, and a faithful government employee for
18 years.'' (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) WASHINGTON -- July 29, 1998 -- CLINTON-STARR, 7-29 --
Monica Lewinsky being driven from her lawyer's office in Washington
on Wednesday. Several people close to Ms. Lewinsky say that her new
lawyers, Plato Cacheris and Jacob Stein, were able to break the
impasse with Kenneth Starr and strike an immunity deal by talking
man-to-man with him. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) LAS TRAMPAS, N.M. -- July 29, 1998 -- NM-GREENS, 7-29 --
Carol Miller, green party candidate for New Mexico's third
congressional district, stands above the 18th-century Spanish land
grant town of Las Trampas. Ms. Miller and other candidates of the
New Mexico Green Party are gaining ground on the political scene
and causing headaches for the major parties with such issues as
land grants. ``People in New Mexico don't like the money going into
the campaigns,'' she says. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- July 29, 1998 -- CHARITY-STAMP-FLOATER, 7-29
-- The Postal Service issued the first American stamp to benefit
charity Wednesday. The stamp, left, which costs 40 cents, provides
32 cents of postage and 8 cents to fight breast cancer and defray
costs of the program. A prostate cancer stamp, right, will be
issued next year. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- July 29, 1998 -- BARRACK-MARKETPLACE, 7-29 --
Democratic National Committee Finance Chairman Leonard Barrack,
left, is a prominent securities class-action lawyer. He represents
some Philadelphia and New York State public pension funds in a huge
class-action cases against companies whose stocks have tumbled
because of undisclosed setbacks or accounting irregularities. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo) New York class-action lawyer Howard
Sirota, right, sees a conflict of interest. ``There is a
non-arm's-length arrangement between Len Barrack and the
politicians hiring him,'' Sirota says. (Frances Roberts/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) ABUJA, Nigeria -- July 29, 1998 -- NIGERIA-OPPORTUNITY,
7-29 -- Theodore Luttwak sells imported Italian marble to wealthy
Nigerians at what he advertises are ``very, very, very, very
competitive prices.'' Abuja, Nigeria's capital-under-construction,
is full of the whiff of oil money and Luttwak - ``just call me
Teddy'' - is out to get his share of the $10 billion that Nigeria
earns each year from oil. ``Look, the human rights here in Nigeria
are terrible, but the opportunities are just fantastic,'' he says.
``Tell me, where else in the world do you have so much money?''
(Roger Cohen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LOS ANGELES -- July 29, 1998 -- MEDITATION-SPACES-3,
7-29 -- Gurmukh in the yoga room of her Los Angeles home. ``You
don't need a million dollars to have a space,'' says Gurmukh, a
kundalini yoga teacher whose celebrity clientele includes David
Duchovny, Madonna, Tim Burton and Courtney Love. ``You just need a
place to return to, to remember who you are on a daily basis. A
home is a spiritual metaphor for the self. Anyplace in it can be
sacred.'' (Marissa Roth/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- July 29, 1998 -- MEDITATION-SPACES-2, 7-29
-- A reflective moment for Deneen and Raymond King at their indoor
pool in Greenwich Village. The Kings say the pool has a meditative
effect on their lives. A poll in House &AMP; Garden last winter showed
that more than 80 percent of respondents believed that having a
quiet place in the home for meditation is a necessity. (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LOS ANGELES -- July 29, 1998 -- MEDITATION-SPACES-1,
7-29 -- Rick Rubin in a prayer pose in his yoga room above Sunset
Boulevard. Rubin, a founder of Def Jam records, once the powerhouse
of rap music, and president of Sony's American Recordings, uses the
room he designed specially in this old mansion for transcendental
meditation, yoga, tai chi and other practices. The room has air
purifiers, sheepskin yoga mats and a stained-glass Buddha etched in
the door. (Marissa Roth/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SEATTLE -- July 29, 1998 -- BACHELOR-WIFE-SPI, 7-29 --
Outside of his home on a half-acre of waterview property, Tom Rodal
poses with his front-yard sign that advertises for a wife. ``I'm
never going to give up. Never!'' says the groom-in-waiting. ``I'll
be persistent - and I will succeed.'' (M.L. Lyke/Seattle
Post-Intelligencer Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- July 29, 1998 -- SUB-BLUE-MAN-APARTMENT-2,
7-29 -- Chris Wink of the Blue Man Group and his wife, Jen
Graffam-Wink, a painter, have made their 800-square-foot apartment
in a landmark building on Lafayette Street a peaceful escape: a
holiday from Wink's work a few steps away. Call it light-Blue, like
the tones of much of its pacific palette. ``I didn't want any
trappings of Blue Man in the apartment,'' says Wink. Designers
Blake Moore and Christian Bunce created a Japanese-style dining
room within a window alcove. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- July 29, 1998 -- SUB-BLUE-MAN-APARTMENT-1,
7-29 -- Chris Wink of the Blue Man Group and his wife, Jen
Graffam-Wink, a painter, have made their 800-square-foot apartment
in a landmark building on Lafayette Street a peaceful escape: a
holiday from Wink's work a few steps away. Call it light-Blue, like
the tones of much of its pacific palette. Wedge wrestling mats let
the Winks' two dachshunds, Boone and Thermis, access the giant bed.
(Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- July 29, 1998 -- CIR-COMPUTER-SPEAKERS, 7-29
-- At right is the Powercube Plus Multimedia Speaker System. It
includes two plastic molded satellites, each 3- by 5- inches, with
both a 3-inch full-range driver, and a 3/4-inch tweeter and a
6-inch woofer in a compact, 14-by-12-by-8-inch wooden cabinet. At
left, Bose Mediamate system. It offers fine midbass performance
from one tiny 2.5-inch full-range speaker in each wedge-shaped,
front-ported, plastic cabinet. (Naum Kazhdan/New York Times Photo)
