from the basement of his home. ``I have had as many negative
experiences as I have good experiences,'' says Kornelis. (Scott
Cohen/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) TAUNTON, Mass. -- July 29, 1998 --
MOVIE-RYAN-REALITY-BOS, 7-29 -- Walter Zagol is a World War II
paratrooper who survived D-Day, the ``Bridge too Far'' at Remagen
and the siege of Bastogne in the Battle of the Bulge. And now, he
has seen ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Despite warnings that the film
may be a rough experience for veterans, he's fine. Got bored after
the gory part, but stayed because ``my grandson wanted to see the
end of the movie.'' That may be a normal reaction for men who
survived the reality behind the myth of ``Private Ryan.'' (Jonathan
Wiggs/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PROUTS NECK, Maine. -- July 29, 1998 -- PROUTS-NECK-BOS,
7-29 -- Charles ``Chip'' Homer Willauer, center, has been leading
the weekly Sunday night sing-along at the Prouts Neck Yacht Club
for 42 years, since he was 17. Change is exactly what this enclave
in the middle of Scarborough does not want. It is set apart from
the rest of the town by the configuration of land, which juts out
from the coastline and encompasses about 150 acres. A walk around
the neck, a very popular evening activity, takes about 45 minutes.
(Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEWTON, Mass. -- July 29, 1998 -- WOM-SPORTS-ROGAN-BOS,
7-29 -- When her family gathers here Saturday to celebrate the 90th
birthday of Katherine Mearls Rogan, talk will likely turn to the
days when she could run faster, jump farther, and swim quicker than
any other woman in the United States. When it does, the honoree
will likely have little to say. ``I didn't think very much of it,''
says Rogan of the nine years, 1924-33, when she competed in track
and field against the likes of Babe Didrickson. ``We didn't make a
big deal of it.'' (Frank O'Brien/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
