<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INVESTORS REACT POSITIVELY TO CENDANT RESIGNATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Cendant, which is struggling to emerge from an
accounting scandal that was disclosed in April, increased more than
8 percent in heavy training and are up more than 16 percent so far
this week. Investors are reacting to the resignation of the
chairman, Walter Forbes, along with eight other directors from the
Cendant board. They are also responding to comments by Cendant's
auditors that they do not expect to further revise estimates of the
accounting irregularities' impact on the direct-marketing and
franchising company.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN'S BAD DEBTS MAY BE LARGER
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials and private financial experts have concluded that
Japan's banking crisis is worse than Tokyo has publicly
acknowledged, with bad debts roughly estimated at $1 trillion, or
nearly twice the official estimate.
</P>
<P>
   BBC SIGNS PACT WITH PBS STATION
</P>
<P>
   British Broadcasting Corp. signed a three-year contract with the
Long Island, N.Y.-based PBS station WLIW to provide three half-hour
BBC World news programs from London every day to that station and
about 25 other public television stations.
</P>
<P>
   DURABLE GOODS ORDERS FELL IN JUNE
</P>
<P>
   Factory orders for big-ticket goods declined two-tenths of 1
percent in June, driven lower by falling demand for aircraft and
autos. Outside of transportation, orders posted their largest rise
in almost a year, 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS JITTERS SEND STOCKS LOWER
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell on concerns that earnings growth will not keep up
with stock prices. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 19.82, to
8,914.96. Broader market gauges also declined. The yield on the
30-year Treasury bond rose to 5.76 percent, from 5.74 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BEHIND THE E-MAIL SECURITY FLAW
</P>
<P>
   The security flaw discovered in e-mail programs this week points
to an industrywide problem _ the danger of programming languages
whose greatest strength is also their greatest weakness.
</P>
<P>
   GM STRIKE PROVIDED LIMITED GAINS
</P>
<P>
   Members of the United Automobile Workers union ratified a
settlement with General Motors and started to return to their jobs,
but the dispute seems to have produced limited gains for both the
union and GM.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA LIFTS MAGAZINE BAN
</P>
<P>
   Canada said it would no longer bar the sale of Canadian editions
of U.S. magazines, but would prevent Canadian advertisers from
buying ads in them. U.S. trade officials rejected Canada's new
approach.
</P>
<P>
   NEW CARRIER PLANNED FOR LAS VEGAS
</P>
<P>
   Two casino companies are helping finance a new airline that is
expected to be announced Thursday by Michael Conway, one of the
founders of America West Airlines. The new carrier, to be called
National Airlines, will link Las Vegas, where many new hotel rooms
are opening, to cities on the East Coast. Harrah's Entertainment
and Rio Hotel and Casino have put up $30 million of the initial $50
million for the airline.
</P>
<P>
   SALES BOLSTER PHARMACIA &AMP; UPJOHN
</P>
<P>
   Profit before a charge at Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn rose 5 percent in
the second quarter, lifted by new-drug sales in the United States
and Europe. But net income fell 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BLOCKBUSTER DEAL CUTS VIACOM NET
</P>
<P>
   Viacom said its second-quarter loss widened because of costs
related to its Blockbuster video chain's new revenue-sharing
agreements with movie studios.
</P>
</TEXT>
