<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-TELECOM-ART-NY     07-29 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-TELECOM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL SELLS MOST OF STATE PHONE UTILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the one of the largest privatization transactions ever,
Brazil sold control of most of its telephone system Wednesday for
about $19 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The auction of the 12 pieces of Telecomunicacoes Brasileiras SA,
known as Telebras, was dominated by Telefonica of Spain, Portugal
Telecom and MCI Communications Corp. _ partners in a loose global
alliance that spent a total of $11.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The sale was a success for the Brazilian government, which
raised 64 percent more than the minimum bids it advertised for the
12 companies of the broken-up Telebras.
</P>
<P>
   Coming at a time when investors have been wary of emerging
markets and economies, like Brazil's, amid the Asian economic
turbulence, the auction's strong demand signaled confidence in the
Brazilian economy, government officials and Wall Street analysts
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   For the big European and North American telecommunications
companies that had winning bids, Brazil is a market with enormous
growth potential. The world's fifth-largest nation with 162 million
people, Brazil has two-year waiting lists for telephones in some
fast-growing areas.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, multinational business customers are the most
profitable segment of the telecommunications industry, and Brazil's
prospects in that area are not as strong as in some more advanced
industrial and commercial nations. Thus, companies like AT&AMP;T, which
on Sunday announced a joint venture with British Telecommunications
to serve multinational business customers, did not make bids.
</P>
<P>
   But the Brazilian market's sheer size and untapped profit
opportunities are too potentially lucrative to ignore for companies
like MCI, Portugal Telecom and Telefonica.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica, which was already the largest phone provider for
Latin America, bought the single richest license, spending $5
billion for control of the phone company that serves the Sao Paulo
region. It also spent $1.2 billion for the wireless carrier that
serves the regions of Rio de Janeiro and Espirito Santo.
</P>
<P>
   The success of Telefonica in Wednesday's auction only serves to
strengthen the alliance with MCI, which is to square off against
the AT&AMP;T-British Telecom venture and Global One consortium, which
includes Sprint, Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   For the auction, Telebras was split into three local phone
companies, one long-distance carrier and eight wireless providers.
While the Brazilian government owned only about 20 percent of
Telebras, it controlled 51 percent of the voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   The total sale was about 13 percent larger than London's
privatization of British Telecom for about $16.8 billion in the
early 1990s, according to Securities Data of Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The auction of Telebras took about four hours on the trading
floor of the Rio de Janeiro stock exchange. Near the exchange,
police officers used tear gas, water cannon and batons against
thousands of angry demonstrators, the Reuters news service
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the Brazilian government contend that the
privatization plan was a plot to deliver one of the nation's most
valuable corporate assets into the hands of foreigners on the
cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, which had been relatively slow in joining the global
wave of privatization and deregulation, has now sold one of its
last remaining state assets. The government had already sold its
stakes in Embraer, an aircraft manufacturer, and in steel,
petrochemicals, railroads and much of the electricity industry.
</P>
<P>
   Among the large buyers Wednesday were Telecom Italia S.p.A.,
which spent about $3 billion, and a Brazilian partnership of
Andrade Gutierrez, a construction company, and Inepar, a
communications and electric power equipment concern, which spent
$2.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Gutierrez-Inapar consortium spent $2.9 billion for control
of the local phone company serving the Brazilian northeast, now the
country's fastest-growing region.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia spent $1.8 billion for the local phone company
that serves the southern and central areas of Brazil, about $600
million for the wireless company that serves the southern region
and about $570 million for the wireless company that serves the
northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Telesystem of Canada spent about $650 million for the wireless
company than serves the region of Minas Gerais and about $160
million for the wireless carrier for northern states in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal Telecom acquired the wireless company for the Sao Paulo
region for $3.1 billion. Iberdrola, a Spanish electric power
company, acquired the wireless carrier for the Bahia and Sergipe
regions for $370 million. The wireless company for the central and
southwestern parts of the country was acquired by Splice, a
Brazilian high-technology company, for $380 million.
</P>
<P>
   While Wednesday's bidders could be concealing the identity of
U.S. partners, MCI appeared to be the only such company to win any
of the licenses. It spent $2.3 billion for control of Embratel,
Brazil's long-distance and international carrier.
</P>
<P>
   To acquire Embratel, MCI had to beat out Sprint, the No. 3 U.S.
long-distance company. The two companies' initial, sealed bids were
within 5 percent of each other, prompting an open auction process,
which MCI won.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices in Brazil surged Wednesday after the Telebras
auction. The main index of the Sao Paulo stock exchange rose 223.93
points, or 2.2 percent, to close at 10,542.41.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, American depository receipts of Telebras rose
$4.9375, or 4.4 percent, to $118, after only two hours of trading.
Also on the New York Stock Exchange, a basket security representing
shares in the 12 spun-off companies of Telebras rose $5.6875, or 5
percent, to $119.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian government was advised on the sale by Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter and by Salomon Brothers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
