<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAYING-FOR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MINISTER LEADS PUBLIC PRAYERS FOR RAIN
</HEADLINE>
 RAIN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GALE M. BRADFORD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEATHERFORD, Texas _ Minister Terry Jones says he believes that
God uses famines and droughts to send his messages.
</P>
<P>
   And when everyone is complaining about the lack of rain, ``the
message I personally get is to stop complaining about it and do
something,'' said Jones, who runs the Provision Center in
Weatherford. ``The only thing we can do is what he told us, and
that's to pray. After we pray, we need to look up and thank him.
Then I can't wait to see the first raindrop.''
</P>
<P>
   The killer heat wave that has plagued North Texas for more than
a month continued Wednesday, with the official temperature hitting
103 degrees at Dallas/Fort Worth airport. And for the second day,
Jones led a noontime prayer for rain on the courthouse lawn. He
said the prayers will continue until the rains come.
</P>
<P>
   As about 20 people joined hands and prayed, the wind picked up
and the temperature reading on a nearby bank thermometer dropped
from 99 to 97 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   One man held a red placard reading, ``Prayer works'' toward
downtown traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers honked in response. Others showed their approval
with a thumbs-up motion. One driver shouted that a ``rain dance''
is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Jones applauded the drivers and called the response ``an 80
percent improvement'' over those at Tuesday's prayer time.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those praying Wednesday wore shorts. Some carried
Bibles; others had water bottles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord, we need it to rain,'' Jones began, asking that the group
members acknowledge their agreement to pray together at a set time
each day and ``to give God all the glory'' for divine grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a need, right? And the need is for rain,'' Jones
appealed, looking skyward. ``He's going to send the rain, and we'll
persist till it comes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said that as he called county churches to recruit support,
he was asked why he chose the courthouse lawn as the place to pray.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I studied prayer meetings where they had similar
circumstances, maybe disasters, as in the old days, they chose to
come together in the center part of town, the marketplace, the town
square,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   So he applied to use the courthouse lawn and paid a $20 fee, and
Parker County commissioners approved his request Monday to use the
courthouse lawn.
</P>
<P>
   The permit procedure was set up after Richard Hogan, Texas state
director of American Atheists, objected to a Nativity scene on the
square.
</P>
<P>
   When informed about the noonday prayer service, Hogan noted the
irony of some parts of the country praying for rain to stop
recently, while ``we are praying for it to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Hogan said he was pleased to hear that the
application process is in place and working.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Plugge, who said he baled hay until 2 a.m. Wednesday to
avoid the daytime heat, joined the prayer group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time it cools off is night. I'm trying to work by the
light of the moon. The vegetable and melon farmers have already
about lost their crops, and the hay people are just holding on,''
he said. ``The hay crop is about a third what it should be, which
has begun to affect cattle prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to rain,'' Plugge said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Jones agreed.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
