<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PRISON-ABUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR INDICTED IN ASSAULTS VIDEOTAPED AT TEXAS JAIL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Mo., Hawaii, Idaho, Mass., Okla., Wis., Wyo.)  (jw) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A mock riot staged for a training video for guards, in
which prisoners were hit, kicked, shocked with a stun gun and
bitten by police dogs, has led to the indictment of four jailers on
federal charges of violating the civil rights of three inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners used in the videotaping, at the Brazoria County
Detention Center, just south of Houston, were from Missouri and had
been transferred to Texas under a widely criticized program to make
money from vacant jail cells by filling them with out-of-state
inmates. The program, involving thousands of prisoners from more
than a half-dozen states, has been the subject both of numerous
court proceedings questioning its constitutionality and of prisoner
complaints of harsh treatment and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The indicted jailers are Lester Arnold, 47, a former lieutenant
with the Brazoria County sheriff's office; David Cisneros, 38, a
former deputy and canine handler in the office; Robert Percival,
36, a current county jailer, and Wilton Wallace, 51, a former
lieutenant for Capital Correctional Resources Inc., a company hired
to help county officials with the program.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments were handed up on Monday but were sealed until
the arrest of Arnold, Cisneros and Percival this morning. Wallace
was already in custody, having been arrested in June on a civil
rights charge involving a separate incident at the jail.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments, announced by U.S. Attorney James DeAtley and
Don Clark, special agent in charge of the FBI's Houston office,
accuse all four officers of assaults on one of the Missouri
prisoners, while Arnold is charged with assaults on two others.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Cisneros, Percival and Wallace face as much as 10
years in prison and a $250,000 fine each. Conviction of Arnold
could mean 30 years and a $750,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments resulted from a yearlong inquiry by the FBI,
spurred by the videotape, which was made by jailers in September
1996. The video, in which guards could be seen kicking inmates,
goading dogs to bite them and shocking them with a stun gun, first
came to light during court proceedings on a lawsuit brought by a
group of Missouri inmates, including the three whom the indictments
cited as victims.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the video was made public last summer, by The
Brazosport Facts, a local newspaper, Missouri canceled the contract
under which 415 of its prisoners had been jailed at the Brazoria
County center. Missouri brought its prisoners home, and both the
FBI and Texas Gov. George Bush promised an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Under the prisoner transfer program, which at its height
involved more than 5,500 prisoners, out-of-state inmates are kept
either in city and county jails or in privately run prisons that
operate under the jurisdiction of local officials.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to make use of cells that had become vacant in
Texas after new prisons opened around the state in recent years.
That would ease a crush of prisoners in other states while making
money for local jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   But prisoners from elsewhere in the country often found the
conditions much harsher in Texas jails.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 2,600 prisoners _ from Hawaii, Idaho, Massachusetts,
Oklahoma, Wisconsin and Wyoming _ are still being held under the
transfer program, said Jack Crump, executive director of the Texas
Commission on Jail Standards. ``We have them in jails ranging from
San Antonio to Texarkana to Dallas,'' Crump said. ``All across the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   The program has become smaller, he said, because it was always
intended to work that way, not because of the Brazoria County
incident or the broader controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very obviously Texas didn't enter into this for a long-term
effort,'' Crump said. ``We had some bed space available at the
time. It certainly appeared to us that we could afford to use those
for out-of-state inmates. Other states obviously are resolving
their shortage of housing and recalling the inmates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
