<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   BofA Execs Exit As NationsBank Flexes Muscle  
   
 By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In another sign that NationsBank is in the driver's seat in its
merger with BankAmerica, two more of BofA's top seven executives
are leaving the bank.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice Chairman Kathleen Burke, head of human resources and the
bank's highest-ranking female, told colleagues last Friday that she
is leaving the bank in two months.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, her NationsBank counterpart, Charles Cooley, was
named corporate personnel executive of the combined bank and will
report to NationsBank Chairman and CEO Hugh McColl, who will head
the new BankAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Jack Meyers, BofA's vice chairman of risk
management, gave notice that he would be leaving, too.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus of top BofA officials began shortly after the $63
billion merger with North Carolina-based NationsBank was announced
in April.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Lockhart, head of retail banking, and Martin Stein, head
of technology and computer operations, announced then that they
would leave after their posts were filled with NationsBank
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers, 55, and Stein, 58, expressed interest in retiring even
before the merger with NationsBank was announced.
</P>
<P>
   But the departure of four of BofA's top seven officers, in
contrast to no resignations by NationsBank's top brass, suggests a
definite power shift to the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Neither bank could say yesterday how the approximate 240
executive appointments have been split between BofA and
NationsBank. But NationsBank clearly has the majority. When 35
executives were named to high consumer and corporate banking posts
in May, for example, 21 came from NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a powerful combination, and I will remain a big
booster,'' said Burke, 47. ``But after a lot of dialogue with the
two CEOs and my counterpart at NationsBank ... the career
opportunities didn't match with my aspirations.''
</P>
<P>
   Also yesterday, NationsBank corporate affairs director Lynn
Drury was given company-wide responsibility for public relations,
internal communications, charitable contributions and corporate
special events.
</P>
<P>
   BofA Executive Vice President Cheryl Sorokin was named
government policy executive, responsible for international, federal
and state relations. NationsBank's James Kiser was named corporate
counsel and secretary.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank also has been beefing up its Montgomery Securities
investment banking unit, which it acquired separately last year.
Yesterday, it hired Salomon Smith Barney veteran Mark Hallock to
head a group that will provide money to buyout firms. A few weeks
ago, it signed former Deutsche Bank securities boss Carter
McClelland as co-head of investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   The BofA bank merger still needs to be approved by shareholders
and federal regulators. Both banks are shooting for a September 30
closing date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
