<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 SEC Goes After Net Fraud   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Responding to a torrent of complaints about fraud on the Internet,
the Securities and Exchange Commission yesterday announced the
formation of a special unit to fight it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Office of Internet Enforcement, which operates under the
auspices of the SEC Enforcement Division, is collecting e-mail
gripes ( &LR; enforcement(at sign)sec.gov &LR; ) and focusing on
investigations of widespread fraudulent operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to protect investors and boot scam artists off
the Internet,'' said John Stark, who heads the two-person unit.
``The Internet provides a lot of good information, but a small
group of users is trying to rip people off.''
</P>
<P>
   Stark said the division is about to get two more officials from
the SEC, with which it shares finances and facilities.
</P>
<P>
   While the SEC has pursued litigation in the past against
Internet companies accused of fraud, the Office of Internet
Enforcement represents a concerted effort to step up the battle
against online securities fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the SEC has brought more than 30 cases involving
Internet fraud. The probes include nearly every type of investment
scam, such as phony stock offerings, stock-price manipulation,
affinity frauds that target specific ethnic or religious groups,
and pyramid schemes in which funds from new investors are used to
pay off promised returns to other investors.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent scam involves an alleged $7.2 million ponzi
scheme, in which Massachusetts-based Royal Meridian International
Bank &UR;  &LR; deceived widows and the elderly into forking over fixed
income and other investments to purchase fraudulent securities
issued by RMIB.
</P>
<P>
   The division, acting as a civil-enforcement agency, typically
seeks injunctions and fines against guilty parties. In some cases,
the SEC may assist in criminal cases with the aid of state attorney
generals, the FBI, the Justice Department and local police.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC's online Enforcement Complaint Center now receives more
than 120 e-mail complaints a day of potential securities fraud via
the Internet, according to Stark.
</P>
<P>
   When it launched a Web site in June 1996 to register gripes, it
received 10 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Securities fraud over the Web has mushroomed in recent years
along with the bull market on Wall Street, industry observers said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a Federal Trade Commission report this month said
the Web is overrun with a variety of online scams _ ranging from
pyramid schemes and get-rich-quick offers to fake businesses that
don't deliver products as advertised. The study is based on
information gleaned from 250,000 users during the past 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are gambling on investments, and that brings
with it, unfortunately, gross cases of fraud and misconduct,''
Stark said.
</P>
<P>
   Stark said he was unaware of travelzoo.com, a controversial
Bahamas-based Internet company that is giving away stock to lure
consumers to its site and bolster online traffic. It is uncertain
how much the stock is worth or whether the practice is legal,
industry observers said.
</P>
<P>
   An SEC spokesman declined to say whether travelzoo.com, which
advertises discount airfares and resort packages, is under
investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
