<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Why Huge Corporate Marriages Are Busting Out All Over  
   
 By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The six biggest corporate mergers in history have all occurred in
the past three three months. Investment banker Paul Deninger put
that in perspective.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It would be like six batters busting the home run record in
the same season,'' said Deninger, who tracks mergers for Broadview
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers Group knocked the first one out of the park on April
6, by offering $72.6 billion for Citicorp. A week later,
NationsBank blasted off a $62 billion bid for BankAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   May produced two more record-breakers, when Daimler-Benz
overtook Chrysler for $39.5 billion, and SBC placed a $62.5 billion
call to Ameritech.
</P>
<P>
   Last month AT&AMP;T offered $60 billion for cable-giant TCI, and
this week, Bell Atlantic said $52 billion was GTE's number.
</P>
<P>
   Three mega-deals in telecom, two in finance and one in
manufacturing: What's the message?
</P>
<P>
   Deninger thinks that telecom and finance executives have decided
that, to respond to deregulation and rapid technological change,
``the bigger you are the better off you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Powell, a member of the Federal Communications
Commission, happened to be in San Francisco Tuesday speaking to 70
telecommunications lawyers &UR;  &LR; the day the GTE news broke.
</P>
<P>
   They naturally asked how the FCC would handle this third
mega-deal in as many months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mergers are overwhelming,'' he confessed. ``They're
swamping the government (review) system.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Powell, one of two Republicans on the
five-member FCC, is against them.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in his hourlong remarks, Powell painted himself as a
staunch free marketer, who would prescribe strong doses of
deregulation for the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Policy-makers should learn to err on the side of the market,''
he said, repeating Yoda-like: ``When in doubt, trust the market.''
</P>
<P>
   But Powell _ the 35-year-old son of retired General Colin Powell
_ acknowledged the dark side of these market-driven mergers. The
recent mega-deals have been heralded as promoting lower prices by
increasing competition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But competition brings economically more &LR;  efficient &LR;  prices,''
he noted. What that means is charging prices that cover the true
cost of producing a good or service.
</P>
<P>
   Phone bills are a good example of inefficient pricing. It may
cost $10 to deliver basic phone service in San Francisco and $100
in rural Sonoma County, but customers in both areas pay the same
rate.
</P>
<P>
   That might have been fine when the phone monopoly could average
out costs, but it won't work as telecom rules are revised to
encourage a competitive free-for-all, he said. Telephone
deregulation is already pressuring rates up for some people.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the turd in the punch bowl nobody wants to talk
about,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   But even if some people's rates must rise in the short term,
Powell believes most of us will be better off in the long run if we
trust the competition to set prices and services.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not so sure. Banks, which have also been merger-crazy, have
steadily increased their fees. Does that mean other industries are
also inefficient and need mergers to create ``more efficient''
pricing?
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to see where this merger mania will end. Baseball
players have an October deadline to bust Roger Maris' home run
record. But in the boardrooms, they could still be swinging for the
fences when spring training starts next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail ( &LR; abate(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR; ). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
