<HEADLINE>
UNDER PRESSURE, N.Y. ASSEMBLY PASSES BILL CURBING PAROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also sidebar, NY-PAROLE-DEMS) 
(bl) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Democratic-controlled New York state Assembly
passed a bill Wednesday sharply restricting parole for first-time
violent felons, handing Gov. George Pataki a big election-year
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The passage of the legislation _ already approved by the
Republican-controlled state Senate and thus on its way to becoming
law _ marked an embarrassing acknowledgment by the Democratic
leadership that it had misjudged public sentiment on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The 128-20 vote stirred hours of passionate debate on the floor
of the Assembly. The measure's supporters argued that it would keep
violent criminals off the streets longer, while opponents attacked
it as an election-year gimmick that would do nothing to
rehabilitate prisoners before they return to society.
</P>
<P>
   The vote came in an unusual one-day special session that
Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver called after Assembly Democrats
came under intense attack from Republicans for failing to pass the
measure during the regular legislative session, which ended last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The move was a major policy reversal for Silver, a Manhattan
Democrat, who has acknowledged that he finally took action on the
bill to defuse a politically potent issue that had Democrats from
conservative districts fearful that they could lose their seats on
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   The bill now goes to Pataki, who has said he will sign it.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would take effect Sept. 1 and is expected to usher
in far-reaching changes to the state's criminal justice system. It
will take away the New York State Parole Board's ability to grant
early release to first-time violent felons, no matter how
rehabilitated they are deemed, and require them to serve at least
85 percent of the maximum sentence before being released under
supervision. Three years ago, the Legislature approved a similar
measure for violent felons with previous convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, only a handful of inmates serve more than
two-thirds of their maximum sentence before they are released on
parole. Because 30,000 inmates in New York are eligible for parole
each year, many experts believe that the new law will cause the
prison population to grow well beyond its current level of 70,000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The debate on the floor was sharp and personal, with many
liberal Democrats attacking the measure. The moment that Silver
decided to allow a vote on the measure, the outcome was decided.
Seventy-five Democrats and all 53 Republicans voted for the
legislation. Twenty Democrats voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the members of the Assembly began to vote on the
measure, a protester in the gallery screamed, ``Shame, shame!'' and
then sneered, ``Thank you for your courage!'' before being led away
by security officers.
</P>
<P>
   The floor debate underscored the deep ideological divide among
Democrats on criminal justice issues. Assemblyman Anthony Genovesi,
a Democrat from Brooklyn, harshly criticized the measure, saying it
merely extended prison sentences by a few years without providing
programs to insure that inmates are rehabilitated when released.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy that brought us here is not a product of the
parole system,'' he said. ``It's a product of the failure to
rehabilitate people in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Genovesi added: ``We're not doing anything here. We're
increasing sentences slightly.''
</P>
<P>
   But Assemblywoman Carmen Arroyo, a Democrat from the Bronx,
chastised her colleagues for not having passed the legislation
sooner so that violent criminals would be behind bars longer. ``I
believe we are here to do justice today,'' she said before the
vote. ``But there's much more that we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The parole measure was a pillar of Pataki's criminal justice
agenda this year. As part of his effort to have the proposal
enacted, he seized on the case of Jenna Grieshaber, a 22-year-old
nursing student who was killed in Albany in November 1997. Police
said her killer was a neighbor, Nicholas Pryor, who was on parole.
The governor named his proposal to end parole ``Jenna's Law'' and
enlisted her parents' help in his statewide campaign for the
legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
