<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CLINTON-STARR-NY     07-29 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN APPOINTMENT WITH TRUTH? 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 29:
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and independent counsel Kenneth Starr have
reached a reasonable compromise in the deal to have Clinton testify
at the White House rather than before a grand jury. That is a
significant step in maintaining the dignity of the presidency. But
his videotaped testimony, on Aug. 17, should be only a preliminary
to the more essential steps of telling the truth and explaining his
conduct to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   The desire for a president who can be believed and who can
govern in an undistracted way is growing. One measure of that could
be found in the panel assembled on Tuesday by ABC's ``Nightline.''
It consisted of Lanny Davis, the most loyal defender of Clinton's
conduct in office; George Stephanopoulos, who helped put him there,
and David Gergen, who was hired to organize Clinton's first term.
Their unanimity on Clinton's needs as to political survival and his
obligations to the American people was striking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time for him to come forward,'' said Davis.
Gergen added that the president ``ought to take charge of his own
defense'' and ``tell the complete truth'' in legal proceedings and
then before the nation. ``It's absolutely essential. I think people
still doubt his word. And he's having a hard time governing. This
is his quagmire. This is becoming his Vietnam.'' He added, ``I
think if he doesn't tell the truth in this situation, if he's
thought not to tell the truth, I think the rest of his presidency
is going to be in serious peril.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos, who in his role as an ABC commentator was the
first Clinton associate to speak of impeachment, said that truth
was the president's best defense against that fate. ``He should do
what he should have done six months ago _ come forward now, tell
the truth, take responsibility.'' A restoration of public respect
for the president is ``the only way he can govern the country,''
Stephanopoulos said.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of such counsel, White House spinners were all over
the place Wednesday morning saying that the president was not
persuaded. Then came the news from David Kendall, his private
lawyer, about the Aug. 17 testimony. If agreeing to that date is
simply another of his defensive tactics, Clinton's troubles will
not end. If it means he has taken charge of his fate, as Gergen
urged, then Clinton may have decided that his legal vulnerabilities
do not preclude an appeal for public forgiveness and congressional
understanding, if the allegations are true.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by David Gergen quoted above may seem apocalyptic,
but it is worth remembering that he was in the Nixon White House
during Watergate, and he knows something about letting slip those
opportunities when the bleeding can be stopped. His remarks touch
on a curious legacy from President Nixon, which takes the form of a
public readiness to forgive a president who opts for candor rather
than the extended cover-up. Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, in saying
that sexual indiscretions alone would not bring down a president,
was signaling that many in his party would be swayed by
presidential openness.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took what could be a step toward openness Wednesday. But
he has to understand that he inhabits a unique political space.
Neither artful handlers nor skilled lawyers can relieve him of the
burden of his presidential contract with the American people. As
his former colleagues said, it is past time for Bill Clinton to
pick it up. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0548 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9414 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     07-29 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: `I FIGHT ... I'M SORRY ... I'M ANGRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BOX-TYSON) 
(af) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ His clothes were cool, a black T-shirt under a
dark gray pin-striped suit. Not exactly courthouse attire. And with
the air-conditioning blasting, the conference room in the Richard
J. Hughes Justice Complex was even cooler as the questioning of
Mike Tyson began. And he reacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cold,'' he said. ``Aren't you?''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the image Tyson was trying to project, ``cold'' was
a bad choice of words. It was a reminder of what he has always been
as a boxer and sometimes as a citizen: cold, cruel, combative. And
what, in a loss of cool minutes later, he would be again. In
another moment of truth, he was being himself.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't very likely to prevent the State Athletic Control
Board from licensing Tyson as a boxer. Nor should it. His return to
a New Jersey ring for a New Jersey hotel-casino is too lucrative
for the state coffers to reject his application. After all, isn't a
boxer supposed to be cold, cruel and combative?
</P>
<P>
   What did they expect, a seminarian? But for more than two hours
in Wednesday's hearing, Tyson's image appeared all warm and cuddly,
a candidate for canonization.
</P>
<P>
   What you heard most often was that Tyson had more ``integrity,
honesty, character and responsibility'' than when he bit Evander
Holyfield's ears. His lawyer, Anthony J. Fusco Jr., proclaimed that
Tyson was now ``a better person for it'' and Tyson's eight
character witnesses agreed.
</P>
<P>
   After only one session that lasted about one hour, Dr. Bertram
Rotman, a Wayne, N.J., psychologist, portrayed Tyson as ``a big
teddy bear.''
</P>
<P>
   His surrogate mother, 93-year-old Camille Ewald, described him
as ``very sad and very sorry.'' His wife, Dr. Monica Tyson, called
him a ``very good husband, a very good father.'' His friend, Tom
Patti, said Tyson ``has been a victim far more often than he has
been a perpetrator.''
</P>
<P>
   His spiritual adviser, the Rev. Muhamed Siddeeq, predicted that
boxing was Tyson's preparation for a ``greater calling,'' that ``I
see Mike solving many of the world's problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In trying to explain the ring's ``tremendous pressures,'' Chuck
Wepner, once a heavyweight contender known as the Bayonne Bleeder,
predicted that ``Mike is smart enough to know that if he ever did
it again, he would be banned for life'' and Bobby Czyz, a
three-division champion, had ``no reservation that Mike is
remorseful.''
</P>
<P>
   His new adviser, Shelly Finkel, described the Holyfield incident
as ``an anomaly that happens under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, as Tyson answered assistant Attorney General Michael
Haas' questions, the pressure began to build. Speaking at first in
a quiet, gentle voice, he talked about being on probation until
next March for his rape conviction, then he was asked if he
operated any other business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged, ``I'm sorry for what I did,'' but soon he
blurted out: ``I'm cold. Are you cold?'' Then he was asked why he
had bitten Holyfield's ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know why I bit Holyfield,'' he said. ``I don't
even know how I was. In a rage. I went berserk. Let me take you
back to the first fight.''
</P>
<P>
   He talked about how Holyfield had butted him, then resumed
butting him in their second fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting weak,'' Tyson said. ``I was desperate, irate. I
just snapped.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would would display ``integrity, honesty, character
and responsibility'' now, Tyson said: ``I'm just a man. I'm no bad
guy. I'm no good guy. I do what's responsible for me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he might repeat the Indiana rape crime and the
Holyfield incident, he blurted: ``Both of those ordeals internally
ruined my life. You think I'm gonna do it again?''
</P>
<P>
   Fusco mentioned that Tyson had a statement to read, but Tyson
blurted: ``I don't want to say it now. I'm angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusco told him, ``Relax, Mike,'' then said: ``He's not angry at
you, Chairman. He's angry at himself.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Fusco later said, ``How many times does a man have to
be asked, `Are you sorry?' '' Tyson blurted: ``You know what I
mean, man. Why do I have to relive my ... ''
</P>
<P>
   In the lobby later, Mike Tyson insisted, ``I never lost my cool;
I was just expressing my hurt and frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   But he really had expressed who and what he is: cold, cruel and
combative. Just like boxing itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
