<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9418 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-DOMESTIC-PARTN     07-29 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-DOMESTIC-PARTNERS-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        HOUSE PASSES ANTI-DOMESTIC PARTNER AMENDMENT - SAN FRANCISCO
COULD LOSE $65 MILLION IN HOUSING FUNDS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Elliot Zaret  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 29 -- In what critics call a blow to both gay
rights and local autonomy, the House voted Wednesday to pull the
plug on an estimated $65 million of federal housing funds to San
Francisco unless the city repeals a domestic-partner law.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted, 214-212, to include in the housing and veterans
spending bill an amendment by Frank Riggs, R-Napa, that would
prevent San Francisco from using any federal housing money ``to
implement'' a city ordinance that forces companies doing business
with The City to provide domestic partnership benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a poorly disguised assault on a persecuted minority,''
said Rep. Tom Lantos, D-South San Francisco. ``It is simply
preposterous for Congress to interfere with an ordinance of a city
that merely provides for equality of opportunity and fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Riggs had planned to introduce a broader plan that would have
targeted any city with such a domestic-partner law, but since San
Francisco is the only city with the ordinance, he decided to narrow
it to specify the city code.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people want leaders who respect and support,
rather than dishonor the sanctity of marriage,'' said Riggs, who
defined marriage as ``the covenant between one man and one woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really think that we should elevate the relationship
between unmarried people as that between two married people, and if
we don't this is a form of discrimination?'' said Riggs.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-San Francisco, who estimated that the city
could lose more than $65 million in federal funds if the measure is
enacted, said the amendment interferes with the city's autonomy.
That's hypocritical, she said, for a Republican party that has put
state and local rights at the core of its agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi quoted a Riggs statement from a congressional debate on
block grants in which Riggs urged congress to ``decentralize
authority and responsibility and, yes, funding and revenues back to
the states. In turn we will be dispersing power to our fellow
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great idea, why not support it today?'' said Pelosi.
``This body is not the city council of any city in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Waxman, D-Los Angeles, suggested to Riggs that, ``If he
wants to get involved in the laws of San Francisco, that he go to
San Francisco and run for city council.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure is the first of at least two Republican anti-gay
rights proposals expected to be tacked on to appropriations bills.
Rep. Joel Hefley, R-Colo., plans to introduce an amendment later
this week to nullify President Clinton's executive order that makes
homosexuals a ``protected group'' against discrimination in federal
employment.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's debate crossed party lines. Two Republicans --
Reps. Jerry Lewis of Redlands, Calif., and Connie Morella of
Maryland -- spoke against the measure during the debate. They were
joined by 31 other Republicans who voted against the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no justification for this intrusion in local decision
making,'' said Morella. ``Frankly, it sets a terrible precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from other areas of the country also took
interest in the proposal, because of the jurisdictional questions
it raises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It attacks home rule not only in the city of San Francisco,
but it attacks home rule in every city in America,'' said Rep.
Dennis Kucinich, D-Ohio, the former mayor of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan was of particular interest to Bay Area
Representatives. The entire Bay Area delegation including
Republican Rep. Tom Campbell, of Santa Clara voted against the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation is discriminatory, hypocritical,
mean-spirited, and ill-conceived,'' said Rep. Lynn Woolsey,
D-Petaluma.
</P>
<P>
   Though passed by the House, the plan still has a ways to go
before it becomes law. The measure was is not expected to be
included in the yet to be passed Senate version of the spending
plan.
</P>
<P>
   In order to become law, the measure would have to remain in the
final version after House and Senate leaders hash out a compromise
bill, then that bill would have to pass both houses and be signed
by the President.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
