<HEADER>
A9419 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX     07-29 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAILEY'S COACH SHOWS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The coach behind coach Chan Gailey
visited Cowboys camp yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   And we're not talking about Jerry Jones here.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey's head coach at Americus (Ga.) High School, Jimmy
Hightower, now retired, was in Wichita Falls to check on one of his
two star pupils. Gailey's only one of two because Hightower, 69,
also coached former Cowboys running back and now NFL head coach Dan
Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Hightower said that Gailey's leadership abilities were evident
way back when he was a starting sophomore quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a real student of the game,'' Hightower said. ``He was
always the first guy to practice, the last guy to leave, the one
who really studied the scouting reports and always wanted to know
why we did things. That's not always the case with a high school
football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Hightower said he gave Gailey ``more leeway than any two
quarterbacks I ever coached.'' One time, Hightower gave Gailey the
option of going for the first down late in a tie game, or punting.
``He said, `Coach, you'll have to make that decision. That's what
they pay you for.'''
</P>
<P>
   Like they say: what goes 'round, comes 'round. &QL; 
WANDERING MINDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys receivers dropped an inordinate number of balls in
morning practice, and Gailey acknowledged it was a sign of a squad
with its mind elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our concentration level went down this morning,''
Gailey said. ``The offensive side especially. The thing I talked
about is we have to learn to handle prosperity. We had two good
practices in a row, and we have to learn to handle that and have
another one. We can't have two good practices and relax a little
bit. I thought we finished practice better than we started practice
today. I was glad to see that. We salvaged something out of the
last half of practice.'' &QL; 
SCHEDULE IS GOOD FIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have five preseason games plus two scrimmages this
summer. Gailey was asked if that's too much of a load for his
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not this year,'' Gailey said, ``and really, in general,
that's about what a lot of teams have.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey called the full schedule, ``an opportunity. You don't
have to hit each other so hard. You know you're going to have seven
opportunities to go live against somebody else. So you don't have
to bang on each other so much in training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey added, however, that he and his coaches will have to be
smart about the work schedule on the days between games and
scrimmages. ``We're not going to run roughshod over our football
team.'' &QL; 
YES, THAT'S $1 BILLION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones didn't back off the idea that the new Cleveland
Browns will cost the owner-to-be something approaching $1 billion.
But he did provide some context to explain the extraordinary
number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what that franchise will sell for,'' Jones
said, but ``I know if you looked at it as an asset, it's one of the
most unique assets. Certainly it's different than an expansion
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Browns, Jones said, ``will be able to compete, and I believe
compete for a Super Bowl immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said, by the way, it's unlikely the value of the Cowboys
will be learned in his lifetime. That's because he doesn't intend
to sell them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' Jones said, ``and I'll never know. The only
real way to establish value is when you see a transaction.'' &QL; 
FAMILY FRIENDLY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys played host to their first Family Day, on the
suggestion of Gailey. Families of players surrounded the field to
watch afternoon practice, then later joined players for dinner in
the cafeteria. &QL; 
THEY SAID IT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that's what we had Beau Morgan here for.''_ Jerry
Jones, Cowboys owner, when told that Troy Aikman had been roughed
up while attempting a quarterback sneak in goal-line drills at
Tuesday's practice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, I feel like my grandma when she used to tell me to
give her a bucket because her feet were so swollen. That's how I
feel after practice. I just want to put my feet in a bucket.'' _
Billy Davis, Cowboys receiver &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
