<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-JURORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURORS SOUGHT TO DISCIPLINE ACCUSERS, NOT FINANCIALLY BREAK THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sidebar with NY-BRAWLEY-SUIT) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ When jurors in the Tawana Brawley
defamation suit finally spoke Wednesday, they said they hoped their
verdict would satisfy Steven Pagones by clearing his name. They
said they wanted to teach a lesson to those who would accuse first
and ask questions later.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was a lesson delivered with a wagging finger, not with a
monetary bludgeon. The jurors said they saw no point in a
multimillion-dollar award that would destroy Pagones' accusers
financially.
</P>
<P>
   For all the enmity that the Brawley case had engendered over the
years and for all the delays and endless stretches during the trial
when the jurors were kept waiting outside the courtroom, while
who-knows-what went on inside, the jurors displayed little
hostility toward the participants.
</P>
<P>
   They ignored the most divisive question of all _ whether Ms.
Brawley was a victim, or the perpetrator of a hoax. ``There's
enough divisiveness in this country,'' said juror Glen Heinsohn.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, this jury of factory workers and public servants,
who sounded awed by the college and graduate degrees of the
participants in the trial, managed to reduce eight and a half
months of arduous, often mind-numbing testimony and the rare
exciting courtroom moment to a simple statement: the Brawley
advisers _ the Rev. Al Sharpton, C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox _
had lied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0557 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
