<HEADER>
A9426 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-BRICKYARD-TEX     07-29 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRICKYARD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR COULD PASS INDY IN OWN BRICKYARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Like a freight train of Chevrolets and Fords
hooked up in the draft, NASCAR's Brickyard 400 is bearing down on
the mystique and the majesty of the Indianapolis Motor Speedway's
Indy-car traditions.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's Winston Cup stock-car series already was the nation's
fastest-growing spectator sport when it, with the blessing of
Speedway president Tony George, ran the inaugural Brickyard 400 at
IMS on Aug. 6, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later _ and aided and abetted by the wrist-slitting
rift in open-wheel racing between George's Indy Racing League and
the Championship Auto Racing Teams _ the Brickyard 400 is closing
the popularity gap on ``The Greatest Spectacle in Racing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I hate to even touch that one,'' defending Brickyard 400
champion Ricky Rudd said as practice began yesterday for the race's
fifth edition on Saturday. ``Indy has speed to sell, and
technology. Stock cars are a different sport. I'm still a fan of
the Indy 500, but I don't think they did the race any justice when
they split the sport. It has hurt the recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it wouldn't be fair for me to say stock cars are bigger
now than Indy-cars'' at IMS.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd does not have to. As far as the almighty television ratings
are concerned, the Indy 500 has become just another race.
</P>
<P>
   The 5.6 rating for May's telecast on ABC of the 82nd Indy 500
was down 18 percent from 1996, the last time the race was run on a
Sunday. The rating also was down 33 percent from 1995, the last
year that Championship Auto Racing Team stars such as Michael
Andretti, Jimmy Vasser and Bobby Rahal competed at IMS. A rating
point represents 980,000 households.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Daytona 500 _ NASCAR's season-opening Super Bowl
_ has outrated Indy in each of the past three years. The 7.7 rating
for February's Daytona 500, the kickoff to NASCAR's 50th
anniversary season, was 38 percent higher than Indy. And even
less-renowned Cup events like the DieHard 500 at Talladega (Ala.)
Superspeedway on ABC (5.7) and the 2-year-old Texas 500 at Texas
Motor Speedway in Fort Worth on CBS (5.4) posted numbers comparable
to the famed Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time Indy 500 champion Al Unser Jr. said the TV numbers _
and grumblings from corporate America and fans _ should be telling
George the thrill is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to tell Tony. He knows,'' said Unser, who is
scheduled to compete in the first International Race of Champions
event at IMS tomorrow. ``Rick Mears puts it really good. He wears
the Indy 500 ring on his finger (as a four-time winner) and so do
I. But when we won the race, it was something. It was the top of
the game. Now it's not. And it's really a shame that it isn't. At
least we did it (win) when it was a race.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Cup race, NASCAR's Craftsman Truck Series is
scheduled to compete at nearby Indianapolis Raceway Park tonight.
And NASCAR's Busch Grand National Series is booked for the same
venue tomorrow night. Combined with the IROC finale, the weekend
looms as a showcase for full-bodied racing in the heartland of
open-wheel country.
</P>
<P>
   As per tradition, IMS officials do not routinely announce
attendance figures for either the Indy 500 or Brickyard 400. But
the 300,000-seat grandstands were filled in May for the Indy 500
and the Cup race also is a sellout. Fred Nation, vice president for
corporate communications and public relations for IMS, said
Speedway officials stopped taking ticket orders for the 1999 Indy
500 at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   But the sizzle that once marked the month of May has waned
noticeably since 1995, a fact driven home this year when George
opted to condense the traditional two weekends of qualifying drama
into two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's always made the Indianapolis Motor Speedway and the
Indy 500 is that it's the best of the best in one series,'' said
Jeff Gordon, winner of the inaugural Brickyard 400. ``That's what I
think we hold right now. We've got the best of the best in
stock-car racing. It's all in one event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we're here, and I'm in the Brickyard 400, I'd love to
see it be the top event here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton, rising star of Roush Racing's five-car Ford stable,
conceded that the Brickyard 400 does not enjoy the storied
traditions associated with the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I venture to say that right now there's more interest in the
Brickyard 400 than there is in the Indy 500,'' Burton said. ``But
to say an event that's in its fifth year compares wouldn't be
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Nation, who regularly travels an IRL circuit where empty seats
are plentiful, said the organizers of domestic open-wheel racing
are being challenged by NASCAR's runaway growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brickyard 400 is a major event because of the heritage of
the Indianapolis 500,'' Nation said. ``People say, `Which one do
you like the most?' It's like which of your children do you love
the most? You love them both, for different reasons. We want to see
the Brickyard 400 grow. But in our opinion, it will never overtake
the Indy 500.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0558 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9427 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-GM-UNION-NYT &LR;      07-29 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GM-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE AUTO DEAL THAT RESOLVES LITTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 30:
</P>
<P>
   The most telling fact about union-management relations at
General Motors is that the agreement announced Tuesday to end the
strike promises that top officials of the union and the company
will talk to each other regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Such a promise would be unnecessary at Ford or Chrysler, which
have managed to maintain better relations with their workers while
making their plants more efficient. Management and workers at GM
have traditionally viewed each other as the enemy, something that
seems not to have changed. Told that GM's stock price had fallen
Wednesday, a union official responded, ``That's good,'' explaining
that he was pleased that GM executives would lose a little money.
</P>
<P>
   It is good news that the strike is finally over, but it is far
from clear that much was accomplished by either side. When the
strike began, GM was talking about ending a system at one Flint
factory where workers had to meet daily production quotas and could
then call it a day, even if they had only worked for four hours.
They wanted the workers to be required to work the entire day. What
the company got was a promise that some of the quotas would be
increased, but the system will remain.
</P>
<P>
   The union won specific promises of investment at certain plants
and promises that those plants would not be closed or sold until
the end of next year. That assures that those issues can be
addressed in next year's national labor negotiations, which
threaten to be just as confrontational as was this strike, which
was ostensibly over local issues.
</P>
<P>
   There is little reason to believe that anything fundamental has
changed. GM, whose dominance of the American automobile market was
once so great that antitrust action was considered, appears to
remain in a long-term decline, the result of poor management
decisions and hostile labor relations.
</P>
<P>
   It would be wonderful if the renewed contacts promised by the
new settlement led to a real change at GM and made it easier for
the lumbering giant to compete in a world auto market that is
replete with excess manufacturing capacity. But there is scant
evidence that will happen. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
