<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-MOTHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER'S LEGAL VULNERABILITY IS SEEN AS MOTIVE FOR LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-MOOD, CLINTON-TRIPP,
CLINTON-TALKINGPOINTS) 
(th) 
 By IAN FISHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Monica Lewinsky's legal troubles began last January, her
first phone call was to her mother, Marcia Lewis. The two, by all
accounts, are extremely close.
</P>
<P>
   So close, it seems, that when federal prosecutors granted Ms.
Lewinsky full immunity from prosecution on Tuesday, a similar deal
was given Ms. Lewis, Ms. Lewinsky's shopping partner, roommate and,
perhaps most relevant, her confidante.
</P>
<P>
   One lawyer familiar with the case said it was the mother's legal
vulnerability that ultimately helped bring Ms. Lewinsky to the
table.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a well-documented case on the mother,'' one lawyer
familiar with the case said Wednesday. ``They always knew the
pressure point was Monica's mom.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the possible evidence against Ms. Lewis is not known. But
in conversations taped by a former colleague, Linda Tripp, Ms.
Lewinsky, according to lawyers who have heard the tapes, is quoted
as saying that her mother thought it was a ``brilliant'' idea for
Mrs. Tripp to fake an injury to avoid receiving a subpoena in the
Paula Jones sexual misconduct case.
</P>
<P>
   She also says that her mother told her to lie about the nature
of her relationship with President Clinton in a deposition to the
Jones lawyers. If that is true, Ms. Lewis could have been charged
with obstructing justice.
</P>
<P>
   Given their strong relationship, Ms. Lewinsky is believed to
have confided to her mother many of the details of what Ms.
Lewinsky now reportedly acknowledges was a sexual relationship with
the president.
</P>
<P>
   That knowledge, perhaps imparted over time as any relationship
developed, could be crucial to the case that independent counsel
Kenneth Starr appears to be building against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knew everything,'' Lucianne Goldberg, the New York
literary agent who has heard some of the tapes, said Wednesday. The
impression given on the tapes, she added, was that the two are
``very close.''
</P>
<P>
   That became evident from the start of Starr's pursuit of Ms.
Lewinsky. When federal agents working for Starr first confronted
Ms. Lewinsky, she called her mother, and the agents had to wait in
a hotel in northern Virginia for hours for Ms. Lewis to take the
next train from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the big deal?'' Ms. Lewis asked the investigators,
according to several reports published since then. ``So she lied
and tried to convince someone else to lie.''
</P>
<P>
   To Steven Schragis, who published a book that Ms. Lewis wrote on
the private lives of three male opera stars two years ago, it made
perfect sense that her daughter would call her in a time of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcia Lewis was an extremely competent, aggressive,
intelligent, worldly woman,'' Schragis said. ``I'm using a lot of
cliches here, but she knew the score. She knew what was going on.
The light bulb was on.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he said it was Ms. Lewis who devised a novel marketing
strategy for her book: the hint, never addressed in the book, that
she had an affair with Placido Domingo. He has denied knowing her
more than casually.
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since she divorced Ms. Lewinsky's father, Dr.
Bernard Lewinsky, a Los Angeles oncologist, Ms. Lewis, 49, and her
daughter carved out a comfortable life in which they rarely strayed
far from each other.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, while Ms. Lewinsky worked as aide in the
White House and later in the Pentagon, they shared a two-bedroom
apartment at the Watergate complex overlooking the Potomac River.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Starr called Ms. Lewis before a grand jury, and the
result was a public relations disaster for the independent
counselor. Ms. Lewis testified for two days but became ill at one
point, leaving the courthouse looking pale and distraught. It was
an opportunity that three men in her life _ her lawyer, Billy
Martin, her former husband, and her then fiance and now husband, R.
Peter Straus, a New York media executive _ took to excoriate Starr
and his tactics. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
