<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AGREES TO VIDEOTAPED TESTIMONY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton headed off a potential
constitutional crisis Wednesday by agreeing to provide videotaped
testimony to a grand jury investigating whether he had sex with
Monica Lewinsky and tried to cover up the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement worked out between Clinton's lawyer and
independent counsel Kenneth Starr calls for the president to
respond to prosecutors' questions Aug. 17 at the White House with
his attorneys present.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an effort to achieve a prompt resolution of this entire
matter the president will voluntarily provide his testimony,''
Clinton's private attorney David Kendall told reporters following a
meeting at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement, Starr withdrew a subpoena issued for
Clinton's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement allows Clinton to avoid becoming the first
president to personally appear before a grand jury investigating
criminal allegations against him. It also ends the prospects of a
legal challenge to the withdrawn subpoena, a fight that likely
would have reached the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton agreed to the videotaped testimony after Kendall failed
Tuesday to convince U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson to
delay the interrogation until September. During a closed-door
session, Starr's deputies reportedly told the judge they were
willing to accommodate most of the president's demands about
testifying, but not a monthlong delay to avoid interrupting the
scheduled Aug. 15 start of Clinton's vacation to Martha's Vineyard
in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The session with prosecutors _ scheduled two days before
Clinton's 53rd birthday _ sets up a likely conflict between the
president and the 25-year-old former intern over the nature of
their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Paula Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit against the
president, both Clinton and Lewinsky denied under oath ever
engaging in sex. Clinton has publicly made similar comments and has
said he never told anyone to lie.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry said Wednesday he ``had no
reason to think'' the president would not make the same denials in
his grand jury testimony. Asked whether the president would prefer
to testify before or after Lewinsky, McCurry said: ``You'd have to
ask his attorney that. I don't know,'' Clinton's lawyers did not
return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision to provide testimony came a day after
Lewinsky was granted immunity from prosecution in exchange for
cooperating with Starr's grand jury. In interviews with Starr's
deputies, Lewinsky reportedly said she is prepared to recant her
earlier sworn denial that her relationship with Clinton involved
sex.
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting in New York, Lewinsky reportedly provided
prosecutors with details of her sexual encounters with Clinton at
the White House and how they discussed ways to keep their
relationship secret.
</P>
<P>
   Citing sources close to the case, the Washington Post reported
that Lewinsky plans to turn over physical evidence Starr could find
helpful in building his case against Clinton. The material includes
telephone message recordings with the president's voice and a dress
that could be tested for identifying DNA evidence against the
president.
</P>
<P>
   During the session with Starr's deputies, Lewinsky acknowledged
typing the so-called ``talking points'' _ two pages of suggestions
on how to mislead Jones' legal team.
</P>
<P>
   But the former intern provided information about the document's
origins that conflicts with statements by Linda Tripp, whose secret
tape recordings of Lewinsky's phone conversations triggered the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky reportedly is prepared to say the talking points were
compiled from conversations with Tripp, not with the help of anyone
from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, a former White House secretary who befriended Lewinsky
when they worked at the Pentagon, denied the claim during brief
remarks on the steps of the U.S. District Courthouse as she ended
eight days of testimony before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allegations to the effect that I contributed to or assisted in
any way with the creation of the talking points are as illogical as
they are patently false,'' Tripp told reporters. ``I have testified
to the fact that I had nothing, let me repeat, nothing to do with
preparing the so-called talking points.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Starr's deputies were preparing for a series of
briefings with Lewinsky and her attorneys before she goes to the
courthouse _ probably within the next two weeks _ to testify before
the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with Clinton's Aug. 17 videotape session, Lewinsky's
impending testimony fueled speculation that Starr's investigation
is drawing to a close and a report to Congress _ as required by
federal law _ is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're now in the closing throes of this; at least, I
hope so,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, a Utah Republican who chairs the
Senate Judiciary Committee. ``Once the president has testified, I
think (Starr) is going to make his recommendations within a short
time after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermont Sen. Patrick Leahy, the ranking Democrat on the
judiciary committee, said ``the time has come'' for Starr to issue
his report and ``wrap this sucker up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
