<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PHANTOM OF CAMPAIGN REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 30:
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to campaign finance reform, Newt Gingrich is like
the phantom of the opera. He likes to do his dirty work at night.
The House speaker plans to resume debate Thursday night on the
Shays-Meehan bill, with votes on more than a dozen killer
amendments designed by foes of reform to split the bill's
bipartisan support. The House has thus arrived at a critical moment
for the cause of reform. In the last several weeks, Republican
moderates have stood with Democrats to defeat the amendments. If
they do so again, reform legislation can pass the full House next
week.
</P>
<P>
   After promising to finish the bill by the end of the session in
mid-August, Gingrich has repeatedly scheduled and canceled debates
and then held many of them at night. In the last week, the speaker
has also stepped up his pressure on Republicans to support
amendments that would compel Democrats to vote against the
legislation. Two such amendments are most in danger of passing. One
would repeal much of the Voter Registration Act of 1993, the
so-called motor voter law that made it easier to register,
especially for the poor. Another would require congressional
candidates to raise at least 50 percent of their funds from within
their districts, which would also penalize candidates in poor
areas. Republicans who favor reform and who are sympathetic to
these measures should realize that attaching them to the
Shays-Meehan bill would doom its chances in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Rep. Martin
Meehan, D-Mass., the legislation would ban unlimited ``soft money''
donations and curb fund-raising for attack ads broadcast by
independent groups. At least 40 moderate Republicans have worked
with the Democrats in recent weeks to beat back killer amendments
and sustain bipartisan support for Shays-Meehan. They must not flag
in their support now.
</P>
<P>
   Among these independent Republicans are several from the New
York region. They include Michael Forbes, Benjamin Gilman, Amo
Houghton, Sue Kelly, Rick Lazio and James Walsh of New York; Bob
Franks, Rodney Frelinghuysen, Frank LoBiondo, Marge Roukema and Jim
Saxton of New Jersey, and Nancy Johnson of Connecticut. For these
lawmakers, the votes this week are among the most important of
their careers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
