u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-LPGA-PAK-NYT &LR;      07-29 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-PAK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID CRUSH OF FAME, PAK TAKES HOOPLA IN STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario _ A few months ago, Se Ri Pak never imagined
that she would be overwhelmed with interview requests. Or that
phone calls to her hotel room would have to be screened. Or that
dozens of charitable organizations would want her to make
appearances or donations. Or that her presence at an LPGA
tournament would mean more fans and more news media.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Pakmania, the stir created by Pak, a 20-year-old
South Korean who is the hottest player in golf. Pak will attempt to
win her third major of the year starting Thursday, when the du
Maurier Classic begins at Essex Golf and Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Having already won the McDonald's Ladies Professional Golf
Association Championship and the U.S. Women's Open, Pak could
become the first player since Pat Bradley in 1986 to win three
majors in the same year. And Pak, as a rookie on the LPGA Tour,
could also become the first woman since Mickey Wright in 1961 to
win three consecutive majors.
</P>
<P>
   With four victories since May, including last week's Giant Eagle
LPGA Classic, Pak has soared to the top of the tour's money list
($768,211), becoming a star in the process.
</P>
<P>
   How much interest has Pak created for the LPGA? More than 500
credentials have been issued to the news media for this week's
tournament, more than 300 above last year's demand. And 76 of those
applications came from South Korea, where Pak has become the
nation's biggest sports hero.
</P>
<P>
   If Pak wins again this weekend, the focus on her will become
even more intense. But so far, Pak has handled the pressure, the
attention and the growing expectations as easily as she hits a
drive down the middle of the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have pressure; I'm happy,'' Pak said during a
pre-tournament interview this week. ``If I didn't play well, who
would care?''
</P>
<P>
   But many people do care about Pak, which is causing problems.
Her agent, Sung Yong Steven Kil, was angry Wednesday that someone
at Pak's hotel had revealed where she was staying, causing her
phone to ring with unwanted calls.
</P>
<P>
   Pak may soon have to start registering under an assumed name.
And while Pak loves to play, Kil and Pak's parents have become more
concerned about her schedule. Every LPGA tournament wants Pak now,
and she will have to learn to pace herself. Pak will be playing in
her sixth consecutive tournament this week, and while she plans to
take next week off, look for her to take longer breaks in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Se Ri to have a long career, like Nancy Lopez,'' Kil
said. ``We don't want her to burn out. We didn't know she would
attract this much attention this quickly. It's not just interviews.
So many charities, over 1,000, have contacted her, asking her for
money. We don't even know who most of them are. When we ask for
more information, they can't do it. You have to be so careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez has become a mentor for Pak. The hope is that Pak's
popularity can help the entire tour, the way Lopez's did in 1978,
when as a rookie she won five consecutive tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is putting us on the map,'' said Lorie Kane, who is
seventh on this year's money list. ``Annika Sorenstam and Karrie
Webb got us there, but she is working from that. She is a very
strong young woman and she's a really nice kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Hurst won the year's first major, the Nabisco Dinah Shore,
and Colleen Walker is the defending du Maurier champion. But for
the last few months, the spotlight has been on Pak. And her peers
have definitely taken notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tasted being one of the top players, and I'd like to be
one of the feared players again,'' said Laura Davies, who won two
majors in 1996, but who is without a victory on the LPGA Tour this
year. ``When my name goes on the leader board, no one cares
anymore. They might look, but probably figure I'll do something
wrong and fall off.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with Se Ri, you just count down the holes until she
catches you. It doesn't matter how old you are. If you're good,
you're good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
