</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAVORITE OF PARCELLS LIKELY TO MISS SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ill.)   (bl)  
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The New York Jets may have suffered a setback
on defense when Casey Dailey, a rookie linebacker from
Northwestern, sustained a foot injury on the last play of Tuesday's
practice that could end his season before it really began.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Parcells said Wednesday that he had planned a heavy
workload for Dailey, a fifth-round draft choice. Parcells said he
had figured Dailey as a pass rusher as well as a special teams
player and had been impressed with the way he quickly picked up
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to do some of the things we did with Carl Banks
and Lawrence Taylor and Andy Headen,'' Parcells said, invoking
names of the New York Giants' great linebacking corps of the 1980s
and early '90s. Parcells said he hoped to use Mo Lewis and Chad
Cascadden, along with Dailey, in some schemes that would confuse
the offense about who would be rushing the passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hurts us,'' said Parcells, who, for the first time this
camp, seemed glum at one of his news conferences. ``The kid was a
pretty good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how after only a week, and with an untested player, he
could have such a high opinion, Parcells said: ``I coached the
position for 20 years. When you see one, you know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Following surgery, Dailey is expected to be out at least 12
weeks. But the Jets do not yet know whether they will have to put
him on injured reserve for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Curtis Martin will sit out the entire week to rest
his injured hamstring. Parcells said that he is not concerned about
the injury, which happened last Saturday, and said that Martin
would play if there were a game this week.
</P>
<P>
   Next Question
</P>
<P>
   Do not ask Bill Parcells about individuals yet, he reiterated
following Wednesday's first scrimmage of camp.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he does not want to talk about the quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, though, Glenn Foley, who may be tired following
eight days of taking most of the snaps, had little success
Wednesday alternating against first- and second-string defenses. In
three drives, he led the offense to only a field goal by John Hall.
He completed 13 of 23 passes, which gained only 97 yards. He was
intercepted once, and one pass was batted down.
</P>
<P>
   In each of his three drives, Vinny Testaverde led the offense to
points as he completed 15 of 22 passes for 170 yards. He passed for
touchdowns to Alex Van Dyke and Dedric Ward, and also got a field
goal from Hall.
</P>
<P>
   But the coach was voluble about the things that matter to him
most: playing smart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't too bad on penalties,'' he said. ``The mechanics of
running the game _ getting in and out at the right time _ worked
pretty well. I'm trying to get them game-ready. I've got to start
get them acting as a team. We've got a game next week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' exhibition opener is at Philadelphia on Thursday,
August 6. Last year Parcells established the Jets as a smart,
well-drilled outfit, and he wants them to start out that way
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's scrimmage was marked by the continued improvement of
Marcus Coleman, who is backing up Otis Smith at right cornerback,
and the running and receiving of the backup Robert Farmer. Leon
Johnson, who replaced Martin as the feature back, had the day's
longest run of 9 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Mawae Anchors Line
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line could be at its strongest in years with Kevin
Mawae (pronounced muh-WHY) anchoring center. He is surrounded by
Matt O'Dwyer at right guard and Todd Burger, an off-season pickup
from the Bears, at left guard. Jumbo Elliott is at his accustomed
left tackle spot, while Siupeli Malamala is trying to hold off the
rookie Jason Fabini of Cincinnati at right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I'm on a line where there isn't a
rookie among the first five,'' Mawae said. ``It's helped us get off
to a big start.''
</P>
<P>
   Mawae came from Seattle, where a five-year, $17 million
free-agent contract with the Seahawks made him the National
Football League's highest-paid center in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys rag me about being the $17 million man,'' he said.
``They tell me they can't do certain things because they don't make
that kind of money. But the notoriety I got because of the
contract, my teammates have great expectations from me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
