<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMBODIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CAMBODIA'S IMPERFECT ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 30:
</P>
<P>
   With a campaign marked by noisy rallies and turnout levels
topping 90 percent, Cambodia's parliamentary election on Sunday was
a feast for a people starved for democracy. Yet Cambodians were let
down by their leaders, who manipulated the election, and by an
international community too inclined to approve a flawed process.
</P>
<P>
   Although voting went smoothly, the campaign was monopolized by
Cambodia's strongman, Hun Sen, who forced his way into power after
losing U.N.-organized elections in 1993. Following his violent coup
a year ago, in which he ousted his co-prime minister and rival,
Prince Norodom Ranariddh, opposition leaders fled the country. When
Hun Sen let them come back, it was to a campaign so controlled that
Ranariddh's return was not covered on Cambodian television. A U.N.
human rights office in Cambodia has confirmed 21 political murders
in the last two months. Almost all the victims are opposition
activists.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of few, preliminary results indicate that Hun
Sen will again lead a coalition government. But opposition parties
contend that the vote count was distorted by widespread fraud.
Given the problems, it seems premature to call the tabulation
``free and fair,'' the description used by the largest
international observer group, representing mostly European and
Asian nations. American observers were more nuanced, but still
minimized the unfairness of a skewed campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition allegations must be investigated before the
results can be accepted. Many Cambodians fear that political
killings might increase, as they did after the 1993 elections.
Worrisome delays in releasing results could indicate that more
manipulation is afoot. The election is over, but Cambodia's
democratic process still requires international scrutiny and
pressure on Hun Sen. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2223EDT &QL; 
