<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIM-GOODWILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE WOMEN `THE BIGGEST QUESTION MARK IN SWIMMING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST MEADOW, N.Y. _ When Goodwill Games swimming began Tuesday
night with the American women routing China, the American men's
team sat together in the stands, cheering wildly. Wednesday night,
when men's swimming began wih the United States facing Germany, the
American women led the boisterous crowd in supporting their male
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The American men, like the women, are favored to win their
round-robin of dual meets. The only surprise in the American
women's 88-34 victory over China was how one-sided it was. The
Americans won 11 of the 14 events, some by huge margins for this
level of competition. There are reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese, embarrassed by too many cases of their swimmers
testing positive for illegal bodybuilding drugs, are trying to
avoid more drug problems. Their 17 female swimmers here include
only one who swam in January's world championships, only two who
swam in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics. The oldest is only 21. The
oldest Americans are Lea Loveless Maurer, 26, and Jenny Thompson,
25.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the Chinese have better swimmers at home that
are clean,'' said John Collins, head coach of the Badger Swim Club
in Larchmont, N.Y., and an assistant coach of the American women's
team here. ``They have demonstrated the importance to them of the
Olympic Games and world championships, and they are not concerned
about other international meets. I think they are thinking about
the 2000 Olympics, and they brought this team to get some
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said that when some American coaches learned the Chinese
women would swim here, they objected.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked why we should give China that credibility when some
countries want to throw China out of the international
federation,'' he said. ``But it is the Goodwill Games, and we are
trying to show good will.''
</P>
<P>
   While this may not be the best team China could present, it
isn't the best for the Americans either. Amy Van Dyken, who won
four gold medals in the 1996 Olympics, is recovering from shoulder
surgery and watched nervously from the stands. Kristine Quance is
pregnant. The world champions Brooke Bennett and Kristy Kowal
passed up this meet to continue training for the U.S. championships
in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their victory, the American women were puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know what to expect from the Chinese,'' said
Thompson, who won the 50-meter and 100-meter freestyles against the
Chinese and anchored a winning relay. ``They ebb and flow from meet
to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   And Maurer, who won the 100-meter backstroke and led off the
winning medley relay, said: ``They are the biggest question mark in
swimming. They're the most unpredictable team I've ever swum
against.''
</P>
<P>
   SPLASHES
</P>
<P>
   In the first dual meet Tuesday night, Penny Heyns, a South
African breast-stroker, led the World All-Stars to a 64-58 victory
over Germany. Wednesday night's second men's meet sent Russia
against the World All-Stars. The women return Thursday night with
the United States against the World All-Stars and China against
Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2224EDT &QL; 
