<SLUG> BC-POWERBALL-VENDORS-YT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILLEGAL VENDORS FEED LOTTERY FEVER
</HEADLINE>
   (See also POWERBALL-GREENWICH) 
(rm) 
 By THE NEW YORK TIMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERSEY CITY, N.J. _ The young woman here rapped on the car
window and waved a stack of Powerball tickets at the driver.
``Notas de Connecticut?'' (``Connecticut notes?'') she offered in
Spanish, before moving on to the next potential customer.
</P>
<P>
   She was not the only person in New Jersey trying to capitalize
on the ballooning Powerball jackpot, according to the state's
Lottery Commission. By Wednesday afternoon, it had suspended the
licenses of six authorized lottery agents for selling Powerball
tickets bought out of state, said Holly A. Lehr, a commission
spokeswoman. ``Some of them were actually advertising outside of
the store, and there were complaints,'' she said. ``Some were
charging double the price.''
</P>
<P>
   She declined to give the names or locations of the suspended
agents or six other agents who were under investigation She said
they faced fines or loss of their license to sell lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey lottery games _ Pick 3, 4 and 6, Cash 5, Lotzee and
Instant Game tickets _ are sold by 6,000 licensed lottery agents
throughout the state, including grocery and convenience stores,
delis and liquor stores, Lehr said.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate case, the manager of an A&AMP;P grocery store in New
Jersey was arrested in Manhattan Tuesday for scalping Powerball
tickets, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The manager, Robert Maher, 31, was soliciting passers-by to buy
$5 worth of Powerball entries for $10, said Detective Joseph
Pentangelo, a Police Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Maher was arrested near Rockefeller Center about 2 p.m. with 144
tickets in his pocket. He was charged with promoting gambling, a
misdemeanor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0569 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9448 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-WORLD-U.S.-HNS &LR;      07-29 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-WORLD-U.S.-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
U.S. starts 
tourney 
with win
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ For their first dip into the FIBA World
Championship of Basketball, the U.S. squad did a lousy
impersonation of its ``Dream Team'' predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   About the only resemblance they had was if you looked at the
final score _ which is exactly the way coach Rudy Tomjanovich
wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   A Dream Team this is not. It has no NBA stars, who would have
spent more time scribbling autographs than worrying about the
competition at this tournament. No 20-point scorers every night.
Maybe not on any night. No endorsement contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But what these Americans do have is a unity and a bulldog
attitude that was a rousing success in their opening game. The U.S.
survived a slow start (hey, it's OK to be nervous when you're
replacing a Dream Team), then rolled to an 83-59 victory over
Brazil on Wednesday at Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Michael Hawkins, who so far is the closest thing the
Americans have to a go-to guy, had 12 points, 10 assists and seven
rebounds. The 10 assists were the most in USA Basketball history
during a World Championship game.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no one-man show. Nothing with this team will be.
Only three players reached double figures, led by Wendell Alexis'
13 points.
</P>
<P>
   But it was players like Duke's Trajan Langdon, who wasn't even
on the squad five days ago, coming off the bench to knock in a pair
of 3-pointers just before halftime for some valuable breathing room
during a close opening 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ashraf Amaya (3-for-3) and Brad Miller (4-for-4) coming
off the bench with strong showings. It was a team defense that wore
down the Brazilians, who figure to be middle-of-the-pack pretenders
in this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In short, this was just a team. A good, cohesive team. The Dream
part will have to come later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win as a team,'' said Tomjanovich, without question
the perfect coach for this team of unstars. ``We don't have the big
superstar, a dominating player. We don't have a guy we can go to
every night and say he's going to get the job done. We have to do
it as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Test No. 1 was passed with flying colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we don't have any dominant players,'' said Alexis.
``Every night, it's going to have to be somebody different.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, when the Americans play the more potent Lithuanians, it
will have to be everybody playing differently. And better. The
Americans were a cohesive unit, true. But they did not play
particularly well against a Brazilian team they were expected to
dominate.
</P>
<P>
   In the first moments, Jason Sasser squirted up a couple of shots
that even a Greek god couldn't have helped find the basket. David
Wood missed three shots in 30 seconds, and the U.S. was in a 6-1
hole after four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The game remained close throughout the first half. But with
Brazil up 27-24, Hawkins hit a pair of free throws and then Jimmy
King tapped in a miss. Langdon then fired up the first of his
3-pointers, and Miller, who still hasn't missed a shot for the U.S.
in exhibitions or on Wednesday, scored on a layup.
</P>
<P>
   That 9-0 blitz was the foundation of a 16-5 run to close out the
half, which ended with Langdon's second trey.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians never threatened in the second half as the U.S.
wore them down and steadily pulled away.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Trajan to come in here and hit those 3s was a big boost
for us,'' Alexis said.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy who was cut from the team a week earlier,
returned from Europe to the U.S., then was recalled after Mateen
Cleaves' ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good feeling to get a chance to come in and help,''
Langdon said. ``I kept telling myself I was going to be on the
bench for a while. But when I got in there, if I got my looks, I
wanted to take them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear the beginning of their first game in the World
Championship was a little overwhelming to this team.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable the players would feel some pressure to live
up to Dream Team standards, even though they don't have the
credentials to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us awhile to get rid of the jitters,'' said Hawkins,
who ran the team smartly. ``We definitely were anxious. But our
bench did a heck of a job. And our defense got our offense going,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Alexis: ``It definitely wasn't the same feeling as in the
exhibitions. This was a little more nervous, like we were on the
start of a long trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said he wasn't alarmed when his team started the
game cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing good basketball; we just weren't getting the
ball in the basket,'' he said. ``But our guys didn't panic. We
stuck with the defensive intensity, and that was the key to the
game, really, holding them under 60 points offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I think we saw tonight is that we're a team that is 12
deep. Depth is one of our strengths. To me, our starting lineup is
good. But they're just the guys who start the game. I also rely on
the other guys who don't start. The bench was big.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we've been talking about all along, to compete on
every possession. That's the only way we're going to be able to be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the U.S. starters combined for only 31 of the
team's 83 points.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, the starters don't expect to play that poorly
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an excellent win, a great win,'' said Wood. ``I'm amazed
at how much better we can get. As a team, we really made some
mistakes in this game that I know we won't be making in a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's four or five teams that could beat us. But if we
really lock in for 40 minutes, it's going to be hard for anybody to
beat us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
