<DOCNO> NYT19980729.0570 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-29 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-OAKLEY-NYT     07-29 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-OAKLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KNICKS' DEPARTING ENFORCER SPEAKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)  (mk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the end, after he spent a decade plunging into
peril for the Knicks and absorbing blows like an air bag for their
superstar, no one protected Charles Oakley. Patrick Ewing did not
return the favor.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing did not dive in front of the Knicks' president, Ernie
Grunfeld, to keep the team from trading Oakley to Toronto for
Marcus Camby. But as Oakley sat in a Manhattan restaurant
Wednesday, just a coin flip from Madison Square Garden, he did not
lay an elbow into Ewing for allowing his exile. Oakley spilled the
blame in Grunfeld's lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something about New York fans, you can't fake them,'' said
Oakley, who was relaxed and in good spirits as he talked with
reporters in New York just over a month after the draft-day trade.
``Ernie knows what he did. And fans know what he did. He might have
come out and said, `Well, we need to get younger.' But you traded
three young guys just two years ago. I don't want to hear it. Just
be a man about what you've done. Don't say you're getting younger.
You got one young body, and a dozen old ones. How young are you
going to get?''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley is 34 and Camby is 24, so the math is obvious. Next year,
Oakley will be a free agent, as will Camby. And because of Camby's
athletic youth, he has been viewed as the best deal for the future
of the Knicks. ``They probably didn't want to re-sign me at the end
of next year,'' Oakley said. ``And they probably want to re-sign
Marcus. I don't know, we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a part of Oakley that doubts the team's immediate
future _ the one that stretches as long as the three years left on
Ewing's contract _ will lead to a title without his bouncer-like
presence beneath the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how long I'll be in Toronto, but for the Knicks,
I don't see them winning a ring anytime soon,'' Oakley said. ``So
it's a dog race to get the ring. Now they don't have a guy who can
do the work, the hard and dirty work. They got a lot of guys on
that team to please. A lot of guys need shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley never needed to be a go-to man. Although he pushed for a
less Ewing-oriented offense if it meant more shots for Allan
Houston and Larry Johnson, Oakley was content with his occasional
18-foot jumper and with toiling away in obscurity for his 10 years
next to Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not knocking Patrick, because he's a franchise player no
matter who comes here,'' Oakley said. ``But Allan and Larry will be
the young bodies to get over the hump to win the championship. They
have to get their shots for the Knicks to go to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   But with that said, Oakley has always known that the ultimate
asset was Ewing. In all their time together, the two never grew
close. Oakley still has not returned a message that Ewing left for
him weeks ago. But there was a certain businesslike respect for
each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with Patrick for 10 years, and it wasn't easy playing
beside him because he was the main guy,'' Oakley said. ``Night in
and night out I just tried to make his job easier, as far as the
dirty work. I understood that this was his team. I was willing to
make it better.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby will arrive billed as the answer to the Indiana Pacers'
athletic duo of Antonio Davis and Dale Davis; they both burned the
Knicks with their shot- blocking and second-chance points in the
playoffs last spring. But Camby will also have to accept his
inferior place in the scoring hierarchy. ``He's a young
superstar,'' Oakley said. ``I don't know if he can take it. He'll
have to get used to it because there ain't no shots, I'm telling
him now, unless he's got a hoop in his back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby will have to find his niche with the Knicks, just as
Oakley did. But nothing the spindly Camby can offer physically will
fill the role of enforcer that Oakley played so well. Just how soft
the Knicks will be in Oakley's absence can be measured in December,
when the Raptors play the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   While Oakley is looking forward to facing his old team, in many
ways he will always be a Knick. If one day the Knicks honor him for
the decade of service, Oakley will be happy to answer the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they call me,'' Oakley said with a smile, ``I hope it
ain't Ernie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
