<HEADLINE>
TALKS ON RANDY JOHNSON DRAG ON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Wash., Ohio)   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The New York Yankees continue to talk to the
Seattle Mariners about Randy Johnson as Friday's midnight trade
deadline draws near, but their bid may ultimately hinge on whether
Johnson agrees to a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   According to one executive with knowledge of the discussions,
Yankees general manager Brian Cashman has made it apparent that the
value of his offer will depend greatly on whether Johnson can agree
to an extension. Seattle wants a three-player package in return for
Johnson, and the Yankees being discussed include Ramiro Mendoza and
Mike Lowell, a minor-league infielder, and possibly Hideki Irabu
and second baseman Homer Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the executive, Cashman is leery of dealing a
substantial package for Johnson and then seeing Johnson depart as a
free agent after this season. For example, Cashman might be willing
to part with Mendoza and Lowell if he knew Johnson would accept a
three-year contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   The only real incentive for Johnson to agree to an extension and
forgo free agency, however, would be if the Yankees gave him an
overwhelming offer _ and at a time when the Yankees are debating
whether to give a big contract to Bernie Williams, that seems
highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Officials around baseball think the Yankees' primary competition
for Johnson will be the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
</TEXT>
