A9451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-COL-PARTISANS-NYT     07-29 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-PARTISANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LET'S ABOLISH PARTISANSHIP, PARTISANS CRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wednesday night in Brooklyn, at the most recent
meeting of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's Charter Revision Commission, it
was even harder than usual to distinguish the chutzpah from the
humbug.
</P>
<P>
   Under discussion was a proposal that, by the standards of New
York City politics, would, if taken seriously, surely rank as
revolutionary. Under the proposal, party primaries would be
eliminated for citywide offices. Instead, there would be one,
anyone-can-join primary, followed by a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   If placed on the ballot and endorsed by the voters in November,
the proposal would overnight turn New York City from a Democratic
town into a nonpartisan one.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, the proposal was described as a cure for just
about everything that ails city politics, from low voter turnout to
a lack of robust debate. Thomas Ognibene, City Council Republican
minority leader, went so far as to suggest that nonpartisan
elections would eliminate the need for term limits.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the commission see enough promise in the proposal
that they have hired an eminent political science professor to
analyze its implications in depth. They seemed heartened by his
conclusion that it would not violate the Federal Voting Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   What they did not pause to discuss _ at least not in public _
were the immediate political consequences of offering up such a
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   With time running out, the Charter Revision Commission is still
desperately seeking something, anything, that looks enough like an
idea to stick on the ballot in November. Already, the commission
has boldly taken up, only to drop, such ambitious ``reforms'' as
eviscerating the city's land-use review process, eliminating the
job of its second-highest elected official and abolishing the
Independent Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the commission dropped these proposals was,
according to Chairman Peter Powers, that they were too far-reaching
and controversial to pursue in the remaining weeks before ballot
proposals are due in early September.
</P>
<P>
   Which only makes one wonder what the commission members were
thinking in Brooklyn as they earnestly considered the merits of
nonpartisan elections.
</P>
<P>
   Even under the best of circumstances, the idea is not the sort
that Democrats, with a registration advantage in the city of nearly
5 to 1, would happily embrace. Yet these are, let's just say, not
the best of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being above politics, this Charter Revision Commission
is surely one of the most blatantly political creatures in New York
history. It was conceived for no other reason than that the
Republican mayor was peeved at the idea that the Democratic speaker
of the City Council, Peter Vallone, might use a referendum on a
ball park to make political hay at his expense. The commission is
stuffed with former members of Giuliani's administration who, if
they are not actually registered Republicans, all clearly feel
bound by loyalty _ or fear _ to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   For such a baldfacedly partisan body to suggest that the problem
in New York politics is its excessively partisan character is
madness or daring or, perhaps, the ultimate inside joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we have nonpartisan elections?'' asked former Mayor
Edward Koch, a critic of the commission since its creation.
``Simply so as to make it easier for Republicans to disguise
themselves?
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they ashamed of their philosophy?'' he added.
``Apparently. That's why we only elect one once every 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly for the commission, at this point it seems some sort of
joke at its own expense has become all but unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   If, on the one hand, the commission musters the courage to
forward to voters a proposal of real consequence, it will only
focus attention back on itself and its own highly dubious
legitimacy. What would be more preposterous than asking city voters
to decide a major constitutional question all because their mayor
did not want them to vote on the location of a baseball stadium?
</P>
<P>
   If, on the other hand, the commission balks and settles for
something bland and inoffensive, then it will just be advertising
its own superfluousness. Who needs a Charter Commission to propose
a campaign reform package less bold than the one already offered by
the City Council?
</P>
<P>
   Chutzpah or humbug? It's not a pretty choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
