<HEADLINE>
SARATOGA STARTS WITH SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ From the steeplechasers who opened
Saratoga's season Wednesday afternoon, to the 2-year-old fillies
seeking stakes status in the Grade II Schuylerville, the depth of
Wednesday's card served as a reminder of why Saratoga is racing's
best known and most prestigious meet.
</P>
<P>
   And the crowd of 25,570, a record for a July opener, was treated
to an upset in the $100,000 Schuylerville as Jorge Chavez guided
the 17-1 shot Call Me Up to a narrow victory over the favored
Brittons Hill.
</P>
<P>
   After setting a track record at Aqueduct in her first start,
Call Me Up was beaten by 8{ lengths as the favorite in the Astoria
at Belmont. Wednesday she battled Fantasy Lake for five and a half
furlongs, edging clear in the final yards and holding off the late
surge from Brittons Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down the stretch I knew there was a horse coming at me, but my
main concern was to stay straight and finish in front,'' Chavez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Call Me Up covered the six furlongs in 1:12 4/5 and returned $36
for a $2 bet to win.
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES
</P>
<P>
   _ Wagering at New York City Off-Track Betting was down $230,000
Wednesday compared with last year's Saratoga opening day, in the
wake of the decision by the New York Racing Association to withhold
it simulcast television signal from home cable viewers in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   _ The undefeated Mossflower, winner of the Hempstead Handicap at
Belmont by 12 lengths, will miss Sunday's $250,000 Go for Wand
because of a wrenched ankle. The trainer RICK SCHOSBERG detected a
slight filling in her right front ankle after a workout Tuesday,
but he said that X-rays were negative and that the 4-year-old filly
should return to the track in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   _ D. WAYNE LUKAS, who saddles the favored Time Bandit in
Thursday's $100,000 Sanford, will be challenged by his former
assistants DALLAS STEWART (Color of Smoke), TODD PLETCHER (Texas
Glitter) and MARK HENNIG (King's Crown) in the six-furlong race for
2-year-old colts. . . . Yagli, trained by BILL MOTT, is the
favorite in a field of 12 for Friday's $125,000 Bernard Baruch on
the turf.
</P>
</TEXT>
