<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-HARASS-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OFFICE'S `ATMOSPHERE' GOES ON TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rm) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Only two former assistant attorneys general are
named in a sexual harassment case brought by one of their
colleagues that is working its way slowly through a state court
here. But, in a sense, an entire division of the attorney general's
office has ended up on trial.
</P>
<P>
   In her testimony, Barbara Davis, now 40, and other witnesses
have painted a picture of the Criminal Justice Division, where she
worked from 1989 to 1993, as a place of blatant sexual banter and
touching, of male superiors openly conducting sexual affairs with
subordinate women, and of a place where a woman's physical
attributes were fair game for public comment even after death, in
gruesome crime scene photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think the public should know what was going on behind
the closed doors of that department _ what it was like,'' Davis
said in an interview between court sessions recently. ``Women were
just treated like they were nothing, and it was just devastating to
be there. Just the fact of having seven or eight witnesses come
forward to testify about what was going on has restored my faith a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis has accused Richard T. Carley, the former deputy director
of the Division of Criminal Justice, of repeatedly touching and
propositioning her while she worked as an assistant attorney
general in the division. She has also accused the state and her
immediate supervisor, Gregory Sakowicz, of ignoring her complaints
about Carley. She said she had become unemployable as a result of
the harassment and the civil lawsuit, which went to trial five
weeks ago, and is asking for a life's salary as well as unspecified
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The state maintains that Davis failed to notify the right
authorities, and says it acted swiftly to punish Carley once she
filed her suit in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Department of Law and Public Safety, which is
led by the state attorney general, would not comment on the record
about Davis' allegation, noting that the trial, whose outcome will
turn in part on the atmosphere within the Criminal Justice
Division, was still in progress. But one official, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said that the department, which works
closely with the police in investigating and prosecuting prominent
crimes, had a reputation as a ``macho'' outfit in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had 150 lawyers in there, many of whom were ex-cops, and
they were working with police investigators and, yes, it had a
reputation for having a precinct-house atmosphere in those days,''
the official said. ``But it has changed since then,'' the official
added, because of the trial, and because of tightened sexual
harassment laws.
</P>
<P>
   Office atmosphere is a major element in proving sexual
harassment under New Jersey law, said Alan Hyde, a law professor at
Rutgers Law School in Newark who teaches a courses on labor and
employment law, because it can have the effect of discriminating
against women by creating an unbearable working environment for
them. Stressing that he had not followed the Davis case, Hyde said
that the heavily male atmosphere of police work could have the
illegal effect of telling women that they could not be on an equal
footing with men.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sets up the classic sexual harassment case, which comes
from the male defense of a previously male preserve,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde later added: ``You can't hang a sign on the door that says,
`Men Only' in words, but this case seems to say they hung the sign
not with words but with deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Davis and several supporting witnesses described such
an atmosphere. If a crime under investigation was a sex crime
against women, Davis said, Carley would ask for photographs of the
victim and comment on her body. Sakowicz had a gag statue in his
office resembling a penis, a police investigator testifying for
Davis said. Carley, Davis said, displayed pictures of bathing
beauties in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses testified in support of Davis that Carley was
often uncomfortably familiar with women in his department. He began
a meeting with Carol Stanton Meier, a deputy attorney general, by
telling her that she had ``a nice body,'' Meier testified. Another
witness said Carley had dangled the keys for a sports car in front
of her and said, ``If I give you a ride in my Porsche, will you do
me?''
</P>
<P>
   But although the women confirmed stories about Carley's
occasionally lurid language and comments and about the atmosphere
of male swagger in the Criminal Justice Division in the early
1990s, none directly confirmed witnessing the acts that brought
Carley before Judge Maria Marinari Sypek and a jury of five men and
five women.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has accused Carley of touching her breasts, of stuffing
money in her brassiere, of caressing her from behind and of
suggesting that they have an affair. Carley admitted in court that
he was conducting an affair with a division subordinate at the
time, even though he was married. He has since divorced.
</P>
<P>
   But Carley denied that he had touched Davis or requested sex
with her. A state investigator who looked into Davis' charges in
1994 testified that Carley admitted saying things like, ``nice
boobs,'' or ``nice butt,'' but that he had said that the comments
had not been aimed at Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davis maintains that she complained about Carley to
Sakowicz, her direct supervisor, and that Sakowicz did nothing.
Sakowicz denied that Davis came to him, and the state argues that
in any case, Davis failed to take her complaint to any of several
offices established to enforce non-discrimination law for state
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The state asserts that Davis concocted her charges and the
lawsuit after she was passed over for a promotion. Her inability to
find work as a lawyer since leaving state employment in 1994 is not
due to the shock of what happened or the burden of the trial, as
Davis contends, but to her own malingering and use of painkillers
and alcohol, the state maintains.
</P>
<P>
   Once Davis filed her suit in 1994, the state did investigate her
complaints and demoted Carley in rank and in pay, moving him to the
Alcoholic Beverage Control Division, where he has no supervisory
authority.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The sanctions against Carley do not amount to an admission of
guilt by the state, said Cynthia Jacob, the lawyer defending the
state and Sakowicz. Carley may be liable for further punishment,
depending on how the trial comes out.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob maintains that the department's written policy on sexual
harassment gave Davis several places to turn for help, including
the department's Division on Civil Rights, the state's Equal
Employment Opportunities Commission, and the equal employment
opportunities office in the Department of Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we took prompt remedial action,''
Jacob said during a pause in the trial. ``We did everything
employers are required to do under the law when faced with a sexual
harassment complaint.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
