<HEADLINE>
CASINO OPERATORS PLAN TO START LAS VEGAS AIRLINE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Nev., N.Y., Mass., Ga., Conn., Ind., Ariz.)  (jw) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aiming to ensure that a steady stream of visitors will fill the
rising number of hotel rooms scheduled to open in Las Vegas in the
next few years, two casino companies are helping finance a new
airline that is expected to be announced Thursday, several
executives and investors familiar with the plans said.
</P>
<P>
   The new carrier will fly primarily to cities on the East Coast
using single-aisle Boeing 757 jets and will be called National
Airlines, reviving a name that effectively disappeared in 1980,
when the old National Airlines merged with Pan American World
Airways.
</P>
<P>
   The new National is the brainchild of Michael Conway, one of the
founders of American West Airlines, who was ousted as its chief
executive in 1994 as the airline was struggling to emerge from
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The resort companies Harrah's Entertainment Inc. and Rio Hotel
and Casino Inc. have put up $30 million of the initial $50 million
investment in the airline, according to two people involved in the
new carrier. Both Harrah's and Rio declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Several million more has been invested by Wexford Capital
Management, an investment firm based Greenwich, Conn., that is run
by Chuck Davidson, who previously worked with Michael Steinhardt,
the successful hedge-fund manager.
</P>
<P>
   Conway declined comment, but several executives who requested
anonymity and two Las Vegas officials confirmed the plans, which
Conway has long been forming.
</P>
<P>
   A news conference to announce the airline was scheduled for
Thursday morning at McCarran International Airport, the city's main
gateway. But last-minute details, including securing the rights to
the name National Airlines, which was famous in the 1970s for its
suggestive ``Fly Me'' ads, were still being ironed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in negotiations, and we are close to reaching an
agreement,'' said Jeff Kriendler, spokesman for Pan Am Liquidating
Corp., which holds the rights to National.
</P>
<P>
   Many casino owners are nervous because the number of new Las
Vegas hotel rooms is expected to rise 20 percent by the year 2000,
while the number of airline seats for visitors to the city has been
shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Several carriers, including Southwest Airlines and America West
serve Las Vegas, but it is the only major city in the country that
no major carrier uses as a hub. The reason, airline analysts say,
is that mostly tourists, not higher-paying business travelers visit
Las Vegas, giving it the lowest per passenger revenues of any major
city.
</P>
<P>
   Airline traffic is at a high, and Samuel Buttrick, an analyst
with Paine Webber in New York, said, ``In the last year or so, we
have seen major carriers cut back Las Vegas service as they
reallocate limited supply to more profitable markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Those familiar with his plans say that Conway plans to fly to
New York, Boston, Atlanta and other cities on the East Coast that
have spotty service to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The airline will start with four 200-seat 757s, a plane that is
relatively inexpensive to operate on medium- and long-range
flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike is designing an airline that takes into account the
unusual characteristics of the market,'' said Davidson, who also
controls Chautauqua Airlines Inc., a regional carrier based in
Indianapolis. His investment gives Wexford the right to form an
exclusive regional express carrier for the new airline.
</P>
<P>
   But several analysts were skeptical of the new carrier's chances
given the large number of inexpensive charter flights that bring
gamblers into Las Vegas. ``I don't think anybody has ever made any
money in Las Vegas from an airline point of view,'' said one
analyst who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The new airline cannot begin flying until it receives approval
from federal regulators, a process that will take a minimum of six
months and probably longer. With the delay comes a risk that by the
time the new carrier gets off the ground, the red-hot airline
industry may be cooling.
</P>
<P>
   For Conway, the new airline is a chance to rehabilitate his
reputation and show up Phoenix-based America West, which he founded
with others in 1981. The airline expanded too quickly in the late
1980s and was forced into bankruptcy in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Conway was discharged after clashing with
Chairman William Francke, who was brought in to turn around the
airline. While some people at America West remained loyal to the
Conway, others blamed him for the airline's troubles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
