</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIDERHOUSE-THEATER-REVIEW-875(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE CIDER HOUSE RULES': IRVING NOVEL BECOMES A PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(rm) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Forceps, curette, speculum: The use of tools for
both obstetrics and abortions is described in unblinking detail in
``The Cider House Rules,'' the earnest and whimsical stage
adaptation, now at the Mark Taper Forum, of John Irving's earnest
and whimsical novel from 1985. To perform a resurrection, however,
it takes nothing less (or more) than a typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   This heartening use of the machine occurs somewhere in the
fourth of the six hours in this recounting of Irving's sprawling
and eminently topical story of abortion, sex and the American
family, which is centered on the virtuous and eccentric head of an
orphanage, Dr. Wilbur Larch. In the scene, Wilbur (played by
Michael Winters) has decided, for purposes of plot too Byzantine to
explain, to write a series of letters to invent an epistolary,
grown-up identity for a sickly orphan named Fuzzy Stone (Tom Beyer)
who died as a child years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner does the doctor begin tapping on his typewriter
(invisible, since most props in the production are pantomimed) than
Fuzzy materializes. At first, he is as feeble as he was in life,
but he draws strength from the new words that Wilbur has invented
for him. Suddenly, he's a vital, straight-backed creature of fire
and eloquence, not to mention a nifty tap dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Tap dancer? Yes, the rhythms of the doctor's typewriter have
found their way into Fuzzy's feet. The word has not only been made
flesh; it dances like a Busby Berkeley boy.
</P>
<P>
   This delightful convergence of literature and show business
embodies what's best in ``Cider House,'' which was conceived by Tom
Hulce and Jane Jones, who have also directed Peter Parnell's
adaptation of Irving's book. The scene is both a tribute to and a
sendup of the various arts of fiction, the ability to summon whole
characters and whole worlds out of air. And while the scene is
executed with a precision that bespeaks long rehearsals, it also
feels happily, headily drunk on the powers of storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   So does much of this two-part production, which runs through
Sept. 27 at the Taper, and the feeling generates a buzz of good
will among the audience that goes far in sustaining attention.
``The Cider House Rules'' has been long aborning, with its earliest
workshop productions beginning in 1993 and an eight-hour version
performed at the Seattle Repertory Theater. The years of care and
affection show in every gesture onstage here. This is undoubtedly a
tale told by enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, you may discover a slight, nagging
dissatisfaction that grows louder as the show goes on. It's not
that the invention of the performers flags. But there is a sense
that if you're going to commit this much time to a play, you expect
it to take you places that ``Cider House'' doesn't often venture.
</P>
<P>
   The experience can be like listening to a love-struck friend
describe the object of his affections. His excitement is
infectious, but you also can't help wondering if his beloved really
warrants it. The form is more beguiling than the content of ``Cider
House,'' and that is not to say that the content isn't meaty. The
play, like Irving's book, which is also being adapted for the
movies, is a heartfelt moral argument for a woman's right to have
an abortion, a topic that obviously remains overwhelmingly fraught,
and for the unorthodox forms that families take in a world where
children are often born unwanted.
</P>
<P>
   But the didacticism and the manipulative sentiment evident in
the novel become even more apparent onstage. The show's creators
have done wonders in telescoping the breadth of ``Cider House,''
which spans the first half of this century. What they haven't been
able to do is link the book's message to convincing developments in
character. This leads to the impression that however charming the
actors are, they are also, to some degree, lecturers, a bit like
characters in Soviet films about a man and his tractor.
</P>
<P>
   The theatrical form of ``Cider House'' was inspired by the Royal
Shakespeare Company's beloved adaptation of Charles Dickens'
``Nicholas Nickleby.'' As in that play, seen on Broadway in 1981,
most of the 22 actors in ``Cider House'' play multiple roles,
including animals and inanimate things like filing cabinets.
Everyone speaks the work's third-person narrative as well as
dialogue. And while John Arnone's handsome tiered wooden set
conjures an appropriate atmosphere of New England rusticity (nicely
enhanced by James F. Ingalls' lighting and David Zinn's costumes),
it is up to the performers to create the specific sense of place
and changing times.
</P>
<P>
   This is all managed with appealing dexterity, including a
high-speed recap of everything that happened in the first half at
the beginning of the second. There is, remarkably, never any
confusion about the plot, which follows the fortunes, with various
detours, of two pivotal figures. There is Dr. Larch, who has turned
an orphanage in the remote, bleak Maine town of St. Cloud's into a
place where women can come either to have their babies delivered or
to receive abortions, an illegal practice at the time in which the
play is set. (His loyal nurses are wittily portrayed by Jane Carr
and Brenda Wehle.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of equal significance is Homer Wells (Josh Hamilton), a resident
of the orphanage whose adoptions somehow never work out and who
comes of age as Wilbur Larch's apprentice. His unorthodox but
thorough studies in obstetrics lead him to feel that he cannot take
the life of a fetus, a conclusion that prompts Wilbur to tell
Homer, in what might be the play's motto, ``You may disapprove, but
you may not be ignorant or look away.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, both the social and the medical facts surrounding
unwanted pregnancies and their terminations are presented in a
series of vignettes notable for their explicit anatomical language.
These scenes range from flashbacks that show Wilbur's tragic,
life-changing encounter as a young man with a prostitute to Homer's
life-changing encounter with a dead fetus. There is a lively
assortment of supporting characters, including the golden couple
(Myra Platt and Patrick Wilson) with whom the grown-up Homer forms
a menage a trois American-style. But the play's central course is
built on Homer's gradual conversion, after finding this provisional
family and fathering his own son, back to his mentor's point of
view.
</P>
<P>
   This is a problem in that Homer, both in the book and the play,
isn't much more than a tabula rasa. The winning Hamilton, whose
face here has an appropriate question-mark quality, does an
excellent job in physically taking Homer from childhood to the edge
of middle age. But he is crippled by a passive part without a
personality, and the emotional journey Homer takes exists largely
on the surface alone.
</P>
<P>
   Winters, who played the ether-addicted Wilbur in Seattle, has
more to work with, and his performance is beautifully modulated.
One wishes, however, that his persona were a little more distant
from the gruff but loving fathers of sentimental sitcoms and
midcentury movies. (His voice and inflections bring to mind Tom
Bosley in ``Happy Days.'') This is a play, after all, that features
a scene in which Wilbur and Homer, their backs to each other, rasp
out the previously unspoken words, ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   That's pure John Irving, a writer who combines the mind of a
progressive liberal with the heart of someone who sheds silent
tears at Andy Hardy pictures. This novelist uses his purely
American authorial voice, laconic leaning toward cute, to spin
labyrinthine, self-delighted and ambitious plots of tremendous
narrative drive. It should be pointed out that the concerns of
``Cider House'' go beyond the issue of abortion to the shifting,
contingent rules that people create to survive, both literally and
emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Wilbur, several other characters in ``Cider
House'' very much make their own rules, and they have been invested
with first-rate performances that tear through their thematic
skins. Kevin Jackson and Casey Lluberes, as a black migrant worker
and his teen-age daughter, give haunting, intriguingly shaded
interpretations of a pair governed by a system that a white man
like Homer Wells can never fully comprehend.
</P>
<P>
   The production is also blessed with the pulsating presence of
Jillian Armenante, who plays the rambunctious, vengeful Melony, an
orphan propelled to acts of destruction by unfathomable anger. A
rectangular woman with a megaphone voice, Ms. Armenante brings an
astonishing physical intensity to her part that hits the production
like a concentrated jolt of caffeine. Like many Dickens characters,
she's a gargoyle, all right, but one made up of magnified,
ineffably human traits.
</P>
<P>
   Dickens' ``Great Expectations'' and ``David Copperfield,'' as
well as Charlotte Bronte's ``Jane Eyre,'' figure in ``Cider House''
as bedtime reading at St. Cloud's. As tales of orphans' coming of
age, they are also, of course, antecedents to ``Cider House.'' But
these parentless children from Victorian England have complicated,
stormy souls that transcend formula and what Homer describes as the
``too sweet'' parts of their books. ``Cider House'' still needs
richer intimations of this kind of interior life to make something
truly grand of its likable exterior.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE CIDER HOUSE RULES'
</P>
<P>
   Adapted by Peter Parnell, from the novel by John Irving;
conceived and directed by Tom Hulce and Jane Jones; sets by John
Arnone; costumes by David Zinn; lighting by James F. Ingalls; sound
by Jon Gottlieb; original music/musical director, Dan Wheetman;
production stage manager, Amy Fritz; stage managers, Mary K.
Klinger and Lisa J. Snodgrass; assistant director, Benjamin
Krevolin. Presented by the Center Theater Group/Mark Taper Forum,
Gordon Davidson, artistic director; Charles Dillingham, managing
director; Robert Egan, producing director. At 135 North Grand
Avenue, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Jillian Armenante, Tom Beyer, Jane Carr, Josh Hamilton,
Kevin Jackson, Casey Lluberes, Myra Platt, Brenda Wehle, Patrick
Wilson and Michael Winters. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
