<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AGREES TO TESTIFY IN LEWINSKY INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 2nd, 3rd and 10th grafs to delete references concerning
broadcast of Clinton's testimony via closed-circuit television and
to rearrange other material.) (Eds.: See also CLINTON-TRIPP, CLINTON-MOOD,
CLINTON-TALKINGPOINTS) 
(ART ADV: Photos of Monica Lewinsky and Linda Tripp are being sent
to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton agreed on Wednesday to submit to
questioning at the White House by federal prosecutors in the Monica
Lewinsky investigation after independent counsel Kenneth Starr
withdrew an unprecedented subpoena to compel his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The president's attorney, David Kendall, sought to delay the
testimony, scheduled for Aug. 17, until late September. But the
federal judge supervising the case, Norma Holloway Johnson,
admonished both sides to schedule it sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be permitted the unusual courtesy of having his
lawyers at his side, unlike other grand jury witnesses. Starr was
willing to agree to many of Clinton's conditions in exchange for
the president's decision not to challenge the subpoena on
constitutional grounds and further delay the lengthy investigation,
lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   As the arrangement to secure Clinton's testimony was announced,
new details emerged of the testimony and evidence that Ms. Lewinsky
is prepared to provide to grand jurors under the broad immunity
deal she reached with prosecutors on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence, Ms. Lewinsky turned over a dress and several taped
phone messages from Clinton on Wednesday to the office of the
independent counsel, according to lawyers familiar with Ms.
Lewinsky's case. They said the dress had been sought under subpoena
since late last year, and that Ms. Lewinsky had shipped it to her
mother for safekeeping. The dress became a bargaining chip used by
prosecutors to wield pressure against her mother, Marcia Lewis, and
ultimately was part of the reason Ms. Lewis was granted immunity
along with her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers familiar with Ms. Lewinsky's account said that the
25-year-old former White House intern told prosecutors on Monday
that she had expressed concern to Clinton in December about a
number of gifts he had given her, including a T-shirt, a brooch and
a hat pin, that had been subpoenaed by lawyers for Paula Jones in
connection with her sexual misconduct suit against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky said that the president had made the hypothetical
suggestion to her that ``If you don't have them you can't turn them
over'' to Mrs. Jones' lawyers. Clinton's personal secretary, Betty
Currie, retrieved the gifts and gave them to investigators last
winter, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   That account closely tracks with Ms. Lewinsky's original
proposed testimony, or ``proffer,'' given to investigators last
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's agreement to testify allows him to avoid the
humiliating spectacle of being led under subpoena into a federal
courthouse to appear personally before the 23-member grand jury
that has heard scores of witnesses, from high government officials
to uniformed Secret Service officers, over the past seven months.
But it gives Starr something important as well _ the chance to
confront the president in person and question him extensively on
matters ranging from his relationship to Ms. Lewinsky to alleged
efforts to buy her silence.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has now secured the testimony of the two central and final
witnesses in the Lewinsky inquiry, after Ms. Lewinsky accepted an
immunity agreement that requires her to provide ``full and
truthful'' testimony about what she says was an 18-month
relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky scheduled to tell their stories in
the next few weeks, the independent counsel will soon have the
final pieces of a complex mosaic that may or may not constitute
crimes or impeachable offenses. Starr is expected to quickly
conclude the Lewinsky investigation and prepare a report for
Congress on his findings.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor has said he is investigating allegations of
perjury, witness tampering and obstruction of justice arising from
charges that Clinton carried on a sexual relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky and directed a conspiracy to conceal it.
</P>
<P>
   The final judgment on Clinton will be rendered by the House of
Representatives, should it choose to pursue impeachment hearings,
not by Starr or a court of law.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal attorney, David Kendall, announced the
arrangement for the president's testimony in a brief statement in
the White House driveway on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an effort to achieve a prompt resolution of this entire
matter the president will voluntarily provide his testimony on Aug.
17, 1998, to the Office of Independent Counsel as he has on prior
occasions,'' Kendall said. ``The president's testimony will be
videotaped at the White House with lawyers present. No further
statement will be issued.''
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough in a week of negotiations over Clinton's
testimony came Tuesday, when Starr agreed to withdraw the subpoena
that he issued on July 17, allowing Kendall to characterize the
President's prospective testimony as ``voluntary.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials acknowledged for the first time on
Wednesday that a subpoena had in fact been issued and served on
Kendall last week.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said that when Clinton learned
of the subpoena he instructed Kendall to quickly find ``a way to
get the grand jury the information it needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The official, who insisted on anonymity, ``The president is
obviously looking forward to a prompt resolution of this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The response to the subpoena was the subject of intense debate
within the White House and among the president's official and
private attorneys. Several of the president's political and media
advisers wanted Clinton to comply quickly to avoid the appearance
of stonewalling, but some members of the president's legal team
believed the subpoena was unenforceable and an affront to the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the decision was made to make the president available
for questioning, but only under favorable conditions and not under
compulsion of a subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   In another of the odd twists that have marked this investigation
since it began in January, Linda Tripp emerged from the federal
courthouse 10 blocks from the White House a few minutes after
Kendall spoke and read a statement of her own. She had just
completed her eighth and final day before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp brought her former friend, Ms. Lewinsky, to the
attention of Starr's office on Jan. 12, saying that Ms. Lewinsky
had confided in her details of a long-running sexual relationship
with the president. She provided tape recordings of their
conversations and documents that appeared to point to a conspiracy
to obstruct justice involving the president and Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``This investigation has never been, quote, `just about sex,'''
Mrs. Tripp said in a breaking voice under a sweltering sun. ``It
has been about telling the truth, and the truth matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who chairs the Judiciary Committee,
welcomed news of the president's impending testimony as a sign that
Starr's inquiry was in its ``closing throes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be more than just alleged sexual peccadilloes in
the White House, and frankly all of us would like to get this over
with,'' Hatch said at a news conference. ``I'd be surprised if Ken
Starr would allow this to go well into September.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont, the ranking Democrat on the
committee, was more blunt, calling on Starr to conclude his
investigation and ``give us a report on what he's done to date. Let
the American people, let the Congress do it and let the Congress
act whichever way they want. But wrap this sucker up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
