<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ EXPECTED TO SIT THREE TO FIVE GAMES WITH HAMSTRING INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Rangers expect right fielder Juan Gonzalez, the
major leagues' most prolific run producer, to be sidelined three to
five games with a strain in his right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who last night missed his second consecutive game at
Toronto's SkyDome, expects to return to the lineup sometime during
the Rangers' series this weekend against the Chicago White Sox at
The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those hamstring things are tough to predict,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``We wouldn't hold anyone to three to five
days.''
</P>
<P>
   That merits cause for alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve outfielder Roberto Kelly strained his left hamstring
while running the bases during the Rangers' 11-4 victory April 26
against the Royals at Kauffman Stadium. Kelly went on the 15-day
disabled list and did not return until June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who entered last night's games leading the major
leagues with 116 runs batted in, remains in pursuit of the
single-season record of 190 RBI established by Cubs outfielder Hack
Wilson during 1930. Gonzalez is on pace for 177, but the injury
diminishes his chances.
</P>
<P>
   The injury snapped Gonzalez's streak of 138 consecutive games
played, which represented the seventh-longest among active players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think it's a DL situation,'' Oates said. ``It's a
little worse than what we thought it was. It went from being tight
(Tuesday) night to being tender'' yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who continues to receive treatment, reported progress
after last night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels a little bit better,'' he said. ``I don't know how
many days it will be, though.''
</P>
</TEXT>
