<SLUG> BC-DANCE-ROBBINS-APPRECIATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JOY OF JEROME ROBBINS: IN THE MOMENT, AND FOR ALWAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By OCTAVIO ROCA  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   America has lost its greatest dancemaker.
</P>
<P>
   It may be too soon to contemplate the magnitude of the loss of
Jerome Robbins, who died Wednesday in New York at 79.
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult enough to think of him as old: His recent works
for New York City Ballet, major revivals of familiar Robbins dances
at San Francisco Ballet and even a national tour of his immortal
``West Side Story'' not long ago suggested to all who saw them that
Robbins boasted a youthfulness as eternal as that of dance itself.
</P>
<P>
   No other choreographer in our history touched our hearts in
quite so many ways. A gifted dancer and brilliant stage director,
classical purist, romantic innovator, play doctor and Broadway baby
_ uniquely American in everything he touched _ Robbins changed our
worlds of dance and theater forever.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins was just 25 when he created the ballet ``Fancy Free,'`
following it within months with his choreography for ``On the
Town,'` the hit Broadway musical about three sailors on leave in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   As did his friend and frequent collaborator Leonard Bernstein,
Robbins refused to be tied to the usual provinces of either
classical ballet or musical comedy. His work on the musicals ``The
King and I,'' ``A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum''
and ``Fiddler on the Roof'' burst on the scene alongside his
ballets, such as ``Dances at a Gathering'' and ``Goldberg
Variations.''
</P>
<P>
   He directed Anne Bancroft in ``Mother Courage'' and made Mary
Martin fly in ``Peter Pan'' and Ethel Merman soar in ``Gypsy.''
Mixing jazz and ballet while creating pieces for Broadway troupers
and demanding ballerinas alike, Robbins' choreography made every
gesture tell, every step mirror an emotion.
</P>
<P>
   There is an intensity to a Robbins ballet that can seem at odds
with the jazzy ease of his musicality. He could make singers and
actors seem like dancers, dancers seem like gods.
</P>
<P>
   More miraculous still was the illusion Robbins created again and
again: that whatever intricate combination of gestures and steps
materialized on stage or on film, it seemed to be happening
spontaneously. Drama coaches are fond of advising actors to be in
the moment, and the best way to explain what they mean by that is
to watch a Robbins dance.
</P>
<P>
   There is also no better way to demonstrate all that is best
about the arts in the United States: the optimism, daringness,
urbanity and impossibly youthful innocence at the heart of American
culture that finds their most ravishing expression in Robbins'
choreography.
</P>
<P>
   Rhapsodic or lyrical, eerie or witty, clear, musical or
mysterious _ if the depth and variety of the Robbins oeuvre was
staggering, his humanism remained constant. There is no such thing
as an abstract Robbins piece _ the man loved life too much, and
there is real life in a Robbins dance.
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that our warmest memories of beautiful
dancers picture them in a beautiful Robbins dance. Think of Helgi
Tomasson in ``Goldberg Variations,'' ``Dances at a Gathering'' or _
earlier this year _ in ``Circus Polka.'' Think of Natalia Makarova
and Mikhail Baryshnikov in ``Other Dances,'' Fernando Bujones in
``Fancy Free,'' George de la Pe &LR; n &LR; a in ``Les Noces,'' of Luc &LR; i &LR; a
Lacarra in ``The Cage'' or of generations of Jets and Sharks in
``West Side Story'' and Tevyes in ``Fiddler.'' The memories are
many, and they are sweet.
</P>
<P>
   What proved to be his last seasons with New York City Ballet,
Robbins' home company since 1949, showed the master happily at the
peak of his choreographic powers. San Francisco Ballet's
celebration of Robbins' work this year honored him with a fitting
retrospective of ballets that were created originally for the
company that nurtured both Robbins and Tomasson, perhaps preparing
the way for more Robbins dances in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In ballet troupes throughout the world, in touring musicals, in
the influence he exerted on those who followed _ from Bob Fosse in
``Chicago'' and ``Pippin'' to Tomasson in ``Pandora'' and Michael
Jackson in ``Thriller'' _ the spirit of Robbins will live on.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is tough to accept that the man will not be there
himself. American dance was defined by giants: George Balanchine,
Antony Tudor, Martha Graham and Robbins. We have just lost the last
of them. He was the easiest to love, and the one we will miss the
most.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
