<HEADLINE>
GINGERLY, URMANOV RETURNS TO THE ICE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ For the first time in 16 months, Aleksei
Urmanov of Russia returned to Olympic-style figure skating
Wednesday night at the Goodwill Games. The 1994 Olympic champion
was not trying to reclaim his past as much as he was seeking
confirmation of the possibilities for a healthy future.
</P>
<P>
   A severe groin injury forced him to withdraw from the 1997 world
championships in Lausanne, Switzerland, in March that year, and he
watched the 1998 Winter Olympics not on site in Nagano, Japan, but
in his apartment in St. Petersburg. The men's Olympic champion is
still a Russian, but his name is Ilya Kulik.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult,'' said Urmanov, who at 24 has grown
comfortable with English. ``But it was my injury that destroyed me,
not the skaters competing in the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   He finished second in Wednesday night's short program to Todd
Eldredge, the five-time U.S. champion and former world champion.
Eldredge skated flawlessly after a disappointing Olympic season,
while the rusty Urmanov struggled to land his triple-axel,
triple-toe combination, spun slowly and seemed to run out of gas
after two minutes. Evgeny Plushenko of Russia finished third.
</P>
<P>
   For Urmanov, the important thing was to skate competitively. He
cannot yet rely on his quadruple jump for Friday's long program,
but that is also beside the point. The idea here is not to win but
to test his body and see whether it will hold up under the strain
of competition. He does not know whether he will attempt an Olympic
comeback for 2002 or turn professional. It is victory enough now to
skate without debilitating pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in Olympic form,'' Urmanov said. ``This is just a
check. I don't feel real pain now, but I feel that there was an
injury there.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he feared surgery before the Olympics because the groin
is a delicate area.
</P>
<P>
   So Urmanov continued skating the way people learn to drive;
starting and stopping, nervously applying the brakes when he felt
himself in danger. Perhaps he did not take enough rest and tried to
come back too quickly, he now believes. Ballet dancers told him
that he would need at least a year to recover, and then, one day he
would wake up and the injury would be gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't believe them,'' Urmanov said. ``Now I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   When his luck went bad, it went bad full-time. In January, his
Olympic dreams shattered, Urmanov went to Colorado to have an
American doctor check his injured groin, only to fall during a
workout and open a gash on his knee that required 12 stitches. In
the spring, he competed in a pro-am event called the Ultimate Four
in Binghamton, N.Y., and finished last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I was last,'' he said. ``But it was good for me. I
hadn't competed in a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The original injury was more than a physical setback for
Urmanov. By 1997, he finally seemed to be coming to terms with the
pressure and expectation that come with an Olympic gold medal.
After the 1994 Winter Games, he struggled emotionally, believing
that he now had to win every event, land every jump perfectly,
leaving himself no room for error. He failed to win a medal at the
1994, 1995 or 1996 world championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard after the Olympics,'' Urmanov said. ``It was a
mind problem. My stupid mind. You are the Olympic champion. Nothing
happens. Everyone falls. Everyone makes mistakes. It's not possible
to do everything right. We are not Robocops. We are normal
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Just when he realized it was OK to be fallible, Urmanov got
injured. Once again, he is trying to rebuild the blocks of security
in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love it when everything is fine,'' he said. ``But if I
come to practice and my triple axel or some other jump is not so
good, I'm real close to hating myself. I know this is crazy. I
don't understand why I feel this. If I can't do it today, I can do
it tomorrow. Nothing happens. Life still goes forward.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
