<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: of law.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton's personal attorney, David Kendall, announced the
arrangement for the president's testimony in a brief statement in
the White House driveway on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an effort to achieve a prompt resolution of this entire
matter the president will voluntarily provide his testimony on Aug.
17, 1998, to the Office of Independent Counsel as he has on prior
occasions,'' Kendall said. ``The president's testimony will be
videotaped at the White House with lawyers present. No further
statement will be issued.''
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough in a week of negotiations over Clinton's
testimony came Tuesday, when Starr agreed to withdraw the subpoena
that he issued on July 17, allowing Kendall to characterize the
President's prospective testimony as ``voluntary.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials acknowledged for the first time on
Wednesday that a subpoena had in fact been issued and served on
Kendall last week.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said that when Clinton learned
of the subpoena he instructed Kendall to quickly find ``a way to
get the grand jury the information it needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The official, who insisted on anonymity, ``The president is
obviously looking forward to a prompt resolution of this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The response to the subpoena was the subject of intense debate
within the White House and among the president's official and
private attorneys. Several of the president's political and media
advisers wanted Clinton to comply quickly to avoid the appearance
of stonewalling, but some members of the president's legal team
believed the subpoena was unenforceable and an affront to the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the decision was made to make the president available
for questioning, but only under favorable conditions and not under
compulsion of a subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   In another of the odd twists that have marked this investigation
since it began in January, Linda Tripp emerged from the federal
courthouse 10 blocks from the White House a few minutes after
Kendall spoke and read a statement of her own. She had just
completed her eighth and final day before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp brought her former friend, Ms. Lewinsky, to the
attention of Starr's office on Jan. 12, saying that Ms. Lewinsky
had confided in her details of a long-running sexual relationship
with the president. She provided tape recordings of their
conversations and documents that appeared to point to a conspiracy
to obstruct justice involving the president and Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``This investigation has never been, quote, `just about sex,'''
Mrs. Tripp said in a breaking voice under a sweltering sun. ``It
has been about telling the truth, and the truth matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who chairs the Judiciary Committee,
welcomed news of the president's impending testimony as a sign that
Starr's inquiry was in its ``closing throes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be more than just alleged sexual peccadilloes in
the White House, and frankly all of us would like to get this over
with,'' Hatch said at a news conference. ``I'd be surprised if Ken
Starr would allow this to go well into September.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont, the ranking Democrat on the
committee, was more blunt, calling on Starr to conclude his
investigation and ``give us a report on what he's done to date. Let
the American people, let the Congress do it and let the Congress
act whichever way they want. But wrap this sucker up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
