<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR INVESTIGATING ACCIDENT AT TOWER IN TIMES SQUARE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Ill., N.J.)  (jw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau
announced Wednesday that his office was investigating possible
criminal misconduct in connection with the scaffolding accident at
the Conde Nast building in Times Square. The accident killed an
85-year-old woman and prompted authorities to close off several
blocks around the accidents for much of last week.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have been investigating the accident since it
occurred, Morgenthau said, noting that the inquiry was ``quite
complex and it could take some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said that city officials were also
investigating the collapse of the temporary elevator tower and
that, depending on the findings, the city could file a civil
lawsuit. He said the city would coordinate its investigation with
the district attorney's.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of investigations we're trying to
coordinate as carefully as possible with the district attorney, who
would ultimately have to determine whether there is criminal
liability,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kielar, senior vice president of Tishman Realty and
Construction Co., said the construction manager, Tishman
Construction Corp., and the developer, the Durst Organization, were
cooperating with the investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our understanding that an investigation of this nature
is normal procedure when a fatality occurs,'' Kielar said.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in the district attorney's office cautioned that their
investigation was in a preliminary stage and they refused to give
details.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said a worker or a supervisor would have to engage
in a ``gross deviation'' from standard safety procedures to be
charged with criminally negligent homicide.
</P>
<P>
   The City Buildings Department hired an engineering firm, Wiss,
Janney, Elstner Associates, of Northbrook, Ill., to investigate the
cause of the collapse, said Ted Birkhahn, a department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Osborn, manager of the firm's branch in Princeton, N.J.,
said four engineers would carry out the investigation, beginning
Thursday, but he did not know how long it might take.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to gather whatever data we need from the existing
scaffolding structure before it is destroyed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kielar said Tishman had also hired an engineering firm to
investigate the cause of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   As work on securing the construction site continued, more of the
Times Square area returned to a state approaching normal Wednesday.
Both Avenue of the Americas and 42nd Street were opened to traffic
by midmorning, but West 44th and West 43rd streets between Broadway
and Avenue of the Americas remained closed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-98 2328EDT &QL; 
