<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ROBBINS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEROME ROBBINS, GIANT OF AMERICAN DANCE, DIES AT 79 
</HEADLINE>
   By OCTAVIO ROCA  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerome Robbins, one of the giants of 20th century ballet and a
major figure in the American musical theater, died yesterday at his
home in Manhattan. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   He suffered a stroke Saturday, said Jeffrey Peterson of the New
York City Ballet, the company that was Robbins' home since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins was acclaimed throughout the world for ballets he
created for the American Ballet Theatre, New York City Ballet and
Ballets USA, many of which are now considered to be among the
classics of the repertory.
</P>
<P>
   He was equally celebrated _ and often emulated _ for his work in
the theater, where his dances are the stuff of Broadway legend:
``On the Town,'' ``Gypsy,'' ``West Side Story,'' ``The King and
I,'' ``Fiddler on the Roof'' and others that helped define the feel
of musical comedy and continue to exert considerable influence to
this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerome Robbins' death truly represents the end of an era and
leaves us in deepest grief,'' said Peter Martins, New York City
Ballet's artistic director and Robbins' colleague and student. ``He
was one of the last titans in the world of dance. (George)
Balanchine is gone. So are (Sir Frederick) Ashton, (Antony) Tudor
and (Martha) Graham. And now, Jerry. Today is a very sad day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the true geniuses of our century,'' said Helgi
Tomasson, artistic director of San Francisco Ballet and one of the
leading interpreters of Robbins' choreography. ``He will live on,
of course, in his own dances and in the incredible influence he has
had not just on ballet choreographers but also in the musical
theater. But his death is a great tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I can say that I would not be director of San
Francisco Ballet today if it had not been for Jerry, that without
him I would not have had the career I had or been the choreographer
I am. He was the one who brought me to this country in 1960, who
asked me to join New York City Ballet, who gave me so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Reactions elsewhere in the dance world echoed the grief of his
two star pupils. Michael Smuin, who danced the Robbins repertory at
ABT and today heads his own Smuin Ballets/SF, said, ``The last of
the big ones is gone now, and frankly the one who had the richest
palette. Balanchine tried Broadway too, but he was never as
successful as Jerry was. Robbins could do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not be duplicated,'' said Melissa Hayden, the great
American ballerina and teacher. ``And he will be remembered as an
original.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Jerry,'' said Alicia Alonso, Robbins' former
Broadway and ABT colleague who is today director of the Ballet
Nacional de Cuba, ``is that he always made you happy that there was
such a thing as American dance. No one ever has been more American,
or so full of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Wilson Rabinowitz was born Oct. 11, 1918, the son of
Russian Jews who emigrated to New York. His father ran a
delicatessen, his mother was a housewife who made sure that young
Jerome and his sister, Sonya, took dance and music lessons.
</P>
<P>
   The future choreographer studied briefly at New York University
in 1935, but the Depression was rough on the Rabinowitz family, and
he dropped out of college to take several jobs. Still, he found a
way to take dance lessons, at Works Progress Administration
studios, at summer camp and eventually at the Yiddish Art Theater,
where he landed a small role in ``The Brothers Ashkenazy.''
</P>
<P>
   His first Broadway musical followed: ``Great Lady'' in 1938,
choreographed by George Balanchine, where Robbins kicked it up in
the chorus line with fellow hoofers Alonso and Nora Kaye. By 1940,
all three had joined the corps of the newly formed American Ballet
Theatre. ``This is the most old-fashioned bilge,'' he told Kaye and
Alonso at the time about the company's classical repertory. ``This
is an American company. Why do we have to keep on dancing about
wheat sheaves and Russian Gypsies?'' Robbins recalled the incident
when he received a Kennedy Center Honor in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry was a better dancer than he always thought,'' Alonso
recalled about her colleague, who indeed rose at ABT not only in
the classics but also in new ballets by Tudor, Massine, Lichine and
de Mille. ``But what he always wanted to do was something of his
own culture, his own country. He did, and after all these years,
whenever I think of American dance, I think of Jerry. Balanchine
was universal, but Jerry was and always will be the most American
of choreographers.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins' all-American credentials came early when he worked with
Leonard Bernstein on ``Fancy Free'' in 1944. He and Bernstein would
team again, with spectacular success each time: ``On the Town'' and
``West Side Story'' on Broadway, ``The Dybbuk'' for New York City
Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bernstein, Robbins kept his hand in culture both high and
low, but it was Robbins who may have enjoyed the easier passage
back and forth. He could create ``The Cage'' the same season as
``The King and I,'' make ballet history with the monumental music
of Bach and at the same time make Zero Mostel shimmy in
``Fiddler.'' His musical tastes were voracious but always knowing:
The immortal trio of strippers in ``Gypsy'' rang true, but so did
the elegiac lines of ``Dances at a Gathering.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be impossible to choose what constituted Robbins in his
prime; he was always, it seemed, at the height of his glorious
powers. He created his last new work, ``Brandenburg,'' in 1997, for
New York City Ballet. It was as inventive as ``Goldberg
Variations,'' as exuberant as ``Fancy Free,'' sheer joy, wit and
pleasure in motion. It was just another Robbins ballet, which is to
say, it was a work of genius.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
