<HEADLINE>
OFFICER SHOT IN NEW YORK TAKES A TURN FOR THE WORSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As anguished family members, friends and fellow
police officers continued a vigil around his hospital bed, the
police officer who was shot in the head on Staten Island on Sunday
night took a turn for the worse Wednesday with severe swelling
around the wound.
</P>
<P>
   The condition of the officer, Gerard Carter, 28, who had been
showing some signs of improvement on Tuesday, was downgraded to
extremely critical. Carter was shot in the head at close range
while sitting in a police van in a housing project. He had been
approaching a 17-year-old ex-convict who was wanted for questioning
in a recent killing, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edwin Chang, a neurosurgeon who operated on Carter at the
St. Vincent's Campus of the Sisters of Charity Medical Center on
Staten Island, said he was concerned that the swelling around the
bullet wound was restricting the flow of blood to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not something you want to have happen,'' he said, ``but
how it translates into a future prognosis we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   In previous efforts to stem and contain the swelling, doctors
removed portions of Carter's brain tissue, inserted a catheter into
his skull to drain excess fluid and gave him anti-swelling
medicine, said Bill McCann, hospital spokesman. The bullet is still
lodged in the officer's brain.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow officers were shaken by the fact that Carter _ well known
for going out of his way to help children as a counselor at local
youth programs and as a volunteer at softball games and barbecues _
had been shot and critically wounded by a youth from the projects
he patrolled.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect in the case, Shatiek Johnson, 17, had already been
convicted of manslaughter for beating a homeless man to death when
he was 15. Johnson was charged Tuesday with attempted murder in the
shooting of Carter and with murder in the July 16 shooting death of
Eric Trotman. Before he was shot, police said, Carter had been
approaching Johnson, whom he recognized as someone detectives
wanted to question in the Trotman case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
