<SLUG> BC-SOC-METROSTARS-WIZARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROSTARS BEAT FATIGUE AND KANSAS CITY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.J., Mo., Kan.)  (jw) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Major League Soccer's All-Star Game on
Sunday could not have come at a better time for the MetroStars.
Playing their fourth game in 10 days, the MetroStars scored a 3-2
shootout victory Wednesday night over the Kansas City Wizards at
Giants Stadium, but it seemed they were ready for a rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team is tired,'' said coach Alfonso Mondelo, although the
MetroStars improved their record to 12-9 and went three games over
the .500-mark for the first time in their history. ``The level of
our play came down a little tonight because of fatigue,'' he said
Wednesday night. ``We played without any crispness.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tab Ramos played with his usual gusto again and scored the
first goal in the shootout after Preki had given the Wizards (9-12)
the lead. Giovanni Savarese scored the deciding goal in the
shootout to give the MetroStars their second victory in as many
shootout games this season.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars showed limited movement away from the ball. They
also allowed the visitors plenty of room to operate around their
penalty area and paid the price for their loose marking by yielding
goals to Preki and Paul Wright, both in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   A player the caliber of Preki, the playmaker and scorer for the
Wizards, demands close marking, even if he is far from the danger
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Preki has a lethal left foot and is most dangerous when he
attacks from right to left. He spread the field with accurate
passes that way and he scored Kansas City's first-ever goal at
Giants Stadium by cutting into the middle from the right side and
beating Tony Meola with a curling shot.
</P>
<P>
   Preki's goal, his fourth of the season, came in the 28th minute
and tied the game after Matt McKeon of the Wizards had accidentally
kicked the ball in his own goal in the 13th minute to give the
MetroStars the lead.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon's gaffe came when he tried to clear Mike Dunaney's low
cross from the left side while under pressure from Miles Joseph of
the MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   A header by Savarese that barely missed the goal after a cross
by Diego Sonora on the right was the only thing the MetroStars did
of note for a long period after the goal. As a result, they fell
behind on the goal by Wright with two minutes before intermission.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars picked up the tempo a little after Eduardo
Hurtado entered the game in the 58th minute in place of Marcelo
Vega, tying the game on Savarese's 10th of the season. Hurtado
started the goal with a back-heel pass to Brian Kelly on the left
and Savarese converted Kelly's pass from close range to force the
shootout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
