<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCO SAVES WHAT ROJAS NEARLY FRITTERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rm) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By the time the public address announcer could
hurriedly ask the Shea Stadium crowd to stand for the
seventh-inning stretch, it was too late. The crowd was already on
its feet, lustily booing Mel Rojas as he made the long walk from
the mound to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday night, at least, Rojas would get a small bit of
satisfaction even through the boos. After squandering a lead for
the starter Al Leiter, Rojas was bailed out by the timely hitting
of the Mets as they took their second consecutive game from the
Western Division-leading San Diego Padres. After seeing a four-run
lead disappear, Rojas earned the victory as the Mets pushed in a
run on a sacrifice fly by Luis Lopez in the bottom of the seventh
inning and held on for a 7-6 victory.
</P>
<P>
   And this time the bullpen held the lead with Bill Pulsipher
doing a credible job and John Franco earning the save.
</P>
<P>
   Franco ended the game after a brief scare, fielding a hard
grounder back through the box and firing to Lopez, who had
committed an error to put runners on first and second. Lopez
acrobatically threw to first for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets piled six runs on the Padres starter Joey Hamilton, who
had won his previous four starts, thanks to the work of Brian
McRae, who continued his torrid pace. McRae was 4 for 5 with a pair
of doubles and two runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian has just come,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said.
``He's progressively gotten to the point where he has a real
comfortable swing that he uses every day. The telltale sign about
Brian was about a month ago. If you look at his stats, he was
leading the team in extra base hits and he had struck out only as
many times as he had walked. I think that means that he was seeing
the ball well. He was taking pitches out of the zone and the
pitches in the zone, he was doing damage with them. Now he's built
on that and he's getting singles, also, and he's gotten his average
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas, along with Greg McMichael, turned another solid start by
Leiter into another frustrating evening for the crowd, and also for
Leiter. The Mets ace walked off the mound to a mild ovation with
one out in the seventh inning with a 6-2 lead and runners on first
and second. McMichael, who blew Leiter's chance for a victory in
Leiter's previous start, did little to help him again, allowing a
ground single to Greg Vaughn and then walking Jim Leyritz to load
the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas then came on, drawing boos before his name was even
announced to the crowd. He had had one significant appearance since
being ripped for five runs without retiring a batter in Toronto on
July 1, retiring the side with no damage in Chicago on July 24. But
Wednesday night, that positive experience was quickly forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   After missing on his first three pitches, Rojas finally threw a
strike and drew mock cheers. After another strike got the crowd
momentarily on his side, Rojas walked Wally Joyner, pushing across
a run to cut the lead to 6-4, and the response was mild
resignation. Rojas then got Chuck Finley on a popout for the second
out of the inning, but on a 2-0 count, pinch-hitter Greg Myers
drilled a double down the line, scoring two runs and tying the
score. Rojas finally ended the inning and was serenaded with a loud
chorus of boos as he left the field.
</P>
<P>
   For Leiter, it marked the second straight game in which he left
the field with only two runs allowed and the team holding a lead.
And for the second straight time, he had to watch from the dugout
as he earned another no decision.
</P>
<P>
   With Leiter pitching well, the Mets worked quickly to provide
him with support. Brian McRae led off by bouncing a double down the
right field line past Joyner. He moved to third on an Edgardo
Alfonzo grounder to second base and scored on a sacrifice fly to
center by John Olerud.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza added a run in the fourth inning, blasting his 17th
home run of the season beyond the bleachers in left-center. Todd
Hundley gave the Mets a 3-0 lead in the fifth inning, driving a
two-out, run-scoring single to right after Piazza was intentionally
walked to get to him.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA BASES
</P>
<P>
   REY ORDONEZ, who strained his abdominal muscle on Saturday,
played late in the game after taking batting practice with the team
and fielding balls at shortstop. Manager BOBBY VALENTINE believes
he will be able to start soon. ``Rey looked terrific,'' Valentine
said before Wednesday night's game. ``He took grounders, hit, and
soft-tossed. He felt so good that he took batting practice. He's
close.'' ... BERNARD GILKEY did make his return to the starting
lineup for the first time in eight games Wednesday night with BUTCH
HUSKEY getting the night off in right field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
