u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-KILLER-KID-NYT &LR;      07-29 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-KILLER-KID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY, 10, ACCUSED IN BEATING DEATH OF 4-MONTH-OLD GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A 10-year-old boy from Orange, N.J., was charged
Wednesday with murder and aggravated sexual assault in the brutal
beating death of a 4-month-old girl who had been left in his care
Saturday night while the baby's mother went to a local restaurant,
Essex County prosecutors and investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's mother, Rhakida Daniels, 18, has also been arrested
and charged with child endangerment, prosecutors said.
Investigators said Ms. Daniels left her daughter, Aljaneer Caraway,
and her 1-year-old son alone with the 10-year-old boy in a friend's
home while she went to a White Castle at 11 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials would not say how long Ms. Daniels was away from the
apartment, at 108 Parrow St. But at a news conference Wednesday
afternoon, Essex County Prosecutor Patricia Hurt described an
extraordinarily gruesome crime, which she said had occurred at the
hands of one of the youngest children ever to be charged with
murder in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt and other officials said Ms. Daniels returned to her
apartment to find Aljaneer unconscious in a crib. The baby was
brain dead when she arrived at University Hospital in Newark, Ms.
Hurt said, with a fractured skull, a punctured liver and bruises.
Ms. Hurt said there were signs of sexual assault.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Officials would not describe what, if any, relationship there
had been between the 10-year-old suspect and the victim and her
family.
</P>
<P>
   Under New Jersey state law, the boy is too young to be charged
as an adult. Because he is under the age of 14, the minimum
required for prosecutors to seek adult charges, the boy has been
charged with juvenile murder, which carries a maximum penalty of 20
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, whose name was withheld because of his age, was
initially charged with attempted murder and aggravated sexual
assault. The charges were changed to include murder after the baby
died at University Hospital on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   An investigator, who discussed the case on the condition of
anonymity, said there were conflicting reports describing the boy,
ranging from a good student to ``neurologically impaired.''
</P>
<P>
   At a closed detention hearing on Monday at Essex County Family
Court in Newark, a judge ordered the boy held at the Essex County
Youth Detention Center pending further judicial proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Daniels pleaded not guilty to the child endangerment charge
at an arraignment in Central Judicial Processing Court on Monday.
Ray Weiss, a spokesman for the Essex County prosecutor's office,
said that a public defender had been appointed to handle the
arraignment but that Ms. Daniels did not yet have a lawyer
officially representing her.
</P>
<P>
   At the arraignment, Judge Chester Morrison ordered Ms. Daniels
held in $10,000 bail, and officials said she was still detained
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
