u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-OILERS-NAME-HNS &LR;      07-29 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OILERS-NAME-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Tennessee to change nickname
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
For more than a year, Bud Adams has been under fire from Tennessee
politicians, businessmen, fans and media to change the nickname he
selected for his team in 1959 when the Houston Oilers became a
charter member of the American Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Adams has finally surrendered. In a news conference
Wednesday in Nashville, Tenn., Adams and NFL commissioner Paul
Tagliabue announced the team will have a new nickname, logo,
uniform and colors for the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Adams finally relented is because Tagliabue
guaranteed him that no NFL team will ever be allowed to use the
Oilers name again. They used it for 37 years in Houston before
moving to Tennessee for the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much like a jersey, the Oilers name will be retired,''
Tagliabue said. ``The team's history and tradition stays where it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob McNair, who is trying to get the 32nd NFL franchise for
Houston, has never been interested in Oilers as a nickname.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that if we get a team, we want to start
with a clean slate,'' McNair said. ``The Oilers name belongs to
Bud.''
</P>
<P>
   When Adams explained to the media that the team will still be
called the Oilers this season, he slipped and said, ``We'll play
the 1998 season as the Hou eh, Tennessee Oilers. But as we start
1999 in our new stadium, our team will have a new name.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans support it. They demonstrated to me that they wanted
this to be a Tennessee team. Now, it'll truly be Tennessee's
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who plans to have an Oilers museum at his new stadium,
chose Oilers as the nickname of his franchise because his father,
Boots Adams, was an oil man whose amateur basketball team, the
Phillips 66 Oilers, was a national powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emotional part is all over now,'' Adams said. ``I'm
looking forward to the future.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL Properties' normal deadline for picking a new nickname,
logo, colors and uniform is Feb. 1 for marketing purposes, but
Adams said he wants to announce the new package by the end of the
regular season. The Oilers' last game is Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to include the fans in the process, Adams is going
to form an advisory council of 10 to 12 prominent Tennesseans from
across the state. They will listen to the fans in their areas and
suggest nicknames. Ultimately, NFL Properties will give Adams about
a half-dozen choices. He will make the final decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans have been asking for this for a long time,'' Oilers
coach Jeff Fisher said. ``A day doesn't go by when I don't run into
somebody who asks that question first. Now, we've put that to
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers unveiled a poster Wednesday that says, ``The Winning
Tradition Continues.'' Color pictures of Fisher, guard Bruce
Matthews, running back Eddie George and quarterback Steve McNair
are paired with black-and-white photos of former Houston greats
Earl Campbell, Bum Phillips, Mike Munchak and George Blanda.
</P>
<P>
   The poster says ``Tennessee'' with a question mark after it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to identify with where you play,'' said Matthews, who
joined the franchise in 1983 and is the senior member of the team.
``This is no shock. If it helps get more fans excited, then it's
great.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Tennessee Oilers still sounds strange. Once we identify
with our new name, it will become as commonplace as Houston Oilers
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Elvin Bethea, who played 16 seasons at defensive end and was one
of the greatest players in franchise history, may have spoken for
all the players who spent their entire careers as Houston Oilers.
Bethea chuckled at the idea that changing the nickname will ignite
sluggish ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess Bud wants to put some new sheets on the bed,'' Bethea
said. ``A name change is not going to change the product inside of
a can.''
</P>
<P>
   After playing the last two seasons in the Astrodome and the
Liberty Bowl in Memphis, respectively, the Oilers are playing this
season in 41,000-seat Vanderbilt Stadium, where no game has been
sold out. Team officials said 30 season tickets and 800 single-game
tickets were sold in the first hours after the news conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
