u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BUSINESS-DISTRICT-     07-29 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUSINESS-DISTRICT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS IMPROVEMENT DISTRICT IS DISSOLVED
</HEADLINE>
   ( rm ) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a year of mounting acrimony between Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and several of Manhattan's business improvement
districts, senior city officials said Wednesday they were putting
the Grand Central Partnership, one of the largest and by far the
most combative of the districts, out of business.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Business Services, which is responsible for
monitoring the affairs of the city's 34 districts, said in a formal
statement that the city would not renew the Grand Central
district's contract, which expires Friday. Without its municipal
contract, the district cannot collect the fees that property owners
are assessed for services, including garbage pickup, security and
street beautification.
</P>
<P>
   The department cited ``a pattern of noncompliance with
regulations and noncooperation with officials'' by the board of the
district. It singled out the district's president, Daniel
Biederman, who holds the same salaried position at two other
business improvement districts in midtown Manhattan, for failing to
respond to a City Hall directive in May that he no longer head more
than one of the business improvement groups. The city said his
combined salary is $335,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, city officials said, Biederman and his staff failed
to respond to city requests for financial information, failed to
abide by city rules that require competitive bidding in awarding
contracts, and did not allow sufficient city oversight into the
district's operations.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lhota, the deputy mayor for operations, said in an
interview that the city might have moved to disband another of
Biederman's districts, the 34th Street Partnership, if its contract
were up for renewal. The city contract with that district, like
Bryant Park Restoration Corp., also headed by Biederman, does not
expire until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Grand Central and 34th Street districts stick out
like a sore thumb,'' said Lhota, adding that the city's move
against Biederman's groups did not reflect widespread problems with
the other districts, which were formed in early 1980s to supplement
city services with contributions by property owners.
</P>
<P>
   Biederman and other officials of the Grand Central district
declined to be interviewed, instead offering a terse prepared
statement saying that they were ``surprised'' by the city's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board of the Grand Central Partnership has been
negotiating in good faith on its contract with the city's Law
Department and will continue to do so until this matter is amicably
resolved,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Lhota and other senior aides to the mayor, such
a resolution seemed unlikely Wednesday, because of what they termed
the district's continuing resistance to governmental oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Weeks, commissioner of the Department of Business
Services, said Wednesday that the district had failed to meet
repeated city demands to change its practices in areas ranging from
``late audits to ignoring oversight regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Grand Central district apparently has viewed itself as a
private organization rather than an entity spending public money,''
said Andrew Schwartz, a spokesman for the department. Although the
city did not have evidence of criminal activity by anyone involved
in the district, he said it had received ``many complaints from
merchants and other people that told us the district was not
responding to their requests for information about its
activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement goes to the heart of the unusual place
that business improvement districts have occupied in New York
City's civic structure. In one sense, they act as an arm of
government, augmenting services like police protection and
sanitation, while at the same time acting as a direct extension of
the businesses that finance them.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement also highlights the debate over the money they
spend. The districts contend that the fees they receive from
property owners are private funds. But Giuliani contends that since
the city collects the fees on behalf of the districts, they are, in
essence, public funds, and the city should have a say in how the
money is spent.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the mayor angered people involved in several of the
districts by ordering that their daily operations _ including
private security patrols, the installation of planters and street
signs, and garbage pickup _ be submitted to greater oversight by
the Department of Business Services.
</P>
<P>
   But other changes in the city rules have been directed squarely
at Biederman and the districts he heads.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike any of the other groups, the Grand Central and 34th
Street districts have sold bonds to raise huge sums to pay for
their projects, like the installation of spotlights that illuminate
the facade of Grand Central Station on 42nd Street, and planters,
street benches and signs that have been installed in both
districts. Since first selling bonds in the late 1980s, the Grand
Central district has accumulated a debt to its bondholders of $32
million, according to city records.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Giuliani forbad the districts to use use bond
financing, saying the city could be liable for the debt if a
district encountered financial problems or disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks said Wednesday that property owners in the Grand Central
district would continue to be assessed fees, and that the money
would be held by the city ``to ensure that the holders of bonds are
fully protected.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials and business people who control other business
improvement districts said the directive raised unresolved
questions. Lhota, who acknowledged that the current level of
assessments being paid by property owners in the Grand Central
District would exceed the amount necessary to pay off its bond
debt, said that the city would return some portion of the
assessments to the property owners after they are collected by the
Department of Finance.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the city would ensure that ``level of service to
property owners and tenants in the Grand Central area is not
reduced.'' But he declined to speculate on whether providing such
service would require the city to assign additional police and
sanitation workers to replace those who are now on the payroll of
the district.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Executives at other districts, citing their fears of angering
City Hall, declined to comment publicly on the mayor's action. But
privately, some said that the move raised difficult legal and
financial questions. One was whether the Grand Central group could
continue to operate, at least temporarily, relying on bank accounts
that it had already filled through its bond sales and prior
assessments on property owners.
</P>
<P>
   Some questioned whether Biederman and other directors of the
district might challenge the city in court, arguing that it was
denying them their right to operate what was designed to be a
public-spirited, nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   Although city officials declined to provide details, they said
the decision to deny a contract to the Grand Central group came
after months of abortive negotiations. Although the group's
five-year contract with the city had expired at the end of June,
they said Biederman and his board had been granted a one-month
extension.
</P>
<P>
   During that period, ``BID officials were unresponsive to city
officials,'' said the statement from the Department of Business
Services. After the district's contract expires Wednesday, the
statement said, Biederman and his board had been ordered to provide
the city with a ``full financial accounting of its assets and
liabilities and deliver all books, records and accounts'' to the
city within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Lhota said one possible way to sustain the neighborhood services
that have been performed by the Grand Central group would be to
reconstitute it under new management. ``We would look favorably if
someone stepped forward who was accountable,'' he said, but added
that he knew of no one who was prepared to do so.
</P>
<P>
   One detail of the Grand Central group's finances that has long
been a source of controversy among business people and city
officials is Biederman's salary, which the city's formal statement
Wednesday listed at a combined total of $335,000, plus $30,000 a
year in health benefits, from the three districts he heads.
</P>
<P>
   One executive involved in another district, who agreed to speak
on the condition of anonymity, said the reason for the apparent
collapse in negotiations between the Grand Central group and the
city was that an extension of the group's contract would have
required Biederman to step down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
