<SLUG> BC-WESTFIELD-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTFIELD QUARTERLY REPORT FULL OF PLUSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Westfield America Inc., the real estate investment
trust that owns Topanga Plaza and recently bought the neighboring
Promenade mall in L.A.'s San Fernando Valley, has reported strong
second-quarter earnings on the strength of tenant growth,
acquisitions and redevelopment.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles-based owner of shopping centers across the
United States also announced Wednesday it paid $33.5 million in
cash for The Promenade at Woodland Hills, whose purchase was first
reported by the Los Angeles Daily News in May. The sale closed in
June.
</P>
<P>
   Westfield's funds from operations _ that is, net income
excluding depreciation _ totaled $32.2 million, or 40 cents per
share, on $77 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're effectively meeting our expectations,'' said Randall
Smith, vice president of marketing for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Figures for the comparable period last year were not available
because the company went public in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Of total revenue, $68.7 million comes from wholly owned
properties or properties in which Westfield has more than a 50
percent stake. The rest is from properties in which it holds a
smaller share.
</P>
<P>
   Westfield bought the Promenade from Indianapolis-based Simon
DeBartolo Group Inc., which in turn had purchased the
600,000-square-foot mall in September as part of a portfolio of
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said it was too early to say what Westfield's plans are
for the Promenade, which is only two blocks south of Topanga Plaza,
in Woodland Hills. Westfield has owned Topanga Plaza since February
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it's a really good opportunity for us to maximize the
retail market for the area,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   William Acheson, a senior analyst with Salomon Smith Barney in
New York City, said the $33.5 million price was a good value for
Westfield, which has ``a very good track record'' for beefing up
occupancy at its malls.
</P>
<P>
   The Promenade, which has 75 retailers including the AMC 16 movie
theater and two Macy's stores, is about 56 percent occupied, the
company said, compared with an average 93 percent occupancy rate
for the 26 shopping centers in which Westfield has an interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no worries that Westfield would buy a property that
they didn't think they would make a significant amount of money
on,'' Acheson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
